<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Water board chief comes north to explain
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">
<BR>
<font size=-1>
<A HREF="/appeal.html">Help fight the legal battle for free WWW links</A>
</font>
<P>
<H1>Water board chief comes north to explain
</H1>
<H2></H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt5.gif">
<HR>
</center>
<P>

<P>
8th January 1997
<P>
The boss of the new North of Scotland Water Authority (NoSWA) last  night [TUES] denied 'short-changing' Shetland and said some  councillors were 'not very fair' when they complained about delays to  rural sewerage schemes.
<P>
Alasdair Findlay, NoSWA's chief executive, was speaking on the eve of  a visit to Shetland to meet residents in Whalsay, South Whiteness and  Hillswick, where drainage projects have been put on hold. 
<P>
Speaking on local radio, Mr Findlay said: 'We haven't actually  dropped anything. There are questions of timing when schemes go  ahead.' The board would decide its priorities shortly and he wanted  to hear local people's views before it did.
<P>
NoSWA had reduced charges since it took over from Shetland Islands  Council in April and, unlike the council, no longer charged  householders for sewers if they were not connected to main drainage.
<P>
Mr Findlay said they were committed to a two million pounds Lerwick  sewerage scheme over the next couple of years, cleaning up the town's harbour.
<P>
'I don't think I'd accept any kind of charge that we're  short-changing people in Shetland,' he said.
<P>
Commenting on suggestions that the council had deliberately brought  forward sewerage schemes in its own programme, shortly before NoSWA  began work, he said: 'It would be quite understandable if the council  wanted to get as much work done, or as much work in the pipeline,  before they had to take their hands off the tiller and leave the job to us...' 
<P>
The chief executive said the board served 1.2 million of Scotland's  total population and had to meet European obligations on water  quality as one of its priorities. But they were 'acutely aware' of  their responsibilities to outlying areas.
<P>
<A HREF="/headline/noswa/noswa.html">See our earlier report on this story </A>
<P>



<P>
<BR clear=all>
