<h2>15/8/96</h2>

The only birdy news news of note was a <b>BARRED WARBLER</b> at the Sumburgh Hotel Garden.

<p>

Far fewer moths were around today - with NO new additions to the Shetland list!!!!! Poor Show.

<p>

Jonathan Wills reported the following sightings from the 'Dunter' today.<BR>
1100BST : Two <b>HARBOUR PORPOISES</b> off south-east coast of Noss.<BR>
1130BST : The last of the <b>GUILLEMOTS</b> have gone from Noss (I wasn't there yesterday - no 
passengers, can you believe it?!)<BR>
2005BST : Four (possiby more) <b>KILLER WHALES</b> again passing within a few yards of 
the Score Point, Bressay. Seen at a distance of 500 yards, from on 
land (we'd moored up the boat and gone ashore). My third 
sighting at this location this year and the fourth (counting the 
Bruntland one last month) in this vicinity.
<BR>
As on previous occasions, the whales swam off southwards, at about 
10mph, towards Noss - this time apparently feeding on fish, not seals.
<BR>
They appear to be attracted by the upwelling of water over the 70' 
high underwater cliff which stetches NE of the Score. Every sighting 
has been with the flood tide.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>14/8/96</h2>

There were fewer moths around last night although there was still another new species for Shetland, a <b>LIME-SPECK PUG</b> at Eswick where there was also another <b>DEWICK'S PLUSIA</b>.

<p>

On Fetlar, the <b>BLACK-HEADED BUNTING</b> was relocated along with <b>2 BARRED WARBLERS</b>, a <b>RED-BACKED SHRIKE</b>, and an <b>ICTERINE WARBLER</b>.

<p>

Yesterdays <b>GREENISH WARBLER</b> was still at the Sumburgh Hotel Garden, along with an <b>ICTERINE WARBLER</b> at Sumburgh Head, a <b>BARRED WARBLER</b> on Whalsay, and the first-summer <b>GLAUCOUS GULL</b> was still in Lerwick Harbour - around the Shetland Catch Fish Factory.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>13/8/96</h2>

Its <b>MOTH'S R US and WORLD OF MOTH'S</b> in Shetland at the moment, with at least another <b>FOUR</b> new species for the isles discovered again last night. These were - <b>DEWICK'S PLUSIA</b> at Eswick, a <b>SCARCE BRINDLE</b> on Unst (also only about the 4th ever recorded in Britain), an amazing 4 specimens of the <b>DOGS TOOTH</b> (an equally amazing name for a moth), singles at Sandwick and Unst and 2 at Eswick, but an incredible 14 specimens of <b>THE SUSPECTED</b>, all at Eswick. 
There were also 2 or 3 other specimens which may also be firsts for Shetland but they are currently awaiting confirmation of identification.

<p>

Other unusual records included 150 <B>GREAT BROCADES</b> - 20 in a year in the whole of Britain is exceptional for this species, 12 <b>SCARCE SILVER Y's</b> - 14 in a year in the whole of Britain would be a record number, a <b>BEDSTRAW HAWK MOTH</b> at Norwick, Unst, another <b>GARDEN TIGER</b> at Veensgarth, <b>4 ANGLE STRIPED SALLOWS</b>, a <b>CLOAKED MINOR</b>, and a <b>BLOOD VEIN</b> all at Eswick, and a further <b>3 DOUBLE LOBED</b> - 2 at Norwick and 1 at Eswick.

<p>

Moving on to birds, a <b>GREENISH WARBLER</b> was in the Sumburgh Hotel Garden today, an <b>ICTERINE WARBLER</b> was at Sumburgh Head, at least 2 <b>BARRED WARBLERS</b> were on Whalsay, and a first-summer <b>GLAUCOUS GULL</b> was in Lerwick Harbour.

<p>

On Fetlar, yesterday's Black-headed Bunting could not be relocated but <b>4 BARRED WARBLERS</b>, and a <b>RED-BACKED SHRIKE, ICTERINE WARBLER, and REED WARBLER</b> were seen there.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>12/8/96</h2>

The moth invasion continues with lots of <b>SILVER Y's</b> still evident everywhere. In addition, no less than <b>SIX</b> new species for Shetland were discovered last night - a <b>RED UNDERWING</b> at Eswick, a <b>CLOAKED MINOR</b> and <b>BLOOD VEIN</b> at Fladdabister, <b>2 <i>margarita stiticalis</i></b> (no common name for this one) on Unst, a <b>COMMON CARPET</b> at Eswick, and an <b>ANGLE-STRIPED SALLOW</b> at Skaw, Unst. 

<p>

Butterflies are also still numerous with at least 20 <b>PAINTED LADY's</b> at Sumburgh along with lots of <b>LARGE WHITE's</b>, which were also evident around the town.

<p>

On the birdy front, Fetlar continues to be the place to go at the moment with a female-type <b>BLACK-HEADED BUNTING</b> at Upper Toft today, along with a <b>ROSEFINCH, BARRED WARBLER</b> and <b>2 ICTERINE WARBLERS</b>. Elsewhere there were 2 <b>ICTERINE WARBLERS</b> at Sumburgh along with several <b>PIED FLYCATCHERS</b>, a <b>CURLEW SANDPIPER</b> and <B>RUFF</b> on Unst and <b>4 BARRED WARBLERS</b> on Whalsay.

<p>

Last but by no means least, the regular Sumburgh pod of <b>5 KILLER WHALES</b> were showing well again today.

<p>

What a place!!

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>11/8/96</h2>

Fetlar continues to be the migrant hot-spot of the moment with a <b>ROSEFINCH, BARRED WARBLER, ICTERINE WARBLER, 5 WOOD SANDPIPERS</b> and <b>SPOTTED REDSHANK</b> today. Elsewhere there was a <b>BLACK-TAILED GODWIT, 2 WOOD SANDPIPERS</b> and a <b>WOOD WARBLER</b> at Sumburgh along with a scattering of common migrants.

<p>

<b>SILVER Y</b> moths continued to arrive in smaller numbers again today - it is the largest influx by far of this species.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>10/8/96</h2>

A few autumn migrants were evident today between the rain showers, on Fetlar there was a <b>RED-BACKED SHRIKE, WRYNECK</b> and the <b>ICTERINE WARBLER</b> reported previously is still there.

<p>

The moth invasion has now reduced although there are still a lot of <b>SILVER Y's</b> around.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>9/8/96</h2>

The Fetlar <b>ICTERINE WARBLER</b> is still around the bushes at the RSPB hide at Funzie.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>8/8/96</h2>

The <b>SILVER Y</b> moth invasion has slowed down today although there are still large numbers flying around, especially when the sun comes out! Notable moths discovered during last night included a <b>BEDSTRAW HAWKMOTH</b> at Norwick, Unst (10th recent record) and a <b>DOUBLE LOBED</b> at Baltasound (the first for Shetland).
<p>
Several other migrants moths were evident, mostly of obvious Scandinavian origin, but these were mainly micromoths (less than a centimetre in size), including the second record of <b><i>Agriphila tristella</b></i>, the 3rd-5th records of <b><i>Dioryctria abietella</b></i> and the 7th-8th records of <b><i>Yponomeuta yvonymella</b></i>. Unfortunately most of these micro moths do-not have common names!

<p>

On the bird front several waders are beginning to appear in the isles with single <b>RUFF</b> at north Yell and Tingwall, 210 <b>KNOT</b> at the Pool of Virkie, and 200+ <b>GOLDEN PLOVER</b> at Tingwall. 

<p>

An unseasonal <b>HAWFINCH</b> was also at Sandwick.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>7/8/96</h2>
<a href="silvery.jpg"><img align=right src="silvera.jpg"></a>
The moth invasion continues with the vast majority the <b>SILVER Y</b> <i>Autographa gamma</i> moth. They are usually fairly common migrants to Shetland but not usually in the unprecedented numbers currently being seen. It has been estimated that they were arriving at the staggering figure of around 1,000,000 per hour yesterday (one million!). 
<p>
In addition, more were arriving today! A few scarce species have arrived along with them, most notably a <b>GARDEN TIGER</b> at Fladdabister (the second Shetland record), a <b>GREAT BROCADE</b> at Baltasound (the 7th Shetland record), a <b>BIRD CHERRY ERMINE</b> at Walls (the 5th Shetland record), and a <b>HUMMINGBIRD HAWK-MOTH</b> at Gutcher, Yell (the 13th Shetland record). 
<p>
The isles entomologists are trapping in earnest again tonight as the Silver Y is generally regarded as a strong flying moth and tends to be one of the first species to arrive in an area during a moth invasion, preceeding the invariably much rarer species. This moth influx has not been confined to Shetland, an entomologist on the south coast of England discovered he had at least 3,000 Silver Y moths in his traps last night!
<p>
<i>photo - Silver Y moth - Mike Pennington</i>
<p>

Other interesting news was the hatching of Shetland's first <b>PEACOCK</b> (or peahen) from a clutch of 8 eggs laid by a pair brought to isles by Gilbert Gray at Norwick, Unst. Peacocks are widely kept in captivity, primarily for the stunning display of the males tail feathers as they strut around, they will make an interesting addition to the bird-life of Unst, though how their tail feathers will fare in force 10 remains to be seen!

<P>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>6/8/96</h2>

An <b>ICTERINE WARBLER</b> was near the RSPB hide at Funzie, Fetlar today, and a <b>WRYNECK</b> was on Bressay.

<p>

Many of you will have noticed the plethora of migrant <b>MOTHS</b> and <b>BUTTERFLIES</b> around today. Large numbers have apparently been seen on the continent and with the strong southerly winds quite a few of them have made it to Shetland. Several folk have commented on large 'clouds' of moths and several <b>LARGE WHITE, RED ADMIRAL,</b> and a few <b>PAINTED LADY</b> butterflies around the town. Moth trapping sessions are underway even as I write - I'll let you know the reults tommorrow!

<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>4/8/96</h2>

Four Killer Whales were seen from the m.v. Dunter at Score Point, Bressay at 1230. They comprised a large adult female with a calf and two other medium-sized whales (no large bull present). They were watched for 15 minutes patrolling very close 
inshore - within four feet of the rocks and in water less than 9 feet deep - apparently hunting seals.<BR>
The Large female was seen displaying a skinned seal to the calf as the group swam away quickly towards Voe of Culbinsbrough.
All three adult whales had a notch about half way up the dorsal fin. Apparently the same whales as some seen at the same spot in May (see earlier report).

<p>
<hr>
<p>

