<p>
<hr>
<p>

<h2>25/6/96</h2>

Interesting news of the day was the location by the Seabirds at Sea Team of a <b>'SOFT-PLUMAGED PETREL'</b> 130 km WNW of 
Shetland. The Seabirds at Sea project (funded by the Scottish Natural Heritage, English Nature and other Conservation 
Organisations), systematically records the occurrence of seabirds in the North Sea to build up a picture of their 
distribution at sea, away from breeding colonies. The 'Soft-plumage Petrel' is currently regarded as a generic name relating 
to a group of three different, but superficially very similar species. Only two of these are thought to occur in the 
eastern North Atlantic, and this record is only the 6th of this species group in British and Irish waters.

<p>

The <b>RED-BACKED SHRIKE</b> is still at the Strand Plantation at Gott, central Mainland.

<p>
<hr>
<p>

