<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The Dan Lawn case - Alaska's shame
</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The Dan Lawn case - Alaska's shame
</H1>
<P>
<H2>by Stan Stephens and Jonathan Wills
</H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
<P>
17th December l996
<P>
Governments the world over are always pleading poverty. The State of  Alaska is now so hard up that it has to fire its world-renowned  environmental regulator, Dan Lawn. That hard up, really. Or so it  says. This is highly convenient for the oil industry, who once  described Dan Lawn as 'a jerk and a hard-ass'.
<P><A HREF="dan_lawn.jpg"><IMG SRC="dan_lawns.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=284 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Now, why ever would they think that? Well, Dan Lawn was once the  State's environmental watchman at the Valdez Marine Terminal - the  port that ships oil from the southern end of the Trans-Alaska  Pipeline System, run by the Alyeska Pipeline Service Company (50% owned by BP).
<P>
He was the first Alaska State representative to board the tanker  'Exxon Valdez' in the early hours of Good Friday 1989, a short time  after the ship grounded on Bligh Reef, 25 miles outside the port of  Valdez. The rest is history.
<P>
Dan Lawn is an important part of that history. He had warned the  State that a disaster was imminent. They did not listen. He then  exposed the underlying causes of the disaster. That did not please  some very important people. Under pressure from the oil industry, his  bosses in the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation demoted  him on a spurious charge. One of the world experts on oil spill  prevention was relegated to inspecting garbage dumps and septic  tanks. His union fought for and won re-instatement. The state refused  to obey the court decision. 
<P>
It's not just Dan Lawn who's under attack. The Alaska Department of  Environmental Conservation (ADEC) is indeed short of money and, if  the Alaska State Legislature had their way, there wouldn't be an  ADEC. The department's officials are widely respected in Alaska and  far beyond. There is now serious concern that these committed,  professional people can no longer do their jobs properly, because  they don't have the political backing and the cash that comes with it.
<P>
Dan Lawn had been involved with the regulation, or 'oversight', of  the Valdez Marine Terminal almost from its beginning, nearly 20 years  ago. Before he joined ADEC, he had worked on the construction of the  oil terminal. He carried this knowledge and experience with him as he  began oversight work for the State of Alaska. He started to see  problems developing and promises not being kept in the early eighties.  
<P>
He tried to do oversight but received no backing from his  supervisors. There are letters and non-compliance reports on record  and available for review today. Of course, politics being what they  are, people always protect the hand that feeds them. With industry's  ability and skill to influence everyone through well-designed public  relations, people like Dan Lawn do not have a ghost of a chance to do  a job. In spite of this he continued to try to do oversight, without  any support from the department he worked for or the elected  representatives supposed to be in charge of it.  
<P>
The oil industry attacked Dan instead of solving the problems. In the  late eighties, people who worked for Alyeska, and others in the town  of Valdez, would tear down Dan Lawn as an over-zealous inspector,  trying to get attention by bringing forth problems that they said  weren't really problems.  
<P>
<CENTER><B>Don't fix the problem: attack the messenger </B></CENTER>
<P>
The oil industry has a history, in Alaska as in the North Sea, of  attacking the messenger instead of fixing the problem. Dan Lawn is a  perfect example. They made him the villain, and no one came to his  defence for, once again, they didn't want to disturb the hand that fed them.
<P>
When the 'Exxon Valdez' went aground on Bligh Reef, Dan Lawn blamed  himself for not pushing harder. When he tried to push during the  clean-up efforts, the State removed him from his job and downgraded  his position. The petty incident that led to his firing was a set-up.
<P>
Now Dan Lawn is being laid off from even his downgraded position.  Many in the ADEC-Juneau office have been trying to find a way to get  rid of Dan Lawn for a long time. They finally found a way.
<P>
Today there is no ADEC oversight of the Valdez Marine Oil Terminal  from the Valdez ADEC office.  It is all done by a few visits from  personnel from Juneau or Anchorage, who lack expertise of the history  of the terminal. It is ironic that 85% of the State's income comes  from oil, yet there is very little oversight. In fact the State is  depending on industry to regulate themselves. Dan Lawn was a tough  but fair inspector who was let go because he did his job. Today he  inspects garbage dumps and sewer projects. He is about to be removed  even from that and his position is being eliminated because of lack  of funding.  
<P>
It is unbelievable that a State that has over 20 billion dollars in  reserves cannot supply oversight for the basic needs of its people.   Not only is this an oil run state, but the legislature does not  appear to believe in oversight.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Dumping the problem child</B></CENTER>
<P>
Although the shortages in the ADEC budget are real enough, there are  numerous ways to handle those shortages. It looks like ADEC's  political masters have found a way, with this shortage, to dump their  problem child once and for all.
<P>
When Dan Lawn was removed from his previous job in Valdez and given  his present position, it was challenged and brought before an  arbitrator. The arbitrator ruled in favor of Dan, and the State was  told to give him his old job back.  The Alaska Public Employees  Association (APEA) said in a letter to the State: 'The department  (ADEC), by refusing to honor the arbitrators' decision and award in  Dan Lawn's arbitration, and by reorganizing the department in such a  manner has placed Mr. Dan Lawn in a position of not being able to  ''bump'' horizontally or downward, therefore, laying him off, while  there are numerous employees, ''junior'' to Dan Lawn in DEC service.   We both know the history of the department's treatment of Mr. Dan  Lawn since l987.  I believe this is a continued attempt by the  department to constructively discharge Dan Lawn from his state  service with the DEC.'
<P>
To many people, not just in Alaska this appears almost criminal.  Because politics in the State are what they are, the citizens of  Alaska and Dan will be the losers, and some longtime employees in  Juneau, who work for ADEC and have been looking for a way to get rid  of Dan, will be the winners.  
<P>
When Dan Lawn was removed from his position in Valdez, one in which  he was in charge of the office and oversight of the oil terminal, he  also was denied his ability to use his strong personal belief that  oversight was important both for the health of the industry and  necessary for the protection of the citizens.  
<P>
<CENTER><B>Sidelined AND spied upon </B></CENTER>
<P>
He not only suffered from being chastised by the State of Alaska, but  went through a covert investigation by the oil industry, called the  Wackenhut Investigation.  This was an illegal investigation by a  private security company (who also happen to run security at Sumburgh  Airport in Shetland). It was later examined and deplored by a  Congressional committee. Only the oil industry could get away with it  and they basically did. The State wasn't a bit concerned that this  happened to one of its own employees.
<P>
Since then Dan has formed the Alaska Forum for Environmental  Responsibility, to protect workers from being destroyed, (like the  State is destroying him), to urge State and Federal authorities to do  a better job, and also to do oversight of the industry which the  State was not doing.  
<P>
Dan Lawn's story is very similar to that of many concerned Alyeska  workers who have been mentally and financially destroyed by the  industry they were trying to protect.  
<P>
It is easy to understand the industry's bottom line and arrogant  attitude. It is less easy to understand or excuse the State of  Alaska, which is supposed to represent the citizens and protect them.   When citizens become secondary to the wishes of industry, which  appears to have happened in Alaska, then government has taken a step  backwards. It is obvious the democratic process has backfired and now  represents the few and the rich.  
<P>
<CENTER><B>Bottom-line politics </B></CENTER>
<P>
This kind of outrage is happening everywhere, not just in Alaska.  This world is operating on bottom-line politics. Industry directs  politics through big money and constant lobbying. The citizen and  little guy hasn't a chance.
<P>
Abe Lincoln once said that God must have loved the common man,  because he made so many of us. He also went on to say that those with  special talents are so endowed to help their fellow man - doctors,  lawyers, politicians, etc.  It is obvious now, as it was then, that  most with special talents line their own pockets. Big industry cares  little about human factors. Politicians should, but don't. Dan Lawn  does. In spite of this, Alaska's political leadership has done  everything to harm him.  
<P>
Dan Lawn has been a good friend to Shetland. He came here first in  late 1989, to learn from the people of Shetland how to make a better  job of overseeing the oil industry and carry that message back to  Alaska. He met community leaders, discussed the issues and shared  knowledge on spill prevention with our local authority, Shetland  Islands Council. 
<P>
When the tanker 'Braer' grounded and spilled 85,000 tonnes of oil on  Shetland in January 1993, Dan grabbed a bag and headed for the  airport. Again in his own time and as a private citizen, he acted as  an unpaid adviser to our council during the worst days of that crisis.
<P>
Now he needs our support. He's earned it.
<P>
<HR width=60%>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><CENTER><B>How you can help to right this wrong </B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<B>1</B>  If you would like more details on what has been done to Dan Lawn,  please look at
<BR> <A HREF="http://www.accessone.com/~afersea/danlawn.htm">http://www.accessone.com/~afersea/danlawn.htm</A>
<P>
<HR width=40%>
<P>
<B>2</B>  If you wish to protest at his treatment by the State of Alaska and  demand his reinstatement with full compensation, please e-mail  Governor Tony Knowles of Alaska today, at
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:Office_of_the_Governor@Gov.state.ak.us,afervdz@alaska.net">Office_of_the_Governor@Gov.state.ak.us</A>
<P>
<B>Or write to:</B><BR><UL> Governor Tony Knowles <BR>P.O.Box 110001 Juneau, <BR>Ak.  99811 <BR>Int +907-465-3500 tel <BR>Int +907-465-3532 fax</UL>
<P>
<HR width=40%>
<P>
You may also wish to express your concern to:
<br><UL>
Commissioner Michele Brown <BR>Department of Environmental Conservation <BR>410 Willoughby Avenue, <BR>Suite 105 Juneau,  <BR>Ak.  99801-1795 <BR>Int +907-465-5065  tel <BR>Int +907-465-5070  fax</UL>
<P>
e-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:MBrown@envircon.state.ak.us,afervdz@alaska.net">MBrown@envircon.state.ak.us</A>
<P>
<HR width=40%>
<P>
<B>3</B>  If you would like more information on the work of the Alaska Forum  for Environmental Responsibility, click here  
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.accessone.com/~afersea">http://www.accessone.com/~afersea</A>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><CENTER><B>Thank you for reading this.</B></CENTER></FONT>
<P>





