<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Guest Editorial Comment</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<H4>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">
<BR>
<I>'Great is the Truth, and it will prevail'</I>
<P>
<H1>Time to re-cycle our waste disposal 
</H1>
<H2></H2>
Copyright: <A HREF="mailto:chris.brown@zetnet.co.uk">Chris Brown</A>, Shetland Friends of the Earth
<BR>6th December 1996
<BR><H4>(This article also appears in the print edition of The Shetland Times  <BR>and is reproduced by kind permission of the author)</H4>
</H4>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
</center>
<P>
Christmas 1968 was magical for a 10 year old lad. Apollo 8 had been  around the Moon. The newspapers had colour pictures of the blue Earth  with its wispy white clouds rising over the grey, pockmarked Moon. 
<P><IMG SRC="/pics/earthrise.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=197 HEIGHT=485 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5>
For most people it was when we realised that we all lived on spacecraft  Earth. Just like Apollo 8 on its journey, all we had was what we  carried with us. There was no cosmic grocery store to stop off at to  buy some more oil and a new atmosphere. We either looked after our  environment or our children's children would reap the consequences.  It was about then that the environmental groups started to appear.
<P>
I think of Shetland as some sort of spacecraft, especially when the  weather cuts us off from the rest of the planet. Just like Apollo 8,  we are able to get radio and television messages back and forth but  if we need something from outwith Shetland in an emergency then we  just have to wait until our journey with the weather is over.
<P>
To be honest, this article should not be being written. Back in 1990  the Environmental Act laid down measures that meant the Rova Head  refuse incinerator had to close last weekend. Hindsight will point the finger but in  those five or so years Rova Head's replacement is not sitting ready to  take over. Planning permission still has to be granted and even, if it  is granted this month, a new incinerator is at least two years away.
<P>
This is not so much an 11th hour appeal as an 11:55 call for Shetland  to stop and consider how it wants its waste managed. What do we want  to leave for the future generations that will live on these islands?
<P>
Back in the days of money to burn (pun intended) and less government  support for recycling the Waste to Energy plant with its district  heating system for Lerwick were a good idea; a waste removal scheme  to rank along side the high quality care centres and leisure centres.  But it did not get built and things have changed. The decisions and  reasons of 1990 do not apply anymore.
<P>
Besides money being less available, the government has decided to pay  slightly more than lip service to waste management. Let's be honest  with ourselves: we all create waste and while we pay  the council and water authority to manage it for us we cannot  abdicate the responsibility that we create it in the first place.
<P>
Unlike the Apollo spacecraft, the ones that go to Mars with man on  board will not be able to throw away the waste but will have to mange  and recycle it. This is the position Shetland is in now. In the  recent past we have just thrown away our rubbish and let Rova Head  burn it. Out of sight out of mind. To go down the road of continuing  to do that is to abdicate the difficult decisions of managing our waste. There is such a thing as a waste management hierarchy promoted by  Royal Commissions, the government and the European Union, as well as  environmental groups.
<P>
One of the first things we should be considering is how to reduce our  waste - how not to create it in the first place. Everything we burn   at Rova Head or dump in the ground we buy into Shetland. We pay  freight on all the packaging that comes in.
<P>
We can't stop imports into Shetland so let's reuse as much of the  waste as possible. In the old days bottles used to be refilled. If it is here and we cannot re-use it then let's recycle it into its  original components. Did you know that there is an American company  that produces a material which is used in outdoor clothing which is  made from plastic bottles? 
<P>
Shetland is not so big that community  composting wouldn't work well and there is plenty of land which would benefit. If you cannot do any of the above then this is the time to burn it  and reclaim the energy. But with less waste we do not need such a  large incinerator.
<P>
As you see, the waste management hierarchy in Shetland is upside  down: Let's burn it, let's bring in Orkney's rubbish to burn (are we buying  the rubbish from them or are they paying us to take their rubbish);  let's burn rubbish for the oil companies.
<P>
This last  point is a bit of a touchy one that we in Shetland should  decide with our eyes wide open. Do we wish to become to oil company  waste what Dounreay is to nuclear waste?
<P>
The incinerator as proposed will stifle any true recycling or waste  management in Shetland and it is certainly not a high volume employer  in itself.
<P>
The government has decided that by the year 2000 25% of waste will be  recycled and that 40% of homes with a garden will be involved in  composting. It has also decided that a tax will be put on landfill -   two pounds per tonne for inert waste to seven pounds per tonne for  other waste. This is  to encourage recycling. Incineration reduces the volume you need to  landfill. But this tax wasn't to promote incineration.
<P>
The burning of waste produces waste. That waste still needs to be  dumped and will still incur a landfill tax. Some of that waste is  very toxic and has to be dumped in special landfill. The problem is  that special landfill is not going to remain impregnable. Some  experts say that within 25 years toxins are likely to leak out. So  the more waste we burn the more of this poison we have. So it makes  sense for Shetland's future environmental wellbeing to follow the  waste hierarchy and burn as little as possible, as well as landfill as  little as possible.
<P>
There is a saying from one side of the Pennines or other that  'Where's muck there's brass' and so it is with the oil company waste. Duty  of care is what it is all about. If something is landfilled and later  proves to be a nasty substance that shouldn't be in that landfill  then the duty of care to sort the problem out still lies with the  original owner of the rubbish. 
<P>
On the other hand, if you put the  rubbish through an incinerator the duty of care transfers to owners  of the incinerator. So, yes, there are jobs and money for Shetland in  servicing oil vessels and putting their waste through an incinerator.
<P>
The environmental effects of this though will be here long after the  oil companies have gone and we can see how fickle oil companies are.  Oil companies guarantee nothing in the long term. I assume Shetland  is a long term proposition! The decisions on waste management are not  easy and personally I have difficulty in deciding what  is best. I have a job and would prefer an environmentally sustainable  Shetland. On the other hand I know what it is to not have a job and  realise that if the economy of Shetland is not kept buoyant then the  quality of life for all of us will drop.
<P>
But if I have to fall on one side of the fence or the other then I  think it is against the incinerator as the central plank of our waste  management. Things have changed. Recycling is labour intensive and  markets are opening up for recycled products. Recycling is a long  term option. The government is trying to persuade councils to pay  recycling credits to companies that keep waste from the incinerator  and landfill. Does our SIC have a policy on this yet?. It appears not  but then only 20% of local authorities in the UK have taken up this  pro-recycling option.
<P>
There is money to be made and saved by those with an entrepreneurial  bent. Certain types of paper can fetch up to  80 per tonne, so why  burn it or landfill it?
<P>
My conclusion is that Shetland needs to  plan a sustainable future, not a short term one. We have a small  window of opportunity to decide to do that.
<P>
There is another thing about Apollo 8 that I don't want to see  happening to Shetland. The capsule had splashed down and the US Navy  diver opened the door - and nearly fell off the capsule. The powerful  stench of three men and a week's waste in a small space was a bit  much. Needless to say, the astronauts couldn't smell a thing.
<P>
And why haven't I mentioned the district heating of Lerwick? Well at   400 pounds per metre to install over 11.5 kilometres it was just another  expensive pipe dream. Good for its time. But then that time has gone.
<P>
 




<HR>

<P>
Readers' comments and criticisms are welcomed for publication  
<a href="mailto:editor@shetland-news.co.uk"><img src="/pics/bigemail.gif" align=middle></A>
 
