<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What a way to run a shipping line!
 - Editorial comment
</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>What a way to run a shipping line!
</H1>
<P>
<H2>Editorial comment
</H2>
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
26th November 1996
<P>
We have lived for so long - over two years - with the Government's  proposal to put out to commercial tender the Aberdeen/Orkney/Shetland  shipping services, currently run by <A HREF="http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/websites/pno/">P&O Scottish Ferries</A>, that the  innate absurdity of the idea has become unremarkable. 
<P>
The original list of 19 firms interested in tendering for the  Government-subsidised ferry routes has been whittled down to just  three - P&O, Sea Containers and a putative consortium of Orcargo Ltd  and the publicly-owned Orkney Ferries Ltd, which only appears  interested in running services across the Pentland Firth to Orkney.
<P>
We have no feelings for or against Sea Containers as a company but it  must be evident to the most casual observer that they cannot possibly  have the experience, detailed local knowledge, specialist ships and  friendly, local crews to run our lifeline ferry service.
<P>
It is a very good idea to ensure that the service is run as  efficiently and economically as possible. That is a reasonable and  necessary condition of public subsidy for an operation which can  never be profitable in a purely commercial sense but which is  essential for the profitability of many other enterprises, both in  the islands and on the mainland of Scotland. We hate to sound  unfashionably 'socialist', but that's the way things are.
<P>
The question is whether the Scottish Office has gone about it in the  right way. The indications are that a slavish devotion to the  ideology of the 'free' market has prevented ministers taking a more  sensible and practical approach to the problem of getting value for  the public pound.
<P>
Meanwhile, P&O Ferries are preparing their 1997 brochures for next  year's tourist season, not knowing whether they will still be in the  trade after the Scottish Office finally makes up its mind in February.
<P>
More importantly, they cannot start detailed planning of the three  new ships which must be found if the services to the Northern Isles  are to meet new safety rules which come into effect in the year 2001.
<P>
That is just four years away. This time around, buying an old boat  from somewhere else is not an option, as it was when P&O bought their  existing 'North Boats'. The St Clair, St Sunniva and St Ola are  refurbished 'remoulds' built in the 1970s. Such vessels cannot meet  the new safety standards, however much you spend on them, even if  second-hand ships of the right size were available on the world  market, which they are probably not.
<P>
It will cost around 40 million pounds to build one new ship for the  Aberdeen-Lerwick run alone. To replace all three pasenger/cargo boats  could well cost more than 100 million pounds. This is the single  biggest investment decision for the economy of the Northern Isles in  the next few years. The Government, by its ludicrous insistence on a  time-consuming and ultimately futile tendering exercise, has  knowingly delayed the planning process, which should already have  started if the new boats are to be sailing after 2001.
<P>
It is clear that no commercial firm could possibly consider such a  huge investment, even assuming that a new roll-on/roll-off ferry  built to the new standards would last some 30 to 40 years. The  traffic simply does not warrant it, even if Shetland enters a second  oil boom, as appears increasingly likely. It will have to be mainly a  public investment, just as trunk roads are a public investment. 
<P>
The pressure from Edinburgh (whether or not we are granted a sham of  Home Rule for Scotland) will be for Shetland and Orkney to invest  some of their oil revenues in the project. 
<P>
That pressure should be resisted, for two reasons: essential public  transport networks are and should be a central government  responsibility; and many other communities, not least Aberdeen and  Scrabster, receive substantial economic benefits from the Northern  Isles ferry services. 
<P>
If Shetland Islands Council is to be asked for an investment, so  should councils in Aberdeen, Caithness and, indeed, every part of the  country which trades with the islands. There is no point in asking  Orkney Islands Council for their oil money. They poured much of it  into the Pentland Firth some years ago in a madcap scheme to promote  a 'short-sea crossing' from South Ronaldsay to John o'Groats, as if  the existing 2.5 hour crossing from Scrabster to Stromness were a  problem! Some of the Orkney councillors who voted for that folly are  still, unaccountably, in office.
<P>
There is a deafening silence from the Labour Party on who should pay  for the new boats. As our supposed government-in-waiting, they should  tell us now, and certainly before the General Election, exactly how  they propose to finance the service.
<P>
If we are not very careful (and vocal), we will end up with only two  new 'North Boats', both operating out of Scrabster and one running a  Shetland shuttle service at highly inconvenient and irregular times.  The damage to our export industries, including tourism, will be severe.
<P>
Our air service is already being wrecked by the dictates of the  private market. It is time for a public campaign, led by our MP and  councillors, to stop the shipping lifeline foundering on the same rocks.
<P>
Meanwhile, we look forward to the Prime Minister's no-doubt-imminent  launch of a 'Missiles In Need' appeal, to solicit private charity for  a wholly unnecessary state industry - the Trident nuclear missile  submarine programme.
<P>


<P>
<A HREF="mailto:editor@shetland-news.co.uk">Jonathan Wills </A>




<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright The Shetland News, 1996. 


