</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Editorial Comment</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<H4>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">
<BR>
<I>'Great is the Truth, and it will prevail'</I>
</H4>
<H1> Dounreay's latest radioactive leak <BR>is no surprise

</H1>
Guest Editorial
<BR>
 by Chris Bunyan of  <A 
HREF="http://www.users.zetnet.co.uk/n-base/">N-Base</A>, Lerwick, Shetland

<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
</center>
<P>
 2nd October 1996
<P>
 The radioactive leak from the Dounreay D1206 nuclear reprocessing   plant in Caithness at the weekend, and the subsequent indefinite   shutdown of the installation, is the latest in a catalogue of   accidents and leaks at the site.   
<P>
 Of particular concern is not so much this latest leak - although when   the full details are known it potentially could be serious and  seven gigabecquerals of lethal alpha activity released into the  environment is bad news, however big Dounreay's discharge  authorisations are - but the   state of this plant, which is now about 40 years old with one major   refurbishment.  
<P>
 Environmentalists have long expressed concern that the plant is not   capable of handling the work it is now doing. This is the   reprocessing of over 30 tonnes of core fuel from the now   closed prototype fast reactor (PFR), plus some fuel from the even   older DFR reactor. The plant owners, the UK Department of Trade and   Industry (DTi), are reprocessing this fuel as fast as possible, to   earn money to offset other decommissioning and contamination  clean-up costs.  
<P>
 The DTi have specifically said they want the work done as quickly as   possible, within safety limits etc, etc.  This means the plant is   undertaking the highest workload in its history - 30 tonnes of  spent fuel in five years compared with 30 tonnes over the past three  decades - and it is this which is worrying.       In addition, the reprocessing plant is now managed by a private firm,   W. S Atkins - the folk who managed the building of the Channel Tunnel   - who are also in overall, day-to-day management of the whole site.
<P>
 The cooling system should be completely separate from the 'active'   system in the plant. This could well involve a lengthy shutdown for   the plant, so 'costing' the DTi money. The DTi are known to be    co0ncerned about the maintenance and integrity of the plant and have   told Dounreay not to plan for any more work for the plant when the   PFR and DFR work finishes around 1998/99.  
<P>
 Dounreay wants to fit commercial work in between PFR/DFR work and,   after that work is finished, but DTi has said 'no', they'll have to  wait until they see how things are going because they are concerned  the plant may be too old and suffer a major (expensive) accident.
<P>


<P>
Readers' comments and criticisms are welcomed for publication  
<a href="mailto:editor@shetland-news.co.uk"><img src="/pics/bigemail.gif"></A>
 
