http://www.shetland-news.co.uk:80/editorial/blair.html 194.72.245.173 19970110104411 text/html 17284
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 10:44:14 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 17112
Last-modified: Mon, 14 Oct 1996 00:19:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>'Come on, Tony, light my fire!'or: The Disunited Kingdom
 - Editorial comment
</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>'Come on, Tony, light my fire!'or: The Disunited Kingdom

</H1>
<P>
<H2>Editorial comment
</H2>
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
20th September 1996
<p>



<i>(A version of this article also appeared in The Herald newspaper, published in Glasgow)
<P>
'A poser for Paul Merton: which is the odd one out - Margaret Thatcher, Ted Heath, Salman Rushdie or Tony Blair?'
<P>
'...Yes, Paul, we can see Salman Rushdie's the one with a beard, but that's the wrong answer, unfortunately.'</i>
<P>
Tony Blair is the only one who hasn't visited Shetland yet. Maggie bulldozed her way north just before she became PM in 1979 (she wanted to see where the money came from), Sailor Ted came up in the idle eighties for a chat at the boating club bar, and Salman spent a few days hillwalking here, with a false beard and four minders, during the worst of the Fatwah scare. 
<P>
There is a rumour that even Dr James Gordon Brown MP was once sent to Lerwick by STV, during his previous incarnation as a film director, although there is some doubt about whether he knew where he was. 
<P>
Gordon's chum Tony really should go on a fact-finding mission, and soon, to Scotland's most successful colony. 
<P>
In these islands on the same latitude as Cape Farewell, he'd discover that the stakeholder society he goes on about isn't just a jolly good vision thing dreamed up by Will Hutton, that nice, wise man The Establishment cruelly silenced, by lumbering him with a loopy TV director for his well-meaning but technically unwatchable documentary, 'The State We're In', from the impeccable book of the same name.
<P>
Will Hutton hasn't been here yet either (the air fare from London costs more than a flight to the States for a 20 second film clip) but, if he had, he'd know that Shetland's stakeholder society actually works fine. It has done so for the past 20 years, while everyone else was being mugged by mindless monetarists and no-one north of Gray's Inn Road had heard of Wir Will.
<P>
Tony and Will would find a happy landing after their flight from Aberdeen: unemployment is consistently between 2.5 and 4 per cent; poverty and want rare; social workers are paid to seek out old folk and help them claim their benefits, including an annual Christmas cash bonus from the council; and almost every frail, elderly person has access to sheltered housing, respite care centres and home helps.
<P>
There's more: all children have places in comprehensive state schools which are so good that the idea of private education is laughable; rural primary schools are still open, well-funded and thriving; most pre-school children have access to a playgroup; the health service spends 1,000 pounds a year on every man, woman and bairn; fast, frequent and cheap ferries link the remotest islands at the public expense; the number of Range Rover Discoveries increases in proportion to the mileage of superb roads which, paradoxically, make off-road driving unnecessary (the middle classes will like that one, Tone).
<P>
Sport and the arts are generously subsidised; islands with only a thousand people enjoy leisure centres and heated swimming pools which would make the citizens of Sedgefield puce with envy; community councils receive 11 times the average Scottish funding; voluntary organisations are lavishly supported by mainland standards - at the last count there were over 700 of them for just 23,000 people, including over a dozen religious denominations in a society where sectarianism is unknown; best of all, there's an impressive programme of long-term public investment in local industry.
<P>
Oh, and the council has assets of over 200 million quid, not counting the staff pension fund. It's debt-free (apart from 60 million owed to City loan sharks for building homes for oil workers), and boasts one of the lowest council taxes in the country. Needless to say, the punters never stop moaning about 'da cooncil', particularly since monetarism and 'cuts' have made a belated appearance in the far north.
<P>
In short, every islander has a stake in Shetland, and senses it from before they start school. It isn't a perfect society but it's better than most. Such a pity about the weather, though.
<P>
<i>'Golly, it's windy, Will! Are you sure we didn't catch the flight to Bergen by mistake?'
<P>
'Could be, Tone. The natives certainly speak funny.'
<P>
'It sounds a bit like Norwegian. Ask that taxi driver if he understands English.'</i>
<P>
The parallels with Norway are philosophical as well as linguistic. For, while the rest of Britain watched impotently as the welfare state and public services withered in the lean, mean 80s and 90s, Shetland quietly went about building a small but perfectly formed Scandinavian social democracy. The now disunited Kingdom could have done the same but the Tories preferred to spend their much larger share of the oil revenues on social demolition.
<P>
Shetland's healthy economy and society are not solely the results of the oil money and certainly not because the 26 councillors are a bunch of lefties. The achievements in education, for example, where Shetland knocks spots off mainland toff schools in the exam league tables, have come about because of dogged insistence on the high standards of staffing and funding which, in theory, the state system lays down but no-one seriously expects any more.
<P>
Only a handful of Labour councillors have been elected in Shetland since the oil boom began in the early 70s. Most members of Shetland Islands Council sit as independents. There are a couple of Libdems, a few lapsed, closet Tories and several Shetland Movement Party members who think more home rule would be nice but aren't going to the barricades about it. 
<P>
They all think Tony's Scottish devolution will be a fine thing, if only they can work out a way to stop the Central Belters being even more metropolitan chauvinist than Whitehall.
<P>
This disparate, shifting and sometime bizarre coalition, for all its legendary bureaucracy, personal animosities and procedural bickering, has held together for 25 years during which life for almost everyone in the islands was getting better all the time. 
<P>
There is an underlying ideology, of course, and it is very simple: the greatest good for the greatest number. It is communitarian rather than socialist and embodies a tradition of social solidarity dating back to the late 19th century, when Gladstone's crofting legislation libbed the great lairds and liberated the present generation's ancestors from something very like serfdom. In Shetland they still do not like you getting above yourself. Flaunting personal wealth is bad form. 
<P>
Similar traditions of togetherness and community spirit still thrive in Scandinavia, Alaska and northern Canada. They survive, without Shetland's access to funds, in many parts of Scotland.
<P>
Tony Blair's task is to revive this ancient, civilised instinct with his not terribly new ideas on the 'social' market. He is supposed to be enthusing us with the attractive and fairly obvious idea that governments exist (were, indeed, invented) for the purpose of controlling the excesses of the unregulated market, for the benefit of all.
<P>
The view from Shetland, or at least my view from Shetland, is that he and my former untidy flatmate Gordon Broon are making a hash of it. They may win the election but they are not winning the hearts and minds. Their utterances are dull, mechanical, timid and repetitive - particularly sad in the case of young Broon, once one of Scotland's wittiest men.
<P>
The Labour leader is a frightened man, when he ought to be a bold and inspiring one. Like the reviled Stalinist barons of prehistoric Strathclyde Region, he appears not to trust himself to persuade the punters. Instead of debate, we are given public relations.
<P>
Maybe he doesn't trust them to be persuaded and thinks it safer to pander to their imagined prejudices. But are the voters really so thick that they can't and won't understand reasoned political argument, attractively presented? I doubt it. 
<P>
Take the leader-writers' big issue, income tax, for example: even the dimmest of wits can understand that PAYE and Schedule D are not just some mindless impost visited by vengeful authority on the hapless worker by hand and brain, even though it may feel like that sometimes. 
<P>
Much of our inland revenues are actually spent on useful things which benefit us all, like education, social security, roads and, once upon a time, railways. It isn't all money down the drain, rather an investment in all our futures - and a way of redistributing wealth. Oh my God, what have I said? Redistribute wealth! Perish the thought!
<P>
Just as important as the level of our income tax (which is actually rather low by Scandinavian standards) is whether we get value for money. That seems a legitimate subject for political debate but it takes second place to endless media speculation about possible tax levels to be set in Gordon's broon study at the Treasury.
<P>
If this debate did take place, I'd hazard a guess that some ideas labelled 'extremist', 'leftist' and even 'revolutionary' over the past two decades would prove to have a surprising amount of popular support, when folk saw how much money could be diverted to better ends.
<P>
We obviously don't get value for money from Trident, because it's useless as a defensive and unthinkable as an offensive weapon. It soaks up cash which could and should be used to create a sensible, cheaper defence system for an archipelago lying off the coast of Europe. This would include an effective navy, first-rate air defences (minus the Euro-fighter), better surveillance of terrorist suspects, and a properly funded and trained TA, to make the country untenable by an invader. What do we hear from Tony on these interesting and expensive topics? Not a dicky bird.
<P>
Nor is the cost of a military force in Northern Ireland value for money. The prods and provos obviously hate each others' guts and will continue to do so until sectarian education is eradicated. So the sensible answer could well be partition, with a United Nations force to separate the murderous swine on both sides and help the peaceable majority in the middle get on with business as normal. But anyone who suggests such a sensible and potentially popular solution is ridiculed and disowned as a loony Bennite.
<P>
Harriet Harman and her Great Leader and Teacher might not agree with me, but I suspect there's a lot of political mileage in serious education reform. Not just in cutting off state subsidies to private schools and using the cash to make the state system the best in Britain, but also in telling parents there's no way the state can continue paying for sectarian (sorry, single-denomination) education.
<P>
I rather fancy rather a lot of voters would agree that Britain (and especially the north of Ireland and the west of Scotland) would be a less intolerant, fairer society if taxes for education went only to secular, state schools. If people are daft enough to pay more for the privileges from so-called 'public' schools, or for Protestant, Catholic or Moslem education, that's up to them. 
<P>
If asked (and I won't be) I'd say any private school hiring a young teacher should repay the Treasury the cost of their teacher training, but that's probably an 'extremist' line and I may have to wait a decade or two to hear it discussed at the hustings (let alone hear a Labour leader proposing the abolition of the Monarchy).
<P>
Even within the present miserly education budget, we'd see some changes if we spent the money in a different way, let alone shifted some loot from subsidies for absentee lairds to graze too many sheep on Scotland's overgrazed hills, and even more subsidies for them to plant trees. But on education, to say nothing of rural policy, I'm becoming an embarrassment to the remains of the party I've supported through thick and (mostly) thin these 30 years past, so let's change the subject before I decide to give the Scottish National Party my little pencilled cross at last.
<P>
What about health? Well, yes, indeed. What the public really wants is more people on the dole - the thousands of functionally  illiterate, overpaid, underworked bureaucrats who've infiltrated the National Health Service since 1979 and now clog it up with their highly inappropriate market ideology. Let them sweep, or beg in, the streets, says I. They even refer to the NHS as 'the healthcare industry'. The NHS isn't an industry. It's a service. Nurses, doctors and patients are sick to death (sometimes literally) of what's going on. Oh dear, I'm being embarrassing again...
<P>
Housing? Dare we ask our Labour candidates about the popular idea of giving councils money and power to start building again, or to subsidise young folk to build their own homes? Probably not. It would use income tax sensibly, provide jobs, bring in more income tax and help the economy. Instead, the market will provide. Will it, hell! (Will it , Hutton)
<P>
As for Europe, I still hope to hear Tony Blair explaining that talk of 'restoring national sovereignty' is a charade. For more than 20 years true sovereignty has been exercised globally by financial markets run as casinos. There can be no accommodation with the sharks who operate solely for their own, short-term benefit at other people's expense. The only hope of bringing the collapsing world banking and financial system under democratic control is through organisations like the European Union, acting in concert with other major power blocs. Those who argue otherwise are sad, mistaken and, arguably, unpatriotic.
<P>
Alas, Tony is not about to get into water this deep. He surfs on to victory, on a wafer-thin manifesto with no tax commitments, no hostages to fortune, no consultation and negative intellectual equity.
<P>
Rather than bravely arguing the case for reform, he goes around reassuring the better off that they will be even better off under Labour, and shamelessly courting the Stock Market gamblers who helped Thatcher to privatise and ruin Britain.
<P>
This sticks in the craw of the small but imperfectly formed Shetland Labour Party. Like the rank and file everywhere, they will canvass with heavy hearts and a certain amount of embarrassment, albeit for an excellent candidate, a local man who knows the Labour machine inside out - he used to work for This Great Party Of Ours in Strasbourg - and is no mean country singer forebye.
<P>
We want a crusade, with country music if possible. We have a public relations campaign with jingles. That is why Labour, nationally, may only just scrape home in constituencies where the Libdems, Gladstone's heirs, can pose as the real radicals.
<P>
In Shetland and Orkney (that's the other archipelago, where all the Tories used to be until the BSE crisis ruined the beef farmers) Labour's aim will be to take second place to the amiable, careful Jim Wallace, and to stuff into third or preferably fourth place Mr Hope Vere Anderson (chief of the Clan Anderson, indeed!) - the hapless parachutist whom Conservative Central Office has just dropped on the constituency.
<P>
Shetland has already made one sacrifice which should help Chancellor Broon to balance the books of a minority administration. The council has given the oil industry a deal worth at least 50 millions over the next 25 years, by agreeing a deal to cut operating costs at the Sullom Voe oil terminal. There will be no more royalties for Shetland's public coffers. The nest-egg we have already will have to see us through my dotage and beyond.
<P>
Young Broon's nest egg will be correspondingly a little larger, assuming he doesn't intend yet another giveaway for the oil companies, now busily developing the vast new oil and gas fields in the Atlantic, west of Shetland.
<P>
Our sacrifice will have been worth it if he spends the money on social reconstruction nationwide, rather than the lengthening dole queues which may be expected if Labour's milk-and-water prospectus is voted through on the payroll vote of identikit MPs in suits.
<P>
Why do they all wear ties, by the way? From this distance, they look as if they are for tethering the tribunes of the people in their stalls.
<P>
<i>O tempora! O Mores!</i>
<P>



<P>
Jonathan Wills 




<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright The Shetland News, 1996. 


