<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - MP asks Government to suspend ferry franchising </title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>MP asks Government to <BR>suspend ferry franchising </H1>
<P>
<H2></H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=+1>This is the full text of Jim Wallace MP's letter and detailed  comments to Lord James Douglas-Hamilton MP, Minister of State at the  Scottish Office</FONT></I>
<P>
 Dear James,
<P>
May I take this opportunity to acknowledge the letter which I received  from Mr. W.R.J. McQueen, Head of Transport and Local Roads Division of  the Scottish Office Development Department, inviting me to comment on the  draft service specification for ferry passenger services to Orkney &  Shetland. As well as replying directly to Mr. McQueen, I thought I should  send you a copy of my response, as well as some additional comments and  observations.
<P>
Firstly, in replying in what I hope is a constructive manner, I am in no  way conceding that the Government has done the right thing in abandoning  the general freight subsidy. I have rehearsed the arguments with you, the  Secretary of State and officials often enough without repeating them  here. Suffice to say, for the present, that I believe the freight service  is as much a lifeline service as the passenger service, and both should  be treated as such. And accordingly, insufficient consideration has been  given to the possibility of  an extension of the franchising mechanism,  for example to include the service between Kirkwall and Invergordon. 
<P>
Nor is there anything in the specification which addresses, in a  meaningful way, the case for new replacement vessels. There is a  reference to how bidders would propose to fill the gap until newly built  ships are commissioned for service, but that only seems to make new  vessels less likely. Given that this whole review was sparked off by P &  O s concerns over the cost of replacement vessels, it is astonishing that  the government has been so vague on this issue. Indeed, when I, together  with council representatives from Orkney and Shetland,  met Michael  Forsyth in September last year, he indicated that whilst replacement  vessels couldn't necessarily be stipulated in a contract, bidders could  be asked to indicate what thought was being given to replacement vessels  if they were to win a further tender period. 
<P>
Obviously, if the winning bid involves new ships, that question may be  more readily answered. However, with the current and projected profile of  the shipping market, I don t think it is unreasonable to think ahead. I  must stress that my constituents have accepted refurbished second hand  vessels for years. Many of them have performed well, but it has not  escaped our notice how often the Hebrides are served with new purpose  built ships. It is disappointing, therefore, that so little attention  appears to have been given to this issue.
<P>
These are important issues, and ones which I shall continue to press.  Obviously I want to see the return of a government, after the forthcoming  election, which will be sympathetic to these matters. Whatever one s  political standpoint, the possibility remains that the outcome of the  election could have an effect on policy in this area. (In addition to  addressing the foregoing points, a different government might wish to  permit CalMac to participate in the tendering process). I am therefore  asking you to consider whether or not it would be fairer to suspend the  tendering process to allow potential bidders an opportunity to take into  account any possible change in government and government policy which  might arise. 
<P>
There are further points which I wish to raise in connection with the  introduction of the passenger service franchise. 
<P>
Because the figure of  7.6 million has been negotiated with P & O as a  provisional subsidy for 1996/97, there has been an assumption that the  arrangement will terminate on 31st. March. Indeed I note in the draft  service specification, there is a reference to the existing arrangement  expiring in April 1997. However, even on your provisional timetable, the  new contract is not expected to be awarded until the end of April. 
<P>
Can you confirm when exactly the present agreement expires, and whether  arrangements have been made (and if so, on what terms) to extend the  existing  arrangement beyond the expiry date? This has particular  relevance if a company other than P & O wins the contract. Surely you  cannot be suggesting that they could be awarded the contract on 30th.  April and be expected to start sailings on 1st. May. Where will that  leave passenger bookings? Clarification of the position in what might be  described as the transitional period is required at an early date.
<P>
The government has also promised a consultation paper on bulk freight.  When will this be available? Given that its contents may also have some  bearing on the calculations of potential tenderers, does this not add a  further ground for deferring the final stages of the tendering process?
<P>
I look forward to hearing from you
<P>
(Jim Wallace MP)
<P>
<PRE>

</PRE>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Draft Service Specification <BR>for Passenger Ferry services to the Northern  Isles</B>
<BR>Response from Jim Wallace MP</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
I am grateful for the opportunity to respond to this draft specification.  In my covering letter to the Minister of State, Lord James Douglas -  Hamilton MP, I have expressed a number of reservations about the  government s overall policy, and have suggested that consideration should  be given to suspending the tendering process pending the outcome of the  general election and better particulars being made available regarding  the consultation process on the carriage of bulk freight.
<P>
<CENTER><B>General</B></CENTER>
<P>
In common with some others who have responded, I am concerned that there  is a bias towards the present operator. This is not intended as a  criticism of  P & O Scottish Ferries, but an important observation on  what is meant to be an open tendering process.
<P>
In <B>paragraph 6</B> the Scottish Office makes it the responsibility of  prospective operators to forecast likely future traffic volumes and  revenue for all traffic. The information on current up to date figures  can only be available to the existing operator, thereby giving them a  distinct advantage.
<P>
In <B>paragraph 18</B> reference is made both to the size of vessels employed by  the current operators and  the speeds obtained by the current operator of  the service . This information is self evidently known to the current  operators, but it is surely invidious for other tenderers to have to  approach a competitor bidder for detailed information.
<P>
In <B>paragraph 24</B>, a prospective operator who wishes to use newly built  ships is expected to fill the gap. If, all other things being equal, such  a bid is the most attractive option, the Government should make provision  for the interim period to be filled. In this way there can be no  discrimination against an operator wishing to use new build, as opposed  to the existing operator who, otherwise would presumably enjoy the  advantage of continuity of service. 
<P>
These are important points which must be addressed if the tendering  process is to enjoy public confidence. Consultees should be advised of  steps taken to create even-handedness among bidders before final service  specifications are issued.
<P>
<B>Paragraph 2</B> Is it intended to exclude unaccompanied cars from the ambit of the  subsidy?
<P>
<B>Paragraph 5</B> As already indicated, the timetable should allow for some consideration  by potential operators of the content of the consultation document on  bulk freight, including definitions of what may be covered under these  specific arrangements.
<P>
<B>Paragraph 7</B> - Frequency of Service As efforts are being made to extend the tourist season in Orkney, three  daily sailings should apply from April/May to October. During the winter  months, it may not be necessary for two daily sailings on a Sunday.
<P>
In the case of Shetland, the requirements of the salmon and fishing  industries almost certainly require 6 daily sailings around the calendar.  Ideally these should be night sailings to allow for the day's produce of  white fish and salmon to be transported as fresh as possible, as well as  for passenger convenience.
<P>
If  consideration is being given to an Orkney only bid, the absence of  any provision of an Aberdeen/Stromness/Lerwick service should not  disqualify it.
<P>
<B>Paragraph 9</B> - Orkney/Shetland only service I welcome the fact that consideration is being given to proposals which  may be directed towards serving the specific needs of each island group.  However, tenderers wishing to serve Orkney or Shetland only should not be  required to identify savings resulting from operating an integrated  network, when such a proposal would not be part of their bid.
<P>
<B>Paragraphs 10 - 12</B>: Carriage of Livestock I welcome the requirement that potential operators must make provision  for ensuring sufficient capacity during the main livestock shipment  period, and that the operator will be responsible for ensuring a  satisfactory standard of service.
<P>
Passengers travelling between Stromness and Scrabster have had to put up  with a decreasing amount of livestock on board, which has been to their  comfort and advantage. It would be a retrograde step if the new  arrangements did not ensure continuation of this trend.
<P>
<B>Paragraph 13</B> - Hazardous cargoes There is little indication of the frequency or volume of such cargoes.  This should be made available to those tendering. Is it necessary for  hazardous freight to be carried with passengers or can some goods be  carried on non - passenger schedules?
<P>
<B>Paragraphs 14 - 18</B>:Vessel specification Operators should be asked to state the age of the vessel. Option 1 in paragraph 16 envisages a one or two ship configuration for  the Lerwick/Aberdeen service. Paragraph 14 -rightly in my view -suggests  that there would be difficulties in maintaining a one boat service to  Shetland. I support a two boat option. Overall option 2 has attractions  provided that there was adequate guarantee of meeting required freight  capacity for farmed salmon and fish at the height of the tourist season.
<P>
Whilst the specification refers to a percentage of  passenger berths,  nothing is said about the berths. The standard of berth accommodation  should be specified, with adequate provision of  quality accommodation to  attract tourists and to provide tolerable conditions in rough winter  crossings. A significant and specified percentage should have en suite  toilets and showers. There should also be a requirement for a proportion  of double berths and four berth cabins for families.
<P>
There should also be a certain proportion of berths equipped for disabled  people.
<P>
There should be provision of reclining seats for those not taking berths.
<P>
<B>Paragraph 19</B> - Business plans In terms of passenger pricing, it should be made clear whether journeys  originating in the Northern Isles will have lower rates for cars and  passengers than northbound journeys. Specific reference should also be  made to the availability or otherwise for reduced fares for children, and  concessionary fares for pensioners, students and other categories of  travellers.
<P>
In fixing maximum rates for all categories of traffic, the government  must have regard to the actual prevailing rates, rather than advertised  rates. It would be advantageous if the government could establish   maximum rates at the outset, so that all potential bidders have notice of  these. It is acceptable to increase these rates in line with the retail  price index.
<P>
The government should reserve to itself the power to fix minimum rates if  examples of predatory pricing are established.
<P>
The quality of the service should also include the operator s on-shore  operation, including local booking facilities, lairage, storage etc.
<P>
The Consultation process should include a reasonable cross section of the  islands  population as well as the local authority. Consultative meetings  should take place at least twice per annum, and may be convened ad hoc by  either the operator or the islands council.
<P>
The quality targets set are too low. After making allowances for weather,  the  failure  rate proposed in the specification, both in terms of  cancelled sailings and delays would permit a poorer service than at  present on the Stromness/Scrabster run.
<P>
The target for both operation and punctuality should be at least 98%  (excluding delays etc. attributable to severe weather).
<P>
Complaints should be acknowledged within three working days and responded  to within three weeks.
<P>
As this is a franchised service, the Scottish Office should also set out  its proposals for monitoring the franchise operation and for dealing with  complaints from service users or community representatives.
<P>
<B>Paragraph 20</B> - Contingency costs On balance, I should favour a further agreement between the parties to  take account of additional marine safety requirements during the contract  period.
<P>
<B> Paragraphs 23 -24</B> : Commencement I believe the proposed arrangements are disadvantageous to a potential  operator offering new build capacity. Equally, it is unrealistic to  expect a bidder other than the current operator to be awarded the  contract on 30th. April and start sailings on 1st. May. The Scottish  Office must provide more details of how it intends to cover a  transitional period, including transfer of bookings in the event of a new  operator taking over, and, in any event, it should the arrangements with  the present operator for any continuing interim operation after 1st.  April 1997.
<P>
<B>Paragraphs 28 - 29</B> Comprehension of and fluency in the English language should be a  pre-requisite of crews used.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Other matters</B></CENTER>
<P>
It is recommended that the specification, particularly with regard to  quality requirements, should ask potential operators to indicate what  standards of catering they intend to provide; what provision they intend  to make for the provision of cots and changing facilities for infants;  what medical/first aid facilities will be available on board and whether  it will continue the current small parcel service.
<P>
In addition the specification should stipulate adequate service  requirements for disabled people. Indeed, in a letter to me dated 18th.  April 1996, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton stated that  ...we will wish to  include in the final specification an explicit requirement that  prospective service bidders should take full account of the needs of  disabled people when they submit their tender proposals. It is a matter  of profound regret that there is no reference to this in the draft  specification. I expect confirmation that this will be remedied before  the final specification is sent out and that there will be proper  reference to serving the needs of disabled people (including access to  ferries) over and above statutory requirements.
<P>
I should also wish to draw your attention to  a draft Ferry Customers'  Charter which Shetland Liberal Democrats submitted in May 1995. It  contains a number of points regarding customer service which I would  ask to be considered.
<P>



<P>
<HR>


