<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Hurried Euro-note design missed islands
</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Hurried Euro-note design missed islands
</H1>
<P>
<H2>by Jonathan Wills
</H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P><CENTER>(This feature also appears in <I>The Scotsman Newspaper</I>)</CENTER>
<P>
17th December 1996

<P>
The Austrian designer who left Orkney, Shetland and many other  islands off the map on the new Euro banknote has apologised for  ruffling insular feathers.
<P>
A spokesman for Robert Kalina, chief designer at the Austrian Central  Bank in Vienna, said it was all a mistake. He had been 'in a hurry'  to complete his winning designs in less than six months: 
<P>
'It's not a deliberate insult. Mr Kalina just took a clip-art map off  his personal computer. It's only a draft. You can rest assured the  islands will be on the note when it goes to the printers,' he said.
<P>
The European Monetary Institute in Frankfurt confirmed that plates  for the 14 Euro-notes could and would be changed before they are  engraved late next year.
<P>
Islanders have long been accustomed to the place-ism of metropolitan  chauvinist mapmakers - who customarily put Orkney and Shetland in  little boxes in the Moray Firth and make them look smaller than they are.
<P>
Some years ago staff at BBC Radio Shetland retaliated with a T-shirt  showing a huge map of Shetland. The rest of the UK was in a tiny box  in the bottom left-hand corner.
<P>
Last night (MON) Mr Kalina (44) was on holiday at a secret location,  before starting work in the New Year on what could be the last  Austrian Schilling notes to be issued before the single currency. 
<P>
His office could not say if he might be visiting one of the Greek or  Spanish islands which he had also left out: 'He's delighted that his  design won the competition but time was short and he  concentrated on  the detail of his theme of bridges across Europe.'
<P>
The unintended slight to Scotland's Northern Isles could easily be  righted, Mr Kalina's spokesman said, but to include every last island  in the Euro-archipelago would create practical problems. The Euro  notes would have to be a foot (30cm) across to show the French  Caribbean island of Reunion or Spain's Canary Islands in the right  position and to scale, unless the European Monetary Institute planned  to issue a free magnifying glass to everyone in the Continent.
<P>
'I suppose we could print Reunion on a separate small piece of  paper,' he giggled, nervously.
<P>
Mr Kalina's oversight pushed predictable buttons in the north. Not  all were amused. Highlands and Islands Euro-MP was first off the mark  yesterday: 'Rest assured that all the islands will be firmly on the  Euro-map if Winnie has anything to do with it,' a spokesman in her  office said. 'It's likely that she and Dr Allan McArtney MEP will be  raising this in the European Parliament and standing shoulder to  shoulder with fellow islanders.'
<P>
Shetland councillor Alastair Goodlad, on a business trip to Norway  yesterday, said: 'If the British can leave us off their weather maps,  it's not surprising if Europe leaves us off the banknotes. But they  should remember Shetland is where the oil comes from, and the fish.'
<P>
Dr Goodlad, who has salmon farming and fish processing interests,  mused that there could be advantages if Europe did forget Shetland  was there: 'We could avoid all those Euro-regulations but still get  the money. Maybe we should get some extra cash for being left out?'
<P>
Charlie Simpson of the Shetland Fiddlers Society echoed Dr Goodlad's  comments: 'The weather forecast maps often show us 60 miles too far  south. Even if most of Lapland is now in the European Union, it makes  you wonder if Santa will be able to find his way here.'
<P>
Shetland may have been left off the Euro-map but it is still in the  money. Europe has played Santa Claus to Shetland over 23 years,  pouring a total of 200 million pounds into hundreds of projects. From  being one of the few places to vote against Common Market membership  in 1975, Shetland has become enthusiastic about the European Union.  Councillors regularly visit Brussels and have taken a lead in the  clumsily-named Conference of Peripheral Maritime Regions (CPMR),  which meets in various exotic locations, usually with good beaches. 
<P>
Once the butt of local taunts about Euro-jaunts to Reunion and  Teneriffe, the CPMR is now seen as an important lever for promoting  the islands' concerns about fishing policy and marine conservation.  Councillor Drew Ratter, chairman of Shetland Islands Council's  development committee, is a noted supporter of a 'Europe of the  regions' and only last week contrasted the helpful attitude of  Brussels with the British Government's obstruction. Brussels, he  says, is more understanding and easier to deal with than  Tory-dominated Edinburgh and London.
<P>
Beneath the hilarity over the fudged banknote design lie more serious  issues. The furore came at a bad time for Euro-enthusiasts, adding  useful ammunition to Euro-sceptics looking for a stick to beat  Brussels (and John Major) in last night's Commons vote on European  fishing policy. 
<P>
There is a big following in Shetland for the Save Britain's Fish  campaign, which wants the UK to pull out of the Common Fisheries  Policy, although the majority in the Shetland Fishermen's Association  still backs reform rather than revolution. Critics like Skipper  Magnus Stewart of the trawler 'Defiant' say fish catch quotas and  other Euro-regulations are bureaucratic, unworkable, cause enormous  waste of edible fish, and oblige fishermen to lie to fishery  inspectors in order to make a living.
<P>
The 'realists', like Councillor Ratter and fishermen's association  secretary John Goodlad, say many other islands around Europe have  similar problems with the policy, whether landlocked Austrians have  mapped them or not. Mr Ratter now chairs the CPMR's fisheries  committee, which hopes to influence the Council of Ministers.  Shetland's most urgent demands are for an end to 'flagships' -  foreign boats which register under the Red Ensign to gain access to  British fish; for local control of fishing effort; and restoration of  subsidies to modernise the fleet. 
<P>
More island jobs depend, directly or indirectly, on catching,  processing and farming fish than on oil. As oil declines, fish  becomes even more vital to the Shetland economy. But while fishermen  rail against Europe's profligacy, ignorance and inefficiency, the  companies who process and market the seafood want very much to be  friends with Europe. Europe means customers for smoked salmon and  herring fillets. It also means grants for the new factories to meet  those European hygiene rules. 
<P>
Whether Shetland appears as a microdot on European banknotes or not  is irrelevant to factory owners; and to Lerwick Harbour Trust which  has just won a big Euro-subsidy for an eight million pounds port  development scheme; and to Shetland Islands Council, with its smaller  than expected but still welcome grant from Brussels for a new waste  incinerator. As long as the Euro-honey continues to flow, the money  can look as funny as you like.
<P>
Some time in the early 21st century, there will be a grant  application for a Euro-bridge or tunnel linking Lerwick to the island  of Bressay - allowing further expansion of the port of Lerwick. That  project, and all the other prospects of bundles of Euros, is why the  Save Britain's Fish campaign is doomed.
<P>
Never noted for following their leaders, Shetlanders also voted  against Scottish devolution in 1979. As with Europe, the position has  softened since, although there is a residual fear that a Scottish  Parliament will be dominated by Central Belters even more patronising  and place-ist than Whitehall <B><I>('Ye're frae the Shetlands, eh, son? Dae  youse aw still speak Gaelic up there in Stornoway?'). </I></B>
<P>
Whether Scotland stays in the UK or not is a topic of conversation,  certainly, but hardly a burning issue outside the small local circles  who fully understand the Scottish Office Revenue Support Grant and  Special Island Needs Allowance formulae. Of much greater concern is  that Shetland stays in Europe, whatever those people on the big  island in the little box in the bottom left-hand corner decide to do. 
<P>
This is not solely because the islands have been trading with  Holland, Germany, France and Spain for hundreds of years. We all have  our price. Shetland's is that 200 million pounds (or 266 million  Euros) in grants since we joined against our will, all those years ago.
<P>
We don't care if there's a single currency, as long as we get our share of it.
<P>







<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Jonathan Wills, 1996. 


