<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - BP come clean on Foinaven pollution risk
</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>BP come clean on Foinaven pollution risk
</H1>
<P>
<H2>by Jonathan Wills
</H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P><CENTER>(a version of this article also appears in the Aberdeen newspaper <I>The Press & Journal</I>)</CENTER>
<P>
16th December 1996

<P>
BP's fast-track, frontier philosophy has given Foinaven, Britain's first Atlantic oilfield, a very high media profile. The find lies in the deepest, roughest water ever tackled by oil producers on the UK Continental Shelf.
<P>
If something goes wrong out there, the offshore loading operation 200 km west of Shetland has the potential to drop BP and partners Shell in some very deep public relations water. For on the best of days there is no way to contain or recover more than about 10 per cent of any spillage in the wild, open ocean. Sensitive shorelines and fishing grounds are two or three days downwind in average winter weather.
<P>
If Foinaven oil ever hits the coast of Caithness, Sutherland, Orkney, Shetland - or even the Western Isles and Faroe - the airwaves will be loud with the noise of fishermen, fish farmers and nature lovers saying 'We told you so'.
<P>
BP value their clean, Green image and have gone to unprecedented lengths to reassure the public that they have a handle on the environmental problems. In 20 years reporting on the North Sea oil industry I have never seen an oil company publish anything quite like BP's 83-page 'Environmental Assessment' and five-volume oilspill contingency plan for Foinaven and the other 'Atlantic Frontier' developments.
<P>
BP project managers' tactics for dealing with the environmentalists' concerns over Foinaven are interesting. At first they made the usual assurances but failed to back them all up with facts and argument. When that failed to satisfy organisations like the RSPB, Shetland Islands Council and the Shetland Salmon Farmers' Association, BP stopped hiding behind PR waffle and sent their environmental team back to do some serious science. This showed that many of the concerns were well-founded. A 'peer review group' of university and industry experts told the company they should have paid more attention to the criticisms and been more open to start with.
<P>
Throughout the two-year process of negotiation and consultation with Orkney and Shetland, BP have deliberately avoided holding traditional public meetings where their critics might have put them on the spot. Instead, they hosted 'roadshow' exhibitions where several hundred members of the public came along for 'one-to-one' chats with senior managers.
<P>
The antagonisms of debate were thus avoided in the bid to build a consensus. The result is that Orkney and Shetland are now giving BP the benefit of the remaining doubts, but the islands councils can be expected to go ballistic, under public pressure, if the environmental promises are not kept. Protest has been muted because islanders want the jobs. Some of them have already been hired. But all are conscious that hundreds more jobs in other local industries are at risk if the oil hits the beaches and/or the TV screens.
<P>
BP and Shell have set up and funded an environmental 'forum' where fishermen, fish farmers, birdwatchers, university scientists, councillors and civil servants can discuss the issues. The forum has fewer powers and a smaller budget than the long-established Shetland Oil Terminal Environmental Advisory Group (SOTEAG) and does not plan to commission its own research. But, unlike SOTEAG, it will publish the minutes of its meetings and may even hold public sessions in the future.
<P>
Following the lead of BP's 50-per-cent-owned Alyeska Pipeline Service Co in Alaska after the 'Exxon Valdez' catharsis, the company has teamed up with Shetland's North Atlantic Fisheries College to run a training programme for fishermen and fish farmers, who will help to deploy booms and skimmers if the worst does happen. 
<P>
The heavily revised 'Environmental Assessment' and spill plans are more impressive documents than the much-criticised first drafts. They are better researched and referenced, contain serious scientific argument backed by facts, and are a far cry from the anodyne, unsubstantiated assurances sadly so common in the oil industry's past dealings with the environmental lobby. 
<P>
The most hardened critic now has to admit that BP and their 28-per-cent partners Shell really have listened to criticism and tried to do something about it. And the documents are astonishingly frank about the unsolved problems.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Serious problems reman</B></CENTER>
<P>
The trouble is that there may not be a lot they can do about some of the concerns raised in their own documents: accidental oil spills; clean-up capability; pollution by waste water and chemicals; air pollution; and the potential smothering of seabed life by drilling muds and rock cuttings.
<P>
Although Foinaven is a fairly heavy crude, it does respond to chemical dispersants - at least in laboratory tests. That is the good news. The bad news is that dispersants will only work between six and 14 hours after a spillage, depending on sea conditions and temperature, and in winter all of that 'dispersion window' could be night-time.
<P>
Dispersants are the preferred first defence, with the balance of scientific opinion consulted by BP saying the adverse effects on marine life are likely to be minor and short-lived. It is noticeable that, following concerns in Shetland, the developers have considerably beefed up the spraying capabilities based at the oilfield, to ensure a swift response to spills of up to 50 tonnes. 
<P>
A slick of spilt Foinaven oil will be fairly persistent after the chance of using dispersants has passed. Some will evaporate but in calm weather it could be weeks before the sea disperses most of it - ample time for slicks to reach seabird colonies, fishing grounds and fish farms up to 300km away. BP's environmental managers are uncomfortably aware that the 'Exxon Valdez' slicks did some of their worst damage three weeks and 500km from the site of the disaster. In that incident, dispersant spraying was too late, because of organisational foul-ups and a fierce row about its effects on fish and other wildlife.
<P>
Here the notorious weather of the West Shetland Continental Slope comes to the company's aid. Computer calculations in the Environmental Assessment show that the natural dispersion rate of a slick will vastly increase as the wind rises. The worse the weather, the faster a spill will reach land - but the more likely it is to be broken up.
<P>
If pollution reaches Orkney or Shetland, the 'Atlantic Frontier Oilspill Contingency Plan' comes into play. It is a massive document, detailing every bay and beach where oil containment, recovery and clean-up could be attempted and listing all the booms, skimmers, absorbent matting, boats, storage tanks and paraphernalia - including buckets and spades - that would be needed. There is a lot of emphasis on chains of command and information.
<P>
A key tactic will be to try to divert the oil away from sensitive areas, although most of the 2,000 mile coastline of the two archipelagos could be described as such and it is clear that Mother Nature would have to clean up most of the shoreline. Maps of each location show where booms could be deployed in fair weather, hopefully steering slicks towards recovery equipment and 'sacrificial' beaches. 
<P>
Experience elsewhere strongly suggests that multiple layers of boom would be more effective than the single booms shown on the maps, but the plan says stocks of response equipment kept in the islands could rapidly be augmented by extra kit flown and shipped north from mainland bases, within 48 hours. It is only fair to say there is residual scepticism in Shetland about the feasibility of this strategy in severe weather, when boats and planes are often held up. 
<P>
There remain strong arguments for holding much larger stocks at fish farms and wildlife refuges, as is now done in Prince William Sound, Alaska, but BP are confident they have the gear, the expert staff and the maintenance capability to respond quickly while back-up support is brought in. And they point out that a slick is unlikely to hit Shetland on a wide front. Computer predictions of 'slick trajectories' suggest that relatively small areas of coastline would be impacted, at first.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Unprecedented detail</B></CENTER>
<P>
What has impressed Shetland's conservation bodies and seafood industries in the consultations over the past two years is the unprecedented detail of the spill plan. If the worst came to the worst - a very large spill coinciding with winds and waves too high to use booms and skimmers - everyone knows very little could be done. But at least BP have been seen to prepare for what might be done under optimal conditions. 
<P>
So what are the risks of spillage? 'Not as high as you might think', sums up the answer from BP's 'Loss of Containment Risk Tables': spills of more than 50 tonnes are likely to be very rare events, perhaps only once in the lifetime of the field. Between one and two spills a year are anticipated, mostly less than one tonne and mostly the result of human error in operating topsides and loading equipment. 
<P>
'Total risk' during the drilling phase is estimated at one spill in 33 years. For the production phase the spill risk is stated as one in 34 years. The maximum field life is half that.
<P>
The biggest risk is seen as the cargo export system - pumping oil into shuttle tankers. Here the figure is a spill every 1.7 years. The data have been re-worked after initial criticisms but one problem has been the lack of historical data for offshore loading risks. 
<P>
Cynics may relish Figure 5.1 in the Environmental Assessment, which reveals a tenfold increase in oilspill reports from offshore loading installations on the UK Continental Shelf between 1986 and 1990. 1986 was the year the Department of Trade and Industry started using a spotter plane to identify oil slicks. As the Environmental Assessment puts it: 'The advent of this programme coincided with an increase in spill reports to DTI.'
<P>
Since 1990, it appears surveillance has encouraged better housekeeping to keep the problem under control, with the average spill rate per installation dropping from eight to one per year.
<P>
Some critics reason that, even with the impressive offshore-loading technology being installed at Foinaven, it just has to be riskier than conventional production platforms, exporting oil via rigid subsea pipelines to a land terminal like Sullom Voe. But BP say the water 200km west of Shetland is too deep for conventional production technology.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Increased tanker risks</B></CENTER>
<P><A HREF="petrojarl.jpg"><IMG SRC="petrojarls.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=234 HEIGHT=150 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
So Foinaven uses a 'floater', a Floating Production, Storage and Offloading (FPSO) ship which will receive oil from remotely-controlled, seabed manifolds through flexible flowlines. The oil is processed on board and then loaded through another flexible flowline to a shuttle tanker moored astern. The tanker ships its load to the Flotta terminal in Orkney, braving the Pentland Firth on the way and, incidentally, increasing the statistical risk of tanker accidents.
<P>
'Petrojarl Foinaven' sits in water 500m deep. There have been serious problems installing the flowlines, even before the FPSO ship arrived on site last month. The current varies in direction and speed at different depths. This has caused snaking and snagging of the lines. There are also sudden and unpredictable current surges as ocean water, which has been moving steadily north-eastwards since it left Florida, meets a gigantic, underwater ramp with roly-poly contours - the Continental Slope between Shetland and Faroe. 
<P>
BP believe their FPSO, hooked up to the flowlines and 10 huge (35-tonne) anchors, will withstand the currents - and the 'freak' waves they can cause when they conflict with storm waves on the surface. Satellite radar and anecdotal evidence from fishermen suggest these waves can be spectacular, terrifying and of Cape Horn proportions. A couple of years ago a giant wave in this area was blamed for massive damage to the big tanker 'Mimosa', punching a hole right through her bows.
<P>
When Foinaven was first proposed it quickly became clear there was fairly sparse information about the wild things living in these wild seas. There was a lot of data about seabird and seal colonies along the coastline but no-one knew much about the offshore populations, particularly in winter, when sensible folk avoided the area. 
<P>
<CENTER><B>Coral reefs discovered</B></CENTER>
<P>
A major scientific effort has gone into 'counting critters' and has come up with some ecological surprises. One of the biggest was that a cold water coral lives on the deep ocean floor and, in Faroese waters not far from Foinaven, builds reefs tens of metres high, with a fauna almost as rich and varied as tropical corals.
<P>
The oilfield lies on an important migration and wintering area for mackerel. Thousands of whales pass by twice a year, on their journeys between Arctic feeding grounds and southern breeding grounds. Millions of birds feed out there in the summer months. Even in winter there are flocks of seabirds, particularly fulmars, kittiwakes and gannets. The 'Atlantic Frontier' has been the spur to give us a much better picture of the extraordinary diversity - and vulnerability - of a corner of the planet once thought to be a watery desert.
<P>
The research is still going on and the Environmental Assessment makes no bones about the fact that we still do not fully understand the ecology of an place where oil production is bound to have side effects. For example, data on seabird distribution are complete for only seven months of the year.
<P>
<CENTER><B>An ornithological howler</B></CENTER>
<P>
The authors have edited out most of the howlers which inevitably drew adverse comment during consultation on their first draft. But one remains on page 15: fulmars, kittiwakes and gannets, it says, are 'mostly aerial in habit and are therefore at only moderate risk from oil pollution'. You do not need a Ph.D. in ornithology to realise there is nothing for the birds to eat in the air and they like to eat at least once a day. To feed, they must settle on the sea or, in the case of the gannet, dive into it. If there is oil on the water, they are at very considerable risk. 
<P>
To be fair, the revised document does admit that seabirds on the vast expanse of sea within 100km of Foinaven are 'highly vulnerable' for at least half of the year.
<P>
One of BP's biggest concerns is what happens when thousands of tonnes of drill cuttings, contaminated with synthetic drilling muds, are discharged above the ocean floor. The evidence so far is that the currents should disperse this plume of artificial, toxic sediment and restrict smothering of those rare corals and other life-forms. But no-one really knows.
<P>
The research has revived an interesting argument about the relative merits of 'synthetic' drilling muds (based on emulsions) versus traditional oil-based muds. It strongly suggests that the claims for synthetic muds being more environmentally friendly may have been overstated.
<P>
<CENTER><B>The dirty water problem</B></CENTER>
<P>
The BP scientists have also drawn attention to a continuing problem with all oil production involving offshore loading - an FPSO does not have room  on board for settlement tanks where oil can be skimmed off the surface of contaminated water from the wells, 'produced water', as it is called. 'Petrojarl Foinaven' will used hydrocyclones and electrostatic precipitators to clean the oily water as thoroughly as possible but in rough weather the system may be 'upset' and not work properly. 
<P>
Chronic, low level pollution from oily water discharged over the side will therefore be a continuing problem and there may not be enough equipment on board to deal with peak throughput. At best there will be 40 parts of oil per million parts of water (ppm) when it goes into the sea. A sheen can form at 25ppm in calm conditions. Re-injecting millions of tonnes of this dirty water into the oil reservoir is not an option, we are told, because it would be complicated and too expensive. Instead, fresh seawater will be pumped down to replace the extracted oil, along with all gas not used to power the FPSO.
<P>
Like all oilfields, Foinaven will pollute the atmosphere, adding its burnt gases and vented tank vapours to the global total and contributing to global warming which, it seems, is partly responsible for those ever-increasing wave heights which make this part of the north-east Atlantic such a challenging place to drill for oil.
<P>
At least BP do not have to contend with ice on their new Atlantic Frontier. But their research shows that, not so long ago in the geological timescale, icebergs of Antarctic proportions grounded west of Shetland. Seabed surveys have turned up hundreds of grooves in the ooze on the ocean floor, some of them hundreds of metres long. It was a mystery until geologists realised they were looking at fossilised plough marks, made by icebergs perhaps 12,000-20,000 years ago, when the sea level was at least 100m lower than it is now. This may be further evidence that Big Freezes and Big Thaws can happen more quickly than previously thought.
<P>
The next glaciation will remove all trace of Foinaven and bring environmental changes far more dramatic than anything the oil industry has wrought to date. The question is whether extracting and burning up all this oil and gas will help to trigger the return of the ice and/or flood the world's coastal cities.  So far, no-one in authority is taking very seriously Greenpeace's recent demand that the Prime Minister should call a halt to the West Shetland oil project and go for solar power instead.
<P>






<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Jonathan Wills, 1996. 


