<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Don't bet on a new Yukon</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Don't bet on a new Yukon</H1>
<P>
<H2>by Jonathan Wills</H2>
<BR>
(This feature also appears in 'The Scotsman')
<HR>
</center>
<P>
<P>
21st November 1996
<P>
It's a hundred years since a ne'er-do-well called 'Lying George'  Carmack panned a gold nugget from Rabbit Creek on the Thron-diuck  River in Alaska and started the Yukon Gold Rush. Miners struggling to  pronounce 'Thron-diuck' re-named it 'Klondike'. 
<P>
The weather in the island of Unst this week resembled the Yukon, with  fresh snow covering the otherwise unremarkable drainage ditch on the  croft of Hannigarth where Professor Dennis Buchanan of the Royal  School of Mines and his team have panned out, if not nuggets, some  'highly promising' grains of the yellow stuff. 
<P>
The 900 people of Unst took the news calmly. Over the years they have  learned not too get too excited about new things. Typical reaction to  the discovery of (possibly) commercial gold deposits on the island at  the northern tip of Shetland was: 'That's interesting. We'll wait and see.'
<P>
They've seen booms and slumps before: the kelp industry came and went  during the Napoleonic wars; iron chromate mining was the big thing in  the 1820s; herring was king in the years before the First World War;  the RAF radar station on Saxa Vord hill brought jobs in the Cold War;  and for the past 18 years the Unst airstrip was a bustling offshore  helicopter base - until Chevron Oil pulled out in March this year and  left more than 30 folk without work.
<P>
Unst is more than ready for another boom, as long as it's not too  big. But every island bairn has always known they were sitting on a  gold mine. Why, an RAF man had panned enough of the stuff to make  himself a signet ring, back in the 1960s.
<P>
So there was no gold rush fever in the Uyeasound Public Hall on  Monday evening when Professor Dennis Buchanan of the Royal School of  Mines explained his recent discoveries to an invited audience of  crofters and salmon farmers.
<P>
The geology of Shetland is horribly complicated. The 'Old Rock' has  been squashed, stretched, crumpled, melted and eroded for millions of  years, with the result that in these 567 square miles you may find  every rock type occurring in Scotland, from volcanic lavas to  limestones. The Geological Survey of Unst looks like a child's new  plasticine kit on Boxing Day.
<P>
At Ramnageo ('Raven's Cove') on the south-eastern corner of Unst,  between the village of Uyeasound and the hamlet of Muness, there is  an outcrop of very ancient rock whose name sounds like an  embarrassing personal complaint - phyllitic schist. It started life  as sand, muds and shale in which, under intense heat and pressure,  gold has flowed and congealed. 
<P>
At about one part of gold per million parts of phyllitic schist, it  is not the sort of strike that would have interested 'Lying George'  Carmack. But it is good enough for modern mining techniques and, if a  commercial firm is willing to pay for more detailed exploration,  there could one day be an open-cast mine employing perhaps 15 people  - some say 50.
<P>
If, that is, anyone can decide who has the right to stake a claim.  For the land-ownership of south Unst is almost as complicated as its  geology. For this, many blame an English entrepreneur called  Christopher Wood. Mr Wood was last heard of some years ago in a  village near Bognor Regis, soon after he bought the Muness Estate and  its crofts from the Freed family, absentee lairds.
<P>
Mr Wood caused some controversy when he split the estate into lots  and put it up for auction in London, sight unseen. Among the buyers  was a South African businesman, Ferdie Erasmus, who arrived in Muness  expecting to move in. He found 'his' croft house firmly occupied by a  local family who politely pointed out that, under crofting law, they  had absolute security of tenure and, while they were perfectly happy  to be friends with their new laird, had no intention of moving house. 
<P>
Mr Erasmus took the alleged 'con' in good spirit, stayed on in  Shetland to help build the new Lerwick swimming pool, met and married  the love of his life and is now working for a construction company in Glasgow. 
<P>
What no-one in Unst seems to know is whether Mr Wood is still around  and whether he sold the mineral rights. If he did not, his investment  may yet pay off.
<P>
What is known is that the mineral rights to Hannigarth, one of the  hottest 'hot spots' on Professor Buchanan's map, are still owned by  the Garth Estate, run by John Scott and his family from the island of  Bressay.  In the early 1960s the Garth Estate, unaware that oil was  about to be discovered off Shetland, sold a crofter the land on which  the Sullom Voe Oil Terminal now sits.
<P>
Mr Scott, who is also Shetland's Lord Lieutenant, does not regret  missing the chance of becoming a millionaire out of oil and has no  hopes of getting rich quick through Unst gold:  'I think it's very  unlikely that any mine will ever be called for,' he said yesterday.  'I don't think there are sufficient minerals there. 
<P>
'This gold mine talk is a nonsense and I can't imagine why the  council spent all this money on a glossy report telling us what local  people already knew, - that there are a few spots of gold along the  Hannigarth Burn. I actually think it's worse than that because it may  raise people's hopes falsely.'
<P>
Back at Unst's saloon, the Baltasound Hotel, barman Ronnie Smith said some  of the boys were talking of loading up Shetland ponies and headin'  for the hills, but most were content to whoop it up in the snug bar.  'No-one's tried to pay for a pint with a poke yet,' he said. But at  least it would make a good comic sketch for this winter's Uyeasound  Up Helly A' fire festival.
<P>
If the gold rush comes, it couldn't happen to a nicer island. But  John Scott believes that, for most visitors, the real treasure of  Unst lies in the sensational bird cliffs on the north-west coast of  the 12-mile-long island, at the Hermaness National Nature Reserve.
<P>
Other places have gold. Few have anything like the Muckle Flugga  gannetry. Eco-tourism seems more promising pay dirt for Unst than  shifting a million tonnes of phyllitic schist.
<P>



<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Jonathan Wills, 1996. 


