<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Tinkin' lang in Montana
</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Tinkin' lang in Montana</H1>
<P>
<H2>by <A HREF="mailto:TINGWALL@aol.com">Chris Moisey</A></H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
5th November 1996
<P>
September 2nd marked the first day of autumn and, here in the Rockies, the brief brilliance of the changing of the colours of the leaves makes this for me the most spectacular of seasons. The boulevard that runs past my house to the University is a kaleidoscope of copper, gold and deep russet, and on the hillsides, the gold of the  tamaracks glows against the dark green pines. The Indian Summer is past and a chill invades the air. High overhead, there is the urgent honk of Canada Geese on their way south.  All the memories of summers past are in that poignant call.
<P>
It is the sign every year for some of my contemporaries  to load the wagons and head for winter homes in Arizona and Mexico. They call themselves 'snowbirds', and I look forward to their postcards telling of balmy days while I am complaining of  bitter winter;  but I have decided  that  the seasons are a necessary part of my life. Perhaps I would wish for something less extreme than the climate of Montana,  where in summer we 'die of the heat' and in winter we 'die of the cold', but perpetual summer? I think not. Autumn is a time of reflection. 
<P>
Missoula, Montana lies at the hub of five valleys, and consequently experiences an air inversion problem. The burning of autumn leaves ceased long ago. Now, the leaves are gathered in bio-degradable plastic bags and hauled to the dump. The air is cleaner, but as I fill my Shetland docken kishie with crisp leaves to spill on the Thanksgiving table, I remember the acrid smell of the burning leaves at Chalfont St Peter, Rupert Brooke's 'sad, sweet smell of the rotten leaves', and  for  a necessary time, 'my heart is sick with memories'. I need to remember in the autumn ---- to remember the year, and the years, past; to sum up perhaps. 
<P>
My autumn sadness is as brief as the brilliance of the changing leaves, because by September's end, the shops are filled with Hallowe'en necessities ---costumes, candies, and pumpkins to be carved into goblin faces and set on the porch with a lighted candle inside. And yet, as the little ghosts and goblins appeared at my door on the 31st October, and I fill plastic pumpkins ---and pillowcases---- in response to 'Trick or Treat!'  I am remembering dark 'guizing' nights in Shetland. Was this Hallowe'en?  I do not recall  Hallowe'en from my London years. Was the practice of 'heaving neeps' at someone's door on a dark night the equivalent of the American 'trick' if the householder did not produce a 'treat'? Only once have I failed to be at home with a lighted porch and a supply of treats on Hallowe'en night.  I came home to find my windows soaped: 'Where were YOU?' was the message. I would have preferred the neeps at the door.  
<P>
The Shetland 'guizing' I remember was a simpler affair---an old sheet covered the whole body, and the head part had eyes and mouth cut out---the better to see and eat the curny cake and ginger cordial offered at each household (except for the ones where we threw the neeps). There was a ritual required of the householder: 'Noo wha is dis peerie lass ... I don't tink I keen wha dis is', and the natural response of the guizer was repressed giggles through the curny cake and cordial. Of course, no cars accompanied the little guizers on dark nights, so 'simpler' meant stumbling through the dark of a Shetland winter from house to house, but who would want it otherwise on Hallowe'en?    
<P>
I miss the bonfires of November the 5th, and the little boys calling out 'Penny for the guy' on street corners in London. The only huge bonfire I can recall in Shetland was the one built at the Clump in Braewick when the end of the war was announced. What a bonfire it was, although I am sure there were no fireworks. There were fireworks and bonfires aplenty last time I spent Guy Fawkes Day in London. And I am intrigued by the choice of this date for our Tuesday Presidential Election, after  a very long campaign notable for its lack of either fire or fireworks.
<P>
With Thanksgiving still to come, Good King Wenceslas is already booming his message through the Malls. We like to get an early start on things in the US, and the thrifty among us have already done their shopping at early sales and are prepared for Christmas. I shall wait until the snow falls  to visit the funny little import toy shop, where the smell from boxes packed in foreign countries will transport me to Stove and Smith's in Lerwick on a winter day. Past the pots and pans and nuts and bolts, and straight up the stairs there is a magical place of dolls with non-plastic faces  and toys without elaborate instructions for putting together. And perhaps I will buy a doll there.
<P>
Meanwhile, back at the ranch, old-timers have been observing wildlife behaviour out in the valley of the Bitterroot Mountains, where Native Americans once dug the bitterroot plant for medicine. I am told that muskrats are building their houses 4 feet high beside the ponds, and that this behaviour heralds the worst winter in 100 years. Nobody remembers, but all Montanans are familiar with Charlie Russell's  painting of a single starving steer in a blizzard. 'Waiting for a Chinook' was the title of that 1886 painting. The warm winds came too late to save most of the herds that year, and though the cattle industry recovered from the disaster, when ranching continued, it was on a much smaller scale. 
<P>
Montana is currently enjoying (some would say enduring) an influx of very important and famous persons because it has been touted as Big Sky Country, Land of Shining Mountains and lately The Last Best Place. And inexpensive real estate. Nevertheless, despite our growing sophistication, it is  'not a good thing' in Montana to ignore the warnings of old-timers---no sir.  So I mean to get a copy of the Old Farmers Almanack to check the truth of this; and if I am advised to lay in a supply of aetmell and batten doon da taek---- I will.  








<P>

<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Chris Moisey, 1996. 

<HR>


<H4><center>Look for our sponsors' icons on various pages</center> 
<BR>
 
<BR>
 
<ALIGN=left>
</H4>


<HR>
<A HREF="/features/features.html"><img src="/pics/back.gif"></a> Return to <A HREF="/features/features.html">Shetland News Features Page</a>
<BR>

