<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The use and abuse of a small country</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The use and abuse of a small country</H1>
<P>
<H2>by George Rosie</H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
<P>
	 Remember this; every time you top your glass up with `Highland Spring' mineral water you are doing a good turn for Mohammed Al-Tajir one of the richest men on earth. Because Al-Tajir is the owner of the Blackford Estate near Auchterarder, and for years he has been pumping up the water that runs under that estate, `adding value' and selling it back to the natives (i.e. us). Which is classic economic colonialism. But there are jobs in it for the locals - as drawers of water.  	 <P>And having bought the land Al-Tajir is free to do with it as he will. His will is that the farms on the slopes of the Ochils should be untenanted, that much of the farmland should be left fallow, and that the farm houses and buildings should be abandoned to the wind and rain. The Perthshire locals are now in a state of confusion; grateful for the jobs at Highland Spring; bitter at the way the land has been allowed to decay.  	
<P>
Conjuring up metaphors can be a dangerous game. But the plight of the Blackford estate does say a lot about Scotland; a conjunction of desirable natural resources, industrial weakness and political impotence. But, as things stand, there is nothing to be done. Not without land reform. And land reform is not on Britain's political agenda. So the people of Scotland have no way of insisting that Al-Tajir cleans up or clears out. Al-Tajir is the laird, and the laird rules, OK. 	 In this respect, Scotland is unique in the western world. It offers a totally free market in enormous chunks of land. Anybody from anywhere can buy as much of Scotland as they choose to afford. And what is true for respectable individuals is true for less respectable companies. Any dodgy, drug-funded dummy corporation registered on some Caribbean sand-bank or Pacific atoll can buy its slice of Scotland, no questions asked.  	 <P>This daft and dangerous situation dates back to the free trade days of the late 19th century when Parliament passed an act allowing foreigners - any foreigners - to buy property in Britain. As Britain was the biggest, richest rooster on the midden the idea of that any foreigner would actually be able to afford to buy into Britain was risible. Since then things have changed. There are millions of rich foreigners out there. And Britain - and in particular  Scotland - is ripe for the plucking. 	 <P>And plucked we have been. By millions of acres. For decades now affluent Danes, Germans, Frenchmen, Belgians, Americans and (especially) Dutchmen have been buying their own corners of Western Europe's `last great wilderness'. Huge swathes of the Highlands - such as the 50,000 acres of the Knoydart peninsula - were sold to developers, broken up and flogged off to anglers and shooters from all over the world.  	 <P>And having stumped up their thousands (millions in some cases) they are determined to make the most of their property. Foreign (and English) notions of ownership do not sit well in Scotland. As a result `keep out' and `trespassers will be prosecuted' signs have been sprouting all over the uplands of the north and south. One proprietor (whose estate runs down to Loch Cluny) took to decorating roadside stock fences with notices declaring that `This mountain is closed.' 	 <P>There is a sour irony in the fact that most of the countries from which these new lairds hail make buying land very difficult. The Danes long ago passed measures to stop their rural hamlets being snapped up by Germans on the hunt for holiday homes. The Irish Land Commission insist on knowing who is behind any land purchase. The Swedes and Norwegians are very careful about who buys their valuable farmland. It is virtually impossible for foreigners to buy up large lumps of Switzerland. But Scotland is anybodys. 	 <P>In recent years the lairds have been flexing their proprietorial muscle. Tensions have been growing. Mountaineers and hillwalkers grumble about efforts to restrict their freedom to roam. Local people complain of being barred from much-loved woods, footpaths, beauty spots and beaches. The relaxed attitude of the Forestry Commission to access has been replaced by nervous private owners determined to guard their valuable timber with dire warnings and barbed wire fences.  	 <P>All of this is, of course, an old lament. In 1847 Hugh Miller was complaining bitterly in the pages of The Witness about the effects of `sporting' estates on the Highlands. `The ancient inhabitants were cleared off... to make way for the sheep; and now the people of Scotland generally are to be shut out from these vast tracts, lest they should disturb the game.' Miller warned that if the sporting lairds went unchallenged they would end up `shutting the Scotch out of Scotland'. 	 <P>Nor was Miller alone. A few years earlier one John Robertson wrote a fierce piece in the Glasgow-based National magazine about the effect of landlordism on the people of Glencalvie in Easter Ross. `They dare not now hunt the deer' he wrote `or shoot the grouse or blackcock: they no longer have the range of the hills for their cattle and their sheep; they must not catch a salmon in a stream: in earth, air and water, the rights of the lairds are greater and the rights of the people are smaller...' 	 <P>The enthusiasm of some Arabs for Scotland is well known. The huge estates of Inverinate and Killilan and Wester Ross are owned by those racehorse owners extraordinary, the Al-Mahtoum family of Dubai. The Mahtoums are not universally popular. A few years ago their launch on Loch Duich went up in smoke. The Egyptian-born Fayed brothers who own Harrods of Knightsbridge also own sizeable chunks of Easter Ross around their lavishly-restored Balnagown Castle. (They used to own a lot more but sold off much of it in the 1980s). 	 <P>None of these Arab lairds hold their Scottish properties in their own names. The ownership of all these estates can be traced back to companies in Liechtenstein or Switzerland. The invisible corporate owner is now a familiar syndrome. Some of the most beautiful parts of Scotland are now owned in such tax bolt-holes as Gibraltar, Curacao, Jersey, the Dutch Antilles and the British Virgin Islands. 	 And just as property rights have elbowed Scots off the land, so they have been elbowed off the rivers. The `riparian owners' of our salmon rivers guard their property fiercely, with force if necessary. Water bailiffs and police launches abound. And the advent of the `time share' fishery companies like Salar Properties (owned in Vancouver by the one-time property tycoon Jim Slater) has exacerbated the situation. 	 As the Campaign for Public Angling has been telling us for years (although no one seems to listen) time-share fishing has had the result of excluding local people from the rivers in favour of well-off anglers from the rest of the world.  	 <P>A classic case was the River Conon in Easter Ross whose salmon rights were sold in a secret deal by the North of Scotland Hydroelectric Board to London financier Peter Whitfield (for £1.8 million). Whitfield then sliced the beats up and sold them off on a time-share basis. And the Conon - which was known as a `locals' river - became the exclusive province of the well heeled, mainly from the south of England. But what gives landlordism a uniquely nasty twist in Scotland is the remarkable survival of mediaeval feudalism. Whoever owns the title to an estate usually (although not always) becomes the `feudal superior'. If you own a house in Scotland the chances are you are someone's `vassal' - be it the local builder, the Sheik of Dubai, the Church of Scotland, or some shadowy company registered in Liechtenstein. 	
<P>
As such, your superior can load your property with all kinds of `burdens'. Or charge you, say, £1,000 for a `minute of waiver' to extend your kitchen. Or, in many cases, exercise his or her `right of pre-emption' to step in and buy your house - even if you want to sell it to your favourite niece or nephew. So long as the laird can match the price, the property is his (or hers).  	 <P>Feudalism is an unjust and archaic shambles. Almost everyone agrees on that. The English dumped it in 1290 - more than 700 years ago. But it is one that our politicians and lawyers have failed miserably to address. Promises of reform have come to nothing. Somehow, there is never enough parliamentary time. Westminster always has more pressing business. So Feudalism persists - to the huge advantage of the land-owning classes, some of whom exploit it mercilessly.  	 <P>The last Green Paper on the subject (`Land Tenure Reform in Scotland') was more than 20 years ago. After it was published - nothing. In 1991 the Scottish Law Commission (SLC) published a `discussion paper' entitled (encouragingly) `Abolition of the Feudal System'. Since then - nothing.   	 <P>Meanwhile landowners like Michael Nightingale of Cromarty (a Kentish commodity dealer and one-time Tory politician) continue to use their feudal powers to boost their property portfolios. Highland MPs and local councillors may gnash their teeth but the law is the law. Feudalism is feudalism. When it comes to tampering with the rights and privileges of the landowning classes, reform is, somehow impossible.   	 <P>John Robertson summed up the problem in the pages of the Glasgow National magazine: `Some Legistlatures have made the right of the people superior to the right of the chief' he wrote `British law-makers have made the rights of the chief everything, and those of their followers nothing.' 
<P>
Robertson wrote that in 1844. Since then little has changed. 
<P>

<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of George Rosie, 1996. 

