<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Islands for Sale</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Islands for Sale
</H1>
<P>
<H2>by Rob Edwards</H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
<I>
'I will arise and go now, and go to Innisfree,
And a small cabin build there, of clay and wattles made:
Nine bean-rows will I have there, a hive for the honey-bee,
And live alone in the bee-loud glade...
<P>
The Lake Isle of Innisfree, W. B. Yeats
</I>

<P>
Fancy an island? What would you like? For 16 million pounds there's a 
nice three square
kilometre Caribbean island called Guana which includes a holiday resort and a
golf course. Or for 13 million you could pick up the lovely Panama 
island of San
Jose, 45 square kilometres with 50 beaches. Or does the small Mediterranean
island of Isola Marinella - villa and jetty thrown in for nearly 6 million -
grab you?
<P>
Perhaps a property with a little more class? How about a private atoll paradise
in the Seychelles for 13 million, with its own handy airstrip? Or Esk Island in
the middle of a river in Australia, which for a mere 350,000 pounds 
comes with a small
kangaroo herd? Or, for 200,000, a central American island called Taborcillo,
which used to be owned by John Wayne?
<P>
Maybe something cheaper? For just 3,700 pounds, Lake Charlotte Island 
2 in Nova Scotia
could be yours, all 1,500 square metres of it complete with camping site. Or,
what's this? Clett Island in Scotland, asking price 16,500 pounds, 
'undeveloped'. Hey,
Scotland looks good - the 'treeless beauty' of Mingay for 59,000, the 'historic
ruins' of Hildasay for 110,000, or the 'beautiful wildlife' of the Treshnish
Isles for 1 million.
<P>
Now, this looks very interesting: another Scottish island, 34 square 
kilometres,
with estate, manor house and cottages. Doesn't say whether people live in them
or not. Offers over 2 million pounds. What's it called? Eigg. Rings a 
bell, doesn't it?
<P>
The Germany company that describes itself as the world's only island broker,
Vladi Private Islands, lists nearly 200 islands for sale in every part of the
world in its current blurb. They range from undistinguished lumps of rock that
you could own for a few thousand pounds, to tropical nirvanas that 
would set you
back several million. Some are small, some are large, some come with luxury
facilities, some without any. Oh, and some also happen to be people's homes.
<P>
The blurb lists eight islands in Scotland. As well as Eigg, Clett Island,
Mingay, Hildasay in Shetland and the Treshnish Isles, there is Eilean 
Righ ('farmhouse,
meadow and forest' for 500,000), Rudha'Chruidh ('house, boat house' 
for 195,000)
and the Isle of Pabay ('renovated house, stamp licence' for 395,000). There are
another four islands for sale off the English and Irish coasts (Burgh Island,
Fort Perch Rock, Blue Islands, Cruagh Island).
<P>
Vladi Private Islands, which is run by a staff of three from an office in
Hamburg, accompanies the island descriptions with warnings about the pros and
cons of particular regions. About the English and Scottish coasts, for example,
the company comments: 'Their infrastructure is very good and mass tourism is
non-existent. The beaches are clean and nature has been able to preserve her
equilibrium.'
<P>
The same is true for Scandinavia, it says, but 'some Scandinavian countries
enforce restrictive regulations regarding foreign ownership.' In the
Mediterranean, islands are very hard to come by, and if they do come on the
market, very expensive. Greek islands are the best bet, although, warns the
blurb, 'building permits are often very difficult to obtain.'
<P>
Canada is described as the most popular area for island-buyers, particularly
Nova Scotia where 40 islands are currently for sale. 'Nature's lush vegetation
has remained practically untouched. In addition, the political conditions are
stable and questions of ownership can be clearly regulated on a legal basis,'
says the blurb.
<P>
Vladi Private Islands is less polite about the Caribbean. 'Few 
Caribbean islands
are 100% private with unrestricted ownership,' the company says. 'In many cases
foreigners must apply for a special permit to purchase land. This region's best
point is the magic of its landscapes; its weakest point is its social
structure.'
<P>
New Zealand is portrayed as an island-hunter's dream. 'This country 
has one very
special advantage - foreign ownership has been permitted in New 
Zealand for only
three years. Therefore the prices are still at what we would consider the level
of the 1930s.' 
<P>
Foreign acquisitions in the Pacific, however, are 'complicated by numerous
hindrances', with foreigners allowed to buy islands only in Hawaii, the Fijis
and French Polynesia. Foreign ownership has also been banned in large parts of
the India Ocean.
<P>
In South America the demand for islands has dropped dramatically 'due to
political, economic or social insecurity', the blurb informs us. But this has
the advantage of driving down prices. 'With a little daring, especially in
Brazil and less so in Argentina or Chile, favourable acquisitions can be made.'
<P>
Vladi Private Islands is run by Farhad Vladi, a Canadian by birth. He claims to
have sold over 500 islands over the last 25 years, and to now be 
selling between
30 and 40 islands a year.  He originally sold Eigg to the controversial German
artist, Maruma, for 1.5 million last year, and is now trying to sell 
it again on
the international market.
<P>
Vladi is reluctant to categorise his clients, other than saying that 
90% of them
are from North America and Western Europe, and all of them have at 
least 100,000
pounds 'surplus cash'. They tend to be people looking for somewhere quiet to
which they can escape, he says.
<P>
Scotland offers several advantages to the potential island purchaser, he points
out. It is not a 'banana republic' where you have to worry about being nice to
the right officials. Nor is it the kind of place were he would recommend buyers
to take out insurance against the property being expropriated by government or
enemy authorities, as might be necessary in Cuba, Grenada, the Falklands or the
Seychelles.
<P>
But on the other hand, there is the climate and the midges. There is also,
according to Vladi, the risk that local authorities will restrict developments,
and the Scots' traditional wariness of foreign landowners. 'No 
foreigner is able
to put his island in a box and take it home. The ultimate sovereignty remains
with Scotland. All the buyer has is a piece of paper,' he maintains.
<P>
Islands have long been a source of fascination, fantasies and nightmares. From
Treasure Island and Robinson Crusoe, through Gulliver's Travels and Lord of the
Flies,  to Desert Island Discs and Lucy Irvine's Castaway. They have also been
uniquely private places of business. When Rupert Murdoch wanted to discuss the
future of his News Corporation last year, he invited executives to Hayman
Island, near the Great Barrier Reef, and owned by one of his companies.
<P>
The Virgin boss, Richard Branson, owns Neckar Island, one of the British Virgin
Islands in the Caribbean. He hires it and its 22 staff out to 
visitors for up to
10,000 pounds a day, and does brisk business. The reclusive Barclay brothers,
property millionaires who own Scotsman publications and The European, are
reportedly investing 90 million in building a Gothic castle, swimming pool and
shooting range on Brecqhou, an island in the English Channel which they bought
for 2.3 million two years ago.
<P>
Old Etonian, Andrew Martin, bought Percy Island off the Australian coast for
15,000 and has lived alone there for the last 32 years. He originally intended
to sell it for a profit, but now refuses the multi-million pound offers he gets
from property developers. He explained why recently when he was paid a visit by
the TV crew making Angus Deayton's programme, In Search of Happiness.
<P>
'It's too good to sell to some developer or rich man who's just going to treat
it like a vanity plaything,' he said. 'It's invaluable, like the most precious
jewel in the world. The views, everything running free, knowing that I can walk
around, muster the sheep, shoot the goats, it's what makes my heart beat.'
<P>


<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Rob Edwards, 1996. 


