</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The last Jacobite - Executing Archie</title>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> The last Jacobite - Executing Archie
</H1>
<P>
<H2>by George Rosie</H2>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
They hanged the last Jacobite martyr at Tyburn in London on  Thursday, June 7th 1753 at 12.30 in the afternoon. He was Doctor  Archie Cameron and he went out in some style; light-coloured coat,  red waistcoat, red breeches and a new, well-powdered `bag' (wig). His  `dying declaration' was an address to Sir Richard Glyn, the Sheriff  of London, who was in charge of the hanging (and who couldn't wait to  get it over and done).  
<P>
`Sir, you see a fellow subject going to pay his last debt' Archie  told the fretful Sir Richard. `I the more cheerfully resign my life  as it is taken from me for doing my duty according to my conscience.  I freely forgive all my enemies and those who are instrumental in  taking away my life. I thank God I die in charity with all mankind.'
<P>
After proclaiming to the crowd that he died, as he had lived,  a  faithful Anglican, he announced himself `done with this world', joined  in a few prayers, embraced the clergyman and was duly `turned off'.  His body danced on the hangman's rope for 20 minutes before being cut  down, stripped, sliced open and the heart removed and burned. After  which, Archie's remains were carted off to be buried.
<P>
On the face of it, the hanging of Archie was a piece of wanton  cruelty. The Jacobite uprising had been over for nearly eight years.  The chances of a Stuart comeback were next to nil. Many Jacobites had  been pardoned. Archie's influential brother Lochiel, the chief of  Clan Cameron, was five years dead. Archie himself was no military  man, but a physician who had tended the wounded of both sides in the  `45. His wife was a Campbell and a relative of the Duke of Argyll. 
<P>
Archie's `crime' was to have slipped into Scotland from France to  spread the news that Charles Edward Stuart had abandoned Catholicism  to become an Anglican and to invite the Jacobite clans to steel  themselves for yet another rebellion once George II had been  assassinated. Archie's message went down like a lead balloon. He was  hardly in Scotland a month before he was betrayed (by a Cameron)  picked up and bundled off to London for interrogation, trial and execution.
<P>
But Archie's mission and Archie's fate say much about Jacobitism.  Despite everything that had happened, Charles Stuart was still at  odds with reality. He believed that all he had to do was join the  Church of England and the British people would `come out' for the  Stuarts. It was lunacy, of course, but as the lunatic had the power  of France at his back the British government was obliged to take it  seriously. Seriously enough, at least, to hunt down and execute Archie Cameron.
<P>
Archie's dismal end is significant. It underscores two crucial  aspects of the Jacobite rebellions that popular history forgets;  religious conflict and international power politics. They were always  present. Every time the Stuart banner was raised in the glens of  Scotland, behind it stood a Catholic power, usually France. Where the  Jacobites of Britain saw a crusade to restore their `rightful' king  the British elites saw the manoueverings of Roman Catholic  absolutism. Neither understood the other's point of view. 
<P>
It is an argument that Linda Colley made recently in her remarkable book  'Britons Forging the Nation 1707-1837': `A successful Stuart  restoration would have meant the replacement of a Protestant monarchy  with a devoutly Roman Catholic dynasty. Moreover, since the Stuarts  could never hope to get back without substantial French or Spanish  military and financial aid, it seemed more than likely that their  restoration would be accompanied by a foreign army of occupation, and  not just a foreign army but a Catholic army.'
<P>
As Colley reminds us, by the 1750s Britain was the Protestant power  in Europe. For more than 60 years it had been locked in contention  with the might of Catholic France. If the five Jacobite insurrections  (1689, 1708, 1715, 1719, 1745) are seen as part of that long,  dangerous struggle then the spite of His Majesty's Government towards  Jacobites like Archie Cameron begins to make some sense. This was an  ideology defending itself.
<P>
In fact, it is not too fanciful to compare the situation with the  `cold war' of 1945 to 1990. The parallels are not exact, but they are  striking. Europe - and indeed much of the world - was dominated by  two competing power blocs each with its own persuasive ideology.  Military power was almost equally balanced between them. Each had its  `spheres of influence', colonies and client states. 
<P>
And neither hesitated to dabble in the internal affairs of the  other. Just as the CIA backed the Contras of Nicaragua and the KGB  propped up the Marxist rebels of Angola, so the French regime financed  and armed the Jacobites of Britain.  The Stuarts, father and son,  were pieces in a wider game of power politics. Not pawns, exactly,  more like bishops. Quite useful, occasionally important, but expendable.  
<P>
Archie Cameron was hounded to death by the British government in  June 1753 on the same grounds that the Americans sent Ethel and  Julius Rosenberg to the electric chair in June 1953. He was a threat  to security, a representative of an alien ideology. In 20th century  parlance, Archie Cameron was seen, rightly or wrongly, as a member of  a `fifth column'.
<P>
This international dimension of Jacobitism is brilliantly teased out  in another recent book ('The Jacobites: Britain and Europe  1688-1788') by the American historian Daniel Szechi. He writes:  `...the British  government rightly feared what the Jacobites were capable of  precipitating abroad... Likewise those Continental great powers who  considered allying with the Jacobites did not see them simply as  cannon-fodder, but rather as a force which had the potential,  literally, to destroy their British opponents.'
<P>
Nor was France the only European power to try to intervene in  Britain's affairs via the Jacobites. Szechi points out that, at one  time or another, and for one reason or another, Spain, Sweden,  Russia, the Vatican and even Frederick the Great's Prussia took a  lively interest in the Stuart cause. In fact, the Jacobite soldier  George Keith became the Prussian ambassador to Paris and was involved  (albeit marginally) in the futile Jacobite plotting that went on  after the `45.  
<P>
So, fear of the Continental powers was never far from the British  mind. That fear may have been exaggerated, but it was justified. Both  France and Spain had both shown what was likely to happen to  Protestant `heretics'. And, as Linda Colley argues, the wars with  France had drummed into the British people (Anglicans as much as  Presbyterians and Non-Conformists) a belligerent Protestant patriotism  that was crucial in shaping attitudes. 
<P>
That Protestant mind-set is shown plainly by who `came out' for the  Stuarts when Charles raised the banner in Glenfinnan in 1745. The  clans which rallied around it were, overwhelmingly, Roman  Catholic  or Episcopalian. The Presbyterian families of the far north - the  MacKays, the MacKenzies, the Sinclairs, the Sutherlands - stayed  away. Other Presbyterian tribes - notably the Campbells - joined the  Hanoverian war against Charles.      
<P>
And while there was a flurry of sentimental enthusiasm for the young  prince among the ladies of Edinburgh when he marched into the capital  in the autumn of 1745, the Lowlands proved barren ground. The  regiment he hoped to drum up in Edinburgh never materialised. Glasgow  produced only two recruits, and one of them was a drunk. The way in  which the Jacobites swept aside Sir John Cope's inept little army at  Prestonpans only exacerbated the fear most Lowland Scots felt for the  Jacobites.    There was, it is true, disillusion among Scots with the Union of  1707. But just as strong was the memory of the `killing times' of the  1680s. The mass hangings of Covenanters in the Grassmarket were only  60 years distant. The first Jacobite rising (in 1689) had been led by  Graham of Claverhouse, the scourge of Presbyterianism. All of this was  remembered in the way that old people today remember the `Hungry  `30s' and the rise of Fascism. The Stuarts had poisoned their own  well. Most of Lowland Scotland was relieved to see the Jacobite army  march south. 
<P>
But there was another powerful current running against the Stuart  cause; economic optimism. Mercantile Scotland was doing nicely out of  the British state (and its colonies). Lowland businessmen saw Britain  as many of their 20th century counterparts see the European Union; as  a dripping roast. There was no question of them joining Charles  Stuart in 1745. It would have been like going to the barricades for  John Redwood and Teresa Gorman - only a lot more dangerous. 
<P>
Not that the Whigs had it all their own way. There was some support  for the Jacobites in Lowland Scotland. The muster rolls of the  Jacobite Army reveal that at least a third, and possibly more, of the  recruits were Lowlanders, mainly from the cities, towns and farmlands  of the east coast. And many Scots - like the rest of their  fellow-Britons - were sitting on their hands until a clear winner emerged.
<P>
But this conjunction of militant Protestantism, fear of the Catholic  powers and growing prosperity and political timidity created the  climate in which the Jacobite cause withered. It was apparent in  Scotland. It became even more apparent as the Jacobite army marched  down through the England. If anything, the Anglican establishment of  England was more hostile to the Stuarts than Presbyterian Scotland. 
<P>
Even the Roman Catholic families of Cumbria and Lancashire fought  shy of Charles. The only recruits the Jacobites managed to drum up  were 200 Manchester men, most of them unemployed, many of them from  an Irish background, very few of them with a stake in the economy of  the land. Linda Colley argues that it is a mistake to equate the lack  of active opposition among the English with indifference. `Unless  they were very brave, or very stupid' she writes `they were hardly  likely to take pot shots at an army of Highlanders and risk reprisals  against their homes and families.'
<P>
This sullen hostility did much to undermine Jacobite morale. In  fact, it was crucial. By the time the Jacobite army reached Derby at  the beginning of December, 1745 the leadership - and particularly  Lord George Murray - was in a state of some despair. At a council of  war in Exeter House (now demolished) on Thursday December 5th Murray  pressed for a retreat. His argument was based on the refusal of the  English to `come out' for the Stuart cause.
<P>
A minute of the meeting reports that Murray told Charles that `The  Scots had now done all that could be expected of them. That they had  marched into the heart of England ready to join any party that would  declare for him, that none had, and that the counties through which  the armies had passed had seemed much more enemies than friends to  his cause.' He also pointed out that `... there was no French landed  in England'.   
<P>
Murray made a powerful case. They were in the middle of a hostile  population, hundreds of miles from home. They were short of supplies.  Two Hanoverian armies were lumbering towards them - Wade from the  North, Cumberland from the South. If they were ever trapped and  broken the militias would fall on them like carrion crows and `there  would not be a man escaped.' The situation was hopeless. They should  retreat and build on what had been won in Scotland.  
<P>
Charles disagreed violently. The people of England were cowed by the  Hanoverian `tyrants'. Remove that fear and their love for the Stuarts  would gush like water from a fountain. All would be resolved if they  pressed on to take London. The Hanoverians would flee in front of the  Highland charge, just as they had done at Prestonpans. And the French  were planning an invasion of the south of England. At one point  Charles shouted at his generals `... you ruin, abandon and betray me  if you do not march on.'
<P>
Ironically, the issue was settled by a Hanoverian agent called  Dudley Bradstreet. He was wheeled into the conference posing as an  English gentleman coming to the aid of the Prince with vital - and  completely bogus - information. Bradstreet told the Jacobites that a  third Hanoverian army of 9,000 men under Sir John Ligonier was about  to march. His `disinformation' was enough to defeat Charles. The  Jacobite generals made the decision to retreat back to Scotland.  From the Hanoverian point of view Dudley Bradstreet is the unsung  hero of the insurrection.
<P>
Charles never forgave the way he was overruled by his generals: `In  future I shall summon no more councils,' he announced with  characteristic Stuart arrogance, `since I am accountable to nobody for  my actions but to God and my father and therefore I shall no longer  ask or accept advice.' Nor did he. The decision to face Cumberland on  the hopeless killing ground of Culloden Moor was all his own.
<P>
It is difficult to exaggerate the importance of that `Black  Thursday' in Derby. It was the turning point of the `45. And it  remains one of the great `ifs' of 18th century history. If Charles  had won the argument at Exeter House, could the Jacobites have marched  on and taken London? And if they had, what would have been the  result?  A benign Stuart regime? Or bloody civil war?  They are  questions over which professional historians are still squabbling.  They have yet to reach a consensus.
<P>
`Black Thursday' was, in fact, the beginning of the end for the  Jacobite cause. When the French heard of the decision they abandoned  all plans for an invasion of England. Next day Charles Stuart's army  began the long trail back to Scotland pursued by Cumberland's troops.  They were cursed, jeered and harried all the way to the border by  English civilians. Some died from rural snipers. Exhausted young  Highlanders were butchered by vagrants as they slept in ditches.  Linda Colley sees this as understandable hate `...by the poor and the  vulnerable for outsiders who had dared to shatter the peace of their  communities.'
<P>
In their retreat the Jacobites left behind the 200 men of the  Manchester Regiment at Carlisle. They were quickly rounded up and  taken prisoner. The savagery with which these Englishmen were then  treated is revealing. The colonel, the officers, the regimental  chaplain, seven sergeants and nine other ranks were all hanged, some  in Carlisle, the rest in London. No regiment of the Jacobite army was  treated anything like as harshly. The message to the English people  was clear: meddle with Jacobitism at your peril. 
<P>
The Jacobites turned and fought a successful rearguard skirmish at  Penrith (the last land battle on English soil). And then, on January  17th, 1746 they scattered General Henry `Hangman' Hawley's troops at  Falkirk. `Sir, my heart is broke' the brutal Hawley reported to  Cumberland before going on to accuse his troops of `scandalous cowardice'. 
<P>
After the debacle at Falkirk the Duke of Cumberland took a grip.  Although only 25 years old (the same age as Charles Stuart) he was a  battle-hardened soldier. The skills he had learned in the War of  Austrian Succession at the battles of Dettingen (where he was  wounded) and at Fontenoy (where he was a hero) were brought into play. 
<P>
Cumberland's army (hundreds of them Scots) was marched north to  Aberdeen at the end of February. There it stayed for six long weeks  while Cumberland hammered it into shape. These six weeks were  crucial. If, as has been said, the battle of Waterloo was won on the  playing fields of Eton then the battle of Culloden was won in the  training camps around Aberdeen.
<P>
There is an excellent account of Cumberland's methods in General Rex  Whitworth's little-known biography William Augustus, Duke of  Cumberland. He writes; `Having analysed the enemies' tactics at  Prestonpans and Falkirk, Cumberland and his generals expected the  rebels to adopt similar tactics again: to fire at longish range, then  throw down their firelocks and charge with swords and daggers in both hands.'
<P>
This Gaelic charge had been remarkably effective in the past.  Jacobites had used it to devastating effect from Killiecrankie to  Prestonpans. But the Duke of Cumberland was not Hugh Mackay or John  Cope. `His men had to be taught to withstand the rebels initial fire'  Whitworth writes `and to remain in position even when the enemy made  his terrifying charge, complete with bloodcurdling yells. They could  fire only when given a specific signal to do so, usually by a  particular drum roll.'
<P>
On April 7th, 1746, when Cumberland was satisfied that his troops  were ready, the Hanoverian army broke camp and marched north and then  west along the Moray Firth coast. Offshore, a convoy of supply ships,  guarded by HMS `Fox' kept pace. After ten days of marching,  Cumberland's men caught up with the Jacobite army on Culloden Moor.  The weeks of training paid off. The tactics worked. According to that  fine historian Bruce Lenman `It was the end not so much of a mass  uprising as of an abortive, French-sponsored coup d'etat.'
<P>
The victims of Culloden were many and various. Active Jacobites were  hunted down, burned out, gaoled, exiled and hanged. Highland chiefs -  Jacobites or not - were stripped of their residual legal powers.  Jacobite estates were confiscated and/or sold. Tartans, kilts,  bagpipes, broadswords were banned as weapons of war. As Hanover  stamped its imprimatur on the Highlands, the fragile culture and  society of the Gaels fell apart. It has never really recovered.
<P>
Nor has the Episcopal Church of Scotland. It is the forgotten victim  of Culloden. The Anglicans of the British government turned on it  with a ferocity that shocked many Presbyterians. `After Culloden the  Church dwelt in the shadow of death' says Marion Lochhead in her  (somewhat overheated) history of the Episcopal Church. `The virulence  of persecution of the vanquished foreshadowed the methods of the Nazis.'
<P>
It was almost 50 years before the Penal Laws against the  Episcopalians were lifted. By then the church had been grievously  wounded. Anthony Mitchell, the Bishop of Aberdeen, once listed the  damage; in 1689 the Episcopal Church held two-thirds of the people of  Scotland with 600 clergy; by the 19th century the church had 40  priests and only a twentieth of the people. Now membership is 35,000  - less than one hundredth of the Scottish people. Without the support  of English immigrants (lay and clergy) it might well have ceased to exist.
<P>
Archie Cameron was one of the Jacobite leaders who fled with Charles  Stuart on the French ship `L'Hereux'. He joined his brother Lochiel's  regiment of the French Army as a surgeon, and when Lochiel died  served with Ogilvie's regiment. Like all the Jacobites exiles he  longed to return to Scotland. Unlike most, he plotted to make it  happen. There must have been times when he wished he hadn't.
<P>
Jacobitism itself ended not with a bang, not even with a whimper,  but with a giggle. After Charles died, drunk and degenerate in 1788,  his mantle was taken up by his brother Henry, a Roman Catholic  cardinal. Henry IX, the last Stuart pretender, died in 1807, but not  before he had commissioned Canova to sculpt a memorial in Rome to the  Stuart `kings'. It was partly funded by George, Prince of Wales, the  first Hanoverian to climb into Highland tartans.  
<P>
When `Henry IX' left the European stage he was replaced by those  amiable English eccentrics the `Sobieski Stuarts', who declared both  their descent from Bonnie Prince Charlie and the authenticity of  their book of colourful tartan patterns. The Sobieski Stuarts are  partly responsible for what Tom Nairn dubbed the `Great Tartan  Monster' which still slithers across the British landscape.
<P>
The fact is, the Jacobite ghost still walks. As Murray Pittock  rightly says `The Jacobite cause's own icons of struggle, loyalty,  Highland patriotism, sacred kingship, art, fertility and episcopacy  transmuted themselves into various manners of understanding  Scotland's continuing problems of identity.... The metaphor and  symbols endure.'
<P>
None of which would have made any sense to Archie Cameron as he  stood on the gallows at Tyburn that June day in 1753. There is  something poignant about Archie's death, even after 243 years. If  nothing else, he is a reminder that there was more to Jacobitism than  red-shanked tribesmen with Lochaber axes. Archie Cameron was a  physician and a civilised man. He had studied Moral Philosophy under  the great Francis Hutcheson at Glasgow University and medicine at  Edinburgh and Paris.
<P>
Like many of his kind he had gone into the `45 with serious  misgivings. But through it all he had been loyal to the Stuart cause.  As a result he was about to be crushed in the gear wheels of European  power politics. But the last Jacobite martyr made a suitable exit.  Archie went to his death asking God to `... hasten the restoration of  the royal family without which this miserably divided nation can  never enjoy peace and happiness.'
<P>


<P>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of George Rosie, 1996. 


