<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News -  A Night Between Weathers
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Funny Old World</H1>
<H2> A Night Between Weathers
</H2>
by Jonathan Wills
<P>
(a shortened version of this feature appears in Scotland on Sunday)

</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<P>
11th November 1996

<P>
'Information overload' is making us ill, it said in an English newspaper which I have stopped reading because it overloaded my brain's random access memory. 
<P>
I am also giving up American politics, so my cerebral soft disc can cope with the forthcoming Shetland Islands Council by-election in Yell, South. 
<P>
Presidential Tuesday was 'a day atween wadders', a Shetland expression for a fine day between sleet storms. What with the global warming and the windier North Atlantic, our weather windows are narrowing. The Fifth of November was really only a night between weathers.
<P>
The Bressay whole-island-bonfire-and-fireworks-with-warmdogs-to-follow having passed off in a flat, black calm and without injury, I carefully extinguished my sparkler, booted up the Word Wide Web and logged on to the Atlantic weather chart and the latest picture from a satellite high above my head. It took so long to come up on the screen that I phoned our as yet unprivatised Coastguards instead.
<P>
Their information load was brief and to the point. After days of waiting for a weather window to deliver a motorboat to Unst, the island at the end of the British world, my luck was in. The wind would not reach Force Eight again until 3am. I could make the island of Yell, 30 miles away, and complete the voyage next day.
<P>
I was in the Mid Yell pub before closing time. Being the same age as Scotland's National Health Service, I joined the table where my pal, the local doctor, was enjoying an evening off. Besides, I needed his sofa for the night.
<P>
I had recently written a piece about his new defibrillator for jump-starting heart attack victims and, when I searched the digital datafile for a picture of him, I found one of a rabbit and a clown riding a pedalo across a notorious tide race, sponsored by hilarious spectators. The doctor was the rabbit. This was not the dignified mugshot GP Magazine was looking for, digital or not.
<P>
The clown, a notorious Yell ferryman, was in the bar to sign the rabbit for his next medical fund-raiser - welding up an old Volvo so it would float and driving it across that sound between Yell and Unst. A prototype had almost circumnavigated the Mid Yell Pier, but the battery shorted out and there was no defibrillator handy. 
<P>
It was one in the morning, back in the doctor's kitchen, before I remembered what day it was. I tried to reach the American election results home page with my laptop but the Internet had apparently crashed in the US because so many people were trying to do the same thing at the same time. But it was clear, the instant we switched on the telly, that Bill n' Hil had 'made the land again', if not The Hill.
<P>
Until then I had no idea Ralph Nader was the Green's presidential candidate. The BBC broadcast their election special from an echo chamber in Washington DC, so it was difficult to hear all Nader's replies to the duty Dimbleperson.
<P>
Gavin Esler had earlier called it 'an idea-free campaign' but one of Slick Willie's few ideas had been to enrich President Bill Gates of  Microsoft by connecting every American school to the Internet. Revolutionary. The kids might start to enjoy learning, as long as they didn't all try to log on at once. 
<P>
Nader had even better ideas and, now the election was safely over, the US networks were giving him primetime to put them across.
<P>
'The corporation is the power centre in our politics,' he said. If corporations could rent American politicians (and some of ours) there was no prospect of the Comeback Kid or anyone else tackling the big issues of education, health and pensions. Campaign funding reform came first. 
<P>
Nader is a sort of Will Hutton with added Nature Study. Like the author of 'The State We're In', he says the interests of corporations cannot be reconciled with the interests of society. Not only do we let them buy our elected representatives but we also model our social institutions on commercial firms whose structure is inappropriate for delivering welfare, health care and schooling. 
<P>
It is clear by now that private insurance is not going to help the 23 per cent of American children living in poverty. Nor is the internal market going to fix the British NHS. Clarke-Brownian economics, endogenous growth theory notwithstanding, can't deliver jobs without destroying even more of the Nature that so few politicians have studied.
<P>
They don't have a Green candidate in Yell, South. There is a Labour Party member standing as a Lib Dem, and that is curiosity enough. But the corporate virus Ralph Nader was trying to talk about (until he was cut off by a video clip of defeated Republicans calling Clinton 'socialist') is found even in remote islands, thousands of miles from Washington DC.
<P>
A new secondary school for Shetland is delayed by confusion over the Government's bizarre 'Private Finance Initiative'; fat cats of the privatised Hydro Board can no longer guarantee a reliable electricity supply (28 power cuts in my island this year); the market-oriented Royal Mail curtails the hours of country post offices; privatised BA pulls out of island air services and then posts record profits.
<P>
The local NHS and Social Work Department suffer bureaucratic sclerosis - it can take a two-hour meeting of 11 corporate professionals to decide whether an old lady with arthritis needs a home help, day care or hospital. This decision used to be taken by a doctor and social worker who knew the patient personally.
<P>
Even in islands enriched by a tiny slice of BP's corporate profits from Sullom Voe, clowns and rabbits still have to make old Volvos drive on water to finance essential medical equipment for country doctors.
<P>
There's a growing shortage of GPs. Medical students opt for glamorous, highly-paid specialities, not the long hours of single-handed rural practice. No doubt the social marketeers will explain their solution to this crisis on our own Election Night Special. It will probably involve self-diagnosis by e-mail.
<P>
Jonathan Wills
<P>




<P>
<HR>


