<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>De Minimis Non Curat Lex
<h5><I>(It's Latin, Dummy: 'The Law Does Not Concern Itself With Trifles')</I></H5>

</H1>
<H2>by Stoura Clett
</H2>

</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>5th November 1996</B>
<P><UL><LI>
It's turning into a vintage winter for Scottish Hydro Electric.  Another three hour power cut (sorry, chaps, 'temporary service  outage') in British West Bressay last night. Our editor was on the  ferry to Beautiful Downtown Lerwick when it happened and had to  return before the end of his Labour Party meeting, to make sure the  newdesk didn't crash when the power came back on again.
<P>
His suggestion that Da Hydro and all the other privatised national  utilities be immediately re-nationalised without compensation and the  Tory MPs who voted for it thrown into jail did, not, I fear, find  much favour with the Blairies at the meeting, including Rockin' Jimmy  Paton, the new prospective candidate and former roadie for Elvis Voe  and the Heoganaires.
<P>
Thrown into jail? Surely a bit strong, Jon? Not at all, according to  our editor, who was more than usually incandescent after his second  'outage' in 72 hours. The poor, old-fashioned dear holds firmly to  the principle that the party whip system, which shunts privatisations  through the Hice of Cummings for Governments which don't have a  majority of votes at the ballot box, amounts to 'suborning a Member  of Parliament'. This, he assures, me, is against some law dating back  to the 14th century and never repealed. 
<P>
Lord, luv a duck! What a bor-ring relic this man is! Being a child of  the Thatcher Era (described by our grumpy editor as '17 years under  enemy occupation' - what can he mean?) I thought suborning MPs was  perfectly normal.
<P>
<hr width=60%>
<P><LI>
Still, the power cut was shoved off even the inside pages by the  rib-tickling news that the 'Petrojarl Foinaven', lovely big thrusting  oil pumper that she/it is, did a decidely wimpish about-turn  yesterday and headed for shelter, of all things, off Skelda Ness -  instead of facing the gale and picking up her anchors like a real man  (this gender business with ships is so confusing, isn't it?).
<P>
Loved the spin doctoring by our very own resident Shetlander in  charge of BP's Foinaven oilfield operations (didn't even know the  company was feeling peaky, myself): Les Thomson of Hillswick, for it  is he, told Radio Shetland listeners the diversion was actually a  positive thing because it gave Shetlanders their one and only chance  to see the big beast before she disappeared over the horizon for the  next 17 years.
<P>
Gosh, what a treat. I bet they're dancing in the streets of Skeld  tonight, Les! But don't bet the croft your new baby won't be back inshore soon.
<P>
<hr width=60%>
<P><LI>
Seeing we're being beastly to BP, wot abaht this one, eh, nudge, nudge?  
<P>
According to page 15 of their 'Environmental Assessment' for the new  Atlantic oilfields, the fulmars, gannets and kittiwakes out there on  the dotted line at the edge of the Continental Shelf (sounds like a  swish new Lerwick bistro, doesn't it?) are 'mostly aerial in habit  and are therefore at only moderate risk from oil pollution'. Just  read that again, girls, will you?
<P>
Lord, luv a gannet! Has hunky Dr David Monk, BP's Head of Gannets,  Northern Hemisphere, gone off his chump? Pete Raptor, my favourite  and suprisingly tame ornithologist, reminds me that although it is  indeed true that these birds spend most of the day flying around,  there is one tiddly little problem. The silly things have to eat and,  as there is nothing for them to eat in the air, they land on the sea to feed. 
<P>
And here we come to the big intellectual leap forward, probably a  leap too far for poor David Monk: if there's an oil spill on the sea  where they alight it could, believe it or not, actually get on their  feathers and spoil their entire week! Moderate risk, my tail!
<P>
Isn't science wonderful? Pity there's not a little more of it in the  Environmental Assessment.  Never mind. In appendix A4 we learn the  reassuring news that the chance of an oil spill from 'Petrojarl  Foinaven' ''failing to maintain station'' is, wait for it, one in 625 years.
<P>
With statistics like that, I'm certainly going to stop worrying,  right now this very minute.
<P></UL>
 






<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P>
 <B>4th November 1996</B>
<P>
<UL><LI>
Life in the corporate fast lane is a risky business, so the wise  high-flyer is always on the look-out for a nice little earner if that  early retirement package should land on the doorstep sooner than expected.
<P>
There is none wiser than our own dear chief of corporate affairs,  Malcolm The Terrible. He's known for some time that one day he'll  have to give up the day job, as whit we aa mun do, hae we or hae we  no a cru. Malkie's already a well known groupie on the folk scene but  rumour has it he's planning a new career as a rock'n'roll impressario.
<P>
More than rumour, dear friends: neighbours on Discovery Hill (so  called because you can see more Range Rover Discoveries from there  than anywhere in the northern hemisphere) were astonished on Sunday  lunchtime to behold the entire cast of tearway local rock combo The  Red Vans trooping into the Green's Swiss-style residence, Fort  Acolyte, for a working brunch.
<P>
They'd have been even more astonished if they'd been inside the  building, for no sooner had the lads got their grubby paws around a  pre-prandial snifter than a bleeper went off deep in the bowels of  the South-Fork-style kitchens.
<P>
Panic gave way to hilarity as their host frantically scrabbled  through various drawers, safes and lockfast places, searching for the  miniaturised electronic device. Turned out it was just His Holiness  checking The Hairy One's satellite tracking transponder to find out  where he was if he wasn't in church.
<P>
The word on the street, pop pickers, is that after a fairly heavy  session The Red Vans agreed to hire him as a roadie. Or was it the  other way round? One can never quite tell with Malkie.
<P>
<hr width=60%>
<P><LI>
Speaking of security, what price the head of the Sitewide Hostile  Intruder Termination Executive (it's an acronym, dummy!) at BP Sullom  Voe? Try driving in the main gate without a pass and all hell lets  loose. But for energetic and determined trespassers - mainly the  Delting sheep (so far) - there's another way.
<P>
The big gale back in January '92 laid waste some 20 yards of the 10  foot high perimeter fence where it runs into the sea at Orka Voe on  the north side of the oil terminal site. No big deal, you may say.  But, Heavens to Betsy, a little bird tells me the fence is still wide  open, almost five years later!
<P>
No need for alarm, however. For everyone knows that even the most  determined terrorist would easily be deterred by having to put on  green wellies and walk a punishing couple of miles around the shore from Toft. 
<P>
A passing goose shooter from Orka Flats tells me he hears BP are  thinking of hiring Big Malkie as their security adviser, once he gets  his Golden Goodbye from Da Coonty. Such a pity he's signed up with  The Red Vans already and won't have time!
<P></UL>






<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>2nd November 1996</B>
<P>
<UL><LI>
Oh Lawks! There's my old chum Malcolm Green caught spending £27,000 (honest) on a Junior Spymaster Kit to de-bug Lerwick Town Hall! And the Rector of St Magnus knew absolutely <I>nothing </I>about it! Dontcha just <I>love </I>it? But how terribly unkind of a certain councillor, whom I will not name as long as the monthly direct debit keeps kicking in, to remark in my hearing: 'What makes them think a spy could make out what Malkie was saying anyway, even if he <I>didn't </I>wrench the tape recorder out of the agent's hands and try to ram it down his froat?'

<p>
<LI>
My Dears! Did you notice that dinkie little boat Golden George (Mmm! Hunky!) has bought the Foula men? Quite, quite divine! One just <I>adores </I>the paint job. I mean, have you <I>seen </I>the peerie bird they've painted on either side of the front - or 'bows', as our pedantic old salt of  an editor calls it? Pierhead skippers ask me what sort of <I>avifauna </I>it could possibly be. Oh, come on, chaps, you must have guessed by now. It's a Wild Goose! No barnacles on my bottom. Get it? Barnacles? Geese? Oh, never <I>mind</I>!

<P>
<LI>
Winter's here, and no mistake. A girl can hardly keep her perm on straight in all this wind and rain! Why, only this morning I bumped into <I>darling </I>Andrew Harmsworth, Da Coonty's evangelical 'agricultural officer', who helps all those poor crofters fill in forms asking for even more Hill Livestock Compensatory Allowances, or 'subsidies' as we intellectuals call them. 'Beastly Day, Andrew!' I chirrupped, accelerating across King Harald Street to avoid the religious tract the <I>pet </I>was about to offer me. 'Da grund wis needin' hit!' he replied. Isn't it quaint how simply everyone is trying to speak dialect these days, even the aristocratic diaspora?

<P>
<LI>
And then they had that <I>marvellous </I>power cut for three whole hours in British West Bressay last night - first proper one of the season, I believe. TV off all over Shetland, forcing people to play <I>charades </I>and take strong drink, even! Our crusty old editor called Da Hydro's 0345 number to complain and swears he got a recorded message saying the number had been changed. So he dialled that one but, silly old butterfingers that he is, found himself talking to Thames Water instead! What a hoot! They had no <I>idea </I>where he was! Come to that, nor did the Hydro lady in Perth (of all places) when he finally got through.

<P>
<LI>
For Heaven's sake don't tell my old chum Bobbity Washoot (now we really <I>are </I>talking hunky!) but his <I>hits </I>are not what they seem. The poor chap's website has a weensie little  problem. It takes two clicks, not one, to reach the news pages and, worse still, his boffins are using those awful, clunky old frame things, so while he thinks he's getting <I>heaps </I>of hits, he's actually getting less than a tenth of the ones those awful bullies (<I>pirates</I>, really, Bobbity confides) are clocking up at Shetland's Number One site - you know where. Call me a beach, but, as they say, 'Great is the truth, and it will prevail'!

<P>
<LI>
Speaking of Bobbity's snailmail website out there in Newsprintland, what's become of  my old friend Spike? Don't <I>ask</I>, please. It's so terribly, terribly sad.
</UL>
<P>

Simply must dash! There's a <I>man </I>at the door 
<P>
'Oh! Er, why don't you come up and see me, officer?'
<P>
<I>Cheerio eeno!</I>


<P>
<HR>


