<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - 'Refusing to knock at Death's door'</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Funny Old World</H1>
<H2>'Refusing to knock at Death's door'</H2>
<P>
by Jonathan Wills
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
11th October 1996
<P>
It's a bit late now, after 20 years in the business, but I am  beginning to suspect that I'm no longer man enough to be a member of  Her Majesty's Press, if I ever was.
<P>
My credentials have been questioned twice in the past year, by  proper, trained journalists who happened to be personing  the  newsdesk of a certain mainland daily when my district news copy on a  suicide arrived in their basket.
<P>
The police euphemism when a sad person takes their own life with a  shotgun is 'a sudden death with no suspicious circumstances'. I  normally despise euphemisms but, great big squeamish softie that I  am, I find this one more civilised and comforting than the stark word  'suicide'.
<P>
If, and only if, the victim is a well-known person who has taken some  prominent role in the local community over the years, a brief  obituary is called for, drawing on old news files and quotes from a  few folk who knew the deceased well. Usually a friend of the bereaved  family can arrange for a photograph of the departed in happier days -  what is known in the trade as 'a collect pic'.
<P>
In a small patch like mine (and everyone else's, for that matter),  this must be done with some delicacy if we are not to distress the  bereaved even further. The same applies to accidental deaths,  particularly those involving children.
<P>
What I am increasingly asked by some mainland newspapers of a certain  hue is, in the words of the young newsdesk lady in the most recent  incident: 'Why haven't you done a death knock?'
<P>
This involves knocking on the front door of the grieving family,  offering them synthetic sympathy, and persuading them to give you an  interview and a picture.
<P>
It is actually quite easy to do death knocks. The recently bereaved  are often garrulous. They commonly give you very juicy quotes and  lots of emotive actuality. The point is that they are invariably in  shock and in no state to decide if they should talk to the media. I  think they deserve more respect, whether they have lost loved ones in  a spectacular horror like Dunblane or  just another car crash.
<P>
After the successful death knock, you are supposed to write something  like this: 'A hysterical mother yesterday broke down and wept  uncontrollably as she told me of her three-year-old daughter's  horrific death fall from a cliff...etc.'
<P>
You don't need to disturb the mother to know that she will be  sobbing, and probably screaming, a few hours after her child has  died. It seems to my old-fashioned, untrained mind that what you  ought to write is: 'The shocked parents of a three-year-old girl who  died in a cliff fall were last night under sedation and being  comforted at home by relatives and friends.'
<P>
That is euphemistic but it is all you can or should say.  The most  unimaginative reader realises the bereaved will hardly be 'over the  moon'. The demand from the Harry Hardnose school of newsdesking is  for 'actuality': blood, guts, tears and meticulously chronicled  wailing and gnashing of teeth. Some TV and radio news programmes are  becoming almost as depraved.
<P>
I find this unpleasant, prurient and semi-pornographic. But then I  only drifted into journalism and was never properly trained. So, once  again, I refused to do the death knock for the young lady on a far newsdesk. 
<P>
Not very politely, I explained that, in my opinion and knowing the  deceased and his distressing family circumstances, a death knock  would amount to intrusion on properly private grief. This, I rashly  suggested, was against the National Union of Journalists' code of  conduct (yes, there is such a thing and some of us old fusspots still  try to follow it).
<P>
'It's not against any code of conduct I know of,' was the tart reply.  Well, of course, she wouldn't, would she? Union membership is rather  out of fashion at the moment in our trade, so she had probably never  seen the clause in the NUJ code of conduct which does indeed say a  journalist shall do nothing to intrude on private grief.
<P>
The previous time this happened, an angry news editor was the phone  within minutes, to berate me for my wimpishness. He reminded me where  my bread and butter came from and demanded the full gories. The  newsdesk, not I, would decide what was in good taste and what wasn't.  I was unable to satisfy this gentleman and he hung up, after a few  parting insinuations.
<P>
Fortunately, I am a freelance, not an employee, and can choose not to  do the dirty work. My customers can take or (more probably, these  days) leave what I file to them. I can always go to the handline  fishing instead. It's the poor souls who actually work for these  crass sensation-mongers who deserve your pity.
<P>
Apart from the morality of death knocks, there are practical  considerations. Every local district in the world has its 'stringer'.  There are millions of us. Without us the big papers would have to  spend fortunes flying crack correspondents out to cover every bus  crash, hotel fire, shipwreck and man biting dog. Or, more likely,  they wouldn't bother to report anything involving single-figure  casualties beyond the cities of the plain.
<P>
Flying death-knock squads cost loadsamoney and invariably cause local  outrage. A good bad example was the reporter who, quite  disgracefully, doorstepped the widow of the pilot killed in the  Shetland air ambulance crash earlier this year. Shetland-based  journalists who treated the widow with respect did not file such a  heart-rending story but were tarred with the tabloid brush and  themselves became local hate objects for a while. 
<P>
The problem with stringers, and our strength, is that we are part of  the community. People have to trust us. We must be on friendly but  properly distanced terms with the local police, firefighters, health  board, hospital, council, court officials and coastguards. In  particular, the population at large must trust us never to betray  sources and not to be partial or for rent. If we lose that trust, we  can't get any information, have no stories to sell and will soon be  at the handline full-time.
<P>
If we do our job properly, we must often write reports which, however  factual and fair, drive local authorities and personalities into a  frenzy of indignation because they did not want their neighbours, let  alone the outside world, to know what was going on. A recent example  was the vilification of journalism as a trade by certain salmon  farmers who, thanks to the efforts of the local press, were revealed  to be doing naughty things with banned chemicals in order to make a  quicker buck.
<P>
Unlike big city reporters, who may never meet today's target again,  we must live with our 'victims' long after the national media have  lost interest in the story which gave offence. This causes some  tension and the occasional punch-up in the boozer. We do not expect  to be universally liked in our communities. But we do what we can to  earn at least a little respect, and a living at the same time.  Outraging the local public's sense of what is right and decent at a  bereavement is counter-productive, to say the least.
<P>
Journalists in general are now rated in public esteem slightly below  pimps and only a little above politicians and dope dealers. The  voyeurism of some newsdesks has a lot to do with that.
<P>
I have just been to our annual Shetland Careers Convention, where I  once again broke it as gently as possible to dozens of sixth-formers  and their parents that journalism can indeed be a slightly dirty  trade. If you're 'interested in creative writing', then go in for  that, not journalism, I always say. 
<P>
But no-one's going to take any notice of a cynical old hack in a  dirty mac, even if his scruples have brought him to the brink of  packing it in. So this year there was the usual crop of talented,  determined trainees. Let's just hope they skip the journalism college  classes on death knocking and later have the courage, as members of   the union and the human race, to tell importunate news editors where  they draw the line.
<P>
They could be out of paid job then, of course. There'll be nothing  for it but stringing a district for life. They needn't blame me. As I  told their parents, so long ago: 'Don't put your daughter on the  page, Mrs Worthington.'
<P>


<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1995.


