HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 10:49:54 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 11616
Last-modified: Wed, 04 Dec 1996 23:14:11 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The Bressay Essay</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The Bressay Essay</H1>
<H3>'My vessel is stopped and making no way through the water'

</H3>
<P>
by Jonathan Wills, 5th December 1996

<H4>(This feature also appears in <I>The Orcadian</I> newspaper, published at Kirkwall, Orkney.)</H4>
<HR>
</center>
<P>
I am always nervous before my night on duty at the Bressay Junior Club, which takes place every winter Wednesday in the public hall. Fortunately, we have been breeding like fruit flies in Bressay. A century of depopulation has been reversed, with a vengeance. There are now several dozen parents in the island, so my turn doesn't come round very often.
<P>
My problem is that I can't stand loud noises. If ever I were captured by The Enemy Within, they would only have to turn up the volume on Radio One in my interrogation cell for 20 minutes and I would break down and give them all they wanted - National Insurance number, Clydesdale Bank PIN, postcode, mother-in-law's maiden name, Christmas card list, the lot.
<P>
The acoustics of our otherwise lovely little Bressay Hall are best described as 'resonant' and the noise on Junior Club Night is indescribable, although lessened by a few hundred decibels since the inestimable Morag organised things like table tennis, pool, draughts, baking and painting to keep the little dears busy. Every island should have a Morag, to say nothing of a Jessie, a Julie, a Sheila and all the other capable mothers (and some fathers, it must be said) who keep order. I hope I didn't forget to mention anyone there.
<P>
My allotted task for the evening was baking. With half a dozen little helpers, who knew a lot more about the business than I did, we soon had three dozen mincemeat pies in the oven. A few eight-year-old purists raised eyebrows at the Readymix frozen pastry I had bought that morning for the occasion. Being very keen on The Environment and self-sufficiency, thanks to the excellent green indoctrination policy of our island school, the younger generation tend to disapprove of people who can't or won't make their own pastry out of real flour and stuff, but they were far too well-brought-up to mention it.
<P>
There is nothing quite like a freshly baked mincemeat pie, almost but not quite too hot to eat. The scene when the pastries were served was like one of those Serengeti TV safari documentaries, where the lions tear a wildebeeste to pieces in seconds. The last pie had just disappeared down a ravening Junior Club gullet when my daughter, who played a leading role in the pastry-cutting operation, appeared in the kitchen to ask where hers was.
<P>
Oh dear... and I had scoffed three myself. But Wir Katy's tears soon dried when I explained that the greatest accolade any cook can ask for is a clean plate (even if the floor is covered in pastry crumbs). She cheered up and we went home, the bairns to beddy-byes and me to the cybergarret, to check that the day's news was up on the net.
<P>
Then the expletive-deleted power went off. By my calculations it was the 30th power cut in Bressay this year. Something of a record, even for the privatised Hydro Board, which appears to spend more on executive share options and public relations (their slogan, believe it or not, is 'We Give You The Power') than on the Bressay electricity supply which, among other things, fires up the TV transmitters for the whole of Shetland. 
<P>
Seeing as how Inspector Morse had just fizzled out in a snowscreen, I was surprised to find my phone call to Da Hydro answered so promptly. They are obviously spending a lot of money hiring all those poor folk who sit on the phone, waiting for all-too-frequent protests from Shetland. The tone of the lady on the other end suggested that she had been inundated by irate couch-tatties demanding to know what I wanted to know: why the power was off; when would it be on again; when the next temporary service outage would be; and whether we got a refund.
<P>
As usual, the unfortunate lady in Perth, or wherever, had not the slightest idea. She was just a buffer between me and the Big Cats I really wanted to tear limb from limb. <I>Their</I> numbers are all now ex-directory. Someone had sent her on an expensive course where psychologists train them not to lose the rag with incandescent customers whose computers, mobile phones, clock-radio-alarms, washing machines and central heating pumps have just gone bump in the night. 
<P>
I explained that the problem was they <I>didn't</I> give us the power. They charged us quite a lot for a service which was now farcical. I asked her to convey to her superiors my full and frank opinion of their abilities. In return for my telling her my postcode (that's because they don't actually know where Shetland is, let alone Bressay), she agreed to take my phone number. She would call me back 'when the power was re-connected'. She would <I>what</I>? My brain went numb. The line went dead.
<P>
The last time the power had tripped, and it wasn't long ago, I dialled Scottish Hydro's 0345 number and was greeted by an Essex voice: 'Fank you for callin' Thames Worter. This is Cheryl. 'Ow can I 'elp you?' OK, I may have punched the wrong number. It was dark and I was furious. But Cheryl's question was not as silly as it seemed. After all, the privatised utilities are all trying to become one-stop shops, flogging us electricity, gas, water, phone connections and, for all I know, optic-fibre pizzas. So, in an ideal, free-market world, like wot Mrs Fatcher used to go on abaht in Essex, there is no theoretical reason why Thames Water should not compete with Da Hydro for our business. Maybe they really could help me.
<P>
Cheryl and I had a good giggle about that, not least when we discussed the logistics and likely response times if they tried to send a repair crew of plumbers and sparkies from Thurrock to Bressay in the middle of a November storm. I liked Cheryl's style and promised to buy her an alco-pop if our Escort Xri's ever crossed. This was <I>before</I> the Budget, you understand. 
<P>
Cheryl's not her real name, of course. She would be fired if identified as the employee who frankly agreed with me that privatisation was a disaster, the utilities should be re-nationalised without compensation, and the MPs who voted for resetting the public's assets should be imprisoned without electricity or limit of time, in the Tower of London, preferably in chains and denied slopping-out facilities. Their friends would, of course, be allowed to bring them food and buckets, as long as they paid the warders a percentage. We are not unmerciful in the Bressay Independent Labour Party. Vengeful, Old Testament, very cross, yes. But never unmerciful.
<P>
In the past six weeks I have canvassed this policy among long-suffering workers in British Telecom, British Airways, British Petroleum and even Da Hydro. Not one opposed it outright, although I did get a couple of cautious 'no comments' from people who knew I wrote for <I>The Orcadian</I>.  Most agreed that, as the parliamentary bills for privatisation were passed by the party whip system, this amounted to suborning Members of Parliament - which, as even Essex Woman knows, is against some ancient law wot 'as never bin repealed. Or didn't orter a bin, anyway. The legislation thus bulldozed through the Hice of Cummings in 17 years under a political army of occupation was therefore null and void.
<P>
I don't yet know what my tartan-trewed friend, Hope Vere Anderson, thinks about this. We have only just met and are getting along famously. I don't want to spoil our promising relationship by raising such controversial matters, not until we are on 'No, no, it's <B>my </B>round!' terms, anyway. 
<P>
If That Lot do get back in, I may need someone to give me a reference when Sir John Feet-Robertson takes the golden goodbye from NoSWA, after all. But I must tell Hope, in all faith and charity, that if he wants preferment for himself (let alone for me) he must stop telling reporters, as prospective parliamentary candidate in the Unionist interest, that his own Conservative Chancellor of the Exchequer is a numpty and didn't orter have doubled the air passenger duty and hiked the tax on Bressay boatmen's diesel.
<P>
This is going to be a <I>very</I> interesting election. Hope Vere Anderson is a true original and will go far, probably as far as Fair Isle, where they very sensibly have their own electricity system. We need more candidates like Hope, people who will tell it like it is and tell the party whips where to stuff their spin-doctored evasions and cynical sophistries. 
<P>
Meanwhile, I have acquired a generator, to ensure that I remain on-line to report the hustings. It's Japanese, needless to say. Well, someone has to <I>make</I> things, now that we don't any more. And very wonderful it is too, if almost as noisy as the Bressay Junior Club. Da Hydro may have run out of excuses about the wrong kind of birds hitting their power lines but, as long as privatised BP Grangemouth keep sending up those one-gallon cans of lead-free by first class post (the only possible explanation for the price they charge), I shall no longer run out of juice. I am forwarding the invoice for the generator to Da Hydro, with a copy to Thames Water.
<P>
What's that? First class post is indefinitely delayed because the Flying Skip only has one door to load cargo? Heavens to Betsy! Privatise Brutish Ridiculous Airlines of the Isle of Man at once! 
<P>
It's privatised <I>already</I>? That's the problem? Oh, I see.
<P>
As my P&O chum (the Scott who's still speaking to me) said, not a couple of power cuts ago: 'If you've time to spare, travel by air.'
<P>
It was some hours into the latest power cut, by the way, before I realised I was still wearing the apron I had donned to help with the mincemeat pies. It's a rather fetching little number, sold by the Royal National Lifeboat Institution, and features the colourful signal flags used for routine comunication by mariners, and indeed everyone else, in the days before Edison, Marconi, the Wright Brothers and James Logie Baird. I have only just noticed that the code flag for the letter M for Mike (Forsyth?) is identical to the Scottish Saltire. 
<P>
According to the RNLI apron, confirmed by my copy of (Gordon?) <I>Brown's Signal Reminder</I> - which I really must return to my former employers, the Commissioners of Northern Lights, some day soon - Scotland's national ensign also means: 'My vessel is stopped and making no way through the water'.
<P>
They can say that again. 
<P>
A very Happy Christmas Blackout to you all...
<P>


<P>
<BR>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996. 


