<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The Ken Speckle Papers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The Ken Speckle Papers</H1>
<H2>An Alarming Epistle from Grim Story Esq.</H2>
<HR>

<P>

</center>
<P><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="speckbig.jpg" hspace=10 vspace=5>
<I>Being further extracts from the papers of the Reverend Kenneth Speckle BD (failed), Edin, (1747 - ?), sometime incumbent of the disjoined parish of Stobister and pendicles, edited and prepared for the press, at no inconsiderable pains, by Dr Jonathan Wills.</I>
<P>

<P>

<br clear=all>

<HR>

<P>
<i>
<P>
<STRONG>My journal, kept at ye Manse of Stobister, Breezey Isle, Zetland.  ye 28th day of October, yr. of our Lord 1796.</STRONG>
</I>
<br clear=all>

<P>
<P>
Young Grinnyskull and Dicka Nastigirth called by this morning with a missive under the hand of Grim Story Esq., limner and engraver at Lerook. It bore the legend 'Most Urgent and Confidential' but I had perforce to wait some hours before opening it, while my visitors sat in the parlour tasting the latest consignment of claret, new brought on the 'Shark' from the port of Ardwell in Galloway, and discoursing at length on matters parochial.
<P>
When at last they rose and departed, opining that the vintage was 'ower weel', I retreated to my study where, with trembling hands, I opened Mr Story's communication. It read as follows:
<P>
'Respected and reverend Sire,
<P>
'I have the honour to inform you of a most remarkable circumstance concerning the character and conduct of your former friend, Cap'n Bob Wellshot of Sharniefield, in the town of Lerook. As you will recall, Cap'n Wellshot was some years past entrusted with the management of 'Ye Zetland Intelligencer', and the emoluments therefrom, after a lengthy selection procedure involving minute examination of the register of births.
<P>
'All went well for a time, until Cap'n Wellshot refused a request by his scribes for higher wages. He not unreasonably maintained that all available funds were required for the construction and fitting out of his new barque, the 'Peyroise', whereupon the disgruntled hands enrolled in a combination and threatened to withdraw their labour. At this, Cap'n Wellshot flew into a passion and placed an announcement in the publick prints at Edinburgh, soliciting inquiries from suitably qualified artisans to replace the malcontents.
<P>
'Cap'n Wellshot had some time before engaged as editor of his organ a down-at-heel blackguard, that repellent radical, Dr Witney Garlick. Dr Garlick, being on friendly terms with the mutineers, took it upon himself to intervene and persuaded the ringleaders to accept of Cap'n Wellshot's handsome offer of a farthing a day. He then presented himself at his employer's chambers, anticipating congratulations, and intimated that he would be pleased to agree to a similar augmentation of his own salary.
<P>
'The proprietor astonished Garlick by upbraiding him in the presence of a common journeyman printer, refused his request and roared that Garlick must sign new indentures which would permit Cap'n Wellshot to write the weekly commentaries on publick affairs himself. This the editor refused, whereupon he was threatened with physical violence, peremptorily dismissed the service of Ye Zetland Intelligencer and ejected from the portals of Castle Sharniefield, with Cap'n Wellshot's intemperate imprecations raining about his head.
<P>
'Dr Garlick, as you well remember, thereupon closeted himself in your cellar with sundry sympathetic Writers to the Signet and subsequently sued Cap'n Wellshot at law, the upshot of which was that Cap'n Wellshot was so horrified when he heard what Dr Garlick proposed to tell the tribunal, that he promptly settled the case out of court for a sum equivalent to a year's wages, and appointed a relative, Mistress Trout, in the good doctor's stead.
<P>
'The money was soon drunk and for some years Garlick eked out a pitiful existence, retailing tittle-tattle to the cheaper sort of penny sheets upon the continent of Scotland but, about a twelvemonth past, he commenced in business with the undersigned. I had, as you may have heard, devised an ingenious method of evanescent publishing, employing a lanthron of exceptional brilliance, a complicated arrangement of prisms, an abacus, seventeen yards of stout twine and several distorting mirrors (manufactured by a Mr Fresnel). With this apparatus we were able to project the image of a page of writing upon walls at a great distance, and soon began daily transmissions of intelligences both local and national.
<P>
'My reason for engaging Dr Garlick was that, notwithstanding his loathsome personal habits, execrable political opinions and notorious, irreligious character, I found him an indefatigable scribbler, willing to work long hours in a damp cellar for small reward. 
<P>
'We had considerable success with our 'Evanescent Zetlander and Daily Advertiser for Ye County of Zetland and Many Other Parts Forebye' and soon gentlemen of quality were favouring us with commissions to compose announcements extolling the virtues of their goods and services to the publick. 
<P>
'This came to the attention of Cap'n Wellshot, who had for years nurtured a simmering resentment over Dr Garlick's success against him at law. Cap'n Wellshot being well furnished with manservants, scullery wenches and specie, he determined to gain a monopoly of this new science and ordered an underling to construct an evanescent publishing apparatus superior to mine own, regardless of expense. This task the underling performed to the best of his abilities but, the hapless youth being but a novice in the art, the resulting contraption was deficient in almost every particular.
<P>
'What was the more aggravating was that, every time Cap'n Wellshot selected a suitable wall for a-projecting of his own intelligences and announcements (for no customers had favoured him with theirs), he found his publick distracted by a parallel and simultaneous, but infinitely more entertaining, display from my apparatus. His roars of outrage could, it is reliably reported, be heard in the Isle of Breezey with a favourable wind.
<P>
'When he discovered that my evanescent publishing machine was able (by bending the light from his own emissions through a superior prism) to project images of 'Ye Zetland Intelligencer' upon my chosen wall, dyke, window pane or even wooden panelling, thus augmenting considerably the pitiably small audience he had secured for his business, his wrath and wounded pride knew no bounds. He engaged lawyers at vast expense to pursue Dr Garlick and me at the Lawting, and obtained injunctions preventing us from intercepting his transmissions - or even utilizing the same walls.
<P>
'The lawyers at first cautioned him against such a proceeding (knowing full well that the law of copy writing could not encompass evanescent publishing) but, seeing him determined upon it and that he was willing to make them even richer men than they already were, did his bidding.
<P>
'The result, Respected Sire, is that you are joined in the lawsuit as a co-conspirator of Dr Garlick, and liable to lose all your goods and chattels along with him, even if Cap'n Wellshot's plea should fail, as it most certainly will. For the expenses of lawyers are such that many good families have thus been ruined and brought low by cynical and vindictive litigation, leaving the legally vanquished as monetary victors.
<P>
'The purpose of my communication is to advise you most urgently of your peril, and to offer, gratis, the services of my barber and wig-maker, should you wish to alter your appearance and flee the countrey of Zetland, as I heartily exhort you to do. Dr Garlick has already shaved off his 30-year growth of beard and looks 50 years older, now that the ravages of time and dissipation are revealed to his horrified contemporaries - who know him not. He and I sail on the morrow's evening tide for another jurisdiction, where we and our apparatus shall be free from the legal threats lying over us, and free also to continue our business with impunity. I pray you shall accompany us, for your temporal salvation and the rescue of your honour from obloquy. 
<P>
'I have the honour to remain, as ever, Your obedient servant and solicitous co-religionist,
<P>
<img src="/pics/mark.gif" align=left>
<br clear=all>
<I>(Grim Story, His Mark)'</I>
<P>
This extraordinary epistle hath left me quite dis-commoded. I know not what to do, but the omnipotent wrath of Cap'n Wellshot strikes fear into my heart and I am now almost decided to take ship with Mr Story and his accomplice. I shall sleep upon the matter and meantime instruct my housekeeper to pack my trunks.
<P>
<I>(<B>Editor's note:</B> At this point the journal becomes indecipherable, owing to copious maroon-coloured stains which laboratory analysis has recently shown to be a mixture of human blood and a claret of 1795 vintage, from the Bordeaux region of France. A singular curiosity is a crude stamp across the manuscript, evidently of later date, which says 'Copyright and Personal Property of Captain Robert Wellshot, Master of All He Surveys'.  There is also a suspicious tear through several pages of the journal, which appears to have been made by the point of a dagger or kitchen knife. A further report on the forensic tests will appear in a future edition of The Ken Speckle Papers.)
<P>
</I>



<HR>


