<DOCHDR>
http://www.shetland-news.co.uk:80/funny/speckle5.html 194.72.245.173 19970110105016 text/html 11021
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 10:50:20 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 10849
Last-modified: Mon, 16 Sep 1996 12:40:29 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - The Ken Speckle Papers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>The Ken Speckle Papers</H1>

<HR>
<P>
(This feature also appears in the Hairst 1996 edition of 'The New Shetlander' magazine).

<P>

</center>
<P><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="speckbig.jpg" hspace=10 vspace=5>
<i>Being further extracts from the papers of the Reverend Kenneth Speckle BD (failed), Edin, (1747 - ?), sometime incumbent of the disjoined parish of Stobister and pendicles, edited and prepared for the press, at no inconsiderable pains, by Dr Jonathan Wills.

<P>

<P>

<br clear=all>

<HR>

<P>
<i>
Manse of Stobister, Breezey Isle, Zetland.  ye 15th day of September, yr. of our Lord 1796
<BR>

<P>
<STRONG>Unto the Hon'ble. Sir Michael Firspyte PC, Lord High Keeper of the Great Seal of Scotland, at the Castle of Edinburgh:</STRONG>
</I>
<br clear=all>

<P>

Respected Sire,

<P>
Your esteemed favour of the 23rd June, requesting further intelligences concerning the state of society and morals in this archipelago, reached me only this day by Dicka Nastigirth's hand. He apologised profusely for the tardiness of delivery, explaining that the master of Mr Pino's sailing packet had been uncertain whether to continue carrying His Majesty's mails, in view of the recent controversy anent the Government bounties upon the sail packet trade betwixt Zetland and the continent of Scotland.
<P>
There is much to report. I shall endeavour fully to acquaint you with the situation, employing my customary brevity of expression.
<P>
There hath lately been a great revolution in the Zetland Commission of Supply, Canon Shand having been ousted by a junto of Sir Jas. Bloob, Lady Eastings and Commissioners Wullamandra Whitret, Magnus Defects and Grotty Redlen. Canon Shand continues to wear the fineries of office and to preside, nominally, at publick sessions of the Commissioners, but his writ runs no longer.
<P>
The occasion of the coup d'etat was the signing of a new covenant with the British Peat Oil Company. Canon Shand weakly protested the document, whining that it amounted to unconditional capitulation to the demands of this enterprising company of adventurers.
<P>
This cavilling Sir Jas. silenced with the immortal words: 'Nivirduleetboy. Dirgottenwis biddabaasan doolchoost haytasignit. Hayta, man! Hayta! Anmi chobsatstekk, furbye.'
<P>
It was, however, the decisive intervention of that great benefactor of mankind, Mr Black Mekkie, which convinced the remaining doubters of the wisdom and propriety of agreeing terms: 'Boogasuv gorrusbeatlads. Amnotblurry Eeanclark. Kupper dirrisbest, burrit worrunt goorenuff.'
<P>
At this, Canon Shand fled the chamber with a wild shriek. He was later heard sobbing at the offices of Mistress Waddermary, the Town Crier, where he made a poor fist of explaining the Solemn Vod bargain to the assembled multitude, rioting in protest beneath the balcony. Some of the impertinent, ungrateful wretches - boors from the island of Whalesahoy - thereupon took a handsaw and attempted to cut through the timbers supporting what remained of the Canon's civic dignity.
<P>
As Commissioner Whitret observed that same evening, when conversing with some gentlemen from the City of London, lately come north to explain the state of the Commissioners' finances to the cashier Thews: 'It seems to be the amends which nature makes to those whom she has not blessed with an elevation of mind, to indulge them in the comfortable mistake, that all is wrong which falls not within the narrow limits of their own comprehensions and relish.'
<P>
At the next meeting of the Commissioners, Mr Thews had doleful tidings. The Treasury was bare, notwithstanding the pact with British Peat and the Shalloot Corporation. Immediate economies were imperative.
<P>
Stilling the feeble murmurings of such few Commissioners as presumed to question the veracity of Mr Thews' statement, and uninterrupted by the stoical Inspector of Schools, Mr Hakkie Rollover MA (who bore his customary glazed countenance, the while humming leisurely to himself), Sir Jas. Bloob outlined his prospectus for restoring thrift to the countrey of Zetland:
<P>
<i>Item First:</i> The parochial schools in the remoter districts to be suppressed forthwith, there having been numerous complaints from masters of quarries and manufactories, that the schools had tended much to corrupt their servants, by teaching them to read and write; that they would be more obedient and dutiful, were they more ignorant and had no education.
<P>
At this, the venerable Commissioner Billsmitten ventured a halting protest: 'The institution of parochial schools is to the honour, as well as the utility of Zetland,' he said, whereupon several of those present feigned drowsiness. 'It shows the wisdom and patriotism of our ancestors in a high degree,' he continued, to the sound of snoring from the benches opposite. 'At these necessary and useful little seminaries of literary knowledge, established in every parish, many have received the first principles of literature and religious knowledge, who have become ornaments to their country, and blessings to mankind.'
<P>
Sir Jas. ignored this interjection and gave the floor to Lady Eastings: 'Might not the schoolmasters also keep the side post offices, where only a runner is requisite?' she inquired. 'The opportunity of the scholars would be yet very useful in sending intimation of letters lying at the office to persons who do not regularly call at the office, thus saving the inordinate expense of a postmaster.'
<P>
Commissioner Whitret indicated that he wished to assist Lady Eastings in her quest for economies: 'Dukeens, whinnayewissabairn, deymeddwis takkapaet ta'a skule wiwirrsletts, anmimidderwiswint tamakka draaerfooa gruel apo da Sabbath nicht fur wir wikksdenners. Kinweeno sevvtwaatree penniesdatwye?'
<P>
Sir Jas. beamed benevolently upon the stout-hearted, well-intentioned representative of the landed interest from Solemn Vod: 'Ayedootitill takkmairasdat,' he said, and proceeded with his prescription for frugality.
<P>
<i>Item Second:</i> Instant suspension of the disgraceful practice, but lately intimated to Mr Thews as a result of his diligent inquiries among carters and packmen, of conveying able-bodied scholars to school at the publick expense.
<P>
At this, there were cries of: 'Fie! For shame!' 'This is a scandal!' and 'Naebdytellwis abootdat, Chim!' The assembly thereupon spontaneously voted a unanimous resolution of approbation for this proposal (Commissioner Slimbo having absented himself briefly from the chamber to answer the call of Nature).
<P>
<i>Item Third:</i> Disposal of the Poor's Dwellings, for a trifling consideration, to the Adolph Rachman Provident Society for the Relief of Distress in Congested Districts, this having been advocated by no less a person than the Hon'ble. Sir Michael Firspyte, a personal friend of Mr Rachman.
<P>
This was likewise approved, Mr Slimbo not having returned from the privy offices. Mr Defects then vouchsafed the opinion that, as the outer islands were now so sparsely inhabited, it might answer the Treasury's needs if they were to relieve the publick of the expense of ferries to those remote districts, their crews being the most unmannerly and importunate gang of over-remunerated rascals it had ever been his misfortune to encounter.
<P>
Sir Jas. cordially thanked Mr Defects for his contribution: 'Magniedatwis daverraneeist tingapomilist!' quoth he.
<P>
Commissioner Youngjock, the Master of Keldabister, could take no more of this: 'I say, dat's a frightfully bad show, du keens, Chim!' he said. 'Du personally assured me afore dis convocation commenced dat du jolly well widna vent dy prejudices on my constituents in Breezey, what?'
<P>
Sir Jas. retorted: 'Dirnaeneedo pankin,'
<P>
'I beg dy pardon?' said Keldabister.
<P>
'Knappin airsfurst,' Sir Jas. snapped and, with a well-aimed gavel at Commissioner Hendrasdochter, moved next business.
<P>
At this point Mr Smeeg slid into the chamber, wearing hose and doublet several sizes too large for him, and whispered into Mr Black Mekkie's ear. Mr Black Mekkie then rasped inaudibly into Sir Jas. Bloob's sinistral aural appendage.
<P>
'Bairns, bairns, wullhayta gitootahere, whick! Dirfan dryrottida riffoda toonhoose!' Sir Jas. exclaimed, leading the stampede for the marble staircase.
<P>
The next item on the agenda was thus not reached but it behoves me to inform you of it, nonetheless. It was a motion in the name of Mr Black Mekkie himself, ordering the expenditure of 13,100 pounds Scots for consultant gentlemen to advise on how best to fit up and expedite a testimonial dinner for Mr Thews, who had detected, amongst his clerks and serving wenches, the unmistakable signs of moral turpitude, lascivious conduct and excessive indulgence in tea, snuff, laudanum and hallucinatory fungi.
<P>
The public spirited and indefatigable Mr Thews (according to an unpublished encomium in my possession, drafted by Mr Black Mekkie's man of business, Mr Yawn Risible) had unhesitatingly penned a missive to all his subordinates, instructing them to report instantly to him any suspicions of improper or immoral conduct by their fellows, on pain of dismissal.
<P>
Furthermore, upon word of this memorandum reaching the publick prints, Mr Thews had interrogated in his cellar an underling suspected of betraying, to Dr Witney Garlick's semaphore scandal sheet, 'Ye Daily Zetlander', the existence of this confidential communication. The said underling, notwithstanding membership of an illegal combination or 'union', had broken down and confessed, immediately upon being shown 'the instruments'.
<P>
If any further intelligences should reach me, dear sir, fear not that I shall lose no time in communicating same to you, via the good offices of Dicka Nastigirth and his runner, Young Grinnyskull.
<P>
I remain, with the utmost respect and my compliments to the Great Seal,
<P>
Your humble servant in Christ,
<P>
(Kenneth Speckle BD (failed), Edin.)
<P>
<i>Post scriptum: I am obliged to you for the remittance which, I greatly fear, is excessively handsome remuneration for such small services as I am able to perform for you and His Majesty.
</i>




<HR>


