<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Shetland Museum Exhibitions - 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Shetland Museum</H1>
<H2>Exhibitions Diary 1996</H2>

Shetland Museum,<BR> Lower Hillhead, Lerwick ZE1 OEL
<BR>
TEL (01595) 695057
<BR>
FAX (01595) 696729<BR>
Feel free to  
<A HREF="mailto:shetland.museum@zetnet.co.uk"><img src="/pics/bigemail.gif"></a> the Museum if you would like more details.
<ALIGN=center>
<HR>
<P>
<STRONG>
Please note that the programme of exhibitions below<BR> is subject to alteration at any time

</STRONG>
<P>
<HR>
</center>


<P>
<STRONG>24TH AUG.-13TH SEPT. - JANE COX MARTIN
</STRONG><BR>
Jane studied at Salisbury College of Art and, during 30 years, has painted in Scotland and Shetland, England and France. Formerly living in Hillswick, she now lives with her husband at Walls.
<P>
<STRONG>DOD DOW- 'Same Old Rock'
</STRONG><BR>
This is Dod's third show in the Museum gallery, as Shetland continues to inspire his work. Several of his watercolours depict older dwellings, crofts and outbuildings, and the unchanging, unyielding aspect of the landscape. Others feature boats and harbours, with the ever-present sea and sky.
<P>
<STRONG>14TH SEPT.-4TH OCT. - JENNA & LIZZA HUME
</STRONG><BR>
Jenna's work is based largely on the ever-changing landscape of Westray, her home island. The sea is an important source of ideas for her work, providing a sense of continuity with the past yet a feeling of impermanence and change. Lizza combines knitted pieces and other media to serve as a record of her experiences of life on an island. The colours found in the flotsam and jetsam of the beach have influenced the natural faded shades which are present in her work.
<P>
<STRONG>5TH-25TH OCTOBER - RAB MILLER & MICK DONLEAVY
</STRONG><BR>
Rab is showing another set of mood paintings and some sculptures, capturing the essence of today's varied cultures and styles. Mick's first ever exhibition is inspired by the wildlife and scenery in Shetland. He also experiments in different media, and has an interest in body art.
<P>
<STRONG>26TH OCT.-15TH NOV. - ANITA COUTTS
</STRONG><BR>
Anita, whose past work has been mainly colourful, surreal work, brings together a range of Shetland watercolour paintings of people and places from the past.
<P>
<STRONG>SHONA ANDERSON
</STRONG><BR>
Shona has lived in Reawick all her life, and trained as a model painter before taking up a placement at Bonhoga Gallery. She has been painting for the last few years, mostly in finely-detailed watercolours of animals.
<P>
<STRONG>16TH NOV.-6TH DEC. - PETER BRUCE
</STRONG><BR>
Peter plans to exhibit mainly Shetland, Scottish and, possibly, New Zealand watercolour landscapes, plus some figure paintings.
<P>
<STRONG>SOUTH MAINLAND ART GROUP
</STRONG><BR>
This is the second exhibition by the Group, formed in 1992. The group provides opportunities for members to learn through the experience of others. This exhibition will show the wide variety of styles and subjects produced by members throughout the year.
<P>
<STRONG>7TH-31ST DEC. - STEPHEN GORDON
</STRONG><BR>
Born and brought up in Lerwick, Stephen started drawing cartoons under the name 'Smirk' while at University. For over 15 years he has contributed to the Shetland Times cartoons of both a political and general satirical nature. This exhibition, mostly in watercolours, offers an insight into some of his more 'serious' work.
<P>
<STRONG>SUSAN TIMMINS
</STRONG><BR>
Susan will be showing a series of black and white photographs which will reflect her long-time preoccupation with emigration and its effects on subsequent generations.






<P>
<BR clear=all>

