<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Call to widen tug campaign

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Call to widen tug campaign
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
8th November 1996
<P>
Despairing of the Government paying for a salvage tug to help tankers  that get into trouble around Shetland, the islands' marine director  is calling for a wider political campaign.
<P>
Captain George Sutherland will tell Shetland Islands Council's marine  committee next week that shipping minister Lord Goschen 'has no  intention of positioning a salvage tug in the Fair Isle area this  winter', despite a Government report recommending an emergency towing  vessel for the south Shetland coastline where the tanker 'Braer'  drifted ashore almost four years ago.
<P>
In papers for the meeting, published yesterday (THURS) Capt.  Sutherland reports that the council has support from Orkney Islands  Council, local MP Jim Wallace and the shipping trade press. He  recommends councillors should 'maintain pressure through enlisting  wider political support and continuing with media exposure where possible'. 
<P>
He also wants to pursue the matter through the European Union and  with the leaders of other councils in the Highlands and Islands.
<P>
Council convener Lewis Smith has already written to Lord Goschen  expressing 'grave concern' at the lack of action following a report  by Captain Chris Belton RN, who came down in favour of a  two-million-pounds-a-year salvage tug to cover the Fair Isle Channel  during the winter months.
<P>
Lord Goschen recently replied, saying he had 'favourable reports' of  'trials' with such vessels in the Dover Straits, the South-Western  Approaches and the Minch. But he said the risk of accidents was lower  in Shetland because 'marine traffic is comparatively light'.
<P>
'Harbour tugs can also provide some cover and offshore supply vessels  with towing capabilities do operate in the area,' the minister said.
<P>
'Emergency towing vessels are not a cheap solution to the problem of  vessels in difficulty and we can only embark on such major, long-term  expenditure when we are fully convinced that they will give the  taxpayer good value for money,' he concluded.
<P>
Capt. Sutherland says the minister has 'misplaced faith' in the  capacity of harbour tugs in severe weather and in suitable tugs which  may just happen to be passing when there is an incident.
<P>
A similar campaign is running in Orkney, where marine director  Captain Bob Sclater strongly backs Capt. Sutherland's arguments but  says the Pentland Firth is even more dangerous than the Fair Isle  Channel, with stronger tides and more tanker traffic, and needs an  emergency towing vessel of its own. 
<P>
Capt. Sclater points out that the number of large vessels using the  Pentland Firth will increase next year when shuttle tankers start  hauling 50,000 tonne oil cargoes to the Flotta terminal from the new  Foinaven oilfield.
<P>
Emergency towing vessels were stationed in Prince William Sound,  Alaska, following the 'Exxon Valdez' disaster in 1989, and in  Cornwall after the 'Sea Empress' pollution earlier this year.
<P>










<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

