<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Fisherman drowns despite brave rescue attempt
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Fisherman drowns despite brave rescue attempt
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

26th July 1996
<P>
A young Peterhead fisherman risked his life in a vain attempt to save a drowning shipmate off Shetland early yesterday (THURS) morning.
<P>
The trawler 'Sharona' was hauling nets 47 miles south-east of Sumburgh Head when crewman John Main, 58, fell overboard around midnight.
<P>
Twenty-one year old Gordon Strachan dived in to help him but Mr Main, of Ugie Road, Peterhead, appeared to be dead before the rest of the crew could pull him and Mr Strachan out of the water.
<P>
Within 40 minutes of the accident, Shetland Coastguard's rescue helicopter 'Oscar Charlie' was on the scene with a doctor on board. Both men were winched up and flown to hospital in Lerwick, where Mr Main was pronounced dead.
<P>
Mr Strachan was later released from hospital into the care of the Lerwick Fishermen's Mission, who arranged his travel home to Mallard Drive, Peterhead. 
<P>
It is understood that Mr Main, the ship's cook, was sitting on the rail when he was struck by the trawl cod end and knocked over the side.
<P>
Mr Strachan was unhurt. Although 'very shaken and numbed', he spared the victim's family the distress of having to identify the body, by going with police to the Lerwick mortuary to do it himself.
<P>
Fishermen's Mission Superintendent Cliff Powell said: 'He's a very brave young man.'
<P>
The 'Sharona' meanwhile headed for Peterhead, where she was expected to dock last night.




<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

