<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Tanker with 'pinhole' leak sent away
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Tanker with 'pinhole' leak sent away
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


26th July 1996
<P>
The Liberian tanker which spilled oil in Sullom Voe on Tuesday was due to sail for a repair yard last night (THURS), without her 120,000 tonne cargo of North Sea crude.
<P>
Council harbour officials and oil terminal operators BP ordered the 135,000 tonne 'Eurus' to empty cargo tanks and leave the port after divers failed to locate the source of the leak of up to three tonnes of oil.
<P>
Depute port director Jim Dickson said it appeared to be 'a pinhole' which had only leaked under pressure when the tanker was loading. The 'Eurus' was 'perfectly safe' to sail.
<P>
He said the ship's classification society - responsible for providing certificates of seaworthiness - would be informed of the incident.
<P>
The pollution was sprayed with dispersants and cleaned up by wave and propeller action.




<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

