<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Isles welcome Tory price controls on sea freights
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Isles welcome Tory price controls on sea freights
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

24th July 1996
<P>
Scots Secretary Michael Forsyth's new price controls on sea freights to the Northern Isles, and the restoration of subsidy for bulk cargoes, were greeted with delight in Shetland last night (TUES).
<P>
Councillor Magnus Flaws, chairman of Shetland Islands Council's transport committee, said on local radio: 'We're very happy indeed. We made reasoned arguments and the Scottish Office seems to have listened to them.'
<P>
He welcomed the price ceilings, announced by Mr Forsyth in a Commons written answer: 'This does away with the monopoly position people were worried about,' Mr Flaws said.
<P>
He was particularly pleased with the guarantee that, whichever company won the contract to run the 'lifeline' passenger/cargo service between Lerwick and Aberdeen, they would have to carry livestock during the peak autumn shipping season.
<P>
The increased subsidy on livestock exports, from 33 per cent up to 50 per cent of freight costs, was 'a benefit to us, and a good one', he said.
<P>
The council was delighted the way was now open for a privately owned shipping company to secure European funding for building new ships on the route. P&O Scottish Ferries' two Shetland ferries are both over 25 years old.
<P>
There was also relief that the Government rejected the idea of running the Aberdeen-Lerwick service with only one ship: 'It's all good news for Shetland,' said Mr Flaws, a member of the Shetland Movement party campaigning for more home rule in the islands.
<P>
P&O Scottish ferries managing director Terry Cairns said he had not yet studied Mr Forsyth's statement in detail but it appeared to contain 'no problems' for the company.
<P>
P&O are currently bidding to retain the Government-subsidised ferry services to Orkney and Shetland, under a tendering process started by Mr Forsyth's predecessor, Ian Lang MP.
<P>
The Scots Secretary made his statement in response to a report on ferries by the Scottish Affairs Committee, which took evidence in Shetland last winter.
<P>
'The Government's overriding priority remains the need to ensure the viability of the lifeline passenger services to Orkney and Shetland,' Mr Forsyth said.




<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

