<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Council ports boss condemns 'nonsensical' refusal to make marine insurance compulsory
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Council ports boss condemns 'nonsensical' refusal 
<BR>to make marine insurance compulsory
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

24th July 1996
<P>
Government arguments against compulsory insurance for ships are 'nonsensical', according to Shetland Islands Council's marine director, Captain George Sutherland.
<P>
For three years the council has been urging shipping ministers to make all vessels carry insurance in British waters, so that there is someone to pay up if a ship runs aground and spills oil.
<P>
In papers published yesterday (TUES) for next week's council policy committee, an exasperated Capt. Sutherland makes an outspoken attack on the Government, accusing ministers of 'procrastination' over three years.  He says a consultation document sent out last month shows the Government is 'reluctant to make continued trading conditional on holding appropriate insurance'.
<P>
'This is clearly wholly unsatisfactory,' he tells councillors, noting that the council is still 1.5 million pounds out of pocket for helping to clear up the mess after the 'Braer' tanker wreck. The Government itself had costs of 600,000 pounds after an uninsured Russian fish factory ship, the 'Borodinsky Polye', foundered near Lerwick in late 1993.
<P>
The Department of Transport argues that insurers cannot be compelled to provide cover: 'In extreme market conditions business operations might be placed beyond the law by a requirement to be insured,' the consultation paper says. 
<P>
Compulsory insurance could 'distort the working of a free market' and put insurers under 'moral pressure' to cover 'commercially unsound' risks, civil servants believe.
<P>
Capt Sutherland's scathing reply is that this is 'nonsensical' and unworkable.  If shipowners cannot afford to insure hulls, machinery and cargoes, they should not be in business, he says.
<P>
He also advises councillors to press for a national contingency plan to deal with oil spills and formalise who is responsible for what. He rejects Government pleas for 'voluntary agreements' to carry out 'non-statutory, implicit duties' after spills.
<P>
'For so long as the Government fails to require compulsory insurance for all vessels in UK waters, local authorities and harbour authorities dare not commit themselves to unconditional agreements,' he says.
<P>
Capt. Sutherland says he was 'surprised' the council was left off the Government's list of organisations to be consulted, but recommends they  send a strongly worded letter to the Transport Department.




<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

<HR>







