<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Wallace renews call for a tug
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Wallace renews call for a tug
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
21st June 1996
<P>
The Scottish Liberal Democrat leader, Jim Wallace MP, last night 
[THUR] renewed his plea for the Government to station a salvage tug 
in his Orkney and Shetland constituency.
<P>
For the third year running since the tanker 'Braer' drifted 
helplessly onto rocks in Shetland in 1993, Mr Wallace said harbour 
tugs at the Sullom Voe and Flotta oil terminals were 'not really 
adequate' to help a disabled tanker in the open sea.
<P>
He welcomed shipping minister Lord Goschen's decision to pay for a 
tug off Wales and Cornwall this winter, in addition to those 
stationed at Dover and Stornoway, but said: 'This only underlines the 
need for a similar salvage tug ... around Orkney and Shetland.'
<P>
He assumed the two tugs already in place had proved their worth but, 
in view of a recent tanker incident in the Minches after the 
Stornoway tug's winter contract had ended, he urged the minister to 
look at all-year-round salvage cover.
<P>
In a letter to Lord Goschen, he said: 'I appreciate that any 
additional cover does cost money, but surely the experience of the 
'Braer' and the 'Sea Empress' highlights just how much it costs NOT 
to have adequate precautions in place.'



<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

