<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Tanker had engine failure at Sullom Voe</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>Tanker had engine failure at Sullom Voe</H1>
<H2>           </H2>
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
28th March 1996
<P>
A Norwegian tanker suffered an engine failure while leaving the Sullom Voe oil terminal last month, it was revealed yesterday (Wednesday).
<P>
A report to Shetland Islands Council's marine committee said the engine of the tanker 'Prospekt' failed on February 24 as she was leaving Jetty One in the council-controlled port.
<P>
After the ship was brought alongside again, engineers found the problem was a faulty governor. The ship was repaired and allowed to sail, council officials said.
<P>
Two other incidents involving tankers last month are detailed in the report, published yesterday. 
<P>
A Liberian tanker, the 'Knock Sheen' had too much oxygen in her tanks - a potential fire risk - and was sent out to sea again on February 28, until inert gas levels were restored.
<P>
Inspection of the Bahamian tanker 'Singa Star' on February 19 showed an instrument on the bridge was not working properly.
<P>
Both ships subsequently loaded their cargoes and sailed without any more trouble.
<P>
Council policy is to publish even minor incidents involving tankers at Sullom Voe, partly as a deterrent to sub-standard ships.


<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

