<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Air crash report calls for better runway lighting

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Air crash report calls for better runway lighting
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
7th November 1996
<P><A HREF="crash4.jpg"><IMG SRC="crash4s.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=270 HEIGHT=130 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
A report by accident investigators into the Shetland air ambulance  crash six months ago says better runway lighting is needed at  Tingwall Airstrip, where the Loganair plane was trying to land at  night in crosswinds gusting to gale force.
<P>
The cause of the crash may not be known until after a Fatal Accident  Inquiry in February.
<P>
The accident bulletin, from the Air Accidents Investigation Branch  (AAIB) of the Department of Transport, says the pilot was effectively  flying 'blind' and could not see the airfield lights as he banked the  plane in a tight turn on his second attempt to land. He had earlier  overshot because of the crosswind.
<P>
The airstrip owners, Shetland Islands Council, say they are  discussing improvements with the Civil Aviation Authority, while  Loganair have already imposed new wind, visibility and height limits  on night-flying by pilots with less than a year's experience of the  Shetland airstrips.
<P>
The pilot, Capt. Alan Young (37) died instantly when the  Britten-Norman Islander plane hit the ground at 125 knots, a mile  short of the Tingwall runway, at 11.36pm on May 19 this year. He had  been based in Shetland for nine months and was married with two young children.
<P>
A doctor on board was seriously injured. His life was saved by the  only other passenger, a nurse who escaped with minor injuries. They  were returning to their base at Lerwick's Gilbert Bain Hospital after  a 200-mile mercy flight taking a patient to Raigmore Hospital, Inverness.
<P>
The report, published yesterday (WED), finds the twin-engined plane  was fully certificated, properly maintained and airworthy, with all  systems functioning normally at the moment of impact. The position of  the controls suggested Capt. Young was trying to gain height when he crashed.
<P>
Captain Young was a fully licensed pilot with over 3,800 hours'  flying experience, including eight night landings at Tingwall in the  previous six months. Because of a 'miscalculation', his medical  certificate had expired 19 days before the fatal flight, technically  invalidating his radio licence, but he had made an appointment for  his medical during the week of the accident. Loganair have since  improved their record-keeping to make sure this cannot happen again,  the report says.
<P>
The post-mortem produced no evidence of medical problems which could  have affected Capt. Young's performance on the night of the crash. He  was 15 minutes over his permitted duty hours for the day but this was  within the limits of 'discretion'.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Cause still unknown</B></CENTER>
<P>
The bulletin does not blame Capt. Young or establish the cause of the  accident but implies that he may have become disoriented by the lack  of ground lights in the narrow valley where he had to turn the plane  to line up for the final approach to the runway.
<P><A HREF="crash7.jpg"><IMG SRC="crash7s.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=252 HEIGHT=172 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
The weather at the time was marginal, with a strong easterly wind  gusting to 37 knots, low cloud and rain. The airstrip lies a mile  north end of the narrow part of the Tingwall valley, where violent  wind squalls are common in strong crosswinds blowing over the  surrounding hills. 
<P>
Shetland Islands Council's transport director, Joe Gray, said  yesterday (WED): 'Discussions have already begun with the Civil  Aviatin Authority about the suggestion for additional lighting. There  is no criticism of the existing system, which is tested and checked  by the CAA regularly. It's a suggestion we can consider. It's not an  urgent thing.'
<P>
Transport committee chairman Magnus Flaws said: 'It's obvious that  the airport has been run to the entire satisfaction of the CAA, up to  this tragic accident. It was up to full standards.' He promised the  council would consider what more needed to be done as soon as possible.
<P>
Last night (WED) Dr Gerald Freshwater, who almost died of severe  crush injuries in the crash, said: 'It would be improper of me to say  anything that might prejudice the Fatal Accident Inquiry, or to  second-guess the comments of the AAIB inspector, still less to upset  Mrs Young further. It was a tragic occurrence and I hope that people  will remember that Captain Young lost his life in the service of others.'
<P>
Dr Freshwater (47), who is still recovering from his injuries, said:  'We must do whatever it takes to make sure there continues to be an  air ambulance here. We will always need specialist care which cannot  be provided at our local hospital, excellent as it is.'
<P>
Nurse Maureen Polson (27), who found herself still strapped in her  seat at the rear, after the tail section of the aircraft flipped over  the rest of the wreckage, was sway from Shetland yesterday (WED) and  could not be contacted for comment on the AAIB report.
<P>
<CENTER><B>Loganair were last to see report </B></CENTER>
<P>
Although the council and Dr Freshwater have had a draft copy of the  report for some weeks, Loganair managing director Scott Grier said he  first saw it in a fax from the BBC radio station in Shetland  yesterday (WED) morning.
<P>
'The bulletin has not tried to speculate on the cause of the accident  and certainly has not established the cause,' he said. 'I'm pleased  the report does not criticise the pilot or the company. We've been  flying in the islands since the late 1960s and we're continually  reviewing our procedures to make sure our operations are as safe as possible.' 
<P>
Mr Grier said he would be talking to the council about the runway  lighting recommendation, which 'made some sense' to him. 'Anything we  can do, we'll follow through,' he pledged.
<P>

The AAIB have their own home page on the Internet at <A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/aaib/aaibhome.htm">http://www.open.gov.uk/aaib/aaibhome.htm</A>.







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

