<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Foinaven hook-up may start today

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Foinaven hook-up may start today
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
7th November 1996
<P><A HREF="anchors.jpg"><IMG SRC="anchorss.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=252 HEIGHT=144 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
BP's production ship for the new Foinaven oilfield was preparing to  leave the shelter of the Shetland coast last night (WED) to hook up to ten  35-tonne anchors 100 miles offshore.
<P>
A company spokesman in Aberdeen said a last-minute snag with a steel  drum on one of the anchor handling tugs accompanying the 'Petrojarl  Foinaven' was not expected to delay the massive operation, due to  begin today (THURS).
<P>
BP denied dockside rumours that the trouble was on board the  production ship itself.
<P>
Lerwick Harbour has been busy with the big tugs over the past few  days as BP prepared to take advantage of an expected 'weather window'  after gales which set up heavy seas earlier in the week.
<P>
The 200-million-barrels Foinaven field lies in the deepest and  roughest water ever drilled in UK waters to produce oil. The  'fast-track' development has been dogged by technical problems and  labour disputes in the Spanish shipyard which converted the former  Russian ship into a 'Floating Oil Production, Storage and Offloading'  vessel, or FPSO.
<P>
First oil production is scheduled for March next year, 14 months  later than the original target, but the development is still expected  to set a record the time between discovering and bringing on stream a  major oilfield.
<P>
The 'Petrojarl Foinaven' will load 60,000-tonne shuttle tankers in  the open ocean. The field is due to be pumping 85,000 barrels a day  by 1998, with an estimated production life of up to 17 years.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

