<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Generator sales boom as first snow falls

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Generator sales boom as first snow falls
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
7th November 1996
<P><A HREF="snow2.jpg"><IMG SRC="snow2s.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=222 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Shetland retailers who sell portable electricity generators reported  good business yesterday (WED) after the first snowfalls of the winter.
<P><A HREF="snow1.jpg"><IMG SRC="snow1s.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=111 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Demand for 'gennies' was brisk at Thulecraft Ltd of Lerwick as  manager John Watt found customers looking to insure themselves  against the chaos of last winter's power cuts.
<P>
The Shetland News editorial department in Bressay is one of the local  firms installing its own standby generator, after the frustrating  experience of more than 20 power cuts this year.
<P>
After Tuesday's perfect, calm evening for Guy Fawkes Night bonfires  and fireworks, wet snow and sleet showers brought icy roads to  sheltered districts by yesterday morning and a white mantle for the  highest point of Shetland, Ronas Hill (450m). 
<P>
A brief north-easterly gale blew further wintry showers over the  islands during the day and forecasters say we are in for a chilly week.
<P>










<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

