<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Call to ban research on fertilising the sea

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Call to ban research on fertilising the sea
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
6th November 1996
<P>
Norwegian research to make plankton grow faster, by putting  artificial fertilisers into the sea, is 'dangerous nonsense'  according to the international local authorities' environmental  organisation, <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/coms/kimo/">KIMO</A>.
<P>
Speaking in Lerwick yesterday (TUES), after KIMO's sixth annual  conference in Orkney, KIMO secretary Rick Nickerson said the European  Union should immediately halt funding for the project.
<P>
The 40 councillors at the meeting unanimously condemned experiments  by the multi-national  Norwegian company Norsk Hydro to fertilise the sea with nitrates, the  chemicals which cause pollution problems in shallow coastal waters  when rain washes them out of farmers' fields into rivers.
<P>
Mr Nickerson said there could be 'disastrous' effects on life in the  oceans if the 'Maricult' experiment got out of hand.
<P>
'Once these substances are put into the sea there would be no way of  controlling their effects,' he said. 'Councillors also agreed it was  ludicrous that the European Commission should  financially support this project when it was asking local authorities  all over Europe to spend billions on sewage treatment plants - to  reduce nitrate inputs into the sea and meet EU directives on water  quality and urban waste water regulations.
<P>
'The newly-launched European research programme Maricult is a joint  scientific and industrial effort consisting of several projects,' he  explained. 'Norsk Hydro has initiated and will support Maricult which  is to run for five years. Scientists from Norwegian and German  research institutes are involved and the European Community is said  to have provided financial assistance through its marine research programme.'
<P>
Scientists have described Maricult as programme aiming at a better  understanding of how plankton growth relates to nutrients in the sea.  Norsk Hydro say the research will study the effects of adding  nutrients, along with biological ways of making the sea more  productive. They believe artificial fertilisation could increase  harvests of seafood to help make up for an expected world shortage of  food protein.
<P>
Mr Nickerson said: 'For the very first time, the ultimate goal of  marine scientists is to  release substances in large quantities into the oceans. If these  experiments are successful, they see their experiments as a precursor  to large scale ocean fertilisation.'
<P>
If it did prove possible to increase fish stocks by dumping nitrates  and other fertilisers into the sea, he said there were 'serious  questions' about the effects, which could reduce the variety of sea  life, interfere with Nature's food web, reduce oxygen levels and lead  to damaging blooms of marine algae. 
<P>
KIMO called on the European Commission to think again about the whole  project and make sure it would have no harmful effects.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

