<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Superb new trawler arrives for Whalsay crew

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Superb new trawler arrives for Whalsay crew
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
5th November 1996
<P><A HREF="antares.jpg"><IMG SRC="antaress.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=252 HEIGHT=137 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
A nine million pounds super-trawler pulled into Lerwick Harbour on  her maiden voyage from Norway yesterday (MON), altering course so the  proud skipper could show off his latest command to nurses and doctors  at Shetland's hospital.
<P>
Skipper Laurence Irvine (50), a father of five, is one of eight  shareholders in the 12-man crew of the 1,762 tonne 'Antares'. His  24-year-old son, Laurence Junior, is a crewman.
<P>
The boat handled well in a gale on the 200-mile crossing from the  builder's yard in Flekkefjord, West Norway, where she was launched  last week by the skipper's wife, Irene. 
<P>
After calling briefly at his home port of Symbister in the isle of  Whalsay, Mr Irvine made a detour on the way to Lerwick to load gear  and stores, taking the 211-foot-long steel-hulled vessel in by the  south entrance at Breiwick, where staff at the Gilbert Bain Hospital  could have a better view.
<P>
'I was in the hospital after I was taken seriously ill last year and  they looked after me very well,' he said. 'I promised them then I'd  give them a first look at the new boat.'
<P>
The project was financed by the sale of the old 185-foot purser  'Antares' (formerly the 'Radiant Star'), a loan from the Clydesdale  Bank in Lerwick and a nine per cent shipbuilder's subsidy from the  Norwegian Government. 
<P>
Asked if it was a risky investment at a time of reduced catch quotas  and uncertainty in the industry, Mr Irvine said: 'We always invest  everything we earn back in the boat. I never worry at nights about  it. You either have to move with the times or get left so far astern  you can't catch up.'
<P>
The 'Antares' is the third ship of her class built for Whalsay crews  in the past year. Islanders are currently investing over 30 million  pounds in their fleet and another new boat is due from Norway in  three weeks' time.
<P>
The crew plan to fish for herring, mackerel and other pelagic fish up  to 500 miles from home, on grounds from the west of Ireland to the  Arctic Circle.  
<P>
<CENTER><B>The fourth of the line</B></CENTER>
<P>
Skipper Irvine's first berth when he left school at 15 was with his  father on the old wooden seine-netter 'Zephyr', just 66 feet long.   Their first 'Antares' was an 86-foot purse-netter built by Forbes of  Sandhaven in 1975. 
<P>
She had the same eight shareholders as the latest, fourth, 'Antares'.  The stable partnership has been one of the successful and innovative  in an island noted for its dogged commitment to the fishing through  lean times and fat alike.
<P>
In 1978 they built their first steel ship, a 106-footer from another  yard in Flekkefjord, followed in 1985 by the purchase of the 'Radiant  Star', re-named the third 'Antares', which they lengthened to 185  feet the following year.
<P>
The new vessel is a marvel of hi-tech. Fitted with enormously  powerful winches, she handles a net worth over 100,000 pounds,  'flying' it like a kite under water on steel hawsers. The 'Antares'  can fish just above the bottom in the deep waters of the open  Atlantic, or near the surface  when pursuing shoals on the shallower  banks of the continental shelf around Shetland. 
<P>
The latest full-colour sonar on the luxuriously-appointed bridgetells  the fishing master how many fish there are, what species and how deep  they are swimming. Once on board, refrigerated seawater tanks and a  quick-freeze plant keep the catch in prime condition for market.
<P>
Satellite phones, faxes and e-mail keep the 'Antares' in constant  touch with her agents, LHD of Lerwick, and help the skipper make the  all-important decision on which market to head for to get the best price.
<P>
'With the speed of this boat and the ability to freeze the fish down  in two hours, rather than 24, we can reach markets in Scandinavia or  Britain to land the product in the best condition for the best  price,' Mr Irvine said.
<P>
<CENTER><B>'We're no Hoover' </B></CENTER>
<P>
He indignantly denied environmentalists' claims that the trend to  bigger and more efficient boats is 'hoovering up' the shoals and  destroying the sea's ecology:
<P>
'We actually have less fish to catch on the quota than with the old  boat,' he said. 'Europe has cut the mackerel quota by 30 per cent and  the herring by half. But the price of mackerel has shot up from 115  pounds a tonne to around 600, so we'll probably land less fish but  hopefully make more money.
<P>
'We're not hoovering the sea. We'll only we working full out when  we're catching species like horse mackerel and blue whiting, where  there are no catch quotas.'  
<P>
The 'Antares' is a handsome, massively-built ship, powered by a 2,800  kilowatt Wartsila diesel engine and designed to take the worst the  north-east Atlantic can throw at her. Which is just as well, because  the winter fishing for large 'Atlanto-Scandian' herring will take her  hundreds of miles into stormy Arctic waters between Iceland and  northern Norway.
<P>
Mr Irvine has never considered taking a less stressful job on shore:  'I'm not cut out for anything else,' he said. 'This boat is something  we've worked for all our lives. There's always doom and gloom in the  fishing  and I can't say it's a piece of cake but the main  uncertainty is if they keep cutting the herring and mackerel quotas.  As it stands now, I think we can scrape through. If they cut it more  we'll certainly be in trouble.'
<P>
He points out that the 'Antares' is a purely commercial venture, with  no public money involved. They did inquire about assistance from  Shetland Islands Council and were offered it, but found they could  get a slightly better interest rate from the bank.
<P>
Mr Irvine would not speculate on what size of boat the partnership  might go for next: 'The next stage is to try and pay for this one,'  he smiled, and turned to his desk to deal with a pile of official  paperwork from the Departments of Transport and Fisheries.
<P>
At this moment an electronics engineer popped his head in the door of  the skipper's cabin with a last-minute snagging list. He wanted to  know which of the crew cabins had the faulty TV set. 'I don't know.  You'd better check them all,' said Mr Irvine, as the rest of the crew  worked in a gale and rain on deck to load gear in time for fishing  trials, due to start on Thursday.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

