<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Floater seeks shelter on Day Three
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Floater seeks shelter on Day Three  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
5th November 1996
<P><A HREF="petrojarl.jpg"><IMG SRC="petrojarls.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=234 HEIGHT=150 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
BP's new oil production ship, designed to withstand the worst waves in the world had to seek shelter last night (Monday) just three days after arriving on station at the Foinaven oilfield west of Shetland.
<P>
Operation manager Leslie Thomson said the 'Petrojarl Foinaven' would be sheltering on the west side of the islands until the weather eased enough to start hooking up the ship to 10 huge anchors, already laid in 1,400 feet of water, 100 miles from land.
<P>
Mr Thomson said it was an unexpected opportunity for islanders to see the ship which otherwise would have remained out of sight over the horizon for all of her working life.
<P>
When anchored, BP say the ship can ride out hurricane force winds and seas 100 feet high.
<P>
Last night the wind was force 8 gusting 9, at the Lerwick Coastguard station.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Picture strictly Copyright of Kieran Murray, 1996.

