<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Foinaven's 'floater' arrives to hook up

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Foinaven's 'floater' arrives to hook up
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
3rd November 1996
<P>
A new phase of offshore oil development began at the weekend, in wild 
seas 100 miles out in the Atlantic west of Shetland.
<P>
BP's giant oil production ship 'Petrojarl Foinaven' arrived on 
station at the Foinaven oilfield, Britain's first 'Atlantic Frontier' 
development, at 9.30am on Saturday after a 1,130 mile journey from a 
shipyard in Spain.
<P>
The 'floater' will be held in position by 10 anchors in 1,400 feet of 
water on the edge of the continental shelf. During the winter BP plan 
to connect the 'Floating Production, Storage and Offloading facility' 
(FPSO) to flexible hoses which will bring the oil up from 
remotely-controlled seabed wellheads and manifolds into the 95,000 
barrels capacity tanks on board. 
<P>
Production is due to begin in the spring, using 60,000 tonne 
'shuttle' tankers which will moor astern of the 'Petrojarl Foinaven' 
and ship the oil to the Flotta terminal in Scapa Flow, Orkney. 
Foinaven has estimated reserves of over 200 million barrels.  Gas 
from the field will power turbines on board the FPSO or be 
re-injected to maintain pressure in the oil wells.
<P>
The project, originally described as a pioneering 'fast-track'  development, has been delayed a year by technical problems, design  changes and strikes in the shipyard where the former Soviet submarine  tender was lengthened and converted. 
<P>
The Foinaven oilfield lies under some of the roughest water in the  north-east Atlantic. The area can experience freak waves when storms  conflict with upwellings of the North Atlantic Drift current. Large  ships have been damaged by such waves but BP believe their new  floater, swivelling to face the wind and waves, can cope with the  worst the West Shetland weather can throw at it.
<P>
They say the technology of loading tankers offshore has already been  tried and tested in exposed locations in the northern North Sea,  where winter weather is almost as bad. 
<P>
After islanders voiced worries about potential pollution, the company  set up a consultative committee on environmental concerns and  produced an 83-page 'Environmental Impact Assessment' and a  five-volume oilspill contingency plan - designed to cope with any oil  which may reach the shore. Fishermen and fish farmers in the islands  are being trained to use floating booms and skimmers, to contain and  retrieve spilled oil, but BP spokesmen insist the risks of pollution  are low and spills are likely to be very small.
<P>
The company has steadfastly refused to hold a public meeting in  Orkney or Shetland to debate the environmental issues, preferring  'one-on-one' contact with the public at 'roadshows' which have  visited the islands twice.
<P>
<CENTER><B>A second bonanza in prospect?</B></CENTER>


<P>
Foinaven is the first of several fields being developed in an area  believed to contain almost half the UK's known oil reserves. Many of  the finds lie in water so deep that conventional production platforms  and submarine pipelines are not practicable. But there is speculation  that the giant Clair field, in shallower water just 40 miles west of  Shetland, may require a new pipeline to the Sullom Voe oil terminal  in the early years of the 21st century, bringing the islands a second  oil bonanza.
<P>
With the price of oil high and continuing unrest in the Middle East,  the pressure is on to solve the technical problems of producing oil  from the 'challenging' environment west of Shetland. Reserves in this  politically stable, free market area are doubly valuable when  companies reflect that only about six per cent of the world's oil  provinces are free from state ownership and control.
<P>










<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

