<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Trust spending freeze may thaw next year

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Trust spending freeze may thaw next year
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
2nd November 1996
<P>
The freeze on spending by Shetland's cash-rich charitable trust is  likely to end late next year, after trustees heard yesterday (FRI)  they had 8.1 million pounds of unspent revenue.
<P>
The trust, run by all 26 Shetland councillors and two independent  trustees, has been funded by Shetland's oil revenues over the past 20  years and now has total assets worth over 203 million pounds, 17 per  cent more than a year ago.
<P>
After setting aside funds to maintain the real value of the trust and  refurbish buildings, plus 15 per cent for 'contingencies', the  trustees still have 13.9 million pounds available next year,  according to a budget strategy report approved yesterday. But they  only plan to spend 5.8 million pounds of it.
<P>
Trust chairman Bill Manson said he felt 'disappointment and  frustration' that the council of which he is a member could not move  faster to resolve its own financial difficulties.
<P>
This 'inhibited the trust from making immediate full use of its  resources,' he said. The financial future was 'little clearer' than  it had been a year ago.
<P>
The trust's policy is only to accept spending bids previously  approved by Shetland Islands Council. For the past two years the  council has refused to agree any 'new bids'. The council, which fears  its general fund is running into an 'unsustainable' deficit, is  trying to save five million pounds a year by 2000 AD. 
<P>
Council convener Lewis Smith said after the trust meeting in Lerwick:  'During the next financial year, if the council gets its financial  situation under control, then as far as I'm concerned the council can  start making new bids to the trust.'
<P>
Mr Smith said a long-delayed care centre for elderly people in Unst  (pop. 900), Britain's most northerly inhabited island, was 'the priority'.
<P>
One reason for prudence has been uncertainty about oil revenues but a  new deal with the oil companies was signed this summer to ensure the  future of the Sullom Voe tanker terminal. 
<P>
The council also has a problem with a 60 million pounds housing debt  run up in the 1970s when thousands oil workers flooded into the  islands. Negotiations are continuing with the Government to write off  the debt, but are complicated because the money is mostly owed to  private finance houses, not to the Public Works Loan Board, and a  write-off would thus affect the Public Sector Borrowing Requirement.
<P>
Independent trustee John Scott, who is also Shetland's Lord  Lieutenant, told the meeting he objected to consideration of a report  which discussed the council's housing debt. 'This is nothing to do  with the trust,' he said. 'It is council business. These are totally  separate bodies.' Mr Scott's motion to defer the report until the  'inconsistencies' were sorted out failed to find a seconder among the  councillors around the table, who included his own son, Tavish Scott.
<P>
Mr Manson said later: 'I don't think there's any trustee who doesn't  want to spend this money. If the council takes too long to make a  decision (on new bids) then we'll have to have a serious debate about  our future policy.' He would not comment on the suggestion that the  trust might start accepting bids from outside bodies , without  reference to the council.
<P>
Candidates for helping to spend the eight million pounds surplus  include: a leisure centre at the village of Aith, for the rural areas  of the West Mainland of Shetland; a project to develop the music  industry in Shetland; and some 'non-statutory' education items, such  as extra school music tuition and nursery education. Observers  believe this could partly solve the current budget crisis in the  education department, which has called in consultants to help it save money.
<P>










<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

