<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Scalloway old folks' home is saved

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Scalloway old folks' home is saved
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
2nd November 1006
<P>
A Church of Scotland old folks' home in Shetland was saved from  closure at the second attempt yesterday (FRI), when the Shetland  Islands Council Charitable Trust approved a capital grant of up to  882,000 pounds. 
<P>
The deal to reprieve the Walter & Joan Gray Eventide Home in the  village of Scalloway faltered six weeks ago when so many councillor  trustees were away on official business that trust chairman Bill  Manson could not get a quorum.
<P>
Yesterday there was a better turnout and the grant went through on  the nod. Councillors had earlier agreed that, because it helped  continue an existing service, the project would not violate their  policy of making no new bids to the charitable trust meantime.
<P>
The grant, including VAT, will pay half the costs of rebuilding the  home but retaining the attractive facade of the 19th century building  on the Scalloway waterfront.
<P>
The council will provide up to 138,000 pounds a year towards running costs.
<P>
Council social work director Bill Bennett had earlier said there were  'compelling financial reasons' to agree the Kirk's request. It would  have cost the council 1.7 million pounds to provide a similar home  for the 10 residents and 10 day-care clients.
<P>
The Kirk had said it would have to close the home because it could  not afford to lose 119,000 pounds a year running it.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

