<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Self-help makes Yell a safer place to be

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Self-help makes Yell a safer place to be
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
2nd November 1996
<P>
It is now a lot safer to have a heart attack in one of Britain's more  remote islands.
<P>
Helped by a 50 per cent grant from the British Heart Foundation, the  1,000 residents of the Shetland island of Yell have bought a 5,600  pounds defibrillator machine for their local ambulance.
<P><A HREF="mcdonnell.jpg"><IMG SRC="mcdonnells.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=204 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Defibrillators are used to 'jump start' heart attack victims and  monitor their condition while the ambulance is on the way to  hospital, saving precious time when the patient arrives at casualty -  in this case 30 miles and a ferry crossing away from Yell.
<P>
Dr Mike McDonnell, the island's GP, says the new equipment fills a  gap in emergency care: 'Now you can choose to have your heart attack  on Yell, knowing you'll be no worse off than those in the rest of  Scotland,' he said yesterday (FRI), after the defibrillator was  formally presented to the local ambulance.
<P><A HREF="defib.jpg"><IMG SRC="defibs.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=152 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
The Scottish Ambulance Service in Shetland has assisted with training  and modified the Yell ambulance to accommodate the new equipment.
<P>
Dr McDonnell said the 'paradox' in the past had been that the further  a patient was from hospital, the less the chance of access to a defibrillator. 
<P>
'The Scottish Ambulance Service Trust has declined to provide  defibrillators to the ambulances based in the remoter areas because  of the problems of ensuring training for contractors, who are not  directly employed by the trust,' Dr McDonnell said.
<P>
'The odd ones out ... are those living in the remoter areas of  Scotland who are served by contracted-out ambulances, often based at  local garages and manned by local bus drivers or car hirers.'
<P>
Health boards in the Highlands and Islands were attempting to tackle  the problem and seeking assistance from the British Heart Foundation. 
<P>
'Frustrated by delays in supplying essential equipment, our own  remote, rural community has already solved its own problems,' the doctor said.
<P>
In Yell the islanders have set up a Health Centre Support Group which  provides equipment such as nebulisers for those with asthma, blood  testing kits for diabetes sufferers and physiotherapy equipment for home use. 
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

