<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Pupils stay home after school bus protest

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Pupils stay home after school bus protest
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
31st October 1996
<P>
Fourteen children on the west side of Shetland are staying home from  school as parents protest about a new school bus route.
<P>
The primary and secondary pupils from the crofting townships of Twatt  and Clousta did not return to school in the village of Aith this week  after the October break.
<P>
They stand at their former pick-up points each morning while the  school bus stops and waits for them a few hundred yards away. Three  minutes later, the bus drives on and the children go home.
<P>
Head teacher Glenda Moffat said today (THURS) the situation was  'regrettable' and 'unfortunate'. She said the parents had been to see  her and had stressed they were not deliberately keeping their  children home from school.
<P>
'They say they've still not been officially informed that the  arrangements have been changed,' she said.
<P>
This morning White's Coaches manager John White, who recently won the  contract in competition with a relative of one of the parents, said  he was meeting the terms of his contract with Shetland Islands Council.
<P>
'I told the parents about the new arrangements the day before the new  term started,' he said.
<P>
'I'm using a bigger bus than the former operator and bairns like it  because it's better than being crammed three to a seat in a minibus.  This tender was awarded on the basis that we would stop at the main  road pick-up points and I'm doing just that.
<P>
'I regret any inconvenience to the pupils who have to walk a little  further but the maximum extra distance is only 600 yards.'
<P>
Parent Janet Davidge said she was worried about road safety at the  point where Mr White now stops to collect the pupils: 'They have to  walk diagonally across the crossroads. There are blind corners and no  verges on the side roads. 
<P>
'It's the Wild West out here,' she said. 'In winter we have violent  gales, heavy rain and snow. The weather is absolutely hellish and  five-year-olds are expected to walk through it. By the end of  November it'll be pitch dark at that time of morning.
<P>
'We just want the bus to come the same way as before,' Mrs Davidge  said. 'We phoned the council and they said they hadn't changed the  route. We don't know who to believe any more.'
<P>
Education director Jim Halcrow backed Mr White: 'He's meeting the  terms of the contract. It's the responsibility of parents to make  sure their children go to school. We're providing transport for them  to do so. If they choose not to use it, parents must make their own  arrangements.'
<P>
He said the Clousta to Aith route was unaffected by the council's  recent decision to cut back on some school transport as an economy measure.
<P>
Today all of Aith School's pupils were kept at home - when a power  cut after a fault in a transformer blacked out the school.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

