<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  'Robust' meeting on air service complaints

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   'Robust' meeting on air service complaints
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
1st November 1996
<P>
A Shetland councillor last night (Thursday) appealed to air travellers  to tell the council about their experiences under the new set-up  after British Airways withdrew from island air services.
<P>
Tavish Scott, vice-chairman of the Shetland Islands Council transport  committee, was speaking after a 'robust' meeting where senior staff  from British Regional Airlines and Loganair were given 'a hard time'  about concerns in Shetland, Orkney and the Western Isles.
<P>
'People are already finding it difficult to book flights to go away  at Christmas-time,' he said. 'You can't necessarily get the day you  want, nor the best fare.
<P>
'There's also a big concern that it's no longer possible for business  travellers to reach Edinburgh or Glasgow from Shetland in the  morning. The airlines admitted we had a cast-iron case and they're  going to have to look at it. They know fine this shouldn't have  happened,' he said.
<P>
Mr Scott also complained about timetabling confusion, saying staff at  Sumburgh Airport did not even have a timetable when he asked for one  on his way south to the meeting.
<P>
'The people from the airlines had a hard time. They haven't done a  great job communicating to any of the island groups and people regard  it as a <I>fait accompli</I>,' he said.
<P>
He said the public could help the council argue from 'facts rather  than anecdotes' by letting the transport department know the details  of their experiences, good and bad, with the new flight arrangements.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

