<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - 'New Advance' is a new beginning for Foula
   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> 'New Advance' is a new beginning for Foula
</H1>
<H2>  </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
1st November 1996
<P><A HREF="ferry.jpg"><IMG SRC="ferrys.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=234 HEIGHT=155 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Shetland's latest ferryboat was delivered at last yesterday (Thursday)  but it will be a while yet before the 'New Advance' is snug in her  specially-built home port on the island of Foula (pop. 50).
<P>
Around 40 local people and journalists greeted the 38-foot boat as  she chugged into the west Shetland port of Scalloway just before 10am  yesterday after an overnight voyage from the builders' yard in  Stromness, Orkney.
<P><A HREF="lewis.jpg"><IMG SRC="lewiss.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=238 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>

Welcoming the new arrival on behalf of Shetland Islands Council,  Convener Lewis Smith said: 'I'm absolutely delighted to see the boat  here at long last. It's been long awaited and very controversial. But  she is here now and she can be based in Foula.'
<P>
It is eight years since the council started planning the new pier and  ferry. The 'New Advance' is the second attempt. An earlier version  was rejected as unsuitable. The boats cost around 400,000 pounds each.
<P><A HREF="rope.jpg"><IMG SRC="ropes.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=154 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Mr Smith said it was 'a new beginning' for Foula: 'It gives the  island a tremendous advantage to have this ferry now. She's a very  good-looking and trim ship. I'm sure she'll do the job admirably.'
<P>
After three weeks of weather delays in bringing the boat north, Mr  Smith admitted that everyone concerned with the project had felt  'very tense' over the past few days.
<P><A HREF="detail.jpg"><IMG SRC="details.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=256 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
The next problem is to find a skipper willing to live in Foula, after  Captain Allan Cook resigned earlier this year and left the island.
<P><A HREF="rob.jpg"><IMG SRC="robs.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=248 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Mr Smith said: 'The post has been advertised, and we hope that there  will be a skipper appointed as soon as this is practicably possible.
<P>
'The intention is that the New Advance should be based in Foula.  She's designed to be based in Foula and that is where she will be  when we have a skipper for her, and when minor alterations are made  to the lifting gear at the pier there.'
<P>
The new one million pounds harbour in Britain's most remote inhabited  island is unsafe in violent storms and the 'New Advance' will have to  be lifted out of the water.
<P>
The Orcadian who skippered the boat from Stromness to Scalloway,  Colin Garriock, was happy with the way she performed during the  14-hour crossing: 'No complaints at all', he said.
<P>




<BR clear=all>





<BR clear=all>










<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
