<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - It's true - Foula ferry sails north at last

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  It's true - Foula ferry sails north at last
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
31st October 1996
<P>
Eight years after Shetland Islands Council started planning an  improved ferry service to the island of Foula, a purpose-built Foula  ferryboat was at last steaming north last night (WED).
<P>
The 400,000 pounds 'New Advance' left Richardson's boatyard in  Stromness, Orkney, hopefully bringing to a close a celebrated and  expensive saga of blunders and disappointments.
<P><A HREF="advance1.jpg"><IMG SRC="advance1s.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=161 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Prolonged gales over the past three weeks had prevented the boat  sailing for Shetland but last night Shetland Islands Council's marine  department confirmed she was on her way to her first port of call,  Scalloway Harbour, where the twin-engined, 38-foot fibreglass-hulled  vessel is due at nine this morning.
<P>
Last night the council's convener, Canon Lewis Smith, said he was  thinking of going to Scalloway to meet the new arrival: 'But I'm not  sure if it's bad luck for a minister to see her first,' he joked.  Canon Smith is Rector of St Magnus Episcopal Church in Lerwick.
<P>
The recent bad weather was not the first bad luck or delay for the  project. Four years ago the council rejected the 'Westering  Homewards', the first ferry built specially for the 18-mile exposed  crossing to Britain's most remote inhabited island. That boat, which  also cost 400,000 pounds, failed sea trials. After failing to find a  buyer, the council handed her over to Shetland's fisheries college as  a training vessel.
<P>
A new harbour, and a crane to lift the new ferry out of the water at  Foula, have brought the total bill for the project to almost two  million pounds. Around 50 people live on the island.
<P>
Last year a skipper was hired for the Foula ferry and a chalet was  shipped to the island for him to live in. But the boat was delayed  and, after disagreements with other islanders, Captain Allan Cook  left before ever taking command of his little ship. The council has  advertised for a new skipper willing to live in the island but has  not yet made an appointment.
<P>
Government regulations say the skipper and crew must possess full  professional qualifications, which until now have been in short  supply on Foula. A training programme has meant further expense for  the council. 
<P>
Council policy is to base the ferry in Foula. Councillor Jim Gear, a  Foula resident, insists that is the only way to provide a reliable  service, arguing that a Foula-based crew can more readily take  advantage of breaks in the weather to make the run to West Burrafirth  on the Shetland Mainland. 
<P>
A Foula base also means five part-time ferry jobs bringing cash into  the island.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

