<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Fishermen take their case to the top

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Fishermen take their case to the top
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
31st October 1996
<P>
Shetland fishermen are going to the top today (THURS) to put their  case for drastic reform of Europe's common fisheries policy and to  protest against the proposed 40 per cent cut in the number of boats.
<P>
A delegation from the Shetland Fishermen's Association and Shetland  Islands Council spent yesterday preparing for today's high-level  meeting with European Fisheries Commissioner Emma Bonino.
<P><A HREF="goodlad.jpg"><IMG SRC="goodlads.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=241 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Association secretary John Goodlad said the session was 'a  first-class opportunity to put Shetland's concerns to the person who  is ultimately responsible'.
<P>
Mrs Bonino has aroused the wrath of Scottish fishermen with her 40  per cent proposal. The Shetland delegation will also explain to her  why they want 'early action' to control foreign, 'flagship' fishing  vessels - which fly the Red Ensign to get a share of Britain's fish  catch quotas.
<P>
Mr Goodlad, who was due to address the European Parliament yesterday,  said he would put the case for European funding to rebuild and  modernise the Shetland fleet. 
<P>
Backing up the fishermen's delegation are two Shetland councillors -  Loretta Hutchison from the fishing island of Whalsay and Drew Ratter,  chairman of the council's development committee.
<P>
Mr Ratter said in Brussels yesterday: 'We hope to bring home to Mrs  Bonino how very vulnerable Shetland and other remote fishing European  communities are to a 40 per cent cut in the fleet. We rely very  heavily on fishing and the proposed reduction is too high.'
<P>
In Tenerife last week a new European fisheries committee,  representing islands and coastal communities all around Europe, gave  Mr Ratter the go-ahead to lead the campaign for reform. 
<P>
'We have problems in common with places such as the Canary Islands  and we need a united front in lobbying European institutions and  committees,' Mr Ratter said. 'We agree there's a need for  conservation and reducing catching capacity for some fish stocks but  we want a complete reconsideration of the current proposals.'
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

