<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - The last voyage of the 'Tobol'

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  The last voyage of the 'Tobol'
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
31st October 1996
<P><A HREF="tobol.jpg"><IMG SRC="tobols.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=288 HEIGHT=146 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
A grey Soviet ghost from the Cold War lay at anchor off Lerwick,  Shetland, yesterday (WED), on her last voyage to the breaker's yard.
<P>
The 6,000 tonne 'Ugra' class ship 'Tobol', a former ammunition ship  for the Soviet submarine fleet, is under tow by the Russian tug  'Atriya' from Murmansk to Bombay, where she will be scrapped.
<P>
The tow parted off Norway last week in severe weather. The tug  skipper managed to re-connect with a temporary towline and told  Coastguards he wanted to shelter off Shetland while he made up a new  cable for the three-month, 16,500-mile passage to India.
<P>
The tug has visited Lerwick before, in 1992. The skipper told harbour  officials yesterday he expected to be under way again by the end of the week.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

