<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - £20,000 bug-sweeper makes Town Hall secure

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  £20,000 bug-sweeper makes Town Hall secure
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
30th October 1996
<P>
Shetland Islands Council has spent 20,000 pounds on sweeping Lerwick  Town Hall for electronic bugs - allegedly at the request of the  Scottish Office.
<P>
But rumours that council bosses also eavesdrop on staff phone calls  are not true, a council leader said.
<P>
Vice-convener Jim Smith told the full council yesterday (TUES) the  anti-bugging devices were bought by chief executive Malcolm Green,  without councillors' knowledge. They cost 'around 20,000 pounds.
<P>
Mr Smith said it was essential to ensure secrecy when the council was  negotiating with the oil industry and Government representatives. 
<P>
Speaking on local BBC radio after the meeting, he said: 'They don't  want to be overheard ... and we've been asked by some of the Scottish  Office people to ensure that the place is what they call secure  before they actually come in and speak to us. And that's it. We just  have an anti-bugging device which tells us if anybody's planted  microphones or whatever.'
<P>
Last night the Scottish Office said they had no knowledge of anyone  asking the council to install anti-bugging devices.
<P>
Earlier, Mr Smith explained that there had been no need for Mr Green  to tell councillors about the equipment because he had 'delegated  authority' to deal with security at the Town Hall, which houses Mr  Green's offices and the council chamber, currently being refurbished.
<P>
Answering questions from Councillor Loretta Hutchison about alleged  covert surveillance, Mr Smith denied rumours that the council  monitored staff calls. They had a call-logging system, as many  organisations did, but no-one eavesdropped on phone conversations. To  record a single day's calls would use up 500 hours of tape, he said.
<P>
Mrs Hutchison said after the meeting that she had been tipped off  about the de-bugging gear by 'someone of standing' and had done a bit  of detective work herself before asking the question.
<P>
'I was very annoyed about having to ask such questions about the  council but I felt I had to do it,' she said.
<P>
Last night a spokesperson for the local government union, Unison,  said: 'We're very glad to have this assurance that staff calls are  never monitored.'
<P>
During the past two years Mr Green and his senior staff have been  involved in lengthy negotiations with BP, Shell and the Government  about the future of the Sullom Voe oil terminal. 
<P>
During the secret talks, senior council representatives were given  confidential briefings including private oil company information, Mr  Smith said.
<P>
A new deal to secure oil supplies for Sullom Voe was concluded in the  summer. It involves the council in the management of the plant, which  BP run on behalf of 30 oil companies. 
<P>
Mr Smith confirmed that talks were now going on behind closed doors  about the Shetland oil terminal's role, if and when large quantities  of oil and gas are produced from the new oilfields west of the islands.
<P>
The sums of money involved are huge. West Shetland is believed to  contain almost half of Britain's known oil reserves. Shetland Islands  Council's oil revenues, held in a charitable trust, are now worth  over 200 million pounds and the council stands to make further  millions out of land rents and possibly other fees if a new pipeline  is laid from the west side fields
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
