<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Councillor slams 'cop-out' on ferry study

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Councillor slams 'cop-out' on ferry study
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
30th October 1996
<P>
An attempt to stop the appointment of consultants to advise Shetland  Islands Council how to save 750,000 pounds a year on its inter-island  ferry services was heavily defeated yesterday (TUES).
<P>
Councillor Jim Gear said it was 'a nonsense' and 'not appropriate' to  hire consultants at a cost of up to 80,000 pounds, when the council  had the expertise itself and had already conducted a year-long  internal study which had showed how to save 'hundreds of thousands of  pounds'. He moved they reject the idea.
<P>
Councillor Lindsay Smith agreed, saying the decision to bring in  outsiders was making the council 'a laughing stock with the public'  but transport committee chairman Magnus Flaws said they needed 'new ideas'.
<P>
Former transport chairman Jim Irvine said he was 'shocked' when the  council ditched the internal review and went for outside consultants:  'It's just a cop-out,' he said.
<P>
Mr Flaws said the internal review had only come up with 'short-term'  economies and it had become clear to him that they could not make  progress on the 'pretty hard decisions' needed in the longer term. He  revealed that 10 companies have been asked to tender for the job.
<P>
Asking councillors to review the ferry service put them in 'an  impossible position' because of the conflict between the interests of  their island constituents and the council's need to save money: 'They  also have to live in these islands,' he said.
<P>
Councillor Leonard Groat said: 'Nobody should be afraid to let the  service come under scrutiny of outside consultants at any time'. 
<P>
Convener Lewis Smith said: 'We may even reject everything they tell  us. The council is not abdicating its responsibility. The decision  willbe made by councillors.'
<P>
After further debate, the full council voted 14-4 to proceed with the  consultancy exercise for ferries, which receive a subsidy of six  million pounds a year and have some of the cheapest fares in Britain.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

