<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Leisure department's fate is sealed

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Leisure department's fate is sealed
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
30th October 1996
<P>
A final attempt to save Shetland Islands Council's leisure and  recreation department failed yesterday (TUES), leaving officials  clear to go ahead with the break-up of the 21-year-old organisation,  in an attempt to cut costs.
<P>
Councillor Florence Grains tried to persuade a meeting of the full  council to delay a decison on the department's future until after  talks with the Shetland Arts Trust and Shetland Recreational Trust,  which council leaders want to take on much of the old department's work.
<P>
'We're taking things in the wrong order,' she said. 'Things are  getting a bit confused.' Discussion with the trusts 'should take  place first and the decisons later, rather than the other way round.'
<P>
Councillor Leonard Groat said a lot of work had been done already and  asked what staff would think if the council changed its mind again. 
<P>
Vice-convener Jim Smith noted that Mrs Grains did not oppose handing  the museums and archives section of leisure and recreation back to  the education department and assured her: 'If the trusts don't agree,  we won't be tranferring anything to them'.
<P>
Mrs Grains' motion was then heavily defeated, as the leisure  department's first and only director, John P. Nicolson, sat  grim-faced in the public gallery. Mr Nicolson, now retired, is a  candidate in a forthcoming council by-election.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
