<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - College jobs for the axe

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  College jobs for the axe
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
30th October 1996
<P>
Four jobs are to go at the Shetland College of Further Education,  Shetland Islands Council agreed yesterday (TUES).
<P>
College principal Gordon Dargie said early retirement packages for  two lecturers and one technician were approved.
<P>
He would also try to re-locate a Building Construction lecturer  elsewhere in the council. The lecturer's post was 'no longer required  because of a downturn in the number of trainees from the local industry'.
<P>
The offer to find the lecturer another job is seen as a possible  compromise with the education union EIS, which had warned of  industrial  action if compulsory redundancy went ahead.
<P>
The union's general secretary, Ronnie Smith, is the son of Shetland's  education chairman, Lerwick Labour councillor Bill Smith.
<P>
The original target was to cut five posts at the college. Mr Smith  senior said recently he regretted the need for the job losses. 
<P>
Mr Dargie said: 'The job losses are part of a number of measures  taken following a review and consultation of staff on reducing  running costs at the college.'  The range of courses offered would be  maintained.
<P>
Shetland College is one of only two in Scotland still under local  authority control. There are plans to set it up as an independent trust.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
