<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Islands rolling in public cash as cuts continue

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Islands rolling in public cash as cuts continue
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
29th October 1996
<P>
The charitable trust which has husbanded Shetland's oil revenues for  20 years is awash with money it is loath to spend, while the islands  council continues to make budget cuts.
<P>
The Shetland Islands Council Charitable Trust is now worth 203  million pounds, says trust financial adviser Andrew Matthews, who is  also the council's finance director.
<P>
In a report published yesterday (MON) for this Friday's trust  meeting, Mr Matthews reveals that trustees have a 13.9 million pounds  'surplus' to spend in the financial year 1997/98, after investing 1.1  million pounds to maintain the trust's value - and setting aside 15  per cent for 'contingencies'. 
<P>
But he advises the 26 councillors and two independent trustees to  spend just 5.8 million pounds next year and to continue their policy  of only accepting spending bids previously approved by the council.
<P>
Mr Matthews says the 8.1 million pounds surplus is 'available at  present prices for each year into the future' but adds: 'I would  caution against regarding the whole figure as being able to fund  ongoing revenue expenditure: such an approach would preclude one-off projects.'
<P>
Among the major projects currently delayed because of the council and  trust policy of 'no-growth' budgets are a care centre for old folk in  Unst, Britain's most northerly inhabited island, and a leisure centre  for the village of Aith on the west mainland of Shetland.
<P>
Some councillors are looking to the trust to bail out the council's  education budget, currently under severe pressure as outside  consultants examine ways to cut spending.
<P>
Education chairman Bill Smith said yesterday (MON) he favoured using  trust cash for 'non-statutory' items in Shetland's much-admired  education service. 
<P>
'We have to be careful we don't spend Shetland's own money on things  which are the Government's responsibility to fund,' he said, but  'possibilities' were nursery education and the extra music tuition  for which island schools are famous.
<P>
The charitable trust's 20th annual report lists some impressive  achievements over the past year in social welfare, community projects  and industrial development.
<P>
Chairman Bill Manson reports spending of 550,000 pounds on the  Independence at Home Scheme, designed to help the inform or elderly  to avoid going into hospitals or instituions; another 600,000 pounds  was spent on Christmas bonuses to almost every pensioner household;  and 84,000 pounds went to a Community Alarm Syetem which allows the  housebound to call for help around the clock.
<P>
The trust assisted a wide range of projects run by voluntary  organisations and other Shetland trusts, ranging from marriage  guidance and sports halls to a new history centre in the island of Bressay.
<P>
Loans totalling over 300,000 pounds were made to farmers and crofters  and the trust's hire purchase company provided 1.2 million pounds for  local industry to buy equipment. The company also built a new  livestock marts and agricultural marketing centre and contributed to  the new 11.5 million pounds swimming pool and bowls hall at the  Clickimin Leisure Centre in Lerwick.
<P>
The current market value of the trust's assets is equal to almost  9,000 pounds for every man, woman and child in the islands.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

