Last-modified: Sun, 27 Oct 1996 11:54:47 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Doctor's concern at exodus from Yell

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Doctor's concern at exodus from Yell
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
27th October 1996
<P>
Yell, Shetland's second biggest island, is suffering 'dramatic'  depopulation, according to figures compiled by the island's doctor.
<P>
The crisis highlights problems affecting many of Shetland's offlying islands.
<P>
Dr Mike McDonnell has told Yell Community Council of his worries  about the future of the remote community where he has been the GP for 22 years.
<P>
He says Yell (pop. 1,024) has lost 12 per cent of its people in 10  years because of lack of work and a low birth rate. He calculates the  male unemployment rate at 10 per cent, compared with around four per  cent for Shetland as a whole.
<P>
Dr McDonnell says he supports measures to help the neighbouring  island of Unst (pop. 900), which recently lost more than 30 jobs when  oil company Chevron closed down its helicopter base at Baltasound  airport. But he believes Yell's employment problems are 'more  insidious, yet more profound' and calls on Shetland Islands Council  to assist all three North Isles - Yell, Unst and Fetlar (pop. 100).
<P>
In his letter to the community council, the doctor says: 'The  population figures maintained at the Yell Health Centre are more  accurate and more telling than the 10-yearly census returns, and show  a quite dramatic fall in the Yell population ... from 1,169 ten years  ago to the current level of 1,024 - which is the lowest ever recorded  on Yell. Unfortunately the trend is continuing.'
<P>
'Yell has the lowest proportion of under fives in Shetland; the  figures represent the lowest birth rate in the county and indicate  that the falling numbers are not being offset by an increase in  births. The employment picture also gives rise for concern,' Dr  McDonnell says. 
<P>
He warns that a proposal to base the Yell-Unst ferry at Belmont on  Unst, rather than Gutcher, Yell, could lead to even more losses.  Ferrymen and their families would be forced to move to Unst to keep their jobs.
<P>
Yell has faced crises before. In the 1960s a special conference was  held there, to plan development initiatives, after the collapse of  the Antarctiuc whaling industry which formerly employed many Yell  men. The economy picked up when the island gained mains electricity  after the 'Yell For Light' campaign and, in the mid-1970s, when  Shetland Islands Council started a ro-ro ferry service.
<P>
Fast, frequent and cheap ferries allowed many Yell folk to commute to  work at the Sullom Voe oil terminal on the other side of Yell Sound  but in recent years oil-related work has tailed off. Island  industries such as fishing, shellfish processing, knitwear,  agriculture and tourism have not been able to provide enough new jobs.
<P>
Yell's current difficulties reflect similar concerns in other small  communities. Fewer than 4,000 of Shetland's 23,000 inhabitants now  live on the offlying islands of Yell, Unst, Fetlar, Whalsay,  Skerries, Bressay, Fair Isle, Foula and Papa Stour. Burra Isle and  Muckle Roe are linked to the Shetland Mainland by bridges but Bressay  is the only other island which could practicably be linked by a  bridge or tunnel and that could cost over 20 million pounds.
<P>
As the council moves to cut its spending, the six million pounds a  year subsidy for inter-island ferries is under scrutiny, with  consultants being hired to advise on economies. 
<P>
Dr McDonnell is one of many islanders who fear that fare increases  and less frequent sailings would accelerate the drift to the Lerwick  area, where half of Shetland now lives within 10 miles of the  county's only town.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

