<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Sentence deferred on woman who threatened police with shotgun

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Sentence deferred on woman who threatened police with shotgun
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
25th October 1996
<P>
A woman who threatened two police officers and an SSPCA inspector with a shotgun in Walls, Shetland, escaped a prison sentence at Lerwick Sheriff Court yesterday (THU).
<P>
On September 13 last year police constables John MacLean and Donna Newton went with SSPCA inspector Ron Paterson to investigate allegations of  animal neglect on a croft at Houll, Walls, on Shetland's remote west side.
<P>
They were confronted by crofter Margaret Jean Fraser (55), who pointed a shotgun at them. It later proved to be unloaded but the police did  not know that at the time.
<P>
Defence solicitor Bobby McDonald said this was a type of offence that could not be 'brushed aside', but he asked Sheriff Colin Scott  Mackenzie to take into consideration that Fraser had 'no income at  all' and her savings had 'dwindled to few hundred pounds'.
<P>
A social inquiry report concluded that some benefits could be gained  by deferring the sentence. Mr McDonald said that his client was  considering applying for social assistance.
<P>
He said: 'Keeping her in contact with the social services and  carrying out a psychiatric report at the same time will benefit Mrs Fraser.'
<P>
Sheriff Colin Scott Mackenzie accepted the recommendations and decided to defer sentence until April 17 next year. He told Fraser: 'I am  satisfied ... that you are no danger to the public. If you co-operate  with the social work department the outcome of this can be quite different.'
<P>
At Fraser's first appearance in court the sheriff had praised the  police officers for their courage and steadfastness in disarming Mrs Fraser.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

