<TITLE>The Shetland News - SNP man promises higher pensions

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  SNP man promises higher pensions
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
24th October 1996
<P>
An independent Scottish Parliament would increase pensions  immediately and remove standing charges on electricity and phones for  pensioners, Willie Ross, the Scottish National Party's prospective  parliamentary candidate for Orkney and Shetland said yesterday (WED).
<P>
The promise came as the Queen opened the last parliamentary session  before the general election, due by May next year.
<P>
Mr Ross said: 'Scottish pensioners have been hammered by successive  Tory governments, and have been abandoned by the Labour Party.' Only  Scottish independence could offer 'a bright future for elderly Scots', he said.
<P>
The prospective candidate cited a recent Age Concern survey in which  77 per cent of Scots said pensions were too low.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
