<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Chopper trip to reassure Foula

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Chopper trip to reassure Foula
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
23rd October 1996
<P>
A council helicopter yesterday (TUES) flew Shetland ferries boss  Captain Mike Hogan to Foula, to reassure frustrated islanders that  their new ferry will be delivered as soon as weather permits.
<P>
Last night the 400,000 pounds 'New Advance' was still waiting for a  break in the weather at Stromness Harbour, Orkney, where builders  Richardsons completed her two weeks ago.
<P>
Britain's most isolated island community is looking forward to the  last chapter in the six-year Foula ferry saga.
<P>
A spokeswoman for the council's marine operations department said  yesterday: 'We're planning to make the move towards getting her here  at the weekend.'
<P>
The forecast was looking 'more hopeful for the weekend' she said.  'We're ready to sail her to Shetland provided that we're not let down  by a change in the weather.'
<P>
The council is currently recruiting a new skipper for the 18-mile exposed Atlantic crossing to Foula after Captain Allan Cook, hired as skipper last year, resigned before his new command was ready for sea.
<P>
Meanwhile Foula (pop.50) has not been served by a ferry for the last three weeks because of poor weather. Capt. Mike Hogan met islanders  in a bid to defuse the island's ferry crisis.
<P>
Foula residents claimed the council showed a lack of commitment to  the service. There was a backlog of cargo waiting to come in and  livestock to leave the island for market.
<P>
At present one ferry serves Foula and Papa Stour from the pier at  West Burrafirth on the Shetland mainland. The shorter and more  sheltered crossing to Papa Stour has operated around 20 times during  the last three weeks.
<P>
Councillor for Walls and Sandness, Foula resident Jim Gear, said: 'It  brings at home to everyone who is aware of the fact that this is the  sort of level of service which we suffer under when the ferry service  isn't run from the island.'
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

