<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Video plan to boost Scalloway harbour

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Video plan to boost Scalloway harbour
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
23rd October 1996
<P>
Plans for a promotional video to bring in business to a half-empty  council harbour at Scalloway, Shetland, could cost up to 25,000  pounds, members of the Blackness Pier Committee will hear this week.
<P>
Captain Malcolm Brennan, small ports manager for Shetland Islands  Council, says advertising should be 'as widespread as possible'. The  video would cost between 9,000 and 25,000 pounds, depending on how  much archive material is used.
<P>
Harbour works at Scalloway over the past decade have cost over 6  million pounds but traffic has slumped dramatically from 488 vessels  in 1993 to just 365 last year. 
<P>
The improved port facilities were built largely in response to demand  from the local fishing fleet but the number of fishing boat callers  dropped from 268 in 1994 to only 158 last year.
<P>
Delays in developing the new Atlantic oilfields - for which Scalloway  is the nearest port - have dashed hopes for increased oil-related business.
<P>
Captain Brennan says Scalloway should be represented at the Scottish  Fishery Exhibition in Aberdeen next March and the video would also be  'a powerful tool' for attracting small cruise liners, the oilfield  supply industry and general cargo work. 
<P>
The committee of councillors and port users has already agreed they  need a business plan to turn around the fortunes of the loss-making  harbour and cash in on its strategic position as Shetland's main west  coast port.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

