<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Hands across the sea

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Hands across the sea
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
22nd October 1996
<P>
Shetland fishermen's secretary John Goodlad has been building  alliances with Norwegian fishermen, by attending their annual conference.
<P>
On his return from Norway yesterday (MON) Mr Goodlad said his talks  with the Norwegian Fishermen's Association had been 'very good and open'.
<P>
He found they had similar problems to the Shetland fleet, including  'the whole question of fewer fishermen in the future and fewer boats,  the conflict between big and small boats, as well as the increasing  price of quotas'.
<P>
Mr Goodlad said: 'For example, there's a huge debate on the decision  taken by the Norwegian government to allow an American company to  come in and buy 12 licences for white fish trawlers.'
<P>
The visit was the third of its kind in recent years, as the Shetland  fishermen try to get an insight into the views of Norwegian fishermen  who are often on the opposing side during quota negotiations.
<P>
Similar thinking lay behind last month's move by Councillor Drew  Ratter, Shetland Islands Council's development chairman, when he  hosted the first meeting of a new European committee where fishing  communities from the fringes of Europe, such as Galicia and the  Canary Islands, can discuss common problems.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

