<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - MPs to debate new marine safety rules

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  MPs to debate new marine safety rules
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
21st October 1996
<P>
Nearly four years after the oil tanker Braer went aground at the  southern tip of Shetland, MPs are to debate a legal framework to make  the seas safer.
<P>
Shetland councillors say the Government's response to Lord  Donaldson's report on 'Safer Ships, Cleaner Seas' does not go far enough.
<P>
Islanders are taking a keen interest in the debate and Shetland  Islands Council's line is that little has changed to improve marine  safety since  the Braer disaster.
<P>
In July the council approved a report by their marine director,  Captain George Sutherland, who accused the Government of  'procrastination' and said civil servants' arguments against  compulsory insurance were 'nonsensical'.
<P>
The council is demanding a ban on Russian klondykers and other  uninsured ships carrying dangerous cargoes and large quanities of  fuel in UK waters.
<P>
In the Government's opinion compulsory insurance could 'distort the working of a free market' and put insurers under 'moral pressure' to cover 'commercially unsound' risks.
<P>
The Department of Transport argues that it cannot force insurance  companies to provide cover: 'In extreme market conditions business  operations might be placed beyond the law by a requirement to be insured.'
<P>
'This is clearly wholly unsatisfactory,' Captain Sutherland said.  Shipowners who could not afford insurance should not be in business.
<P>
The council has gone to the Court of Session to claim 1.5 million  pounds of compensation for helping to clear up the mess after the  'Braer' tanker wreck. The Government itself is owed large sums.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

