<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Shellfish ban is lifted at last

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Shellfish ban is lifted at last
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
21st October 1996
<P>
Shetland Islands Council has lifted the ban on harvesting shellfish,  imposed earlier this year on parts of the coastline after tests  showed high levels of paralytic shellfish poisoning (PSP).
<P>
According to the Environmental Services Department, measurements of  PSP in Clift Sound, around Burra and Trondra, off Skelda Ness and in  Basta Voe are again at an acceptable level and there is no longer any  risk to the public.
<P>
The levels of PSP were among the highest recorded in the UK this year, and were most unusual for Shetland, where cold Atlantic waters normally keep the poison at bay. Orkney, lying further south, has had almost annual warnings about PSP.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
