<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Sullom Voe millions are no use to the council

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Sullom Voe millions are no use to the council
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
19th October 1996
<P>
Land rents of £7.6 million from the Sullom Voe oil terminal  will make no difference to Shetland Islands Council's budget  problems, a senior official told the council's policy committee  yesterday (Friday).
<P>
The money has been kept in a 'suspense account' but finance manager  Graham Johnston said half of it would be given back to terminal  operators BP under the recent deal to guarantee the future of Sullom  Voe after the year 2000.
<P>
The other half would go into the council budget for 1997/98 but  policy chairman Jim Smith said it would do the council no good  because the Scottish Office would deduct it, pound-for-pound from  their grant to the council.
<P>
'This money is treated as income by the Scottish Office and that will reduce our grant from them. It makes no difference in the council's  need to save five million pounds annually by the year 2000. If we  don't do that we're running into a deficit,' he said.
<P>
Mr Johnston told the policy committee that, despite the problems with  the General Fund, their balance sheet had 'fundamental strength',  supported by 'substantial' reserves of over £417 million.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

