<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Leisure grants under attack

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Leisure grants under attack
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
19th October 1996
<P>
Shetland's generous grants for leisure and recreation came under  attack yesterday (Friday) as councillors discussed how to dismantle the  department that hands them out.
<P>
Unst councillor Joan Easten told the policy committee: 'We must look  very carefully at leisure and recreation. I can't see how to maintain  the grant scheme, while other council services are due to be cut.'
<P>
In the current financial year 1996/97 the Leisure and Recreation  department is giving away nearly £1.2 million to sports and  swimming clubs, voluntary organisations, playschemes, the arts,  community halls and other projects.
<P>
Councillor Willie Tait, chairman of the marine committee, said new and well-maintained ferries were very important for Shetland and it was difficult to explain to the public why so much money went to leisure  and recreation when there was not enough to replace old ferries.
<P>
Leisure committee chairman Billy Stove warned that the Leisure and  Recreation Department was 'an easy target'. He said: 'Let's have a balance between Leisure and  Recreation and the other council services.' Shetland had a good sporting tradition and he called on councillors  to maintain this.
<P>
The policy committee accepted a report by education director James  Halcrow on how the leisure department should be divided between the  Education Department, Shetland Recreational Trust and Shetland Arts Trust.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

