<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Viking gold invades island salmon farms

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Viking gold invades island salmon farms
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
18th October 1996
<P>
A new Viking invasion is taking place in Shetland, with Norwegian  salmon farmers exporting their capital west over the sea, to escape  Oslo government restrictions and maintain access to European Union markets.
<P>
As Norway clamps down on salmon production, partly in response to  complaints from Shetland about unfair competition, so many Norwegians  are investing in the islands that islanders may lose control of the  35 million pounds a year industry.
<P>
Magnus Flaws, chief executive of the Shetland Salmon Farmers'  Association, said yesterday (Thursday) the Norwegian government was  issuing no new salmon farm licences and was re-assessing existing ones. 
<P>
'This creates a situation where there's no room for expansion,' he  said. 'Some of these companies are looking outside Norway and,  obviously, they're looking at Shetland. Some of the local salmon  farmers may sell out, because these (Norwegian) companies do have a  lot of money.'
<P>
With salmon prices at a record low - between 75 and 80 pence per  pound, Mr. Flaws said many farms were under severe economic pressure.  The break-even point is between 95 and 100 pence a pound.
<P>
He hoped prices would recover once negotiations to restrict Norwegian  salmon exports to the rest of Europe were concluded.
<P>
'Some farmers might be able to live for half a year with these  prices, given the fact that they have other sources of income. Others  will have to sell earlier,' he said.
<P>
Drew Ratter, chairman of Shetland Islands Council's development  committee, said the council's ability to help was restricted. He  welcomed the flow of Norwegian money.
<P>
'It helps to develop the industry further,' he said. It proved that  Shetland was a perfect place to grow salmon. Jobs were being secured  and even more might be created.
<P>
The industry produced around 12,000 tonnes of salmon in Shetland last  year and employs almost 700 people, directly and indirectly.
<P>
According to Frank Johnson, managing director of Framgord, Shetland's  biggest salmon producer, processor and seller, the Norwegian money  has come at just the right time.
<P>
Last month Framgord announced a deal with the Norwegian company  Nordvik, which will rear thousands of extra tonnes of salmon at sites  which Framgord has acquired on the west coast of the islands.
<P>
Mr Johnson said: 'Investment has to come during a recession, in order  to remain competitive.' The co-operation with Nordvik would ensure a  steady flow of salmon into Framgord's new 2.4 million pounds  processing plant at Lerwick.
<P>
As salmon prices have fallen in recent years, Shetland producers have  been looking at new markets. Mr Flaws said: 'We have to keep our eyes  open for any new species that could grow in this (water) temperature.  People can diversify, maybe even to grow mussels alongside salmon farms.'
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

