<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Three seek Yell council seat

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Three seek Yell council seat
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
18th October 1996
<P>
Next month's Shetland council by-election in the island of Yell will  be a three-cornered contest between an ex-councillor, a former  council director and a local resident.
<P>
When nominations closed yesterday (THURS) the nominations for the  Yell South poll on November 14 were: 
<ul>
<P>

*  Lerwick lawyer and Children's Panel Reporter <B>Sandy Cluness</B>, who  represented the Twageos ward in the town during the early 1980s. He  will stand for the Shetland Movement party; 
<P>
*  Liberal Democrat candidate <B>John P. Nicolson</B>, from the village of  Scalloway, who recently took early retirement as the islands  council's leisure director after a high profile row with chief  executive Malcolm Green; 
<P>
*  <B>Alan Ogden</B>, the only candidate living in Yell (pop. 1000), is  standing as an independent at his second attempt to win a council seat.
</UL>
<P>
The by-election follows the resignation of Councillor Peter Guy, who  has left the islands for a new job in Yorkshire. Mr Guy won the South  Yell seat as an independent at a by-election in 1993 and was  re-elected unopposed the following year. He was chairman of the  council's leisure and recreation committee, and also chaired the  islands' licensing board and tourist authority.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

