<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - New council blunder - dementia centre 50% over budget

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  New council blunder - dementia centre 50% over budget
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
17th October 1996
<P>
A council care centre for dementia sufferers in Shetland will cost half as  much again as originally thought, it was revealed yesterday (WED).
<P>
Councillor Leonard Groat, chairman of Shetland Islands social work  committee, said he was 'very annoyed' when he discovered that  conversion work on the former Viewforth eventide home in Lerwick  would cost 220,000 pounds more than the 438,000 pounds budget.
<P>
He pledged that the centre for 15 dementia patients and some day-care  clients would still open as planned late next year - and the budget  blunder would have 'absolutely no effect' on home helps and other  community care workers.
<P>
Mr Groat blamed the 50 per cent miscalculation on the council's  design department, which has since been re-organised: 'When this  project was approved we thought the costing of 438,000 pounds was all  we needed but only a year and a half later we discovered the  problems,' he said.
<P>
A report on the affair by social work director Bill Bennett for  tomorrow's (FRI) meeting of the council's policy committee says: 'Due  to the time scale available this costing did not benefit from the  advice of service or structural design consultants. This work was  undertaken later.'
<P>
The consultants, who included Stirling University's 'Dementia  Services Development Centre', recommended design changes for patients' safety  - and complete replacement of the boilers and much of the electrical  system at Viewforth.
<P>
Mr Bennett says the extra cost can be met by using 115,800 pounds  allocated by Shetland Health Board for looking after dementia  sufferers, and by moving 104,200 pounds from the council's own  'community care revenue budgets'.
<P>
Mr Groat said it was not 'over-spending' but 'under-budgeting'. The  220,000 pounds had been held for 'contingencies' and using this money  to complete Viewforth to the proper standard would have 'absolutely  no effect' on care in the community for elderly and disabled people.
<P>
In March this year the council voted to reduce spending on home  helps, to help finance the new dementia centre.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

