<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News - Being away from it all is a bonus, says new firm

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Being away from it all is a bonus, says new firm
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
17th October 1996
<P>
Geography has traditionally been the big problem for business in  Shetland, but a new company based in the village of Scalloway plans  to 'capitalise on remoteness'.
<P>
AB Associates Ltd, run by former Shetland council development officer  Andrew Blackadder, says being far from the madding crowd is a  positive advantage when selling business advice and social/economic  research skills to other remote areas throughout Europe.
<P>
Mr Blackadder, a qualified town planner who specialises in handling  applications for European Union development assistance, said: 
<P>
'I think we're fairly unique among consultants, in combining  experience in economic policy and analysis with European affairs, and  this gives us the opportunity to take advantage of a gap in the market.'
<P>
Fellow directors include: Mr Blackadder's former boss - retired  council development director Jack Burgess; publishing expert Susan  Fogg; and Shetland College business studies lecturer Maureen Christie.
<P>
AB Associates has already won a contract with Shetland Islands  Council to carry out European work formerly done by Mr Blackadder and  Ms Fogg when they worked for the council.
<P>
Now they plan to become a new Shetland export business: 'So far our  work has come mainly from Shetland,' Mr Blackadder said, 'but we're  hoping to persuade companies and public authorities in other island  and rural areas to make use of our skills and special insight into  island and rural problems.'
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

