<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Shetland News -  Dole figures down but boom is tailing off

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Dole figures down but boom is tailing off
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
17th October 1996
<P>
Unemployment in Shetland fell slightly last month but there are signs  that the 25-year oil-fired boom in the islands' economy is tailing off.
<P>
Although only 3.9 per cent of the registered working population was  out of a job - one of the lowest figures in the UK - the total of 465  jobseekers was 123 more than in September last year.
<P>
Recent redundancies in the building trade, aviation and oil-related  work have contributed to the trend, while Lerwick Harbour's dramatic  36 per cent decline in traffic this year is reflected in fewer  fishing industry jobs and a downturn in oilfield supply boat business.
<P>
The Shetland dole queue figure of 3.9 per cent compares with 7.5 per  cent for the UK, Scotland's 7.9 per cent, Highland's 8.7 per cent and  five per cent in Aberdeenshire. 
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

