<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - 

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Council agonises over cuts as £7.6 million lies unused in the bank  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
16th October 1996
<P>
Land rents from the Sullom Voe oil terminal, totalling 7.6 million  pounds, were kept in a 'suspense account' by Shetland Islands Council  officials last year, rather than being spent on council budgets,  councillors will hear later this week.
<P>
The council's policy committee will be asked on Friday to approve the  decision, described by officials as 'prudent' while negotiations with  the oil industry about a new deal were still going on. 
<P>
The deal, agreed earlier this year, provides a rent of around three  million pounds a year from Sullom Voe when existing agreements run  out in August 2000. 
<P>
Keeping last year's rent in the bank left the council's current  account in the black by just 800,000 pounds on March 31, instead of  8.4 million pounds.
<P>
With another 7.1 million pounds due from Sullom Voe in the current  year, councillors are still trying to find economies of five million  pounds a year by the turn of the century, and recently voted to hire  consultants to tell them how to save on schools and ferries.
<P>
The Shetland council is making progress towards staying solvent in  the 21st century but serious problems remain, according to the latest  annual report and accounts, published yesterday (Tuesday).
<P>
Finance manager Graham Johnston tells councillors their balance sheet  has 'fundamental strength', supported by 'substantial' reserves of  over 417 million pounds.
<P>
Although the education and transport departments continued to spend  over budget, other departments made savings and control over General  Fund spending in the finacial year 1995/96 was 'adequate', he says.
<P>
'This should not give rise to complacency, however, since long term  budget projections continue to indicate the creation of insupportable  General Fund deficits if nothing is done to contain them,' Mr Johnston writes.
<P>
Although the council still faces uncertainty over future Govenment  support for its 82 million pounds-a-year revenue spending, it has the  opposite problem on its capital programme, which was underspent last  year by 11.8 million pounds, or almost 30 per cent. 
<P>
'More effective programme co-ordination and management' is needed,  according to the finance department.
<P>
The council was again debt-free last year, apart from a 60 million  pounds housing debt, run up in the 1970s to house incoming oil  workers. Negotiations with the Scottish Office are continuing, with a  view to  writing off the loans, mostly from private financiers.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

