<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Oil funds may pay for new school

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Oil funds may pay for new school
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
15th October 1996
<P>
New buildings for Shetland's senior high school could be an  investment for the islands' oil revenues, according to convener Lewis Smith.
<P>
Former pupil Mr Smith said yesterday (MON) the Government's Private  Finance Initiative was 'the only way' to fund a new Anderson High  School in Lerwick - but the main investor could be the council's own  charitable trust, through its property company, Shetland Leasing and  Property Developments Ltd (SLAP).
<P>
The 180 million pounds trust currently invests most of its Sullom Voe  oil terminal revenues in the Stock Market and Government securities.
<P>
The issue came up when the Shetland Education Committee yesterday  discussed a list of expensive maintenance work on the Anderson High,  part of which dates back to 1862.
<P>
Councillor Tavish Scott (Liberal Democrat, Lerwick Harbour and  Bressay) asked why there had been no progress in the past two years  on a replacement school.
<P>
Mr Smith likened the existing buildings to 'a barrack block on a  peninsula', remote from playing fields, expensive to heat and with  'appalling' access and facilities for the disabled. 
<P>
The council had already decided the 'only sensible option' was a  'greenfield' site at Clickimin on the western outskirts of the town,  where the new school and halls of residence could use the gymnasium,  swimming pool and sports grounds owned by Shetland Recreational Trust.
<P>
'I think the Private Finance Initiative, as long as the present  Government is in power, will be the only way we can finance a new  Anderson High School. I suspect if there's a change of government  it'll still be the only way,' Mr Smith said.
<P>
'There are possibly ways in Shetland in which we can do that and not  have an outside company providing the private side of the finance ...  We could use our own capital and there would be a return on that investment.'
<P>
The 33 million pounds project was 'top priority for the council's  whole capital programme'.
<P>
The committeee asked officials for a detailed report on the new  school by the end of this year, along with proposals from consultants  on ways to save money on their 23 million pounds annual education budget.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

