<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Road rage on the information superhighway

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Road rage on the information superhighway
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
15th October 1996
<P>
A prosecution is likely after electronic road rage blocked one of the  fastest-growing lanes of Britain's information super-highway for  seven hours over the weekend, it was revealed yesterday (MON).
<P>
Several thousand customers of <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/">Zetnet Services Ltd</A>, the Shetland-based  Internet access provider, suddenly found themselves in cyber-gridlock  late on Saturday night. Electronic mail and Internet access through  the company's Manchester computer banks slowed to a crawl as the  traffic jam spread nationwide.
<P>
Zetnet technical director Tim Cole was called in to his Lerwick  office to deal with what at first looked like a computer failure. But  it quickly became clear that a 'malicious' user, surfing after hours  in London University's computer centre, was deliberately jamming the  system.
<P>
Mr Cole explained yesterday (MON): 'It seems there was an argument  between one of our customers and the user of another system on  Saturday night, all very silly and childish. The user of the other  system decided to do something very nasty and bring down the whole of  Zetnet in revenge - a case of road rage on the information superhighway. 
<P>
'Technically, what this as yet unidentified person did was send  continuous streams of very large packets of information to one of our  140 local call rate phone lines. The effect was that our normal  traffic was getting bullied out of the way, which brought 95 per cent  of our customers to a standstill,' Mr Cole said. 
<P>
The situation was so serious by 4am on Sunday that Mr Cole had to  call out BT Net's senior technical manager, Peter Willis. He traced  and cut off the offender's access to Zetnet and normal surfing was  resumed by 7am.
<P>
Mr Cole said a prosecution in England was 'likely' under the Misuse  of Compters Act. 'We were hit and damaged very badly, and so was BT  Net, by someone acting like a little kiddie,' he said. He likened the  situation to a 'hard nut' biker driving the wrong way up the M62,  causing accidents and 'forcing other drivers off the road'.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

