<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Cheaper job on school budget savings

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Cheaper job on school budget savings
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
12th October 1996
<P>
Asking mainland experts how to save money on island schools is a lot  cheaper than hiring outsiders to suggest economies in ferry budgets,  Shetland councillors learned yesterday (FRI).
<P>
Papers published for next week's education committee meeting reveal  that two redundant Strathclyde Region officials are willing to  examine the islands' 23 million pounds annual education budget - for  fees and expenses of 10,000 pounds.
<P>
Last week councillors agreed to a budget of 50-80,000 pounds for  consultants to come up with annual savings of 750,000 pounds on the 6  million pounds a year cost of council ferry services.
<P>
The ferries job is going out to tender but the education review will  not, if councillors accept the advice of education director James Halcrow. 
<P>
In his report, Mr Halcrow says the scope of the education  consultants' work should be limited to 'the range of possible areas  for initial policy consideration by the council, along with an  assessment of the likely implications in quality of service and  expenditure terms'.
<P>
This is taken to mean that Shetland's own education officials will  draw up the detailed plans for savings to put before the council next year.
<P>
Mr Halcrow said yesterday (FRI) the terms of reference for the study  were 'fairly broad brush'. Rumours that the consultants would be  drawing up 'a hit list of schools for closure' were 'pure speculation'.
<P>
As expected, Mr Halcrow recommends hiring former Strathclyde Region  chief executive Neil McIntosh and former Strathclyde senior depute  education director David Alexander. Both men retired during local  government reorganisation earlier this year and now work for the  COSLA Consultancy, set up by the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities.
<P>
Mr Halcrow said: 'There was no need to go out to tender, nor would  you have been able to get this kind of expertise in the open market.'  He said about half of the consultants' fees would be 'retained by  COSLA for the benefit of local government'.
<P>
Councillor Bill Smith, Shetland's education chairman, said yesterday  (FRI) he had no comment on the proposal not to go to tender. 
<P>
Asked about the cost difference in the consultancy exercises for  education and ferries, he said: 'It's all to the good. I hope the  effects will be in the same proportion.'
<P>
Mr Smith, a veteran Labour councillor, has firmly resisted cuts in  Shetland's 37 schools, which consistently produce some of the best  results in Scotland.
<P>
The controversial decision to hire outside consultants is part of a  council-wide drive to save a total of 5 million pounds a year by the  end of the century.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

