<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Fisheries scientist denies Greenpeace charges

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Fisheries scientist denies Greenpeace charges
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
11th October 1996
<P>
A senior Scottish fisheries scientist yesterday (THURS) denied  <A HREF="http://www.greenpeace.org/">Greenpeace</A> allegations that the Government is promoting the  exploitation of deep-sea fish stocks west of Scotland.
<P>
Dr John Gordon of the Dunstaffnage Marine Laboratory near Oban said  British and European Union public money was funding research about  life on the deep sea floor and the effects of catching fish which can  live up to 80 years.
<P>
The impetus for the new fishery was coming from fishermen, not from  Government, he said.
<P>
Greenpeace have asked the Prime Minister to ban the developing  deep-water fishery, saying species like Orange Roughy, Round-nosed  Grenadier and Black Scabbard Fish are slow-growing and cannot  replenish themselves if fished intensively.
<P>
The environmental campaigners' UK chief executive, Lord Melchett,  wrote a personal letter to John Major in August, warning of 'a  biological disaster' and economic collapse of the trawler fleet if  fishing effort continues in waters up to 3,000 feet deep, west of  Shetland and the Hebrides.
<P>
Dr Gordon said Greenpeace were 'right in a way'. The fish did mature  very slowly, living in constant darkness and near-zero temperatures.  There was evidence that some species produced few young. While there  could be good catches in the early stages of a deep-sea fishery,  these could rapidly decline as older fish were caught and not  replaced by younger stock.
<P>
'We have to be cautious in exploiting these stocks but the Government  is not advocating or promoting it, rather helping research to find  out more,' he said. 
<P>
Dr Gordon is due to give a second lecture about deep-sea fisheries  next week at the <A HREF="http://www.nafc.ac.uk/">North Atlantic Fisheries College</A> in Scalloway, Shetland.
<P>
College principal Morgan Goodlad said yesterday that market economics  were likely to limit the fishery: 'The cost of harvesting them is  higher, because you need bigger ships, working further from shore,  and more expensive gear. And they're difficult to market because they're new. 
<P>
'They're also very ugly fish, totally unattractive. To cover the  higher cost of catching them you need a premium price, not what you'd  get for putting them in fish fingers,' Mr Goodlad said. 'On top of  that, the sustainability of the fishery must be highly questionable.'
<P>
Dr Gordon said a few Scottish boats were following the lead of the  French fleet and targeting Orange Roughy in particular, but most UK  landings of deep-sea species were still a 'by-catch' of trawling for  the more valuable, and better-known, Monkfish and Blue Ling.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

