<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Leisure and recreation under the hammer

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Leisure and recreation under the hammer  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
11th October 1996
<P>
Shetland councillors yesterday (THURS) elected Councillor Billy Stove  as new chairman for their Leisure and Recreation Committee - and  immediately agreed to scrap their Leisure and Recreation Department  as an economy measure, without knowing how much money the move will save.
<P>
The committee remains in being but will hand over most of the  department's functions to the council's Education Department and two  charitable trusts, after approving in principle a review by education  director James Halcrow.
<P>
The defunct department's museums, archives, community work and sports  staff will transfer to education, the committee unanimously agreed  after a short debate. 
<P>
Most of the properties run by leisure and recreation, including  Lerwick's Islesburgh community centre, youth hostel and Garrison  Theatre, will be managed in future by the independent Shetland  Recreational Trust, if detailed negotiations between the council and  the trust are successful. The council will retain ownership.
<P>
Councillors also agreed to ask the recreational trust to manage the  council's sports pitches, playgrounds and public parks. Mr Halcrow  said the trust had 'a good record' and already provided a booking  service for some council-owned properties.
<P>
The leisure department's tourism promotion work moves to the  Development Department and the Shetland Arts Trust will be asked to  take over all arts projects.
<P>
Mr Halcrow's 14-page report said it was 'not possible to quantify, at  this stage, the savings which will accrue'. He made no mention of  redundancies, other than not replacing the recently retired leisure  director, John P. Nicolson. 
<P>
An eight-member review group of councillors suggested the changes  earlier this year, as part of a search for economies. The leisure and  recreation department currently costs around 4.8 million pounds a  year and hands out oil fund grants worth over 1.1 million pounds to  dozens of island sports clubs, playschemes, village halls and voluntary groups.
<P>
Mr Halcrow said he could not make detailed recommendations on how a  reduced grants budget should be allocated until councillors  themselves decided what the overall cuts should be.
<P>
The new committee chairman, Mr Stove, is a Lerwick councillor who was  formerly vice-chairman. He succeeds Councillor Peter Guy, who  recently resigned when he moved to North Yorkshire. Councillor Bobby  Johnson was elected as the new vice-chairman of the only council  committee which will no longer have its own department to supervise.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

