<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News -  No cash for snow-bashed fences

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   No cash for snow-bashed fences
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
11th October 1996
<P>
Shetland crofters seeking council compensation, for fences allegedly  flattened by snowploughs during last year's Christmas blizzards, will  be out of luck if councillors accept a recommendation by officials.
<P>
A report for next week's Shetland Islands Council roads committee  says the council's insurers, Zurich Municipal, have rejected the 17  claims, totalling 7,500 pounds.
<P>
Roads and transport director Joe Gray says although there is 'no  evidence of fault or negligence' by snowplough drivers who cleared  500 miles of roads in five days, it would be 'reasonable' to use the  council reserve fund to compensate people whose fences, in his  opinion, were 'most probably damaged by the council during snow clearing'.
<P>
But, while he is 'not unsympathetic' to the claimants, Mr Gray says  the council has no legal liability in the absence of proof and, if it  did pay for the fencing, might be unable to resist future claims when  insurers refuse to.
<P>
'It should not be forgotten that crofters have a responsibility to  protect their own assets in the same manner as everyone else,' he  says in his five-page report. 'Presumably, the option not to carry  this type of (insurance) cover was borne of their own free choice.'
<P>
'This conclusion has been arrived at after much consultation and  consideration,' Mr Gray says, but, on the advice of council legal  staff, he firmly recommends 'no further action'.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
