<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Foula ferry really is ready this time

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Foula ferry really is ready this time
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
10th October 1996
<P>
The two million pounds, six-year saga of a new ferry for Foula,  Britain's most remote inhabited island, is nearly over.
<P>
After building a special pier costing over a million pounds, and a  400,000 pounds boat which failed sea trials, Shetland Islands Council  announced yesterday (WED) that their second attempt at a Foula ferry  was a success, after spending another 400,000 pounds. 
<P>
Only bad weather is now preventing delivery of the 38-foot-long 'New  Advance' from Richardson's boatyard in Stromness, Orkney, to Foula (pop. 50).
<P>
Last minute hitches over certificates for the boat brought new delays  after the builders finished work more than a month ago. The council  is currently recruiting a new skipper for the 18-mile exposed  Atlantic crossing.
<P>
Foula councillor Jim Gear said yesterday: 'It's been a long time.  We're all very pleased that we now have a solution, with a ferry  which we believe will be satisfactory.' The island had suffered  because of the delays but he hoped the Foula economy could now start  to develop again.
<P>
The Foula ferry fiasco has attracted national media attention as one  problem after another dogged what once seemed a straightforward project:
<P>
*  The original design proved unstable at speed in following seas,  leading to an official inquiry and acrimony among councillors about  who was responsible (no-one was, it emerged);
<P>
*  The council had to repay European grants for the boat, which was  eventually converted to a training vessel at Shetland's fishery college;
<P>
*  The islanders' insistence on having their ferry based on Foula,  rather than the Shetland mainland, meant an expensive crane had to be  fitted, to lift the boat out of the water during the winter;
<P>
*  Foula-based crew hired for the first ferry had to be kept on   while the second one was built and the island was served meantime by  a mainland crew;
<P>
*  The council shipped a chalet to Foula to house Captain Allan Cook,  hired as skipper last year. But he resigned after six months, changed  his mind and then resigned again earlier this year after  disagreements with other islanders.
<P>
*  Under Government regulations, unless the council can recruit a  fully qualified skipper the ferry will still have to be based at West  Burrafirth, on the Shetland mainland.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

