<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News -  Suburban fence causes offence at ancient monument

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Suburban fence causes offence at ancient monument
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
10th October 1996
<P><A HREF="fence.jpg"><IMG SRC="fences.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=254 HEIGHT=162 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Suburbia is creeping up on one of Scotland's most famous prehistoric  sites but yesterday (WED) Shetland councillors granted planning  permission for a fence which has caused offence to Historic Scotland,  keepers of the 2,000-year-old Broch of Clickimin.
<P>
The Edinburgh-based quango which looks after ancient monuments  opposed a retrospective planning application by Laurence Chapman, The  Willows, South Road, Lerwick.
<P>
Mr Chapman had already concreted in the posts for the 'ranch style'  wooden fence, unaware that he was doing wrong. His new house is a few  hundred yards from the famous Pictish fort, already surrounded on  three sides by the suburbs of Lerwick (pop. 7,500).
<P>
In a letter to Shetland Islands Council's planning committee, Ewan  Young of Historic Scotland said the fence was 'utterly inappropriate'  and would have 'an unfortunate visual impact upon this important  structure' and 'further detract from its archaeological and  architectural significance'.
<P>
Promising the council's planning department 'full support to resist  firmly the proposal', Mr Young said the setting of the broch had  already been 'compromised' by new house-building in the area: 'The  effect has been visually to place the broch in, and thereby to  associate it with, suburbia,' he wrote.
<P>
Local councillor Billy Stove said the building restrictions were  'stupid' and 'astounding'. All his constituent wanted to do was fence  in the horse which he and his wife kept in a paddock next to the house.
<P>
'It seems you can't even put up a clothes line in case you spoil the  view of the Picts' Castle from a quarter of a mile away,' he said.  The fence would only be a metre high. He moved approval, against the  advice of the planning department and Historic Scotland, who would  only agree to a post-and-wire fence.
<P>
Councillor Drew Ratter, a crofter with considerable fencing  experience, seconded Mr Stove but warned: 'You can easily have  problems with horses and one-metre-high fences.'
<P>
The controversial structure was then approved without a vote.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

