<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Ferry consultants must save £ 0.75m, 'in good English'

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Ferry consultants must save £ 0.75m, 'in good English'
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
9th October 1996
<P>
Consultants advising Shetland Islands Council how to run its ferries  better must be literate and come up with annual savings of around  750,000 pounds, councillors agreed yesterday (TUES).
<P>
They approved a consultancy budget of between 50,000 and 80,000  pounds and a brief for the job, which goes out to tender shortly and  has already attracted interest from more than 30 firms.
<P>
The transport committee said the review should be 'comprehensive' and  must result in a ferry service which is 'satisfactory, efficient and  affordable' while ensuring 'the social and economic wellbeing of the islands'.
<P>
The project, due for completion by the end of March next year, is  part of a council-wide drive to save a total of 5 million pounds a  year on the general fund.
<P>
Committee chairman Magnus Flaws sought to allay Councillor Jim Gear's  fears of cuts in services by saying the consultants could only  recommend. It was for the council to decide and there would be  'widespread consultation' during the process.
<P>
The ferrymen's union TGWU fears the review may bring wage and job  cuts. TGWU district officer John Taylor said last week he did not  understand the need for outside consultants but senior councillors  insist the price will be worth it if long-term savings are made in  the ferries budget, currently running at between five and six million  pounds a year.
<P>
A stipulation by council transport director Joe Gray is for the  review to be 'in good English, free from grammatical and  typographical errors'. In his draft terms of reference, Mr Gray went  on to say he would require 'a comprehensive method statement'. 
<P>
Our Management-Speak Correspondent writes: 'This is understood to  mean tenderers must say exactly how they plan to do the job.'
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

