<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Crewman flown to hospital with burns

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Crewman flown to hospital with burns
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
9th October 1996
<P>
A ship took part in a winching exercise with a Coastguard helicopter  off Shetland yesterday (TUES) morning - and five hours later did it  for real with an injured crewman.
<P>
Coastguards said the British-registered oilfield standby ship 'Viking  Ranger' was 20 miles west of the island of Foula when second engineer  Robert Jones, from Montrose, suffered burns in an accident on board  at around 3.30pm.
<P>
The rescue helicopter 'Oscar Charlie' was scrambled from Sumburgh  Airport. The crew airlifted Mr Jones from the deck, in a Force 8 gale  and heavy seas, and flew him to the Gilbert Bain Hospital in Lerwick,  where he was landed at 5.05pm.
<P>
Last night the hospital refused to confirm that Mr Jones was a  patient and declined comment on his condition.
<P>
Earlier in the day the 'Viking Ranger' had exercised with the same  helicopter while on passage from the West Shetland oilfields to  Lerwick, where the ship was due late last night (TUES).
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

