<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Fishermen's leader piles on the political pressure

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Fishermen's leader piles on the political pressure
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
9th October 1996
<P>
Shetland fishermen's chairman Josie Simpson is spending a second week  on the road, lobbying politicians for reforms in fisheries policy.
<P>
Mr Simpson, a retired herring boat skipper, is at the Conservative  Party Conference in Bournemouth, with colleagues from mainland  Scottish ports, to press the case for more local control of  fisheries, better stock conservation, rebuilding the fleet and  controls on foreign boats exploiting waters around the Northern Isles.
<P>
Last week Mr Simpson and Shetland Fishermen's Association secretary  John Goodlad lobbied the Labour conference in Blackpool, as the  Scottish Fishermen's Federation stepped up efforts to make fishing  policy a major issue at the forthcoming general election.
<P>
This week Mr Goodlad is flying to Brussels, to urge the European  Union to take 'a very firm line' with Norway in this month's  negotiations about the share-out of mackerel catches.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

