<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Lottery bid possible for Westside leisure centre

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Lottery bid possible for Westside leisure centre
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
9th October 1996
<P>
The National Lottery Fund may be asked to help build the long-delayed  Westside Leisure Centre, says Shetland Recreational Trust chairman Joe Irvine.
<P>
Writing in the annual report of the trust, published yesterday  (TUES), Mr Irvine says trustees are 'frustrated' by lack of progress  on their eighth leisure centre, planned for the village of Aith in  the west mainland but stymied by a continuing freeze on spending by  Shetland Islands Council's Charitable Trust.
<P>
Mr Irvine, who is head teacher of Brae Junior High School, says the  public demand is clear: more than half a million people passed  through the doors of trust's seven centres last year, 23 times the  total population of the islands.
<P>
He describes another record year as fitness-crazy islanders flocked  to the new 11.5 million pounds Clickimin swimming pool and bowls hall  in Lerwick.
<P>
Mr Irvine says the trust suffered 'a severe blow' when it lost the  services of manager Andy Meyers, who has moved to a new job in the  south, and his predecessor John P. Nicolson, whom councillors last  year forced to resign as a trustee, under a controversial new policy  preventing council officials serving on trusts.
<P>
Mr Meyers and Mr Nicolson, who has since retired after 21 years as  the council's leisure director, are praised in the report as 'a  formidable double act' who oversaw the building of the recreation  trust's 'magnificent facilities' throughout the islands.
<P>
The most popular leisure centres of all in the 12 months to March  this year were on two offlying islands, each with a population of  only around 1,000. 
<P>
In Whalsay, the pool and leisure centre at Symbister attracted some  47,000 patrons, 47 times the local population. Unst, Britain's most  northerly island, was almost as keen on fitness and fun, with  admissions amounting to 37 times the number of residents. 
<P>
The trust was founded in the early 1980s, with an endowment from the  islands oil revenues, and charged with promoting health and social  welfare, through sports and leisure activities for all ages.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

