<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - BSE threatens council's beef investment

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  BSE threatens council's beef investment
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

8th October 1996
<P>
Council investments of around 800,000 pounds in Shetland's beef  industry are threatened by the continuing BSE crisis, according to a  detailed report for today's (TUES) meeting of Shetland Islands  Council's development committee.
<P>
Andrew Harmsworth, the council's agricultural officer, reveals the  full extent of the problem for the first time. 
<P>
He tells councillors that although there have only been 12 BSE cases  in Shetland's 2,316 beef breeding cows and heifers, involving just  eight out of 167 herds, the current price drop of 30 per cent is 'a  severe strain' on farmers and crofters.
<P>
He says solving the financial crisis is 'well beyond the capacity' of  the council's grants budget, which for over a decade has used oil  revenues to encourage farmers and crofters to keep more and  better-bred cattle, thus improving the land and diversifying  agricultural incomes. 
<P>
Largely as a result of the council's efforts, 'dwindling' beef cow  numbers in the early 1980s have increased by a fifth in 15 years,  sustaining 'a very valuable asset' now worth 1.3 million pounds a  year, Mr Harmsworth says.
<P>
Although losses on beef are compensated by current high prices for  Shetland's staple trade in lambs, he believes the council's  investment is now 'under threat' and beef herds will decline again if  the market remains depressed next year.
<P>
Development committee chairman Drew Ratter, who is also secretary of  the Shetland Crofters' Union, said yesterday: 'We've been working  hard to improve the health of our beef cattle for years and this blow  is no fault of our own.
<P>
'We don't have the fodder to keep stock over the winter so we're  forced to sell and take a loss. Ninety per cent of all BSE cases are  in dairy cattle. Our hill-fed beef is a good, clean product.  Suckler-cow producers who have no record of BSE should have different status.'
<P>
Mr Ratter, a crofter who is himself selling cattle at auction today,  said the Government's performance on the BSE cull and compensation  was 'a piece of nonsense' designed to 'postpone spending until after  the election'.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

