<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - New Muckle Roe Brig scheduled for '98

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  New Muckle Roe Brig scheduled for '98
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
<P>
8th October 1996
<P>
A new one million pounds bridge to one of Shetland's most picturesque  islands is planned to start construction in two years' time, with not  a mention of toll charges or the Government's Private Finance Initiative.
<P>
Shetland Islands councillors are expected to grant planning  permission tomorrow (WED) for the 100-yard long bridge to Muckle Roe  (pop. 103), almost half a century after the old bridge was rebuilt by  the former Zetland County Council.
<P>
The existing bridge has a 10 tonne weight restriction, which prevents  tourist coaches visiting the island, causes difficulties for crofters  and contractors moving heavy machinery, and hinders truck drivers  delivering central heating oil and agricultural fertiliser.
<P>
David McNae of the council's roads department said yesterday the new  structure would bring the road to Muckle Roe into line with council  policy of no weight restrictions. Assuming planning permission is  granted, he hoped to put the project out to tender early next year  and to make a start in the spring of 1998.
<P>
The old bridge, parts of it dating to before the First World War,  will then be demolished.
<P>
Mr McNae said there were no plans for bridge tolls.
<P>
Planning officials are recommending contractors to take care not to  pollute the narrow, tidal Muckle Roe Sound during construction and  demolition works, and to avoid a nearby site of special botanical  interest, the Muckle Roe Meadows.
<P>
The three-mile-wide island is a thriving crofting community and has  some of the finest coastal scenery in Shetland.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
