<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Isles suffer total power failure

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Isles suffer total power failure
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

<P>
7th October 1996
<P>
The first of the winter's big power cuts meant no hot breakfast or  Sunday roast for much of Shetland yesterday (SUN), when a broken  lightning conductor at the Sullom Voe Terminal's power station  tripped out the islands' entire electricity grid.
<P>
A Hydro Electric spokeswoman said the incident was 'serious' but  denied it had anything to do with a new generator at the company's  Lerwick power station, which has suffered teething troubles over the past year.
<P>
She said equipment at Lerwick failed to detect the fault, which led  to the blackout.
<P>
Every consumer in Shetland was affected by the major power cut at  8.45am. Hydro engineers managed to restore electricity to Lerwick  within 15 minutes. Southern and western parts of the islands were  re-connected at 11.20am but many areas were cut off until shortly before 1pm.
<P>
The incident came after a night of high winds and rain, following a  series of momentary power cuts in some parts of the islands during  the past few days.
<P>







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

