<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Sail Shetland makes a promising start

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Sail Shetland makes a promising start
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
4th October 1996
<P>
Over 200 representatives of local businesses attended a fund raising event organised by Sail Shetland Ltd. in the Clickimin Centre last night (THUR).
<P>
In November last year Sail Shetland succeeded in its bid to attract the Cutty Sark Tall Ships Races to Lerwick in 1999. The company will be responsible for organising the event, which is expected to attract  thousands of visitors  to the islands.
<P>
Chairman of Sail Shetland, Canon Lewis Smith, said in his address: 'The choice of Lerwick as a host port is wonderful news for Shetland. The stay provides a focus for the whole community to work together on a major international event, an event which will be the biggest and most spectacular Shetland has ever known.'
<P>
According to Bob Steele, treasurer of  Sail Shetland Ltd., 80,000 pounds of the 500,000 pounds needed to stage the spectacle has been already raised before last night reception.
<P>
The idea of last night's meeting was not just to raise as much money as possible, but to make local businesses think what they might gain by sponsoring the event. The Tall Ships will generate an estimated 2.2 million pounds in the local economy.
<P>
More than one hundred square riggers, schooners and yachts are expected in Lerwick harbour between the 9th and the 12th August 1999. Shetland is  the half-way mark on the races between St. Malo in France and Aalborg in Denmark.
<P>
Guest at the reception was Brigadier Robin Duchesne of the International Sail Training Association, which has organised the  races since 1956. He said: 'At least half the crews have to be aged between 15 and 25.We are absolutely strict about that. The Cutty Sark Tall Ships Races are really about young people.
<P>
'We are international. The first prize goes to the ship that has done the most to promote international understanding and  friendship,' he said.
<P>
Shetland Islands Tourism director Maurice Mullay is expecting 4,000  extra visitors for the cavalcade of sail, besides the 3,000 crew  members. He said: 'We have to make sure that there are adequate facilities, enough beds for instance. We will put out an appeal to the general population for spare beds to cope with this demand.
<P>
'I have every confidence in the people of Shetland to come forward as they have in the past,' he said.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

