<DOCHDR>
http://www.shetland-news.co.uk:80/headline/melchett/melchett.html 194.72.245.173 19970110123336 text/html 4825
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 12:33:41 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4654
Last-modified: Fri, 04 Oct 1996 19:47:03 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Greenpeace asks PM to halt West Shetland oil

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Greenpeace asks PM to halt West Shetland oil
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
5th October 1996
<P>
The top man in Greenpeace UK has written a private letter to the  Prime Minister, asking him to stop oil production from Britain's new  West Shetland oilfields - and to take a world lead in solar power and  other sustainable energy.
<P>
BP and Shell have already spent hundreds of millions of pounds on  developing the first three fields in the 'Atlantic Frontier' up to  100 miles west of Shetland - Foinaven, Schiehallion and Clair.
<P>
Peter Melchett, executive director of Greenpeace UK, wrote to the  Prime Minister on August 21. The letter, seen by The Shetland News  Agency yesterday (FRI), said there was no need to exploit the oil,  because there was plenty elsewhere, and no 'common benefit' from doing so.
<P>
Lord Melchett said there was a 'serious contradiction' in the  Government's energy policy. The Department of Trade and Industry was  'fast-tracking' BP's new oilfields, despite Environment Secretary  John Gummer's commitment, at the Rio eco-summit four years ago, to  reduce the amount of carbon dioxide from burning oil, gas and coal.
<P>
'Relatively simple calculation shows that the world's atmosphere  cannot sustain the use of more than a few per cent of known fossil  fuel reserves,' Lord Melchett said.
<P>
'If there is one place which is a touchstone for Britain's commitment  to environmental protection and sustainable development, it is West  of Shetland... There are new and considerable risks to people and the  environment which arise through the largely untested and ''frontier''  technology which the industry intends to employ.'
<P>
The Greenpeace boss charged that there had been 'very little public  debate and almost no Parliamentary scrutiny' because the projects  were being 'fast-tracked with minimal public information'.  Even  statistics about seabirds, collected for the oil companies by the  Joint Nature Conservation Committee, were classed as 'commercial in  confidence'.
<P>
He told Mr Major: 'Greenpeace calls on you to halt the development of  the oilfields west of Shetland and, in so doing, to give the world  leadership by showing that you intend to put Britain and its energy  policy on a true path to a more sustainable future.'
<P>
A BP spokesman in London said yesterday (FRI): 'We decline to comment  on a private correspondence between Lord Melchett of Greenpeace and  the Prime Minister.'
<P>
Downing Street said yesterday (FRI) that the Prime Minister had  replied to Lord Melchett but regarded such letters as 'confidential'.
<P>
The 500 million barrels Foinaven oilfield is due on stream in April  next year, loading tankers at a wellhead in 1400 feet of water, 100  miles west of Shetland.
<P>
Lord Melchett told Mr Major it was 'remarkable' that only one British  government building had a solar electric panel. Solar energy could  provide two thirds of our energy needs, even in Britain. Renewable  energy sources were more abundant than fossil fuels, yet the  Department of Trade and Industry spent roughly twice as much on  publicity and promotion for the oil industry as it invested in solar  technology.
<P>
Lord Melchett also attacked proposals to exploit stocks of deep water  fish in the same area of the Atlantic, saying the ecology of the deep  ocean was 'fragile' and could not sustain heavy fishing: 'It is  widely feared that the development of fisheries for these very deep  fish is very likely to result in a biological disaster,' he wrote.
<P>
Fishermen from Shetland and elsewhere are gearing up to exploit the  shoals of Orange Roughy and other deep-sea fish.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

