<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Shetland can do better at recycling

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Shetland can do better at recycling
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
4th October 1996
<P>
'Alarming' statistics show that a six-year-old Shetland scheme to  re-cycle aluminium cans for charity has failed to stop islanders  throwing away more than 60,000 pounds' worth of the valuable metal.
<P>
Vic Thomas of Shetland Amenity Trust yesterday (THURS) called for  renewed efforts to halt the waste.
<P>
'The trust has run the scheme since 1990 and the marvellous efforts  of schools, youth clubs, canteens, offices etc. have raised over  6,000 pounds for national charities, school funds and local groups,' he said.
<P>
'Last year in the UK over 40 million pounds' worth of aluminium cans  were thrown away and lost to the recycling industry. Here in Shetland  we recover and recycle 11 per cent of available cans. That's a loss  of 11,000 pounds a year.
<P>
'This alarming discovery means we throw away more cans each year than  we've collected since the scheme began. Shetland has dumped over  60,000 pounds' worth and is continuing to do so,' Mr Thomas said.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

