<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Killer disease attacks pet bunnies

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Killer disease attacks pet bunnies
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

4th October 1996
<P>
'Bleeding Bunny Disease' has reached Shetland, only four years after  the first case was reported in the south of England.
<P>
The good news for farmers and crofters has brought heartbreak to  island children as their pet rabbits succumb to the killer plague,  known to vets as viral haemorrhagic disease.
<P>
Shetland vet Juliet Nicolson said yesterday (THURS) her practice on  the west side of the islands had had 20 pet rabbit deaths reported in  the past fortnight.
<P>
'It causes internal bleeding and liver damage and is always fatal,'  Mrs Nicolson said. How it spread was unknown but it could be blown on  the wind, carried by birds, or through food or bedding.
<P>
A Scottish Office spokeswoman said they had reports of cases in wild  and domestic rabbits.
<P>
'It's quite virulent and there's a high mortality rate,' she said. It  was made a notifiable disease in 1991 and the first case was in 1992.
<P>
The Scottish Office recommended pet owners to vaccinate their rabbits.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

