<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Union rejects pay cut for ferry crews

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Union rejects pay cut for ferry crews
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
3rd October 1996
<P>
The transport workers' union TGWU yesterday (WED) flatly rejected a  proposed 27 per cent pay cut for some Shetland ferrymen and demanded  an urgent meeting with island councillors.
<P>
TGWU district officer John Taylor was speaking in Aberdeen after a  flying visit to consult his members on council ferries to the small,  offlying islands of Fair Isle, Foula and Papa Stour.
<P>
Last week ferry managers gave the union a report which advocates the  wage reductions as part of a council-wide ecnomy drive.
<P>
Mr Taylor said the union spent two years negotiating a pay and  conditions deal, signed in 1994 with the council: 'We will accept no  changes whatsoever but require an urgent discussion to see if there's  a hidden agenda.' 
<P>
He feared the plan was to base the Foula ferry crew on the Shetland  mainland rather than their home islands. Papa Stour is already served  by a mainland crew and it would be impracticable to base the Fair  Isle ferry at the small, exposed Grutness Pier which is the mainland  terminal for the ferry 'Good Shepherd IV'.
<P>
Last night Councillor Alastair Goodlad, vice-chairman of the  council's marine committee, said on local BBC radio: 'There had  better not be a hidden agenda.' Council policy was to base the Foula  ferry in Foula, and that was that.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
