<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News -  Fishers lobby Labour conference

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Fishers lobby Labour conference
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
3rd October 1996
<P>
Leaders of Shetland's fishermen are in Blackpool to lobby the Labour  Party conference and Dr Gavin Strang MP - the man tipped to be  fisheries minister if Labour win the general election.
<P>
Shetland Fishermen's Association chairman Josie Simpson and secretary  John Goodlad joined colleagues from the Scottish mainland in arguing  the case against foreign 'flag-ships' - which register in UK ports to  get a bigger share of British fish stocks.
<P>
The delegation also put the case for reforming the European Common  Fisheries Policy and for schemes such as 'scrap-and-build' to  modernise the fleet.
<P>
Dr Strang, whose wife Bettina hails from the island of Bressay, is  well acquainted with the Shetand fishermen's case, having been  briefed in detail by Mr Goodlad at a meeting last month.
<P>
Meanwhile Mr Goodlad yesterday (WED) described as 'a gross  exaggeration' a report by the Scottish Council, Development and  Industry, which said 40 per cent of UK fish landings were illegal and  part of a multi-million pounds fraud.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

