<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News -  Divers warned of legal and safety dangers

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>   Divers warned of legal and safety dangers
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
3rd October 1996
<P>
A team from the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) has arrived in  Shetland to urge salmon farmers to obey the law when using divers to  work on their fish cages.
<P>
Frank Murray, HSE's senior Scottish inspector, said yesterday (WED)  the aim was to encourage safe practice 'rather than get people prosecuted'.
<P>
Mr Murray said there was evidence some divers working on salmon farms  were not fully trained or registered, ignored standard safety  procedures and, because of ignorance, were hazarding their long-term health.
<P>
'The smallest (diving) team possible is a supervisor and two divers,  but the practicalities of coping with underwater hazards, handling a  boat, recovering a diver in an emergency, etc., mean that a team will  normally need to consist of at least four professionals, sometimes  more,' he said.
<P>
HSE had heard of 'much smaller' teams working from boats in remote  areas, which was 'both unsafe and illegal', Mr Murray said.
<P>
He offered free advice to fish farmers, diving contractors and  individual divers.
<P>









<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

