<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Three ferry crews face 27 per cent pay cut

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Three ferry crews face 27 per cent pay cut
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


2nd October 1996
<P>
Shetland council ferry bosses want to cut the pay of some inter-island ferrymen by 27 per cent, as part of an economy drive.
<P>
Reliable sources close to talks with the men's union, the TGWU, say the islands affected are Foula (pop. 50), Papa Stour (35) and Fair Isle (pop. 70).
<P>
The four-man crews of these ferries work shorter hours than their colleagues on services between the main Shetland islands but are paid the same, under an agreement signed in 1994 after a prolonged dispute.
<P>
A report on negotiations with the crews at the council's Joint Consultative Committee (JCC) was withdrawn from the agenda of the Shetland Islands Council Marine Operations Committee yesterday (TUES).
<P>
Chairman Willie Tait said the staff side had 'declined to discuss it' as they wanted more time for consultation with ferry managers.
<P>
Marine director Capt. George Sutherland said yesterday he could not comment on what went on at the JCC, which met in private: 'The consultation process is still going on,' he said.
<P>
It is estimated the proposal could save the council over 70,000 pounds a year in wages.
<P>
TGWU official John Taylor was in Shetland yesterday to meet his members on the ferries but neither he nor shop stewards were available for comment. ENDS






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

