<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Discipline 'not appropriate' for unauthorised spending

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Discipline 'not appropriate' for unauthorised spending
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


2nd October 1996 
<P>
It would not be 'appropriate' to discipline Shetland council officials who spent 90,000 pounds on repairs to a pier without formal approval, their boss said yesterday (TUES).
<P>
Captain George Sutherland, marine operations director and depute chief executive of Shetland Islands Council, told his committee the spending on the ferry ramp at Symbister in the island of Whalsay had been brought forward after a survey showed the work was urgent.
<P>
The figure was still within the total repairs budget because other projects were delayed, but Capt. Sutherland expressed 'regret' that 'the correct procedures' were not followed and promised staff would be better trained in future.
<P>
'There's no question that they weren't aware of the proper procedure,' he said.
<P>
Referring to a recent case where two senior leisure department officials were disciplined after similarly unauthorised spending of 134,000 pounds on recreation projects, Councillor Tavish Scott said the council had to be consistent: 'I wouldn't like to see double standards,' he said.
<P>
Councillor Brian Gregson asked: 'What is the possibility of disciplinary action?'
<P>
'I considered it,' Capt. Sutherland replied, 'and decided it would not be appropriate.'
<P>
After hearing that the marine department had a high turnover of management staff recently, the committee voted unanimously to approve the spending retrospectively, but instructed Capt. Sutherland to give the full council more details of the affair later this month.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

