<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Engineer makes new start in 'fragile' island

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Engineer makes new start in 'fragile' island
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


2nd October 1996
<P>
A skilled engineer made redundant at Britain's most northerly airport has lost no time in setting up his own business and winning a promising contract.
<P>
Jack Barclay, from Haroldswick, in the island of Unst (pop. 900), has invested 100,000 pounds in Unst Inshore Services, supported by Shetland Enterprise and Shetland Islands Council.
<P>
Mr Barclay offers an engineering and fabrication service and has won a contract from Globus - the local agents for salmon cage manufacturer Polar Circle - to service and repair all their cages in Shetland.
<P>
Mr Barclay also plans to produce agricultural and fish farming equipment, currently imported at high prices, as well as adapting equipment built by other companies to the specific needs of local businesses.
<P>
The development has secured a total of 50,000 pounds in backing from Shetland Enterprise and Shetland Islands Council.
<P>
Shetland Enterprise chief executive David Finch said: 'This is an important development which will not only benefit the fragile community of Unst but will help farmers and fish farmers source cheaper but equally high quality equipment, by reducing the need to import.'
<P>
Mr Barclay was born in Shetland. His parents were originally from Unst and moved to New Zealand when he was a child. He came 'home' on holiday over 20 years ago on holiday and decided to stay. He married in the island and worked as a lightkeeper before taking a job at the airport.
<P>
He said yesterday (TUES): 'Before the announcement of job losses at the airport, I was thinking about branching out on my own. My redundancy in March and the backing of Shetland Enterprise and Shetland Islands Council gave me the impetus to set up this new venture.
<P>
'I've already secured one major contract and have been doing work for fish farms all across Shetland. Initially the business will provide work for myself and a seasonal apprentice, but it is my hope that, as the fabrication work increases, there will be enough to take on a small number of staff,' he said.
<P>
A fast, aluminium-hulled motor launch Mr Barclay built recently in his spare time has been widely admired.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
