<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Penpals to meet in Canada after 55 years - thanks to 'The Shetland News'

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Penpals to meet in Canada after 55 years   </H1>
<H2>  - thanks to 'The Shetland News'
   </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



2nd October 1996
<P>
A 71-year-old widow from Shetland is setting off for the west coast of Canada today (WED) to meet a penpal she hasn't heard from for 55 years and has never met.
<P>
It's all thanks to 'The Shetland News', who put Jean and Steve in touch for the first time since before Pearl Harbor.
<P>
Jean Williamson, from North Lochside, Lerwick, is on the 10.30am non-stop flight from Glasgow to Vancouver, due to land at 12.45pm British Columbia time.
<P>
Waiting at the customs gate will be 73-year-old Steve Kirton, a retired builder originally from Australia, who says he stopped writing to the 16-year-old Jean in 1941 because he felt she was getting too serious: 'I chickened out. I was very young and very shy,' he said when the two got back in touch in June this year.
<P>
Steve joined the Australian Army after Pearl Harbour, was taken prisoner at the fall of Singapore, and spent three years in a Japanese prisoner-of-war camp. 
<P>
After the war he tried without success to contact the penpal he'd known as Georgina Irvine. But the schoolgirl from the village of Wester Skeld had grown up, married Willie Williamson, moved to the town of Lerwick and was now known by her middle name of Jean.
<P>
When Steve enrolled for a creative writing class in Burnaby, British Columbia, he quickly made friends with fellow mature student Jim Milina, who used a search engine to find Shetland and sent an e-mail to 'The Shetland News'.
<P>
Within 48 hours (after a false start with another Georgina Irvine, no relation!) we traced Jean, who still works in the family painting and decorating business founded by her late brother-in-law, Frank Williamson of Lerwick.
<P>
Jean said she had heard of the Internet but didn't know what it was: 'If it hadn't been for the Internet we'd never have got in touch again. I think it's great. He's a super guy to speak to on the phone. We're very jolly. He's called several times. He was so happy to speak to me for the first time.'
<P>
Neither penpal kept the letters so there will be a lot to catch up on when Jean lands in Canada with her son George as chaperone.
<P>
Jean, mother of six children and eight grandchildren, insists there is no romance in the air: 'As far as I'm concerned, it's just renewing an old friendship.' Taking a breather from the floor during an old time dance in a Shetland village hall at the weekend, she said: 'I'm really looking forward to it. It's such an adventure.'
<P>
Steve, now separated, also has six children - two of them living near him in British Columbia. Following a recent heart attack, he's not able to travel far and is delighted Jean can make the trip: 'After all these years, it's funny to think we've never actually met,' he said.
<P>
The only disappointment for Jean is that she'd planned to bake Steve a special cake and take it with her. But the Canadian Customs said fresh cakes were not allowed as cabin baggage, so now she plans to bake it in B.C. instead.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

