<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Svein Ove is rescued as North Sea wins stormy second round

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>  Svein Ove is rescued as North Sea wins stormy second round
  </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>
30th September 1996
<P>
 New technology let down Norway's prune-powered oarsman in his daring  bid to row alone across the North Sea, Norwegian Coastguards said  this afternoon (MON).
<P>
As a Sea King helicopter flew 32-year old adventurer Svein Ove Ask to  the fishing port of Aalesund, he told rescuers both his satellite  Global Positioning Systems (GPS) had failed two days ago, leaving him  with no clear idea where he was.
<P>
'He activated his emergency beacon at 10.30 BST and was picked up by  the helicopter at noon, about 100 nautical miles from Aalesund,' a  Coastguard spokesman in Bergen said. 'The weather was rough but he'd  been through much worse.'
<P>
Mr Ask, a journalist and father of two boys aged five and three, had  endured seven nights of continuous gales since leaving Lerwick on September 22.
<P>
He astonished critics during the past week with the extraordinary  seaworthiness of his partly-enclosed, 19-foot-long rowing boat, based  on a 1,000-year-old 'Nordfjording' skiff design. 
<P>
In Force Nine gales and 20 foot seas he put out a sea anchor, enjoyed  his favourite snack of dried prunes, and slept in his coffin-shaped  cabin, waiting for the wind to ease.
<P>
'He was in very good condition. He's rough and tough. We think it  should be a big enough achievement for him just to have survived it,'  the Coastguard spokesman said.
<P>
'We expected that something could happen because of the bad weather  we always have at this time of year. It was a very high calculated  risk. We don't like it,' he said.
<P>
In the first five days southerly gales blew Mr Ask over 100 miles  north of his intended course to Bergen, just 180 nautical miles east  of Lerwick. By the weekend he was 85 miles north-east of the Muckle  Flugga lighthouse - further from Bergen than when he started. 
<P>
During the last two days of the epic row the wind veered westerly and  he was making good progress towards Norway when his navigation  equipment failed. In such a small boat, pitching wildly in heavy seas  under overcast skies, it was impossible to obtain an accurate fix of  his position once his GPS equipment had failed.
<P>
This afternoon (MON) a Norwegian rescue service vessel was trying to  find and recover his boat, 'Ingolf Arnasson', named after the Viking  discoverer of Iceland. 
<P>
Norwegian Coastguards had warned Mr Ask not to try the 200-mile  crossing during the equinoctial gale season, but Shetland Coastguards  said he was as well prepared as possible and praised his safety  precautions, while admitting they wished he would leave the attempt  until next summer.
<P>
A senior Norwegian Coastguard said last week he feared expensive  resources could be tied up trying to rescue someone who had no good  reason to be out on the North Sea at this time of year. In the event,  Bergen Coastguards said today's (MON) search and rescue mission had  been 'very straightforward' and had not diverted them from other tasks.
<P>
In early July Mr Ask arrived in Lerwick after a 10-day row from  Maloy, the first man to accomplish the solo crossing for 27 years. He  admitted that his partner Anne Grethe Heen thought he was 'a little bit crazy'.
<P>
Two other Norwegians who left at the same time gave up and were last  month (AUG) rescued during a second attempt when their open boat was  swamped half-way to Shetland. They survived five days adrift in a  liferaft, staying alive by killing and eating a seagull.
<P>








<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

