<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Call for permanent Dounreay shutdown

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Call for permanent Dounreay shutdown
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


1st October 1996
<P>
The leader of Scotland's anti-nuclear councils last night (MON) demanded radioactive waste reprocessing at Dounreay be stopped for good and said statements by the plant managers were 'downright insulting to the public'.
<P>
Shetland councillor Bertie Black, convener of Nuclear Free Local Authorities Scotland (NFLAS), said after the Caithness plant shut down for repairs: 'After yet another radioactive leak into the sea, how dare the management of Dounreay claim that such leaks pose no threat to the public and expect us to believe it?
<P>
'The credibility of the Dounreay publicity machine is totally non-existent. I think we've got to the stage where, hopefully, the population of northern Scotland will demand that this reprocessing ceases entirely,' Mr Black said.
<P>
NFLAS represents 16 Scottish councils who recently complained about the alleged risks of flying spent nuclear fuel rods into Wick Airport on the way to Dounreay.
<P>
A spokesman for Dounreay said yesterday (MON) that the leak discovered in cooling water pipework on Saturday could take months to fix, but the radioactivity levels were a tiny fraction of natural background radiation. 






<P>
<BR clear=all>
