<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Isles welcome for big grant to university

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Isles welcome for big grant to university
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>

1st October 1996
<P>
The Millennium Commission's grant of 33.35 million pounds for the proposed University of the Highlands and Islands (UHI) will help to 'reverse the export of ability and opportunities' from the area, the principal of The Shetland College said yesterday (MON).
<P>
Gordon Dargie, who runs the most northerly college involved in the university project, said the grant was a challenge to the UHI partners - colleges, councils and local enterprise companies - to secure matching funds from other sources.
<P>
'Schools throughout the Highlands and Islands have traditionally achieved the highest standards but the area has traditionally lacked an infrastructure to support higher education,' Mr Dargie said. 'The area traditionally has exported well-qualified school pupils to higher education in the Central Belt and, in doing so, has exported many job opportunities.'
<P>
As a result, Scotland's remoter communities had 'largely had to do without the updated professional qualifications and skills' which were benefiting economic development elsewhere, he said.
<P>
Shetland Islands Council had been a founder member of UHI and the islands' two colleges each had 'something unique' to offer - marine science at the North Atlantic Fisheries College in Scalloway and textile design at the Shetland College of Further Education in Lerwick.
<P>
Mr Dargie said it was 'a great day' after months of preparation and hard work.
<P>
Northern Isles MP Jim Wallace said the Millennium Commission grant towards the 80 million pounds initial budget of the university was 'a huge boost'.
<P>
The multi-campus university, making full use of computer communications, would 'present the Highlands and Islands with new opportunities, not just for students but for local businesses and communities as well,' he said.
<P>
'It is particularly welcome news for those of us who have kept faith with the project and have consistently tried to promote it. It provides real encouragement to ensure that the remaining pieces are quickly put in place.'







<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
