<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - More unauthorised council spending revealed

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> More unauthorised council spending revealed
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


1st October 1996
<P>
A second Shetland council department has admitted spending public money without proper authority.
<P>
Marine director George Sutherland will ask councillors today (TUES) for retrospective permission to spend up to 90,000 pounds on a new ramp and other works for the ferry terminal at Symbister in the island of Whalsay.
<P>
In a paper for the Marine Operations Committee, Capt. Sutherland says a survey showed the work needed to be done as quickly as possible and his officials brought it forward, because some other projects had suffered unavoidable delays.
<P>
Although the total budget for repair and renewal of ferry terminals throughout the islands is unaffected, Capt. Sutherland says: 'It is clear that the proper approval and authorisation procedures were not followed.'
<P>
He explains there have been some staff changes recently but recognises he should 'arrange appropriate training, instruction and guidance' for his managers 'to ensure that the council procedures are rigorously followed in future'.
<P>
Earlier this year the council's former leisure and recreation director, John P. Nicolson, was disciplined by chief executive Malcolm Green after internal auditors reported that 134,000 pounds' worth of recreation grants had been paid without formal approval.
<P>
Mr Nicolson took early retirement in the summer and is still disputing the discipline decision.
<P>
Capt. Sutherland is Mr Green's deputy chief executive. The work at the Symbister ferry terminal is currently under way.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
