<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Banned from Bressay after 'menacing' call

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Banned from Bressay after 'menacing' call
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


1st October 1996
<P>
A Sheriff yesterday (MON) banned a man from visiting the Shetland island of Bressay, after hearing that he had made a 'menacing' phone call to his former partner living there.
<P>
Eric Ronald MacLaren (49), 49 Kalliness, Weisdale, Shetland, appeared from custody before Honorary Sheriff George Henderson in Lerwick Sheriff Court and admitted a breach of the peace outside the office of the Shetland Children's Panel in the town last Monday.
<P>
He also admitted a breach of the peace by phoning the woman and 'threatening to injure or kill himself'. The woman cannot be named, for legal reasons.
<P>
Solicitor Eric Peterson said MacLaren had been unhappy about the outcome of a Children's Panel hearing after his relationship with the woman had broken down. His client apologised for the trouble caused.
<P>
The court deferred sentence until October 24 for social inquiry and community service reports and granted bail, on condition that MacLaren did not contact the complainer again and did not set foot on the island.
<P>
Bressay (pop. 400) has no resident police officer and is served by an hourly ferry from Lerwick, half a mile across Bressay Sound. 






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

