<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Svein Ove is half way there

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Svein Ove is half way there
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


30th September 1996
<P>
Norway's intrepid solo oarsman is back in home waters but still has a hundred miles to go in his hair-raising attempt to become the first man to row from Norway to Shetland and back.
<P>
Svein Ove Ask (32) pulled across the UK/Norway median line near the Magnus oilfield at the weekend. Yesterday (SUN) he was steadily pulling east after surviving a week of continous gales between Shetland and Norway.
<P>
Coastguards said he was north of latitude 62 degrees and about half way across, although the southerly gales had blown him over 100 miles north of his intended track. Yesterday's south-westerly gale was helping him in the right direction, for the first time since he left Lerwick last Sunday.
<P>
A French trawler skipper who spotted Mr Ask's tiny boat on Saturday altered course to investigate, fearing the 19-foot 'Ingolf Arnasson' was a liferaft from a wrecked ship.
<P>
Mr Ask told the trawler by radio he was well and did not need any help.
<P>
It is thought he will try to head for Maloy, the fishing port he left in June on the first leg of his controversial expedition. 
<P>
Some Norwegian rescue service bosses consider him foolhardy but Mr Ask insists he has the right boat for the job and so far has confounded critics who advised him not to attempt the return crossing during the equinoctial gales.
<P>
<a href="/svein/svein.html">Follow Svein Ove Ask's progress</A> rowing to Norway, with the Shetland News.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

