<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Svein is further away than when he started

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Svein is further away than when he started
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



28th September 1996
<P>
The Norwegian trying to row from Shetland to Bergen in the middle of the autumn gales was last night (FRI) more than 30 miles further from his goal than when he set out from Lerwick five days ago.
<P>
Svein Ove Ask, a journalist and father of two from Nordfjordur, ignored a bad weather forecast and warnings from Norwegian Coastguards when he set off in a 19-foot-long wooden boat for the 208 mile trip.
<P>
Although he has now rowed half the distance from Lerwick to Bergen, persistent southerly gales have blown Mr Ask far off course.
<P>
The defiant oarsman, attempting a feat even the Vikings would have baulked at, says he has food for another 15 days and his partly-enclosed boat is designed to cope with violent North Sea gales.
<P>
There was no radio contact with Mr Ask yesterday (FRI) but a satellite logged him as he at last crossed the Greenwich meridian in latitude 61.6 degrees, 115 miles north of the southern tip of Greenland.
<P>
Senior Norwegian Coastguard officials have severely criticised Mr Ask's expedition but the veteran of five abortive attempts to row alone from Norway to Shetland points to his successful crossing from the fishing port of Maloy to Lerwick in June this year.
<P>
Two other Norwegian rowers who attempted the crossing in July survived by the skin of their teeth when they were rescued from a liferaft five days after their open boat capsized. They were forced to eat a raw seagull to survive.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

