<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Nicolson-Green feud rumbles on

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Nicolson-Green feud rumbles on
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



28th September 1996
<P>
The feud between retired Shetland council director John P. Nicolson and his former boss, chief executive Malcolm Green, reached new heights of bitterness yesterday (FRI).
<P>
Writing his first ever letter to 'The Shetland Times', the former leisure and recreation director accused the council chief of 'harshness and brutality' in his 'management style'.
<P>
Mr Nicolson said Mr Green did not reply to a request for a meeting to discuss the allegations earlier this year but had 'certainly told me very succinctly where to go' when he had complained on other occasions.
<P>
He had never been given details of the 'procedures' which Mr Green said existed for staff complaining of harassment.
<P>
Mr Nicolson, who was disciplined by Mr Green earlier this year after procedural confusion over 134,000 pounds of recreation grants, said he had suffered 'harassment and vindictiveness' in a 'bullying, over-bearing culture'.
<P>
His concern was for 'other council employees who ... might have less in the way of family and other support'.
<P>
He said so much power was now concentrated in the chief executive's office that Mr Green's position had become 'impregnable' and the position of other staff 'less secure'.
<P>
In a side-swipe at councillors who last week refused to overturn the disciplinary finding against him, Mr Nicolson said there was no 'political intervention at the appropriate level'.
<P>
'What we have now is the absence of very necessary checks and balances,' he said.
<P>
After criticism by five pro-Nicolson councillors during last week's secret council debate on the affair, Mr Green publicly denied the charge of vindictiveness. Yesterday his secretary said he was 'unavailable for comment' on the letter and referred calls to the elected council convener, Lewis Smith.
<P>
Mr Smith said he would consider whether to comment once he had studied the letter. 
<P>
Meanwhile Mr Nicolson has said he is willing to be a candidate at a Shetland Islands Council by-election in the island of Yell next month.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

