<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Sensational view of lunar eclipse

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Sensational view of lunar eclipse
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


27th September 1996
<P>
Those few Shetlanders who were awake at three am today (FRI) enjoyed a spectacular view of the total eclipse of the Moon.
<P>
After days of thick cloud, the sky over the islands suddenly cleared as the full moon rose on Thursday evening. By 3.20am BST the lunar eclipse was total, the first since April 1994.
<P>
Right on cue, a flock of migrating geese flew south over Bressay Sound, silhouetted against the pale orange moon.
<P>
Coastguards, police officers and port controllers at Lerwick and Sullom Voe were among the awed spectators.
<P>
At The Shetland News, grizzled old hack Jonathan Wills was so moved by the sight that he woke up his 10-year-old son Tom.
<P>
'I've finally found out how to wake that boy up,' he said. 'He was out of bed and at the window in seconds. If only we could have lunar eclipses in the mornings.'
<P>
And no-one got a picture. Or did they? If you did, please e-mail  <a href="mailto:editor@shetland-news.co.uk">editor@shetland-news.co.uk</a>  now!






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
