<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Svein-Ove answers critics of his expedition

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Svein-Ove answers critics of his expedition
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


27th September 1996
<P>
Svein-Ove Ask, who yesterday (THURS) spent a fourth day battling high winds and heavy seas north-east of Shetland, has hit back at critics of his attempt to row alone from Shetland to Norway during the equinoctial gales.
<P><A HREF="safety.jpg"><IMG SRC="safetys.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
In an open letter, written before he left Shetland on Sunday afternoon, and released in Norway yesterday (THURS) by his friend and spokesman Jonny Birkelund, Mr Ask (32) said the critics should back him or ban him:
<P>
'Never before have so many talked so much about which they know so little,' he said. 'Rescue Leader Sigurd Torp, at the Main Rescue Centre at Sola, Norway, commented to the newspaper ''Bergens Tidende'' in negative terms about my rowing expedition across the North Sea. 
<P>
'Totally without knowledge about my project, he says that crossing the North Sea is hazardous. As far as I know, a boat such as mine has never before been built in Norway. Torp and others who speak with expert knowledge cannot, based on experience, comment on the safety of a closed-compartment vessel like this. 
<P>
'I have learnt from previous errors and have found a solution which works very well safety-wise. This concept has been used in successful crossings of oceans far wider than the North Sea. A properly secure crossing of the North Sea is fully possible, even in bad weather. I maintain that the degree of difficulty is not very high, either,' he wrote.
<P>
Mr Ask said his safety equipment, including items compulsory on much larger vessels, could make the rescue service's work easier, and thus not 'tie up large resources', as Mr Torp had claimed.
<P>
Mr Torp and other critics should 'either accept that expeditions like this can still be allowed to take place' and help to make them absolutely safe, or 'work towards a total prohibition'.
<P><A HREF="safety2.jpg"><IMG SRC="safety2s.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Mr Ask, a journalist and boat repair expert, is attempting to become the first man to row from Norway to Shetland and back. His 19-foot 'Nordfjording' boat is custom-made, combining thousand-year-old wooden boat building traditions with modern materials such as divinycell and epoxy.
<P>
In contrast to their Norwegian counterparts, Shetland Coastguards have praised his safety precautions, while saying they wished they could have dissuaded him from putting to sea.
<P>
Mr Ask estimated the 200 mile crossing would take 15 days at most but on Day Five yesterday (THURS) continuing southerly gales were still driving him north rather than east.
<P>
As he crossed the Greenwich meridian at 61 degrees north yesterday (THURS), winds were forecast to ease to near-gale force seven and veer south-westerly, allowing him to start clawing east towards the oilfields midway between Shetland and Norway.
<P>
 
 <BR>
<a href="/svein/svein.html">Follow Svein's route during his voyage</A>, with daily updates on his position, taken from his 'Argos' satellite transponder system.




<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

