<DOCNO>WT12-B39-163</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA092-000992-B001-112</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.shetland-news.co.uk:80/headline/tankers/tankers.html 194.72.245.173 19970110123953 text/html 4168
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 12:39:56 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 3997
Last-modified: Thu, 26 Sep 1996 18:00:45 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - New call for a winter tug

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> New call for a winter tug
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


27th September 1996
<P>
Shetland's council leader has renewed demands for a salvage tug to be stationed in the islands during the winter months, after discovering that a Government report favours the idea.
<P>
As the first of the winter gales swept over Shetland yesterday (WED) Convener Lewis Smith published his letter to Viscount Goschen, the shipping minister, complaining that the Department of Transport had 'taken no action' on the findings of Captain Chris Belton RN.
<P>
Capt. Belton carried out a review of salvage tugs around the British coast after the tanker 'Braer' broke down and went aground on the southern tip of Shetland in January 1993, spilling 85,000 tonnes of oil.
<P>
Mr Smith said councillors were 'gravely concerned' at the lack of progress in the past three years, in view of Capt. Belton's recommendation for an emergency towing vessel to help disabled tankers in and around the Fair Isle Channel.
<P>
'There is essentially no difference between the towage and salvage provision in this area before and after the Braer,' Mr Smith wrote.
<P>
He noted that a similar recommendation for a tug in the Western Approaches was 'apparently similarly ignored until the 'Sea Empress' incident brought that omission to prominence'.
<P>
He said the 'Sea Empress' had 'again drawn attention to the futility of depending on harbour tugs for salvage'.
<P>
<h4><b>Port boss criticises tanker tracking scheme</b></h4>
<P>
Meanwhile Captain George Sutherland, marine director for the Shetland council, has criticised a new Department of Transport scheme for electronic tagging of tankers.
<P>
In a report published yesterday (THURS) for next week's meeting of the council's marine operations committee, Capt. Sutherland says the new Automatic Ship Identification and Reporting System (AIRS) is 'embryonic' and 'parochial', being limited to the range of coastal VHF radio - 40-miles or so.
<P>
He wants AIRS tried out on Sullom Voe oil terminal tankers but says it may not be compatible with ship-tracking technology in Norway and other countries.
<P>
He believes it will be 'well into the next century' before there is a universal, internationally agreed radar surveillance system to tell shore authorities where individual tankers are at any one time.
<P>
Capt. Sutherland also calls again for changes to the wording on nautical charts showing the 'Areas To Be Avoided' (ATBAs) by large vessels around the Shetland coast. He thinks tankers not carrying oil should be subject to the same rules as laden ships, because they commonly carry thousands of tonnes of contaminated ballast water and fuel oil.
<P>
He complains that passing ships do not have to observe the same safety routeing procedures as Sullom Voe tankers and warns of the 'continuing potential' for head-on collisions on the edge of the ATBAs.
<P>
Councillors are asked to re-affirm their marine safety policies and to continue lobbying efforts nationally and internationally.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

