<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - New monopoly in the air

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> New monopoly in the air
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



26th September 1996
<P>
The Aberdeen-based airline Business Air are pulling out of Shetland, leaving Loganair's franchised British Airways Express operation with a monopoly on air routes to the isles.
<P>
The decision means fewer daily flights and poorer connections for travellers and comes on top of British Airways' recent announcement that they are quitting the far north after half a century.
<P>
The news of the third shake-up in island air services in five months was broken to councillors and other members of Shetland's tourism advisory panel by Loganair managing director Scott Grier in Lerwick yesterday (WED) afternoon.
<P>
Tourism director Maurice Mullay said: 'I'm very disappointed although it's not entirely unexpected ... It means a cut from seven to five return flights a day but we hope the lower cost operation may eventually mean lower fares. We're going to miss Business Air as they've been first-class partners in promoting Shetland tourism.'
<P>
Councillor Tavish Scott said Business Air's decision created a monopoly and gave a poorer service which was not in the best interests of Shetland: 'It can't be good news,' he said. 'Business Air forced some price competition on the route.' He said councillors would be keeping a sharp eye on Loganair/BA Express fares.
<P>
Business Air founder and managing director Ian Woodley confirmed last night (WED) they would cease operations to Sumburgh Airport from October 26, after three years of flying to the islands.
<P>
Mr Woodley expressed 'regret' at the decision: 'We gave British Airways a run for their money but neither BA nor Business Air was making a profit,' he said. 
<P>
'This may well be the opportunity for the services to the islands to begin to run on a viable basis.'
<P>
'I don't think there will necessarily be a diminution of service,' he said, although he admitted connections with ongoing flights would 'not be 100 per cent'. Passengers' bookings and fares would be honoured when they were transferred to British Airways Express.
<P>
Mr Grier, who has 20 years' experience of the Loganair operation in the Northern and Western Isles, said British Airways Express would adopt the British Airways' fare structure, including discount and promotional fares.
<P>
Referring to recent criticism by Scots Industry Minister George Kynoch, Mr Grier said: 'The perception of air fares is that they're very high. In fact a very high proportion of passengers are on discounted or promotional fares. We'll be looking for ways to offer lower fares and we'll give passengers a fair deal. But it's more important now to get the operation up and running smoothly.'
<P>
He agreed with Mr Woodley there was 'over-capacity' on the route. He promised inter-island flights operated by Loganair for BA Express would continue as normal.
<P>
British Airways Express would operate a winter timetable of five return flights a day between  Aberdeen and Sumburgh, Mr Grier said. Three would use 64-seat ATP aircraft, one flight a 34-seater Saab 340 and the fifth a Short 360.
<P>
'We feel we've got quite a strong product. We hope to make as many onward connections as possible and we recognise the importance of the air services for tourism,' said Mr Grier, a member of the Scottish Tourist Board.
<P>
Tourism director Mullay said Mr Grier knew the islands well and had said he was willing to listen: 'We've always had a good relationship with him,' he said.
<P>
Yesterday's (WED) news contradicted Business Air's promises when they were taken over by Airlines of Britain in April this year. A Business Air spokeswoman said then: 'It's Business Air as usual. Competition on the routes to the islands will continue.'
<P>
Last month British Airways decided to pull out of six loss-making routes to the Scottish islands, handing over to the BA Express franchise operation run by the Airlines of Britain Group, which  includes Loganair and Business Air.
<P>
BA's chief executive, Bob Ayling, said at the time that the national airline had experienced 'almost 50 unprofitable' years' in the Northern and Western Isles.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

