<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Scallop dredgers' unwelcome catch

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Scallop dredgers' unwelcome catch
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


26th September 1996
<P>
Two Shetland fishermen are furious about a killer net which fouled their gear east of Shetland earlier this week.
<P><A HREF="mononet.jpg"><IMG SRC="mononets.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Brothers Stanley and Steven Gray were dredging for scallops east of the island of Bressay with their boats 'Sola Gratia' and 'Elly Gerda' when Steven's gear caught on the tangled lump of nylon monofilament drift net.
<P>
'It destroyed a day's fishing,' Stanley said yesterday (WED). 'It took eight hours to clear it. We suspect it was lost by a big foreign boat. This stuff is incredibly destructive and ought to be banned.'
<P>
The net was landed at Morrison Dock in Lerwick. Entangled in the pile of mesh, six feet across and three feet high, were dozens of prawns, fish and big crabs.
<P>
A spokesman for the Scottish Fisheries Department said it was legal for British boats to carry monofilament nets outside the six-mile limit, and foreign vessels outside 12 miles.
<P>
John Uttley of Scottish Natural Heritage said they had previously expressed concern about the use of monofilament nets because of the damage to seals, porpoises and dolphins which cannot see the fine nylon mesh in time to avoid becoming trapped in it.
<P>
'These nets, when fishing or when lost, have the potential to entangle all sorts of wildlife, including cetaceans, seals and seabirds,' he said. Monofilament nets had been blamed for the deaths of dolphins off the Irish coast.
<P>
'They're selective at fishing, in that they only catch larger fish, but they're very non-selective on big sea mammals and seabirds,' Mr Uttley said.
<P>
The Gray brothers said the incident was the final straw for them after they suffered severe losses because of the 'Braer' tanker pollution three years ago.
<P>
'There are no scallops left in the south of Shetland because of pollution and only small shells in the north because it was overfished when boats had to move north after the Braer,' Stanley Gray said. They had not received full compensation and planned to sell up and switch to cockle dredging with a smaller boat.
<P>
'You can't make a living any more at the scallops, even without discarded monofilament nets fouling your gear,' he said.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

