<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Government moves on ship transponders - but tanker owners slow to volunteer

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Government moves on ship transponders   </H1>
<H2>  - but tanker owners slow to volunteer
   </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


25th September 1996
<P>
The Government has installed equipment to identify and track oil tankers around Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles - but not enough ships are volunteering for electronic tagging, according to the civil servant in charge of the scheme.
<P>
Steve Harding, project officer at the Marine Safety Agency (MSA), said yesterday (TUES) that a major foreign tanker owner, trading to the Shetland oil port of Sullom Voe, had converted its fleet but many others had not.
<P>
'The coastal stations are set up. It's all effective and working and we're just waiting for people to come and join us,' he said. The UK Government hoped all tankers and other vessels carrying hazardous cargoes would meet the target date of 1999, proposed by Britain at the International Maritime Organisation (IMO).
<P>
It is understood that it cost less than 80,000 pounds to set up the three receiving stations - a small fraction of the price tag on a coastal radar system. 
<P>
The MSA project uses the same principle as the radio transponders fitted to civil airliners for decades past. In the USA, similar technology tracks hire cars and railway containers, as well as tagging criminals on parole.
<P>
Mr Harding said the beauty of the MSA's automatic ship identification and reporting system (AIRS) was that it linked VHF radio and satellite navigation equipment already installed on most tankers. 
<P>
All shipowners had to do was convert their onboard computers. Coastguard stations could then pinpoint the ship's position, identify the vessel and hopefully avoid unpleasant surprises like the 'Braer' tanker wreck.
<P>
Lord Donaldson's inquiry into ship safety recommended such a system in 1994, a year after the 'Braer' broke down unseen on a dark January morning and later drifted ashore on Shetland, causing extensive pollution.
<P>
Northern Isles MP Jim Wallace last night congratulated the Marine Safety Agency on its achievement: 'I'm always prepared to give credit where credit's due,' he said. 'In Shetland we've been calling for a transponder system since before the Braer went aground.' 
<P>
Mr Wallace said the Government should now put the pressure on the IMO and, failing agreement there, the European Union could require all large ships to convert to the system.
<P>
Mr Harding said the AIRS equipment had been installed since March to cover the Fair Isle Channel, the Pentland Firth and the North Minch, using stations at Compass Head (Shetland), Dunnett Head (Caithness) and Melvaig.
<P>
'It only costs around 500 pounds to convert a ship's computer,' he said. 'The clever bit is that the equipment only responds automatically if the ship is in the area you want to cover, so you can avoid clogging up your receiver with too many signals.'
<P>
Yesterday (TUES) at least one mariner was using a similar system off the Shetland coast to send his position to Norwegian Coastguards. Solo rower Svein Ove Ask was pulling in the general direction of Bergen, as a satellite logged his position from signals sent by a tiny transponder on board his 19 foot boat. (See separate story)






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

