<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Nicolson may stand for Yell South

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Nicolson may stand for Yell South
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



25th September 1996
<P>
A former Shetland council director who took early retirement after a row with the council's chief executive last night (TUES) declared himself ready to stand at next month's by-election in the island of Yell.
<P>
John P. Nicolson said he was willing to be nominated for the poll on November 14 to replace Councillor Peter Guy as member for Yell South. 
<P>
As director of leisure and recreation, Mr Nicolson formerly reported to Mr Guy, who has chaired the leisure and recreation committee for the past two years. 
<P>
'I'm very interested in standing if I get enough electors to nominate me,' Mr Nicolson said. 'I know something about the workings of the council, I think I could do a reasonable job for South Yell and I have an awful lot of friends among the Yell folk.'
<P>
Mr Nicolson said if elected he would 'set aside' any hard feelings or 'sour grapes' about the circumstances of his departure from the department he ran for 21 years. He was recently disciplined by chief executive Malcolm Green after an investigation into procedural confusion about 134,000 pounds' worth of grants to recreation projects. Councillors rejected his appeal.
<P>
'Vindictiveness gets you nowhere,' he said last night, 'but there are things that need to be done for the good of the community as a whole.'
<P>
Mr Nicolson would not be the first Shetland council director to stand for election. His former colleague Peter Malcolmson won a Lerwick seat for the Liberal Democrats in 1994 after an acrimonious dispute which led to him leaving his post as social work director.
<P>
As officials made arrangements for the Yell South poll, council leader Lewis Smith yesterday paid tribute to Mr Guy, who is leaving the islands after his recent bereavement and intends to start a new life in North Yorkshire.
<P>
'Peter has been an enthusiastic and hard-working councillor,' Convener Smith said. 'He has served his constituents well and played a full part in the life of the council.'
<P>
As chairman of the Leisure and Recreation Committee and of the licensing board, Mr Guy had shown 'considerable ability and a flair for conceiving new and imaginative initiatives', Mr Smith said.
<P>
'The council joins the community in thanking Peter Guy for his commitment to Shetland and we wish him well in the future.'
<P>
Maurice Mullay, chief executive of Shetland Islands Tourism, also expressed regret at Mr Guy's departure. As an enthusiastic chairman of the new tourist authority he had been a great asset to the islands.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
