<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Svein battles against the weather

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Svein battles against the weather
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


25th September 1996
<P>
Solo rower Svein Ove Ask was blown off course yesterday (TUES) as his bid to row back to Norway from Shetland ran into heavy weather.
<P>
The 32-year-old Norwegian journalist hauled on his oars all day, against heavy seas and southerly winds gusting to gale force eight, but only succeeded in slowing his northerly drift. 
<P>
As night fell, Mr Ask and his tiny boat 'Ingolf Arnasson' were still just 15 miles off Unst, the most northerly Shetland island. Once past Unst, he has no chance of returning to Shetland unless there is a dramatic improvement in the weather.
<P>
Last night the weather was deteriorating, with waves of up to 40 feet and gales reaching Force 10 forecast tomorrow in sea area Viking, between Shetland and Norway.
<P>
The oarsman carries food and water for 20 days. He said before he left Lerwick on Sunday that he was hoping the wind would veer south-westerly, allowing him to make headway to the east. 
<P>
Mr Ask's average course during the first 48 hours of the planned 10-day, 200-mile crossing is taking him towards Lofoten, 600 miles north-east of Shetland and far to the north of his intended landfall at the fishing port of Maloy.
<P>
In June he rowed alone from Maloy to Lerwick, the first man to achieve the feat since 1969.
<P>
<a href="/svein/svein.html">Follow Svein Ove Ask rowing to Norway with the Shetland News</A>





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

