<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Setback for Bulgarians as Howard appeals

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>    </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


25th September 1996
<P>
Two Bulgarian refugees in Shetland heard yesterday (TUES) that the Home Office still wants to deport them, despite a recent grant of political asylum.
<P>
A spokeswoman in London confirmed that Home Secretary Michael Howard was asking the Immigration Appeals Tribunal to reverse a decision by an adjudicator in favour of Georgi Spasov and Dmitar Dmitrov earlier this month.
<P>
The two men led a strike on board a fish factory ship in Lerwick last year and say they fear persecution and imprisonment by former Communists, if returned to Bulgaria. 
<P>
They have the support of island church groups, trade unionists, councillors and Orkney and Shetland MP Jim Wallace, but Mr Howard's officials decided to deport them in June. Mr Spasov and Mr Dmitrov successfully appealed to an immigration hearing in Glasgow.
<P>
Yesterday Mr Dmitrov was working on a Shetland building site. He took the news calmly but did not want to say anything that might antagonise the immigration authorities.
<P>
Both men are working for Lerwick building contractor WAG Construction (Shetland) Ltd, where director Mrs Mary Leask said the firm did not wish to comment, 'for fear of jeopardising their case'.
<P>
Lerwick interpreter Derek Herning, who has worked unpaid on the case for over a year, said: 'It's a disappointment but it was half expected. I didn't think the Home Office would let us get away with this.'
<P>
Canon Lewis Smith, convener of Shetland Islands Council, said he was 'disappointed but not surprised' by Mr Howard's move.
<P>
'Georgi and Dmitar are members of our community now and Shetland wants them to stay,' said the canon who, as rector of St Magnus Episcopal Church in Lerwick, acted as pastor to the 'Rotalia' crew during their exile in Shetland.
<P>
'They've already presented their case successfully and I trust they'll be able to achieve the same outcome when the appeal is heard,' he said.
<P>
The two men were represented at the hearing last month by solicitor Paul Seils of the Scottish Refugee Council. Their victory was seen as a major diplomatic blow for the Sofia government, dominated by ex-Communists, and for British Home Secretary Michael Howard. 
<P>
Bulgaria is on the 'white list' of countries which, in Mr Howard's opinion, do not threaten the civil rights of their citizens.
<P>
When they were granted political asylum on September 12, Mr Seils said the decision vindicated the two Bulgarians' 'realistic' fears of persecution. 
<P>
'The Home Secretary has been naive in his assessment of the way ... the Bulgarian government operates,' Mr Seils said. It was 'patent nonsense' that no-one had a justified fear of persecution in a 'white list' country such as Bulgaria.
<P>
Mr Seils was not at his office to comment yesterday (TUES) but it is understood that the appeal may be heard in about 10 days' time. 
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<h2>Background to the Bulgarian saga:</h2>
<P>
Mr Spasov and Mr Dmitrov were on the four-man strike committee which led protests at living conditions aboard the Bulgarian fish processing ship, or klondyker, 'Rotalia', stranded without fuel or supplies at Lerwick during the winter of 1994/95. 
<P>
The crew were backed by the Bulgarian Seafarers' Union, the International Transport Workers' Federation and Euro-MPs including Winnie Ewing and European Union president Klaus Hensch.
<P>
After a three-month strike for arrears of wages, dating back three years, most of the crew accepted repatriation in April last year. But the privatised state shipping company Okeanskiy Ribolov then reneged on a deal brokered by Jim Wallace MP, and did not pay the men all they were owed.
<P>
Mr Herning has been in regular touch with Bulgaria and says many of the repatriated crew are still unemployed. Strike leader Jordan Jordanov, who returned to the port of Burgas to pursue claims against the company, has been bankrupted, his marriage has ended and he has lost his home. 
<P>
Mr Jordanov has now been forced by lack of funds to close an office he had opened and it is increasingly difficult to get in touch with him, Mr Herning says.
<P>
Home Secretary Michael Howard is himself the son of two pre-war refugees from oppression in Romania. There has been speculation that his parents would not have been permitted to remain in the UK under Mr Howard's strict new immigration rules.
<P>
Scots Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace MP last night called on Mr Howard to relent.
<P>
'The Home Secretary should have the good grace to accept the decision (to grant political asylum),' Mr Wallace said. 'The Government already puts plenty of hurdles in the way of genuine asylum seekers like Georgi and Dmitar, when they have already satisfied the adjudication officer.
<P>
'They should just be allowed to stay,' he said.
<P>
Shetland Trades Council chairman Coin Mackay said: 'When Bulgaria's ambassador to the United Nations accuses his own government of being behind attempts to kill him, it wakes you wonder what Mr Howard is talking about.'






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

