<TITLE>Shetland News - Gannets drop chopper in the guano

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Gannets drop chopper in the guano
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



24th September 1996
<P>
An optical illusion sent a search and rescue team on a wild Solan Goose chase yesterday (MON).
<P>
The crew of the Shetland Coastguard helicopter 'Lima Charlie' were on a training exercise near the bird reserve island of Noss when they saw what appeared to be orange smoke from a marine distress flare.
<P>
For over half an hour they searched the rocks below the 600-foot cliffs, looking for shipwrecked mariners, but found nothing except thousands of Gannets, also known as Solan Geese.
<P>
Returning to the spot where they had originally seen the 'flare', the truth dawned: the illusion had been created by a patch of sunlight on the birds' droppings which encrust the cliffs, making a streak of white guano look orange.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

