<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Airborne cuppa for lone rower

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Airborne cuppa for lone rower
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


24th September 1996
<P><A HREF="coffee1.jpg"><IMG SRC="coffee1s.jpg" ALIGN=left WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=216 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Lone Norwegian rower Svein Ove Ask last night (MON) enjoyed a flask of hot coffee, some chocolate bars and a daily paper - delivered by Coastguard helicopter.
<P>
The crew of the Sumburgh-based search and rescue helicopter were on exercise east of Shetland when they rendezvoused with the intrepid oarsman's 19 foot boat.
<P>
Mr Ask was well and cheerful, 24 hours into his 200-mile row home to Norway. Despite rowing 35 miles since he left Lerwick on Friday afternoon, adverse winds had driven him north along the Shetland coast and he was still only six miles out to sea.
<P><A HREF="coffee2.jpg"><IMG SRC="coffee2s.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=252 HEIGHT=153 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Shetland News photographer Graeme Storey, who was on the helicopter Lima Charlie, said Mr Ask told them by radio he was 'doing fine, with no problems and quite happy'. He 'looked in the pink' and was astonished and delighted when the helicopter appeared overhead and lowered a bag with supplies.
<P>
Last night Mr Ask was making some headway in choppy waves and a Force 6 southerly wind, east of the offlying islands of Out Skerries.
<P>
Mr Ask is attempting to become the first man to row from Norway to Shetland and back. He made the westbound crossing in 10 days at the end of June. Norwegian Coastguards are tracking his progress by satellite.

<P>
<a href="/svein/svein.html">Follow Svein Ove Ask rowing to Norway with the Shetland News</A>



<P>
