<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Iron Age farm discovered in Yell

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Iron Age farm discovered in Yell
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


24th September 1996
<P>
Archaeologists have uncovered a 2,000 year old Iron Age farm in the Shetland island of Yell.
<P>
At the end of a four week excavation for Historic Scotland, at Bayanne House, Sellafirth, Shetland Amenity Trust archaeologist Val Turner said yesterday (MON) they had found an Iron Age house which appeared to be the same age as the Shetland brochs - round tower forts from around the time of Christ.
<P>
'It's come as something of a surprise to both the archaeological team and Sellafirth residents alike, as the field which covered it was completely flat, with no stone visible,' she said.
<P>
The coastal site is being eroded by the sea and has been known about since the 1880s, when it was dug into and tools were found.
<P>
This summer's dig by freelance archaeologists Hazel Moore and Graeme Wilson has revealed several floor levels of a house which had been repeatedly rebuilt.
<P>
Ms Moore said they uncovered a complex of walls and middens, and a small, flimsy structure on top, with a stone tank and a hearth inside: 'This seems to have been a shelter, possibly for Iron Age fishermen preparing shellfish for bait.'
<P>
Geophysical survey by experts Alan Stapf and Michele Graham suggests there are far more substantial remains that at first thought, Ms Turner said.
<P>
The finds include burnished pottery. Ms Turner said: 'I've never seen anything quite as fine as this before. It may even have been imported.'
<P>
Site owners Tony and Liz Gott are said to be delighted with the discovery and hope it will eventually become a visitor attraction.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

