<DOCHDR>
http://www.shetland-news.co.uk:80/headline/osprey/osprey.html 194.72.245.173 19970110124356 text/html 4195
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 12:43:59 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4024
Last-modified: Mon, 23 Sep 1996 20:41:12 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Salvaged Dounreay wave machine is radio-active

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Salvaged Dounreay wave machine is radio-active
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



24th September 1996
<P>
by Rob Edwards
<P>
(a version of this report also appeared in 'Scotland on Sunday')
<P>
After the Osprey wave power machine was wrecked by the power of the waves, a few days after being installed off Dounreay last summer, it was hard to imagine that anything else could go wrong. But, in line with Murphy's ineluctable Law, it has.
<P>
Wreckage salvaged from the seabed over the last four months has repeatedly turned out to be contaminated with radioactivity from the Dounreay nuclear plant. On four occasions since May, monitoring by Dounreay scientists has discovered contamination by caesium 137 on sections of the crumpled 800 tonne device.
<P>
'This is another damning example of the environmental damage being caused by Dounreay,' said Graham Stein from Friends of the Earth Scotland.  'The nuclear industry has blocked the development of wave power in the past. That it should now pollute it as well is like rubbing salt into the wound.'
<P>
Dounreay's spokesman, Morris Grant, said that the contamination originated from 'historical discharges' from the plant's outfall pipe. What he described as 'small spots' of caesium 137 were found on material salvaged from Osprey on 29May, 10 June, 11 June and 2 July.
<P>
Grant said that the highest level of radioactivity measured was 'less than 500becquerels'. Particles containing over a million becquerels of radio activity found on the Dounreay foreshore in the past were regarded by heath experts as potentially lethal.
<P>
Osprey was developed by an Inverness company, Applied Research and Technology(ART), at a cost of 4 million pounds with the aim of generating 3.5 megawatts of electricity. Its massive steel structure collapsed onto the seabed 300 metres offshore in the Pentland Firth in August last year, after unfilled ballast tanks were 'crushed like empty coke cans' by unexpectedly powerful waves.
<P>
Osprey, which stands for Ocean Swell Powered Renewable Energy, was deliberately sited near Dounreay so that it could make use of the nuclear plant's power lines for connection to the electricity grid. The sea there was also thought to have a 'suitable wave power regime' for the generation of power.
<P>
ART brushes aside any suggestion that the Osprey project is ill-fated, and plans to install a revamped 'Osprey 2' in the same place next summer. 'The company is more than happy with the site and will demonstrate its confidence by going back there with Osprey 2,' said a spokesperson for ART. 'The site is excellent for the company's purposes.' 
<P>
Before the first Osprey was installed, the Scottish Office's Industrial Pollution Inspectorate warned that laying its power cable across the beach at Dounreay risked radioactive contamination. There were delays in towing the device up from where it was made on the Clyde because of a tug failure. And during Osprey's launching ceremony, a bottle of 12-year old malt whisky only broke at the second attempt.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Rob Edwards, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

