<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Lone rower leaves for home

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Lone rower leaves for home
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


23rd September 1996
<P><A HREF="svein3.jpg"><IMG SRC="svein3s.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
A 32-year-old Norwegian oarsman was alone with a bag of prunes on the North Sea last night (SUN).
<P>
Svein Ove Ask, a journalist from Nordfjordur, is bidding to become the first man to row solo from Norway to Shetland and back.
<P><A HREF="svein2.jpg"><IMG SRC="svein2s.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
He made the 10-day westbound crossing in June at his sixth attempt, on a diet of prunes, cereals and liver pate.
<P>
Yesterday, after his last hot meal for 10 days - a Sunday roast at a friend's house in Lerwick - he climbed into his tiny boat and pulled east into a head wind, with a bag of prunes in his locker and a pat on the back from Shetland Coastguards.
<P><A HREF="svein7.jpg"><IMG SRC="svein7s.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
District Officer Les Snaith said Mr Ask had taken as many safety precautions as he could. 
<P>
'We're better able now to offer advice to others because we've learnt so much from the way Svein has prepared his boat,' Mr Snaith said.
<P><A HREF="svein6.jpg"><IMG SRC="svein6s.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Mr Ask, father of two small boys, said it might seem dangerous but he was very safety-conscious: 'Safety is everything, and I have two Global Positioning Systems, two emergency beacons, an emergency radar transponder, and I'm using an 'Argos' satellite positioning beacon all the time on my way over.
<P>
'My boat is also my lifeboat, and it has a lot of buoyancy in it. Over 500 kgs of buoyancy, so it will float even if it capsizes.
<P><A HREF="svein9.jpg"><IMG SRC="svein9s.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
'It will take me maybe 8 to 10 days, but this depends on the weather. I have enough food for 20 days, and water too. I don't count how many miles I have done, I count how few I have left to do. Every ten miles I think that is now only 170, or 160 miles to go. It is better to count down this way,' Mr Ask said.
<P>
Last night the weather forecast was for strong, contrary winds and choppy seas on the lone rower's intended route. 
<P>

 <BR>
<a href="/svein/svein.html">Follow Svein's route during his voyage</A>, with daily updates on his position, taken from his 'Argos' satellite transponder system.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

