<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - No quorum for crucial trust meeting

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> No quorum for crucial trust meeting
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


21st September 1996
<P>
The future of a Church of Scotland old folks' home in Shetland is still in doubt, after councillors failed to turn up at a meeting of their charitable trust yesterday (FRI).
<P>
The trust was due to discuss the Kirk's 882,000 pounds grant application for the Walter & Joan Gray Eventide Home in Scalloway, but 15 of the 26 councillor trustees were absent on other business.
<P>
Chairman Bill Manson, the trust chairman, said they were one short of a quorum and the meeting would have to be postponed. He would consider using his delegated powers as chairman, if necessary to avoid delay to the Kirk's plan to rebuild the home.
<P>
Shetland Islands Council has already approved the 50 per cent grant for the home and yesterday's abortive meeting had been seen as a foregone conclusion.
<P>
Councillor Florence Grains said the absence of so many councillors from the trust meeting was 'totally disgraceful'.
<P>
'When you stand for the council you give a commitment and you should honour that commitment,' she said.
<P>
Councillor Magnus Flaws said many members were away on council business. All but four of the absentees had sent apologies.
<P>
Mr Manson said it was the first time in his experience that the trust had been inquorate.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

