<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Shetland research may ease power cuts

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Shetland research may ease power cuts
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


21st September 1996
<P>
Thirty electrical engineers from all over Europe have been on an expedition to a windswept Shetland hill, to see experiments on new power line designs which could make Christmas power cuts just a bad memory - and also save the lives of hundreds of swans. 
<P>
E.A.Technology Ltd, the research arm of the electricity generating companies, is testing hydro poles made from composite materials which won't rot or snap like wooden poles in winter storms.
<P>
Dr Brian Wareing and his colleagues are also experimenting with new transmission lines, conductors and insulators which can survive repeated assaults by Shetland's wet snow, salt spray and hurricane-force winds.
<P>
Susetter Hill, near the village of Voe, has some of the worst weather in Europe, according to Dr Wareing, a world expert on ice and snow on power lines. It rivals the wicked climate at other EA Technology research stations on Rannoch Moors and in the Dumfriesshire hills.
<P>
'We're testing gear from various manufacturers, including British firms, and we think we could have some world-beaters here,' Dr Wareing said. 'A side benefit is that geese and swans seem to be able to see the insulated transmission cables we're using and are less likely to kill themselves, and cause power outages, by flying into the wires.'
<P>
Video cameras and sensors on the equipment record what happens to the poles in sleet storms and sudden, violent changes of wind speed and direction. A computer in a portacabin squirts the information down a phone line to a laboratory in Chester, where the scientists work out which equipment has the best chance of survival.
<P>
Frank Otto, from the Dresden Electricity in eastern Germany, was impressed with what he saw: 'We have a lot of old concrete poles in rural areas and we're very interested in replacements that will last longer.'
<P>
Norweb engineer Graham Whitfield flew north from Manchester to see the test site. 'We have some pretty extreme weather in east Lancashire but I reckon if something can stand the winters here in Shetland it's good enough for Norweb,' he said.
<P>
The tests have shown that insulated cables cut down corrosion caused by salt spray on coastal power lines. Another promising device uses strimmer wire to reduce wind vibration on insulators, a major cause of failure.
<P>
Dr Wareing and his colleague Dr Steve Stocks are trying out tapered, hollow fibreglass poles which flex up two feet in high winds. The walls of the tubes thicken as the diameter narrows: 'It's like an aircraft's wing: if it bends it won't snap,' Dr Stocks explained.
<P>
These man-made materials might seem environmentally unfriendly but they should last 50 years, will save on forests and can be re-cycled, he said: 'We have to import all our wooden poles from Scandinavia because we can't grow them in Britain. And you shouldn't burn the old ones in your Rayburn anyway, because they're impregnated with arsenic.'
<P>
The scientists' only regret was that the weather failed to perform on cue for the visitors to the company's biggest UK test site: 'It was a lovely sunny day with light winds,' Dr Wareing said. 'But I'm sure it'll get worse as soon as our guests have departed.'
<P>
Sure enough, as the visiting engineers left for the airport a stiff easterly wind sprang up and Susetter Hill was once more shrouded in low cloud.
<P>
Last Christmas much of Shetland was without power for up to five days when blizzards felled dozens of wooden hydro poles. Scottish Hydro Electric admitted they did not reacted to the emergency as fast as they should have, and promised an improved service.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

