<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Bidding for the next Westside oilfield

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Bidding for the next Westside oilfield
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



20th September 1996
<P>
Councillors will meet in private at noon today (FRI) to hear a progress report from SIC chief executive Malcolm Green on Sullom Voe's bid to handle oil shipments from the Schiehallion field - the second of the new Atlantic oilfields.
<P>
Schiehallion is due to go on stream in 1998 and BP's Sullom Voe oil terminal is pushing hard for the contract to receive oil via shuttle tankers which will load in the open ocean.
<P>
Sullom Voe failed to win the shipments from the nearby Foinaven field, 100 miles west of Scalloway. BP awarded the contract to Elf Aquitaine's Flotta terminal in Orkney. But Foinaven has been delayed 12 months by technical problems - and the growing realisation in the industry that the weather west of Shetland is more severe than in the northern North Sea.
<P>
The council's recent deal with the oil companies, to ensure the future of Sullom Voe's East Shetland Basin trade, means councillors are now committed to working in partnership with BP to promote the Shetland terminal.
<P>
The agenda for the meeting give no details of what is to be discussed.
<P>
Meanwhile, there are reports that BP have had a very successful test on their Clair field, lying north of Schiehallion and in shallower water, closer to shore. Industry speculation suggests Clair may start pumping oil through a floating production and storage vessel before the year 2000. The field is so large that longer-term exploitation of the reserves will require a pipeline, but technical problems remain with extracting oil from the very complicated subsea geology 40 miles west of Eshaness.
<P>
Council insiders believe the third pipeline into Sullom Voe could trigger an entirely new deal with the industry, possibly bringing major financial benefits to the islands.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
