<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Foula gets used to the waiting game

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1>    </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


20th September 1996
<P>
The 50 islanders of Foula are still waiting for their new ferry, six years after Shetland Islands Council started to build a boat which could be based there in a purpose-built harbour.
<P>
The latest snag is the Plimsoll Line painted on the side of the 'New Advance' - launched recently at Richardson's yard in Stromness, Orkney, but unable to sail for Foula because of paperwork problems. The boat was due to be delivered last weekend.
<P>
Reports from Orkney say the boat sits too low in the water when fully loaded and the Shetland council is refusing to accept her until she meets the specification in every particular. Safety regulations insist that the Plimsoll Line must always be clear of the water.
<P>
The council wasted 400,000 pounds three years ago on an abortive, attempt to build a ferry for the exposed crossing from the Shetland mainland to Foula. The 'Westering Homewards' has since been re-named and handed over to the North Atlantic Fisheries College in Scalloway, as a training vessel. The second attempt has also cost around 400,000 pounds.
<P>
Foula councillor Jim Gear said yesterday (THURS) he was 'concerned' about the latest hold-up, but delays were something Foula had got used to: 'Having it here and having it right is more important than having it tomorrow,' the ever-patient Mr Gear said on local BBC radio.
<P>
It is understood that one possible reason for the problems is the weight of mandatory safety equipment, which has increased the displacement of the 'New Advance', whose size was limited by the need to lift her out of the water when based in Foula during the winter months.
<P>
Councillors are anxious to avoid a second 'Foula ferry fiasco'.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

