<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Councils demand nuclear flights ban

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Councils demand nuclear flights ban
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


20th September 1996
<P>
Sixteen Scottish councils campaigning against nuclear hazards have called on the UK Government to ban flights carrying radioactive waste to the Dounreay reprocessing plant on the northern tip of Scotland.
<P>
Dounreay has countered by inviting protesters to come and see for themselves.
<P>
The Scottish Nuclear-free Local Authorities organisation (NFLAS) says the flights to Wick airport are risky because:
<p>
<ul>
<li>Containers used for the waste could burst in a crash;
<P>
<li>There is no compulsory routing for planes landing at Wick;
<P>
<li>Radar cover in the area is less than 100 per cent;
<P>
<li>Military aircraft frequently use the same airspace, increasing the risk of mid-air collision;
</ul>
<P>
A report by Greenpeace and NFLAS says eight of the 47 known radioactive flights to Wick since 1991 took place during military exercises, 'implying no account is taken of the increased risks during these periods'.
<P>
The report says military flights in the area are expected to increase by about 28 per cent during the next two years: 'The possibility of nuclear flights encountering unannounced high speed military jet traffic in this area cannot be ignored.'
<P>
At a meeting in Shetland this week, NFLAS Convener, Shetland Islands Councillor Bertie Black, condemned the International Atomic Energy Agency's decision to allow nuclear materials to be flown in flasks which can only withstand a 30 mph impact:
<P>
'The whole idea behind the flask design was supposed to be that, no matter what the accident or transport mode, no radioactivity would be released. Clearly that cannot be the case with the obsolete type B flask.
<P>
'Little or no attention has been given to the risks posed by the high level of military flights in the vicinity of Wick. Should a jet collide with an air transport bound for Wick then the whole area would be showered in deadly radioactive waste,' Mr Black said.
<P>
'That is why we are calling on the Secretary of State for Scotland, Michael Forsyth, to step in and meet his responsibilities to protect the people and environment of Scotland and call a halt to these dangerous and potentially deadly transports.'
<P>
A spokesman for AEA Technology Ltd at Dounreay said yesterday (THURS): 'We have a long-established working relationship with the airport and we're confident in the procedures they have in place to ensure passenger and cargo flights in and out of Wick are undertaken safely.
<P>
'The transportation of nuclear material by air is strictly regulated. Stringent international standards are strictly observed by Dounreay on all moves of material and if regulations were to change we would immediately adopt them,' the spokesman said. 
<P>
'Dounreay have been undertaking reprocessing work for over 30 years. This latest consignment means it's business as usual at the site.'
<P>
He revealed the nuclear plant had invited Greenpeace and other campaigners against 'nuclear dumping' to come and visit the site: 'We have an open door policy and just now we're trying to set a mutually convenient date for the visit,' he said.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

For more information on this and other related environmental subjects vists the <a href="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/coms/kimo/">KIMO</a> pages.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

