<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Svein-Ove is determined to row back home

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Svein-Ove is determined to row back home
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>



19th September 1996
<P>
The man who rowed alone from Norway to Shetland in July has arrived back in the islands to collect his 19 foot boat for the return trip.
<P>
Svein-Ove Ask (32), a journalist from Nordfjordur, was unmoved by pleas from Shetland friends who asked him to wait until next summer.
<P>
Coastguards said yesterday (WED) they also wished he would not embark on the perilous 200-mile crossing during the season of equinoctial gales.
<P>
'No, I think it will be all right. I plan to leave at the weekend, once I see what the weather is like,' said Mr Ask, the father of two young children, as he looked over his boat 'Ingolf Arnasson', stored in a Lerwick warehouse since his epic row three months ago.
<P>
He explained his detailed plans for dealing with emergencies, such as a capsize, and said he was not afraid of being alone in heavy seas at night, far from land: 'I have done a lot of night rowing on the Norwegian coast. It does not worry me. I know what I am doing,' he said.
<P>
Les Snaith, Shetland Coastguard district officer at Lerwick, said Mr Ask had been to visit them to discuss his plans. 
<P>
'His boat seems pretty well-founded and he's as well-prepared as he could possibly be, short of having an escort craft with him,' Mr Snaith said. 'He reckons it'll take him about 10 days.
<P>
'He's got a radio beacon this time which will let the Norwegian Coastguards know via a satellite where he is at all times.
<P>
'I wish we could dissuade him from going,' Mr Snaith said. 'But he's one of these exceptional people who feel the challenge is worth the risk. We can't stop him and, if he's prepared to take the risk, then that's the bottom line.'
<P>
Mr Ask cheerfully admitted when he arrived at Lerwick from Maloy in July that his partner Hanne Grete Heen (32) thought he was 'a little bit crazy'. The couple have two sons, Arne (5) and Iver (3). 
<P>
Mr Ask is a specialist writer on boat restoration and is well known in Norway for making five abortive attempts to row to Shetland before his successful crossing. There is no record of anyone making the return trip alone in a rowing boat.
<P>
The seas around Shetland during the equinoctial gales can be among the roughest in the world but yesterday (WED) the weather seemed set fair, for a few days at least.
<P>
Two other Norwegian rowers who gave up an attempt to row to Shetland in June tried again last month. They were rescued after drifting for five days in a liferaft, when heavy seas swamped their open boat half way between Bergen and Lerwick.
<P>
Mr Ask believed his specially adapted 'Nordfjording' craft, with its self-draining cockpit, was better equipped for the voyage.





<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
