<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Scalloway Hotel re-opens at last

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Scalloway Hotel re-opens at last
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


19th September 1996
<P>
A hotel which lay derelict for years in the Shetland village of Scalloway re-opened yesterday (WED) after a refit costing over half a million pounds.
<P>
The Scalloway Hotel in Main Street, once described as an eyesore, welcomed back an old patron for the occasion - Scottish industry minister George Kynoch, making a two-day visit to the islands.
<P>
Performing the opening ceremony, Mr Kynoch recalled that he knew the building well from the days when he visited Scalloway regularly as a businessman, before going into politics.
<P>
Shetland Enterprise and Shetland Islands Council partly funded the restoration of the handsome building by entrepreneur Abdelhaq Zaoui, whose first job in Shetland, 20 years ago, was as a shipyard worker at Moore's slipway across the road.
<P>
Mr Zaoui, who runs the nearby Kiln Restaurant and Fisherman's Arms, took over the only hotel in the picturesque fishing village after it was badly damaged by fire two years ago. The refurbishment has created 24 en-suite bedrooms and a 54-seat restaurant.
<P>
Local councillor Iris Hawkins said it was 'a great day for Scalloway' and 'a dream come true'.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
