<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Kynoch hits out at air fares

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Kynoch hits out at air fares
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


18th September 1996
<P>
A Government minister last night (TUES) hit out at airlines for the high cost of fares to Shetland - and suggested the Scottish Tourist Board should do something about it.
<P>
Scottish industry minister George Kynoch told guests at a Highlands and Islands Enterprise reception in Scalloway, Shetland, he was amazed at the 231 pounds price tag on his Business air return ticket from Edinburgh to Shetland - more than a return flight to New York. Some of his staff paid 10 pounds less with British Airways.
<P>
'I'd just come back from two weeks' holiday,' Mr Kynoch said, 'and I found the ticket to Shetland waiting for me. When I saw the price I just about collapsed. I thought - why aren't we chartering an airliner for this?'
<P>
The tickets for Mr Kynoch and five Scottish Office officials accompanying him on the two-day visit came to over 1,300 pounds - not counting the flights for board members of Highlands and Islands Enterprise, holding an 'away-day' meeting with the minister in Lerwick,
<P>
Mr Kynoch said islanders kept asking him: 'What are you going to do about air fares to Shetland?' His reply was that prices like this were 'shackling' the tourist industry in its efforts to attract visitors to Shetland and other scenic parts of the Highlands and Islands.
<P>
'I really do think the Scottish Tourist Board could help,' he said. 'I'm going back to Edinburgh to ask them to approach the airlines who've taken part in a recent very successful promotion to attract people from south-east England to visit Scotland.'
<P>
Together with Highlands and Islands Airports (HIAL), he believed the tourist board could put up a very strong case that visitors should not be put off by the high cost of visiting the islands.
<P>
During his speech Mr Kynoch praised HIAL for the improvements they had made to Sumburgh, Shetland's main airport, and complimented the local enterprise company and Shetland Islands Council for their successful partnership with the islands' 'great entrepreneurial spirit'.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

