<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shetland News - Minister's close encounter with Claws

   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/pics/parch.gif">
<center>
<IMG SRC="/pics/header.gif">

<P>
<H1> Minister's close encounter with Claws
   </H1>
<H2>    </H2>
<img SRC="/pics/ftt6.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt7.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt8.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt9.gif">
<img SRC="/pics/ftt0.gif">
<HR>
<P>
</center>


18th September 1996
<P>
Scots industry minister George Kynoch came face to face with a monster of the deep in Shetland yesterday (TUES), and narrowly escaped a nipped finger.
<P><A HREF="lobster.jpg"><IMG SRC="lobsters.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=206 HEIGHT=180 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5></A>
Mr Kynoch met the Mother of all Lobsters during a visit to a shellfish hatchery at the North Atlantic Fisheries College in Scalloway. The irate crustacean objected to being picked up by a minister of the Crown, or anyone else.
<P>
College principal Morgan Goodlad showed Mr Kynoch the special tanks where up to 5,000 baby lobsters are raised from the eggs of a single female. The college has pioneered techniques which prevent the tiny lobsters cannibalising each other and has released over 10,000 to the sea, in a bid to restore wild stocks after years of over-fishing.
<P>
Mr Kynoch said: 'This is an ingenious project which shows the potential of Shetland's traditional industries.'
<P>
He said he was no stranger to Shetland, having had business interests in the isles' knitwear industry before he became a minister. Later he visited his old firm, The Shetland Woollen Company in Scalloway, and was shown round the new premises of one of his former business competitors, Judane Knitwear of Lerwick. 
<P>
After meeting staff and students in the textile department at The Shetland Further Education College, he inspected Lerwick Fish Traders' new salmon processing plant in Lerwick.
<P>
Travelling with Mr Kynoch were the board of Highlands and Islands Enterprise, holding their annual meeting in the recently opened Shetland Seafood Centre in Lerwick.
<P>
The minister later presented Shetland Enterprise with an award to mark their success in signing up 32 island companies for the 'Investors in People' scheme which promotes staff training.






<P>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>

Words strictly Copyright of Shetland News Agency, 1996.
<BR>
Pictures strictly Copyright of Force 10 Photos, 1996.

