<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>P&O Scottish Ferries - </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="monks.jpg">
<center>


<IMG SRC="pnomainlogoblack.gif" align=center>

<H2>Welcome to the Shetland Islands<BR>a holiday you will never forget
</center>  </H2>
<CENTER><img src="pnostrip2.gif"></CENTER>


<CENTER><H3>      </H3></CENTER>

<P><a Href="jarls.jpg"><Img align=left src="jarlss.jpg" hspace=5 border=0></A>

Many people have landed on Shetland before you but most famous were the <A HREF="http://www.shetland-tourism.co.uk/vikings/vikings.html">Vikings</A> - their influence is still very prevalent today.
<P>
The sea is part of everyday life in Shetland which makes it the natural way to reach Britain's northernmost islands, some 100 in all, which have a dramatic history and a character all of their own.  Sailing towards Shetland in summer there is scarcely any night, just a dimming of the sky around midnight, known in Shetland as the 'Simmer Dim'.
<P><a Href="cmin.jpg"><Img align=right src="cmins.jpg" hspace=5 border=0></A>
Many people have landed on Shetland before you - some as early as 3 000 BC - but most famous were the Vikings who landed and made Shetland their home.  All around Shetland you can see historical treasures.  Visit Jarlshof where seven distinct civilisations can be traced amongst its ancient dwellings; Mousa Broch, Britain's best example of an Iron Age Fort; and Scalloway Castle, built by the cruel Earl Patrick Stewart.
<P>
Everyone who visits Shetland is awed by the stunning cliff scenery considered by many to be the most beautiful and dramatic in Britain.  Widlife abounds.  Native <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/sigs/ponies/">Shetland ponies</A> roam free, <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/sigs/seals/">seals, porpoises</A> and otters can be seen and the vast colonies of  <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/sigs/birds/bird1.html">gulls and gannets</A> are breathtaking.  The angler will enthuse over the rich loch and sea fishing and seldom anywhere today will you find the freedom and the friendship that still exist in Shetland.
<P><a Href="burning.jpg"><Img align=left src="burnings.jpg" hspace=5 border=0></A>
Perhaps you will spend some time reading or listening to the fascinating myths and sagas of the Vikings brought to life by the many historical settlements that surround you.  Those interested in more modern history will enjoy seeing the places associated with the 'Shetland Bus', of WW II fame.  The Vikings came from Scandinavia as did the Shetland Bus and each weekend in the summer it will be possible for you to sail direct from Lerwick to Bergen in Norway, sailing in the wake of the Vikings and the Shetland Bus.


<P>


