<DOCHDR>
http://www.shetland-news.co.uk:80/websites/lht/oilrelated/oilrelated.html 194.72.245.173 19970110103146 text/html 6439
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 10:31:49 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6268
Last-modified: Sun, 07 Jul 1996 22:28:35 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lerwick Harbour Trust - Home Page</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- <BODY BACKGROUND="lhtparch.jpg"> -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFEF2">
<center>
<IMG SRC="lhtlogo.gif">

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>

<H1>Oilfield logistical support
<br>
Lerwick - the obvious choice</H1>
<H3>
whatever the weather...whatever the time
</H3>
</center>
<CENTER><img width=600 height=3 src="lhtstrip.gif"></CENTER>
<P>


<P><A HREF="oilbasin.jpg"><img src="oilbasins.jpg" align=left hspace=10 vspace=5 border=0></A><P>
A look at the map shows why Lerwick Harbour has been a logistics support centre for 25 years of offshore oil exploration, construction and production in the northern North Sea - and now the Atlantic Frontier:

<UL><LI>Nearest to the East Shetland basin.
<LI>Close to the West Shetland fields.
<LI>Handy for decommissioning older North Sea installations.</UL>
<P>
Based at Lerwick, you save money, cut turnaround time, speed up deliveries and improve safety  - with the security of full engineering back-up and communications. 
<BR>You can virtually halve your fuel costs, because Lerwick is so much nearer to the action. 

<BR>
  
<BR clear=all>
<STRONG>(Clicking on the map will let you view a 107k version with all details clearly visible)</STRONG>
<BR clear=ALL>
<P>
<STRONG>Lerwick Harbour</STRONG>
<P><A HREF="supply.jpg"><IMG SRC="supplys.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 BORDER=0></A>
<P>
<BR> <BR>
<UL><P><LI>8 hours' steaming time from the Brent Field.
<P>
<LI>110 nm from the fields West of Shetland.
<P>
<LI>Overnight ferries to the UK mainland.
<P>
<LI>Daily flights to Aberdeen, with regular connections to the UK, Europe and North America.
</UL>
<P>
<BR clear=all>
<STRONG>Always open</STRONG>
<P>
Two entrances make Lerwick accessible in all weathers. Harbour staff, pilots, tugs, Customs, agency and consular cover are on call 24-hours, year-round. 
<P>
The harbour has full radar surveillance, well-marked, dredged channels, deep anchorages, good shelter, small tides and <A HREF="http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/websites/lht/information/information.html">ample berthing</A>. Bunkers, water, refuse disposal and cranes are at the quayside, day and night. 



<BR CLEar=all>
<P>
<STRONG>All you need...and more</STRONG>
<P>

<A HREF="dock.jpg"><img src="docks.jpg" align=left border=0 hspace=10 vspace=5></A>
<P>
Extensive repair facilities include a floating dock for 2,750 tonne dwt vessels - plus trained divers, coded welders, skilled shipwrights, marine engineers and essential spares. There is <A HREF="http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/websites/lht/information/information.html">10,000 feet of quay space</A>, backed by extensive  shoreside facilities and development land. 
<P>
Our biggest support base, OIL Shetland, has six berths with 21 feet of water at MLWS, heavy lift capacity up to 110 tonnes and 175,000 square feet of warehousing.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<STRONG>When it comes to taking things apart again </STRONG>
<P>
With more than 20 acres of open storage, O.I.L. is an ideal location for marshalling redundant equipment during oilfield abandonment operations.
<P><A HREF="dalesvoe.jpg"><IMG SRC="dalesvoes.jpg" ALIGN=right WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=171 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 border=0></A>

The Dales Voe Rig Jetty is another prime site for the growing business of decommissioning work. Specialist offshore vessels, heavy-lift ships and the largest barges can berth alongside in deep, sheltered water. 
<P>This purpose-built base is also available to prepare modules and plant for offshore construction, and for rig workovers and inspections. 
<P>
<STRONG>Keeping it clean - and keeping costs down</STRONG>
<P>
Companies based around Lerwick Harbour specialise in safe, environmentally-friendly disposal of offshore wastes, with the minimum of expensive landfill. 
<P>
A new incinerator, meeting the latest air quality standards, is planned for 1998 and will offer a much-needed service on the doorstep of the Shetland oilfields.  
<P>
<STRONG>Safety First</STRONG>
<P>
The North Sea and the north-east Atlantic are getting rougher and windier. New developments are in the wildest water out west. A base at Lerwick Harbour reduces long passages in winter storms. Our powerful fire-fighting harbour tug can tow disabled vessels and assist berthing. Lerwick Lifeboat and Shetland Coastguard's Search and Rescue helicopter are on call at all times.

<P>


<P>
<CENTER><H3><STRONG>Lerwick - at the centre of the offshore oil industry
</STRONG></H3></CENTER>
<P><A HREF="oilbase.jpg"><img src="oilbases.jpg" align=left border=0 hspace=10 vspace=5></A><P>

Lerwick Harbour is the most accessible, efficient and economical port for oilfield support in the northern North Sea - the right package in the right place at the right time. 
<P>
The further north you work, the more logical to choose Lerwick. The nearest ports on the British mainland are the remote ones - particularly in winter. Lerwick is right at the centre - and the facilities are as good as many big city ports.
<P>
At Lerwick Harbour Trust we've been working with the offshore oil and gas industry for over a quarter of a century. We know what you need - and how to deliver it on time. 
<P>
Like many of the local service companies based around the harbour, Lerwick Harbour Trust has ISO 9002 quality assurance accreditation. 
<P>
If, after looking at the other pages, you want to know more about Britain's Top Port, or discuss any detailed requirements in confidence, please <A HREF="mailto:lkharbour@lht.zetnet.co.uk">email us</A> today.
<P>


<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<CENTER><img width=600 height=3 src="lhtstrip.gif"></CENTER>
