<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lerwick Harbour Trust</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFEF2">
<center>
<IMG SRC="lhtlogo.gif">

<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<P>
<h1>Welcome to 'Britain's Top Port'</h1>
</center>
<CENTER><img width=600 height=3 src="lhtstrip.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H1>Lerwick Harbour</H1>
<H2>
Hub of the Shetland Tourist Trade
</H2>
</CENTER>
Tourism is big business for Lerwick Harbour. The bustling port is a visitor attraction in its own right, as well as being Shetland's main port of entry.
<P><A HREF="harbour1.jpg"><IMG SRC="harbour1s.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 BORDER=0></A>
<STRONG>Cruise ships</STRONG> have been calling at Britain's most northerly town for more than 60 years; Lerwick's superb natural harbour lies just north of the 60th parallel, a natural port on cruises to Norway, Iceland, Faroe and the north of Scotland.
<P>
A Lerwick stopover is a popular introduction to these hundred beautiful islands for thousands of first-time visitors. Lerwick now welcomes more cruise passengers than any port in Scotland.
<P>
<STRONG>Mini-cruises</STRONG>, using <A HREF="http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/websites/pno/">P&O Scottish Ferries</A>' scheduled overnight sailings, offer a leisurely way for passengers to discover the islands during the long hours of summer daylight.
<P>
<STRONG>Cruising yacht</STRONG> arrivals number more than 300 a year. Most of them make Lerwick their first landfall. The yacht-friendly port is a convenient base for exploring the 900-mile Shetland coastline.
<P><BR> <BR clear=all>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>Cruise Operators: make Lerwick your next port of call</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P><A HREF="upright.jpg"><IMG SRC="uprights.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 BORDER=0></A>
Lerwick harbour and the Shetland Tourist industry have the facilities, the skills and the experience to make sure your ship's visit is a success.
<P>
The port is open in all weathers, around the clock, equipped and staffed to handle the largest cruising vessels. Pilots and two tugs are available 24 hours, with radar-assisted approach if required. Deep-water anchorage and quays are sheltered from all winds.
<P>
Cruise ships of up to 15,000 tonnes grt can lie alongside at berths with potable water and bunkers.
<P>
For large ships at anchor, your launches run a five-minute shuttle to a floating pontoon in a sheltered dock, equipped to modern safety specifications. The small tidal range, just 2 metres, adds to ease of operation.
<P>
Services available include 24-hour Customs clearance, shipchandlery, dockside security, bonded stores and ship's agency. Hotels offer excellent facilities. Scheduled air and sea links to the mainland are fats and frequent, telecommunications are world-class.
<P>
Cruise operators find professional standards here equal to much larger ports in Britain and Scandinavia. That is why they come back year after year.
<P>
<B>P&O Scottish Ferries</B> run a varied programme of Shetland and Orkney holidays, ranging from two-night mini-cruises to 14-day package tours. The company has a weekly excursion from Lerwick to Bergen, Norway, in the summer months.
<P>
Full details, including sailing schedules, fares and advance booking, are available from <A HREF="http://www.shetland-news.co.uk/websites/pno/">P&O Scottish Ferries' home page</A>.
<P>
<A HREF="buses.jpg"><IMG SRC="busess.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 BORDER=0></A>
<B>Visiting Yachts</B> have their own sheltered berths in <B>The Small Boat Harbour</B>, right in the centre of Lerwick. Boats from Scandinavia, Germany, the Netherlands, France and mainland UK are most numerous but it's not unusual to meet boats from as far away as the USA, Canada and Australia.
<P>
<B>Customs</B> clearance is available at the dockside, where sailing skippers will also find fresh water, bunkers and refuse disposal. Nearby are groceries, banks, shipchandlers, car-hire Admiralty Chart agents and a boatyard skilled in repairs and maintenance for sailing craft.
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.shetland-tourism.co.uk/">The Shetland Tourist Centre</A> overlooks the yacht harbour and provides information, updated daily, on activities and tours around the islands.
<P>
A few steps along the waterfront the <B>Lerwick Boating Club</B> always has a friendly greeting for visiting sailors. There is an hospitable bar, with musical entertainment at weekends. Yacht crews may use the laundry and showers.
<P><A HREF="lakota.jpg"><IMG SRC="lakotas.jpg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 BORDER=0></A>
The club runs a weekly programme of sailing events; visitors are most welcome to take part. The annual Round-Bressay Race, Skerries Race, Lerwick Regatta and Inter-club Regatta (where crews compete from all over Shetland) are popular attractions.
<P>

Lerwick hosts several major international sailing events: the annual <B>Bergen-Shetland Race</B> is a highlight in May and attracts over 50 yachts; every two years the <B>Dutch North Sea Triangle</B> calls at Lerwick; and the port is also on the itinerary of the <B>Round Britain and Ireland Race</B>, run every four years by the Royal Western Yacht Club of England.
<P>
The Cutty Sark Tall Ships Races will visit Lerwick in early August 1999. The visit by the fleet is being locally arranged by <A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/sigs/sail.shetland/">Sail Shetland</A>, and the port is looking forward to this historic occasion.

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>

We look forward to hearing from you at Lerwick Harbour Trust, to discuss your requirements for next season. Just  <A HREF="mailto:lkharbour@lht.zetnet.co.uk">email us</A> today. We promise you won't be sorry you made contact. 
<P>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<CENTER><img width=600 height=3 src="lhtstrip.gif"></CENTER>
