<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>Europe Writes...</H1>
<P><I>Notes from London by David Whitehouse</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>EMU to give travellers a break</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>A traveller with $1,000 visits each of the 15 member states of the European
Union (EU), converting the hard-earned currency at each frontier.  Because of
commission charges the $1,000 becomes $500 before any of the trip expenses have
been met.  Economic and monetary union (EMU) is scheduled to come into effect on
January 1, 1999.  Initially it may only involve a small group of EU countries --
perhaps Germany and France, along with the Benelux countries -- but a start will
have been made. The project is often seen as distant and remote from the
concerns of ordinary citizens.  The intergovernmental conference (IGC), opening
in Turin at the end of March, will be keenly aware of the need to transform the
EMU project from a technical, bureaucratic exercise into an open, democratic
process that is relevant to real people. <BR></P>
<P>The currency swindle carried out daily by European financial institutions
provides a promising example of how this could be achieved.  People need to know
in advance what their travelling is going to cost, but this is often be
impossible with fluctuating exchange rates.  In some countries black market
operators prey on the naive.  Price transparency would be of great help to
travellers.  At present fluctuating exchange rates mean that it is hard for
travellers to compare the real value of goods and services across borders. EMU
would make pricing differentials crystal clear and so travelling consumers would
benefit from strengthened international competition.  European legislation on
the dubious banking practice of charging at both ends of an international
currency transaction would mean we really are moving in the right direction.<BR></P>
<P>Travellers have been growing accustomed to the liberty afforded by the
absence of passport controls among the Schengen group of EU countries --
Benelux, Germany, Spain, Portugal, Greece and Italy.  With the accession of the
Nordic countries to Schengen, and assuming an easing of terrorist tensions in
France, this benefit will be extended much further.  The signs are that Europe's
policy-makers are, not before time, waking up to the economic importance of the
travelling public, and starting to take their interests into account.<BR></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Time Travel - Celebrating the Year 2000</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Greenwich in London has beaten off a fierce challenge from Birmingham to win
the race to host Britain's millenium celebrations in the year 2000.  Lying in
the south east of the capital, Greenwich is already a hugely popular tourist
destination.  It lies on a longitude of zero and so, in the 19th century, world
commerce depended on sea charts which used Greenwich as the Prime Meridian.  At
a conference in Washington DC in 1884 it was decided to use Greenwich mean time
to standardise time all over the world.  Greenwich Observatory, not to mention
the Cutty Sark, have proved themselves as massive long-term tourist attractions.<BR></P>
<P>The Imagination Group Ltd has been selected by the government-appointed
Millenium Commission to design and develop the event, which will consist of
entertainment and educational activities lasting throughout the year.  They will
propose the erection of 12 pavilions, each focusing on a different aspect of
time, and arranged to form a giant time circle.  The Price Waterhouse
consultancy, commissioned by the government, believes that 10m-15m visitors will
be attracted to the area. <BR></P>
<P>Given that figure, Greenwich was vulnerable to legitimate criticism from its
Birmingham rival in that, like London as a whole, the area suffers from a poor
transport infrastructure.  Massive improvement to the local rail service would
be needed. Hopes rest with the Jubilee Line, part of London's underground, and
the Docklands Light Railway, both of which are to be extended to take in
Greenwich.<BR></P>
<P>The Greenwich bid benefited from strong support from the City of London, and
was chosen mainly because the government believes that the long term economic
benefits will be greatest there.  Greenwich Peninsula, a derelict site owned by
British Gas, will be transformed.  The Hausner consultancy, also commissioned by
the government, believes that &#163;500m will be invested in the area, and that
10,000 permanent jobs will be created.<BR></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>All roads lead to Brussels?</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>An ambitious high-speed rail network intended to link London, Paris, Cologne
and Amsterdam will have Brussels at its core. The project is one of a series of
planned international transport links in Europe, known as trans-European
networks (TENs), and trumpeted by the European Commission as bringing home the
concrete benefits of European integration to travellers. Journey times would be
slashed. From Brussels, time to Paris would be cut from 2 hours 25 mins to 1
hour 20 mins, and to London, from 3 hours 15 mins to 2 hours 5 mins. Yet despite
the Commission's claim that it is &quot;transforming a network into a patchwork&quot;,
quarrels over funding and political rivalries have reduced progress to a snail's
pace. <BR></P>
<P>The Brussels-centred network is not expected to be operational until at
least 2005 &#151; only the section between Lille and the Channel Tunnel is
currently in use.  Belgium took seven years before finally agreeing to finance
the system, with tensions between the Flemish and Walloon communities
contributing to the delay.  The country's regionalised structure meant that
planning permission had to be given separately in Flanders and Wallonia as well
as in Brussels.  The Walloons were eventually able to secure the inclusion of
the town of Li&egrave;ge on the route, despite the engineering complexity and
extra expense involved.  In Germany progress has so far been so slow as to be
barely perceptible: only a small stretch of track near Cologne is currently
being upgraded.<BR></P>
<P>Elsewhere TENs are hampered by a similar lack of momentum.  A proposed
high-speed rail and combined transport link between Berlin and Verona is going
nowhere fast. Germany and Italy stand to gain the most in economic terms, though
the route must necessarily pass through Austria. So the Austrians are
understandably cagey about being drawn into any funding commitments. The greatly
delayed Channel Tunnel was a prime example of the acute difficulty of getting
agreement on finance.  With European finance ministers procrastinating over how
much to spend on the project, Eurotunnel, the private sector operator, was
simply unable to service its debts. <BR></P>
<P>&quot;Many countries behave as if construction and funding are the job of
someone else,&quot; snaps EU transport commissioner Neil Kinnock. The private
sector, which needs a return on its investment within a reasonable period,
cannot be expected to shoulder the entire burden. Part of the problem is that
many of the future benefits, such as time saved, less congestion and pollution
on motorways, and accelerated trade in goods and services, are very difficult to
quantify.  Improved transport links across the continent would make every
European country more attractive as a tourist destination and therefore bring
further real economic benefits&#151;gains which are liable to be overlooked by
national administrations focusing solely on the purse strings.<BR></P>
<P><I>David Whitehouse works in London as a copy editor at the Economist
Intelligence Unit, part of The Economist Group. </I></P>
<HR>
<H3>Air Travel Updates</H3>
<H4>Noted in <I>The European</I></H4>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Copenhagen</B> International Airport will build a new passenger terminal
to be shared by its main client, Scandanavian Airlines System (SAS), and two new
clients, Lufthansa and Thai International.  &#164;  Britain's Virgin Group has
signed an agreement to acquire 90% of <B>Belgium's</B> second-largest airline,
EuroBelgian Airlines.  EBA will be renamed Virgin European Airways but will
operate separately from parent Virgin Atlantic Airways.  &#164;  <B>Frankfurt</B>
will open a second airport railway station to accommodate high-speed intercity
trains.  Dubbed Terminal 3, it's expected to begin operation in 1999.  &#164; 
<B>Paris</B> may build a third airport north of Beauvais in Picardy to relieve
overcrowded Charles de Gaulle and Orly.  Another possible site is south of
Chartres; the final decision will depend on TGV connections.  &#164;</P>
<P><I><B>The European</B> is a weekly English-language newspaper providing
the latest in political, financial, and cultural news from Europe.   It is
available by subscription in the United States; call <B>800-875-2997</B> (In
Canada <B>201-627-5872</B>).</I></P>
