<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<H1>Following in the Poet's Footsteps</H1>
<P><I>by Nathalie Zeidman</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>From Wordsworth to Peter Rabbit</I><BR></H2> 
<P>There's no lovelier corner of England than the Lake District, and no better
way to explore it than to settle in to one of its quaint villages.  A good
choice is Ambleside at the north end of Windermere, the largest of the lakes. 
Ambleside is a center for coach tours, scenic walks, and lake excursions, as
well as a stop on the Morris Dancers' circuit.  It's also the heart of
Wordsworth country.  But you don't have to be a poetry lover to head straight
for the Wordsworth shrines; most tourists do.   The best place to start is Dove
Cottage, four miles up the road from Ambleside.<BR></P>
<P>Local buses make the run hourly.  The small house where the poet wrote some
of his finest poetry has little to distinguish it from other white-washed,
slate-roofed cottages in Cumbria -- only a small sign.  Everything there is
small: the rooms, the garden, the desk where he wrote, &quot;My heart leaps up
as I behold a rainbow in the sky.&quot;  Only the talent was big.<BR></P>
<P>Across the Rothay River from Dove cottage is Grasmere, the village most
associated with Wordsworth.   At the river's edge a self-service coffee-and-tea
garden offers, along with tea and scones, a view of the churchyard where the
poet lies.  Above Grasmere, the hills are sleepy with sheep and, in the spring,
new-born lambs.  The village itself caters to tourists who come in busloads and
overrun the shops.  Hand-knit woolens, crystal, and salon paintings are a bit
pricey; but Grasmere  gingerbread, as good as its reputation, is within most
budgets. <BR></P>
<P>The second-most visited Wordsworth shrine is Rydal Mount, an easy
mile-and-a-half walk from Ambleside along a narrow ridge that parallels the
road.   In the distance, views of Loughrigg Fell recall the paintings of
Constable and Thrner.  It's a friendly walk.  Ramblers pause to chat about the
early blooming hawthorn or late blooming lilac as they hold open one gate after
another.  Rydal Mount, a handsome manor house, is kept as it was in the poet's
day by his descendants, who live there.  Wordsworth himself designed the
terraced gardens to provide the privacy he needed to compose his poems.  
Visitors following his footsteps find themselves inspired.<BR></P>
<P>The noted Victorian art critic John Ruskin also lived in the Lake District
in a fine home on public display.  But by far the most noted Victorian author to
live there was Beatrix Potter, creator of Peter Rabbit.  A nostalgic visit to
Potter's Hilltop Farm is on the itinerary of several coach tours.<BR></P>
<P>Bus tours are a good way to go if you don't enjoy driving on the &quot;wrong&quot;
side of the road but do enjoy knowledgeable commentary laced with wry humor. 
Brown's Luxury Coach Tours is headquartered in Ambleside, and better-known
Mountain Goat Tours has an office there.  Each operates half-day and full-day
tours.  One popular excursion in the half-day &quot;Five  Tarns Tour.&quot; 
<I>Tarn</I> is Norse for &quot;small lake&quot;, as <I>fell</I> is Norse for &quot;mountain.&quot;
 The Vikings, early invaders, left vocabulary as well as sheep for the &quot;uncivilized&quot;
Celts.  <BR></P>
<P>In addition to Hilltop Farm, the &quot;Five Tarns Tour&quot; takes you to
the sixteenth century village of Hawkshead, where the parish church with its
twelfth-century Norman tower looks down on the grammar school Wordsworth
attended, and a town square unchanged by time.  Along the way the coach dips
into Little Langdale valley.  The landscape here turns craggy with slate
outcroppings and the fell burns coppery in the afternoon sun.  Once copper
mining and slate-quarrying country, today it's the haunt of rock climbers.<BR></P>
<P>Another outstanding coach trip climbs Kirkstone Pass, at 1500 feet England's
highest, on the way to Ullswater, where, if the season is right, you'll see
Wordsworth's &quot;host of golden daffodils.&quot;  Wherever you go in the Lake
District, no matter the season, dry stone walls pattern the landscape.  Once
they defined private pastures.  Now these parti-colored, rough-cut rocks topped
by the bluest of slate turn the slopes into an iridescent patchwork.  It's a
comfort to the eye, and a miracle of artisan engineering: these dry stone walls
have stood four centuries without a glob of mortar.<BR></P>
<P>If you're staying in Ambleside, you don't have to join a tour to go
exploring.  Windermere at the south end of the lake is only fifteen minutes by
bus.   Full of Victorian charm, Windermere alas is also full of tourists.  But a
walk downhill to the lakeside suburb of Bowness, past cricket fields,
bow-windowed bed-and-breakfasts, and sweets shops, is pleasant.  From Bowness
you can return to Ambleside more leisurely by steamer. <BR> </P>
<P>If you're tired of meeting bus and steamer schedules, at the tourist office
you can pick up for 12p (20 cents) a map with three easy walks in and around
Ambleside.  Even without a map you can find your way to Stock Ghyll Park and its
waterfall: follow the road that climbs behind the Salutation Hotel through
groves of oak, birch and elm, being careful not to crush the delicate blossoms
of wild garlic that last the summer.  Half-hidden in the mist, Stock Ghyll Falls
seems the perfect background for those rituals the Druids practiced, even before
the Saxons came or the Rornans settled at the lake-end of town.<BR></P>
<P>One ritual still practiced in Ambleside is the yearly visit of the
Kendal-Westmorland Step Dancers.  Any Saturday in May, teams from Harrowgate,
Ripon, Merseyside and Kendal turn the Garden Center's parking lot into a
theater-in-the-round.  The program is traditional.  Colorful dancers, graceful
even in thick clogs, twirl ribbons, clash staves, wave garlands, and swing
partners to the accompaniment of concertinas, banjoes, horns and drums.  What a
way to welcome spring!  Originally Morris dancing was performed by men as a
fertility rite.  In the early nineteenth century, female mill workers in
Lancashire took up clogging when conversation at the workplace was banned.   The
women whose uniform included wooden shoes with iron bands began tapping out
their message to each other over the clatter of the looms.   On the way home
from work they often continued their &quot;Morris code&quot; on the cobblestone
streets.  It doesn't work with  Reeboks or Birkenstocks, tourists find.<BR></P>
<P>For a town of only two thousand those streets are pretty sophisticated.  A
number of shops display high fashion clothing and if you need real walking
shoes, Ambleside is the place to buy a pair.  A half dozen stores including a
wholesale outlet out-fashion Fifth Avenue's Ambercrombie and Fitch.  You won't
find souvenir shops.  After all, Wordsworth, though he had an government office
here, didn't live here.  However, the stationer's carries a stock of slate
coasters with scenes of Dove Cottage.  As for the makings of a picnic lunch, you
can pick up sandwiches, sweets, fruit and drinks at any one of a dozen catering
shops.  Dinner presents no problem.   In addition to hotels, many of which are
noted for their cuisine, moderately priced restaurants like Luigi's and
Bertram's serve authentic Italian dishes and local fish; forty dollars for two
includes wine.  Hotels tend to be more expensive, pubs less so.<BR></P>
<P>After dinner there isn't much to do:  walk to the lake, stroll to the
bowling green; drop in at a pub, the movie house, the jazz club.  Or return to
your room and watch telly.  British television is really no better than
American; it only seems so.  Maybe because you're in Ambleside.  &#164;</P>
<P><BR></P>
<HR>
<H2>Getting There</H2>
<UL><LI>By rail: to Windermere from Euston Station, London, changing at
Oxenholme, 4 hours; 15 minutes  to Ambleside by local bus or cab.</LI>
<LI>By National Express Coach:  to Windermere from Victoria Coach Station,
several times daily, 5&#189; hours;</LI>
<LI>By car: via Ml or M6, linking with other motorways.</LI></UL>
<P><BR></P>
<H2>Staying There</H2>
<UL><LI>Churchill Hotel and Pub; Lake Road, Ambleside, Cuubria LA 22 OBH,
England;  No elevator.  Ask for a back room; quiet with view of the fell.  </LI>
<LI>Kirkstone Foote Country House Hotel, Kirkstone Pass Road, Ambleside,
Cuubria LA 22 9 EH; seventeenth century manor house, lovely garden setting, some
cottages; l block from town center.</LI>
<LI>Borrans Park Hotel, Borrans Road, Ambleside, Cuubria LA 22 OEN; edge of
town near Lake windermere; old-fashioned charm in small park, reputation for
good food.</LI></UL>
<H2>Getting Around</H2>
<UL><LI>Two companies operate full day and half-day tours: Brown's Luxury
Coach Tours  and Mountain Goat Tours.</LI></UL>
<P><I> - Nathalie Zeidman</I></P>
<HR>
