<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Athens</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<H1>Thomas Cook</H1>
<P><B><I>What's Up in European Rail</I></B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<UL><LI>Sunday Eurostar service between London and Brussels will be completely
revised, with many journeys now following a 7-day-a-week pattern.<BR></LI>
<LI>Additional TGV services will be introduced from Lille Europe (Eurostar
station) to Marseille and Montpellier.  New trains from Lille Europe to
Bordeaux, Rennes, and Nantes will also be introduced.<BR></LI>
<LI>The <I>Marie Curie</I> Paris-Stuttgart EC train will be replaced by a
Strasbourg-Stuttgard IR service with connections to and from Paris.  The <I>Orient
Express</I> will run approximately two hours earlier from Paris and one hour
later from Budapest.<BR></LI>
<LI>The couchette train between Madrid and Paris, <I>Puerto de Sol</I>, will
no longer run.  Summer-weekend couchette cars from Oostende to Verona (trains
1218/19) are also withdrawn.<BR></LI>
<LI>Berlin-Kiev sleeping cars will run in the <I>St. Petersburg </I>Express to
Warsaw, and will then be conveyed via the Polish/Ukraine border instead of
traveling via Brest.  This will avoid the need for passengers to have Belarus
transit visas.<BR></LI>
<LI>The <I>Napoli</I> Express will be withdrawn and replaced by a new EN train
from Paris to Roma Ostiense.  The <I>Gallelei</I> will be rerouted via Modane
and renumbered, but plans to run this train via Pisa have been scrapped, and it
will continue to serve Bolgna.  The <I>Parthenon</I>, which previously ran in
high summer from Paris to Brindisi, connecting with ships to Greece, will be cut
back to Ancona, losing its name in the process.  The Lausanne-Milano train at
1113 (connecting out of the <I>Lutetia</I> from Paris) will become a Pendolino
train, operated by high-speed tilting rolling stock under the new <I>CISALPINO</I>
banner.<BR></LI>
<LI>The <I>Balt Orient Express</I> is withdrawn but retained between Budapest
and Bucharest as the <I>Muntenia</I>.  These two cities are also linked by a
new EuroNight train, giving a faster journey.  The overnight
Berlin-Prague-Vienna train, <I>Sansouci</I>, has been withdrawn as a separate
train, but the through cars continue to run, being conveyed in the <I>Metropol</I>
between Berlin and Breclav.   The <I>Bart&oacute;k B&eacute;la </I>(Stuttgart-Budapest)
will be extended to start from Frankfurt.<BR></LI>
<LI>A new CityNightLine train named <I>Berlin</I> will run Berlin-Z&uuml;rich.
 It will also have a portion from Dresdin to Z&uuml;rich via Leipzig.  The <I>Italia
Express</I> is changed to Rome from Cologne instead of Dortmund, and will no
longer have a portion originating at Frankfurt.<BR></LI>
<LI>There will be a new high-speed <I>CISALPINO</I> Pendolino train between
Geneva and Milan, leaving Geneva at 10:39am and leaving Milan at 6:40am.  Two
additional <I>CISALPINO</I> trains will be added on this route for winter
1996/97.<BR></LI></UL>
<HR>
<P><I>Information courtesy of Thomas Cook Publishing, UK.  The monthly <B>Thomas
Cook European Timetable</B> is the most comprehensive compilation of European
rail schedules available, with more than 50,000 timings for rail &amp; ferry
services throughout Western &amp; Eastern Europe. </I></P>
<P>Visit <B>Thomas Cook</B> on the Internet at
<A HREF="http://www.thomascook.com/">http://www.thomascook.com</A>.</P>
