<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Notes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Miss Elainey's Notes</FONT></H1>
<HR>
<H2><STRONG><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">News and gossip on the European front</FONT></EM></STRONG></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>&#164; The five most dangerous European countries in which to take the
wheel yourself?  Turkey, Portugal, Spain, Macedonia, and the Czech Republic,
according to a United Nations report quoted in <I>Cond&eacute; Naste Traveler</I>.
 Sweden, Norway, Denmark, Ireland, and France enjoy the top European slots at
the safer end of the list.  (We presume that out of fairness, they <I>didn't</I>
include downtown Paris!)</B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">&#164; Montenegro and Croatia are hard at work
rebuilding their coastal tourist industries, where more than 400,000 visitors
flocked annually before the onset of the Balkan wars.  Repairs in Croatia's
Dubrovnik, which prior to the fighting was one of Europe's best-preserved
medieval cities, are well underway, and numerous hotels and resorts along the
region's famous beaches are being refurbished with high hopes for a resumption
of tourism.  If the current peace effort holds, look for terrific bargains this
fall and winter, as operators try to get newly re-opened properties and newly
re-hired staff up to speed for next year's summer season.</FONT></B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>&#164; The Greek Islands remain one of the most popular destinations for
American cruise travelers, with more than 50,000 Yanks floating about the area
each season.  But for the next few months, take care where your ship is schedule
to land:  labor unrest at Piraeus is disrupting service for some lines, and may
spread to other ports.  Local unions are upset at the proliferation of low-wage,
non-Greek crews.</B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">&#164; Other troubled waters:  European
environmentalists find themselves at odds over plans to widen, dredge, lengthen,
or otherwise upgrade canals in varous EU countries.  Proponents believe that the
canals, which were important freight routes in the days before lorries and
autobahns, can once again play a role and help reduce Europe's widespread truck
pollution.  Others oppose the work, fearing damage to fragile wetlands, fishing
areas, and bird habitats.  For tourists too there is both upside and downside:
more &amp; longer canals will offer greater travel options, but your floating
hotel may be likelier to share the &quot;road&quot; with a petrol barge.  And in
at least some of the projects, historic bridges might have to be altered or torn
down to allow for larger ships.</FONT></B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>&#164; Big changes may be coming to the operation of trains in the
Netherlands.  The government-run service is going over to private ownership,
with the former chairman of Philips Electronics at the helm.  The new CEO is
known as a fierce master of efficiency, while Dutch Railways is regarded as one
of the industry's more slothful beaurocracies; expect sparks to fly.</B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">&#164; Along with fighting over passengers, the
new Eurotunnel is in a scrap with English Channel ferry companies over duty-free
sales.  Complaining that the ferries' onboard shops give boat operators an
unfair edge, the rail tunnel owners are backing a European Commission move to
eliminate duty-free sales by 1999.  While their advantage lasts, the ferries are
making the most of the $300 million-dollar business -- the largest part of it in
liquor and cigarettes -- by cutting prices even further to keep travelers on
board.  But Eurotunnel, which can sell duty-free at its Calais and Folkestone
terminals, is matching the cuts and then some, making for some of the lowest
booze prices in Europe.  Among other effects, the competition has led to the odd
spectacle of French shoppers traveling to England to buy cognac!</FONT></B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>&#164; Speaking of tunnels:  if you thought the Paris M&eacute;tro was
deep, wait 'til you see what the ever-ambitious French are digging into now.  In
an effort to ease the monumental traffic jams afflicting modern-day Versailles,
plans are underway for a $2 billion vehicle tunnel more than 500 feet below the
historic town's surface.  The tunnel, which will charge a toll of about $1.50,
is expected to be completed in 2002.</B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">&#164; The venerable Vespa, Italy's classic
motorscooter, is fifty years old.  More than 15 million have been put on the
road since the two-wheeler's introduction at the close of World War II.</FONT></B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>&#164; Venetian gondoliers banned the traditional accordian-playing
singers from their boats earlier this year, due to disputes over union dues. 
The quarrel has been under negotiation and is expected to be solved soon.</B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">&#164; Already engulfed by English in movies,
advertising, and rock-n-roll music, many stalwart defenders of Europe's native
tongues are finding the Internet to be final straw.  Close to 90% of all content
on the Information Superhighway is in English, and because it's impossible for
any individual country to regulate the Internet as it does other media, the
newest &quot;plague&quot; of language contamination cannot be battled by
legislation.</FONT></B></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-1">Articles appearing on this page are &copy;1996
Personal Programs and/or the contributor.  All rights reserved.  Opinions
expressed are those of the writer(s). Travel information is by nature subject to
frequent change; travelers should always verify information prior to relying
upon it.  Personal Programs does not represent and does not endorse products,
companies, or offers referenced on this page, and cannot be responsible for
errors, changes, or omissions.  Please send comments to Personal Programs at
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A></FONT>. </P>
