<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Vivey; Charlie Chaplin Sleeps Here</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Charlie Chaplin Sleeps Here</H2>
<P><B><I>Vivey: French with good manners</I></B><BR></P>
<P><I>By Kit Snedaker</I><BR></P>
<P><B>There&#146;s nothing funny about Vivey.</B>  Maybe that&#146;s why
Charlie Chaplin spent the  last 25 years of his life in this little Swiss town. 
Vevey is just one of those charming, convenient spots on the shore of Lake
Geneva that&#146;s been inhabited since the Romans put it on the map, as a
staging area called Vibiscum.  Curved around the lake shore, the town&#146;s
narrow, winding streets, smart shops, interesting eateries, fountains, castle,
market and parks are not only lively, but user friendly.  No homeless.  No
stretch limos, either.  When the Chaplins bought a house in the suburb of
Corsair in 1952, Vevey didn&#146;t fuss over them. They lived happily ever
after.  Well, almost.  Charlie died in 1977, and was buried in Corsair&#146;s
graveyard.  Several years later his wife, the former Oona O&#146;Neil, got a
note saying: Your husband&#146;s body has been stolen and we are holding it for
ransom.  Her public reply: I won&#146;t pay a single Swiss franc.  No matter
where his body was, she told authorities, he lives in my heart.  This delighted
the thrifty Swiss.  Police doubled their efforts and found the casket dumped in
a nearby pasture.  They caught the men who had taken it, put them in jail and
reburied Charlie under tons of concrete.<BR></P>
<P>Not long afterwards, in 1982, town fathers commissioned British sculptor
John Doubleday to do a statue of &#147;the little tramp.&#148;  They set it up
in a tiny square on the Quai Pardonnet, a waterfront park.  The first day it
stood there and everyday since, a passerby picks a flower and tucks it in
Charlie&#146;s outstretches hand.  Standing there in shoes so big the toes turn
up, bamboo cane bent at an improbable angle, Chaplin has a perfect view of the
swans on Lake Geneva or Lake Leman, as the Swiss prefer to call it.  On benches
behind him locals and visitors sit and watch the swans, too, but hold up a
camera and watch the scramble.  Strangers rush to put a protective arm around
Chaplin&#146;s shoulders or dust off his derby or make sure his flower is fresh.
 Vevey is crazy about him.<BR></P>
<P>There&#146;s even a restaurant with his name misspelled -- Charly&#146;s
Cafe. But only one; the Swiss don&#146;t exploit celebrities.  Not for them
souvenir Chaplin coffee mugs, calendars, or plaques saying Chaplin Ate Here.
Acceptance is what Vevey gave the Chaplins, and a place to live at once
sophisticated and &#147;small town&#148;.  But &#147;small town&#148; just an
hour away from snappy Geneva by fast, clean, regular trains; and minutes from
the countryside.<BR></P>
<P>A helicopter overview sorts it all out:  mountains rise just behind town,
vineyards run down their slopes;  the Rhone flows placidly through a nearby
village into the lake.  Air Glacier&#146;s owner/pilot, Ernest Devaud, loves to
show off his Canton of Vaud.  When he isn&#146;t taking passengers flightseeing,
he delivers building material up the mountain or hurries to a rescue -  human or
cattle.  In fact for just 50 Swiss francs per year, any farmer can call Devaud
anytime to chopper in and pull a cow out of a crevasse or take someone down the
mountain to a hospital.  He swoops over the moody, medieval Chateau Chillon made
famous by Lord Byron&#146;s The Prisoner of Chillon, then circles Castle Aigle
(once a fortress, now a wine museum), Chateau d&#146;Oex, a ski resort with
cheesemaking center, and Eschallens&#146; Bread and Wheat Museum.  Maybe Chaplin
didn&#146;t get to all those spots, but they make his Vevey more interesting.
Wine, cheese, mountains, castles and museums indicate what this part of the
world is all about.<BR></P>
<P>Four museums are right in town, each of them new, bright and shiny.  The
Museum of Old Vevey, in a 16th Century castle near the lake, is the smallest - 
one floor.  The Swiss Camera Museum is all glass and hands on; try cropping a
shot with magnetic frame, and see the antique Kodaks with the photos they made. 
The Game Museum in Castle Tour de Peilz, at the end of the esplanade, tempts
visitors to stop and play. But the best is the Alimentarium.  Despite its
off-putting name, this food museum is graphic and grabbing.  A huge sculpted
apple with a bite out of it welcomes visitors.  At the exhibit of what the
average Swiss eats in a month, an attendant is ready with an explanation.  Much
as in the States, a Swiss diet is high in meat and fat, but with twice as much
cheese and wine.<BR></P>
<P>Nearby stands the mockup of a hut from North Cameroon with appropriate
grains and vegetables in original baskets.  Take pictures; touch the exhibits. 
Children romp through.  If there&#146;s a lot of chocolate, old and new, at
least the brand name of the museum&#146;s founder, Nestle, is discreetly hidden.
 Bread and wheat are celebrated in the two-year-old Bread and Wheat House at
Echallens.  Since this is a Living Crafts Museum, it begins with a bakery and
small restaurant.  Visitors smell croissants, bread and pastry baking.  Bakers
roll, cut and braid breads at an open counter. Children crowd up to knead and
shape their own snacks.  Then they watch their efforts slide into any of four
different kinds of ovens.  Old flour mills, grinding stones and harvesting
equipment stand on the floors above, illustrating the whole history of grain
cultivation.  And on the top floor a voice-over slide show describes it all.<BR></P>
<P>Wine has its own museum at Castle Aigle.  Here in the Rhone Valley thrifty
Swiss saved the best parts of a 13th century castle and filled it with wine
memorabilia.  They left the arrow slits in the walls and fireplaces big enough
to roast an ox.  Among the drinking cups and wine presses a drawing on one wall
dates from the 18th century when the castle was Aigle&#146;s prison.  A lonely
prisoner sketched his homeland there on the wall of his cell, adding a sad
lament underneath.  The Swiss had the good sense to leave that, too.  From his
tiny window the prisoner could see the vineyards that stretched in all
directions.  They still do.<BR></P>
<P>One of them, Clos du Boux at Epesses, belongs to Luk Massy.  During the
harvest his days are 18 houre long.  Pickers toss bunches of fat green grapes
into wedge-shaped baskets.  Men hoist them on metal backpacks and walk down hill
to dump in the crushers.   Massy is not only famous for his white wine, but as
the central character in John McPhee&#146;s book about the Swiss army, &#147;Concorde
Swiss&#148;.  He talks more about working in vineyards in Sonoma, Argentina an
Australia than his experiences with McPhee, however.  Harvest here is a romp
compared with Napa and Sonoma.  More pickers laugh; more new wine is passed
around. Settled in at a long wooden table beside an antique crusher, vintner J.
P. Potterat, is asked if he&#146;s ever considered updating his equipment.  &#147;If
I didn&#146;t do it this way,&#148; he answers, &#147;you wouldn&#146;t visit
me.&#148;  In vino veritas.  Visitors are solicited.<BR></P>
<P>Up in the Vaud Alps above Epesses, Jean Raynaud and his family make the last
gruyere of the season at their summer chalet.  A mixture of skimmed evening and
whole morning milk from their 62 cows heats in a copper cauldron over a wood
fire.  Two little boys push trucks along the stone floor.  A cat paces the wall
licking its chops.  When the milk is warm Raynaud measure out a dropper-full of
rennet and squeezes it in.  He swings the cauldron off heat, stirs it with a
long metal fork.  The milk, now solidified to junket, breaks into curds and
watery whey.  Then the cauldron swings back on the fire to firm the curds the
old-fashioned way.  If they used modern equipment would visitors like me drop
in?  Visitors welcome here, too.  While the curd heats visitors sit down at a
kitchen table set with bread, cheese, plates, carved wooden spoons and two
wooden buckets of pudding-thick, beige cream from the evening&#146;s milk.  Dip
in the  wooden spoons and lick off that sweet, fat goodness.  Sip some hot,
sweet, cinnamon tea.  Put shreds of pungent, aged gruyere on homemade bread and
take a crusty bite.  Sip new wine. Nothing ever tasted better.<BR></P>
<P>Maybe Chaplin didn&#146;t see all this, but he knew it was there.  Every
Saturday morning his cook, or his wife came to Vevey&#146;s market square where
farmers bring just-picked vegetables, apples or pears depending on the season,
and handmade cheese.  Fruity white wine from nearby slopes waits in stores
around the square.  Fresh bread and croissants are heaped in the windows of
nearby bakeries.  Buyers stock up and settle at an outdoor table for coffee and
pastry.  Vevey isn&#146;t funny at all.  It&#146;s French with good manners, and
respect for life&#146;s essentials.  This civilized mix of rural and urban,
lakes and mountains suited America&#146;s little tramp, from the top of his
derby right down to the worn-out soles of his enormous shoes.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Getting There:</B>  Although most major carriers fly directly to Geneva
from gateway cities, the best way to start a Swiss experience is on Swiss Air. 
Geneva&#146;s airport is friendly, and clean. Fast trains run from  there to
Vevey at least every hour.  Staying There:  Hotel des Trois Couronnes, 49 Rue d&#146;Italie,
right on Lake Geneva has high ceilings, brass beds and a magnificent view of
Lake Geneva.  The park with Charlie&#146;s statue is out the back door, through
the terrace and across the road.  Rates are from about 200 Swiss francs to 400. 
Another good spot is Hotel Du Lac, also on Rue d&#146;Italie with rates about
the same. Hotel de Famille by the railway station is less.  All prices include a
continental breakfast.<BR></P>
<P><B>Getting Around:</B>  Vevey, indeed all of Switzerland, has good, fast
public transportation.  The railway  station is in the middle of town and hotel
concierges have handy time tables.  There are also frequent  buses. You can rent
a car for the week or the day for trips into the mountain or  see the Vevey
Tourist  Board for group tours. Vevey&#146;s tourist board offers a variety of 
packages.<BR></P>
<P><B>What To See:</B>  To get an overview of the area, take a helicopter
flight on Glacier Air.  Rates vary  depending on the season and length of
flight. Owner Earnest Devoid loves his business so much he says, &#147;It doesn&#146;t
matter if someone bothers me for a few minutes so long as he&#146;s interested
in flying.&#148; Devoid frequently takes people who can&#146;t afford a ride
along with him on a transport just to give them a taste of flying.  Guests are
welcome, depending on the season, at the grape harvest or up in the Alps at a
chalet to watch and taste homemade cheese. Museum of every sort, including
miniature soldiers (in Morges) dot nearby  towns.<BR></P>
<P><B>When to Go:</B>  Anytime. In the winter ski packages are excellent; in
summer there&#146;s sightseeing and  mountain climbing and swimming.  Places to
Eat:  Besides good hotel restaurants, Vevey has Charly&#146;s Cafe for Asian
food and Fontana, an Italian restaurant on Rue de Centre, Amis on Rue des Jarden
and Bel-Air on Rue du Nord for fondues and raclettes (melting cheese spooned on
potatoes and vegetables, a Swiss national dish). Chex Aziz serves Tunisian food,
and small tea rooms or bakeries with tables and good Swiss coffee are
everywhere.<BR></P>
<P><I>- Kit Snedaker
</I></P>
