<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Edinburgh</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Edinburgh</FONT></H1>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">by Bosley Wilder</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<P><EM><B>&quot;Edina! Scotia's darling seat</B></EM></P>
<P><B><EM>all hail thy palaces and tow'rs,</EM></B></P>
<P> <B><EM>all hail thy palaces and tow'rs,</EM></B></P>
<P><B><EM>Where once beneath a monarch's feet</EM></B></P>
<P><B><EM>sat Legislation's sov'reign pow'rs!&quot;</EM></B><BR></P>
<P>Rain spattered against the windows of the Edinburgh Express heading out of
London's Victoria Station, but inside the train it was  pleasant and
comfortable.  The journey north that would take me into Scotland:  the land of
castles and refineries, someone had said.  Three and a half hours later, I was
met at Edinburgh's uncrowded Waverly Staion by friends, having enjoyed varied
views of sheep grazing, villages, and the shorelines of eastern England and
Scotland.  As we drove away from the station, I became keenly aware of tall,
serious-looking, dark granite houses and office buildings.  They looked as if
they had been constructed by tall, serious people.<BR></P>
<P>The following morning my host advised me to take a taxi downtown in order to
get my bearings and some maps, to help find my way around this gracious city of
750,000.  The cabbie was cooperative and friendly, and once I got my American
tongue around the directions in a way that a Scotsman could understand. we were
off to the Tourist Information Office.  As for his  half of a chat we had on the
way down, I dinna ken bahr-ely a word -- though this improved mightily through
the day, as my ear adjusted to the clipped pronunciation.<BR></P>
<P>In due time, armed with my map and other information, I found the Royal
Mile, which extends from the granite majesty of Edinburgh Castle to the Palace
of Holyroodhouse, the Queen's residence in the city.  Today the Royal Mile is
lined with shops and museums, and its cul-de-sacs contain such interesting sites
as the house where the first encyclopedia was printed, or the Poetry Society of
Edinburgh, which  houses a great collection of twentieth century poets in
Gaelic, Scots, and English.  There is John Knox's house, the People's Story
Museum, the High Kirk of St. Giles, and the Museum of  childhood (probably the
noisiest museum in the world!).  There is Camera Obscura, with its unique optic
views of the Castle grounds, and the Brass Rubbing Center -- too many
interesting places to mention.<BR></P>
<P>Edinburgh Castle, at the head of the Royal Mile, receives over a million
visitors a year, who come to view the ancient battlements -- some dating back to
the eleventh century -- and the Crown Jewels of Scotland.  The Palace of
Hollyrood House, at the other end of the Mile, offers a visit to the chamber
where Rizzi, Mary Queen of Scots' purported lover, was murdered -- the dried
bloodstains on the floor are reportedly his -- with a voyeur's peep to the room
where Queen Elizabeth II dines during the two weeks she spends in Edinburgh
during the summer.  There is also a massive ballroom, whose walls are lined with
portraits by Jacob de Viet; almost all are likenesses of Charles II, king from
1660 to to 1685, and renowned for many things though not for his modesty.  It
was Charles who rebuilt the Palace in its present form.<BR></P>
<P>Hollyrood Park, adjoining the Palace, retains 650 acres of lovely garden and
magnificent parkland, which makes its way from the gentle slopes of blooming
gorse and broom at the edge of the city, up into the steep hills to the sheer
rock of Salisbury Crags and the windswept summit of Arthur's Seat, a long
extinct volcano.  The Parkland is a greatly-loved walking and climbing place. 
It was in the nearby Pentland Hills that Robert Louis Stevenson frequently came
to do his writing.<BR></P>
<P>Having just three days to spend in the city, I had to make choices.  I had
taken an open-air, double-decker sightseeing bus my first day, and was glad I
did, for it gave me a basic grounding in attractions and logistics.  In the
remaining time I was able to visit The National Gallery of Scotland, whose
masterpieces of European art give Edinburgh its claim to being the &quot;Athens
of the North;&quot; the home of Robert Louis Stevenson, with a plaque of the
poem commemorating his street's lamplighter; and the impressive monument to
Scotland's greatest poet, Robert Burns, he of  &quot;My luve is like a red, red
rose...&quot;<BR></P>
<P>Time did not permit me to visit the Royal Observatory or the Botanical
Gardens, and I had to pass on an attraction called &quot;Prince Charlie's
Extravaganza.&quot; I also missed an exciting football (soccer) fray between the
Hibernians and the Midlothians, but was treated to an informal singing fest by a
Newcastle team on the express train returning to London.  The lads were cheerful
and entertaining, if none too sober, as they rendered their lyrics to &quot;the
wild bloomin' heather in the wild mountain time.&quot;  At their stop at
Newcastle-on-Tyne, one of them forgot to get off the train; later, as the doors
re-closed and the train finally started up, a straight, terse message came over
the loudspeaker:  &quot;We apologize for the delay at Newcastle, which was
caused by platform duties.&quot;  Merry Olde England!<BR></P>
<P>Edinburgh has recently been declared a World Heritage City by the Monuments
and Sites Council of UNESCO, an award that puts it in on a footing with the Taj
Mahal, the Pyramids, and the Imperial Forum in Rome.  During the month of
August, the city plays host to the now legendary Edinburgh International
Festival. Marking its fiftieth anniversary this year, this lively carnival of
performance art was started in 1946 as an official entertainment for troops and
refugees, a &quot;lightening of spirit&quot; after the dreadful events of World
War II.  The popular Fringe entertainment began as a volunteer effort by some
talented young people who, piggybacking at first on the coattails of the
official events, in time became a tradition in itself.  Today the Edinburgh
Festival and Fringe has enormous popularity.  This year 9,000 performers from
more than 36 countries are expected during the 23-day festivities from August
11-31, including hundreds of well-known writers, actors, and artists.<BR></P>
<P>There is music, art, theatre, and of course the well-known Film Festival,
this year to concentrate on Italian films and filmmakers.  There is the Poetry
Festival, an international event run from the Scottish Poetry Library.  The &quot;Tattoo&quot;
involves the military bands playing on the esplanade of the Castle.  Those
interested in what is truly an exciting, world-famous event are being advised
that bookings are tight; it is not too early to reserve lodging for NEXT year's
festival. <BR></P>
<P>Prior to this visit, as I citizen of the world I had been ignorant of how
many of the world's acclaimed scientists have been produced by Scotland!  To
name just a few: Alexander Graham Bell, James Watt, William Simpson, who
discovered chloroform(quite by accident, it is said.)  Other famed  Edinburgh
figures include Mr. Brodie, a respected businessman by day, who burgled his
peers by night, giving rise to Robert Louis Stephenson's well-known novelette,
Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.  And of course there is Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, without
whom there would be no Sherlock Holmes.<BR></P>
<P>My last evening in town, friends drove me into nearby Leith, the Port of
Edinburgh about a mile and a half from City Centre.  There we stopped off at the
club room of the Scotch Malt Whiskey Society, a must for those with special
interest in fine malt whiskies.  As every good Scotsman knows, the taste of pure
single malt scotch whiskey is quite unlike that of grain whiskies.  The original
recipe for this essence of taste--having to do with peatings--is said to have
been introduced by the monks as early as the 12th century.  Certainly it has
been good business for Scotland since 1678.  We sampled some twenty- year old
stuff that was superb. <BR></P>
<P>For a unique way to spend next year's New Year's celebration, singing Robert
Burns's &quot;Auld Lang Syne&quot; right where it was written, consider the
Hogmanay celebrations of Edinburgh, a city that has gained the reputation for
hosting the &quot;Biggest New Year Party in Europe.&quot;  This year the
entertainment is scheduled to include the traditional Torchlight Procession,
Hogmanay Carnival and Street Party, and many more events for the whole family,
from December 30, 1996 - January l, 1997.  And then there is always the essence
of Scottish tradition in this festival city: the Piping in the Haggis, on Burns'
night, January 12.  &#164;<BR></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-1">Articles appearing on this page are &copy;1996
Personal Programs and/or the contributor.  All rights reserved.  Opinions
expressed are those of the writer(s). Travel information is by nature subject to
frequent change; travelers should always verify information prior to relying
upon it.  Personal Programs does not represent and does not endorse products,
companies, or offers referenced on this page, and cannot be responsible for
errors, changes, or omissions.  Please send comments to Personal Programs at
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A></FONT>. </P>
<HR>
