<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Pedaling Paris</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Pedaling Paris</FONT></H1>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">by Jerri Clark Kirby</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<P>The immediate thought of pedaling a bicycle around the frenzied streets of 
the heart of Paris sounds insane.  It's not. It's probably safer than walking,
and is a lot faster.  Biking liberates you to cover distances more quickly while
allowing you to travel streets that are difficult or impossible in an
automobile.  And you can park your bike almost anywhere!<BR></P>
<P>Bike-tour operators in Paris work hard to ensure the safety of participants.
 They offer well-maintained bicycles, encourage the use of helmets, (which are
not required by law but are recommended), and present thorough lessons  in which
they familiarize participants with the bikes and teach proper operation.  And
there is safety in numbers:  a few cyclists riding together have a noticeable
presence on the streets, which accords them all the needed respect.<BR></P>
<P>The guides know Paris inside and out.  They live in the Paris area and have
biked the city many, many times. They comment on the historical  sites, stop for
good photos, fill you in on neighborhood characteristics.  Normally, a tour
covers about 10 miles in about 3 to 4 hours. There are three tour companies who
specialize in English commentary:  Paris Bike, Paris Velo and Paris a Velo. 
Each company has a variety of interesting itineraries which include pedaling by
some of the more renowned sites such at the Eiffel Tower and Notre-Dame
Cathedral, with forays into areas along the St-Martin canal or up to the Butte
aux Calles.  Routes are carefully laid out to avoid heavy traffic on main
thoroughfares. As you cycle along these &quot;backroads,&quot; you gain an
insider's peek into the homes of the Parisians; you see where they shop; where
the kids play; where they walk their dogs; where they go to market; and where
they stroll and chat with others on warm summer evenings.<BR></P>
<P>Each of these three companies also offers night excursions to view
illuminated monuments; the bicycles have lights and, if you really are a biking
enthusiast with good stamina, you can take a 40-mile tour to Versailles which
includes a castle visit during the six-hour tour.  You don't have to be a
professional bike rider; you just need a reasonable level of physical fitness
and a sense of adventure.<BR></P>
<P>Some friends just returned home from Paris, having taken Paris Velo's <I>La
Rive Gauche</I> (Left Bank) tour, and they were very excited about their
new-found method of getting around this busy city.  Before setting off, each
person in the group (totaling five including the guide),  was outfitted with a
bike and helmet. After receiving lessons in how to operate everything and a
basic itinerary, they were off!  They rode past a highly ornate mosque and up a
narrow street called rue Lacepede to place de la Contrescarpe, quaint with a new
fountain.  On to rue Mouffetard, an ancient Roman road which was actually the
main road in southern Paris until the 19th century.  Up a gentle hill to the
Pantheon, the highest point on the Left Bank. The group stopped for a commentary
about the commanding edifice in the shape of a Greek cross, topped by a huge
dome.  At this point, everyone in the group was used to their bikes, at ease
riding in a group, and eager for more.<BR></P>
<P>They rolled on down rue Soufflot to the Luxembourg Garden and off onto rue
Garanciere, a quiet street lined with <I>h&ocirc;tel particuliers</I>.  The
next stop was place St-Sulpice, a lovely square with a fountain facing the
church of the same name.  A few photos were snapped, and then the group
zig-zagged through the St-Germaine-des-Pres area, once a center of international
Bohemian life and most picturesque.  Then on along the quays of the Seine,
taking in the Louvre on the other side of the river and the Musee d'Orsay on the
bikers' side.  They rolled along the long, straight rue de l'Universite, passing
by the Assembl&eacute;e National and the Invalides garden, before arriving at
the base of the Eiffel Tower.  Someone  had a flat tire and  the tour guide put
on another hat: that of mechanic.  He fixed the flat and off they went to
explore the 15th arrondissement, a residential neighborhood of parks, open-air
markets, quiet streets and  picturesque architecture.  Rambling back to the
starting point, they passed by Georges Brassens park, over a short cycling lane
above the TGV train tracks, the place Denfert-Rochereau and Montsouris park;
then, the challenge of a 200 foot climb up to the Butte aux Cailles. The group
took its time and no one had a problem, thanks to the efficiently-geared bikes. 
The effort was rewarding - the Butte has retained an atmosphere of a country
village, complete with apple trees and cobblestones.<BR></P>
<P>Returning to the Paris Velo bike station, the group reviewed their 11-mile,
3-hour trek, gathering around a large map to note favorite places and make
recommendations to the guide for future trips.  My friends signed up for yet
another tour the next day; they swear this is the only way to see Paris up
close.  I certainly plan to try it on my next visit! &#164;</P>
<H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Some Parisian Bicycle Tour Operators:</FONT></H3>
<P><B>&#183; Paris Bike, </B>83, rue Daguerre, 75014 Paris; TEL: 43-20-67-60,
FAX: 43-20-71-93; Two-hour tour: FF150; 4-hour tour FF245; Chateau de Versailles
FF400 (includes entry to Versailles)</P>
<P><B>&#183; Paris Velo, </B>2 rue du Fer-a-Moulin, 75002 Paris; TEL:
43-37-59-22; FAX: 47-07-67-45; 3-hour tour:  FF150; Nighttime Tour: FF180</P>
<P><B>&#183; Paris a Velo, </B>9 rue Jacques-Coeur, 75004 Paris; TEL:
48-87-60-01; FAX: 48-87-61-01; 3-hour tour FF150; Nighttime Tour FF170</P>
<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Bike Tour France</FONT></H2>
<H4><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Carefully Designed Independent Tours for the Loire
Valley</FONT></H4>
<P><BR></P>
<P>For cross-country bicycling, fully escorted tours can offer the advantages
of baggage transport and prearranged meals &amp; lodging, but they also lock you
into a particular schedule and route.  Setting out entirely on your own gives
you freedom, but the missed opportunities and unexpected difficulties that can
mar a poorly planned journey may turn your &quot;dream trip&quot; into a bad
memory.  <BR></P>
<P>If your interest is in bicycling France's beautiful Loire Valley, a company
called <STRONG>Bike Tour France</STRONG> offers a unique service that combines
the best of both worlds:  complete a questionnaire on your trip's basic
parameters (when, how long, number of cyclists) and your own preferences (how
much riding per day, particular interests, etc.), and they will produce a
customized &quot;self-drive&quot; itinerary for you, complete with daily travel
routes, detailed maps of riding terrain and local attractions, affordable hotel
recommendations, and an audio cassette guide to listen to <I>en route</I>.  The
kit also includes a translated glossary of French bicycle terms, a summary of
French traffic laws as they pertain to cyclists, and a wealth of practical
advice drawn from owner Jerry H. Simpson's more than twenty years' experience
bicycling France.  For all of this, the charge is just $37.50 per cycling day
for any number of travelers, with a minimum of 5 days.  All of their tours begin
and end in Blois and include directions on getting to Blois via rail from the
major Paris airports.  If you wish to rent a bike in France rather than bringing
your own, they can also provide you with advance reservation forms so that your
rental is set up and waiting for you upon your arrival in Blois.  For more
information or to request an itinerary questionnaire, contact <B>Bike Tour
France at 5523 Wedgewood Drive, Charlotte NC 28210-2432; telephone
1-704-527-0955. </B><BR></P>
<P>Mr. Simpson is also the author of a guidebook in the Active Travel series,
<I>Cycling France</I>.  The book offers maps, summaries of terrain, and
descriptions of what you can see and do along the way on some of France's best
cycling routes, along with information on planning, packing, and transporting
your bike, and is illustrated with 60 photos and 140 maps.  Order <I>Cycling
France</I> for $12.95 from <B>Bicycle Books, Inc., PO Box 2038, Mill Valley CA
94942; 1-800-468-8233. </B></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">--  Editor</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
