<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - News &amp; Gossip  /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Miss Elainey's Notes</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>News &amp; Gossip on the European Front</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><B>And you thought <I>your</I> bath remodel was expensive...</B> the City
Council of <B>Bath, England</B>, has drawn up a plan to restore the town&#146;s
famous Roman baths to full working condition, with the plumbers&#146; bill
expected to top $2 million.  They&#146;ve asked the English Heritage foundation
to cover half the cost and are hunting about for the rest.  As coroporate
sponsorships are so much in vogue these days, we wonder if they&#146;ve thought
of talking with a <B>soapmaker</B>...  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Pounds of flesh...</B> if you&#146;re Britain-bound, buy everything but
your tea-and-crumpets over here before you get on the plane.  A sudden <B>upward
gust</B> has made the pound sterling among the priciest of currencies, with spot
rates hitting $1.75-$1.80 in some locations.  The more pre-pay options you can
take advantage of&#151;dollar-for-pound hotel packages, transit cards, museum
passes, etc.&#151; the better off you&#146;ll be.  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Record-Breaking Year:</B>  1996 is expected to set a new all-time record
for <B>U.S visitors to Europe</B>, according to the European Trade Commission,
with a whopping nine million of us estimated to have headed over this year. 
<I>(A figure Miss Elainey can confirm, as they were all in front of her at the
Louvre admission queue.) </I> The projection is for twelve million annually by
2000, an increase of 750,000 per year..   
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Personal security for visitors</B> is becoming a mini-industry in
Russia, with concern heightened following the gangster-style shooting of an
American businessman in <B>Moscow</B>.  At least one tour company employs armed
guards to accompany travelers on long rail journeys, and several hotels have
installed metal detectors in lobby entrances.  While most experts say that
Russia can still be visited safely, independent travel is not recommended and
should be undertaken only with considerable care.  Obtaining taxis only through
your hotel, and engaging a reliable translator/bodyguard before venturing beyond
the prominent tourist areas, are among the suggested precautions.  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Finally putting right</B> a much older bit of crime, the English have
returned the legendary <B>Stone of Scone</B> to its rightful place in Scotland&#151;700
years after King Edward swiped it.  Scotland&#146;s ancient kings were crowned
on the stone, which until now has rested beneath the Coronation Chair in <B>Westminster
Abbey</B>.  This past November 30&#151;the feast day of Scotland&#146;s patron
saint St. Andrew&#151;it was shipped north for a solemn installation in
Edinburgh Castle, where it may now be viewed.  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Expect to hear a <I>lot</I> about duty-free shopping</B> on your next
trip.  The Tax Free World Association, a trade group devoted to promoting
duty-free sales, is mounting a publicity drive meant to enlist travelers in the
campaign to save duty-free.  According to a decree of the European Commission
(EC), all duty-free traffic in Europe is to be <B>abolished in 1999</B>.  EC
officials believe that duty-free sales are incompatible with the goal of a
single unified market.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Visitors may be somewhat more appreciative</B> of EC &#147;meddling&#148;
in another area: Europe&#146;s electric standards body, called Cenelac, is being
prodded to complete a plan for reducing the six different types of electrical
plugs found in Europe to <B>a single design</B>, eliminating the need for
travelers to carry a sackful of adapters.  But despite years of meetings,
Cenelac has been unable to settle the matter; part of the problem is that
Cenelac itself is made up of representatives from the various regional
electrical industries&#151;each of whom hopes to avoid substantial conversion
costs by having its current design picked as the standard. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Edgy cigarette smokers</B>, increasingly finding themselves on long-haul
flights with the smoking section eliminated, can hope that an <B>Air France</B>
experiment in compromise works out.  On certain flights to Asia, the French
carrier now bans smoking in <I>all</I> of the seating rows, but provides a
small, powerfully ventilated stand-up area in each cabin where a few smokers at
a time can settle nicotine jitters&#151;without inflicting fumes on the crew or
other passengers.  So far, both smokers and non-smokers have reportedly been
pleased with the arrangement.  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Milan&#146;s Malpensa airport</B> will become an international hub soon,
adding scheduled Alitalia flights to its current charter traffic.  The move is
necessitated by frequent fog and <B>severe overcrowding</B> at Milan Linate.  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>French National Railways</B> are launching a new double-decker train on
the high-speed <B>TGV</B> run between Paris and Lyon.  The new cars will
greatly increase the number of <B>available seats</B>, easing capacity problems
that have cropped up on the very popular route. 
</P>
<HR>
