<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - European Christmas  /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe / France /
England / Germany / Recipies</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>European Christmas</H2>
<P><BR><I>by Jerri Clark Kirby</I></P>
<P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Joyeaux Noel: France</FONT></I></B>
<BR> In France, Christmas begins as an all night party.  After attending
Midnight Mass on Christmas Eve, the French return home for a huge meal, with
numerous courses.  The menu varies from one region to another, in keeping with
local traditions, but often begins with oysters and ends with Buche de Noel, a
cake  shaped like a Yule log. After the meal, gifts are exchanged.  No one goes
to bed  until almost dawn and Christmas Day is spent resting and eating.  Most
homes display a Nativity scene, or &quot;creche,&quot; complete with figurines
called &quot;santons,&quot; (little saints).  Most are made by craftsmen in
southern France and the  molds are passed down from generation to generation. 
Represented are the Holy family, shepherds and wisemen as well as local
dignitaries and characters.  <BR></P>
<P>One tradition is to leave the Christ child figurine out of the manger until
everyone returns home from Midnight Mass. The children are then told &quot;le
petite Jesus&quot; has left the gifts.  Other homes are visited by &quot;Pere
Noel&quot; and his partner, &quot;Pere Fouettard.&quot;    Pere Fouettard
reminds Pere Noel of just how well the children behaved during the  year.  If
they were naughty, they will be visited by Pere Fouettard who brings coal and 
spanks them with sticks.  In some parts of France, Pere Noel brings small gifts
on St. Nicholas Eve, December 6th, and returns on Christmas Eve. Generally,
adults wait until New Year's Day to exchange gifts. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Germany: Christmas Tradition</FONT></I></B> 
<BR>Neighboring Germany is strong in Christmas traditions, yet not everyone is
even aware that the Yule log and the Christmas tree have German origins, or that
Santa's visits combine two old German customs.  The  Christmas hymn, &quot;Silent
Night,&quot; was written in German by  priest and first published in Leipzig. 
In ancient times, December 25th marked the festival of Jul, celebrated by 
Germanic tribes to honor the sun god Fryr.  This marked the winter solstice, the
time of year when the sun reaches its lowest point. These Jul ceremonies
included the decorating of homes with evergreen, and the burning of special
logs.   In the fourth century, to stamp its magnificence on this pagan
celebration, the Christian church advanced  its holiday, changing the
celebration of the birth of  Christ from January 6th, Epiphany, to December
25th.  German folklore tells that the tradition of the Christmas tree may have
been further developed by  St. Boniface in his conversion of Germanic pagans in
the fourth century.  He is said to have dedicated a fir  tree to the Christ
child as a substitute for the Sacred Oak of Woden.  Martin Luther, the German
reformer, added candles to his Christmas fir,  Tannenbaum, in the 16th entury. 
Gilded apples, nuts and paper streamers in  various colors were later ornaments.
 <BR></P>
<P>During the 18th  and 19th centuries, the  holiday tradition of a decorated,
candle-lit tree, gradually spread outside of   Germany, first to England and on
to the New World with the arrival of German  immigrants.  For  German children,
St. Nicholas Day is when a tall white-bearded figure in a sheepskin coat and
crown, or  bishop's hat, goes from home to home rewarding good children with
presents and bad children with lumps  of coal.  Early December is also when the
Christkindlsmarkt, or traditional  Christmas fairs, get under way in  many
locations throughout Germany.  Vendors set up stalls in public squares;
Christmas decorations are  hung everywhere and so begins several weeks of music,
shopping, seasonal food and holiday cheer.  The oldest of these fairs is the 600
year old fair in Munich. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><I>Merrie Olde England</I></FONT></B>  
<BR>England has celebrated the merriest of Christmases since feudal days, when
the halls of grand castles resounded  with merrymaking and feasting.  Heralding
the birth of Christ were Yule logs, plum puddings, boar's head  and caroling. 
Today's England lacks the huge fireplaces for the Yule log, but Christmas
continues to be a  joyful time, with beautiful, elaborate religious ceremonies,
family reunions and happy celebration. Carol  singing at home and at church is a
part of the tradition;  Christmas card sending began in England in the  1840's. 
  On Christmas Eve, stockings are hung above the fireplace or bed, so that
Father Christmas can fill them.  After the children go to sleep, adults decorate
a lush tree and the home with mistletoe, holly and ornaments.  Christmas dinner
is usually served in the early afternoon and includes turkey, roast potatoes, 
mince pie,  and plum pudding served with flaming brandy.  Placed next to each
plate is a Christmas cracker.  Each person pulls the cracker, which gives a &quot;bang&quot;
as it is opened; inside are a paper hat, plastic toy, and message for the
current year.  Everyone wears their paper hats for the rest of the meal.    Many
put gifts of jewelry, money or other fine things into the crackers.   
<BR></P>
<P>At 3:00 pm, the Queen gives her annual message. She discussed the prior
year, plans for the future and positive things about the royal family.  The rest
of the day is spent watching old movies on tv or ice skating on one of the many
frozen ponds in England.  December 26th is Boxing Day, originally a day for the
wealthy to wait on their servants.  Now, it is an extension of Christmas and
another day for the British to party with their friends and family.  &#164;    
If you'd like to experience Christmas in Europe, many companies are offering
tours. One is INTRAV, offering trips including Christmas &amp; New Year's in
Rome, Paris and London;  A &quot;Silent Night&quot; Christmas and New Year's:
Montreux, Salzburg and Vienna.  For information on these trips, which offer the
best of Europe at Christmas and New Year's, call 1 800-456-8100.	</P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Two European Christmas Recipies</I></H2>
<P><I> -- Jerri Clark Kirby</I><BR></P>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR="#FFFF00">Buche de Noel</FONT></B><BR>
<B>Ingredients:	</B>3 eggs, 1 cup sugar, 1-1/2 tsp. vanilla, 1-1/4 cup flour, 2
tsp. baking powder, 1/4 tsp. salt, 1/2 cup milk, 1 tsp. butter  <BR></P>
<P><B>Directions:</B> Preheat oven to 400oF. Grease a 14 x 20&quot;  pan (3/4&quot;);
cover with wax paper.  Grease and flour the wax paper lightly. Beat eggs in a
deep bowl until they are  pale yellow (about 4 minutes). Add the sugar
gradually; beat well after each addition. Add vanilla.   Measure the flour
without sifting.  Add the baking powder and salt.  Mix well, heat milk and stir
in the butter.  Gently fold dry ingredients into the egg/sugar mix.  Do not beat
or mix.  Add hot milk and butter until the liquid is absorbed.  Turn the batter
into the prepared pan and spread evenly.  Bake for 15 minutes until golden
brown.  Remove from oven ;  cut off the crusty ends.  (keep them for decorative
knots) .  <BR></P>
<P>Invert pan, put cake on a linen towel dusted with powdered sugar.  Roll up
the cake with the towel. Let cool for 15 minutes. Unroll and spread with jam or
butter cream frosting to within 1/2&quot; from the edge. Roll the cake again and
cover with towel.  Roll up the crust-off ends to form the knots. Attach them to
the log using toothpicks. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Frosting:</FONT></I></B>	</P>
<P>Ingredienst: 1/4 cup butter, softened; 2 cups powdered sugar; 2 tbs. cocoa
powder, 1/2 tsp. vanilla; 1 tbs. strong coffee, cold. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Preparation:</B> Cream the butter; mix sugar with cocoa; add vanilla to
butter and mix sugar and  coffee in. Ice the Buche and the knots, giving the
appearance of tree bark. For the  ends of the log, use the back of a spoon to
form circles. Decorate with icing in the  form of leaves and berries. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B><FONT SIZE="+3">St. Stephen's Pudding</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P><B>Ingredients:</B>  4 oz bread crumbs; 2 oz self-rising flour, sifted; 2
oz soft brown sugar; 3 oz shredded suet; pinch of salt; 4 oz seedless raisins; 2
medium apples;  grated rind of a lemon; one egg, 3 Tbs. milk.      
<BR></P>
<P><B>Preparation:</B>  In a large mixing bowl combine all dry ingredients;
add raisins, apples (peeled and grated) and the grated lemon rind. Stir
thoroughly to combine everything well. Now beat the egg  into the milk and stir
everything together.  Pack the mixture into a greased,  2 pint pudding pan.
Cover tightly with a sheet of grease-proof paper and then a sheet of  foil.
Steam the pudding for 2 hours; serve with custard sauce or brandy butter.   &#164;</P>
<HR>
