<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Miss Elainey's Notes
/ European Travel News / Russia / Italy / Virgin Atlantic / American Airlines /
Robert Crandall / Richard Branson / travel agent discounts / hotel ratings /
cigarettes / airlines / taxes / State Department</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<H2>Miss Elainey's Notes</H2>
<P><BR><I><B>News &amp; Gossip on the European Travel Front</B></I><BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Gambling Man:</FONT></B>  American Airlines
chairman Robert Crandall, in a tussle with Virgin Atlantic over AA's bid for a
partnership with British Airways, has offered to personally bet Virgin's founder
Richard Branson &#163;100,000 that average U.S./London airfares would fall if
the alliance is approved.  Branson, who like Crandall is a colorful &amp;
controversial figure in the industry, claims the AA/BA deal would be
anticompetitive and is trying to have it blocked by regulators. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">To Russia with Starbucks:</FONT></B>  Magadan
Airlines, a one-time subsidiary of Russia's Aeroflot, has requested permission
to begin offering roundtrip services to Russia from Seattle and Anchorage.  The
airline, which currently runs charters and scheduled services outside the U.S.,
needs approval from the Deptartment of Transportation to begin operating here. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">No Free Lunch:</FONT></B>  Be wary of &quot;card
mills&quot; offering bogus travel agent credentials for a fee.  While these
companies claim you'll get huge travel discounts just by presenting their card&#151;usually
purchased for about $500&#151;in fact the travel industry is losing patience
with the proliferation of bargain-seeking &quot;agents&quot; and is starting to
clamp down.  Delta and Hertz, among others, have begun limiting trade discounts
to valid holders of IATAN cards, which can only be obtained by booking
significant amounts of air travel through the computerized airline reservation
services. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Hail Padania:</FONT></B>  Northern Italians,
frustrated with a perceived lack of representation in the Rome-dominated
national administration, have symbolically declared themselves an independent
country.  The new &quot;nation&quot; of <I>Padania</I>&#151;which is more or
less everything north of the Po River and is headquartered in Venice&#151;has no
plans to actually govern or seek recognition, but can be expected to tweak Roman
noses now and then with the occasional ceremony or press release. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Is Fare Tax a Fair Tax?</FONT></B>  U.S. airlines
are battling over how airline tickets ought to be taxed.  Presently, a straight
10% levy is applied to the amount of fare paid; large airlines argue that this
lets low-fare operators get by with a smaller contribution to the air traffic
infrastructure, though their planes cost as much to control and land as any
other.  They'd like to see the tax calculated on miles traveled and number of
seats, without regard to the fare.  But discounters prefer the current system
and say the biggies are just trying to dodge competition by forcing the lowest
fares to  go up.  Congress will have to decide one way or the other; the current
tax &amp; the rules that govern it expire December 31. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Fewer Yankee Elbows: </FONT></B> Although the
number of Americans traveling to Western Europe each year continues to rise, we
make up a smaller percentage of the tourists you'll bump elbows with over there
than we did a decade ago.  With increased international travel from Asia, the
continuing eager flood of Eastern Europeans, and improving economies for Western
Europeans themselves, you're apt to hear &quot;Excuse me, you're blocking my
picture&quot; in more languages than ever before. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">I'll See Your Two Crowns And Raise You Three
Stars...</FONT></B>  Britain is set to announce a new hotel rating system, which
the English Tourist Board hopes will replace the often inconsistent mix of
crowns and/or stars by which lodgings are labeled.  No details of the new
voluntary system have been offered, but it is expected to go into place before
next year's high season. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">I Demand To See The Consul &#151; Somewhere!</FONT></B>
 If you run into trouble in Zurich, Bordeaux, Poznan, Bilbao, or a host of other
cities around the world, don't be surprised to learn that the American Consul is
out of town&#151;permanently.  Cond&eacute; Nast Traveler reports that federal
budget cutting has left State Department posts as little more than an answering
machines where once small offices were fielded.  Cities that avoided the cut at
the last minute included Florence and Edinburgh. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Marlboro Country:</FONT></B> Although smoking in
general is declining around Europe, it remains more prevalent in some countries
than others.  Greece tops the list with an average of 140 packs consumed per
year per family; Swedes puff the fewest with the consumption rate about 49
packs.  The most costly cigarettes are in Denmark ($4.85), which also has the
highest tobacco tax (83% of the retail price).  Smokers get by cheapest in Spain
($1.05 per pack) and Portugal ($1.85).  And the most popular brand Europe-wide? 
Same as it is here, Philip Morris' Marlboro. 
<BR></P>
<P><I>Miss Elainey is happy to credit The European as an invaluable source of
political, financial, and cultural news from Europe.  The weekly newspaper is
available by subscription in the U.S.: call 800-875-2997 (In Canada
201-627-5872).
</I></P>
<HR>
