<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Miss Elainey's Notes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Miss Elainey&#146;s Notes</H2>
<P><I><B>News and gossip on the European front</B></I><BR></P>
<P>&#183; Easier trips from <B>London Heathrow</B> into the city are at last
on the way.  A new fast rail link, due in June 1998,  will slash the journey
time from the current 45 minutes to just over a quarter-hour.  Paddington
Station, near Hyde Park, will be the destination.  In the meantime, expanded
operations by Airbus will provide some immediate improvement: the coach service,
about $9 each way, now stops at all four Heathrow terminals and has increased
the number of pickup/dropoff points in London from 28 to more than 80.<BR>  
</P>
<P>&#183; The <B>Netherlands</B>&#146; soft-drug tolerance policy may be on
the ropes.  Although the Dutch government still defends the approach, EU
neighbors are complaining that today&#146;s reduced border controls force other
countries to share in Amsterdam&#146;s quasi legal marijuana market, whether
they like it or not -- and most of them don&#146;t.  Some polls show that Dutch
public opinion is shifting on the issue, too.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Hopes for renewed travel and tourism in the <B>Balkans</B> continue
to grow.  Air services to Belgrade were scheduled to resume in July, with
British Airways offering three flights a week to the Serbian capital.  And
Thomas Cook reports that trial runs of passenger trains to <B>Sarajevo</B> have
taken place, though regularly scheduled services aren&#146;t yet available.   
<BR>
</P>
<P>&#183; Designs for the new <B>Euro</B> currency have been selected.  The
winning paper design was created by a team of Barcelona designers, while the 1
Euro coin came from a freelance artist in Frankfurt.  The money, to be
introduced in 1999, is intended to be valid currency in all EU countries,
eliminating exchange rate complications.  Controversy still surrounds the
project, however, and it&#146;s not yet clear whether it will be implemented on
schedule by all members.   
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A popular clamor has persuaded British Telecom to restore some 15,000
of the <B>classic red phone booths</B>, with their original 1930s design, to
locations across <B>England</B>.  In a compromise of past &amp; present, the
old booths feature new phones which can accept your credit or phone card.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Global warming has ski operators in the <B>Alps</B> worrying about a
profit meltdown.  Experts think gradually rising temperatures may be responsible
for declining snowpacks and retreating glaciers.  Low-level resorts in
particular have had trouble making money in a short winter season, and some
climatologists predict shorter seasons to come.  Not everyone agrees; the
director of the Austrian Tourist Board in Tyrol calls the fears &#147;nonsense&#148;
and cites competition from other activities as a more urgent concern.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; In a gaffe that has travel agents chuckling (albeit grimly), <B>Delta</B>&#146;s
Sky magazine offered &#147;agent&#146;s take&#148; as a recent crossword puzzle
clue; the correct response was &#147;tenth.&#148;  It was Delta, you may recall,
who launched last year&#146;s across the-board cut in agents&#146; commissions,
which now fall well short of 10% on many tickets.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>EuroDisney</B> is finally making money.  The theme park reported
a net profit of $29 million for the third fiscal quarter of this year. 
High-speed rail access from <B>Britain</B> via Eurostar is credited with some
of the improvement.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Spain</B> is moving ahead with a new fast rail service between
<B>Madrid</B> and <B>Barcelona</B>.  The $8 billion system, which could cut
travel time between the two cities from 6 hours to 3, may be constructed as
early as 2002.  Meanwhile, Italy is once again looking at plans to bridge the
Italian mainland to Sicily.  Sky-high costs, due in part to the engineering
demands of so large a bridge in an earthquake-prone region, have scuttled the
idea more than once in the past; but the Public Works Minister, citing a new
feasibility study, has put the project back on the table. 
</P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><I>Miss Elainey is happy to credit <B>The European</B> as
an invaluable source of political, financial, and cultural news from Europe. 
The weekly newspaper is available by subscription in the U.S.: call <B>800-875-2997</B>
(In Canada 201-627-5872).
</I></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-2">Articles appearing on this page are &copy;1996
Personal Programs and/or the contributor.   All rights reserved.   Opinions
expressed are those of the writer(s).  Travel information is by nature subject
to frequent change; travelers should always verify information prior to relying
upon it.   Personal Programs does not represent and does not endorse products,
companies, or offers referenced on this page, and cannot be responsible for
errors, changes, or omissions.   Please send comments to Personal Programs at
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A></FONT>.  </P>
