<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Contents / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif" WIDTH="419" HEIGHT="54">
<HR>
<P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Readers Write</FONT></I></B><BR></P>
<H2>When in Rome</H2>
<P><BR><I>by Kevin Ford</I></P>
<P></P>
<P>Shortly after I moved to Rome, in fact the first available moment, I visited
some of the most spectacular constructions ever built.  I walked around the
Coliseum, Arch of Constantine, the Foro Romano, San Pietro, and Santa
Pudenziana.  So, yes, I did see all these monuments, but at the same time I
didn't see anything.   
</P>
<P>My purpose of moving to Rome is to study, and the weekend after I arrived I
started classes.  One of the first classes I attended was Medieval Art and
Architecture and the professor began the class with the Arch of Constantine. 
This is the point when I realized I knew nothing.  Just visiting the sites in
Roma without knowledge of the historical background and/or artistical
representations used during the period of construction is almost pointless.  The
Arch of Constantine is a marvelous piece of work as soon as its construction is
explained.  If you are just looking at the arch a person can easily ascertain
what it was for.  The Arch of Constantine is a triumphal arch erected in 313 AD
upon Constantine's victory into Rome, and its symbolic placement at the bottom
of via di San Gregorio, which led to the Senate.  This is what the untrained eye
will see.
</P>
<P>The trained eye&#151;not to claim that after a total of four classes mine is
trained&#151;will notice all the constructions on the arch and their
significance for that period.  The round reliefs and the rectangular plaques on
the arch were actually taken from earlier imperial monuments and mounted on the
arch, which is why the reliefs, plaques and friezes all look like different
styles, they are.  However, the friezes on each side of the Arch of Constantine
are products of sculptors during Constantine's reign.  When looked at closely
you will see that the reliefs and friezes on the arch are symbols of
Constantine's power.  Due to the illiteracy of the people during the period the
mosaics, frescos, and friezes could relay the pertinent information to the
uneducated lay people, a form of propaganda.  It is also generally recognized
that Constantine was a Christian, thus, he legalized Christianity and
subsequently churches were constructed. 
</P>
<P>One of the early churches which remains today is Santa Pudenziana, built
around 400 AD.  In most churches, which had a standard architectural
construction for the period, the apses were decorated with elaborate mosaics. 
As I stated earlier the mosaics were also used as a form of communication to the
lay people.  These mosaics usually represented a specific story or scene from
the Bible.  The mosaic in Santa Pudenziana mainly represents Christ handing his
teachings to Peter and Paul, but that is not the only scene being represented. 
The background, placement of Christ and the others, and eventually the rest of
the items in the mosaic can be read, to the lay people of the time, of Christ as
the ultimate ruler and teacher of all.  Unfortunately, to a person who comes off
the street in to Santa Pudenziana today without prior knowledge of the imagery
and symbols used during the period, all  this might go unnoticed and a very
important aspect of the church has been missed.  </P>
<P>This is a common problem in Roma.  But there is a solution.  When traveling
anywhere where you plan on seeing major historical sights, begin by joining a
professionally-led tour.  If you prefer to go by yourself, precede your visit by
reading about the sites that you will see; choose books that concentrate on the
period around the construction of the sites.  Most books will use examples of
major constructions in defense of the author's argument; at the same time the
books will cover standard imagery and symbols used by artists of the time,
giving you a good background to the style of the period and enhancing your
general interpretive abilities.  You will also notice a growing interest in the
material you are reading and an increasing desire to view the constructions in
person.  Although I've concentrated on references to Rome, I believe this can be
useful advice for anywhere.  But to reference Rome one more time: it is a city
that has survived through more than 2000 years of history and every time you
change position there is a high probability that the next construction or
monument you encounter will be built during an entirely different period,
therefore it is extremely beneficial to have some knowledge about the different
types and styles of art and architecture.  This will undoubtedly aid you while
walking through the cobblestoned streets of Roma and subsequently make your
visit that much more enjoyable.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
