<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>The Channel Islands</H1>
<P><I>by Spencer Pryor</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>&quot;Little pieces of France, fallen into the sea and swept up by
England&quot;</I></B></P>
<P><I>- Victor Hugo</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Famous French author Victor Hugo certainly knew what he was talking about
when he described the Channel Islands thus. At just eight miles from France at
their nearest point and over 100 miles from England this group of small islands
has a unique culture and spirit of independence not seen in many larger
countries.<BR></P>
<P>Most tourists make their first landing in the islands on the largest island,
Jersey, which at just over 45 square miles, contains the only large airport in
the group. The main problem with Jersey is that it's a little overpopulated with
84,000 people squeezed into those 45 square miles. However most people live in
the southern part of the island and there are plenty of good walks and scenery
along the coasts of the island.<BR> </P>
<P>As with most European seaside resorts, Jersey (and to a lesser extent the
other islands) is geared up to mass package tourism, albeit at the nicer family
end of the market. It's easily possible for the independent traveller to get
accommodation at fairly short notice, from humble but good B&amp;Bs to five star
luxury at the Hotel L'Horizon or The Longueville Manor Hotel. Jersey Tourism
runs a computerised 'bed bank' scheme from their offices in St. Helier, the
island's capital, which can fix you up with accommodation for a charge of about
$1.50. The only time that it's difficult to get accommodation in the island is
usually in August, when there's a large influx of French tourists, and the
island's premier carnival 'The Battle of Flowers' is in full swing.<BR></P>
<P>The island's capital St. Helier, which contains around half the island's
population is, it has to be said, not the prettiest town in Europe! However,
steps are being taken to rectify this, and the small area in the hub of the town
centered on the cobbled Royal Square is reminiscent of a French provincial town.
It was in this square that the last battle between France and England took place
on British soil in 1781 when the French tried capturing the island. After having
made their way to the capital they were defeated in a pitched battle right on
the steps of the island's Parliamentary chamber and Royal Court, which forms one
side of the square. These buildings date from 1309, although they have been
modernised a number of times since.  Today you can still see some genuine musket
bullet holes high in the wall of the Peirson public house on the corner of the
square. The 'pub' is named after the 24 year-old commander of the British forces
who was killed in the battle and his grave can be found in the neighbouring 
parish churchyard, where coincidentally the commander of the French forces Baron
de Rullecourte also lies. The square was also the scene of the proclamation of
Charles II as King of England after his father's execution. Also see if you can
spot the giant 'V for Victory' sign that was set in the cobble stones of the
square during World War II right under the noses of the occupying German forces.<BR></P>
<P>If you're interested in local culture and traditions, both the island's
Parliament and its Royal Court are 'unofficially' open to visitors. Just ask one
of the uniformed attendants if it's possible to go in and have a look around.
There are a number of fine paintings, including a Gainsborough, on show. If
either the court or the Parliament (The States) are in session it's perfectly
alright to go and sit in the public galleries for a while. However, dress
smartly and above all DON'T take any photos inside, they're particularly touchy
about this! On a Friday afternoon one of Europe's oldest land courts takes place
in the Royal Court, and it's well worth spending half an hour watching as
ordinary people swear oaths, in French, before the court, to exchange property.
It's fascinating how the practising advocates have got the system off to a fine
art, with people leaping up and down all over the place, raising and lowering
their right hands to swear the oaths and so forth. <BR></P>
<P>A couple of other places well worth visiting in St. Helier include the
island's museum, which was recently voted the best museum in Britain, and also
the Victorian covered flower market, where you can see, and buy, lots of the
famous Jersey horticultural produce. Just on the eastern outskirts of St. Helier
amongst the beautiful tress, flowers and lawns of the Howard Davies Park is a
tiny piece of American soil in the form of one of the few American Military
cemeteries in Europe. A number of US aviators and seamen were buried here during
the War and this cemetery is a memorial to them, and maintained by the island's
government in gratitude.<BR></P>
<P>Once outside the capital, there is much to see and do, however your choice
of transport is limited to four options: taxis are expensive; car hire is cheap
and gas is probably the cheapest in Europe, but remember in the Channel Islands
they drive on the left, or middle of the road, depending how wide it is, and
some of these roads are real narrow! There is a good bus service, and a Rover
ticket would cost you about $10 for a week's unlimited travel. Just watch out
you don't miss the last bus back from some of the outlying areas, or if you're
feeling reasonably fit, cycling is a good option. They're cheap to hire and
nowhere is more than 10 miles from St. Helier.<BR></P>
<P>Apart from the island's stunning coastal views the highspots around the
island include the two mediaeval fortresses of Elizabeth Castle and Mont Orgueil
Castle. Elizabeth Castle situated about a mile offshore, but accessible at low
tide was once the home of Sir Walter Raleigh, before he sailed off to the
Americas to discover Virginia, tobacco and the potato. Sir George Carteret who
was the founder of the State of New Jersey was also the Governor of the island
at one time. Mont Orgueil Castle is situated at the closest point to France, and
on a clear day you can see traffic moving along the French coast just 14 miles
away! This huge mediaeval castle overlooks the pretty fishing village of Gorey,
and is well worth a full day's visit. Many times during the islands' turbulent
history the fortress was the only deterrent against French invasion. Indeed in
the 1400s the French managed to storm the castle and hold the island for seven
years until the English recaptured the castle.<BR></P>
<P>In the Parish of Trinity lies one of Jersey's most famous attractions, the
world famous Jersey Wildlife Preservation Trust. Although not strictly speaking
a 'zoo', the Trust founded by Gerald Durell is at the forefront of breeding wild
and endangered species, including the world famous gorillas and orang-utans.
There are thousands of animals here ranging from tiny reptiles up to the larger
mammals. Although entry is expensive by Jersey standards, about $7.50, most of
the money is going towards supporting the animals. A definite must for a day
out.<BR></P>
<P>Once out into the country parishes of the north and west of the island, you
can travel along small wooded lanes, exchanging glances with the pretty Jersey
cattle or admiring the pretty granite faced farmhouses and the occasional
'millionaire's mansion' hidden away amongst the trees. Remember that being an
offshore tax haven is now Jersey's biggest business, and the streets of St.
Helier are paved with big international banks and the trill of the mobile phone
of money men doing deals. <BR></P>
<P>One of the island's most spectacular sights is St. Ouen's Bay (pronounced
St.Wanz), a five mile long stretch of golden sands, with the adjoining foreshore
being the island's only national park and conservation area. An ideal place for
a stroll and to watch the surfers riding the Atlantic rollers.  One of the
things you will see around all  the Channel Islands, is the huge amount of
concrete fortifications dating from World War II, when the Germans invaded the
islands in 1940 and placed them under occupation until 1945, Hitler was
determined to hang onto the only piece of British soil he conquered, and poured
thousands of troops and slave workers into the islands to build an impregnable
fortress out of them. In the end the Allies simply bypassed the islands after
D-Day and starved the islands into submission. The story of the Occupation is
told in several museums throughout the islands and some of the fortifications
are open to the public. The best museum is probably the Underground Hospital in
Jersey, which is a huge complex and which has been restored in part to its
original working state. However when one returns to the sunlight after time
spent underground it's hard to shake off a feeling of sadness at the amount of
human misery that went into building these parts of Hitler's grandiose dreams.<BR></P>
<P>The best way to arrive in Guernsey is by sea, so take one of the frequent
fast ferries from St. Helier for the 28 mile journey to the second largest
island in the chain. St. Peter Port, is without doubt the prettiest town in the
Channel Islands, hugging the hillside of the  port with its quaint narrow
streets and walks, complete with whitewashed houses and cottages. As your ferry
arrives in the harbour, you pass the fortress of Castle Cornet, which is famous
for withstanding a nine year siege during the English Civil War when the Castle
was the last surviving outpost of the Royalist cause in the entire British
Isles. Guernsey, at 25 square miles is even more lilliputian than Jersey,
everything seems to be on a 'toy-town' like scale. On the heights overlooking
the harbour area stands Hauteville House, the home where Victor Hugo spent
fifteen years of his life in the late 1800s during his political exile from
France. Here he wrote many of his most famous works including <I>Les Miserables</I>
and <I>The Hunchback of Notre Dame</I>. Today the house is a museum, owned by
the City of Paris, and dedicated to Hugo.<BR></P>
<P>When you venture into the island's hinterland, you'll come across things
like the smallest chapel in the world at Les Vauxbelets, which was created
single-handed by a French priest during the early parts of this century.
Apparently it's an exact copy of the chapel at Lourdes, but on a much smaller
scale. Guernsey is excellent for walking and enjoying the pleasures of small
sandy coves with clean air, and stunning coastal scenic views.<BR> </P>
<P>The other islands of the group are idyllic if you require a bit of peace and
quiet away from the hustle and bustle of everyday life. Situated a few miles
east of St Peter Port the two tiny islands of Herm and Jethou stand like
sparkling jewels in the sea. A twenty minute ferry trip will take you to Herm,
where just a few people live. Not much to do on Herm except walk and laze and
admire the scenery. Walk to the Shell Beach, an amazing natural phenomena that
consists of millions upon millions of tiny sea shells. Apart from that Herm has
a small pub, a very highly rated hotel and restaurant, the White House Hotel,
and not much else. Take a picnic and enjoy a day out. Jethou is normally closed
to the public as it's a direct Crown tenancy. <BR></P>
<P>A further five miles east of these two islands is Sark, the last remaining
feudal state in Europe. This island with its 500 inhabitants has turned its back
on a lot of the modern ways of the world. Cars are banned, although there is the
odd tractor chugging along the narrow lanes. Most people use horses and carts to
transport goods and chattels around, and although visitors can hire bicycles the
best way to get around is by foot. Sark, unlike the other islands virtually
rises out of the sea and is basically a large two square mile plateau five
hundred feet above sea level. The one small harbour is the lifeline to the
island, no airport here! After walking up the steep hill from the harbour, there
is a refreshing 'pub' situated right at the top of the hill! One of the great
natural sights in the islands is La Coupee, a narrow isthmus about six feet wide
that joins Great Sark to Little Sark, and which is two hundred feet above sea
level with a near vertical drop on either side! Although safer now, with the
addition of side barriers, the locals will regale you with tales of how people
were literally blown off the track in high winds and were never seen again. If
you can afford to spend the time stay overnight in Sark, the place is totally
different after all the daytrippers have left to return to the larger islands.
There are a small number of hotels and B &amp; B's and you'll be made very
welcome.<BR></P>
<P>The 'Cinderella' of the islands is the most northerly, Alderney. Today this
wind swept island of 2,000 inhabitants is an anglers and bird watchers'
paradise. The island has a sort of melancholy charm, partly due to its exposed
position in the middle of the English Channel, just eight miles from France, and
partly due to its recent sad past. The whole island's population were evacuated
'en masse' during World War II escaping just before the Germans invaded.
Alderney was the site of the only Nazi concentration camp on British soil, where
many thousands of slave workers, mainly Russians and Poles, were worked to
death.<BR></P>
<P>The only town St. Anne has a sleepy provincial feel to it but the
inhabitants are a friendly lot, even though they were once described as
'eighteen hundred alcoholics clinging to a rock' - not true I hasten to add!
Alderney's current claim to fame is that it boasts the only working railway in
the islands and the two mile round trip using  restored London Underground stock
is quite something. The railway is open on weekends in Summer.<BR></P>
<P>Four main islands - four totally different lifestyles and outlooks. What
binds them together? Not even a common government! The Bailiwick of Jersey and
the Bailiwick of Guernsey each have separate legislative and administrative
offices. Both issue their own currency and postage stamps. As the oldest part of
the monarchy, many an islander will tell you they were on the winning side in
1066 when they conquered England at the Battle of Hastings, and England in
reality belongs to them. Many of the old facets of island life including the
local language, Norman French, are slowly dying out as the islands become more
cosmopolitan with the ingress of new monetary wealth and immigrants from all
over the world. However the islanders still have a stubborn desire to do what
they want, as they have from time immemorial, by fishing, exploring, trading and
privateering, in order to create a self-sustaining community with no reliance on
'outsiders'. Visit it now before the world changes it too much.  &#164;<BR></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Travel Facts: The Channel Islands</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Getting There:</B>  Numerous daily flights from European airports
including London, Dublin, Paris, Amsterdam and Zurich, mainly landing at Jersey,
although a few do land in Guernsey. Operators include British Airways, Air UK,
British Midland, Jersey European, Air France, and KLM.  Car ferries from
Weymouth in England. 3 -4 hours by high speed catamaran (around $70 return), or
eleven hours by 'mail boat'. Ferries from St Malo in France, and during the
summer from the nearby small French ports of Portbail, Carteret and Granville. 
Carry your passport -- you'll have to clear Customs and Immigration to get into
the islands, even if you're only travelling from the UK.<BR></P>
<P><B>Inter Island Travel:</B> Half hourly flights between
Jersey/Guernsey/Alderney by Aurigny Airlines. About $45 return. Fast ferries by
Condor three or four times a day to most of the larger islands. Jersey to
Guernsey takes about an hour. Jersey/Sark about 90 minutes. Both about $30
return.<BR></P>
<P><B>Hiring a car:</B> Don't forget your driving licence. Either a US or
International driving licence is required and you must be over 20 years of age
to hire a car. Car hire in the islands is generally amongst the cheapest in
Europe, and although the major rental companies such as Hertz, Budget and Avis
have offices the better deals come from local car rental companies. Try Falles
(Tel: 00 1 44 1534 43222 or fax 00 1 44 1534 46917) in Jersey and Guernsey for
friendly service and a good deal. Watch the speed limits:  maximum in Jersey is
40 mph, and Guernsey 35 mph, with some zones being just 20mph.<BR></P>
<P><B>Climate:</B> Slightly warmer and drier than the UK as the islands are
warmed by the Gulf Stream. One of the best times to visit is the Spring around
May, or early Fall when the gorse on the coastal headlands is a riot of color.<BR></P>
<P><B>Language:</B> English is now the universal language though you may hear
a smattering of the old local Norman French in country districts of Jersey and
Guernsey. 95% of all street names are in French though! Mont Gras D'eau, St.
Brelade sort of trips off the tongue!<BR></P>
<P><B>Money:</B> Both the States of Jersey and Guernsey issue their own
currency, the pound, although it is linked to the UK pound for value. As the
Channel Islands are one of the major financial centers of the world you usually
have no problem spending any currency whatsoever! Credit and charge cards widely
accepted. You will have problems using CI currency in the UK - only banks will
exchange it, although there is usually no charge for doing so.<BR></P>
<P><B>Shopping:</B> Although technically not a 'duty-free' area the local
taxes are exceptionally low and compared to France and the UK bargains can be
picked up. French perfume in particular is a bargain. Locally produced sweaters,
Guernseys and Jerseys, are also good value. The Channel Islands are not part of
the EU for customs purposes so watch out for restrictions on the amount of goods
you can return to the US with.<BR></P>
<P><B>Crime:</B> Virtually non-existant. One of the cleanest and safest places
in the world. Any crimes that are committed are usually by 'mainlanders' rather
than locals. It's safe to walk the streets at any time of the day or night.
Stringent anti-drugs legislation including jail sentences for bringing drugs
into the islands in ANY quantity. Police wear the familiar British 'bobby'
uniforms and are unarmed.<BR></P>
<P><B>Food:</B> Wow! Hundreds of restaurants giving all types of cuisine
ranging from fast food to gourmet. Jersey has a number of Food Festivals
throughout the year - a great chance to try a number of different cuisines.
Fish, including Lobster, Sole, and the local speciality Ormers is good, although
Ormers, in my opinion, are a bit chewy! Jersey Royal potatoes, Guernsey tomatoes
and other vegetables grow in abundance in the islands. In Jersey look for the
'Jersey Fresh' label on all local produce. There is one local vineyard in Jersey
producing a Muscadet type wine, but it's not the best and French wine is
exceptionally cheap. Try out the local beers including the ones produced by 'The
Tipsy Toad' brewery in Jersey's St. Peters. A decent three course meal with wine
and coffee afterwards will set you back about $15 - 20 a head.<BR></P>
<P><B>Packages:</B> A few hotels only deal with tour operators but most will
take direct bookings. Contact Jersey Tourism, Liberation Square, St. Helier,
Jersey, Channel Islands, (Tel: 00 1 44 1534  500800 or fax 00 1 44 1534 500899)
and/or Guernsey Tourism, White Rock, St. Peter Port, Guernsey, Channel Islands.
(Tel: 00 1 44 1481 723552 or fax 00 1 44 1481 714951) for full colour brochures
and hotel lists and brochures. They'll be glad to send them to you.  The States
of Jersey also run a Tourism Office in Paris and London and any office of the
British Tourist Authority will have details about the islands.<BR></P>
<P><B>Guidebooks:</B> There are a number on the market including an 'Insight'
Guide to the Channel Islands, and a Berlitz guide. A number of local publishers
produce informed guide books.<BR></P>
<P><I>- Spencer Pryor</I></P>
