<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Rebuiling Giron Castle</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Rebuilding Giron Castle</H2>
<P><B><I>Brick-Laying Provence Style</I></B></P>
<P><I>by Jeanine Barone</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>&quot;If you're staring at the rock for more than a few seconds,&quot;
said Ginour, &quot;it's the wrong rock.&quot;<BR></B>   I had just spent 20
minutes sorting through the rock pile, discarding each one as either too big,
too round, too small, too flat, too irregular.  With a weathered face, shaggy
beard and long curly gray hair topped by a shocking pink cap, Ginou stared over
my shoulder, meditating a moment, his brow wrinkling with intense concentration
as he surveyed the mound and seized a rock with just the right dimensions and
surface.  He continued, &quot;You'll find the right rock once you're in harmony
with it.&quot;  So began my first day restoring a medieval castle in southern
France and my introduction to Henri Gignoux (Ginou), the chief mason of the
project. </P>
<P>It became clear this wouldn't just be a two-week stint in laying stone and
mortar,  a skill hardly needed in New York City.  It was more a session in time
travel combined with Eastern philosophy. We shared spartan rooms with other
would-be masons,  but this was not like any college dorm room.  We didn't need a
clock. The donkey braying outside our window served as our alarm.  No bags of
chips for late night snacks.  Instead, we could reach outside our window and
pick fruit right from the vines crawling up the wall.  No hanging out at the
local bar. We'd sit on the  fortification walls and watch the moon cast a cold
light on the castle above the town of St. Victor.  Out late sipping cappuccino
in the town, we'd meander down dirt paths through a seeming maze of stone
buildings to find our simple room.  Climbing into our twin beds, we'd feel the
aura of the medieval period blanket us.  We couldn't help but to have visions of
armor-clad knights and fair maidens dance in our heads.  </P>
<P>Before my departure I bragged to my friends that I would be rebuilding a
castle. But LeSabrenenque, the organization that conducts restorations in the
area around St. Victor la Coste,  rebuilt everything from paths and bridges to
churches and entire villages.  Founded by Ginou and his wife Simone, Le
Sabrenenque, is headquartered at St. Victor, an 11th century village near
Avignon where we resided for two weeks.  The work is not done quickly. St.
Victor,  Le Sabranenque's first restoration project, took 15 years to complete
-- rebuilding the church and some 15 houses, and clearing rubble and vegetation
to reveal ancient paths, gardens and courtyards. </P>
<P>As one of 35 volunteers, my main project was at Gicon, a 13th century castle
high on a hill half an hour from St. Victor.  Before seeing the site, I had
expected Chateau de Gicon to be one massive structure reminiscent of King
Arthur's days, complete with a moat and drawbridge.  Gicon is actually a series
of buildings, almost like a village, that had fallen three times in its history
and was left in ruin for centuries.  There was no moat or drawbridge, but the
climb through the forest to get there certainly slowed down our progress.  This
plus the stone fortification and sheer cliffs probably dissuaded many uninvited
guests from visiting. </P>
<P>Six years ago, Ginou and his group of volunteer masons started restoring
Gicon, putting in stairs and windows, tiling floors, reconstructing archways and
reinforcing roofs.  The goal was not to bring Gicon back to its original form
but to make it safe for the local wine cooperative to host tasting events. 
These socials would clearly be spoiled if chardonnay-toasting guests were to
stumble off the precipice surrounding Gicon or be knocked out by a section of
crumbling ceiling.</P>
<P>As novice masons, we first tested our mettle with the bucket brigade. 
Twenty of us lined up and quickly passed thirty pound buckets of sand up two
flights of stairs from one individual to the next.  The sand was followed by
pails brimming with water. Worrying that a pail might slip at any moment, I
understood why the &quot;old timers&quot; came dressed in heavy hiking boots
while I naively wore beach sandals. After several mornings of weight training, I
progressed from a two-handed death grip to an almost casual one-handed swing. 
Thirty minutes of this daily was certainly a more social way of muscle building
than back home in the gym listening to the grunts of otherwise silent body
builders.  </P>
<P>More misconceptions were revealed as six of us were led to the cliff top
where we began constructing a stone wall.  In my visions, brick laying should be
a very terrestrial sport.  Therefore, I sunk into the background as volunteers
were sought to climb the scaffolding near the cliff edge or dangle over the
fortress wall only hooked into a safety harness.  I soon found that there were
always plenty of volunteers who didn't mind hanging  precariously in a safety
harness or crawling over a steep-pitched roof.  </P>
<P>The philosophy of laying stone was soon revealed.  Atop a thin layer of
fresh mortar, I lay each rock in no particular pattern, but satisfied with my
efforts. However, this registered as an &quot;F&quot; in Ginou's Masonry 101
class. With a long sweep of his hand, he quickly stopped me and cast my rocks
off the wall. &quot;Placing rocks in the mortar is like music,&quot; he said, &quot;very
fluid and rhythmic.&quot;  He demonstrated by mimicking a conductor and gently
but firmly placing rocks on their long flat surface, one next to the other.  For
the next layer, he laid rocks crosswise with a good layer of mortar between. 
</P>
<P>Try as I may,  I could neither get a feel for the right rocks nor visualize
how a finished wall would look and thought I probably should have stuck with
mixing cake batter rather than mortar. Either I was jinxed or this was a genetic
skill.   My colleagues seemed to have no problem in duplicating Ginou's Zen-like
masonry techniques, while over the next few days,  I accidentally dislodged
several critically placed rocks; made mortar that was as runny as soup; built a
wall only two layers high that somehow resembled a roller coaster; and felt too
silly to meditate over the rocks.  </P>
<P>Not comprehending Ginou's visualizing exercises and with failure weighing me
down, I decided to shadow my more skillful colleagues.  Carol had a knack for
simply stepping up to a stone pile and finding the right rock, and always mixing
mortar correctly.  I took notes from Genevieve who'd done this for five summers:
 on a section of the wall spread a thick layer of mortar  right to the edge;
select big rocks that don't teeter but instead lie flat; lay them on either side
of the wall; make sure they're flush on the outside and then in the middle with
smaller stones.  And with that, my masonry mastery began.  I found rocks that
were big, but not too big; mixed mortar that was thick, but not too thick; and,
like with a jigsaw puzzle, I fit each rock perfectly next to its neighbor. 
Layer after layer, the wall rose to four feet high.  Finally,  I got an
approving smile and a hug from Ginou.  I no longer felt like the outcast mason. 
We neared the top of our wall, using plumb lines to ensure that the rocks were
flush on the top and sides.  </P>
<P>In the end, we all stood back, hands on hips, trowels in hand after  topping
the wall with watery mortar and large, flat stones -- the final stage of a
completed wall.  Like a sculptor critically surveying the delicate curves of a
shoulder or neck in a bust he's labored over, Ginou stood silently over our
piece of work.  We'd been transformed into proud artists.  </P>
<P>Audrey, one of many non-first-timers,  made a mental log entry of another
successful renovation she'd help complete.  For her, this was like returning
home after a long absence, to see changes made while she was gone and relive
memories of past projects, like the stone floor and archway she worked on a few
years ago.  Our last day, we relished the warm breeze and the burning sun on our
arms, the smoothness of the mortar running between our fingers and the cool
firmness of the rocks we selected.  With all our activity centered on the
outdoors, I wondered aloud what we would have done if it were ever to rain. 
Reflecting on the sense of magic here, Audrey replied softly, &quot;It never
rains in Camelot.&quot;  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="-2">Articles appearing on this page are &copy;1996
Personal Programs and/or the contributor.  All rights reserved.  Opinions
expressed are those of the writer(s). Travel information is by nature subject to
frequent change; travelers should always verify information prior to relying
upon it.  Personal Programs does not represent and does not endorse products,
companies, or offers referenced on this page, and cannot be responsible for
errors, changes, or omissions.  Please send comments to Personal Programs at
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A></FONT>. </P>
