<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Surviving Rome / 
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Italy / Crime / Pickpockets /
Crime in Europe / Travel Safety / ATMs in Rome / Travel in Europe / </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>Surviving Rome</H2>
<P><BR><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00" SIZE="+2">The Eternal City's Eternal
Crime Wave</FONT></B></I></P>
<P><BR>
<I>by Jerri Clark Kirby</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Few cities in the world hold as much history, art, beauty and excitement
as Rome.</B>   The food and wine are consistently tasty and enjoyable, (and
don't forget the ice cream!).   It's a city of many attractions and wonderful
characteristics.   Unfortunately, it is also a city of widespread petty crime;
the attractions draw tourists and the tourists draw theives.  Italy actually has
a very low rate of violent crimes against tourists, but pickings are good here
and the lightfingered seem at times to be everywhere.   
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B>The Gypsies:</B></FONT> Although it's a myth that
all Romany (Gypsies) are thieves, like most myths it has its moments of
appearing true.  You've just left the tour bus, walking towards the Trevi
Fountain, mulling over its relative smallness compared to the image you formed
after having seen a rerun of &quot;Three Coins in the Fountain.&quot;  A cute,
ragged boy of about 10 or 12 pokes a piece of corrugated cardboard in your face,
obviously trying to get your attention to beg for a handout.   While your
attention is on his face and that irritating piece of cardboard he's waving
about, he's picking your pocket or purse with his other hand.   He's good at it
and he will probably be far gone before you realize you're missing anything.  
He may have another little boy, and perhaps even an older woman, working with
him.  While he's getting your attention, the others are stealing your
belongings.  They generally work in twos or threes and are gone before you know
you've been hit.   Besides a piece of cardboard, he may use a newspaper, an ad,
a booklet or a map, anything to get your attention for a few moments.  These
kids are very arrogant and open about their activities.  They are too young to
be prosecuted and if they are caught, are usually let go after being scolded by
the police.  The older women are not hard-core criminals, so are usually not
held either.  When  caught they are soon back out on the street, only mildly
inconvenienced. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Pickpockets: </FONT></B> They work in crowded
tourist areas, usually in pairs or groups of three.   One will distract the
victim with conversation while an accomplice performs the robbery.  In one
ongoing routine, one will throw trash at a victim; the second will help the
victim in cleaning up the mess; a third will discretely take the victim's
belongings, disappearing before you realize your passport, money or watch are
gone!  Another variation is for the crook to point out something like catsup on
your trousers or the back of your jacket.   In fact, he's just put it there
himself.  While he offers tissues or his handkerchief to help wipe off the
catsup, another will offer to hold your bag, your camera, your packages.  While
you're wiping up, they've disappeared! 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Motor Scooter Bandits:</FONT></B> Elderly
tourists who have sought to resist petty thieves on motor scooters have suffered
broken arms and collarbones.  These scooter thieves are amazing, actually.  They
run their motor scooters up on the sidewalks, heading for groups of tourists and
snatching purses or bags from someone backing off to get out of their way. 
Sometimes they use a razor or sharp knife to cut a strap -- they are quick and
accurate.  They've gone before you fully realize that you have been robbed. 
They may also approach from behind, moving so swiftly that you hardly have a
chance to react. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Public Transportation:</FONT></B> One very
friendly person engages you in conversation while you're on a bus, perhaps
asking directions or just pointing out interesting sights along the way.  
Another slits your purse or bag with a razor or sharp knife and removes the
contents through the side or the bottom.   By the time you realize how light
your property has become, they've left the bus and blended into the crowds. 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Rental Cars:</FONT></B> Small items such as
cameras, radios, luggage, briefcases and even cigarettes and food will be stolen
from your parked car&#151;a smashed window is quick! Thieves currently seem to
be targeting vehicles pulled into service stations.   It's really best to store
anything you must leave in the car in the trunk; do this a few blocks before you
actually park the car.  If a thief sees you putting something in the trunk, he'd
as soon break open your trunk as smash your window! 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">What to Do:</FONT></B>  If despite your caution
you are victimized, report it to the police. There are tourist police in heavily
visited locations; elsewhere, you'll probably end up at the local police station
but this is a great opportunity to get an inside look at the workings of the
polizia.  Be prepared for a few hours delay in your schedule.  Many Italian
policemen speak passable English but it sometimes takes time to find one.   File
a report and ask for a copy, which may be required if your insurance company
becomes involved.  (It also makes a good souvenir.)   The inside of a Rome
police station, whether local or tourist, is a fascinating place to people-watch
while you're waiting -- and you will wait!  If your passport is stolen, be
prepared.   Have a copy of your passport (kept separately from the original),
and a couple of passport photos.  These will speed up acquisition of a
replacement passport considerably.   Report the loss of your passport to the
American Embassy at Via Veneto 119/A, phone: (39-6) 46741.   They will see to
the replacement .   Also stop by and report any other losses through theft.  
Reports of this nature are incorporated into regular consular releases and
future tourists will be forewarned.  <BR></P>
<P>Having a photocopy of your return air tickets can be helpful in getting them
replaced quickly.  If you're traveling on a railpass keep a copy of that too,
and consider buying loss insurance for it (available from most railpass
agencies.) 
<BR></P>
<P>A few precautions can keep from getting in trouble in the first place.  Try
to leave all valuables in your hotel safe, if one is available.  Take only money
needed for the day, and carry the name and address of your hotel so you'll know
where to tell a taxi driver to go.   It's best to have travelers' checks with
just a little cash money.   If you must take money, credit cards and passport
with you on tours, a money belt worn under your clothing, with openings next to
your skin, is your best bet.  Don't wear expensive jewelry, and leave your
pockets empty.  If you do take a purse, have one with a strap and grip it firmly
with the latch side towards your body.  Be aware of the people around you at all
times.   If you are alert, chances are the would-be pickpockets or thieves will
move on to an obviously less wary mark.  If you are approached in a suspicious
manner by anyone, talk loudly and turn sideways away from them.  Shout at them,
if necessary.  (Shouting at gypsy kids seems to be a fairly reliable way to get
rid of them.)   <BR></P>
<P>If you notice someone following you, first of all give him a strong,
penetrating look.   If a policeman is nearby, go up to him and point at the
follower -- who will become invisible quickly!  Recent arrivals from eastern
European countries seem to be adding to the problems.  Pickpockets and other
petty crimes thrive at crowded tourist sites such as Trevi Fountain and the
Vatican, and in bus and train stations; the train station at Fumico, (Da Vinci
Airport), seems to be a particular gathering place.  The police chase them away
and even have fierce-looking dogs but they reappear quickly.  Always be wary
when you're at any place, like a ticket window, where money exchanges hands.  
<BR></P>
<P>Count your money before you approach to buy something and after the
transaction is finished.  Another thing -- be careful with your phone card. 
It's better to have the numbers you need to make a call memorized or written
down on a piece of paper, only using the actual calling card where you must
insert it into the telephone.   If you need to make a long distance call from a
public place, be sure no one is spying on you; phone thieves can get your number
from right over your shoulder or with binoculars a few feet away.   Thousands of
dollars can be charged to your number before you even receive your bill. 
<BR></P>
<P>Rome is a city everyone should visit at least once.  And while they no
longer encourage throwing coins into Trevi Fountain&#151;it gobs up the plumbing&#151;you're
still free to toss a wish.  With a little caution, your wish will be that you
too may someday return.  &#164;    <BR></P>
<P><I>The State Department will send you a free brochure, &quot;A Safe Trip
Abroad&quot; with tips on how to have a trouble-free journey.  Write to
Superintendent of Documents, U.S.  Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C.
20402.  
</I></P>
<HR>
<P><I><B><FONT SIZE="+2" COLOR="#FFFF00">ATMs: The Occasional Roman Rip-Off 
</FONT></B></I></P>
<P><B>Automatic Teller Machines</B> have justifiably become very popular with
European travelers; they provide cash on the spot, in the desired currency,
without the hassle of cashing traveler's checks and generally at a good exchange
rate.  However, there are occasional reports&#151;particularly from Rome&#151;of
ATMs going through all the motions of a cash withdrawal, with the quaint
variation of not actually dispensing any money!  If you find yourself standing
on the sidewalk with receipt in hand but no lira, report it <I>immediately</I>.
 Depending on the amount involved, it may even be worth a long-distance
Stateside call to your issuing bank.  The problem is, when this sort of glitch
happens the ATM is convinced it gave you money, and it has the transaction
record to &quot;prove&quot; it.  If you wait until you get home to report the
incident, it's your word against the entire Italian banking system&#151;and
you'll lose.  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
