<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Best Links / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo~.gif">
<HR>
<H1>Best of <FONT COLOR="#8000FF">The Online Traveler</FONT></H1>
<P><I><B>European Travel Online</B></I></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Trav<I>elocity:</I></B><A HREF="http://www.travelocity.com/">www.travelocity.com</A></P>
<P>This enormous Internet travel site is now open for business.  There's more
stuff than you can shake a modem at -- reportedly 200,000 pages all told --
though it suffers somewhat from the &quot;mile wide and inch deep&quot;
syndrome; you can find information about almost everything, but not very <I>much</I>
information about anything.  And they need to fix an annoying quirk that makes
you re-select your destination -- starting at the continent level and working
your way down -- each time you change information category.  The best parts are
found in the descriptions of sights and attractions and general travel advice,
which come from travel info pioneers Worldview.  Not much for hotels as yet,
with lots of listings but only name, address, and phone offered.  They're taking
online reservations for some things (including air travel) and hold 'live' chat
sessions with travel personalities.<BR></P>
<P><B>Rail Pass Express: </B> <A HREF="http://www.eurail.com/">www.eurail.com</A>
has added a chat room, the <B>Caf&eacute; Elsys&eacute;es</B>, to their Web
site at .  The online Caf&eacute; was was featured in 1996 at the Internet World
conference in San Fransisco.  Come on in, pour an espresso, and talk travel. 
Rail Pass Express is also in the process of adding a <B>Britain by Britrail</B>
site to go with their excellent <B>Europe by Eurail</B> pages.<BR></P>
<P><B>Forsyth Travel Library:</B> <A HREF="http://www.forsyth.com./">www.forsyth.com.</A></P>
<P>Located in Shawnee Mission, Kansas, Forsyth Travel Library is the US
distributor of the <I>Thomas Cook European Timetable</I> and holds a long-time
reputation as one of the country's leading experts in European rail travel. 
They are also authorized agents for Rail Europe and can provide you with
virtually any type of railpass you require, along with point-to-point tickets,
sleeper reservations, International Youth Hostel memberships, and a good
selection of maps and guidebooks.<BR></P>
<P><B>A Collection of Links for Great Britain</B><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.interactive.line.com/british.html">British Tourist
Authority - British Monthly Planner</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.iinet.com.au/~cam/nt/nttop.html">National Trust
Properties in England</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/state51/knowhere">Knowhere: Alternative
Guide to the UK</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.digimark.net/rec-travel/hostels/euro.menu.html">The
European Hostel Guide</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/tube/index.html">WWW Tube
Journey Planner</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/hotelnet/windsor/home.htm">Windsor Castle</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.rbgkew.org.uk/">Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.city.ac.uk/london/entertainment/museums"> London
Transport Museum and others</A></LI>
<LI><A
HREF="http://catless.ncl.ac.uk/Vegetarian/Guide/Europe/England/index.html">Vegetarian
Restaurants throughout England</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/">Bodleian Library, Oxford</A></LI></UL>
<P><I>(Note: There are more Britain sites in the listings below.)</I><BR></P>
<P><B>European Waterways: </B><A
HREF="http://www.interport.net/cellular/ew.html">www.interport.net/cellular/ew.html
 </A></P>
<P>Lots of information here on cruising the waterways of Europe.  Indulge your
guests aboard a private boat complete with captain, crew, and chef.<BR></P>
<P><B>Residences Orion: </B><A
HREF="http://www.interport.net/cellular/orion.html"><B>www.interport.net/cellular/orion.html</B></A></P>
<P>European apartment living for as long as you like.  Great for families! 
They list a number of properties with locations close to business, cultural, and
recreational centers.  Apartment stays can offer a considerable savings over
hotels, if only because you can prepare most of your own meals and avoid
high-priced restaurants.<BR> </P>
<P><B>World Cellular Service:</B> <A HREF="http://www.interport.net/cellular"><B>www.interport.net/cellular</B></A>
</P>
<P>Need to keep in touch with business or family while traveling?  This company
offers cellular phone rentals for international travelers.   Reserve before
departure; your phone will be there when you arrive.  Available throughout
Europe, Asia, and Africa. <BR></P>
<P><B>Rail Europe:</B> <A HREF="http://www.raileurope.com/"><B></B>www.raileurope.com/</A>.</P>
<P>  Home page of Rail Europe, the official US representative of European
railways.  Lots of information on European rail, including fares and services.<BR></P>
<P><B>Museums in London:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/museums.html"><B>www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/museums.html</B></A>.</P>
<P>Great page to check out if you're heading to Jolly Old London.  Addresses,
phone numbers, hours of operation, etc. for a wide range of London museums,
including some off-the-wall places you may not know about.<BR></P>
<P><B>UK Theatre Web:</B> <A HREF="http://www.uktw.co.uk/">www.uktw.co.uk/</A></P>
<P> Offers up-to-date info on what's playing the West End &amp; other theatres
in London.<BR></P>
<P><B>Hotels in the UK:</B> <A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/hotel-uk">http://www.demon.co.uk/hotel-uk</A></P>
<P>An online information and reservations service for hotels in London and the
rest of the United Kingdom.  For some properties they sometimes offer special
rates available only on the Web.<BR></P>
<P><B>Holland Tourist Information:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.nbt.nl/holland/home.htm">www.nbt.nl/holland/home.htm</A></P>
<P>You can search for a variety of Netherlands travel topics here.<BR></P>
<P><B>Loews Hotels:</B> <A HREF="http://www.loewshotels.com/">www.loewshotels.com</A></P>
<P>They show only one European listing, but it's a gorgeous Monte Carlo
property overlooking the Meditteranean (rooms from about $280).  If it suits you
they'll soon be able to take your reservation over the Net.<BR></P>
<P><B>European Tourist Information Center:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.iol.ie/~discover/europe.htm">www.iol.ie/~discover/europe.htm</A></P>
<P>Another broad-based offering with selected cultural &amp; tourist
attractions profiled.<BR></P>
<P><B>Relais &amp; Chateaux:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/hotelnet/relais/home.htm">www.u-net.com/hotelnet/relais/home.htm
</A> (UK); <A HREF="http://www.calvacom/relais/accueil.html">www.calvacom.fr/relais/accueil.html
</A> (Mostly France)</P>
<P>The very upscale hotel-and-restaurant group has its own Web page now with
information on properties around the United Kingdom and Europe.  They will take
reservation requests for hotels via e-mail.  (In a side note, they have also
begun taking advance reservations through travel agents for the top-rated, often
hard-to-book restaurants.  But show up -- there's a $60 no-show fee if you
don't.)<BR></P>
<P><B>Trencherman's Guide:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.dcs.ex.ac.uk/wcol/food_and_acc/trench.html">www.dcs.ex.ac.uk/wcol/food_and_acc/trench.html</A></P>
<P>A detailed listing of restaurants in England's West Country can be found
here.  They have details of each individual eatery (including pictures of the
proprietors on some).  This is part of the extensive collection of West Country
pages, many of which are very informative.  They do have a tendency to use
overlarge graphics so it's a bit slow going, but often worth the wait.<BR></P>
<P><B>Walking in Britain:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm">www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm</A></P>
<P>&quot;There is an extensive network of local paths throughout the country,
with rights of way extending for some 140,000 miles...&quot;  Thus begins this
page on hoofing it through Britain, and the page extends quite a ways itself as
it imparts a stack of detailed knowledge on the subject.  National Trails are
covered along with less formal routes, and there are plenty of  specifics on
rules of the road and what to watch out for.  A &quot;must read&quot; if you're
planning an English hiking jaunt.  Also a  pleasantly non-commercial site,
though they do advise on the best places to buy maps &amp; gear.<BR></P>
<P><B>Book-Browsing for the Adventure Traveler:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.gorp.com/waisdata/atbook/atsrch.htm">www.gorp.com/waisdata/atbook/atsrch.htm</A></P>
<P>You wouldn't believe how many books there are about traveling until you
spend some time here.  A relative of the Walking Britain page cited above, this
site lets you search by keywords for books on various flavors of adventurous
travel worldwide.  Punching in &quot;Europe&quot; brought up a bevy of unusual
titles, including Rock Climbing Guide to Europe, Slovenia Travel Survival Kit,
and Walking in the Black Forest.  Clicking on individual titles gets you a
synopsis, reviews, price, and online ordering information.<BR></P>
<P><B>Internet Emporium:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.emporium.co.uk/hotguide/index.html">www.emporium.co.uk/hotguide/index.html</A></P>
<P>This site includes a hefty number of English hotels sorted by city or
county.  Information is limited except for a few &quot;featured&quot; hotels,
but there are a lot of names &amp; UK phone numbers if you're building a list of
possible stopping points.  Pages for the featured hotels are quite detailed,
down to rates and driving maps.<BR></P>
<P><B>Affordable London:</B> <A HREF="http://www.bynet.co.uk/afldn/index.htm">www.bynet.co.uk/afldn/index.htm</A></P>
<P>They offer apartment rentals by the week from $506, and apparently take
e-mail reservations.<BR></P>
<P><B>Sisley Garden Tours:</B> <A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/tka/sisley/">www.u-net.com/tka/sisley/</A></P>
<P>This user-friendly tour operator offers garden tours in the UK and France. 
Detailed itineraries, booking information, and even a gardening crossword puzzle
are online at this site.  Unfortunately, we've just been e-mailed that the '96
tours are all filled.  But check it out anyway and think '97.<BR></P>
<P><B>Russian National Tourist Office:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.interknowledge.com/russia">www.interknowledge.com/russia</A></P>
<P>The official site of the Russian National Tourist Office, and very
impressively done.  For Moscow there's a Calendar of Events, Accommodations
Guide, museum hours, and quite a lot more.  St. Petersburg is also covered in
detail.  A must-stop site if you're going to Russia, though hotel information is
limited to names &amp; addresses.  Lots of good pictures which load quickly. 
Linguists only: If you want to test your Cyrillic reading skills, try
www.eurorussia.com.  (You'll need to download special fonts which they have on
hand.)  We have no clue what the site's about, but it certainly looks exotic.<BR></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Stillwell's Bed &amp; Breakfast Guide:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.stilwell.co.uk/welcome.html">www.stilwell.co.uk/welcome.html</A></FONT></P>
<P><BR><B>An extensive guide to &quot;good value overnight accommodation&quot;
in Britain and Ireland, with B&amp;B rooms averaging &#163;16 per night.  They
don't take reservations (or commissions) but provide you with all the contact
information you need to make your own arrangements.  Very detailed and very
comprehensive; if you've ever wondered where you'd stay in Woolacombe, Devon,
they've got three or four choices for you -- and a pub list to boot. 
Exceptionally well-done site with point-and-click maps, fast graphics, and neat
search tools.  You can even  find inns by such categories as &quot;Converted
Barns&quot;, &quot;Older Houses in Ireland&quot;, and &quot;Thatched Buildings&quot;.</B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Camelot International:</B> <A HREF="http://www.itl.net/go/to/camelot/">www.itl.net/go/to/camelot</A></P>
<P>For some quick fun you can do a trace on family roots in Scotland here --
just type in your surname and click.  The info comes back suspiciously fast,
however, and in pretty short order they want to sell you a mug with &quot;your&quot;
family crest on it.  If you want to look for yourself, they also offer apartment
and hotel reservations for your full-fledged genealogy trip.<BR></P>
<P><B>Genealogy in Ireland and the UK:</B>
<A HREF="http://midas.ac.uk/genuki">midas.ac.uk/genuki</A></P>
<P>For a more serious take on ancestor-hunting, start out here.  They provide a
full course on how to get started, where to look, and what to look for.  Then,
for Ireland and the United Kingdom, they'll take you into as much detail as you
can handle, on regions, archives, family names, and more.  As far as we can
tell, they won't try to sell you anything at all -- it's run by genealogical
society members who just want to help.<BR></P>
<P><B>Guernsey (Channel Islands):</B>
<A HREF="http://user.itl.net/~bebridel/">user.itl.net/~bebridel/</A></P>
<P>Take a tour of one of the larger Channel Islands on this privately
maintained home page.  Lots of visitor info and a link to very detailed lodging
options for the Islands on Hotel Net (www.u-net.com/hotelnet/channel.htm).<BR></P>
<P><B>Bornholm, Denmark:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.bornholminfo.dk/web/uk/index.htm">www.bornholminfo.dk/web/uk/index.htm</A></P>
<P>A home page for the &quot;ideal holiday island&quot; off the coast of
Denmark.  It's a favorite with bike riders due to 200+ km of cycling routes
networking the scenic island.  The site offers details on places to stay, too.<BR></P>
<P><B>Women Business Travelers:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.delta-air.com/womenexecs">www.delta-air.com/womenexecs</A></P>
<P>Delta Airlines and American Express co-sponsor this collection of
information and advice for female business travelers, whose needs &amp;
interests are too often neglected despite their estimated 40% share of business
travel.<BR></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Paris: </B><A HREF="http://www.paris.org/">www.paris.org</A></FONT></P>
<P><BR><B>Virtual information on virtually everything in the World's Favorite
City.  The site is huge so be prepared to spend some time exploring.  &quot;Paris
Kiosque&quot; is an online magazine with top-quality articles and an immensely
detailed, up-to-date &quot;What's On in Paris&quot; calendar.  There are city
maps, tons of pictures, and you can even download a Metro map (if you have the
patience - it's big).</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Travel to Turkey:</B> <A HREF="http://www.turknet.com/">www.turknet.com</A></P>
<P>Grand Circle Travel, a tour operator specializing in Turkey, is present
here, along with an online magazine (Turkish Style) and a guide to Turkish
hotels.  A good stop if you're heading to Istanbul.<BR></P>
<P><B>Dr. Memory's Travel Pages:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.access.digex.net/drmemory/cyber_travel.html">www.access.digex.net/drmemory/cyber_travel.html</A></P>
<P>Profiled in a recent <I>Travel Weekly</I> article, this &quot;eclectic&quot;
home page can link you to more than 2,000 travel sites around the Net, from
run-of-the-mill to off-the-wall.  It's a non-commercial site run part-time by a
guy who wanted to learn Web programming and picked travel as his favorite
subject.  Worth a visit to see what he's come up with.<BR></P>
<P><B>Hotels in Israel: </B><A
HREF="http://www.netmedia.co.il/info/hotelassoc/">www.netmedia.co.il/info/hotelassoc/</A></P>
<P>Prices, info, and photos covering a selection of Israeli lodging options.<BR></P>
<P><B>Belgium:</B> <A HREF="http://www.freesun.be/Epicirie.html">www.freesun.be/Epicirie.html</A></P>
<P>An English-language online magazine about Belgium -- what's on, where to
stay, where to go.<BR></P>
<P><B>Golf Travel Online:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.travelernet/two/twpages/http.gto.com">www.travelernet/two/twpages/http.gto.com</A></P>
<P>A worldwide database of golf vacations and resorts.<BR></P>
<P><B>Overseas Connection:</B> <A HREF="http://www.overseasvillas.com/">www.overseasvillas.com</A></P>
<P>If you're looking for the plushest in digs -- or just want to drool over
some -- this outfit can rent you a villa, castle, or penthouse in a variety of
locales. Our favorite was a Paris apartment with personal chauffeur and a
balcony view of the Eiffel tower.  Their &quot;Property of the Month&quot; is a
14th-century manor in the English countryside; they don't give a rate, but it
comes with eight bedrooms, a library, tennis courts, gymnasium, and a full-time
chef &amp; maid.  Don't bother getting out the Novotel vouchers...<BR></P>
<P><B>Internet Bike Resources for Europe: </B><A
HREF="http://www.abeline.it/fbp-eur.htm">www.abeline.it/fbp-eur.htm</A></P>
<P>This site presents a jumping-off point for a variety of Web resources on
bicycle travel in Europe.  Sponsored by Florence (Italy) Bike Pages, which cover
biking in and around Florence in good detail.  Other links for Austria, Britain,
Netherlands, Switzerland, and Sweden.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Castles in the Air, Castles Everywhere:</B>
<A HREF="http://fox.nstn.ca/~tmonk/castle/castle.html">http://fox.nstn.ca/~tmonk/castle/castle.html</A></P>
<P>A set of web pages devoted to nothing but castles -- tours, histories,
legends, and more.  If your heart quickens at ancient grey stones towering in
the mist, be sure to stop by.  The webmaster is a true castle lover and it
shows.  There's even a &quot;Castles for Kids&quot; page for the little knights
and maidens in your court.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>County Kerry:</B> <A HREF="http://ireland.iol.ie/kerry-insight">http://ireland.iol.ie/kerry-insight</A></P>
<P>All about one of Ireland's most beautiful &amp; historic regions, including
Tralee and the Dingle peninsula.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Edinburgh:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.efr.hw.ac.uk/EDC/guide/contents.html">www.efr.hw.ac.uk/EDC/guide/contents.html</A></P>
<P>Online guide to Scotland's leading city.  Includes a large city map (54k)
with point-and-click links, and detailed descriptions of sights and attractions,
although no lodging information.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Britain by Boat:</B> <A HREF="http://www.rscom.com/boat/">www.rscom.com/boat/</A></P>
<P>The official site of British Waterways, an organization devoted to promoting
travel on Britain's extensive canal system.  They have a map of the canal
system, a searchable index of information on boat services, and a listing of
links to other British boating Web sites.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Britain by Foot:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm">www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm</A></P>
<P>Everything you need to know before setting out to see the British
countryside on foot, including where to get trail maps, what to bring, and where
to stay along the way.  </P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>London Walking Tours:</B> <A HREF="http://scim.co.uk/londonwalks/">http://scim.co.uk/londonwalks/</A></P>
<P>The oldest walking tour company in England's capital, London Walks gives a
complete rundown on their offerings here, and you can e-mail them for more
information.  Dozens of tours are described and they are all just &#163;4.  The
web site also gives profiles of their many experienced guides, so you'll have an
idea who you're walking with.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>European Motorhome Travel:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.spectrav.com/27035.html">http://www.spectrav.com/27035.html</A></P>
<P>A California operator for motorhome rentals in Europe.  Brief information on
rates, models, etc., and a toll free number (800-468-3876) for reservations. 
Also, see <B><A HREF="http://www.drm.de/">http://www.drm.de</A></B>for more
detailed online data from a German rental firm.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Tuscany Camping:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.ats.it/metamarketing/toscana.html">www.ats.it/metamarketing/toscana.html</A></P>
<P>Extensive listing of campgrounds and related info for Italy's lovely Tuscan
region.  A point-and-click map lets you pick your area and takes you to
alphabetized listings.  Most are just address and Italian phone number, but some
can be clicked through to pages of their own with prices and other details. 
Nicely done site.</P>
<HR><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="79">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>In Italy Online:</B>
<A HREF="http://lainet3.lainet.com/~initaly/index.html">http://lainet3.lainet.com/~initaly/index.html</A></FONT></P>
<P><B>A self-described &quot;webzine compiled by American writers who have
lived twenty years or more in Italy.&quot;  Packed with information, including
an interesting page on farm stays in Italy with details on how to book one for
your next trip.  Italian cooking vacations, villa rentals, events calendar, much
more. Terrific &quot;visit to Italy&quot; and winner of a number of awards.</B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>International Home Exchanges:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.homexchange.com/ten/index.html">www.homexchange.com/ten/index.html</A></P>
<P>International postings of homes and apartments for rent or exchange.  Lots
of listings for Europe including some wonderful-sounding villas.  The site
provides ample detail on each property including what location the owner is
looking to trade to; some listings will either exchange or simply rent to you.
You can search by country for properties that interest you.  This site is an
excellent resource if you're looking for the advantages of private lodgings for
a longer stay overseas.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Vienna City Guide:</B> <A HREF="http://www.atnet.co.at/Tourism/Vienna/">http://www.atnet.co.at/Tourism/Vienna/</A></P>
<P>A straightforward site whose many pages offer &quot;lots of useful infos&quot;
for your Vienna visit.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Hospitality Exchange:</B>
<A HREF="http://hospex.icm.edu.pl/~hospex/WhatIsHospex.html">http://hospex.icm.edu.pl/~hospex/WhatIsHospex.html</A></P>
<P>This organization facilitates low- or no-cost temporary lodging for
traveling students and academics by maintaining a database of those needing &amp;
those offering a place to spread a sleeping bag in varied locales.  You're asked
to join in order to get digs, but there's no charge. They just provide the
communications infrastructure; all lodging arrangements are up to members to
work out privately by email.</P>
<HR><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="79">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Online Guide to the Baltics:
<A HREF="http://www.omnitel.net/OurSite/Travel/viyp">www.omnitel.net/OurSite/Travel/viyp</A></FONT></P>
<P><B>WOW!  If you're heading to Vilnius, Kaunus, Klaipeda, Riga, or Minsk,
don't miss these terrific online guides.  Lavish detail, particularly good for
lodging but covering just about everything else you could want too.  Some of the
graphics are a bit slow but the data is worth waiting for.  You can also order
the complete guides, ranging from 48 to 80 pages, in free printed versions by
sending the publishers International Reply Coupons.  Details at the Web site.</B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>E-Mail European Rail Schedules:</B> <A HREF="http://www.bahn.de/">www.bahn.de</A></P>
<P>At this site you can enter a query on schedules or services on European
railways, and you will get an automated e-mail response about half hour later
with route details.  We tried it and it does work; they say they processed over
34,000 queries last month.  It may seem a cumbersome way to get information, but
the 30 minute turn-around can just about beat Rail Europe's telephone on-hold
time some days!</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Swiss Rail:</B> <A HREF="http://www.sbb.ch/">www.sbb.ch</A></P>
<P>Timetables, routes, and other information on the extensive and scenic Swiss
railway system.  The timetable query form produces fast, detailed results for
point-to-point travel options, and covers major international routes as well as
Swiss..</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Ecotourism:</B>
<A HREF="http://greencross.unige.ch/tournet/tournet.html">http://greencross.unige.ch/tournet/tournet.html</A></P>
<P>If you want to ensure that your travel is easy on the Earth, this
Swiss-based organization can help identify some options.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Travel, Packing and Photo Hints:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.afn.org/~afn11300">www.afn.org/~afn11300</A></P>
<P>Betty, the author of this page, is a veteran of travel to seven continents,
and herein shares some pithy experiences and advice.  Also offers an extensive
collection of Web travel links.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Inside Flyer Magazine Online:</B> <A HREF="http://www.insideflyer.com/">www.insideflyer.com/</A></P>
<P>Randy Peterson, guru of frequent flyer information, has a snazzy online
version here.  Check out the reviews of airline FFB programs before you choose
which ones to join.</P>
<HR><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="79">   
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>French Travel Gallery:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.bonjour.com/wta">www.bonjour.com/wta</A></FONT></P>
<P><B>Very flashy, high-tech site with beaucoup info on travel in France
organized by region and topic.  Exceptional hotel listings, including that true
rarity -- genuine budget lodgings (as low as Ff220, or about $47) in Paris. 
Many can be booked online.  Lots more to see here; if you have the browser
plugin RealAudio (and you can download it free if you don't) you can even listen
to pronunciation of a few essential French phrases, such as &quot;O&ugrave; sont
les toilettes, s'il vous pla&icirc;t?&quot;</B> </P>
<HR>
<P><B>Walkabout Travel Gear:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.walkabouttravelgear.com/">www.walkabouttravelgear.com</A></P>
<P>A very interesting collection of travel accessories &amp; essentials.  They
also have a good deal of travel info and advice, a chat forum, and a large
collection of online links (including our own EuroData, which shows their good
taste!).  Stop here on the way to wherever you're going.<BR></P>
<P><B>Wimbledon: </B><A HREF="http://www.wimbledon.org/">www.wimbledon.org</A></P>
<P>If Walker Jackson's article (EV #4)  on his tennis-travel adventures piqued
your interest, check out the British tennis classic's own site on the Web. 
Activity here has calmed down somewhat since the tourney's end, but the page is
still there.<BR></P>
<P><B>Lofoten Islands</B>:
<A HREF="http://home.sn.no/~perkaa/hist/vestvaag.html">http://home.sn.no/~perkaa/hist/vestvaag.html
www.adventuroustraveler.com/atb/europe/g3656.htm</A>;
<A HREF="http://www.lofoposten.no/home/lte/fiskmus.htm">www.lofotposten.no/home/lte/fiskmus.htm</A></P>
<P>The first of these is a &quot;Welcome to Lofoten&quot; page, which deals
mainly with Vestv&aring;g&oslash;y Island; some interesting local info and a
colorful map.  The second profiles a book, &quot;Climbing in the Magic Islands&quot;
from The Adventurous Traveler Bookstore.  There is a brief excerpt (which makes
the islands sound magic indeed!) and ordering information.  The third site is
for the Norwegian Fishing Museum, and has a nice photo of the museum --
impressive setting! -- and a list of current exhibitions.  There's also a link
to a Lofoten Tourist page, but it's still mostly under construction.<BR></P>
<P><B>National Gallery in Prague: </B>
<A HREF="http://www.czech.cz/NG/">www.czech.cz/NG/
</A></P>
<P>Though still a-building, this collection of pages includes interesting
information on the history and current exhibits of Prague's premier art museum.<BR></P>
<P><B>Hungarian Hotels:
</B><A HREF="http://www.columbus.hu/travelpg/hungexp.htm">www.columbus.hu/travelpg/hungexp.htm
</A></P>
<P>Tables provide prices, for a long list of hotels in Budapest and elsewhere. 
Detailed descriptions are only online for a few, however.  But if you've got a
place in mind and want to know what it costs, you may find it here.<BR></P>
<P><B>Venice: A Cultural Tour:
</B><A HREF="http://www1.iol.it/tci.sdp/html/e2006.htm">www1.iol.it/tci.sdp/html/e2006.htm
</A></P>
<P>A terrific site from Touring Club Italiano, with detailed descriptions (and
very tiny pictures, that you can expand if you like) of just about everything
you'd want to see in Venice.  Download the whole page to add to your EuroData
itinerary notes -- and match it to the site below to know when to schedule what.<BR></P>
<P><B>Venice Museum Hours:
</B><A HREF="http://www.srtours.com/vmuse.html">www.srtours.com/vmuse.html
</A></P>
<P>Just what it says -- a list of hours of operation for Venetian museums. 
Information on closed days could be particularly helpful to check out if you're
planning a short visit.</P>
<P></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif">
<P></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Baby Boomers' Venice:
</B><A HREF="http://www.writing.org/venice.htm">www.writing.org/venice.htm
</A></FONT></P>
<P><B>They bill this as a &quot;guide to Venice for the over-forty&quot; but
we think the well-written advice found here would be useful to travelers of any
age.  Not selling anything, just a collection of handy and interesting tips on
eating, staying, and getting around in this lovely city.  Some nice photos too,
that don't take all day to arrive.</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Little Venetian Glossary:  </B><A
HREF="http://www.portve.interbusiness.it/wetvenice/glossario/glossario.html">www.portve.interbusiness.it/wetvenice/glossario/glossario.html
</A></P>
<P>Think you know Italian?  Check out this compendium of Venetian lingo.  Each
word is laid out next to the &quot;classic&quot; Italian version, along with an
English translation.  A definite take-along if you like knowing what you've
ordered for lunch.<BR></P>
<P><B>Cycling in Search of the Cathars:
</B><A HREF="http://www.eclipse.co.uk/pens/cat.html">www.eclipse.co.uk/pens/cat.html
</A></P>
<P>Brief profile of a book by two writers who spent four months bicycling
around the mountains and valleys of South-west France, following the history of
the Cathars.  You can email the British publisher for information on where to
buy the book.<BR></P>
<P><B>Portugal: </B><A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/peth">www.demon.co.uk/peth
</A></P>
<P>Nice site called &quot;Portugal Traveler's Handbook.&quot;  Tips and advice
on getting to, staying in, and getting around the country.  Accomodations
database is slick but seems to cover only youth hostels at present.  A nice
touch is the page of Travelers' Logs, with short descriptions by various
travelers of their experiences.<BR></P>
<P><B>European Walking Tours:
</B><A HREF="http://www.walkingtours.com/">www.walkingtours.com
</A></P>
<P>This site offers detailed itineraries for the hikers' tours they conduct in
a variety of European countries.<BR></P>
<P><B>Italiatour: </B><A HREF="http://www.zenonet.com/italiatour/">www.zenonet.com/italiatour/</A></P>
<P>Italiatour is the tour-operating division of Alitalia, the Italian airline. 
They have information available here on the variety of Italian vacation packages
available.  Nice site, but slow; they need to tame the graphics. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Driving in Europe:
</B><A HREF="http://www.ideamerge.com/motoeuropa1/index.html">www.ideamerge.com/motoeuropa1/index.html
</A></P>
<P>This site offers a wealth of advice if you're planning to take the wheel
over there.  No maps, but plenty of text, and links to European car rental
sites.<BR></P>
<P><B>Thomas Cook</B><A HREF="http://www.thomascook.com/">www.thomascook.com
</A></P>
<P>The venerable travel company is offering a 5% discount to customers who book
through its Internet service.  Information on the large family of Thomas Cook
publications, including the <I>European Timetable</I>, is also offered here. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>European Union
</B><A HREF="http://www.eurunion.org/">www.eurunion.org
</A></P>
<P>Put together by Europe Magazine, the house organ of the EU, this site
includes an archive of European Union history.  Fairly dry stuff but there's an
excellent listing of US tourist information offices and embassies, listed by
country (find this at www.eurunion.org/states/mslist.htm).<BR></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>France in Your Glass
</B><A HREF="http:///www.inyourglass.com">www.inyourglass.com
</A></FONT></P>
<P><B>These designers of specialty trips to the French wine regions (whose &quot;France
in Your Fax&quot; service is also noted in this issue's Check It Out section),
has put up an award-winning page with plenty of detail on their intriguing
culinary tours and vacation packages.<BR></B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Small Italian Hotels:
</B><A HREF="http://www.gteinc.com/">www.gteinc.com
</A></P>
<P>This site contains a variety of listings for small hotels, B&amp;Bs, villas,
pensiones, etc. for the budget traveler heading to Italy.  Current promotions
include rooms for 2 at a 3-star hotel in Rome, under $100 from November
3-December 26; rooms for 2 at a 3-star hotel in Rome, under $100 from November
3- December 26; and rooms for 2 at a 2-star hotel in Florence, under $100 from
November3-December 26, 1996.<BR></P>
<P><B>London Theatre Tickets:
</B><A HREF="http://www.theatredirect.com%20/">www.theatredirect.com 
</A></P>
<P>This ticket broker for New York, San Fransisco, and London stages also
offers good deals on hotel/theatre packages.<BR></P>
<P><B>Continental Fare Specials:
</B><A HREF="http://www.flycontinental.com/">www.flycontinental.com
</A></P>
<P>Following in the path of American Airlines and others, Continental is
offering special fare deals that are only publicised through an e mail
newsletter.  Travelers can sign up for the free weekly bulletins at the
airline's Web site. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Hotel &amp; Travel Index:
</B><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/htio/">www.traveler.net/htio/
</A></P>
<P>The 1500-page Hotel &amp; Travel Index is a quarterly compendium of hotel
amenities &amp; room rates at destinations worldwide, and is widely used by
travel agents.  Their new home page on the Web features a long list of hotels in
various destinations, most with pictures and detailed information including
rates.  Most tend to be upscale (4 star and up).<BR></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif">
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Fodor's: </B><A HREF="http://www.fodors.com/">www.fodors.com
</A></FONT></P>
<P><B>Super online magazine!  The well-known guidebook publisher offers
excerpts from their books, including extensive hotel reviews, along with plenty
of other information in a very clear and attractive setting.<BR></B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Isles of Scilly: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.compulink.co.uk/~issco/">www.compulink.co.uk/~issco/
</A></P>
<P>Scilly Skybus, the airline that serves these tiny, distant British islands,
has posted schedules and fares here on the Web.  They may be moving soon, so if
the URL above is no good, try Lycos or another search engine.
<BR></P>
<P><B>Aer Lingus Ticket Auctions:
</B><A HREF="http://www.aerlingus.ie/">www.aerlingus.ie
</A></P>
<P>One of the hot new trends for Internet airline sites is the ticket auction: 
typically, a number of seats on a particular route, sometimes for particular
dates, are put up for auction, and online visitors can submit bids via email;
highest bids win.  The Irish carrier Aer Lingus is the latest to give this a
try.<BR></P>
<P><B>Gay Travel:
</B><A HREF="http://www.pridetravel.com/">www.pridetravel.com
</A></P>
<P>The Pride Travel Information Network offers information and a stack of
Internet links for those interested in gay- and lesbian-friendly destinations,
tour operators, and other travel info.  The &quot;Destinations&quot; section
doesn't presently cover Europe, but a number of the tours have European
destinations, including a French river barge cruise.<BR></P>
<P><B><I>Booking Air Reservations Online </I></B><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Internet Travel Network:</B>  <A HREF="http://www.itn.net/">www.itn.net</A>
 </LI>
<LI><B>PC Travel:</B>  <A HREF="http://www.pctravel.com/">www.pctravel.com/</A></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><B>TravelWeb:</B>  <A HREF="http://www.travelweb.com/plane.html">www.travelweb.com/plane.html</A></LI></UL>
<HR>
<P><B>Search The Web!</B></P>
<P><I>Don't forget to check with the Internet's premier search providers for
more sources of travel information: </I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo!</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://guide.infoseek.com/">InfoSeek</A></P>
