<BODY><P><I>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</I></P>
<H1>Rome's Siren Call</H1>
<P><I>by Carina Dingemans</I></P>
<HR>
<P>Long after the screeching sound of mopeds and enervating rush of traffic
have left your ears, Rome will remain forever etched in your memory. Whether
it's the vast pink sprawl of the Roman baths, the impressive physical and
spiritual power of St. Peter's, or just the bright yellow blossoms of mimosa
that deck the city in spring and early summer, the city will bid you return
again. Cultivated, capricious and at times awesomely beautiful, Rome is not a
city to be forgotten. 
</P>
<P>Built upon layer after layer of culture, Rome has always managed to preserve
the great works of its past without being immolated by them. A monument to
Rome's modern heritage is the Galleria Nazionale d'Arte Moderna, which houses an
increasingly vigorious collection of international modern art. Established in
the late 1800s, the museum should not be missed:  not only for the quality of
its collection, but for the reminder it gives that our century can hold its own
amid the marvels of earlier times.  
</P>
<P>The museum, situated at the north end of the Borghese Gardens, affords the
visitor the opportunity of strolling back to the city centre through the gardens
and along the Pincio. From here you can gaze out over one of the finest
panoramas of the city, and on an early evening in summer observe one of Italy's
favorite pastimes -- the passagiata. Here you will see Romans old and young
taking a leisurely sunset stroll, looking at the view and (most important) at
one another. 
</P>
<P>The latter day popes, once some of the greatest patrons of the arts, now
preside over the vast task of preserving and restoring the wealth of fine art,
sculpture, tapestries and other incalculable treasures stored up by their
predecessors. The fruits of their endeavours are on display in no less than 10
Vatican Museums (open Monday-Saturday 9am to 2pm October-June; longer hours in
summer.). A monument and record of the Christian experience, the Vatican art
collection is also a testament to the will of the human spirit. Pope John Paul
II described the collection thus: &quot;They will speak of history, of the human
condition in its universal challenge and of endeavours of the human spirit to
attain the beauty to which it is attracted.&quot; 
</P>
<P>We have the popes' love of beauty to thank for the roll call of painters,
sculptors and architects who created some of the seminal works of art history
under their patronage. The buildings and gardens of the Vatican are home to
works by Fra Angelico, Donatello, Botticelli, Raphael, Bernini and Poussin; and,
of course, Michelangelo's murals in the Sistine Chapel, recently restored and
given a new brush of colour. If you have the time and energy for nothing else
while you are in Rome, slip into the abbreviated tour of the Vatican that
encompasses the Chapel. You may have seen the individual murals a thousand times
before, but only by being there can you appreciate the sheer breadth and
physicality of the original. 
</P>
<P>Rome is a city of churches; they proliferate in every square, however
modest, and seemingly on every street corner. They are visited as much for their
secret treasures as for prayer and meditation. During a hot, or wet, day's
sightseeing they make a tranquil refuge from the world outside as well as being
a rich source of artistic discovery. The 16th century Church of Santa Maria
degli Angeli is entered through an inconspicuous door set in the ruin of what
was part of the 3rd century Baths of Diocletian. Inside, the church has been
sculpted by Michelangelo from the old tepidarium (the warm room between the
steam room and the cold plunge) into an elaborate marbled interior. The outlying
ruins of these Diocletian baths also house the Grand Hotel, an aptly-named haunt
of politicians and celebrities (doubles from around $280).   
</P>
<P>Looking at the turbulent state of today's Italian politics -- headquarted in
the late Baroque buildings of the Palazzo del Quirinale -- you might think that
the spirit of the ancient Romans, with their enjoyment of power, lives on in
their modern day counterparts.	&#164;
</P>
<HR>
<H1>How to Avoid Making a Brutta Figura</H1>
<P><I>by Julie Robinson</I></P>
<P></P>
<P><B><I>Figuring out what's not done in Italy</I></B></P>
<P></P>
<P>In Italy, beautiful country that it is, making a <I><B>brutta figura</B></I>
ranks as deserving more hell fire than the seven deadly sins combined.  For the
country which houses Vatican city and where most of the population would call
themselves good Catholics, that's saying something.  The Italians spend their
lives, between capuccinos and voting for yet another doomed government,
wondering if they're guilty of making this brutta figura. So what exactly do
they intend by the term? Brutta figura literally means an &quot;ugly figure.&quot;
In other words, making one of these is the social gaffe, the faux-pas (no, this
isn't a guide to Paris. We're still talking about Italy). It's the putting your
foot in it, not quite doing things the way a particular society expects you to
do them. 
</P>
<P>The first thing to remember is that lots of things we might consider gaffes
do not fall into this category in the Italian social etiquette. You are not, for
example, cocking up if you arrive at a phone cabin, see a long queue (no,
queue's not quite the right word -- let's stick with a &quot;large disorganised
heap of otherwise elegant individuals&quot;) and leap into the cabin as soon as
the previous occupant comes out.  No, this constitutes a bella figura; you're on
the way to being cool and beautiful.    Nor is it making a brutta figura to
leave your mobile on in an important meeting, and interrupting the Chairman's
speech to take a call from your wife who wants to know   whether you want
spaghetti or tagliatelle for dinner. That's a case of showing you're not going
to be intimidated - you score a good 9 out of 10 for that ploy. 
</P>
<P>So, come on, spill the pepperoni already. What behaviour <I>would</I> send
me hurtling towards Dante's inferno? Well, if you hire a car, watch out.
Traffiquette is a dangerous area where the possibilities of making a speedy
figura are rife. Stopping at a traffic light which is red, but where no traffic
is coming from either side, merits minus 10 on the road from hell to purgatory.
The logic is clear:  you're holding up the guy in his brand
new-from-the-concessionaria Alfa Romeo speedster from getting it home to show it
to mamma.  What worse figura could you make?  On a more serious note, post
offices, police stations (should your traffic infractions come to that), and
other public offices are a well-known breeding ground for foreigners infringing
the norms of accepted behaviour. DON'T dare to question the advice of  the guys
behind the desk. It's part of their job description to send you to another
line/office/building/city. The sooner you learn this and accept it with good
grace, as do the nationals, the better for your mental health and general image.
  The same goes for ticket offices. These are part of the divine mystery and any
attempt to genuinely understand the 133 different train and ticket types, not to
mention the supplements, kilometer calculations and special offers, will be met
with pitiful glares if not outright hostility.  Asking for clarification is on a
par with asking the Pope to prove the Trinity to you. Have faith. Nobody's out
to fleece you. There's an unspoken code of honour (mainland Italy has, after
all, acquired something of value from its Sicilian cousins). 
</P>
<P>Have you figured it out yet? The key is to leave your rationality at home.
Ours is not to reason why, as the saying goes. And it goes without saying that
you won't remember a word of this as you're sitting basking in the beautiful
Venice sunshine savouring your cappuccino. Just don't do it in the afternoon!
Deadly sin number eight and a classic in the brutta figura league.  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>Some Travel Resources for Rome &amp; Italy:</I></B></P>
<P></P>
<UL><LI>Amphitryon Holidays: 1-800-424-2471</LI>
<LI>CIT Tours / Italian State Railways: 1-800-CIT-TOUR
</LI>
<LI>Perillo Tours: 1-800-431-1515</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>Further Information:</P>
<P><B>Italian Government Travel Office<BR>12400 Wilshire Blvd., Suite 550<BR>Los
Angeles, CA 90025<BR>1-310-820-0098
</B></P>
