<TITLE>European Visits: Vienna</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Vienna</FONT></H1>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">by Susan Ladika</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<P><STRONG><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">A City of Empire Retains Her Glory</FONT></EM></STRONG><BR></P>
<P>Once the seat of a sprawling empire of fifty million, now capital of a
nation of less than eight million, Vienna has maintained a facade worthy of its
former glory.  Opulent neo-Gothic and neo-Baroque buildings line the boulevard
ringing downtown, while the imposing spire of Gothic St. Stephen's  Cathedral
towers over the central city.  Three stunning palaces grace various sections of
the city; the Vienna Woods, inspiration for Strauss' waltzes, cradle the
northwest edge.  Vienna's historical roots run deep, as deep as the Danube River
that bisects the city.<BR></P>
<P>First settled by Celts around 800 BC, then conquered by the Romans, the
country fell under a succession of rulers.  In 996 the first deed containing the
name &quot;Austria&quot; was recorded, and this year the country celebrates its
1,000th anniversary.  During those early days, the country grew under the
relatively peaceful reign of the Babenberg dynasty.  But the dynasty died out in
1246, giving rise to the Habsburg empire that would rule Austria for more than
600 years and make the country the dominant force in Central Europe for much of
that time.  Shortly before the Habsburg era crumbled with the country's defeat
in World War I, the Austro-Hungarian Empire stretched north into what are now
Poland and the Czech Republic, east to the Ukraine and Romania, and south to
Bosnia and Italy.  But the vestiges of that great empire still can be seen today
-- in the buildings that decorate the street corners; in the people who populate
the town.<BR></P>
<P>This isn't a city of blue-eyed blonds, with last names like Fischer and
Schmidt.  Serbo-Croat and Polish can be heard on the subway, and dozens of
streets are named for those who came from the East.  Perhaps symbolically, the
cornerstone event of this year's anniversary celebration focuses on the Danube
River, which snakes its way through Austria on its course from the Black Forest
to the Black Sea.  The exhibit, to be housed in the 12th century  underground
vaults of the Scots Monastery (Schottenstift), will focus on the history and
culture of those who peopled the banks of the Danube and commemorate the
writers, painters and musicians who brought it fame.  Austria first rose to
power in 1683 with the defeat of the Turks who besieged Vienna.  In 1740, Maria
Theresa became the first woman to inherit the throne.  During her 40 years of
rule, she implemented many social reforms, helped fill the empire's empty
coffers, and gave birth to 16 children.  Among them were Marie Antoinette, who
married French King Louis XVI and later was guillotined, and Marie Louise, who
married Napoleon.<BR>  </P>
<P>Maria Theresa also left some of the most palpable traces of the Habsburg
empire in the city today.  Although she didn't commission the construction of
Schonbrunn -- the Habsburg's magnificent summer palace -- much of it was
redesigned under her instruction, and the empress' presence can be felt
throughout the palace.  Of the more than 1,400 rooms in Schonbrunn, about 40 are
open to the public. Among the most notable are the State Apartments, decorated
in 23&#189;-karat gold, and the Million Room, adorned with scores of priceless
Indian and Persian miniatures.  Under the empress, and the succeeding line of
Habsburgs,  Schonbrunn hosted posh balls and lavish banquets; at age 6, Wolfgang
 Amadeus Mozart performed there for the empress and her court.<BR>  </P>
<P>Following World War II, Vienna (like Berlin), was divided into four zones of
occupation by Allied forces, and the British set up headquarters in Schonbrunn. 
The main Habsburg palace, Hofburg, remains one of the most important buildings
in the inner city.  Its earliest sections were constructed in the 1200s, and
successive rulers added their own touches.  Over the years Hofburg developed
into a sprawling complex of more than 2600 rooms.   The royal apartments most
reflect the influence of Empress Elisabeth &quot;Sisi&quot;, who ruled over the
empire with her husband, Francis Joseph, until her assassination in 1898 by an
Italian anarchist. Sisi, a German princess, couldn't abide strict court
etiquette, and caused quite a stir by insisting on outfitting her apartments
with gymnastics equipment.<BR></P>
<P>Also housed at Hofburg is the Spanish Riding School, established in the late
1500s.  The performance has changed little over the years, as the striking white
Lippizaner stallions are put through their paces, often to the strains of one of
Austria's beloved composers.  At the Palace Chapel (<I>Burgkapelle</I>), the
Vienna Boys' Choir stirs the soul, performing classical and modern works during
Sunday Masses.  The third Habsburg palace, <I>Belvedere</I>, was built in the
1700s, but secured its place in history two centuries later: the palace was the
residence of Franz Ferdinand, whose 1914 assassination in Sarajevo gave rise to
World War I. Actually two separate buildings, <I>Oberes Belvedere</I> (Upper
Belvedere) contains works of 19th and 20th century Austrian artists,
particularly the gold-touched paintings of Gustav Klimt.  The lower floor of the
building houses a continually changing display of artworks.<BR></P>
<P>In <I>Unteres Belvedere</I> (Lower Belvedere), Baroque art is showcased. 
Some of Austria's most treasured art is on display at the <I>Kunsthistorisches
</I>(Art History Museum), located across from the Hofburg.  The Art History
Museum was constructed in the late 1800s to house the treasure trove of artworks
collected by the Habsburgs as their empire expanded. The most prized rooms are
the Egyptian-Oriental Collection, which contains  everything from mummies to
bronzes, and the Picture Gallery, housing an overwhelming collection of
paintings from throughout Europe, with works from Brueghel, Durer, Rembrandt and
Raphael among the most prominent.<BR></P>
<P>The Art History Museum and its twin, the Natural History Museum, are among
the dozens of historic buildings lining <I>Ringstrasse</I>, Vienna's most
beautiful boulevard.  In the mid-1800s the medieval walls cradling downtown were
razed to make way for construction of the Ring; buildings from this era, along
with the art and history of the time, are commemorated in a special exhibition
at the <I>Kunstlerhaus</I> (Academy of Fine Arts).  Other elegant buildings
along the Ring are the <I>Rathaus </I>(Town Hall), whose tower pokes above the
trees in the surrounding park, and the <I>Burgtheater</I> (National Theater),
crowned with busts of influential writers.  Inside the Ring stands what is
arguably Vienna's most visible symbol, <I>Stephansdom</I> (St. Stephen's
Cathedral).  Its towering steeple and distinctive roof tiles of green, yellow,
and white dominate the heart of downtown.  Founded in the 12th century, the
cathedral was destroyed by fire a hundred years later, then rebuilt in the
Gothic style.  With a bit of energy, one can climb the 344 steps of St.
Stephen's south tower for a stunning view of Vienna and its surroundings. <BR>
</P>
<P>A few blocks away is the <I>Staatsoper</I> (State Opera). Built in the
1860s, the Opera was subject to such criticism that one of the architects killed
himself.  But it quickly became a favorite in the hearts and minds of the
Viennese, and has long been considered one of the leading opera houses in the
world.  Like many other grand buildings in the city, the Opera was destroyed by
Allied bombs during World War II; reconstruction took 10 years.  Today an opera
or ballet, accompanied by the Viennese Philharmonic orchestra, is performed
every evening  September to June.  <BR></P>
<P>Vienna is a city steeped in musical tradition, which will be remembered this
year in an anniversary exhibit called &quot;The Message of Music,&quot; 
featuring everything from antique musical instruments to historic musical scores
to portraits of famous musicians.  Beethoven, Mozart, Strauss and Haydn are
among the composers who brought Vienna renown, and tiny museums to these greats
are scattered around town in homes where they once lived. Although born in
Salzburg, Mozart composed such world-famous operas as &quot;The Marriage of
Figaro,&quot; &quot;The Magic Flute,&quot; and &quot;Don Giovanni&quot; while
residing in Vienna.  But he died penniless at age 35, and was buried in a
pauper's grave.  The German-born Ludwig van Beethoven moved to Vienna at age 22
and lived in numerous apartments around the city; he was often evicted because
of his vile temperament and late-night compositions.  Through  works like &quot;The
Blue Danube&quot; and &quot;Tales From the Vienna  Woods,&quot; Johann Strauss
Jr. made features of the Vienna landscape  synonymous with waltzes.<BR></P>
<P>The outdoors has a vital role in the lives of the Viennese, who can be found
out for a Sunday stroll in even the most inclement weather.  Among their
favorite haunts is the <I>Lainzer Tiergarten</I> (Lainz Animal Reserve), once a
hunting ground for the Habsburgs.  It also will be the site for an anniversary
exhibit on the history of hunting in Austria. Austrians also frequent the <I>Prater</I>,
a game preserve for the aristocracy that was turned into a public park in 1766. 
Today, the 3,200-acre Prater features an amusement park whose giant ferris wheel
(the <I>Riesenrad</I>) is visible from many parts of the city. There also are
miles of pathways, a swimming pool, tennis courts, horseback riding trails, a
golf course, and facilities for almost any sport.<BR></P>
<P>For a true taste of the countryside, the <I>Wienerwald</I> (Vienna Woods)
is just a short ride from downtown, with miles of hiking trails wandering
through the rolling hills and lush woods.  There's even a public swimming pool
perched on a hill overlooking the city.  On the way back down from the Vienna
Woods, travelers can pass through the quaint village of Grinzing, notable for
its wine pubs (<I>Heurige</I>). Many still make their own wine from the
vineyards that grow almost outside their doors.  Most have cheerful,
vine-covered gardens, and dish up hot and cold meals and hearty servings of
Austrian <I>gemutlichkeit</I>.  &#164;</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I>Susan Ladika is a free-lance journalist based in Vienna.</I></P>
<HR>
<H4><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Selected Anniversary Events</FONT></H4>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">&#183; Open Season - the History of Hunting in
Austria:</FONT></B> The Hermes Castle in the Lainz Game Reserve (Lainzer
Tiergarten) in the city's 13th District will feature an exhibit on the
importance of hunting in the imperial household. Weapons, paintings and
figurines depicting hunting scenes, and photographs of the Habsburgs hunting
will be on display. The exhibit will be open Wednesday through Sunday and
holidays from 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Admission is 50 schillings (about $5 per
person).  Through Feb. 16, 1997.<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">The Danube, 1,000 Years of Austria - a Journey:
</FONT></B> Celebrating the people and culture of the Danube River, this exhibit
will be held in the Scots Monastery (Schottenstift), Freyung 6. Also featured
will be the artists who helped bring the Danube fame. The exhibit will be open
daily from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is 90 schillings (about $9). May 23 to
Sept. 29 1996.  <B><I>(See story next page -- Ed.)</I></B><BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Dream of Happiness - The Art of Historicism in
Europe:</FONT></B> The grand buildings of the Ringstrasse are Vienna's most
visible symbols of historicism.  Exhibits of artworks and historical
developments during this era also will be on display at the Academy of Fine Arts
(Akademie der Bildenden Kunste),  Schillerplatz 3. It will be open daily from 10
a.m. to 6 p.m.  and Thursdays from 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. Admission is 90 schillings.
Sept. 13 1996 to Jan. 6, 1997.</P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">The Message of Music - 1,000 Years of Music in
Austria:</FONT></B>  With its rich musical tradition, Vienna has the world's
largest collection of musical instruments, scores and portraits of musicians.
Many will be on display at the Palais Harrach, Freyung 3. The exhibit will be
held daily from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. and Thursdays from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. Admission
is 90 schillings.  Oct. 27 1996 to February 1997.<BR></P>
<P>For more information, contact the Austrian National Tourist Office in New
York: <B>212-944-6880</B>. </P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080"> - Susan Ladika</FONT></I></P>
<HR>
<H2>The Danube: 1,000 Years of Austria, a Journey.</H2>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">by Julius Formanek, Jr.</FONT></I><BR></P>
<P>This year Austria celebrates the fact that the name <I>Ostarrichi</I>
appeared for the first time in an offical document with many concerts,
exhibitions and other events.  Of course today's Austria has only few things,
geographic or political, in common with the Ostarrichi from 996; but what
Austrians are celebrating is not a nation but an idea, which is represented by
the name Austria.  The Danube embodies this idea, and the history, culture, and
way of life of this region, with so many different nations living along the
river's 2,800 kilometers, is the object of the Milleniums-Exhibition &quot;Die
Donau: 1000 Jahre Osterreich; Eine Reise,&quot; presented through September in
the catacombs of the Schottenstift in Vienna.<BR></P>
<P>The presentation team, led by Dr.Gunther Dumriegl, attempts to capture in 16
&quot;chapters&quot; the feelings and moments in time that can convey to a
visitor the idea of Austria.  Chapter One features black &amp; white photographs
over the last 30 years; in Chapter Two, installations by artists like Fabrizio
Plessi and Hiroshi Sugimoto expound on the idea of &quot;Water&quot;.  Chapters
3 &amp; 4 tell about the landscape and the economic development of the
Danube-region.  The connection of history and Austria's important personalities
is the theme of Chapter 5.  Many original documents and more historical objects
are shown in Chapter 8, the central part of the exhibition.  The role of the
church is illuminated in Chapter 10, where among many other objects you will
find the original 1816 manuscript of the christmas song, <I>Stille Nacht,
heilige Nacht</I> (&quot;Silent Night&quot;) by Josef Mohr and Franz Gruber. 
Chapter 11 tells us the story of the region's Jewish culture, one of its most
important influences.  But, this chapter also shows us a dark side in the
history of the people of the Danube. <BR></P>
<P>Other chapters touch on the history of wine (Chapter 6), art (Chapter 13),
film (Chapter 14), Music (Chapter 15), and literature (Chapter 16). Among the
many exhibits are pictures of Klimt and Schiele, musical manuscripts of Strauss
or Mahler, and personal belongings of Peter Altenberg or Johann Nestroy. My
personal favorite is Chapter 12, &quot;Nature,&quot; where a fantastic
ten-minute multi-media show takes us into the romantic Danube Valley; here it is
neither a geographic nor a political valley, but just a beauty; sit down, listen
and look.  You will like it.  &#164;<BR></P>
<P><I>Julius Formanek, Jr. is the owner of a small 3-star hotel and a proud
resident of  Vienna.  He invites you to visit his Web page at
<A HREF="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/Fuerstenhof">http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/Fuerstenhof.</A></I></P>
