<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/checkit.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<HR>
<P><B>We regularly comb the marketplace to see what's on tap for European
travelers, and in each issue of <I>European Visits</I> we'll list some the
better bargains or more unusual offerings here on the <I>Check It Out</I> page.
 Keep in mind that prices and availability are always subject to change. 
However, we do our best to check what we publish, and everything listed here was
available as <I>EV</I> went to press.  If you find something of interest, do us
a favor -- tell them you saw it in <I>European Visits</I>!</B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Steigenberger Reservation Service</B> has unveiled their &quot;Summer in
Europe&quot; hotel program, which carries on the Dollars &amp; Sense discounts
we reported last issue.  From April 1 to September 30, SRS can provide you with
first-class or deluxe accommodations in dozens of European cities at up to 45%
off regular room rates.  Some examples include the Hotel Europa Tyrol in <B>Innsbruck</B>
at $179, the Savoy in <B>Berlin</B> at $199, and the Hotel Quirinale in <B>Rome</B>
at $179 (prices are for twin; singles are lower).  Your rates are guaranteed in
US funds when you book, so there are no currency surprises.  In most cases a
buffet breakfast is included.  SRS represents some quality budget properties as
well, with rates as low as $119 in <B>London</B> or $99 in <B>Brussels</B>. 
They can put together special package rates for groups, too.  <B>800-200-1111</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Maupintour</B> has taken advantage of the opening of the Main-Danube
canal to put together a river cruise that takes you all the way from <B>Vienna</B>
to <B>Amsterdam</B>.  Aboard the deluxe hotel ship M/V Queen of Holland, the
20-day trip takes in <B>Regensburg</B>, <B>Nurnberg</B>, historic <B>Rothenburg</B>,
and <B>Cologne</B> (among other stops) as it wends its way via the Danube,
Main, and Rhine Rivers.  Shore excursions, including <B>Munich</B> and <B>Heidelberg</B>,
and nearly 50 meals are included in the $5630 land/cruise price (pp/do).  Single
supplements and add-on airfares are available.  Maupintour, <B>800-255-4266.</B></P>
<HR>
<P>If you're skipping a European jaunt this year for lack of time, consider
<B>TWA's</B> &quot;City Getaway&quot; packages.  You can have three nights in
<B>Paris</B>, <B>Rome</B>, or <B>London</B> from as little as $750 pp/do <I>including</I>
<I>airfare</I> from New York.  Airport transfers and breakfasts are included,
and you get 5,000 frequent flyer points to boot.  Discounted connecting flights
from other departure points are available, as are additional nights.  A choice
of hotels from budget to deluxe is offered.  TWA Getaway Vacations, <B>800-GETAWAY</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Did Nathalie Zeidman's article on <B>Budapest's</B> spas (<B><I>EV</I></B>,
<I>April</I>/<I>May</I> 96<I>)</I> tempt you?  Contact <B>Tradesco Tours</B>.
 They have a package that includes 21 nights at the Margitsziget Health Resort,
with half-board and complete spa therapy, starting at $1814 pp/do.   Includes
round-trip air from New York with departures June 8, 29, July 20, and August 10.
 <B>800-833-3402</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>If you've wanted to visit <B>Poland</B>, July might be the time: the
Polonaise Music Festival of Warsaw/Cracow runs July 25 to August 2.  Highlights
will include a a concert at the Royal Castle in Warsaw, a performance of
Mozart's Magic Flute, entertainment by Folklore Dance Ensembles, and many more
attractions.  <B>Pat Tours</B> can provide more information: <B>800-388-0988</B>.
 Another good source information on Poland's many travel opportunities is <B>Orbis
Polish Travel Bureau Inc</B>., <B>212-867-5011</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>The longtime publication of railway travel, <B>International Railway
Traveler</B>, has recast itself as <I>The Society of International Railway
Travelers</I>.  Under the new heading IRT will augment its quality journalism
with a selection of carefully planned rail tours, including a week-long Grand
Tour of <B>England</B> &amp; <B>Scotland</B> featuring travel on the legendary
Royal Scotsman train, &quot;through the beautiful Scottish mountains and glens&quot;.
 Contact IRT at <B>800-IRT-4881</B> for more information.</P>
<HR>
<P>Interested in seeing Europe by the more leisurely self-propelled routes? 
Try <B>Euro-Bike and Walk Tours</B>, <B>800-321-6060</B>.  If you prefer
floating, <B>Travcoa</B> offers a luxury escorted tour that includes a balloon
ride over Burgundy; <B>800-992-2003</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Members of <B>Best</B> <B>Western</B>'s Gold Crown Club can earn a
one-year membership in Hale Irwin's Golf Passport program, which entitles the
holder to 2 free rounds of golf at more than 1,600 courses around the world,
including <B>Ireland</B>, <B>Scotland</B>, and <B>Spain</B>.  The passport
also qualifies for discounts of 10%-15% off hotel packages at many golf resorts.
 It takes 1250 points for a single membership or 2400 for a double.  Best
Western Gold Crown Club, <B>800-237-8483</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Consumer Reports Travel Letter gives a good rating to the <B>Entertainment
Europe Hotel Directory</B> when it comes to discount hotel plans for European
travel.  The half-price hotel card sells for $47 and gets you a significant
discount from regular rates at more than 800 European hotels.  Entertainment
Publications, <B>800-445-4137</B>.  (CR's monthly publication for travelers
offers a wealth of  objective, best-value information along these lines: for
subscription information call <B>800-234-1970</B>.)</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Austria</B> will be a great visit in 1996, as they celebrate their
1,000-year anniversary.  You'll find festivals, special museum exhibitions,
concerts, and much more on the agenda.  The US office of the Austrian Tourist
Bureau can send you brochures.  <B>212-944-6880</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>If you plan on doing a lot of shopping in Europe, ask your travel agent for
a <B>Europe Tax-Free Shopping</B> brochure before you go.  This program is
designed to make it easier for you to claim the VAT tax refunds you're entitled
to as a visitor.  If your agent doesn't have the information, contact the &quot;Europe
Tax-Free Shopping&quot; office in Chicago at <B>312-382-1101</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>The <B>Eurostar</B> train is getting a lot of attention, but cross-Channel
airlines aren't standing idle.  <B>British Midland</B> is advertising one-way
fares from <B>London</B> to <B>Paris</B> or <B>Brussels</B> for just $109,
plus a variety of further European destinations at $139.  They also have a &quot;Discover
Europe Airpass&quot; that can save you money on multiple journeys.  British
Midland, <B>800-788-0555</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>American Airlines'</B> international business class offers something
unique: personal video players.  Passengers in the plush new business cabin are
provided with a Sony portable video player and their choice of films from an
in-flight library of ten titles.  AA has also upgraded pitch (room between seat
rows) to 50&quot;, making it one of the roomiest business classes in the air. 
American Airlines, <B>800-433-7300</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>You may not think first of <B>Istanbul</B> when you think jazz, but their
24th annual International Music Festival starts June 6 and features a variety of
musical performances ranging from classical to ballet to pop -- and yes, to
jazz.  <B>Megatrails</B>, a tour operator with a variety of Mediterranean
packages on offer, can tell you more at <B>800-547-1211</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>The <B><I>Educated Traveler</I></B> newsletter offers (among many other
things) an annual listing of  the best museum tours around.  Two of their
European picks for 1996 are <I>Villas and Bardens in the Veneto and Lake
Regions of Northern Italy</I>, a tour emphasizing &quot;palaces, villas,
museums, and gardens&quot; sponsored by the Connecticut State Museum of Natural
History (800-486-4460) and <I>Britain's Maritime Heritage</I>, an itinerary
including &quot;London, Portsmouth, Bath, Oxford, and the 18th century
shipbuilding village of Bucklers,&quot; put together by the Mariner's Museum of
Newport News (804-591-7795).  The Educated Traveler is available by
subscription, $39 per year; <B>800-648-5168</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Copenhagen</B> is 1996's Cultural Capital of Europe, and a vast number
of special events, performances, and exhibitions  are scheduled throughout the
year.  The agenda includes a run of the new Hans Christian Andersen Musical at
Copenhagen's Gladsaxe Theatre.  Call the Danish Tourist Board for a full kit of
information: <B>212-949-2333</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>If you need to stay at The Ritz at least once in your life, now's the time. 
The legendary <I>luxe</I> <B>London</B> property is marking its 90th
anniversary with a number of special packages.  &quot;Putting On The Ritz&quot;
offers a one-night stay with champagne, fruit, flowers, and a comfortably late
checkout for $320.  Could be a great way to celebrate your arrival in London, or
a memorable &quot;one last night&quot; to wind up a trip.  Bookings, <B>800-525-4800</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Want to see &quot;everything&quot; on your European cruise?  Check out the
Everything Cruise.  Departing July 15 from <B>Helsinki</B>, Finland, this
packed excursion features stops at <B>St</B>. <B>Petersburg</B>, <B>Tallinn</B>,
<B>Riga</B>, <B>Klaipeda</B> (Lithuania), <B>Gdynia</B> (Poland), and <B>Copenhagen</B>.
 An optional tour of <B>Vilnius</B> can be added.  Air from New York is
included at $2199 pp/do.  <B>EuroCruises</B>, <B>212-691-2099</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>If you're a true Anglophile and would like a bit of <B>England</B> on hand
all year, Fleet Street Publications can handle stateside subscriptions to a wide
variety of British magazines and newspapers -- you can even have the <I>Sunday
Post</I> delivered to your door each week for $95 per year.  Write Fleet Street
Publications, PO Box 301369, Escondido CA 92030, or fax <B>619-432-6560</B>. 
Another way to keep Jolly Old England on tap is with the <B>British Video
Collection</B>: they carry hundreds of British video titles ranging from BBC
comedy classics (&quot;Fawlty Towers&quot;,  &quot;Yes, Prime Minister&quot;) to
unique travelogues (&quot;Secret Gardens of Ireland&quot;, &quot;Walled City of
Chester&quot;).  Call <B>800-959-0061</B> for the complete catalog.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>France</B> fanatics can get a taste of their favorite country by mail,
too -- quite literally.  <B>Joie de Vivre</B> in Modesto, California has a
complete catalog of authentic French delicacies ranging from foie gras to
candied chestnuts to dried wild mushrooms.  Call for their mouth-watering
catalog and you can begin re-living those memorable meals at home.  They also
offer a set of Cordon Bleu cookbooks and videos to help you do it right.  <B>800-648-8854</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>DERrail</B> is actively promoting  &quot;hotel trains,&quot; which offer
overnight rail travel between a number of major European cities in newly-built
sleeper cars with facilities and services closer to that of a hotel than the
traditional night train.  Pre-boarding, room service, personal showers and WCs,
and other amenities are making the hotel trains a favorite with business and
leisure travelers alike. Some of the routes covered are <B>Bonn-Berlin</B>,
<B>Cologne-Vienna</B>, and <B>Hamburg-Zurich</B>.  Eurail passes are valid
although a supplement ranging from $77 to $111 per person is payable for
accommodations.  For budget travelers, the new trains also offer reclining seats
in second class.  DERrail, <B>800-782-2424</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>For mountain-hiking fans, an important number to take along to Italy is that
of <B>Club Alpino Italiano</B>, which owns nearly 600 huts in the mountain
districts that can be used for a small fee by campers.  They publish an annual
guide complete with maps and information on access &amp; tariffs.  You can write
to them at Via Ugo Foscolo 3, 20122 Milan, or in Italy call <B>(02)720-230-085</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Rail Europe</B> is offering a 50% companion discount on three railpass
products:  the Benelux Tourrail Pass (for <B>Belgium</B>, <B>Luxembourg</B>,
and the <B>Netherlands</B>); the France Railpass, and the Swiss Pass/Flexipass.
 The discount gives two people traveling together a half -price pass for the
second person.  Some date restrictions apply to the Swiss passes.  Another new
bargain is the UK France Sampler, which offers three days unlimited train travel
in <B>France</B>, a one-way Eurostar ticket, and three consecutive days' rental
car with unlimited mileage in <B>Britain</B>. Prices depend on rail and rental
car classes selected.   They've also extended booking hours to Saturdays for the
summer.  <B>800</B>-<B>4EURAIL</B></P>
<HR>
<P>Travelers who really want to <I>live</I> in the country they visit often
turn to homestays in place of hotels.  In <B>France, Accueil France Famille</B>
can arrange paid lodging with host families in <B>Paris</B> and the
countryside.  Write to them at 5, rue Fran&ccedil;ois Cop&eacute;e, 75015 Paris,
or in France call <B>(1) 45-54-22-39</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>A new express bus service, <B>Cityzap</B>, was scheduled to make its debut
in Europe March 1.  Targeting younger independent travelers with low fares, free
Cokes and snacks, and onboard MTV music videos, the line will run
air-conditioned coaches from <B>London</B> to <B>Paris</B> and <B>Amsterdam</B>,
with one evening and one morning departure from each city.  The 50-seat buses
take the Channel Tunnel using <I>Le</I> <I>Shuttle</I> vehicle trains, cutting
journey time to 6 hours London-Paris, an hour more for Amsterdam.  One-way fare
is $49 per person, with discounts available for multi-city travel.  Contact
Thomas McFerran Reservations at <B>800-430-9070</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Taking your laptop computer (and EuroData, of course) abroad?  Worried about
theft or dropping it on the platform as you run for the train?  <B>Safeware
Insurance</B> now offers international coverage for your computer equipment --
which your homeowner's policy may not.  Find out more about their policies at
<B>800-800-1492</B>, or go saf on CompuServe.</P>
<HR>
<P>For road vacations in Europe, <B>Europe by Car</B> may have the most
comprehensive selection of rental options.  They offer 1- to 3-week packages
from as little as $99 (for a Fiat Panda in <B>Germany</B>), with many
additional models available including minibuses.  Hotel discounts offered too. 
Make advance reservations at <B>800-223-1516</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Our Family Abroad</B>, specialists in gay &amp; lesbian travel, has put
together a package excursion to <B>Paris</B> that includes the legendary
Bastille Day Gay Ball on the Quai de la Tournelle.  The 6-day tour includes
visits to musums and P&egrave;re Lachaise Cemetery, where Oscar Wilde, Gertrude
Stein, and Alice B. Toklas (among others) are laid to rest.  Price is $947
land-only or $1724 including air from New York (pp/do; single supplement $434). 
The tour departs July 9.  Special Tours &amp; Travel Ltd. handles reservations:
<B>800-999-5500</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Best Western</B> has added four new properties to its portfolio in <B>Spain</B>.
 They are the Hotel Cortezo, near the Prado in <B>Madrid</B>; the Hotel Barajas
near Madrid airport (a short distance by rail or road to the capital); the Hotel
Gravina near Plaza Cataluna in <B>Barcelona</B>; and the Hotel Becquer in the
heart of <B>Saville</B>.  They have also increased their already generous
roster of hotels in <B>Germany</B> with eight new ones.  As with all Best
Western European hotels, the new listings offer a combination of 3- or 4-star
amenities with reasonable prices and easy advance booking from the States. <B>800-528-1234</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>If you're looking for lodging in those small, traditional, family-run hotels
of <B>Italy</B>, Group Travel Enterprises' &quot;Small Italian Hotels&quot;
program represents almost 170 of them.  They can book villas, farmhouses, and
castles too, along with Italian rail and rental car arrangements.  Prices are
excellent with 3-star rooms starting at $71 in Rome, $80 in <B>Milan</B>, and
$85 in <B>Venice</B>.  Many other destinations are represented.  Visit Group
Travel Enterprises on the World Wide Web at  http://www.gteinc.com or call <B>800-66-ITALY</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Alamo</B> has got week-long auto rentals as low as $100 in <B>Belgium</B>,
<B>Germany</B>, and the <B>UK</B>, or from $150 in <B>Austria</B>, the <B>Netherlands</B>,
and <B>Switzerland</B>.  Rates are for economy cars, and other fees/charges may
apply.  <B>800-522-9696</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>EuroSeven</B> offers a &quot;Discover Jewish London&quot; program which &quot;explores
the history and culture of English Jews from the Norman Conquest to today.&quot;
 The fully-escorted tour, starting at $1545 pp/do, departs May 1, July 10,
August 7, and October 9.  Contact EuroSeven at <B>800-890-3876</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Those hand-held translators are getting more powerful every year.  One of
the latest models, the <B>World-Mate Translator</B>, contains 10,500 words in
each of 15 different languages, along with ten categories of complete phrases
and an 8-country currency exchange calculator -- it's about the size of a
paperback book and totes at just 5&#189; ounces.  Order for $99 from Travel
Smart, <B>800-327-3633</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>More smoke-free flights: <B>Lufthansa</B> will ban the butts on all
trans-Atlantic routes beginning June 1, as will <B>USAir</B>.  Call <B>800-645-3880</B>
for Lufthansa fares and destinations, <B>800-872-4738</B> for USAir.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Country Cottages</B> has a 1-week countryside vacation plan in <B>France</B>
that offers a selection of 125 privately owned homes, ranging from <B>Provan&ccedil;al</B>
villas to an 18th-century stone cottage in <B>Burgundy</B>; though many
properties are turn-of-the-century or older, all offer modern amenities
including private baths and up-to-date kitchens.  All furnishings are provided,
and the package includes a minivan for exploring the area.  Prices start at $999
per person, land only.  <B>800-674-8883</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Finally, a most unusual offering comes from <B>Grandtravel</B> in Maryland:
they specialize in putting together vacations designed especially for
grandparents &amp; grandchildren.  Among their present offerings is a 13-day
tour of <B>Switzerland</B> that takes in a number of Swiss villages and cities
and includes walking tours, &quot;gentle&quot; hikes, cable-car and cog-railway
rides, and informative museum visits.  Add a visit to a real-life chocolate
factory and a bobsleigh ride, and you have a trip that both generations can
enjoy equally.  Sensibly, they gear their tours to the age groups of the
children: there's a July 22 departure for children aged 7 to 11 and an August 5
departure for older kids 12 to 17.  All-inclusive land prices are $4450 per
adult and $4415 per child.  For more information about this or other &quot;very
special vacations for grandparents and grandchildren&quot;, contact Grandtravel
at <B>800-247-7651</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Credit Where Credit Is Due:</B>  While we dig up <I>Check It Out</I>
nuggets from a great variety of sources, we'd be lost without our &quot;wicking
stick&quot;, the excellent coverage found in <B><I>Travel Weekly</I></B>.  The
premier newspaper of the travel industry, published twice weekly by Reed Travel
Group, <B><I>TW</I></B> offers exhaustive coverage of travel issues, companies
and products.  If you're professionally involved in the travel business and
don't have a subscription, you're missing out.  Call Reed at <B>800-360-0015</B>
or visit them on the 'Net at <A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/two">http://www.traveler.net/two</A>.</P>
<HR>
