<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - The Hague; Des Indes
Hotel / Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">A Dutch Stone Dowager</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>Des Indes' Ghostly Charm, by Kit Snedaker</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<P><!--A Dutch Stone Dowager  Des Indes Ghostly Charm By Kit Snedaker-->The
Hague's des Indes Hotel, more than a century old, doesn't look a day over 50. 
This Dutch stone dowager has been as carefully preserved as a hot house tulip,
but like any lively old society matriarch, des Indes isn't sustained by care
alone.  A large part of the hotel&#146;s charm stems from its exciting past: 
the celebrities, the secrets, the ghosts.<BR></P>
<P>Des Indes was classy from the beginning.  On July 15, 1881 Empress Eugenie,
wife of Louis Napoleon, put her signature at the top of the first page of the
register.  Years later John Philip Sousa signed in with a staff of musical
notes; Arthur Rubinstein simply penned his name.  So did author Thomas Mann and
King Gustaf Adolf of Sweden.  Chang Sui-Chi listed himself as Secretary of the
Chinese Ministry of Ceremonies and Li Ching-Su included both his titles: <I>Mandarin
of the Third Grade</I> and <I>Secretary of the Chinese Ministry of Punishments</I>.
  
<BR></P>
<P>Big name guests were scarce during World War I, even though Holland was
neutral.  If it hadn't been for Mata Hari, born Margaretha Zelle in Dutch
Friesland, things might have been slow at The Hague's best hotel.  As a snappy
little German spy, Mata Hari used des Indes so frequently in her work a Dutch
television crew chose the hotel as the location of a documentary about her.  For
drama, however, des Indes never saw anything like Anna Pavlova.  The 50-year-old
ballerina arrived in a cold January, 1931, with an ominous cough.  She was
scheduled for a farewell performance of her signature role, the dying swan from
Swan Lake, at the Tivoli Theater.  The cough came on, she said, after spending
hours helping injured passengers when her train jumped the track outside of
town.  By showtime the cough had become pneumonia and the star lay abed in the
hotel, gasping for breath.   
<BR></P>
<P>Tradition dies hard.  A standing-room-only crowd waited impatiently as the
orchestra struck up the opening bars of Tchaikowsky's score.  The Tivoli
scrambled to improvise.  A quick-witted electrician looked about, grabbed a pink
spot and bounced the light around the empty stage as though it were Pavlova
turning into the ethereal  dying swan.   Dying indeed!  At half past midnight,
moments after the pink spot took its final curtain call, Pavlova drew her last
breath.  From then on the room behind the front desk was called the Anna Pavlova
Room in her memory.  
<BR></P>
<P>With good reason, as it turned out. From time to time puzzled guests report
seeing a woman in white tutu and pointes wandering down the grand staircase late
at night, as though waiting for her cue.  At the bottom she steps lightly
forward and just disappears. 
<BR></P>
<P>After World War II a younger specter began to show up.  In one of the rooms
(no one will say which) a guest glanced up from his bath to see a Nazi officer
in his undershirt, braces hanging over his uniform trousers, shaving at the
basin.  The officer toweled off and moved through what is now a wall, but put
there since the war.  The startled guest heard breaking glass, a shot and the
Nazi disappeared.  One explanation points to the hotel's black years of German
occupation when Nazis used the des Indes as an officers' billet.  On the roof,
in abandoned pigeon coops Dutch resistance workers hid Jewish refugees and
downed allied flyers waiting to be spirited to England.   
<BR></P>
<P>Between ghosts and traditions the hotel isn't an easy place to run with
seamless service, even in good years.  Not long ago, for instance, a Dutch
actress phoned from Paris to say she left her diamond rings behind.  The manager
assured her he wouldn't rest until he found them.  He did.  In the men's room. 
The rings went off by messenger.  She never asked where they were found and the
manager didn't burden her with that unsolicited information.  Des Indes has been
through enough to understand discretion. 
<BR></P>
<P>Haile Selassie's extended stay in 1958 called for even greater diplomacy. 
The pint-size potentate was uncomfortable at meals because dining room chairs
only brought his head level with his plate.  To bring him up to imperial
eye-level with his guests, the hotel built a throne-like high chair that raised
the Lion of Juda from plate-level to monarch-level -- at least even  with his
dinner partners.    Selassie's chair is still in the lobby, but the hotel hasn't
been so lucky with other memorabilia.  Most of the monogrammed door handles
disappeared into the pockets of light-fingered guests.  A Persian rug rode out
the front door on the shoulders of two men posing as rug cleaners.  A couple of
priceless Chinese vases vanished out the window of the Pavlova Room.   <BR></P>
<P>Despite such lapses in good manners, the hotel has not lowered its standards
a bit.  Des Indes's waiters still wear white gloves to pass such hors d'oeuvres
as Beluga caviar and golden snail eggs.  At banquets they stand, one behind
every two guests, to serve meals the may begin with foie gras and Dutch pea soup
and last into the night.  After dessert these same white-gloved waiters
ceremoniously warm cigars over a flame, clip the ends, dip them in Cognac and
offer one to each male diner. 
<BR></P>
<P>Such courtesies aren't limited to guests.  Des Indes also feeds celebrated
animals.  Every year the hotel opens Den Haag's toney horse show with a banquet
for the entries.  In the park in front of the hotel's entrance, show horses
prance up to silver platters of oats and apples on a long table set with silver
candelabra.  Visiting riding teams, the Canadian Mounted Police, for one, are
feted the same way.  Des Indes has also invited circus elephants to their own
elegant brunch. 
<BR></P>
<P>It's difficult to know whether the tone for the place is set by the hotel or
the town.  Unlike the rest of determinedly middle-class Holland, The Hague is an
elite village.  Its center, a 13th century Hall of Knights, is the seat of the
country's parliament.  The Queen opens the proceedings with a royal flourish
every September even though she is sworn in (not crowned) in Amsterdam, the
capital.  The royal family calls Den Haag home and the Dutch speak of it the way
Americans refer to such exclusive communities as Kennebunkport, Maine, Newport,
Rhode Island or Grosse Pointe, Michigan. 
<BR></P>
<P>If The Hague is the nation's aristocratic heart, des Indes represents stout,
corporal Holland.  For more than 100 years the hotel has remained stately and
plump, aloof from fire, war and natural disasters, sheltering guests and their
ghosts, gathering legends, a survivor by pride of place.  &#164;<BR></P>
<P><I>Des Indes Hotel, Lange Voorhout 54-56, 2514 EG The Hague, Holland. Ph:
070-363-2932, Fax: 070-345-1721.   Guide Michelin gives des Indes a Grand
Comfort rating. 
</I></P>
<HR>
