<TITLE>European Visits: Cathar Country</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Castle-Hopping Cathar Country</H2>
<P><I>by Douglas Walters</I><BR></P>
<P><B><I>Valleys of Vineyards, Limestone, and History</I></B><BR></P>
<P><B>The Corbieres region in southern France</B> is wind:  wild, wandering
wind, blowing over dazzling white-rock mountains swarming with lizards and
covered with Mediterranean steppe. There&#146;s a little water running down;
small rivers such as the Agly, a crystal-clear stream which threads its way
spectacularly through the narrow, precipitous rock walls of the Galamus Gorge. 
Corbieres is also cassoulet and red wine, the capital of the former, and one of
France&#146;s premier regions for the latter.  In this respect it&#146;s genuine
grass-roots French Culture, far removed from Europe&#146;s discos and urban
sprawl. But most of all, Corbieres is Cathar country.<BR></P>
<P>The Cathars were fanatical Middle Age religious heretics.  They&#146;re long
gone now, victims of the Crusades, but their memory is alive and well.  It lurks
in their remote, abandoned castles in Corbieres, about ten  in all. Most of them
were commanding-heights fortresses, literally built on to the highest points of 
steep rock hills.  The Cathars&#146; aim was, like that of most religious sects,
to escape the rest of the world.  Strictly ascetic -- the Greek origin of the
word cathar means &#147;pure&#148;    they rejected certain beliefs of the
Catholic Church, including the Holy Sacraments and ecclesiastical hierarchy. 
This naturally put them at odds with the Church, ensuring their demise.  The
Cathars&#146; belvederes helped them achieve spiritual eternity, but they couldn&#146;t
escape the French government.    The King&#146;s troops finished them off by
starving most of them out and burning alive the non-repenters in the Thirteenth
Century.  <BR></P>
<P>Today the remnants of their castles overlook vast bucolic valleys of
vineyards and limestone held in place by stunted Mediterranean oak and juniper. 
The Chateau de Foix is the westernmost and most accessible stronghold, about an
hour south of Toulouse off Route Nationale 20.  The rest of the Cathar castles
run roughly eastward to the Mediterranean, irregularly spaced from each other at
ten to 40-minute driving intervals.  Corbieres&#146;s winding provincial roads
make for relatively easy access...until the last few hundred meters before each
castle.  This is where you briefly need your hiking boots because the final
stretch to reach most of the castles is rocky and steep.  Off-road vehicles
couldn&#146;t make it, even if they were allowed to try.  Pack-mule power 
facilitates maintenance work.  As a result, most of the Cathar castles have no
tourist facilities whatsoever, except an isolated cashier (you pay for
everything in France).  This makes the self-guided tours pleasantly close to
nature, and far less crowded and cluttered than most other places in the
country.You pay a nominal $2 fare, then hike the last few steep, rocky meters
up.   This takes anywhere from 10 to 30 minutes depending on the castle and your
lung capacity.<BR></P>
<P>But get ready:  once up you can see forever, and then some.   And you
quickly take to heart the cashier&#146;s advice to hang on to any railings, and
not stray close to unfenced edges.   Corbieres, you see, is the windiest place
in France.   There&#146;s usually a decent blow going on in the valley bottoms,
to say nothing of the castle promontories where sustained winds of 30-70mph are
far from rare, even on clear days.   Gusts are frequently much higher, making it
easy to realize why the Cathars sought out their splendid isolation here.  On
the other hand, this is also the warmest part of France, so you can make the
visit at almost any time of the year.   Outside of the French tourist season in
late spring, and especially fall are best.   This is when the castles are
deserted, and only the wind keeps you company.   It&#146;s a cheap, exciting way
to spend a day, or even a week if, like all self-respecting tourists, you
intersperse the Cathars with some wine degustations.<BR></P>
<P>After a day of castle-hopping, it&#146;s best to eat regional specialties at
an auberge or one of the ubiquitous chambre d&#146;hotes (bed &amp; breakfast)
you&#146;ll stay at.  Most of them are reasonably priced (around $25-40 per
night excluding supper) in pleasant surroundings.  There are few fast-food
joints in Corbieres.    The French government has been generous with Corbieres,
reinforcing local efforts to make the region as receptive as possible to
tourists.   The aim has been to make Corbieres&#146;s Cathar legacy and the B&amp;B
the drawing cards of the region&#146;s tourist industry, maintaining Corbieres&#146;s
folksiness.  And it works.   Building facades in native rock have been restored
or re-done in even obscure towns, to say nothing of places like Cucugnan.   This
is a small Corbieres village, immortalized in French literature by the
19-century French writer Alphonse Daudet in a humorous short story about the
local priest.   From high in the distance, Queribus and Peyrepertuse, both
Cathar citadels, peer down over the vineyards on Cucugnan.   But you don&#146;t
have to be a history buff to appreciate the legacy of the Cathars.   Bien au
contraire:  a good day&#146;s castle-hopping is a lot like skiing the nearby
Pyrenees (hint).<BR></P>
<P>Back at the inn at sundown you&#146;re sunburned, windburn and exhausted.  
At first you just want to hit the sack.   After all, it&#146;s late and, in
addition to communing with the Cathars, driving has taken its toll.   A couple
of times you&#146;ve had to stop for some semi-wild burrows at the roadside.  
They stuck their scruffy heads in the car and you couldn&#146;t resist their
curled up hooves and big, imploring eyes begging you to offer whatever tidbits
you had.   As the sun set you&#146;ve also slowed down to get a better look at a
few sanglier wild pigs foraging at the roadside.  There&#146;s an indescribably
positive feeling in topping off the day at a B&amp;B with a late, genuine French
meal, maybe even some roast sanglier, a popular French dish.   You&#146;re
breaking bread with total strangers from different parts of the world.  One
minute they seem as distant as the Cathars 900 years before.   Then you start
discussing the wind and the clouds howling through the castles, and what life
must have been like for the Cathars.   And before you&#146;ve even left Cathar
country, you&#146;re making plans to return to it.   &#164;</P>
<HR>
