<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Check It Out!</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>Best Buys, New Products, &amp; Intriguing Offers in
European Travel			</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Check It Out!  Best Buys, New Products, and Intriguing Offers in
European Travel--><I><B><FONT SIZE="+1">We regularly comb the marketplace to
see what&#146;s on tap for European travelers, and in each issue of European
Visits we&#146;ll list some the better bargains &amp; more interesting offers
here in the Check It Out pages.  Keep in mind that prices and availability are
always subject to change.  And if you find something of interest, do us a favor
-- tell them you saw it in European Visits!</FONT></B></I></P>
<HR>
<P><B>KLM</B> is advertising an &#147;Amsterdam Super Stay&#148;, with
all-inclusive air and land from $539 PP/DO.  It includes four days and three
nights in a deluxe Amsterdam hotel and r/t air from over 200 cities in the U.S. 
Extra nights are available; through March 15 1997.  KLM Royal Dutch Airlines,
<B>800-374-7747</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Forsyth Travel Library</B>, specialists in European rail travel, is now
offering <B>American Airlines</B> frequent flyer points with the purchase of
European rail passes &amp; other products.  In what is believed to be the first
such program ever offered, rail travelers can earn 500 AAdvantage miles with any
purchase of rail passes, supporting guides, and related services totaling $500
or more.  At the $1,000+ level, the award is 1,000 AAdvantage miles.  Complete
details on the program, and on Forsyth&#146;s many other offerings, can be
obtained at their Web site (<A HREF="http://www.forsyth.com/">www.forsyth.com</A>)
or by calling their Kansas City headquarters at <B>800 367-7984</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>If your church or choral organization is looking for a group travel
opportunity, <B>Gateway Music Festivals</B> is sponsoring a Choirs in Quiet
Places tour to <B>Nottingham, England</B> next June 10-15. Besides round-trip
transfers from London Airport to Nottingham and 5 nights at a first-class
Nottingham Hotel, the package includes a number of choir concerts at various
venues, a Candlelight Promenade Concert at Newstead Abbey, individual choir
clinics with special guest conductors, and many other perks.  Prices start at
$875 per person (plus airfare to London) with a minimum group of 40 travelers. 
Contact Gateway Music Festivals at <B>800-331-8579</B>, or visit them on the
Web at <A HREF="http://www.musicfestivals.com/">www.musicfestivals.com</A>.    
</P>
<HR>
<P>For the ultimate in high-tech traveling, check out <B>Salzburg</B>&#146;s
new &#147;smart watch&#148; venture.  In a deal cooked up with  Swiss watchmaker
<B>Swatch</B> and a local software firm, visitors can buy a uniquely equipped
watch which not only tells time, but can be programmed with a &#147;smart chip&#148;
that records all the details of an available Salzburg visitor package.  Instead
of carrying a separate card, you need only strap on the watch before setting out
each day to take advantage of the package&#146;s prepaid features.  The packages
themselves (available with or without the $50-$60 watch) include access to most
of the public bus system, lunches &amp; dinners daily, admission to top
attractions, and hotel accommodations.  Prices start at $138 per night per
person; slightly higher during the Easter holiday period.  Contact Salzburg&#146;s
US representative at <B>212-212-1768</B>, or e-mail
<A HREF="mailto:105150.1007@compuserve.com">105150.1007@compuserve.com</A>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>TravelBug</B> is offering <I>Burgundy Biking -- The Wine Routes of
France</I>, an 8-day biking/walking tour through <B>France</B>&#146;s Cote d&#146;Or,
from $3650 PP/DO, land only; single supplement is $395.  This and a number of
similar offers, including some in Italy and Portugal, are detailed at their Web
site (www.travelbug.com), or you can phone <B>800-TRAVEL-4-YOU</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Radisson Edwardian</B> hotels in <B>London</B> are offering
guaranteed-dollar rates from $154-$295 per night for deluxe properties including
the Mountbatten, Hampshire, Marlborough, and Savoy Court hotels (among others). 
Full breakfast is included, and the rates are per room so two stay as cheaply as
one.  Rates are through Feb. 28, with a new set of discounts ($163-$318)
applying in March and early April. Some restrictions apply.  <B>800-333-3333</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Call it the &#147;move in and leave&#148; plan...<B>TWA</B> has momentarily
won the frequent flyer one-upsmanship tussle, with a new program that lets you
earn frequent flyer points when you buy a house!  A joint effort of the airline
and Better Homes &amp; Gardens Real Estate, the program lets you rack up as many
as 80,000 FFB points when you buy &amp; sell a home through BH&amp;G.  You need
to register ahead of time for the program; for more information call <B>800-654-5409</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>London&#146;s <B>Gatwick Airport</B> has opened Britain&#146;s first
airport &#147;cyber cafe&#148;.  Located in the South Terminal, the new hangout
offers coffee, snacks, and Internet connections for time-killing or
email-checking travelers.  There are 10 PCs on location which rent for &#163;3
(about $5) per half-hour.  And yes, they have on-site tech support.  
</P>
<HR>
<P>The <B>British Tourist Authority</B> is offering a guidebook to settings in
the <B>United Kingdom</B> at which popular films were made; included are sites
from <I>Braveheart</I> and <I>Rob Roy</I>, along with the TV series <I>Brideshead
Revisited</I>.  To get a copy, send a self-addressed business-size envelope with
55 cents postage to <B>BTA, 551 Fifth Avenue, Suite 701, New York NY 10176-0799</B>.
 Specify the material you are requesting.</P>
<HR>
<P>If you want to combine your travel with work or study, the experts are <B>Transitions
Abroad</B>.  Their annual <I>Alternative Travel Directory</I> is $19.95, as is
a subscription to their bimonthly magazine.  TA is a good source for both
general information on work/study travel, and for specific organizations,
operators, and travel opportunities.  <B>800-293-0373</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>A fancy-dress ball in <B>Budapest</B> is the highlight of a package offered
by <B>Russiatours</B>, departing February 11.  The  seven-day tour, priced at
$3200 PP/DO, includes deluxe accommodations at the Kempinski Corvinus Hotel and
round-trip airfare from New York.  The ball, held Feb. 8 at the Budapest Opera
House, will feature opera and ballet performances and is catered by Budapest&#146;s
famous <B>Gundel</B> restaurant.  Contact Russiatours, <B>813-987-2477</B>.  
</P>
<HR>
<P>Another <B>Hungary</B> bargain comes from <B>Malev Air</B>, which is
celebrating the nation&#146;s 1100th birthday with a $799 package that covers
round-trip air from New York, 5 nights&#146; hotel, a meal at Gundel&#146;s, and
tickets to an opera or concert performance.  Price is PP/DO and is valid through
March 31.  <B>800-877-5429</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Some of <B>London</B>&#146;s classic black cabs can now offer personalized,
2-hour tours of the city.  The tours, which include commentary from a
well-experienced driver and run about $95, must be booked ahead by calling Black
Taxi Tours in London at (011) 44-171-289-4371.   Also in <B>London</B>, the
Raphael Gallery at the <B>Victoria &amp; Albert Museum</B> has reopened after a
four-year renovation.  The new environment is described as &#147;magnificent&#148;
and showcases selections from the Queen&#146;s unmatched Raphael collection. 
The V&amp;A is open daily from 10:am to 5:30pm (from noon on Sundays).  <B>(0171)
938-8441</B>.  
</P>
<HR>
<P>When you&#146;re done with England and want to head to <B>France</B> in
style, consider <B>Brittany Ferries</B>.  Their luxury &#147;cruise-ferries&#148;
offer gambling, entertainment, and fine dining as they ply sea routes from <B>Plymouth</B>,
<B>Poole</B>, and <B>Portsmouth</B> on the south English coast to <B>Caen</B>,
<B>St Malo</B>, and other French ports in <B>Brittany</B> (they also go to
<B>Santander</B> in <B>Spain</B>).  We couldn&#146;t locate a U.S.
reservations number at press time, so ask your travel agent.  
</P>
<HR>
<P>If you&#146;d just as soon fly from <B>London</B> to the <B>Continent</B>,
investigate options for departing from London&#146;s <B>City Airport</B>.  The
recently expanded facility now offers a variety of trans-Europe flights&#151;primarily
on small European carriers&#151;and its close-in location (15 minutes from
Liverpool Street Station) and relative uncrowdedness can make your departure a
breeze compared to the hassles of Heathrow.  Before you buy your ticket, also
check out two new players in the budding low-fare European market: <B>EasyJet</B>
and <B>Debonair</B><I> (cute)</I> are out to eat the big airlines&#146; lunch,
with fares like <B>London-Amsterdam</B> $53 and <B>London-Barcelona</B> $74. 
Debonair can be booked through your travel agent; EasyJet only sells direct to
travelers via a London reservation line&#151;from the U.S. call <B>(011-44)
990-292-929</B>.  
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>USAir Vacations</B> are expanding their European offerings and
introducing railpass discounts as well.  For travel completed by Feb. 28,
travelers can save 50% on a companion <B>EuroRail </B>pass when a qualifying
air/hotel package is purchased.  The company is also introducing a series of
low-priced &#147;day trip&#148; excursions that can be added on to any of their
other packages, offering such activities as escorted museum tours or visits to
nearby castles.  <B>800-455-0123</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Antique car fan?  Plan now to take in the <B>Special Grand Prix</B>&#151;an
all-antique race run on the same <B>Monaco</B> course as the regular Grand Prix&#151;this
May 4th.  DeChant Travel Letter reports that American Dream Vacations can book
you a full race package with deluxe lodging, daily breakfast, and an unlimited
mileage Avis rental car (presumably modern!), all from $449 PP/DO.  And in
connection with our Andorra piece this issue, note that ADV is also offering a
package that includes lodging at <I>Le Chateau de Quarante</I>, a lovely
countryside chateau just 2 hours from <B>Andorra</B>.  Later this year, they
expect to be able to offer deals at a hotel just 30 minutes away.  <B>800-221-7213</B>.
 
</P>
<HR>
<P>Defying the idea that prices only go up, <B>KD River Cruises</B> have
lowered 1997 rates for many of their European offerings.  One of the deluxe
cruises available is <I>Cathedrals and Czardas</I>, a 15-day excursion from
<B>Cologne</B> to <B>Budapest</B> and back, following the Rhine, Main, and
Danube rivers (plus the Main-Danube Canal).  Everything but airfare is included,
with costs from $1845 PP/DO.  Departure date from Cologne is March 28.  <B>800-346-6525</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Cosmos Tours</B>&#151;self-proclaimed as the &#147;World&#146;s Best
Budget Touring&#148; and specialists in giving the most bang for the buck&#151;
have come out with their 1997 catalog.  A sample: <I>Imperial Capitals</I>,
which offers 17 days traipsing through the cities of <B>Belgium</B>, <B>Holland</B>,
<B>Luxembourg</B>, <B>Germany</B>, <B>Czech Republic</B>, <B>Slovakia</B>,
<B>Austria</B>, and <B>Hungary</B>, all from just $1624 PP/DO.  Transatlantic
air, nightly lodging, ground transportation by motorcoach, and local sightseeing
are  included.  There are dozens of other packages, and they&#146;re all
available on a London-London basis if you want to add them on to other European
travel plans (some tours can be joined elsewhere on the route).  Cosmos only
books through travel agencies; ask your agent to show you the full catalog, and
take your time browsing.  
</P>
<HR>
<P>Planning rail travel in <B>Spain</B>?  <B>VE Tours</B> in Miami are the
experts, with direct access to Spain&#146;s National Railway ticketing
computers.  They can fix you up with reservations on the exceptionally deluxe
<I>Tren Hotel</I> overnight trains, as well as arrange complete air/rail/hotel
packages for <B>Madrid</B>, <B>Barcelona</B>, <B>Seville</B>, and elsewhere;
they also do <B>Portugal</B> and <B>Morocco</B>.  <B>800-222-8383</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P>Finally, <B>United Airlines</B> has come up with the Splendid Idea of the
year&#151;airline seats with built-in back massagers!  It&#146;s strictly
experimental at this stage, with just one such seat installed on a 747 plying
the Chicago-Hong Kong route.  But if it works out, expect to see the &#147;BackCycle&#148;
seat showing up in first-class cabins everywhere.  (While in coach we&#146;ll
make do with the usual combination&#151;engine vibration and that kid kicking
the back of the seat.  Sigh...)</P>
<HR>
<P><I><B>What does it mean??</B>  If you&#146;re new to travel browsing, you
may wonder about the &#147;PP/DO&#148; abbreviation that you see in most
package-deal listings.  What it means is &#147;per person, double occupancy&#148;
-- in other words, the quoted price is based on buying at least two packages for
a pair traveling &amp; staying together.  If you&#146;re going solo and only
want to buy one package, expect to pay a premium (called a &#147;single
supplement&#148;), usually 20-50% over the listed price.</I></P>
<HR>
<P><I><B>Credit Where Credit Is Due:</B>  While we dig up <B>Check It Out</B>
nuggets from a variety of sources, we&#146;d be lost without our &#147;wicking
stick&#148;, the excellent coverage found in <B>Travel Weekly</B>.  The premier
newspaper of the travel industry, published twice weekly by Reed Travel Group,
TW offers exhaustive coverage of travel issues, companies and products.  If you&#146;re
involved in the travel business and don&#146;t have a subscription, you&#146;re
missing out.  Call Reed at <B>800 360 0015</B>. 
</I></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><I><B><FONT SIZE="+3">Remember to tell them you saw it in
European Visits!</FONT></B></I></P>
