<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Dover Castle / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">You Can Meet the Most Interesting
People at Dover Castle</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>by George E. Blancett</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<P>In the spring of 1979, my wife and I were on our second visit to England. 
On our first trip we were consumed by the splendor and majesty of castles,
palaces and landscape in and around the great city of London.  While on a
limited budget, we had traveled to the upper part of Wales and both sides of
Scotland, Ayr to Edinburgh.  The wonder and awe of our first visit were still
fresh in our  minds; but the second trip was to acquaint us with our most
unforgettable Englishman&#151;Victor Yeakes of Dover, Kent&#151;a charming man
in his late 60s who served as an enthusiastic  &#147;keeper&#148; at Dover
Castle.<BR></P>
<P>A  quick tour of Dover Castle was on our schedule for that beautiful spring
day, but little did we know that my western style hat (cowboy hat) would open
the door to a true friendship.  The hat&#151;with its high peaked dome and band
of brightly colored feathers&#151;was uncharacteristic of my usual attire, but
it was an attention-getter; as proven by our stop at Canterbury, where in
touring the Cathedral we met a group of Boy Scouts who could not take their eyes
off it.  I offered them a closer view, and before long they were passing my hat
around and taking snapshots with it on.   That hat was to play a prominent role
in meeting my most unforgettable English person.<BR></P>
<P>Upon entering Dover Castle a distinguished guard, while looking at my hat,
asked, &#147;May I answer  any questions for you?&#148;  With that introduction
commenced a most enjoyable and informative personal guided tour of the
historically rich castle.  At the conclusion of our tour I didn&#146;t know if I
 should thank him for his kindness, offer a gratuity or just disappear; so I
said, &#147;Can I do anything  for you?&#148;  As we talked during our tour
Marcelle and I told Victor a little about ourselves, and it came up that we had
attended high school with, and had been personally acquainted with, Elvis
Presley.  On our previous trip when we told people we from Memphis, Tennessee we
were frequently be asked if we knew Elvis; so on this trip we carried our Humes
High School 1953 Yearbook&#151;with  Elvis&#146; graduation picture with a
friendship endorsement to me next to it.  We had copies of the signed picture to
give to those who wanted one.  But Victor, instead of requesting an Elvis
picture, said, &#147;I certainly am attracted to your hat band.&#148;  We 
assured him we would send him a similar one upon our return home, which we did.<BR></P>
<P>Over the years we continued to correspond with Victor and learned more about
this remarkable man. Some of Victor Yeakes&#146; talents included a remarkable
storytelling ability, an exceptional talent for writing both prose and poetry,
an artistic ability to illustrate by cartoon, and the unusual hobby of
participating in an all-British organization known as the &#147;War-horse 
American Union Cavalry Society,&#148; where he held the rank of Commissary
Master Sergeant.  He  was very proud of his outfit and he sent us several
photographs of himself and other members of  the society in full-dress American
cavalry uniforms, circa 1860.  Their organization was (and still is) very active
in their fascination with the American Civil War. They didn&#146;t just read
about and  discuss the events; they actually recreated the times and battles by
collecting and making authentic uniforms, armor, wagons and other equipment
appropriate to their re-enactments. 
<BR></P>
<P>We asked him by letter if we could bring him anything on our planned 1983
visit, at which time we learned that Victor had retired from Dover Castle, due
to failing health.  Despite his condition he was insistent that we visit in his
home, and we gladly accepted.  In response to our offer to bring  him something,
he again surprised us with a request for anything associated with the famous 
American Civil War era composer, Stephen Foster.  We went to Foster&#146;s &#147;Olde
Kentucky Home&#148; in Bardstown, Kentucky and collected some memorabilia and
information, from the home and from a two-act musical show (&#147;The Stephen
Foster Story&#148;) presented by The Stephen Foster Drama Association.  
<BR></P>
<P>During our visit in Victor&#146;s Dover home in 1983, he shared additional
information about his American Civil War activities.  He entertained us with his
musical talent by playing some tapes of popular songs he re-recorded changing
the words to fit events of his selection.  He gave us a copy of a photograph, of
himself and another Dover Castle keeper, taken with The Queen Mother of England
upon her installation as &#147;Lord Warden and Constable of Dover Castle.&#148; 
He also gave a copy of a letter he received from The Queen Mother thanking him
for a poem he wrote honoring her installation.  In addition to being entertained
by his musical talents and reading his &#147;majestically&#148; inspired poem. 
Victor also showed us a booklet he had written and illustrated concerning
England&#146;s 1980s incident in the Falkland Islands.  This thirty-page book
contained some very humorous cartoons intended to capture the humanity of the
people  involved.  As a dedication he wrote on the back cover:  &#147;These
Cartoon Sketches Were Drawn From The  Beginning And To The Ending Of The
Falklands War. And Portray The Feelings And Thoughts  Of Untrained Argentine
Soldiers Against Impossible Odds And A Brave and Determined Foe.&#148;  
<BR></P>
<P>A quick reading of this cartooned book may leave an incomplete understanding
of its purpose, but a closer reading coupled with some knowledge of its author,
reveals the sensitivity, love and compassion within this man     He entrusted
this booklet to me to see if anyone might have an interest in publishing. I
still hold the book to pass to the proper person.  
<BR></P>
<P>Victor was never a hero himself.  In 1940, while on military duty in a
foreign country, he suffered a disabling wound which kept him on the &#147;home
front&#148; during World War II.  This was no easy duty.  He showed us a &#147;bombing
map&#148; plotting the sites where thousands of bombs were dropped on the city
of Dover by German planes going to and coming from raids on London.  He told us
of watching some of these bombs drop.   
<BR></P>
<P>Victor also showed us a copy of the March 27, 1983 edition of News of the
World, a local newspaper, where an article titled &#147;A Traitor Stalks the
Castle&#148; described Victor&#146;s encounter with a &#147;tall, gaunt,
gray-featured man standing halfway up the spiral stairs from which there was no
way out of the dungeon&#148; (a ghost?).  The report tells how Victor, with &#147;hair
on the back of his neck lifted,&#148; nervously walked through Archers Bow Tower
after seeing this thing.  The article reported that &#147;there is legend that a
knight was beaten to death near the defences for treachery.&#148;  Knowing
Victor Yeakes, this reported sighting surprises me not.  
<BR></P>
<P>We told Victor we would return to England in several years, and would
contact him when plans were finalized. In the summer of 1987, while planning to
visit England once again, we sent Victor some items we thought he might enjoy. 
This package was returned by the Royal Mail with an endorsement dated August 1,
1987 stating &#147;Undelivered for reason stated&#151;return to sender.
DECEASED.&#148;  What a sad and shocking way to learn of the death of a friend. 

<BR></P>
<P>Marcelle and I will always remember the warmth of Victor Yeakes; he was a
man of intelligence, a man of wisdom, a man of many talents, a man of compassion
and courtesy.  We will remember and cherish that extra personal relationship we
shared, with a man from a country which has provided the world with so many
enduring memories.  To us the memory of Victor Yeakes will be just as important
as all the others.  &#164;  
<BR></P>
<P><I>Dover Castle:  Dover CT16 1HH, Kent; Tel: (01304) 201628</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B><B>Who&#146;s your most memorable European character?</B></B><I>European
Visits</I> invites you to share your essays, observations, or experiences in
this or any other any aspect of European travel.  Send articles of 500-1000
words to <B>Readers Write, European Visits, 4718 Neptune Circle, Ferndale WA
98248</B>; or by email to <A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com,</A>
with &#147;Readers Write&#148; in the subject line.  If your piece is used in
<I>EV</I>, you&#146;ll receive your choice of a <I>European Visits</I> T
shirt, mouse pad, visor cap, or barbeque apron&#151;plus, you&#146;ll be entered
automatically in our semiannual<B> Eurail Pass giveaway</B> (a drawing is held
in January &amp; July each year).   
</P>
