<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Online Traveler -
Internet links - travel bookmarks - Internet access - Web Resources</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<P><I><B>The Online Traveler</B></I><BR></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00" SIZE="+2">rec.travel.europe: A Newgroup for
European Travel</FONT></B></I><BR>Although they receive less media attention
than the World Wide Web, another thriving part of the Internet consists of  the
<B>newsgroups</B> -- basically collections of posted messages, questions,
answers, and endless discussions on particular topics of interest.  There are
literally thousands of newsgroups in existence, on every subject you can imagine
(and, to borrow a line from a popular Internet magazine, a few you'd have
trouble imagining!) 
<BR></P>
<P>Newsgroups differ from the World Wide Web in that they include no graphics,
and unlike Web sites aren't owned or operated by any particular company or
individual.  Picture them as giant bulletin boards in cyberspace, overflowing
with tacked up messages, Post-Its, and notes.  When you got Internet access your
sign-up kit probably came with a newsgroup &quot;reader&quot; &#151; special
software that allows you to access the newsgroup collections and navigate among
them by selecting from a list.  Once you access a particular newsgroup, all of
its recently posted messages are displayed in second list, grouped according to
individual &quot;threads&quot; or ongoing conversations on particular topics. 
Your reader software will then let you browse, save, print, or respond to the
posted messages, or start a new thread by posting a message of your own.  Other
than your normal Internet connection fees, there's no charge for participating
in newsgroups.  For our purposes, the essential newsgroup is rec.travel.europe,
filled with postings on every aspect of European travel.<BR></P>
<P>This is a great place to ask your fellow travelers about their own
experiences, hotel recommendations, destination ideas, and anything else you
want to talk about.  Participants are identified by their e-mail addresses, so
if you start a particularly interesting conversation with someone, you can take
it &quot;private&quot; by corresponding with them directly by email.  You'll see
a bit of advertising on rec.travel.europe, but not very much &#151; posting
unsolicited ads on a newsgroup will make you about as popular as a skunk at a
picnic, and the regular crowd will let you know about it.  If you're a tour
operator or otherwise in the travel biz, the best course for finding customers
here is to be unpushy, join in conversations, share your knowledge, and wait for
opportunities to mention your own offerings when they're directly relevent to
someone's questions or comments.    So if you've just started exploring the
Internet and haven't tried your newsgroup reader yet, go ahead and fire it up. 
Find rec.travel.europe in the list and start mingling with your online
compatriots.  It's interesting and can be a lot of fun.
<BR></P>
<P>And you may find just the answers you're looking for.  
</P>
