<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Germany's
Share-the-Ride Program /  Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine /
Germany  / Travel in Europe / Hitchkiking / Budget Travel</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>&quot;With Drive Central&quot;</H2>
<P><BR><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00" SIZE="+2">On the road with Germany's
share-the-ride program</FONT></B></I></P>
<P><BR>
<I>by Rhea Wessel</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Germany's share-a-ride program is a blessing for both drivers and
riders.</B>  It's not only the cheapest way to cross the country, it's the most
interesting.  I wish someone had told me about the highly efficient and
organised share-a-ride program when I came to live in Germany five years ago. 
All this time I could have had interesting company who would even pay for their
share of the gas.  And I would have been meeting travelers and hearing their
tales from adventures far and wide. 
<BR></P>
<P>The nationwide Mitfahrzentrale MFZ (literally, <I>with-drive-central</I>)
program has offices in most large cities which serve as agents for drivers and
riders.  The nationwide number for the mitfahrzentrale is 19444; from major
cities dial it directly or if calling from out of town, add the city code.
(Example: Frankfurt 069-19444, Munich 089-19444.)  
<BR></P>
<P>My first trip as a driver was from Hamburg to Bonn and I called up the
center to give them the details. I would leave on Sunday at 11:00 a.m. and I had
room for two riders as long as they didn't have too much luggage.  The meeting
point was the MFZ office, strategically set near the autobahn for drivers and
near public transportation for the benefit of riders.  Each passenger paid about
35 marks, or $20 (fees riders pay depend on the length of the drive and are set
by the agency) and we had a jolly old time fighting the traffic together.  One
guy was a computer whiz in his mid-twenties headed to Bonn looking for a job,
the other a student who had visited a friend on the weekend. 
<BR></P>
<P>Once after a vacation, flying in to Frankfurt on a cheap ticket from Madrid,
I decided I would like to make it home to Hamburg without paying as much for the
German train ticket as I did for the flight.  I called up Frankfurt's MFZ to
find someone headed to Hamburg.  I paid a 20 mark fee to the agency, then hopped
in with Izmet, a 33 year-old German of Turkish descent who was headed to Hamburg
for a sales promotion.  He greeted me enthusiastically and before we had even
left Frankfurt,  asked if I knew a place where he could stay in Hamburg.  We
would be arriving late, he hadn't booked anything, and he didn't want to spend a
lot of money.  
<BR></P>
<P>&quot;This is going to be a long ride,&quot; I thought to myself.  But Izmet
turned out to be a great guy and we shared our life stories during the five-hour
drive. When we stopped for gas, I called my roommates to ask if they wouldn't
mind if Izmet slept in our guest room.  In return, Izmet didn't charge me the 35
marks. 
<BR></P>
<P>On another trip from Hamburg to Augsburg, I rode with two young women.  We
cranked up the music and the ride reminded me of a road trip in my high school
days.  Coming from Kaiserslautern to Hamburg, I met Achim, a young German law
student who enjoyed practicing the art of flirting in English; now we exchange
e-mail.  From Frankfurt to Hamburg, a young Brazilian who was a member of a
traditional dance group touring Europe, shared music from his home.  We broke
out a bag of Tostitos bought at an U.S. army post exchange and I was able to
share a taste of my native Texas.        I was so excited about my discovery of
the MFZ that I once practically forced my brother to take riders with him. It
was a winter day, he was tired and I didn't want him to face a long trip home
alone.  So I arranged for him to take two passengers. It turned out that one had
an awful cold and sneezed during the whole trip. My brother lay in bed for a
week trying not to blame me for his illness.  
<BR></P>
<P>I guess riding with the MFZ is like life.  Sometimes you get lucky,
sometimes you don't.  If you're lucky, on your next trip to Germany you'll hook
up with interesting people and see the country from its fabulous network of
roads.  And if you're really lucky, I won't pick you up in my little blue Fiat
with 100,000 miles on it, instead a tank-like Mercedes with a dream driver will
whisk you away.  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
