<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: The Online Traveler</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H1>Check It Out!</H1>
<P><I><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Best Buys, New Products, and Intriguing Offers in
European Travel</FONT></B></I><BR></P>
<P><I><B>We regularly comb the marketplace to see what's on tap for European
travelers, and in each issue of European Visits we'll list some the better
bargains or more unusual offerings here in the Check It Out pages.  Keep in mind
that prices and availability are always subject to change.  However, we do our
best to check what we publish, and everything listed here was available as EV
went to press.  If you find something of interest, do us a favor -- tell them
you saw it in European Visits!</B></I><BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Cedok</B>, the travel agency of the Czech Republic, has a special
deal on a week in <B>Prague</B>.  Airfare from New York plus six nights in a
3-star Prague hotel can be had for as little as $746 PP/DO.  Land-only packages
start at $209.  Valid through October 20.  Contact Cedok, <B>800-800-8891</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Hungary</B> wants to add to the 260,000 American visitors it
received in 1995:  through Oct. 31, Malev Airlines is offering a six-night
package with roundtrip air from New York, lodging at one of several deluxe
Budapest hotels, a city tour, tickets to an opera or concert, and a dinner at
famed Gundel's restaurant, all for $1100 PP/DO.  <B>800-877-5429</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Traveling by railpass, but want to take a break from the train along
the way?  <B>N&amp;S Connections</B> can book you on a Danube River hydrofoil
from <B>Vienna</B> to <B>Budapest</B>, from $75 one way.  <B>800-999-0226</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Another <B>Budapest</B> special comes from <B>FinnWay</B>, a tour
operator specializing in Finland, Scandanavia, and the Baltics.  They are
offering a &quot;Romantic Cities of Central Europe&quot; program which includes
nine days in <B>Budapest</B> and <B>Prague</B> for as little as $799 including
air, PP/DO.  First-class hotels, daily breakfasts, sightseeing tours, and rail
transportation between the two cities is inclusive in the price; you can upgrade
to deluxe hotels from $1299. Seven-day Prague-only packages are available at
slightly lower prices; rates valid through next May. FinnWay, <B>800-526-4927</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A <B>London</B> organization called <B>Uptown Reservations</B> can
assist you with booking stays at private homes in the city center.  Single rooms
with private bath and hotel-like amenities can be had for as little as &#163;55.
 The company can arrange car rentals as well.  In London, contact Uptown
Reservations, <B>+44 (0) 171-351-3445</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A more pastoral home-stay option in <B>England</B> comes from <B>In
the English Manner</B>, which offers 6-night programs at private country homes,
with special focus on &quot;gourmets, golfers, and garden lovers.&quot;  More
information: <B>800-422- 0799</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Perillo Tours</B>, longtime operators of escorted travel packages
to <B>Italy</B> (and elsewhere), is offering an 11-day tour with visits to <B>Rome</B>
(3 nights) <B>Florence</B> (3) <B>Venice</B> (2) and <B>Milan</B> (1), plus
dinner every night in each city&#146;s finer restaurants, from $1799 pp/do; good
through next spring.  A special touch from Perillo is that their tours are
priced the same from any of 50 U.S. cities coast-to-coast; with most tours,
airfare to the East Coast is extra.  You can visit Perillo and learn more about
them &amp; their specials at <A HREF="http://www.perillotours.com/">www.perillotours.com</A>;
or call <B>800-431-1515</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Rail Europe</B>, eagerly promoting their expanded role as a
full-service European travel agency, is advertising some spectacular round-trip
fares for this fall:  <B>NY-London</B> $362, <B>Dallas-Rome</B> $595, <B>Miami-Berlin</B>
$489, and <B>LA-Paris</B> $594 are examples.  Valid Nov. 11 through Dec. 12
1996.  Phone <B>800-4-EURAIL</B> (ext. 3).
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; If you want to shop-til-you-drop a la Fran&ccedil;ais, contact <B>France
Vacations</B>: they have a series of shopping tours to <B>Paris</B> planned,
with departures Sept 28, Nov. 9, Nov. 16, and Dec. 7, featuring roundtrip air
from Los Angeles, five nights' accomodations, some meals, sightseeing, and
guided shopping excursions to Paris' finest department stores and best
bargain-hunting sites.  Cost is from $1395 PP/DO.  France Vacations, <B>800-332-5332</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Entertainment Publications' latest hotel book, the <I>Ultimate
Travel Savings Directory</I>, includes more than 800 hotels in <B>Europe</B>
which participate in their half-price program.  While the &quot;50% discount&quot;
is usually applied to rather inflated list prices, the net rate is still
generally a good deal; it gets thumbs-up from Consumer Reports Travel Letter,
which isn't easily impressed.  Directory &amp; discount card are $59.95 and
valid through the end of 1997. <B>800-445-4137</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>MinOtel</B> has a directory to 650 &quot;charming little hotels
and inns&quot; in 28 <B>European</B> countries; they also have a prepaid
voucher system that let you guarantee rates in advance of your trip without
having to make confirmed bookings.  Doubles start at $120 per night, singles
$93.  Contact MinOtel Europe, <B>800-336-4668</B>.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Icelandair</B> wants to tempt you to visit <B>Reykjavik</B>,
which they tout as &quot;Europe's Adventure Capital.&quot;  A new
Fall/Winter/Spring brochure offers air and land packages as low as $299.  The
airline is also offering direct flights to <B>Glasgow</B> from New York,
Baltimore, or New York, with air &amp; land packages including stays in <B>Edinburgh</B>
and <B>London</B> from $549.  Ask about it at <B>800-757-EURO</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; If you've been hearing about those &quot;Dracula&quot; tours to
<B>Romania</B>, here's the folks that can get you in on one:  <B>Quest Tours
and Adventures</B>, <B>800-621-TOUR</B>.  They have packages to <B>Black Sea
</B>spas and <B>Moldavian</B> monasteries, too.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Eurobus</B> remains an excellent option for rock-bottom prices on
transport around <B>Europe</B>.  Though motorcoaches may lack the comfort and
amenities of rail, a one-month pass on their network, which links 23 Continental
cities, is just $260 (compare to $838 for a month of Eurail).  They also have a
$145 UK pass that connects <B>London</B>, <B>Glasgow</B>, <B>York</B>, <B>Bath</B>,
and other major cities in a loop around Britain.  For details ask your travel
agent or call <B>800-EUROBUS</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Catholic pilgrimage tours to <B>Israel</B> are being organized by
<B>Regina Tours</B>.  Numerous departure dates are available, and some combine
Israel with stops in other countries.  Call Regina Tours at <B>800-228-4654</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Another operator focusing on Christian tours, <B>Ya'lla</B>, has a
series of Millenium Tours in the works for those who want to visit the Holy
Lands at the turn of the century; the tours are timed to coincide with an
expected Papal visit to <B>Bethlehem</B> around Christmas and New Years' Eve in
1999/2000, and will include visits to important Biblical sites.  The company
takes bookings only from travel agents; ask your agent to call Ya'lla at <B>800
644 1595</B> for more details.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; If you've already been to the <B>Holy Land</B> but didn't bring home
any memorable souvenirs, try <B>Worldwide Treasure Bureau</B>, specialists in
affordable ancient coins &amp; collectibles:  they have a limited number of
authentic small bronze pilgrims' crosses, dating from the 6th to 12th century,
for sale at $275 each.  <B>800 437 0222</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>France in Your Glass</B>, designers of specialty trips to the
French wine regions, now has a &quot;France in Your Fax&quot; service which will
send sample itineraries to your fax machine via an automated phone-request line.
 Call 1-800-842-4618 and request document #3 (Bordeaux), #9 (Burgundy), or #5
(Provence).  If you'd rather talk to a representative, call <B>800-578-0903</B>.
 You can also visit them on the Web at <A HREF="http://www.inyourglass.com/">http://www.inyourglass.com</A>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>European Resources</B> is offering a 7-night <B>Amsterdam</B>
stay with roundtrip air from Boston, first-class downtown hotel, daily buffet
breakfast, airport transfers, and a canal tour from $845 PP/DO, valid Nov. 11 to
March 27.  Departures from New York, Baltimore, and Orlando are also available,
as is an $82 stopover in Iceland.  <B>800-375-9207</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A new guide to <B>London</B>'s bars and pubs is available from Seven
Hills Book Distributors; the pocket-size guide details more than 350
establishments with information on hours, food menus, and entertainment.  The
guide is $9.95 at your local travel bookstore, or call Seven Hills at <B>513-381-3881</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; If you want to find the liveliest nightspots all over <B>Europe</B>,
a new guidebook called <I>Let's Party! Europe</I> has hit the shelves.  The $13
book covers everything from discos in Spain to cannabis coffeeshops in
Amsterdam.  If you'd rather party than sleep, they even highlight some of the
night trains in Europe that are most apt to carry a frisky student clientele. 
Available at travel bookstores; from <B>Vagabond Publishing</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Interested in attending a full-scale Elizabethan banquet in an
authentic <B>English</B> palace?  They have one every Tuesday, Thursday,
Friday, and Saturday at the Old Palace in Hatfield, Hertfordshire.  Dinner,
wine, and entertainment are packaged at a single price, and they offer coach
transportation to and from London's West End.  For details write <B>The Old
Palace, Hatfield Park, Hatfield, Hertfordshire, Britain AL9 5NE</B>; or call
<B>+44 (0) 1707-262-055</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <I>Our World Travel</I> is a monthly magazine devoted to gay &amp;
lesbian travel worldwide.  Subscriptions are $45 annually; call <B>904-441-5367</B>.
 <I>Out &amp; About</I> is a monthly newsletter on the same topic: $49 a year,
<B>800-929-2268</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; The <B>Globe Theatre</B> (at least, a rebuilt version) has finally
re-opened on the banks of the Thames, just a short walk from the original site
of Shakespeare's stage.  The new Globe was built with the aim of as much
authenticity as possible, even to the extent of including a partially-open roof.
  It is also the first building since the Great Fire of 1666 allowed to have a
thatched roof -- though in this case, with a built-in sprinkler system.  Perhaps
for these reasons, costs have gone up a bit; today's building ran $12 million,
as opposed to approximately $1500 spent on the original.  If you're
<B>London-bound</B>, check with your travel agent or ticket agency on upcoming
Globe performances.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; For a deal on a <B>London</B> theatre trip, try <B>Theatre Direct</B>'s
Standing Ovation package: six nights' lodging at a Radisson Edwardian hotel,
daily continental breakfast, and tickets to three West End productions -- plus a
backstage tour at the Royal Drury Lane theatre.  Call  Theatre Direct for
pricing, <B>800-334-8457</B>.  You can also email for information at
tdi@ix.netcom.com, or visit them on the Web at
<A HREF="http://www.theatredirect.com/">www.theatredirect.com</A>.<BR>
</P>
<P>&#183; Another item on <B>London</B> theatre came our way recently; the
London Theatre News, a monthly publication reporting on all aspects of the West
End boards, is now available for US subscription at $39 per year.  They offer
show reviews, upcoming attractions, interviews with London performers, and more,
along with a hotline for booking tickets before you go.  A three-month trial
subscription is also available at $21.  <B>800-779-0077</B>.  
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A few issues back, we mentioned the laminated <B>Thomas Cook
European Rail Map</B>, available from Forsyth Travel Library (<B>800-367-7984</B>),
as a great hanging for your wall.  Now for dedicated Europhiles we've found a
nifty companion piece from Map Marketing Ltd:  <B>Europe from Space</B>, a
75x60cm, crystal-clear view of Europe from a satellite high overhead.  With a
scale of 1:8,137,800 and shipped bonded between two pieces of flexible plastic
for easy hanging, it's &#163;16.99 (about $26) plus &#163;9.95 shipping.  You
have to call England to order: <B>+44 (0) 171-736-0297</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; And while we don't like to blow our own horn -- aw, what the heck! 
-- another accessory the true Europhile can't be without is our unique <B>&quot;I'd
Rather Be In Europe...&quot;</B> <I>European Visits</I> mousepad.  Let them
know what you're really thinking as you slave away in that cubicle!  Also
available as a sweatshirt or apron; see the ad
<A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/ratherb.htm">here</A>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Hideaways International</B>, specialists in overseas vacation
rentals, is offering a 4-month trial membership for just $39 (regular membership
is $99/year).  They have a quarterly newsletter and a twice-annual directory of
properties available worldwide at bargain rates, including many in <B>Europe</B>.
 <B>800-843-4433</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A similar service is provided by <B>Villas and Apartments Abroad</B>,
located in New York City, with offerings in <B>France</B>, <B>Italy</B>, and
<B>Britain</B>.  They offer free catalogs and brochures; call <B>800-433-3020</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>American Express</B>, <B>Disney</B>, and the <B>French Tourist
Office</B> have put together a Hunchback of Notre Dame vacation that manages to
combine Parisian history, EuroDisney, and the new hit animation film.  Family
rates in France are advertised as being as low as $59 a night, depending on
hotel.  Ask your travel agent or call <B>1-407-WDISNEY</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Vantage World Travel</B> is offering a deluxe &quot;President's
Tour&quot; to Ireland next spring.  The 13-day, fully escorted package includes
<B>Galway</B>, <B>Killarney</B>, and <B>Dublin</B>, with such treats as a
visit to Ireland's wild coastal Ring of Kerry -- some of the world's most
spectacular seaside views -- and a private lecture from Irish poet Brendan
Kinnelly at the Trinity College Library.  The tour company's president Henry
Lewis will be going along (hence the name).  There's only one departure date,
April 26.  Cost starts at $2999 PP/DO, including air.  Vantage World Travel,
<B>800-322-6677</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; You can get 25% off the price of a <B>Michelin Green Guide</B> for
Europe just by using your American Express card to buy it, via a special
toll-free order number.  The same savings are available on Green Guides for <B>Tuscany</B>,
<B>Venice</B>, <B>Wales</B>, and <B>Scandanavia</B>.  On orders of $25 or
more, shipping is free.  Call <B>800-223-0987</B> ext. 91 for more info.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Here's a name to add to the list of Francophile publications we ran
last issue:  <I>France</I>, a quarterly publication, is an English-language
magazine produced in Europe.  It's $29.95 a year for 4 full-color, oversize
issues news filled with news on French culture, cuisine, arts, and history.  You
can write for a sample issue: <B>France, PO Box 218, Landisburg PA 17040-9986</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Fleet Street Publications is now offering Pitkin Pictorials by mail
order in the US.  Pitkins are those ubiquitous small illustrated guidebooks that
you find on sale at the gift shop of virtually any attraction in <B>Britain</B>;
in case you forgot to buy one while you were there, Fleet Street gives you a
chance to remedy matters.  Over 150 titles available, from <I>&quot;Bath Abbey&quot;</I>
to <I>&quot;York Minster.&quot;</I>  Most are just $6.  For a complete listing
write <B>Fleet Street Publications, PO Box 301369, Escondido, CA 92030</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>American Dream Vacations</B> has put together a 7-day <I>Swiss
Glacier Express</I> package that gives you six nights in <B>Zurich</B>, <B>Zermatt</B>,
and St. <B>Moritz</B>, along with an 8-day Swiss Rail pass and passage on the
famous Swiss Glacier Express train, from $769 PP/DO.  You can also extend the
package to include visits to <B>Lucerne</B> or <B>Interlaken</B>.  <B>800 221
7213</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>London</B>'s tony <B>Athenaeum Hotel</B>, located 200 yards from
Buckingham Palace, is booking rooms with a view of Hyde Park at a special rate
of $295 per night through Dec. 31.  The 5-star property has standard rooms,
apartments, and suites on sale too, celebrating an $18 million renovation. 
Reserve through your travel agent or call <B>800-335-3300</B>.
<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Another deluxe <B>London</B> discount is on tap at the <B>Royal
Garden Hotel:</B>  Through December 13, double rooms are available at a a
prepaid rate of $195 per night.  <B>800-987-9317</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Thistle &amp; Mount Charlotte Hotels</B>' &quot;96 at $96&quot;
promotion continues until the end of the year: with a 4-night booking at any of
more than 60 locations acros <B>England</B>, you get the special rate plus such
perks as free room upgrades and an auto-transmission rental car.  <B>London</B>
is slightly higher with no car, but are still a good deal.  <B>800-847-4358</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Alitalia</B>, the Italian airline, has a fly/drive special
through Oct. 31 with r/t airfare from Boston or New York, plus seven days'
rental of an air-conditioned Alfa Romeo 155 with unlimited mileage, from $877
PP/DO.  <B>800-223-5555</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>New Frontiers</B>' Rail Italia package combines three nights'
accomodation in <B>Rome</B>, two nights in <B>Florence</B>, and two nights in
<B>Venice</B> with 2nd class rail fare between the three cities for just $379
PP/DO.  Through Nov. 5.  <B>800-366-6387</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A fancier <B>Italian</B> sojourn includes cooking lessons with <B>Julia
Child</B>:  for $3,385 you get six nights at <B>Venice</B>'s deluxe Hotel
Cipriani, a special series of gourmet Italian meals at the hotel's restaurant &amp;
at local private homes, and presentations from the famous chef on how to
reproduce the meals yourself.  A non-cooking companion can come along for
$2,530.  Oct. 20-26.  This and other culinary packages are offered by Orient
Express Hotels: <B>800-237-1236</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; And while we're on the subject of Italian food, check out the
<I>Guide to 57 Absolutely Decadent Cooking Holidays In Italy</I>, by Margaret
Cowan.  Order the 231-page, $24.77 book now and receive <I>38 Sensational
Recipies from Italian Cooking School Chefs</I> as a free bonus.  The author, who
has lived in Tuscany, spent years researching the books, which have received
glowing reviews.  Order from Margaret Cowan Direct, Ltd., <B>800-557-0370</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; If you're lookiing for a deal on <B>Spain</B>, try the &quot;World
Heritage Tour&quot; package offered by the <B>Tourist Office of Spain</B>:  the
11-day, self-drive  tour includes first-class hotels, daily breakfasts, airport
transfers, and a 7-day car rental with unlimited mileage from $954 PP/DO. 
Through October 31.  <B>800-738-7222</B>.  
</P>
<P>&#183; France's <B>Relais du Silence</B> hotel group, which represents
small manors, chalets, and chateaux in the <B>French countryside</B>, is now
offering direct US bookings through HSA Voyages.  Rates range from $90 to $200
per night for the carefully-selected properties; an illustrated directory is
available for $5 (refundable with a booking).  Call HSA Voyages at <B>800 653
7262</B> or write them at 5609 Green Oaks Blvd., Arlington TX 76017.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; <B>Berlin</B>'s ultra-deluxe <B>Schlosshotel Vier Jahreszeiten</B>
hotel has a special through Dec. 31 with 2 nights' lodging, full breakfast, one
free lunch or dinner in the hotel's Le Jardin restaurant, and use of the pool &amp;
fitness center; cost is $368 single or $419 double.  The Schosshotel is a member
of the <I>Leading Hotels of the World</I> group.  <B>800-223-6800</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; Whether you're an accomplished artist or just a dabbler, you're
welcome on <B>Charterways</B>' <I>French Painting Tour</I>, departing October
6.  The package combines painting workshops with guided visits to inspirational
settings in Provence; the workshops, land transportation, lodging, and most
meals are included at $1952 PP/DO. <B>800-869-2344</B>.  
</P>
<P>&#183; A facinating train ride to the 5,900-foot peak of <B>Switzerland</B>'s
Mount Rigi is available through October 20: in celebration of the route's 125th
anniversary, the original steam engine and original 60-passenger carriage have
been put back in service for the 35-minute journey from <B>Arth-Goldau</B>
(near Lucerne).  Fare is $30 per person, with a 50% discount for Swiss
Flexipass, Europass, or Eurail pass holders.  Contact Switzerland Tourism, <B>212
757 5944</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; A fly/drive package to the <B>Netherlands</B> is on offer from the
<B>Kemwel Group</B> through Oct. 31.  Round-trip air on Martinair is matched
with a 7-day car rental, with prices ranging from $651 (NYC) to $838 (West
Coast).  The hefty Dutch 17.5% car rental tax is included.  Kemwel, <B>800-678-0678.<BR></B></P>
<P>&#183; Through October, <B>Belgian Sabena Airlines</B> has a &quot;city/country&quot;
deal giving you roundtrip air from New York, 2 nights at a first class hotel in
<B>Brussels</B>, 2 nights in a <B>countryside chateau</B>, and a five day car
rental; from $1099 PP/DO.  Contact Sabena, <B>800-955-2000</B>.<BR></P>
<P>&#183; In closing, if you're finally ready to buy that <B>Greek island</B>
you've always wanted, there's one for sale.  The tiny isle of <B>Ioannas</B> is
available for a mere $856,000.  There's a beach but no residence; the realtor,
Halcyon Properties,  estimates an additional cost of about $1.1 million to build
a luxury villa on the property, including water desalination plant.  The company
has less lofty offerings as well; you can contact Halcyon at (0)1323-891639.  If
you'd rather spend your mad money in a literary fashion, the <B>London</B> home
in which <B>AA Milne</B> wrote his <I>Winnie the Pooh</I> books is on the
market.  Asking price is &#163;1.2 million; the agent is John D. Wood at <B>(44)
0-171-352-1484</B>.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>What does it mean??</B>  If you're new to travel browsing, you may
wonder about the &quot;PP/DO&quot; abbreviation that you see in most
package-deal listings.  What it means is &quot;per person, double occupancy&quot;
-- in other words, the quoted price is based on buying at least two packages for
a pair traveling &amp; staying together.  If you're going solo and only want to
buy one package, expect to pay a premium (called a &quot;single supplement&quot;),
usually 20-50% over the listed price.<BR></P>
<P><I>Credit Where Credit Is Due:</I>  While we dig up Check It Out nuggets
from a variety of sources, we'd be lost without our &quot;wicking stick&quot;,
the excellent coverage found in Travel Weekly.  The premier newspaper of the
travel industry, published twice weekly by Reed Travel Group, TW offers
exhaustive coverage of travel issues, companies and products.  If you're
involved in the travel business and don't have a subscription, you're missing
out.  Call Reed at <B>800 360 0015</B>.</P>
