<BODY><P><I>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</I></P>
<H1>Meet Malta</H1>
<P><I>by Sophia Dembling</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>Europeans know the little country well, Americans hardly at all</I></B></P>
<P></P>
<P>Mention Malta and many Americans get a sort of pained, puzzled expression on
their faces -- which, loosely translated, means &quot;I've heard of Malta but
don't exactly know where or what it is.&quot; Asked to hazard a guess, they
might place Malta in Africa, or maybe near Spain. 
</P>
<P>May we be excused for our ignorance? It's such a small place, just three
tiny inhabited islands and three uninhabited islets in the Mediterranean, about
halfway between the coasts of Sicily and North Africa. The main island, Malta,
is about the size of Martha's Vineyard.  But small as it is and little as we
know about it, the powers of Europe's past knew it well as a stepping-stone
between Europe and North Africa. Players in Malta's history include the Romans
and Phoenicians, Arabs and Carthaginians, Castilians and British (from whom
Malta became independent in 1964).  Napoleon did unutterable damage in a mere
six days occupation; but Malta stood firm against Hitler despite massive
bombing, earning the nation the George Cross depicted on its flag. 
</P>
<P>The Knights of the Order of St. John, an elite multinational order of
fighters and healers, have something to do with the things we do sort of know
about Malta.  You might recognize the Maltese cross, which is the insignia of
the Order of St. John. Its four arms represent prudence, justice, temperance and
fortitude.  And you've heard of the Maltese falcon -- the Mediterranean
peregrine falcon -- which was the annual rent required by Roman emperor Charles
V when he gave the island to the knights in 1530. This modest fee could not be
paid today. The falcon has vanished from Malta, shot, trapped and otherwise
harassed out of existence.  
</P>
<P>The knights were not altogether thrilled with the gift of the little island,
which is no kind of natural paradise. The land is rugged, dry and rocky, though
these days barely in evidence in its natural form because Malta is one of the
world's most populous countries. It takes no more than half an hour to drive
between any two points on the main island and that is accomplished without ever
breaking out into wide-open spaces;  the island is virtually solid with jumbles
of buildings built of native limestone. 
</P>
<P>There are some spots that offer the more familiar ambiance of a
Mediterranean island. Marsaxlokk (say mar-sa-shlock),  the country's fishing
capital, is a village in the southeast where tourists idle in harborside cafes;
colorful boats called luzzus bob on the water, protected by eyes of Osiris
painted on their bows; fishing nets of fine nylon, like pastel-colored hair, are
laid out on the pavement to dry or rest in what looks like impossibly tangled
piles, easily unfurled by fishermen. But Marsaxlokk seems removed from the
bustle of the island and the thick history that coats it. 
</P>
<P>Malta is dense, not only with people and towns but with history and historic
sites -- it has been called a huge open-air museum. The legacy of its long
history includes prehistoric ruins older than Stonehenge and sites visited by
Saint Paul, whose shipwreck on the island brought Christianity to this devoutly
Roman Catholic country. 
</P>
<P>It is the Knights of Malta, however, who left the greatest physical mark on
Malta, after successfully defended it from the power-hungry Ottoman Empire in
1565. The knights reigned on the island for 270 years, building fabulous
churches and lavish monuments to themselves -- each nationality had its own
palace -- before losing power due to increasingly dissipate lives of drinking,
fighting and womanizing. The order still exists but has given up its wicked ways
and returned to its original charitable intents.  The knights, particularly
Grand Master Jean La Vallette (the grand master was the order's elected leader) 
were responsible for the creation of the gorgeous old city of Valletta after the
defeat of the Ottomans.  Valletta was to be, decreed La Vallette &quot;a city
built by gentlemen, for gentlemen.&quot;  Valletta, considered the world's first
planned community, was heavily fortified, its stone ramparts rise sternly from
the water. A sightseeing cruise of the Grand Harbor and tributaries offers a
vivid impression of the seriousness of the walled city's intent. 
</P>
<P>These days Valletta is a popular cruise port and holiday spot, mostly for
Brits, who still have a sentimental connection with Malta --the last British
troops shipped out in 1979.  Europeans also flock to Sliema, St. Julian's and
Paceville, touristy beachfront suburbs of Valletta, though Malta's beaches are
not nearly as glistening as those in other Mediterranean spots.  
</P>
<P>While America has yet to discover Malta, we are being targeted to take
notice. Paul Galea, director of marketing for the National Tourist Organization
of Malta says that while it is unlikely Americans would travel such a distance
for beaches far less attractive than those in the Caribbean, the abundance of
historic sites puts the nation in competition for tourists with Prague, Paris
and Venice.  The Malta National Tourist Office, once part of the United Nations
mission, became freestanding last June and has offices in New York City. While
there are no direct flights from here to there -- Air Malta flies daily from
London and Rome, less often from other European cities -- Joseph Paolino, Jr,
American ambassador to Malta, said that instating direct flights between Malta
and J.F.K  International Airport is a priority for him.  &quot;As Americans,
we're used to just getting on a plane and going,&quot; says Galea. 
</P>
<P>A likely appeal for Americans is language -- their own, that is. Malta has
two official languages, Maltese and English, which is a leftover of about 160
years of British rule.  Maltese, whose closest cousins are Lebanese and classic
Arabic, has in the written form an abundance of consonants and makes liberal use
of the letter X. Italian, too, is widely spoken, particularly on the television,
much of which comes from nearby Italy.  And, a boon in a nation where tourism is
the top industry, the Maltese people have a courteous and welcoming way about
them.  &quot;We don't make any special efforts, it just comes out naturally,&quot;
said professional guide Anna Muscat. At celebrations for the Feast of St. Paul
in February, locals happily related their history to visitors as a parade
passed. A restaurateur accepted dollars from a group of American tourists who
hadn't had a chance to change money, drawing the line only when one tourist
tried to charge a shared salad.  &quot;Madame,&quot; he said gently. &quot;I
cannot put half a salad on a credit card.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Malta could be part of a European tour or visited during a Mediterranean
cruise. Valletta is an ideal cruise port. It's a small, walkable city, its
narrow and sometimes steep streets thick with European-style palaces and
churches, easily visited in an afternoon.   Near the city's main gate is what
little is left of the Opera House, once an ornate affair designed by E.M. Barry,
architect of London's Royal Opera House, but  bombed to near  smithereens in
1942.  Fortunately, not all Malta's sites suffered so. Once Malta recovered
economically from the war, &quot;Then, thank God, we realized we have to start
taking care of our national heritage,&quot; said Anna. 
</P>
<P>Take in the stirring view of the Grand Harbor from Barraca Gardens, a
slightly ragged oasis of arches, palms, flowers and statuary originally built
for the pleasure of the Italian knights. The Grand Masters Palace is suitably
impressive for those exalted personages with two courtyards, a tapestry room
with hangings depicting fanciful scenes of the West Indies, a throne room; and
an armory in the former stable. The Manoel Theater is a gilded bauble still in
use, fashioned after Italy's Palermo theater and dating to 1731.  And the
premier sight is the vast, baroque St. John's Co-Cathedral, with its floor of
369 inlaid marble tombstones and a painting by Carravagio in the oratory.
Dedicated to the knights' patron saint, St. John the Baptist -- whose life is
depicted in a painting around the enormous vault -- the church embodied the
wealth and power of the knights without subtlety. 
</P>
<P>Within St. John's Co-Cathedral, each of the knights' nationalities had a
chapel: the Chapel of France contains the mausoleum of Vicomte de Beaujolais,
brother of King Louis Phillipe, sculpted as a languid, lounging youth. The
Chapel of Castile is the most rococo according to the taste of Grand Master
Manoel De Vilhena, which was, sniffs Anna, &quot;very bombastic.&quot; 
</P>
<P>One of city's the most impressive restorations is the prosaic-sounding
Mediterranean Conference Center in Valletta, built as a hospital in the 1500s
and elegantly restored to practical use. The wards -- great sweeping halls with
vaulted ceilings and marble floors -- now are exhibition areas and a modern
theater has been added. Here, too, you may see the Malta Experience, an
audio-visual presentation about Malta's complicated past. 
</P>
<P>A few days' visit is enough time to see the island's other sights. The ruins
of  Hagar Qim are among the most imposing of the country's 30 prehistoric sites
(only about a half dozen are open to the public), which date from about 3600 to
3200 BC. Ggantija, two prehistoric temples on the island of Gozo, a short ferry
ride away, are among the oldest freestanding structures in the world and also
may easily be visited in the course of a weeklong tour. The whys, hows and whats
of these sites, with their great stone portals and various altars, are still
just being guessed at, though prehistoric man is believed to have worshipped
goddesses of fertility within their thick walls. 
</P>
<P>All over the country, Malta's riches are represented by its churches, the
center of Maltese life, focal point of the nation's many festas, or festivals. 
&quot;They are not just museums,&quot; said Anna. &quot;They are lived in.&quot;
  
</P>
<P>St. Mary's Church in Mosta is one of the largest in Europe. It has a
glorious, airy blue, gold and white dome and its own miracle: On April 9, 1942
at 4:40 p.m., with 300 people in the church, a bomb crashed through the dome but
did not explode. A replica of the bomb is displayed in the sacristy.  In Rabat
is the small, dank grotto in which St. Paul recovered from the trauma of his
shipwreck mishap; and the House of Publius, considered the first church in Malta
because it was here Roman governor Publius brought St. Paul to preach his
gospel. Virtually all of underground Rabat is a catacombs, an eerie maze of
rocks and tunnels from which all remains have been removed, though one's
imagination might be excused for picturing them in their stony resting places. 
</P>
<P>Mdina, called the silent city, is a fusty aristocrat set high on a hill in
the island's center. It was first a Roman town, then Arabic, then Norman, each
group wiping out traces of the last until what remains is an elegant walled
medieval town. Mdina (pronounced em-deena) was home to Maltese nobility during
the knights' reign. Never deemed worthy of being invited into the Order, the
nobility retired to Mdina under autonomous rule while the knights lived in
Valletta.  Mdina is in a state of both picturesque decay and rebirth, as moneyed
Maltese move in, restoring and renovating. Only residents' cars are allowed
within city walls, so it is pleasant to stroll the quiet narrow, twisting
streets. Bona-fide &quot;sights&quot; are limited. The walk-through Medieval
Times offers a glimpse of medieval life in Malta. For those with a taste for the
grotesque, there is the graphic Museum of Torture. Better yet, simply linger
over a cup of coffee and a sweet at the Fontanella atop the ramparts and enjoy a
view of nearly all of the island and lots of deep blue sea. 
</P>
<P>There are not many places that can be viewed in almost its entirety while
sitting over a cup of coffee -- or in a week's sightseeing. But don't think you
know it all yet. With 6,000 years of history, Malta has much more to teach you
than you can learn in a week. 
</P>
<P>Still, it's a start.  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Some Travel Resources for Malta</I></H2>
<P><I>Sophia Dembling</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Getting there</B></I></P>
<P>Air Malta flies daily from London and Rome, less frequently from other
cities, including Milan, Barcelona, Paris, Cairo and many others. There also are
ferries between Malta and Sicily, a trip of about eight hours.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Climate
</B></I></P>
<P>Malta bakes in summer, winters are mild but can be wet. The sirocco -- a
hot, dry wind from North Africa -- blows May and September.  Money The lira (LM)
divides into 100 cents. These days, one lira equals about $2.75. Most
attractions charge about one lira admission. Prices, by European standards, are
not bad -- one can dine well for about $30, not including drinks.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Food</B></I></P>
<P>
Happily, Malta's cuisine has much in common with Italy's. It's hard to go wrong
with fish -- ask your server what's good. The bread is heavenly, and be sure to
try the local snack, the pastizzi, a buttery little meat- or cheese-filled
pastry. Traditional Maltese food (they particularly like rabbit) isn't easy to
come by, but you can find it at the Palazzo Constanzo Restaurant in Mdina. La
Cave in the Castile Hotel in Valletta, serves good pizzas and pastas in a
wonderful, dark, stone cellar. Gesther is a cozy spot for lunch in Xaghra on
Gozo.</P>
<P><I>Ed. Note: See also <B>Dining in Malta</B>, below</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Gozo</B></I></P>
<P>The ferry to Gozo takes about 20 minutes and is free going, about $4
returning. A helicopter offers a great view and costs about $38 one-way. Among
Gozo's sights are the Citadel in Victoria (visit the Folklore Museum, a
hodgepodge of interesting artifacts); the Azure Window, a natural stone arch;
and the prehistoric ruins of Ggantija. Gozo is slower-paced and more rural than
Malta and a popular getaway for well-heeled European. 
</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Packages</B></I></P>
<P>Malta's tourism is heavily geared towards package tours. Among the operators
offering Malta tours:</P>
<UL><LI>Group Wholesale Travel's seven-night package ranges in cost from $435
to $803, land only, depending on season and hotel. <B><I>1-800-TOUR GWT</I></B></LI>
<LI>Amelia Tours International's all-inclusive seven-night package is
$565-$1002. <B><I>1-800-SICILY-1</I></B></LI></UL>
<P>Other packages are available and other operators offer Malta tours; contact
a travel agent.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Guidebooks</B></I></P>
<P>Finding information on Malta can be challenging, but look for the Cadogan
guidebook (Globe Pequot Press, $12.95).
</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Information</B></I></P>
<P>
<B>Malta National Tourist Office</B><BR> 
<B>Empire State Building</B><BR><B>350 Fifth Ave., Suite 4412</B><BR><B>New
York, NY 10118</B><BR><B>(212) 695-9520</B></P>
<HR>
<H2>Dining in Malta</H2>
<P><I>by Myra Cummock</I></P>
<HR>
<P>In Malta there are lots of good restaurants and cafes, but if you are on a
budget, restaurants which display Tourist Menus offer great value for money.  A
typical three course Tourist Menu dinner is made up of soup, egg-mayonnaise or
fruit juice, sirloin steaks, pork chops, or omelet, all served with french fries
and salad then either ice cream or tea or coffee, all for about L2M ($5.70)
including a glass of wine.  Most restaurants and cafes also offer a full cooked
breakfast including tea or coffee and toast for around L1M. 
</P>
<P>If you wish to try Maltese food, the local fish Lampuki is popular, as is
bragiolli (beef olives) or rabbit done in a wine sauce.  If you're staying in
the Bugibba area, Granny's Restaurant at the Square is by far the most popular
-- but get there early or be prepared to wait. Another great place is the San
Paolo cafe, where homemade burgers are a meal in themselves at 40cents each, and
the quick wit of the owner and his wife make eating there a pleasure.</P>
<HR>
<P><I>An online resource for Malta:</I></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.utoronto.ca/security/malta0.htm">A Malta Home Page</A></P>
<HR>
