<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Home Exchange /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">A Home Away From Home</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>Swapping Doorkeys When Going Abroad, by Chip Lynch</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<P>My first home exchange took some work and organization, but it was more than
the effort.<BR></P>
<P>Starting a home exchange is simple:  I placed a listing on my home in a
publication called Trading Homes International.  They publish a new book
approximately every quarter; your home is listed in the newest book following
your membership and payment (about $60.00 annually).  Upon joining, you&#146;ll
receive the most recent copy and you can start looking through all of the
listings.  There&#146;s a brief description of a home, the area and the owners. 
They range from basic apartments to luxurious villas, from New York to San
Francisco, from Paris to London and in between.  The listing also tells you
where the owners would like to trade, and what time of the year they&#146;d like
to do it.  Some are open to all areas; others are very specific.   
<BR></P>
<P>I got excited about all of the possibilities and wrote to a dozen different
listings in England, France, Spain and Portugal.  I wrote a very descriptive and
friendly letter, telling about my home itself, my town and the surrounding areas
and cities.  I pointed out all of the reasons why they would want to come stay
in my home!  I also included the driving distances to interesting areas a little
further away.  (I pointed out that I live about two hours from Vail and four
hours from Aspen, etc.).  I listed all of the recreational activities, as well
as lots of cultural, historical and other interesting highlights about the
region I live in.  I also included a colorful brochure that my Chamber of
Commerce puts out on my town.  I live in a very nice home, but it is rather
suburban and only two years old, so I emphasized the region as opposed to the
home itself; but I did give a detailed description of the home so that they
could see if it suited their needs.   I sent off my inquiries and waited for my
listing to appear in the next issue. 
<BR></P>
<P>I received my first response within a matter of weeks; however, they
pleasantly turned down my offer.  As did the next, and the next and the next. 
They were polite to send such nice rejection letters, but I was getting very
discouraged.  About a month later, a larger envelope arrived in the mail for me;
and sure enough, it was a response from a woman in England who had placed a
listing for her farmhouse in France.  She was very interested in doing an
exchange!  As France was tops on my list, I was excited to say the least.  I
immediately wrote to her with more details about my plans.  Within a few days
she had called to chat and we hit it off immediately.   
<BR></P>
<P>This part of the exchange is the most time-consuming and takes the most
effort, but it is absolutely necessary to take time for careful planning. 
Planning everything in advance is essential when it comes to a successful
exchange.  I was lucky because her home was vacant most of the time; she had
bought it as a vacation home.  This made planning of dates much easier for us. 
We talked back and forth, and wrote a few times as well, before we actually
agreed to an exchange.  We sent pictures of our homes and described our
respective areas in more detail.  Her home was in an area of France called the
Charente, an area which at first glance seemed isolated, and which no one I
talked with had ever visited.  She wanted to visit Denver, while my home was
actually 25 minutes from the city, on the outskirts of Boulder instead.  But as
we talked more often, it became apparent that with a home exchange everything is
not going to be perfect; some compromise and flexibility is necessary from both
parties.  Before long we were confirming dates and times, and within a few
months of our first contact, I had purchased my plane ticket.  I had a house
named Bassinaud to go to in France! 
<BR></P>
<P>Meanwhile the listing for my home appeared in the next issue of the Home
Exchange book, and I began receiving offers for exchanges from England, France
and other parts of the U.S.  I received about a dozen offers, all of which
seemed worthwhile and a few spectacular.  But since I had already planned my
exchange, I had to send off my own rejection letters&#151;with difficulty as I
was very happy with the response, and would&#146;ve loved to take all of the
offers!   
<BR></P>
<P>Before my departure for France, I had some home exchange details to attend
to.  Since there was to be somebody staying in my home during my absence, the
planning was slightly different than that of a regular trip.  The home had to be
in &#147;user friendly&#148; condition for my guest.  This meant a long letter
explaining all of the idiosyncrasies of my home, like how to work the stereo
system, the VCR, the thermostat, the door locks, the answering machine, the
microwave, the porta-phone, the jacuzzi and the little deely-bobber that you
have to wiggle for the sprinkler system.  This is in addition to the
instructions on watering the houseplants, the potted outdoor plants and the
flower beds.   We had also agreed that she would be using one of my cars, so
that had its own set of details to be written down.  Throw in directions to
everything, restaurant recommendations, suggestions, hints, comments, and
suggestions, and soon I had pages of information for her.  (I never knew how
many words it took to describe the everyday stuff around my house!).  I&#146;d 
checked in with my insurance company (it was fine), my neighbors (ready and
excited to help her out), and my friends (who were watching my dogs at their
home while I was gone).   I also left her local emergency numbers (they&#146;re
different in Europe), those of my local friends and neighbor, plus the closest
hospitals, grocery stores, gas stations and other conveniences.  It definitely
took some more preparation than I was used to!  I  left a key hidden in a
strategic place, and one with the neighbor just in case.   When I finally drove
away to the airport, I took a deep breath and just hoped for the best. 
<BR></P>
<P>I  arrived in France, rented a car and headed towards my French farmhouse. 
She had already sent me detailed directions to the house (as I&#146;d done for
her).  During the drive southwards through France, my anticipation was growing
daily.  I stopped in wonderful, beautiful places along the way, falling madly in
love with the country in a matter of days.  Would the home I was heading to live
up to my high expectations?  I started to think I was crazy, taking a gamble
like this.  It could end up being anything, anywhere!  I was to arrive at the
house on my fourth day in France.  It was located in a tiny village called
Juignac; I could only locate it on the detailed regional Michelin map; it was
too small for the other maps I&#146;d found.  As I drove into the area, passing
through the city of  Angouleme,  I breathed a huge sigh of relief.  I only had
about twenty miles to go, and the region was stunning; farmlands and vineyards
interspersed with wooded areas, small villages and hills rolling off into the
distance.  I turned off the highway at the ancient town of Montmoreau, and
passed over a stone bridge onto a winding road.  It led through a small village
called St. Amand&#146;s, where the old men were playing a mysterious game with
croquet-like balls in the tiny town square with its stone fountain.  In a few
very rural miles, I reached the road which was my destination.  It was lined
with tall, lacy trees, giving it almost a forest feel; the first turnoff had a
small sign pointing down a winding driveway: Bassinaud.  I drove a few hundred
yards, emerged from the trees, and there was my 17th-century farmhouse.     
<BR></P>
<P>Situated on a small bluff, it sat by itself surrounded by meadows; there
were views in every direction of the rolling hills and farmlands, complete with
grazing sheep and cows.  The only other structure in sight was an old barn,
built into the hill directly across the small valley on which the house sat. 
The inside was also wonderful: thick whitewashed walls, terra cotta tiled
floors, old exposed ceiling beams, heavy wooden doors.  The kitchen, dining and
living areas were all just one big room, anchored by a huge wood burning stove. 
All of the windows were tall and multi-paned, curtained with very French looking
and yellow fabric.  Further in, I found the two pretty bedrooms and the
bathroom, which had been modernized and was good sized.  (There was also a newer
dishwasher, clothes washer and small refrigerator, all very useful in the coming
days).  Many of the furnishings were antique, some original to the house and
going back hundreds of years.  The whole effect was immediate on me&#151;none of
it was fancy; all of it charming.  
<BR></P>
<P>I spent three weeks in the farmhouse.  I frequented the nearby outdoor
markets on market days and brought back goat cheese, chicken, duck, five
different kinds of asparagus, eggs and eggplant, all locally raised or grown.  I
drank delicious $2.00 bottles of local wine and had warm bread to go with it.  I
sat in small cafes and patisseries and drank coffee and watched and chatted with
the local people; visited stunning chateaux and quaint villages and incredible
cities with endless shops; saw barking deer, strange birds and wild turkeys.  I
traveled all over the region, driving for hours through stunning countryside and
never encountered any American tourists.  I had the best vacation of my life and
stayed in my new favorite place in the world&#151;without paying a dime for
lodging. 
<BR></P>
<P>Obviously my home exchange in France worked out wonderfully; that&#146;s why
I like to share my experience with other travelers.  I&#146;ve since become
great friends with the owner of the house; she has visited me more than once,
and I plan to return again to her place in France this spring for another three
week stay.  You must look into a home exchange!  That is what I&#146;ve been
saying (shouting!) since I returned from my own.  Gambling on the combination of
my first home exchange with my first trip to France added up to a perfectly
wonderful trip of a lifetime for me.  It could work for you, too. &#164;  
<BR></P>
<P><I>To find out more about home exchange, contact Trading Homes
International, P.O. Box 787, Hermosa Beach CA  90254; Phone:  (310) 798-3864,
FAX: (310) 798-3865
</I></P>
<HR>
