<P><B>What does it mean??</B>  If you're new to travel browsing, you may
wonder about the &quot;PP/DO&quot; abbreviation that you see in most
package-deal listings.  What it means is &quot;per person, double occupancy&quot;
-- in other words, the quoted price is based on buying at least two packages for
a pair traveling &amp; staying together.  If you're going solo and only want to
buy one package, expect to pay a premium (called a &quot;single supplement&quot;),
usually 20-50% over the listed price.</P>
<P><B>Credit Where Credit Is Due:</B>  While we dig up Check It Out nuggets
from a variety of sources, we'd be lost without our &quot;wicking stick&quot;,
the excellent coverage found in <I>Travel Weekly</I>.  The premier newspaper of
the travel industry, published twice weekly by Reed Travel Group, <I>TW</I>
offers exhaustive coverage of travel issues, companies and products.  If you're
involved in the travel business and don't have a subscription, you're missing
out.  Call Reed at <B>800 360 0015.</B>  Remember to tell them you saw it in
European Visits! 
