<TITLE>European Visits: Greece's Hidden Jewel</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Greece's Hidden Jewel</FONT></H1>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">by Gordon Laughiand</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<P><STRONG><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">A Memorable Ride, and Tracks Through
the Hotel</FONT></EM></STRONG><BR></P>
<P>Whenever I eat a Greek olive or see a massive stone column on a public
building do I think of the Acropolis or of the wonders of Delphi?  No, I am
reminded of a railway on the north side of the Peloponnese of Greece.  Railfans
that you are, I am sure you will understand.<BR></P>
<P>In 1991, while on a visit to this ancient land and after absorbing so many
ruins that our minds could appreciate no more, my wife and I found our way to a
most fascinating and beautiful valley with a cog railway line.  Talking
(English/German) one morning with a rail worker in a Grecian town, where
monasteries and nunneries are seemingly glued to the very tops of stone
mountains, I was told of a very interesting railway.  One that, I was assured,
seldom sees tourists and very few Greeks.  That was the clue that I needed.<BR></P>
<P>Leaving Athens at 8:30 one morning we were forced to ride a special bus west
for one hour as far as Corinth due to track work on the meter gauge line.  This
did, however, give us a different view of the railway bridge over the Corinth
Canal.  At the Corinth station the &quot;only Inter-City  meter gauge train&quot;
was waiting and we departed behind a diesel-electric engine.  (Apologies may be
due here to the RhB and others  for this Greek claim).  A couple of hours later,
after continuing west along the very beautiful shoreline of the Guff of Corinth
toward Patras, we arrived at Diakofto.  On the south side of the station was a
2-foot gauge track waiting for the 12:15 train to Kalavrita to terminate and
then depart.  It was about an  hour late but its turnaround time was minimal
because it had only two cars, with what looked like a very large commercial air
compressor coupled in between.  Very definitely a unit train, the &quot;locomotive&quot;
 seemed to pull and push at the same time whatever the direction.  The weather
was hot so the side panels were largely off the engine to allow better cooling. 
In fact the &quot;engine&quot; was just a diesel-powered generator.  Motored
trucks resided in each of the two passenger cars.  The bogies carried side rods
to couple the wheels for the necessary flatland adhesion and, of course, the cog
assembly was in the middle of each powered truck.<BR></P>
<P>We captured a front seat and the climb started south up to the mouth of a
granite river canyon that had never been pierced by more than this little
railway.  In later years a road was attempted through the rocks but to no avail.
 The Vouraikos river commands all but the track bed, which in places is laid
through partial and complete tunnels and over iron and rock bridges.  A road was
finally established some miles to  the east.  Topping out of the deepest part of
the valley, after running most of the time on the rack, the  train arrived at
our destination:  a village called Zahlorou.  Zahlorou, at 2086 feet elevation,
is maybe half-way to the southern terminal of Kalavrita, fourteen miles from the
Gulf of Corinth.<BR></P>
<P>Terming Zahlorou a village is a bit generous but it is a place to
appreciate.  The trains make their noise as they pass through but when they
leave, only the river music takes over the audio entertainment.  There are two
or three buildings by the station, one of which was our hotel.  The track passes
directly through the area between the kitchen and the dining tables and
continues over a bridge to the remaining portion of the settlement.  On the
other side of the river is a very small store, possibly a bakery, ouzo supplier
and a handful of houses.  A one-lane dirt road allows motor vehicles into
Zahlorou from Kalavrita but not into our part of town.  How peaceful!<BR></P>
<P>The best reason for this station stop is that for many years it served the
lower end of a steep donkey trail that rose to Mega Spileon, a monastery built
over 3000 feet above sea level by Orthodox Byzantine monks in 362ad.  Access now
is available by using the aforementioned road that would not fit into the river
canyon.  A hike up the mountain trail was worth the effort, if only for views of
the beautiful scenery.  The eight-story monastery itself was very fascinating. 
It had been secured to the side of a vertical granite mountain peak, a
construction site that seems to have been popular in ancient Greece.  Hard to
believe this could have been done over fifteen hundred years ago -- or even
today!<BR></P>
<P>Zahlorou has one of the few passing tracks on this line and therefore is a &quot;hotspot&quot;
of railroad activity.  No CTC here, so the crew throws a switch if needed. 
Occasionally, due to a relaxed schedule, trains do meet here but there are
usually only two units in operation each day.  As I recall, each of the two made
two round trips a day.  The passenger service accommodates the local residents
with mail and incidental drop-offs.<BR></P>
<P>I could never really find out when freight service ended, but steam engines
were said to have been phased out in the late 1950s.  The line was built for
mining about the turn of the century and two of the old steamers are on display
at the terminals along with an ancient wooden passenger coach at Kalavrita. 
There are a few box cars and hoppers available for maintenance work.  The forty
year old diesel-electric passenger units are repaired at the main shop in
Diakolto, but are occasionally shipped to Austria for major rebuilding.  Spare
generator cars are switched in and out frequently I was told.<BR></P>
<P>We took a ride up to Kalavrita on the second day of our visit.  While the
size of a good small town, it has little to offer except the Helmos skiing slope
in the winter and historical monuments and religious structures the year long. 
Frankly, we stayed only an hour or two until the next down train.  Lunch at the
station was good but not spectacular.  The most noted story about Kalavrita is
told about a horrible crime against humanity that happened during World War II. 
Greeks had the courage to resist the Nazi forces that controlled that area, and
late in 1943 the invaders decided that they would teach a lesson to the patriots
who were giving them trouble.  So they gunned down and shoved all 1,400 male
residents, men and boys alike, off cliffs.  The females, young and old, were
closed in a school across from the rail station and then the whole town was set
on fire.  The hands of the church clock in the center of town are now fixed at
2:34 to remind everyone of the infamous act.  It must be said that many visitors
to Kalavrita today are German citizens who come to show their shame of the Nazi
action.<BR></P>
<P>In closing, I would be remiss if I did not mention the hotel and food
service in the little hotel &quot;Romantzo&quot; in Zahlorou.  This hotel would
be hard pressed to gain a Michelin listing of even the minimum.  It had only
five or six rooms, a bit threadbare, but perfectly clean.  Our room, with
balcony, would have allowed us to drop a water balloon on the train roof had we
wished.  The view of the station was prima -- and that was important.  The open
air library and dining room of the hotel was seven paces across the track from 
the front door and close to the river.  The food was the best that we had on our
two week Greek tour and on  the cruise ship that followed.  Admittedly, not as
fancy, but the hotel owner/waiter and his wife and  mother served food, plain,
but to die for.  We also had  help-yourself service from the freezer and bar. 
Both  of us would urge any railfan or just people searching for beauty and
tranquillity, if in or near Greece, to consider a visit to this wonderful area. 
It was a bit expensive however.  Our stay of two nights, with all our meals and
service included, was a drachma or two over $52.00.   &#164; <BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">This article originally appeared in Issue Number
68, Fourth Quarter 1995, of <B>ETE Express</B>, the newsletter of European
Train Enthusiasts, Inc.  Reprinted by permission.  European Train Enthusiasts is
a nonprofit organization devoted to the subject of European trains and railway
operations.  Membership, including a subscription to <B>ETE Express</B>, is $15
per year.  For further information, contact ETE at PO Box 22392, Sacramento, CA
95822, or visit their Web site at <B><A
HREF="http://www.sterns.com/sterns/ete.html">http://www.sterns.com/sterns/ete.html</A></B>.
 </FONT></I></P>
