<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - On the Rhone (Part 1)
/ Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">On the Rhone</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>A Tale of Province (Part 1), by M. Johnston</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--On the Rhone Part 1 by M. Johnston--><BR></P>
<P>To a winemaker, professional or amateur, the tart, yeasty aroma of freshly
crushed fermenting grapes in the crisp autumn air is one of life&#146;s supreme
delights.  And there are few places in the world where the eager enophile can
savor this experience in greater measure than in the tiny village of
Chateauneuf-du-Pape at grape harvest time.
<BR></P>
<P>	&#147;Like a pastry freak in the world&#146;s largest bakery,&#148; I
suggested to my wife as we strolled leisurely past a  succession of street-front
wineries toward the town square. 	&#147;Or a 5-year-old loose in F. A. O.
Schwartz,&#148; she replied, as Small Son ran his toy racing car along the
pitted stone walls behind which fermenting grapes gurgled contentedly in
concrete cells.
<BR>	&#147;Just think, Son&#151;some of the best wines in the world are made
right here.&#148; 	Arne looked up at me with big eyes. <BR> &#147;Are they
better than yours?&#148;<BR> &#147;Well....&#148; 	&#147;They&#146;re
different,&#148; my wife explained. 	&#147;Right.  And we&#146;re here to find
out what makes them different, so maybe we can&#151;&#148;<BR>&#147;Look at
that big tractor!&#148; Arne pointed as another wagonload of grapes from a
nearby vineyard was  towed through the arched entrance of a winery just ahead of
us.  &#147;Daddy, what&#146;s French for &#145;tractor&#146;?&#148; 	<BR>&#147;Uh....&#148;
reaching for the well-thumbed Larousse in my back pocket. 	<BR>&#147;<I>Tracteur</I>,&#148;
my wife supplied, and Arne echoed &#147;Trac-TOOR!&#148; 
</P>
<P>We reached the wide port where the tractor had entered.  Inside the spacious
room, two men in tanktops were lifting a metal lid from a raised portion of the
stone floor.  	&#147;They&#146;re going to dump the grapes into  that big hole,&#148;
I pointed.  &#147;Stems and all, notice -- remember the big machine they used in
Bordeaux to take the stems off?&#148; 	<BR>&#147;What&#146;s French for &#145;stem&#146;?&#148;
Arne wanted to know as the pulpy, purple mass was shoveled into the gaping hole.
	<BR>&#147;Stem...&#148; flipping through pages of Larousse. 	<BR>&#147;<I>Tige</I>,&#148;
Emily replied. 	<BR>&#147;Right.  They leave the tiges on here to add character
and tannin.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;Some of those grapes are white,&#148; Emily noted.
&#147;Or are they just unripe?&#148; 	<BR>&#147;Good question.  We&#146;ll have
to ask the Brunels.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;Speaking of whom,&#148; looking at her
watch, &#147;we told them we&#146;d arrive by four, and it&#146;s already half
past.  We&#146;d better start looking for their house.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;I guess
so.&#148;  A last deep breath. &#147;Boy, does that smell good.  Take a whiff of
that, Arne.&#148; 	Small Son tried valiantly, but produced only a muffled
wheeze. &#147;I can&#146;t smell anything.  My nose is full of gunk.&#148;  He
frowned, &#147;What&#146;s French for &#145;gunk&#146;?&#148; 	Emily produced a
Kleenex.  &#147;Blow.&#148;<BR></P>
<P><B>Anne and Andre Brunel are the proprietors of the Cailloux vineyards of
Chateauneuf-du-Pape.</B>  They were among a half-dozen vineyard owners from the
major wine-producing districts of France who had responded to our inquiries
about the possibility of a working visit during the Fall harvest.  We planned a
three-week tour of the wine country, and it was our hope to spend a week or so
learning what we could about local vineyard management and winemaking
techniques.  
<BR></P>
<P>Our interest went back several years, during which we had stocked a fairly
respectable cellar, made our own wine from local grapes, and were now starting a
small vineyard in northern Maryland.  We knew that harvest time was a busy one
in these areas, which would leave little time for social amenities.  But we 
hoped that by offering to help with the picking of the grapes, we would have an
opportunity to learn first hand while being useful instead of just in the way. 
We made it clear in our inquiries that we did not expect to be paid for our help
(local pickers can earn decent wages by being in the right place at the right
time during the harvest), although some assistance with accommodations would be
appreciated.  Most of the people we wrote to replied and expressed interest in
the arrangement.  The Brunels&#146; response had been the most cordial, and
that, combined with our long-standing fondness for Rhone wines, was the reason
for our choice. 
<BR></P>
<P>Unlike Bordeaux, where the winery, vineyard and owner&#146;s residence are
frequently part of the same  complex called a chateau, the facilities in
Burgundy and Rhone are often widely separated.  In Chateauneuf-du-Pape, the
vineyards are distributed over a wide area surrounding the town, but the
harvested grapes are brought into town to the cuveries&#151;garage-size
buildings with crushers and presses&#151;for processing.  Most of the owners
live elsewhere in the village, or in neighboring towns like Orange and Avignon.

<BR></P>
<P>We found the Brunels&#146; residence from the directions they had sent&#151;one
of several three-story row houses a block from the square.  The houses are
mostly stone or stucco, with shuttered windows, heavy doors, and an occasional
wrought-iron balustraded balcony lined with flower pots.   A number of cars were
parked  with two wheels up on the narrow sidewalk which separates the house
fronts from the steep, winding  street.  A tawny cat was sitting in one of the
open doorways, washing a white paw, and a spotted basset hound was sprawled
asleep at the base of a wide set of concrete steps snaking up between two
buildings. 
<BR></P>
<P>The Brunels had not yet returned from the day&#146;s activities in their
vineyard.  We tacked a note on their  door and, leaving our rented car half on
the sidewalk with the others, strolled back down to the town square to wait.  We
called it a &#145;square&#146;, since most French towns we had visited were
situated around a plot  of ground in the centre ville with a fountain or an
arrangement of colorful flowers.  The square in Chateauneuf-du-Pape is little
more than an intersection of five narrow roads, with a tree-shaded fountain  off
to one side and a cafe/bar with a cluster of outdoor tables across the street. 
A tourist information center (no English), hotel, and bakery were situated on
the other corners.  We sat at one of the tables at  the cafe and ordered a
carafe of the local white and a Coke for Arne.<BR></P>
<P><B>The major entertainment of the town quickly became apparent.</B>  The
amount of traffic which surges  through the square defies reality; huge trucks,
tractors and tourist buses, many seemingly wider than the streets themselves,
all descend upon the tiny intersection and somehow manage to emerge unscathed on
 the opposite side.  There are no traffic lights&#151;only a few white stripes
painted on the crosswalks.  Add to this a steady parade of pedestrians, animals,
bicycles and mopeds, and the real wonder is that there aren&#146;t any
accidents.  Not even a close call.<BR></P>
<P>The square became even more lively near six o&#146;clock as the rest of the
town&#146;s population began returning  from the vineyards.  Our hosts were
among them, and had no trouble picking us out of the crowd. 	</P>
<P>&#147;You&#146;re dressed for travel,&#148; Anne Brunel told us after
introductions, &#147;and everyone else is dressed for  work.&#148;  Anne and
Andre Brunel complement each other perfectly. She is animated and talkative, and
he is quiet  and reserved.  Both are young and attractive&#151;Anne is slim,
freckled, with reddish hair usually bound up  under a silk head scarf; Andre is
blond and sturdy in a James Dean sort of way, a resemblance enhanced  by jeans,
boots and a cowboy hat.  Both speak excellent English. 
<BR></P>
<P>Our welcome was warm but necessarily brief&#151;work still remained to be
done transferring the last load of  grapes to the fermentation tanks.  Andre
excused himself to see to this task while Anne escorted us to a  charming
two-story stucco house on a cul-de-sac a few blocks away, the residence of Andre&#146;s
parents  where we would be staying during our visit.  In spite of its proximity
to the town square, the setting here was tranquil and quiet, with no sign of
traffic.    Across the road a green blanket of vines sloped gently outward
toward a range of low hills, behind which  lay the Rhone River.  In the other
direction, a patchwork of red barrel-tile roofs could be seen clustered  around
the base of a steep hill.  The top of the hill was dominated by the towering
shell of the Pope&#146;s  Castle, after which the town is named.  Only two
ancient and crumbling walls remain, but they are still a  vivid reminder of the
vast scale on which the 14th-century Roman inhabitants of this region thought
and built. 
<BR></P>
<P>We were to occupy the ground floor of the house; Andre&#146;s parents live
upstairs.  Inside we found a  comfortable bedroom with twin beds and a floor
mattress for Arne.  A large picture window with heavy wooden shutters provided a
scenic view of the vineyards and hills.  Next to the bedroom was a bathroom
without a bidet (&#147;A shame,&#148; Emily remarked. &#147;No place to soak
tired feet.&#148;), and across the hall was a kitchen with fridge, stove, dishes
and silverware.  The rest of the downstairs was essentially a storeroom,  and
contained a very welcome washing machine. 
<BR></P>
<P>Outside, a wide gravel driveway separated the house from a tree-lined garden
of roses, yellow daisies,  begonias and potted geraniums, all in full bloom. 
Arne immediately busied himself creating roads and hills in the driveway pebbles
for his travel toys, while Anne filled Emily and me in on life in Chateauneuf-
du-Pape. 	<BR>&#147;It isn&#146;t always this hectic,&#148; she assured us,
removing the scarf from her head, &#147;only during the  vendage, when all the
grapes must be picked within the specified period of time.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;Specified?&#148;
	<BR>&#147;By law.  Regulations here are very strict, to protect the reputation
of our wines.  For example, one cannot  begin picking before the authorized date
without specific written permission.  Only certain kinds of grapes can be grown
in our vineyards, and the boundaries are strictly defined.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;I
know that your wine is normally a blend of a lot of different varieties.  Is
there any regulation on the  proportions used?&#148; 	<BR>She shook her head. &#147;That
is strictly up to the individual, as long as the grapes are among the 13 
recognized varieties.  But usually it is simply a matter of what kind of grapes
happen to be growing in a particular vineyard&#151;the owner will use it all
anyway, as long as it doesn&#146;t exceed the allowed maximum.&#148;       
<BR>&#147;That&#146;s regulated too?&#148; 	&#147;Oh yes.  Forty-four
hectoliters per hectare.  That&#146;s ... let&#146;s see, less than 400 gallons
per acre.&#148; 
<BR>	&#147;When did the harvest officially begin this year?&#148; Emily asked
as she unpacked our suitcases on the bed.  	<BR>&#147;We started over a week
ago.  There&#146;s another week or so of work left to be done.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;And
how does the quality look this year?&#148;  	<BR>&#147;Very good.  The weather
has been hot and the alcohol will average well over 13%.  But because of very
bad weather last spring the harvest will be small.&#148; 	<BR>There go the
prices again, I thought. 	<BR>Anne looked at her watch. &#147;I must get back. 
When do you plan to join us for the picking?&#148;  	<BR>&#147;Right away,&#148;
I said.  &#147;I&#146;ll go with you tomorrow morning while Emily does some
shopping, then she&#146;ll  join us.&#148; 	<BR>&#147;Fine.  We work from 7:30
to 11:30, then resume from two till six.&#148;  	<BR>&#147;I think I&#146;m
beginning to appreciate the long lunch hours here in France,&#148; I told her. 
<BR>She grinned. &#147;You&#146;ll appreciate them even more after you&#146;ve
spent four hours stooping to pick grapes.&#148;  She gathered her gloves, scarf
and shears.  &#147;We leave from in front of our winery, just up the block on
the main street into town.  Meet me there at 7:15.&#148;  &#164; 
</P>
<P><I>&#147;On the Rhone&#148; will continue in our next issue.</I></P>
<HR>
