<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Venice</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Venice: Views and Venues</H2>
<P><I>by Nathalie Zeidman</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Years ago I was standing in a crowded vaporetto</B> chugging along
Venice's Grand Canal when a young American near me pointed to a deteriorating
palazzo and said loud enough for everyone to hear:   &quot;Back home we'd call
that a slum.&quot; To this day I regret not telling him off.  &quot;Sure,&quot;
I might have said, &quot;Venice's marble palazzos need  cleaning, repairing and
propping up.  They've been around for centuries, providing home base to more
than a few interesting people:  Marco Polo, Othello and his crew; Byron,
Browning and Ruskin; Peggy Guggenheim.&quot;  And I envy them all, I might have
added, though I'm not sure I'd want to live here year-round; with winds off the
Adriatic, winters are cold and damp, summers humid and mosquito infested. 
Spring and fall are ideal.  I prefer fall and that's when I usually go to
Venice.<BR></P>
<P>No matter how often I've been there, like all tourists, I head straight for
St. Mark's.  It's reassuring to find every landmark on the Square in place: the
Renaissance Doge's Palace, the celebrated Bridge of Sighs, the Prison (Casanova
slept here); the simple Campanile and elaborate Clock towers; dazzling St.
Mark's Basilica itself.  The church's rooftop statues, in particular the larger
than life gilded bronze horses, are standouts among golden spires and Byzantine
domes.  I love those horses as much for their history as for their massive
grace.  Created in 4th Century  B.C. Greece, they were liberated almost a 1000
years later by Emperor Constantine and brought to the Byzantium he conquered and
renamed for himself.  In the 13th century the horses were again liberated -- by
the crusaders this time -- and carted of f to Venice, where they have been
sitting on the portico's roof ever since.  (Today the portico horses are a
reasonable facsimile -- the original was moved several decades ago to the
Basilica's museum.)    If the exterior of St. Mark's Basilica dazzles, the
interior overwhelms with decorative marble,  porphyry, mosaics depicting scenes
from the New Testament and a gold altar piece enameled and bejeweled in
Constantinople a millennium ago.  But all this imported art doesn't deflect from
Venice's native artists; Tintoretto, for one. Il Scuelo di San Rocco, a gorgeous
Renaissance building with Baroque woodwork, showcases a series of 56 canvases by
the master.  Other Tintorettos are in the churches of Santa Maria della Salute
and San Georgio.  The Franciscan Gothic Santa Maria dei Fran, largest church in
Venice, has a number of Titians and a Bellini Madonna.<BR></P>
<P>Another collection is housed in a former convent-church, now the Academia
Delle Belle Arti.  Okay -- the Academy of Fine Arts.  I have a penchant for
using Italian names; I love the language even in my fractured phrasing.  I'll
seize any opportunity to say,  &quot;Bon journo,&quot; &quot;Scusi,&quot; &quot;Palazzo
Rezzonico.&quot;  I'm crazy about the Palazzo Rezzonico not so much for its
elegant Venetian Baroque furniture as for the view from its balcony of the Grand
Canal and aging palazzos.  I'm fond of Peggy Guggenheim's palace just because it
is a palace, a palace a rich American bought and lived in surrounded by her
collection of modern and contemporary art.  Tintorettos and Canelettos
notwithstanding, the masterpiece of the Adriatic is Venice herself, all 117
Islands, 150 canals and 400 bridges.  To detour along a ribbon of canal shaded
by a row of modest palazzos and suddenly find myself in a sun-drenched square
with tables and chairs, potted plants, and a menu posted on the wall is to come
upon an unexpected treasure.  After six visits I still can't speak Italian but I
can eat it &quot;Con gusto.&quot;  I can hardly go wrong with a plate of recis e
bisi, a bowl of risotto, a platter of frito misto, a glass of wine. 
Valpolicella or Soave will do nicely.<BR></P>
<P>When I've eaten too well several days in a row I like to take lunch at the
outdoor market at the foot of the Grand Canal's famed Rialto Bridge.  Crowded
with shops and shoppers, the bridge, as old as The Merchant of Venice, curves
high enough to allow an armed galley to pass under.  At the bottom of the Rialto
steps large carts filled with produce and cheese from the country and  local
pastas do a thriving business.  In the fall pears from Lombardy and grapes from
the Po are bountiful and pyramids of flame, celedon and jet tilt the carts
precariously.  Along with fruit I like chunks of assorted cheeses and a. half
kilo of pasta pudding studded with citron.  Although there are benches at the
Rialto boat landing I prefer to enjoy my snack sitting on the stone steps.  It's
a good place to follow the canal traffic.  Families coming to the market by
motor boat, gondola or vaporetto get off empty-handed, and back on with string
bags bulging.  Concessionaires deliver wholesale quantities of food;  I once saw
a motor boat with nothing but crates of live pigeons.<BR></P>
<P>On a warm day I like to board vaporetto no.6 from St. Mark's to the Lido, a
resort island in the  Venetian lagoon.  No longer the haunt of the literati, the
Lido still attracts visitors.  Several smart beach-front hotels rent cabanas to
sun-deprived northern Europeans, and a public casino, nothing as snooty as Monte
Carlo's, offers &quot;the big chance.&quot;  A walk on the sand, lunch on the
terrace of the Hotel des Bains are all I need to be reminded of one of my
favorite novellas, <I>Death in Venice</I>.<BR></P>
<P>On the other side of the lagoon lie three other islands dear to me:  Murano,
Burano and  Torcello.  At least once on every visit I must go to all three. 
Getting there is half the fun.  At the back of St. Mark's Square, among the
souvenir shops, cafes and money exchanges is a modest arch.  Through the arch a
mysterious passageway winds along a canal one could almost leap  across, and
passes dark palazzos converted to apartments like so many on the Grand Canal. 
Turning a corner I always expect to stumble on a masked figure or two left over
from carnival.  Instead I'm in the open at a long strip of dock, the Fondamente
Nuove.  Vaporettos leave from here every half hour, give or take, for the
islands.<BR></P>
<P>Murano, the largest of the three, is famous for its blown glass.  Colors and
shapes can be  exquisite or, as in recent years, garish.  My soul isn't mated to
Disney monsters in startling hues, and the more conventional pieces are
expensive, but I enjoy watching the craftsmen at work, blowing bubbles that may
last forever.  Another ten-minute steamer ride and I'm in Burano, a fishing
village known for its lace. Venetian lace, in my grandmother's day called &quot;Pointe
Venise&quot;, is celebrated so I spend a little time at the stalls.  Just
looking -- some of what's sold in Burano, I've heard, is made in China.  One
would have to be an expert to tell the difference.<BR></P>
<P>Mainly what I like to do on Burano is walk the narrow streets, look at the
small cottages in shades of henna, blue and gold and greet the women and
children:  &quot;Bon journo, signorina; bon journo, bambini.&quot;<BR></P>
<P>Two steamer whistles and a chug-a-lug bring me from Burano to Torcello.  I
spend most of my  day in Torcello.  There is no industry here.  The village
square is overgrown with grass and both  the church and the cathedral, each
dating from at least the 11th century, are in disrepair.  But the cathedral's
Byzantine mosaics, jeweled portraits of the Madonna and The Last Judgment are 
exceptional.  What I like best about Torcello besides its mosaics is the Locanda
Ciprini.  Set in a  grape arbor, this locanda or country inn looks out upon the
sea,   How relaxing it is to idle along  an arbor path, circle the locanda and
wind up at one of the little wrought iron tables for a  Campari and soda.  After
a while I'm ready to move to a properly set dinner table.  At the Locanda
Cipriani my soup, salad and dessert may vary.  As long as I start my meal with
gnocchi, tiny potato or semolina dumplings in a light sauce, I'm happy.  The
Locanda's gnocchi is as  delicate as Burano lace, as light as Murano glass.  Do
I exaggerate?  Ask some people who come to Torcello just to eat that gnocchi.<BR></P>
<P>The Locanda Cipriani is well patronized yet I always feel my little party is
the only party in the  arbor.  No doubt this sense of privacy accounts for
Hemingway having spent days there at work at one novel or another. The family
that owns Torcello's Locando owns Harry's New York Bar and the new Hotel
Cipriani, both beyond my means.  The Locanda is not and I've thought of spending
a night or two in one of its feather-bedded rooms.  But grape arbors and
seaviews notwithstanding, in Venice I like my breakfast coffee and rolls in
front of a window that overlooks a canal, a bridge, a palazzo.  If that Venice
scene is a slum, I'll take it anytime.  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Getting There:</B> Alitalia flies from key North American cities to
Venice via Rome.  From the Marco Polo Airport, boats take visitors to a terminal
near the Piazza san Marco, and from there a vaporetto will take you to your
hotel (or close to it).  Travel lightly when coming to Venice to save the hassle
and expense of porters.  Many international <B>trains</B> arrive at Venice,
including night trains from Paris, Brussels, Vienna, and Budapest; refer to the
Thomas Cook European Timetable for timings.  (When you're looking it up,
remember that within the European rail system, Venice is referred to as &quot;Venezia.&quot;)
 Trains may stop at Venezia Mestre, an inland station, at Venezia SMN (the main
station), or both; if the former, you must disembark and board a local train for
the short ride to Venice &quot;proper&quot;.  If you're <B>driving</B>, you'll
have to leave your car at a carpark on the mainland.  Spaces are limited and can
be costly in high season; if you're staying long, you may save by leaving your
vehicle with a garage in Vicenza or Padua and buying a 2nd class rail ticket to
Venice.<BR></P>
<P><B>Staying There:</B>  Venice has a great variety of hotels, from the
fabulous (and fabulously expensive) to small, economical pensiones.  Hotel rates
in Venice are much affected by season: if you want to go during the famous
Carnival (takes place in early spring), reserve far in advance and be prepared
to pay.  Take care when you see a terrific hotel deal &quot;in Venice&quot; that
it's not located in Venice Mestre, the city's relatively unattractive, and quite
canal-less, mainland suburb. 
</P>
<P>Information: <B>Italian National Tourist Offices, 630 5th Avenue, Suite
1565, New York NY 10111; 212-245-4832</B>.
</P>
<HR>
<H2>The Visit of the Northern Counts</H2>
<P><B><I>An 18th-Century Extravaganza Is Planned for the Venetian Carnival</I></B><BR></P>
<P><B>Been there, you say?  Done that?</B>  If you're looking for something
very unsual -- and you've been stuffing it away in the old mattress -- you'll be
interested in a unique and spectacular tourism event being planned for next
year's Venetian Carnival by Hello America, a tour operator based in California. 
Casting travelers themselves as both audience and costumed, choreographed
participants, the company will orchestrate the re-enactment of an actual event
which took place in 1782, the historic visit of Nicholas Petrovic (heir to the
Russian throne and son of Catherine the Great) to the high and mighty nobles of
the opulent, powerful Republic of Venice.  The Tzarevich was accompanied by his
wife Maria Feodorvna, her brother Prince Frederick von Wurttemberg, and a large
retinue of nobles and courtiers. Venice greeted the wealthy &quot;Northern
Counts&quot; with all the pomp and grandiose splendor for which the time and
place were deservedly noted.<BR></P>
<P>Participants may choose their own roles in advance, selecting from a long
list of specific historic individuals including not only the royalty, nobles and
dignitaries of the Russian court and retinue, but also exotic ambassadors from
the many countries which paid court to the Republic of Venice at that time. The
Venetian nobility will be represented by authentic descendents of local noblemen
and noblewomen, and the many receptions, balls, and banquets that marked the
18th-century extravaganza will be played out over a seven-day period in some of
Venice's most beautiful and historic private palaces.<BR></P>
<P>This elaborate, breathtakingly deluxe program includes lodging in the most
refined hotels that Venice has to offer, including the Hotel Gritti, the Luna
Baglioni, the Bauer Grunwald, and the Monaco &amp; Grand Canal.  Catering will
be in the hands of world famous companies such as Dino Boscarato and Harry's Bar
and will represent the very best of Venetian cuisine.  All participants will be
fitted with Domino cloaks, &quot;Bauta&quot; masks, and &quot;Zendalo&quot;
veils, along with authentic period costumes of precious brocades, silks, laces
and gold embroidery; the costumes are designed and provided by Stefano Nicolao,
the famous Oscar nominated designer of the film Farinelli.  (We are not talking
paper hats for dinner at &quot;Medieval Times&quot; -- according to the
organizer, individual costumes range in value as high as $12,000.)  Prior to re
enactments the participants will receive instruction on court etiquette by a
professional Master of Ceremonies, and lessons in 18th century dances by
professional choreographers.  The program will also feature appearances from
prominent Venetian personalities and writers, and for at least one dinner a
private orchestra is hired.  Some events will be filmed with copies available at
the close of the week.<BR></P>
<P>As one might expect such an extravagant experience does not come cheap. 
Costs depend on the importance of the personality one chooses to portray, and
range from $33,500 to portray Maharani, wife of the Indian Maharajah, to $57,000
for the haughty soul who chooses to be Tzarevich Nicholas Petrovic himself. 
(Reflecting the elaborate nature of the production, the costlier and more
prominent roles include six extra nights in Venice &quot;for necessary
rehearsals with our choreographer.&quot;) <BR> </P>
<P>Intrigued?  Bored?  Wealthy?  Contact Hello America, Inc. (member of ASTA)
for more information, by fax at (805) 965-2393 or by email at<A
HREF="mailto:helloamerica.com@info">info@helloamerica.com</A>; they also offer
an &quot;online brochure&quot; on the Web at<A
HREF="http://www.helloamerica.com/venice/venice1.htm">http://www.helloamerica.com/venice/venice1.htm</A>.
 The program will take place from Feb. 5 to Feb. 13, 1997.  Pricing is per
person per personality, starting at $29,800 incuding meals, costumes, events,
hosts and guides, local transportation, and lodging.  Airfare to Venice is
additional.  &#164;	
</P>
