<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Fabulous Wimbledon</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Fabulous Wimbledon</H2>
<P><I>By Walker Jackson</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Walker Joe, you backpacked to the Wimbledon Tournament?</B> Yes!  Not
once, but four straight years starting in 1989. Why would anyone backpack to
Wimbledon?  To get the fabulous reserved tickets the All England Tennis Club
saves for the public; to save money; and to enjoy the challenge.  The tickets
are limited;  if you want a regularly priced ticket, you have to line up (or
queue) by eight the night before and sleep there. Otherwise, a Centre Court or
Court 1 ticket, where the best players are scheduled to play, can cost $200 if
bought from a scalper. 
<BR></P>
<P>I've enjoyed twenty fabulous days at Wimbledon and, if I had to pick one day
to tell about, it would be the second Thursday in 1991. Why?  I got to sleep in
a soft, warm bed the night before, after three nights on Somerset Road; take a
lovely hot shower, eat a sumptuous breakfast, and purchase an unbelievable
ticket at a ridiculously cheap price.  Only a tight wad would enjoy sleeping on
a road?  Well... I resemble that remark.<BR></P>
<P>The day, July 4,  1991, started at my bed and breakfast.  The night had been
strangely quiet: no fireworks.  Mrs. Jackie Dodd -- you knew she was Irish the
moment she smiled -- served me  orange juice, coffee, eggs, bacon, toast, jam,
and I paid her &#163;22 ($38) for the amenities.  Wimbledon's ticket windows
would be open at 10:30, and I wanted one more shot at getting a ticket. I had no
idea what to expect.  &quot;Wimbledon is like a box of cho-co-lates.&quot;<BR></P>
<P>After thanking Mrs. Dodd, I sprang to my feet, hoisted my backpack, and was
off to the kingdom of tennis one more time.  The 4th was a gorgeous day, and I
walked and whistled. Blue skies and the sun were smiling back at me. Wimbledon
had been marvelously different this year due to the incessant rains of the first
week  (Rain delays caused more tennis to be played on courts each day to catch
up).  I walked briskly for twenty minutes to reach the `Wimbledon Special,' a
double-decker bus near Southfield Station, where London fans leave the train. 
The fare was 40 pence (70 cents) and there were only a few passengers on board.
This was an encouraging sign.  No queue materialized along Church Road as the
bus headed for the `Big W,' and my insides churned with excitement, realizing I
might luck out and get an excellent ticket to view some spectacular tennis
action. Bringing along my rabbit foot and four-leaf clover was paying off.<BR></P>
<P>Reaching the ticket gate I asked the pretty lady, &quot;Got any tickets,
luv?'&quot;   &quot;Yes, sir, we have Court 1 tickets for &#163;18 ($30),&quot;
she replied with a friendly smile.  &quot;Who's playing, luv?&quot;   &quot;The
first match is Edberg against Champion followed by Becker and Forget,&quot; she
replied in an anxious manner. A line was forming.  I couldn't believe my ears. 
She was offering a ticket to watch the No.1 and 2 seeds play the French
connection, in a quarter-final match, for a measly $30.  These Quarter- final
matches are normally played on Wednesday and the price would have been $55.  
Furthermore, I would've had to queue all night to get it.  My luck was
wonderful, but uncanny.  I knew for sure Somebody up there was watching over me.
Without hesitation, I passed the price of the ticket to the patient lady and was
off to Left Luggage to park my backpack.<BR></P>
<P>Play was scheduled to start at noon, two hours earlier than usual.  There
was little time to dilly-dally about, so I headed for Gangway 4 in the southwest
corner.  I reached Row U, Seat 012, after a 10-minute journey.  I could have
made it in about seven minutes, but I detoured by the Long Bar for a pint of
bitters.  (Man does not live by tennis alone.)  I brought the pint along in a
tall cup, being careful not to spill a drop.  The seat was one tier up, a great
location with a grassy view.  A party of middle-aged English ladies were to my
right, and on my left were Kaye and Roger Bacon from Houston, Texas.  I never go
anywhere that I don't run into a few saddle whipped Texans.  The English ladies
played tennis regularly at their club;  Kaye was a player too and she was
excited.  This was her first Wimbledon.  They had been very lucky to get these
seats, but were unaware of this fact.<BR></P>
<P>Roger was a golfer, and he looked more link-whipped than saddle-whipped.  He
had knocked himself out playing golf in Scotland, where the couple had visited
before coming to London.  Roger was so excited, he napped frequently.   The roar
of the crowd, welcoming Stefan Edberg and Thierry Champion, woke Mr. Bacon and
he managed to stay awake until the warm-up was over.  Edberg served and volleyed
brilliantly to take the first two sets, but in the third set, the momentum
shifted to Champion.  Champion hung tough and was leading 5-4. He had won the
first two points of Edberg's serve, when `the machine' opened his throttle and
won three games in a row, dashing the Frenchman's hopes.  Scores were 6-3, 6-2,
and 7-5. Edberg played some solid tennis.  So, what's new.  It's Stefan's
consistency coupled with his intense desire that makes him the great champion he
is.  Mr. Cool seldom beats himself.  (He's hanging it up after 1996.  I'm
saddened.)<BR></P>
<P>Boris `Red' Becker and Guy `Peacock' Forget, another Frenchman, whom I'd
never seen play, entered the arena, took chairs separated by the tall chair,
selected weapons, and started their warm-up. Shortly, the umpire shouted play,
and the game began.  `Red' was lucky the `Peacock' didn't strut all over his
posterior.  Forget had many chances to get on top and stay there, but he kept
choking on the critical points.  Who better than I knew how he felt?  Guy played
brilliantly, except for about three points and that was enough for his downfall.
Four times in the tantalizing fourth set tie-break, Forget had a chance to take
the match to a fifth set, but could not convert .  . not once. I believe Becker
was pulled from the jaws of the whale many times by divine guidance.  I'd
cheered very hard for the Frenchman and felt that Forget let me down. He should
have won the match. The scores were 6-7, 7-6, 6-2, 7-6. Such a super match with
the wrong outcome.  I do not dislike Becker, who, for some reason, I want to
call `Red.'  It's my nature to pull for the underdog.<BR></P>
<P>These two quarter-final matches had been sensational and priced right; all
made possible by the many rain delays of the first week. What a great finale to
another fabulous trip. Every chocolate had a nut in it.  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>More Information:</B> I have over 40,000 words written describing my
four trips to Wimbledon, and some helpful suggestion about how to do it without
spending your life's savings.  Fabulous Wimbledon for the Hardy is an
interesting and witty account that includes much more than tennis.  For a 3.5&quot;
disk in ASCII format, send a $4 money order to Walker Jackson, 8432 Pine Glen
Road, Sebring, FL  33870.  The Wimbledon area is a charming and safe place with
many friendly pubs and shops. Bed and breakfast places are readily available at
reasonable prices.  London is only a thirty minute ride on the underground
(train), which is convenient and cheap. A backpacker will love the queue and a
day in the grounds.  It's one very exciting place to be during the tournament. 
If you play the game, treat yourself to one Wimbledon. Yes! I figured my 1991
expenses:  Airline ticket $670 purchased several months in advance, during an
airline price war; food $140, 2 bed and breakfast accommodations $75,
transportation $40, 1 Centre Court ticket and 3 Court 1 tickets $170,
entertainment and miscellaneous $85. Are four fabulous days at Wimbledon worth
$1180? Does the sun shine in Florida?<BR></P>
<P><I>Walker Jackson,  retired engineer and avid  tennis player, is planing
his next Wimbledon for his 100th birthday -- or maybe a bit sooner.</I>
</P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>European Visits</I></B> invites you to send in your own favorite
travel story.  Check <A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/faves.htm">here</A>.</P>
