<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Paris on the Cheap  /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe / Paris /
France / Budget Travel</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>Paris <I>on the Cheap</I></H2>
<P><BR><I>by Susan Milligan</I></P>
<P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Yes, It Can Still Be Done -- If You're Very
Very Careful</FONT></I></B>
<BR>
<B>Paris. Glorious, romantic, inspiring.</B>  But why should it cost you? 
Never known as one of Europe's big bargains, Paris is pricier than ever, so
expensive that the tourist thinks he is making a mathematical error when
calculating French francs to the dollars, deutchmarks or schillings he brought
for the trip. No, that's not a mistake: it really is $3.00 for a can of Coke
sold outside the Eiffel Tower.  Worse, it seems everything costs, wherever you
go. Museums charge as much as Ff40 (eight bucks) to get in, hardly a price meant
to accommodate the starving artist. Le Metro costs about $1.75  for one ride
(though less if you buy a pack of tickets or a day pass).  There are no free
bathroom facilities, it seems, anywhere.  But Paris can be done on a budget.  If
you are very, very careful, you can see Paris on about $75 a day. Here's how to
save:  
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Transportation:</FONT> It's hard to get around this
one. You have to get there, after all, and unless you own a private jet - and if
you do, why are you reading this? - you're going to have to pay some airline to
fly you there. Some tips: Take Icelandair, which often has inexpensive flights
to Luxembourg, which is not too far from Paris. If you can a cheap flight to
London, grab it&#151;then go overland to Paris. 
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Lodging:</FONT>  Don't even think about the George V,
or other luxurious accommodations. You're in Paris, a living, breathing museum&#151;what
are you doing spending all that time in your room, anyway?  There are many small
pensions tucked away in Paris that will be much easier on your wallet.  A good
bet is Hotel Studia (51 Blvd. Saint-Germain, 75005 Paris, Tel: 43-26-81-00).  A
single with the bath down the hall is perfectly adequate and inexpensive at
Ff229 (about $45), including breakfast.  It's also in one of the best
neighborhoods in Paris&#151;near St. Michel, the Notre Dame and the Pantheon.  
In another good neighborhood (near the Champs-Elysees) is the two-star Hotel des
Deux Avenues (38 Rue Poncelet, 75017 Paris, Tel: 42-27-44-35 or 47-66-76-71.
Fax: 47-63-95-48). Rates run at Ff220 for a single, and Ff250 for a double.  For
those of you (and you know who you are) who have always wanted to sleep next to
Jim Morrison, there's always the Hotel a la Renaissance, at #28 Blvd.
Menilmontant.  It's just a stone's throw away from the Pere Lachaise Cemetery,
where the rock legend is buried.  Singles with a shower are a paltry Ff150 - 
though the neighborhood is a bit dicey.  Another option is the Hotel Clauzel, at
33 rue des Martyrs. Conveniently located between the Opera and the Sacre Couer, 
Hotel Clauzel offers rooms starting at Ff200.  
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Food: </FONT> You've got to eat, and it's not as easy
as it used to be to dine frugally in Paris. Some hints:  get a pension that
serves breakfast, and eat there. Forget any romantic notion of skipping the free
baguette, jam and coffee to have cafe creme on the Left Bank - unless you're
willing to pay as much as $5-6 for the coffee alone.  Don't eat lunch in a
restaurant; instead, get a baguette, cheese, fruit and wine at a grocery&#151;or
a quiche at a bakery&#151;and eat in one of Paris's lovely public parks.  It's
much, much cheaper and more fun as well.  Plus, it's hard to get a bad meal at a
bakery in Paris.  For an afternoon snack, try one of the made-on-the-spot,
filled crepes sold at stands throughout the city.  For dinner, you're best off
staying away from the heavily-touristed areas, and heading to some of Paris's
interesting, but somewhat less trafficked, neighborhoods, such as Les Marais or
the area around Luxembourg Gardens.  <BR></P>
<P>To really save money, don't eat French food. Go ethnic; in Paris, this means
eating Greek, Mexican or Asian food. The restaurants are good quality, but less
expensive that the local cuisine.  Still want to feel like you're actually in
France? Go for the tourist menu - always cheaper than ordering a la carte,
though the menus now rarely include wine.  Some recommendations: Au Clos
Saint-Germain, at 90 Blvd. St.-Germain.  The menu, plus the house wine, is less
than Ff100 (about $20).  Bistrot Beaubourg, on rue de la Reynie, a block away
from the Pompidou Center, offers a decent steak for Ff52, and an absolutely
delicious charlotte chocolat for dessert, for just Ff25.  Troll the area around
Saint Michel, on rue St. Andres des Arts. There are a number of reasonably
priced bistros, and the neighborhood is eclectic.
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Shopping:</FONT>  Forget it; you can't afford it. 
But if you want to bring back something French, splurge on some perfume. At
Paris's cut-rate scent shops, it's cheaper than duty-free, and a fraction of the
cost in Budapest, where duties and sales tax make buying perfume a real luxury. 
Two favorites: Parfums de France, 104 Avenue Champs-Elysees (Tel: 42-25-12-97),
and Dany Parfums (13 throughout the city; try the one at 140 Ave. du Gal
Leclerc, near the Orleans m&eacute;tro stop). These places have the best
perfumes and skin care products, for at least 30% off the recommended price. 
For other items, wander the Rue de Rivoli on the Right Bank, or the small
streets off the tony Champs-Elysees.   
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Sightseeing:</FONT>  Buy a museum pass; the most
useful one is the three-day, 140-franc option. This gives you free admittance to
dozens of museums and monuments in Paris, including the Arc de Triomphe. It
sounds expensive, but you would be appalled at how quickly those museum tickets
add up. Another benefit: no waiting at the Louvre - you can walk right in, ahead
of all those people forced to wait by the I. M. Pei pyramid.  The museum pass
also takes away the temptation to see the Louvre all in one day&#151;it's too
much for one visit. Go a few times.  Finally, if you have an ATM card, use it in
Paris instead of traveler's checks.  You won't pay a commission, and you'll get
the best rate irrespective of what time of day or night you take out money.<BR></P>
<P>Something you'll want to be doing as seldom as possible.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<H2><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Paris by Commute</FONT></I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I>Is your &quot;comfort zone&quot; crying out for first-class lodging&#151;or
at the very least a private bath&#151;but your budget whimpering too?  One way
to live well without central Paris' steep hotel rates, and without enduring its
sometimes cheerless, industrial-grade suburbs, is to ask your travel agent to
move you further out into the Ile de France (the province surrounding Paris). 
The region's excellent transportation network puts you within an easy train ride
of the city's attractions, while you bed down in interesting but less costly
environs.   Some possibilities: 
</I><BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Marne-la-Val&eacute;e</FONT></B>, home to
EuroDisney, is just ten minutes from Paris' centrally located St-Michel M&eacute;tro
Station via the RER &quot;A&quot; line.  You needn't be interested in Mickey &amp;
Donald &aacute; la Fran&ccedil;ais to take advantage of visitor-hungry,
reasonably priced hotels clustered near the theme park; try the Ibis with
doubles from Ff340 ($71).  
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B>Fontainebleau</B></FONT> features the splendid
estate where Louis XIV hung out when Versailles got boring; about 40 minutes
from Paris' Gare du Lyon, with frequent service throughout the day.  The Quality
Hotel la Napoleon, near the royal digs, offers doubles from Ff490 ($102).  
<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B>Beauvais</B></FONT>, further afield, offers an
historic cathedral and a small-town feel, with the commute to Paris Gare du Nord
just short of 90 minutes.  The longer ride can get you a much shorter hotel
bill, with doubles from around Ff290 ($60).  <BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B>Chartres</B></FONT> makes a wonderful &quot;home
base&quot; because it's such a worthwhile visit in itself; it also has (of
course) a famous cathedral, and you can be at Paris' Gare du Nord in a little
over an hour.  Because Chartres draws so many visitors from Paris, it's also
rich in restaurants &amp; shops.  You'll find doubles in the Ff350 ($73) to
Ff450 ($105) range.  <BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B>Versailles</B></FONT>, which like Marne-la-Val&eacute;e
is on the RER &quot;A&quot; line from St-Michel (but in the other direction), is
perhaps better known for its deluxe hotels than for bargains; but there are a
few exceptions.  Again try the Ibis chain's offering with doubles from Ff370
($77); or the Bellevue Hotel from Ff360 ($75).  Versailles is a lovely little
town for just walking about, and the legendary Palace can easily earn more than
one day's visit.  
<BR></P>
<P><I><B>One caveat:</B> as most of these places lie along major highways
from Paris, beware of getting shuffled off to am inexpensive roadside motel on
the outskirts if you plan to be afoot.  Make sure your hotel is <B>in town</B>
and the train station within easy reach.   -- Editor</I></P>
<HR>
