<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>Report from St. Petersburg</H1>
<P><I>by Bob Koff</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Dancing at the Masquerade Ball</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>It's been an exciting 24 hours in St. Petersburg, with plenty to reflect on.
 Saturday evening was the Masquerade Ball at Anichkov Palace, held to benefit a
hospice in town. The palace was built in 1741 by Empress Elizabeth for her
lover, and serves as a great party spot for activities such as this.  My wife
Pat and I had gone for our costume fitting a week earlier, at the building which
houses Lenfilms -- once the center of Russian moviemaking, but now in financial
straits like most of the arts in Russia.<BR></P>
<P>We arrrived two hours early for the 9PM party, in order to get our costumes
on and have our hair done by makeup artists.  My Marquis de Sade outfit was
great, and I ended up with a dandy curly grey wig expertly pinned to my head 
The hairdressers were meticulous with those lucky enough to have arrived early,
spending up to thirty minutes per person to achieve just the right look for a
party of nobility.  However, once the line of clients backed up around 8:30 or
so, the emphasis shifted to speed and the five-minute makeover became the rule.<BR></P>
<P>The costumes looked smashing though, and after visiting any number of the
half dozen well-stocked open bars, appearances took on less importance.  It was
a grand way to celebrate, and I was even asked to pose with a few women for a
photo opportunity. I lost a trouser button in the melee and had to visit the
seamstress on call to repair my embarrassing front flap.  I declined to offer an
explanation as to the nature of my loss.<BR></P>
<P>The food and especially the desserts were wonderful, and it was a glimpse
into the lives of those fortunate enough to wander the halls of Czars 200 years
ago. In the half dozen rooms the ball encompassed there was entertainment
ranging from a string quartet with waltzing couples to a pianist and an opera
singer.  Classical music gave way to Russian/American rock around midnight, and
we danced the night away until fatigue overcame desire. After changing back to
our mortal clothes of hiking boots and ski jacket -- and a rabbit-fur hat
purchased recently to deal with the legendary cold -- we walked home along the
Nevsky at 3AM. It's the main drag in town, packed with people shopping for goods
and services during the day, but much quieter at this hour for the 15 minute
walk to our apartment.<BR></P>
<P>Lauren thankfully slept until 7:30 on Sunday, and we felt semi-rested at
least when we rolled out of bed at 8. Our overnight sitter, Maria, joined us for
breakfast, and was out the door for tennis by 9. We decided to try a new museum,
and I called a friend with two little boys who agreed to join us at the
zoological museum.  Peter is a diplomat with the consulate, and his 2- and
8-year-old sons needed some purpose while their mom Linda was visiting sights in
Moscow for the weekend.<BR></P>
<P>We rely on public transportation most of the time to get around, and bundled
up for a non-heated bus ride to the museum in five-degree weather.  We got on
the #7 trolley bus with no problem, and pulled two tickets out of our pocket for
the fare.  Since most Russians have passes, the ticket punch is often
well-hidden, and we didn't have a chance to find it and verify our intentions to
use a ticket; soon a badge-waving bus marshall, overhearing our English and
targeting us as foreigners who didn't know the rules, asked us for our tickets. 
Seeing they hadn't been punched, he demanded a 20,000 Ruble fine (about $4.00),
which is 20 times the fare. But before I could figure out how to say &quot;kiss
off&quot; in Russian, the collective anger of our bus-riding neighbors surfaced.
 Everyone recognized our honorable intentions, and we found we had a dozen new
friends browbeating the marshall with a string of invectives and expletives.  At
the next stop he departed the bus in a huff, having been denied the opportunity
to line his pockets by a crowd no longer willing to accept bureaucratic
bullying. I felt we had just played a microcosmic part in the performance of the
fall of communism.<BR></P>
<P>The museum was a pleasant surprise, with thousands of displays of preserved
animals from all over the world. The mammoths from the frozen lands to the north
were especially interesting, and the adults were as entertained as the kids, who
ran around shouting for our attention to see this 12-foot crocodile or that
40-pound lobster. Lunch was at Carrol's, a McDonald's clone from Finland that is
convienently located around the corner from our apartment. It's a wonderfully
clean and efficient restaurant, and we dined happily on burgers and fries before
retreating to our apartment. Everyone was ready for a well deserved nap.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
