<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>The Thames at London</H1>
<P><I>by Jerri Clark Kirby</I></P> 
<P>The Thames is the chief river of England.  It is 215 miles long. It begins
as four streams - the Thames or Isis, the Churn, the Coln, and the Leach. All
rise in the Cotswold Hills. They join and the Thames flows east and south across
central England, through London and empties into the North Sea. Before it
reaches London, the Thames flows through a farming region that was the first
part of England to be settled.<BR></P>
<P>The Thames is one of the busiest rivers in the world.  Barges carry goods
along much of its length. Canals join the Thames with other rivers, making it a
great network of waterways that covers much of England.<BR></P>
<P>The City of London is on both sides of the Thames. Ships from all over the
world sail up the Thames to dock at London.  Fifteen bridges cross the Thames at
London. Famous ones are London Bridge, Westminster Bridge, Waterloo Bridge, and
Tower Bridge.  Near each bridge is a place to enjoy yet another aspect of
London's multi-faceted cultural menu.  Some are well-known; others less
publicized. The following menu offers up just a few of the many choices the
curious tourist may select.  Starting with Chelsea Bridge to the west and moving
to the eastern Thames Barrier, you can spend days on end exploring these
attractions.<BR></P>
<P><B>Chelsea</B> <B>Bridge:</B>  First opened in 1858, the present
suspension bridge opened in 1937. At the southwest corner sits the Japanese
Peace Pagoda, presented in 1985 by the Nipponzan Sect of British Monks who are
planning to ring the world with similar temples. It's a pleasant place to sit
and contemplate the busy world around you.   Across the street, southeast of the
bridge, is the Battersea Power Station.  Opened in 1940, its 337 foot (103
meters) high chimneys create a well-known landmark.  Not being in service since
1981, it remains preserved as an imposing  building of architectural interest.
<BR></P>
<P><B>Vauxhall Bridge:</B>  Built in 1906, it was the first of London's
bridges to carry trams. Bronze figures at each corner represent Agriculture,
Architecture, Engineering, Education, Pottery, Fine Arts, Local Government and
the Sciences.  Worthy of a leisurely look.<BR></P>
<P><B>Lambeth Bridge:</B>  The pineapples over each end of the bridge are a
tribute to John Tradescant, personal gardener to Charles I.  He was the first
man to succeed in growing a pineapple in England.  Of course, north of the
bridge visit the Houses of Parliament.  Several buildings have stood here; the
present one was designed by Sir Charles Barry and dates from 1852. The Clock
Tower (Big Ben), is 320 feet (97.5 meters) high. &quot;Big Ben&quot; is actually
the hour bell, (13.5 tons), named after Sir Benjamin Hall, First Commissioner of
Works at the time it was hung.  Southeast of the Lambeth Bridge is Lambeth
Palace, which has always been the London residence of the Archbishops of
Canterbury.  While it has been reconstructed in places, its earliest parts date
back to 1245.<BR></P>
<P><B>Westminster Bridge:</B>  The second bridge built across the Thames, this
original stone bridge was finished in 1750, later replaced in 1862 by the bridge
designed by Thomas Page.  Southeast of this bridge is the Old County Hall, the
administrative center for Greater London until recent years.  The foundation
stone was laid in 1912 by King George V.  The Greater London Council was
abolished in 1986 and administrative responsibilities are spread throughout 610
square miles within 32 local London Borough Councils.<BR> </P>
<P><B>Hungerford Bridge:</B>  Charing Cross station was built in 1863 on the
site of Hungerford Market, (from which the bridge takes its name); the cross is
the last of the thirteen crosses erected by King Edward I, one at each point
where the body of his wife Eleanor rested on the way from Nottingham to
Westminster for burial in 1290.  At the southeast end of the bridge stands the
Royal Festival Hall (at the South Bank Centre).  It opened in 1951 during the
Festival of Britain. The concert hall seats 2,930 people and claims some of the
best acoustics in Europe.  This complex also houses other recital rooms,
National Film Theatre and the Museum of the Moving Image (opened in 1988), which
traces the history of movies and television.  Open 10am-5pm Phone (0171)
401-2636 for 24-hour recorded info.<BR></P>
<P><B>Waterloo Bridge</B> is magnificent to behold.  It has five spans, each
230 feet (70 meters). Designed by Giles Gilbert Scott, it officially opened in
1943. Constructed of reinforced concrete, faced with self-cleaning Portland
Stone, it was finally completed by women during World War II.  Just north is
Cleopatra's Needle, a granite obelisk first erected in Egypt around 1500 BC and
presented to the British people in 1819 by Mohammed Ali.  It represents the
Egyptian appreciation for the help given by British naval forces, under Admiral
Lord Nelson at the Battle of the Nile.   Just across the way is Somerset House
which houses the Courtauld Institute Galleries. Built in 1786, it was the
General Registry Office for all births, deaths and marriages.  South of this
bridge stands the South Bank Complex, housing three theaters in one, since it
opened in 1976 and the Oxo Building, said to have been erected in 1932 to defy
regulations on outdoor advertising by incorporating its logo into the building.<BR></P>
<P><B>Blackfriars Bridge</B>, built in 1869, features stone pulpits between
iron arches. These commemorate the 13th Century Dominican Monastery which gave
its name to Blackfriars. Just at the north end is the Unilever House, built in
1932 and housing the London offices of the Unilever Trading Organisation.
Straight north is St.Paul's Cathedral, which took Sir Christopher Wren 35 years
to build.  The 365 foot (100 meters) high dome is second in size only to St.
Peters in Rome. Open 8:30am-4:00pm, galleries 9:45am to 4:15pm Mon-Sat)  Phone
(0171) 248-2705.  The Sea Shell Restaurant, nearby, has excellent food - (0171)
606-9415. Try the daily special.<BR></P>
<P><B>Southwark Bridge</B>, finished in 1921, is the least used of London's
bridges.  Just southwest is Sam Wanamaker's replica of the Globe Theatre, built
on the site of the original Elizabethan theatre.  On the south bank is Southwark
Cathedral, the third largest church in London.  It dates back to the 12th
century; John Harvard, who founded Harvard University, was christened here in
1607.<BR></P>
<P><B>London Bridge</B> was first constructed in Roman times. The present
bridge was opened in 1973 and at 107 feet (33 meters) is London's widest road
bridge.  On the northern side is Fishmonger's Hall,  Livery Hall of the
Fishmongers Company.  Annigani's portrait of Queen Elizabeth II, painted in 1955
and reproduced on British and Commonwealth postage stamps and bank notes, is
displayed here.   Just east is The Monument, completed in 1677 to commemorate
the Great Fire of London of 1666.  The Tower of London is in this area.  Parts
were built back as far as 1078; it has been a fortress, the Royal residence, a
state prison, a mint, an observatory and a zoo.  It is the home of the Crown
Jewels, and the Ceremony of the Keys takes place here daily.  Open 9-6 daily
(10am Sunday), phone (0171) 709-0765 for info.  Clink Prison, at 1 Clink Street
on London Bridge, used to be in the notorious red light district.  These days,
it hosts private parties and corporate functions. Phone (0171) 403 6515.  
Across the river sits the HMS Belfast. Built in 1939, weighing 11,500 tons, it
last saw action in the Korean Campaign in 1952.  You can investigate gun
turrets, mess decks and various other areas of the ship daily 10am-4:30pm or
5:50pm, depending on the season.  Phone (0171) 407 6434.<BR></P>
<P><B>Tower Bridge</B> was constructed in 1894 by Sir John Wolfe Barry.  The
two towers house the machinery for the lifting of the bascules, each one
weighing 1000 tons; each can be raised within 90 seconds.  The Tower Bridge
Museum is reached through the third level of the north tower of the bridge. 
Animatronic characters from the bridge's past bring to life the story of this
unique bridge, told through a series of multi-media presentations inside the
structure.  Kids of all ages really enjoy this.  Opens 10am, closes 4:45pm to
6:30pm depending on the season.  Open 7 days. (0171) 378-1928 for details.
Bramah Tea &amp; Coffee Museum is at Butler's Wharf on Tower Bridge.  A unique
collection of pictures, silver and ceramics illustrate the two great Oriental
trades of tea and coffee which brought romance to the ports of London and a new
social life to Europe.  Open 10am-6pm; phone: (0171) 378-0222 (phone is in the
comfortable cafe which offers great tea, biscuits, crumpets and a basic menu).  
East of the north end of the bridge is St. Katharines, built by Thomas Telford
in 1826 and originally designed to handle valuable cargoes such as ivory, tea
and silver. Presently, it is a commercial, residential and recreational area.
Across the river is the Design Museum, a part of the Butlers Wharf development.
It is a research and resource center for design students, professional designers
and the public. Open: Tuesday-Sunday 11:30am-6:30pm. Closed Mondays. The &quot;Collection&quot;
section contains 20th Century exhibits; the &quot;Review&quot; section contains
plans and prototypes.  The Mayflower is moored just east of here. Captain
Christopher Jones and many of the crew were Rotherhithe men and the  pub here is
named after the ship.  Following along the south side of the river in this area,
one comes upon the Surrey Dock, known as &quot;dead man's dock&quot; because,
during the plague of 1665, this area was used as a mass burial ground.  The
human remains came to light during excavations of this area in 1860.  Just east
rests the Gypsy Moth, a 53 foot yacht.   At age 65, Sir Francis Chichester
sailed her around the world by himself -- a first -- in 1966/67.  The Cutty
Sark, magnificently restored and maintained and last of the great tea clippers,
rests here at Greenwich Pier.  It was completed in 1869 in Scotland.  Open
daily; phone (0181) 858 3445.  The National Maritime Museum is to the  east. 
This was formerly the Royal Hospital School but is now the largest maritime
museum in the world.  Among the exhibits is the coat which Admiral Lord Nelson
wore when he was killed at the Battle of Trafalgar in 1805.  Open 10am-6pm
Mon-Sat &amp; 12-6pm Sun. Phone (0181) 858 4422.   Also here is the Old Royal
Observatory where the Meridian line, which divides the Western and Eastern
hemispheres, runs across the courtyard and out into a park.  Nearby is the Royal
Naval College.  The ceiling of the Painted Hall is something not to be missed. 
It was painted by John Thornhill, who took 20 years to complete this
masterpiece.<BR></P>
<P>Back across the river, east of the Tower Bridge, is Prospect of Whitby,
built in 1520.  Charles Dickens often painted from the veranda; and it was
frequented by many other artists of his time.  The Canary Wharf , just a little
farther east, is easily seen because it is the UK's tallest building at 850 feet
(259 meters) high.  It is a part of a recent Docklands redevelopment project.
Nearby, at the waterfront, is Island Gardens.  It is a small park opened in 1895
to commemorate the spot which Sir Christopher Wren considered had the best view
of Greenwich Palace.  East is Trinity Buoy Wharf, originally built for Trinity
House as workshops for the maintenance of equipment associated with lighthouses,
buoys and beacons.  Look out from here to see the Thames Barrier, moveable gates
that can be raised within 30 minutes to hold back floodwaters.  Begun in 1974,
they first became operational in November 1982; they were first used to
safeguard London in February 1983 and have saved London from flooding over 20
times.  The Thames Barrier Visitor Centre is a 10-year old structure housing
exhibitions, media shows, shops, a riverside walkway, a children's play area,
and a cafeteria. Phone: (0181) 854 1373. A good way to visit is via boat.<BR></P>
<P>Some of London's most famous buildings, finest mansions  and fascinating
sites are along the banks of the Thames.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Visiting Along the Thames</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>All destinations in this article can be reached by riverboat.  Of course,
you can also travel by tube and plenty of information is available on
underground travel.  Contact the London Tourist Board for information at (0891}
505465.  The London City Information Centre is (0171) 332 1456.  For taxis,
phone Computercab (0171) 286 0286 or Dial A Cab at 0171-253-5000; for info on
coach tours,  (0171)730 0202.  River cruises are offered by various
organizations.  Daily sightseeing can be booked at City Cruises, offering 20-30
minutes trips from 10am. London Showboat cruises, including dinner, (a delicious
4-course meal) and cabaret at &#163;39.00.  Information for all Thames River
Cruises is given at (0171) 237 5134.   The Westminster Passenger Association
offers riverboat sailings as well.  They offer special evening cruises with
commentary and bar, to Tower of London. Phone (0171) 930-2062. Contact River
Trips Line at (0839) 123-432 for additional information on Thames river trips.
<BR> </P>
<P>- <I>Jerri Clark Kirby</I></P>
<HR>
<H3>Thames Boat Services</H3>
<P><I>The following notes on Thames boat service are excerpted by permission
from Web Guides, an Internet resource on British travel and recreation.  They
have a lot more to offer, including some great pages on Devon and the south
country.  Check it out at  <A HREF="http://www.wwwebguides.com/">http://www.wwwebguides.com</A>.</I><BR></P>
<P><I><B>To HAMPTON COURT VIA KEW GARDENS:</B> Westminster Passenger Service
Association (Upriver), Westminster Pier, SW1.  Nearest underground station:
Westminster.  Daily 10.30; 11.15; 12.00.</I></P>
<P><I><B>To TOWER OF LONDON:</B> Catamaran Cruisers, Charing Cross Pier, WC2.
 Telephone: (0171) 839 3572.  Nearest underground station: Embankment.  Daily
10.30-16.30 every 30 mins.  Westminster Tower Boat Trips Ltd, Westminster Pier,
SW1.  Telephone: (0171) 237 5134.  Nearest underground station: Westminster. 
Daily 10.20-17.00 every 20 mins.</I></P>
<P><I><B>To WESTMINSTER:</B> Thames Motorboat Company, Tower Pier, EC3. 
Telephone: (0171) 488 0344.  Nearest underground station: Tower Hill.  Daily
11.00-17.40 every 20 mins.    </I></P>
