<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Online Traveler  /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">The Online Traveler</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>European Travel on the Internet</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<HR>
<P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#408080" SIZE="+1">News Briefs</FONT></I></B><BR></P>
<P><B>Expedia, Microsoft's big-time launch into the travel business, is now
online at <A HREF="http://expedia.msn.com/">http://expedia.msn.com</A>.   
Airfares, car rentals, and more than 25,000 hotels worldwide can now be booked
directly through the software giant's brand-new online travel agency.  The site
also has informational pages with general notes and a calendar of events for
hundreds of cities; the information is not exceptionally deep, but it is easy to
navigate and covers a wide range of destinations. 
</B><BR></P>
<P>To use the airfare finder, car rental module, or hotel locator, you need to
register.  This is a fairly quick process in which you provide name, email
address, a login ID and a password (but no credit card&#151;you only need to
provide payment information if &amp; when you actually want to make a booking).
If you are already a registered user of Microsoft Network (MSN) you can skip the
registration step and just use your MSN login and password. 
<BR></P>
<P>The airfare finder, which taps into the <B>Worldspan</B> CRS, is easy to
use and came up with a reasonable set of fares for our usual benchmark, a
Seattle-London roundtrip (from $511 on United).  It was however very slow; about
three minutes to come back with a list of a dozen or so fares, sorted from the
cheapest on up.  On another request, in which we specified a particular airline,
it never came back at all&#151;they may have some database access bugs to work
out yet.  We also tried a Seattle-Milano itinerary, coming up with a reasonable
fare of $849 on TWA.  On this one, however, we were curious about an apparent
bug: clicking on &quot;Flight Details&quot; brought up detailed information on
each segment, including equipment and meal service&#151;but it showed &quot;No
Meals&quot; for all segments, even the transatlantic flights.  We know the
airlines are cutting corners, but it's not that bad yet!  We'll pack a lunch
just in case...<BR> 
</P>
<P>Turning to hotels, we asked to see a general selection (all price ranges)
for hotels in <B>Milano</B>.  Expedia quickly offered up a surprisingly
generous list of choices&#151;many more than we have come to expect from web
sites of this type.  The quantity was boosted considerable by their inclusion of
Utell-represented properties in addition to the usual major chains (Holiday Inn,
Hilton, etc.).  <B>Utell</B>, one of the largest hotel booking agencies in the
world, represents thousands of smaller, non-chain hotels in Europe (see link
below) and is one of the few reliable ways to book budget-priced digs in
advance.  Another independent rep, <B>Steigenberger Reservation Service</B>
(SRS)&#151;specialists in reasonably priced, upscale properties&#151;also
appeared here and there, adding even more depth to the Expedia options.  
<BR></P>
<P>Each of the hotels can be clicked on for a full page of information,
including general room rates and amenities; a few have small pictures, which you
can click on to see larger images if you have the patience for it.  For some
listings you can also view clear, compact city locator maps to get an idea of
where the hotel is in relation to train stations, attractions, etc.  We tend to
put a <I>very</I> high premium on location when choosing a hotel, and were
impressed with this feature&#151;too many Internet hotel sites, and even printed
brochures, fail to give you a clue as to where exactly the property is located. 
Unfortunately, coverage of this feature was uneven: for some reason most Paris
hotels included maps, while most Milano hotels did not.  It may be that this is
a work in progress and they'll provide more complete mapping as the site
matures.  On our wish list, we also think it'd be nice to be able to pull up one
large map with all of the hotels for a city, shown by numbered dots; then you
could start by browsing hotels in your preferred location, rather than having to
go through the list one by one, waiting a few seconds each time for a map to
load.  Somewhat to our surprise, running a search for hotels in Paris with the &quot;$75
and under&quot; option specified actually turned up a short list&#151;mostly
<B>Ibis</B> chain motels and mostly in the suburbs, but given the skyrocketing
costs of a room in Paris these days, finding anything at all in this price range
is remarkable. 
<BR></P>
<P>A major omission in Expedia is that so far they carry nothing about <B>European
rail</B>.  There are no options that we could find for buying railpasses or
making train reservations; unless you plan to fly or drive everywhere, you won't
be able to put together a complete European itinerary here.  Perhaps this will
be added later. 
<BR></P>
<P>We'll keep an eye on Expedia.  Since it comes from Microsoft, rather than
one of the big travel companies, they may be willing to be a bit more innovative
than some of the mega-sites we've seen on the Web so far.  (And of course, since
it comes from Microsoft, one can expect it to be a lot better by the third
revision. :-)  They're off to a good start, and this may well end up being one
of the better one-stop online travel shops.</P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/qtwsm.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
<H2>Quinwell Travel Service</H2>
<P>We're pleased to welcome a new <B>EuroData</B> sponsor on the Web&#151;<B>Quinwell
Travel Service,</B> a full-service online travel agency now offering EuroData to
their visitors at <A HREF="http://www.quinwell.com/">www.quinwell.com</A>.  The
agency, which has physical offices in Boston and the Northeast&#151;but does
business with travelers nationwide&#151;offers an e-mail newsletter, a long list
of <B>worldwide travel links</B>, online ticketing, access to Sabre
Interactive, a travel glossary, meeting &amp; convention services, currency
information, travel tips &amp; advice, and much more.  Pay them a visit today!  
<BR></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+2"><B><I>Fodor's Customized Mini-Guides:</I></B></FONT>  A
particularly nifty feature found at <A HREF="http://www.quinwell.com/">Quinwell</A>
(among other places) is the <B>Fodor Online MiniGuide</B> program.  This <I>interactive
online travel planning aide</I> lets you specify a destination, a few key facts
about your tastes, budget, and interests, and then goes to work assembling your
own personal guide from Fodor's vast store of travel info.  The process is
quick, and when it's done your guide appears as a single customized Web page
suitable for saving, printing, or copying.  The <I>Calendar of Events</I> in
our London version was particularly impressive, as was the <I>Neighborhood
Guide</I> for our specified area (Bloomsbury district).  <B>This gizmo is the
Web at its best</B>&#151;free, fast, and useful.  Check it out!</P>
<HR>
<H2>Two New CompuServe Offerings</H2>
<P><BR><B>TransWorld Airlines</B> has a new spot on <B>CompuServe</B> called
<I>Trans World Access</I>, offering access to worldwide TWA fares and flight
schedules along with extensive information on their frequent flyer program.  If
you're a TWA FFB member, you can earn a bonus of 500 points for booking a flight
here; you can also check out your account status and browse through the FFB
award offerings.  Information on TWA Ambassador Clubs in airports around the
world can be found here too.  Their goal is to put &quot;everything you need to
know&quot; about the airline in one spot.  To take a look, log into CompuServe
and <B>GO TWA</B>.<BR></P>
<P>Another new perk for <B>CompuServe</B> subscribers is on its way, as
travel-information moguls <B>Worldview</B> have announced plans to put their
database at the disposal of the online service's users.  Worldview, providers of
travel data to the massive <I>Travelocity</I> site on the Web, will post
extensive information on attractions, acitivities, restaurants, sports, and much
more for destinations worldwide.  Unlike  <I>Travelocity</I>, however, online
booking will not be offered, at least for a while.  
</P>
<HR>
<H2>ETA (Electronic Travel Auctions)</H2>
<P>A new service hoping to cash in on the popularity of online travel auctions
is due on the Web <B>Jan. 4</B>, offering a myriad collection of airfares,
cruises, tours, etc., supplied by various providers; Hilton has been first to
sign on.  Visitors can browse a database of available products and post bids on
what interests them. Look for ETA at <A HREF="http://www.etauction.com/">www.etauction.com</A>.

</P>
<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#408080">European Travel Sites On the Internet</FONT></H2>
<P><B>The Internet continues to explode with more and more travel offerings.</B>
 You can literally spend days browsing and not begin to cover it all.  Some of
the interesting sites we've run across lately are listed below.  The addresses
were current as of December 25, 1996.   Web pages that deserve special
recognition are indicated with our European Visits &quot;#1&quot; ribbon.  We
welcome your own Internet picks and pans as well:  please write to us at
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com </A>to share your online
observations with fellow travelers.    
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Visiting Budapest:</B><A
HREF="http://www.fsz.bme.hu/hungary/budapest/bp.htm">www.fsz.bme.hu/hungary/budapest/bp.htm
</A></P>
<P>Absolutely top-notch online guide for this romantic city -- stacks and
stacks of information.  Our only gripe was that (at least on our machine, maybe
not on yours) the text was entirely unreadable against a dreadfully garish
background.  We almost left; then changed the browser setting to force a neutral
background, and found ourselves at a real winner of a Web site.  Don't miss it
if you're Buda and Pest bound.<BR></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.hungary.com/tourinform">www.hungary.com/tourinform</A></P>
<P>Another take on Hungary and its captial can be found at this excellent site,
run by the official tourist agency.  In addition to the usual Useful Information
postings, they have a selection of brochures and videos that can be ordered
online. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Rothenburg ob der Tauber:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.rothenburg.de/WelcomeE.html">www.rothenburg.de/WelcomeE.html</A></P>
<P>A well-organized site with a good deal of information about Rothenburg,
including a virtual walking tour and a very detailed hotel &amp; pension listing
with prices.  There are a number of links to individual hotel home pages as
well, some of which you can reserve online.  A map of Rothenburg is available
for viewing, though it is a bit too small to be as useful as one would like. 
They also have a special section on the Goethe Institute. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Brussels:</B>
<A HREF="http://concord.dcbru.be/brussels.htm">http://concord.dcbru.be/brussels.htm</A></P>
<P>This page offers a mixed bag of listings for the Belgian capital.  Some of
the pages are pretty useless&#151;lists of names and addresses only&#151;though
the Pubs page at least offers brief one-line reviews.  There's a link to the
Brussels Exhibition Center home page (http://www.ib.be/peb/e/index.html) if you
want to see what trade fairs are coming up. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Flanders:</B><A HREF="http://www.FlandersCoast.be/">www.FlandersCoast.be
</A></P>
<P>An entire site devoted to the towns along the Belgian coast, from &quot;singing
and swinging&quot; Blankenberge to Zeebrugge.  Accommodations info is uneven;
selecting Brugge as a sample brought up a very long list of hotels, but clicking
on particular properties produces fancy but not very informative pages.  The &quot;Prices:&quot;
entry was blank on every one we checked.  (Hey&#151;maybe they're all <B>free</B>!
Or maybe not.)  There is a lengthy list of museum exhibitions and special
sections on kids' activities in Flanders. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Andorra:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.xmission.com%3A80/~dderhak/andorra.htm">www.xmission.com:80/~dderhak/andorra.htm</A>
</P>
<P>Extensive, well-written information on this tiny little country, presented
in a large single-page format for easy browsing. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Camargue, Provence, Pyr&eacute;n&eacute;es:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.franceguide.com/sud/ukpyr.html">www.franceguide.com/sud/ukpyr.html
</A></P>
<P>A very nice write-up on this romantic region in France.  For a bigger
picture, start up the URL at www.franceguide.com and you can explore many other
pages for the France-bound traveler, including Practical Information, What's
New, Activities, and more.  You can view the site in either French or English,
if you're brushing up on your language skills. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Home Exchange:</B><A HREF="http://www.west.net/~prince/he/europe.htm">www.west.net/~prince/he/europe.htm
</A></P>
<P>This new entry on the Web hopes to be a clearinghouse for people interested
in doing international home exchanges.  Browsing the listings is free, and to
get the ball rolling they are accepting the first 200 listings in each category
free. 
<BR></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.wln.com/~exchange/">www.wln.com/~exchange/</A></P>
<P>A somewhat more mature service is Internet Home Exchange, which charges $39
per year for a membership.  Joining enables you to list your own home, contact
other listees, and gives you access to an extensive list of small B&amp;B and
homestay opportunities across Europe. 
</P>
<HR><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALT="First Place Ribbon" ALIGN="LEFT">
<P><B>The French Connection:</B><A HREF="http://www.webconnection.co.uk/">www.webconnection.co.uk</A>
</P>
<P><B>A terrific find!</B>  This UK-based site presents an enormous amount of
information for visiting the neighbors across the Channel.  Particularly
impressive are the extensive &amp; detailed accommodation listings&#151;farmhouses,
cottages, apartments, chateaux, and more.  The listings, which are easily
navigated by region, offer brief summaries &amp; locations; click on one for a
full description of the property (with photo), instructions on how to get there,
and points of interest in the area, along with seasonal prices.  Most that we
looked at had such extensive write-ups, you could build a whole vacation around
each one.  Booking arrangements vary by listing, with most offering a UK
telephone and/or fax number, and an e-mail contact for some.  Good as they are,
the accommodation pages are just part of what's here&#151;this is one of those
Web sites that seems to get better and better the more you dig into it.  We
found everything from mouthwatering descriptions of &quot;the three famous Prove&ccedil;ale
soups&quot; to a lengthy table of autoroute tolls around France...with separate
columns for car, car &amp; trailer, or motorbike!  The French Connection is a
definite must-stop if you're on your way to France&#151;and if you aren't, after
an hour or so here you might be. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Holland:</B><A HREF="http://www.nbt.nl/NBT-Welcome.html">www.nbt.nl/NBT-Welcome.html
</A></P>
<P>A general-interest Web offering with information for visitors to Amsterdam
and other Dutch destinations.  An extensive Coming Events list and a page of &quot;Amsterdam
Getaways&quot;&#151; profiling some of the interesting day trips that you can
add to an Amsterdam stay&#151;are among the features of this well-presented
site. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>The Virtual Tourist:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.vtourist.com/vt/europe.htm">www.vtourist.com/vt/europe.htm</A>

</P>
<P>This is the starting point for Virtual Tourist's online destination
information, which is a part of Excite's CityNet operation.  Click a point on
the map of Europe to find your way to city-by-city guides.  CityNet is not
really ramped up for Europe, and they mainly offer links to other Web sites;
some good, some less so.  Tech-heads who are curious to know how many Internet
servers there are in Europe&#151;and where&#151;can try VT's server map, at
www.vtourist.com/webmap/europe.htm. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Dover Facts:</B>
<A
HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/rough/europe/great.britain/england/regions/dover.html">www.hotwired.com/rough/europe/great.britain/england/regions/dover.html</A>
</P>
<P>A few good paragraphs about Dover and the surrounding area.  The text is a
bit longer than the URL, but not much.  However, this particular page is only a
distant twig on the &quot;Rough Guide&quot; tree &#151; online travel guides
which are part of HotWired's content and are actually quite good for larger
destinations; we've added them to our Standards.  Work your way out to Dover
from a start at www.hotwired.com/rough/europe, and you'll find lots more
worthwhile along the way. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Utell Hotel Reservations Service:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.hotelbook.com/">www.hotelbook.com</A>
</P>
<P>Begun in 1930 with only two hotels, today Utell International claims to be
the largest hotel reservations and marketing company in the world, representing
6,500 properties in 185 countries.  Their well-designed Web site includes plenty
of hotels for Europe; we checked London and came up with a long list, in almost
all price ranges.  Each hotel has its own page that can be viewed by clicking
the name.  Current rates are quoted, and you can book online.
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Great Britain:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.openworld.co.uk/mosaic/britain/">www.openworld.co.uk/mosaic/britain/</A>
</P>
<P>Open World's Britain page is found here.  They have a guide to
accommodations that you can sort by region, keyword, brand affiliation, or
price, and many additional pages with general information for visiting Bath,
Chester, Edinburgh, and London.  It's co-sponsored by Heritage Cities and the
upscale Relais &amp; Chateaux hotel/restaurant group. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Peaks and Plains of Cheshire:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.macclesfield.gov.uk/">www.macclesfield.gov.uk</A>
</P>
<P>Interested in Cheshire, England and the Borough of Macclesfield?  This Web
site is your starting point.  Plenty of info on what to see, what to do, and
where to stay, including camping &amp; caravaning. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Egypt Online:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.idsc.gov.eg/">www.idsc.gov.eg/</A>
</P>
<P>Visitors to Egypt can get tips on tourist services and cultural attractions
here. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Israel Online Too:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.touristguide.co.il/">www.touristguide.co.il
</A></P>
<P>Find more ideas for your Mideast visit at the online Israeili Tourist Guide
magazine. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Uffizi Gallery:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.waf.it/mall">www.waf.it/mall</A>
</P>
<P>The famous Florence, Italy art gallery has set up a special pre-registration
service for visitors who want to see their most  popular special exhibits.  The
current offering is the &quot;L'OFFICINA DELLA MANIERA&quot; show which ends
January 6, but future exhibits will no doubt be posted.  The idea is that if
you've signed up online, you get to use a special (shorter) queue to get in to
the show.  Sounds like a plan!  From the URL shown above&#151;which is a &quot;Weekend
a Firenze&quot; site devoted to shopping in this beautiful city&#151;navigate to
the &quot;Museum Reservations&quot; page.   (A side note: if you have trouble
reading the site's text against the overly busy background, use your browser to
force a white or gray background&#151;then use the mail-to feature to chide them
about it.  We did.) 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Tours to Go:</B>
<A HREF="http://members.aol.com/Tours2go">http://members.aol.com/Tours2go</A>
</P>
<P>This company's unique service (profiled in the last issue of EV) is designed
to help you sift through the endless variety of tour packages on the market, to
find the ones that best suit your interests and budget.  They work for you and
don't accept commissions from the operators they recommend, so you can trust
them to be on the level.  They recently emailed us to let us know they're on the
Web now, and can be reached electronically at Tours2go@aol.com. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Famous Chefs:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.lagerling.se/rest.html">www.lagerling.se/rest.html</A>
</P>
<P>A review of 21 of the top-rated restaurants in Europe&#151;most with
Michelin stars&#151; each offering a personal histories of the establishment
and/or chef, and sample  menus.  There's also an intriguing page called &quot;The
Best Meal in the World.&quot;  No fries with this one... 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Explore Poland:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.explore-poland.pl/">www.explore-poland.pl</A>
</P>
<P>Everything from cultural attractions to an overview of the wolf-hunting
controversy (they'll explain).  This is your first best stop on your way to
700-hundred-year-old Warsaw, or the rest of this ancient, complex and
fascinating land. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Ireland's Sheen Falls Lodge:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.iol.ie/sheenfalls">www.iol.ie/sheenfalls</A>
</P>
<P>Guided virtual tours of this scenic resort destination on Ireland's western
coast are available here 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Preview Vacations:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.vacations.com/">www.vacations.com</A>
</P>
<P>Preview Travel, operator of two Internet travel sites (and apparently
masters at grabbing the good domain names!) are offering attractive European
hotel bargains online.  Six nights at Paris' respected Hotel California from
$825, and six nights at the Rembrandt in London for $479, are among the current
hot deals; prices are PP/DO.  You can also get low airfare quotes from Preview
via their site at <A HREF="http://www.reservations.com/">www.reservations.com</A>.

</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Ski France:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.fr-holidaystore.co.uk/skiinfo/">www.fr-holidaystore.co.uk/skiinfo/</A>
</P>
<P>Bargains and handy information for ski trips to France are among the many
pages available at this site, put up by British tour operators specializing in
travel to France.  You can select a region to see detailed descriptions of
particular resorts, plus a list of online links to agents who can book you in. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Teen Travel:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.delta-air.com/teen">www.delta-air.com/teen</A>
</P>
<P>While some in the industry scorn the youth market, preferring the
freeer-spending ways of older travelers, Delta has figured out where older
travelers come from&#151; and put up a Web site entirely devoted to teenaged
travelers.  Their motto, accompanied by the image of a backpack: &quot;You've
got your whole life in the bag&#151;isn't it time you took it somewhere?&quot; 
The site offers a pen-pal area, a question &amp; answer page, an essay contest,
youth-oriented worldwide events listings, and links to popular student travel
sites, including an Internet guide to youth hostels and the online bible of
bargain travel, Shoestring E Zine.  Oh, and there's a mention in here somewhere
about flying Delta. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>TWA Bargains:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.twa.com/">www.twa.com</A>
</P>
<P>TWA has added Europe to the list of destinations for which they are posting
Internet-only fare bargains, with a recent sale offering discounts of up to 80%
off regular coach fares.  In the near future, the airline will also begin
signing up subscribers for a low fare email notification service. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Wells Fargo Currency Desk:</B> <A HREF="http://wellsfargo.com/">http://wellsfargo.com</A>
</P>
<P>Now you can order foreign currencies or American Express traveler's checks
online and have them sent to your home or office&#151;one less errand to run
before you pack! 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Cond&eacute; Nast Traveler:</B> <A HREF="http://www.cntraveler.com/">www.cntraveler.com</A>
</P>
<P>The well-known travel magazine has articles, pictures, and extensive hotel,
restaurant, and resort listings. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Best Western International:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.travelweb.com/thisco/bw/common/bw.html">www.travelweb.com/thisco/bw/common/bw.html</A></P>
<P>Best Western represents over 1,300 properties in Europe, which can now be
browsed &amp; booked on the Web.  The site is easy to navigate by country &amp;
city, and each hotel has its own page with extensive detail and current rates;
you can also click to view an optional picture, though regretably they didn't
includ the individual locator maps which have always been a big plus in BW's
printed directories.  (You can order the printed directories online, however.) 
For some reason, the Programs &amp; Promotions page doesn't mention Best
Western's excellent European voucher program or the special offers they
typically have going with providers such as Rail Europe and BritRail.  Be sure
to ask about these. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Travel Wiz:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.travelwiz.com/">www.travelwiz.com
</A></P>
<P>We read that Travel Wiz offered booking for more than 80 hotel chains
worldwide, so we took a look but found it unimpressive:  after waiting too long
for fancy graphics and spending too long filling out a search form&#151;which
had to be completely started over for each query&#151; it offered one hotel in
Paris, one  in London, and zero  in Venice.  Perhaps they don't really intend to
cover Europe, we  thought, so we tried New York just to be fair: three hotels. 
Not sure what they're trying to do here, but they sure aren't doing much. 
</P>
<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#8000FF">The Standards</FONT></H2>
<P>There are a few travel sites so comprehensive we'll repeat their listing
each issue -- these are the best of the bunch and will lead you to lots more. 
Click <A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/online~.htm">here</A> to check them out!</P>
<HR>
