<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Online Traveler -
Internet links - travel bookmarks - Internet access - Web Resources</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"> 
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>The Online Traveler</H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>News Brief:  The Lindner Congress Hotel in Frankfurt claims to be the first
to offer computer terminals with Internet access in every room.  The hotel's 315
chambers also offer voice mail, modems, and fax machines.<BR></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">European Travel on the Internet</FONT></B></I><BR></P>
<P>The Internet continues to explode with more and more travel offerings.  You
can literally spend days browsing and not begin to cover it all.  Some of the
interesting sites we've run across lately are listed below.  The addresses were
current as of October 20, 1996.  We're finding some unusually good web pages out
there that deserve special recognition, and these are indicated below in
<FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">yellow text</FONT>..  We welcome your own Internet picks
as well:  please write to us at eurodata@nas.com to share your online
observations with fellow travelers.   
</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Hotel &amp; Travel Index Online:</B><A
HREF="http://www.traveler.net/htio/">www.traveler.net/htio/</A></P>
<P>Part of Travel Weekly's extensive offerings, this site provides information
on hundreds of hotels worldwide, in various price ranges.  They are beginning to
add detailed reviews for many; these pages come up quickly and have the info you
need, including location and room prices expressed both in local currency and
US$.  We did run into a very high rate of &quot;File Not Found&quot; errors when
picking hotels from the lists that didn't have the &quot;OHG Review&quot;
symbol; these are just links to other hotel listing sites on the Web, or to the
hotel's own page, and many apparently are out of date.  The site is well worth a
visit, however, if you stick to the reviewed listings. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Perrillo Tours:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.perillotours.com/Web_pages/contents.html">www.perillotours.com/Web_pages/contents.html</A></P>
<P>This experienced tour operator is celebrating their 51st with some excellent
off-season specials to Italy.  Detailed information on this and other escorted
tours, including dates and prices into next spring, can be found here. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>4th Dimension Tours:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.4thdimension.com/europe.htm">www.4thdimension.com/europe.htm</A></P>
<P>Extensive information on rental cars, package tours, hotel vouchers, and
more.  Includes a listing of Posadas in Portugal that they can book for you. (
See a profile of 4th Dimensions shopping tours on page pp.) 
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Specialty Travel Index :</FONT></B> 
<A HREF="http://www.spectrav.com/">www.spectrav.com</A></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Their semi-annual print catalog has long been a great
resource for information about special interest tours and travel packages
worldwide.  Now Specialy Travel Index has gone online with their info; you can
browse through hundreds of listings, arranged by country &amp; by category, from
golf tours to beer festivals.  Each one points to a page or so of general
description, with 800 numbers and/or addresses  for contacting individual tour
operators for more information.  (They also offer links when the operator has a
Web page of their own.)  Comprehensive and well organized.</FONT><BR> 
</P>
<P><B>Golfing Scotland:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.spectravel.com/atkins/">www.spectravel.com/atkins/</A></P>
<P>Frances Atkins' Golf Packages are detailed here; one example, &quot;Country
Houses and Castles,&quot; includes ten nights and eight rounds of golf -- both
the lodgings and the links sound fascinating.  They quote both golfer and
non-golfer prices for this and other packages.  If you're a fisherperson, be
sure to check out their 6-day Scottish angling trip. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Rentals in Italy (and Elsewhere!):</B>
<A HREF="http://www.travelsource.com/europe/italy.html">www.travelsource.com/europe/italy.html</A></P>
<P>If the handful of samples they offer is any indication, this outfit's villa-
and apartment-rental catalogs are well worth the $3-$15 they charge.  Most
delightful-sounding is the &quot;Cabianca&quot; ($1324 per week), an apartment
on the top floor of a Venetian palazzo.  They have a half-dozen catalogs for a
variety of European locations; contact them by phone (800-726-6702), fax
(805-482-7976), or email (76413.713@compuserve.com) for more info. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Gay Greece:</B>
<A HREF="http://206.13.101.12/igta/odysseus/index.html">http://206.13.101.12/igta/odysseus/index.html</A></P>
<P>Odysseus, a well-established tour operator specializing many types of travel
including &quot;Greece, the Greek Islands, and Gay &amp; Lesbian Cruises&quot;
can be found here with details of their Mediterranean and European packages.. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>American International Homestays:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.spectravel.com/homes/">www.spectravel.com/homes/</A></P>
<P>This organization arranges stays with families in private homes worldwide. 
Not a great deal of information on the Web, but they do give a brief overview, a
list of countries where they provide services (most!), and contact information.
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Travel Europe Turismo Telmatico:</FONT></B>
<A HREF="http://www.traveleurope.it%2F/">www.traveleurope.it/</A></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">A fancy site which emphasizes Italy, but has links to
many other Web travel spots.  They have a very good hotel search feature which
lets you specify city and one or more keywords, such as &quot;train station,&quot;
&quot;historic,&quot;  &quot;luxury,&quot; etc.  Comes back with worthwhile
detail on the hotels it finds, too, including rates (in Lira). 
<BR></FONT></P>
<P><B>AESU Travel:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.aesu.com/">www.aesu.com</A></P>
<P>If you're a student traveler 18 to 35, or just want to find some of the
cheapest travel offers around, stop by here.  They boast &quot;seven days on a
beach&quot; in the Greek islands for $289; 6 days in Paris, including airfare
and hotel, as low as $916; and other bargains.  Easy-to-use low-fare browser
shows an attractive $502 r/t to London from the West Coast.  Some of these may
have expired by the time you read this, but check for what's new ( the
off-season should be even cheaper). 
<BR></P>
<P><B>STA Travel:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.sta-travel.com/">www.sta-travel.com</A></P>
<P>Another student-oriented travel organization, with discount airfares, chat
room, and information on obtaining an ISIC card, which they say &quot;can help
you get student discounts at many restaurants, museums, and galleries throughout
the world.&quot; 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Shoestring Travel:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.stratpub.com/shoe1.html">www.stratpub.com/shoe1.html</A></P>
<P>This is a very nicely done online 'zine focused on getting by cheaply.  Only
parts of it deal with Europe, but don't miss the extensive list of bargain
accommodations along the backroads of France.  The Webmaster gathers lots of the
best reader-written recommendations and advice from travel newsgroups and posts
it here, which makes for convenient browsing.
<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Boom Chicago of Amsterdam:</FONT></B><A
HREF="http://www.wp.com/Perseus/boom/boomframe.html">www.wp.com/Perseus/boom/boomframe.html</A></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">We have to thank Shoestring Travel's great links page
(see above) for steering us to this one.  A funny and irreverent look at
Amsterdam from a group of people who run a cafe &amp; adjacent theatrical
escapade called &quot;The Boom Chicago Comedy Show.&quot;  If you're wondering
about the title, go visit.  Go visit even if you aren't. 
<BR></FONT></P>
<P><B>Camping in Holland:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.katjeskelder.nl/kkgbhome.html">www.katjeskelder.nl/kkgbhome.html</A></P>
<P>A site devoted to De Katjeskelder Campsite &amp; Bungalowpark, in
Oosterhout, Netherlands.  Campsites, trailer slots, bungalows, and more.  Can be
viewed in several languages and the lingo in English is endearing -- travelers'
campgrounds are offered up as &quot;touristic pitches.&quot;  Doesn't mention,
unfortunately, just where Oosterhout is in relation to anything else &#151;such
as Amsterdam&#151; and we can't find it on the map.  Anybody know? 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Channel:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.travelchannel.com/">www.travelchannel.com</A></P>
<P>Besides information on the cable channel's upcoming programming and special
shows, this site offers quick-search access to some 26,000 pages of travel
information on the Web. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Traveler's Club:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.neosoft.com/~tm/club/index.htm">www.neosoft.com/~tm/club/index.htm</A></P>
<P>Describing itself as &quot;a Web site for travelers of distinction,&quot;
this non-commercial page offers an eclectic handful of essays and quotes related
to travel, plus a very extensive set of links to sites  worldwide. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Swiss Ski and Snowboard Bulletin:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.rs.ch/www/snow/">www.rs.ch/www/snow/</A></P>
<P>If you're planning to ski Switzerland this season, make this site your
friend.  Offers updates, posted daily at 9:00am, on  precise snow conditions and
number of runs open at hundreds &amp; hundreds of ski spots, sorted by region. 
</P>
<P><B>Lisbon Pages:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.puug.pt/Lisboa">www.puug.pt/Lisboa</A></P>
<P>A labor of love from an obvious Lisbon fan.  Good descriptive &amp;
historical information.  Unfortunately a bit slow with more banner graphics than
seem necessary.  Nice long museum list, with bus numbers given but no hours. 
Many of the museums in the list appear to have pointers to Web pages of their
own;  sadly all of these were dead links when we tried them.
<BR>
</P>
<P><B>Portugal Hotel Guide:</B>
<A HREF="http://shiva.di.uminho.pt/~esteves/turismo/portugal-ing.html">http://shiva.di.uminho.pt/~esteves/turismo/portugal-ing.html</A></P>
<P>The online version of a printed guide to Portuguese lodging (ordering
information available).  Good detail, rates, and online booking for some
properties, but the annoying frames setup makes it difficult to navigate, or get
back to where you were when you click on a link that turns out  to be a dud. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Write Your Way to Paris...</B>
<A HREF="http://www.ora.com/publishing/ttales/contest.html">www.ora.com/publishing/ttales/contest.html</A></P>
<P>So EV gives away T-shirts and mouse pads?  Big deal!  The Paris Pages and
FranceScape, Internet tourist guides to France, have joined with the online mag
Travelers' Tales to sponsor a contest for stories &quot;about romance and true
love in Paris.&quot;  The winner gets published and goes to Paris free.  Contest
details can be found at the site shown above. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Walkabout Travel Gear:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.walkabouttravelgear.com/">www.walkabouttravelgear.com</A></P>
<P>&quot;Essential Travel Gear and Information for the Independent Traveler.&quot;
 A very friendly, well-stocked storehouse of travel essentials and accessories. 
Proprietors Brad and Gia offer a personal guarantee on everything they sell, and
maintain a chat room and a quite good list of Web links.<BR> 
</P>
<P><B>Izon's Backpacker Journal:</B>
<A HREF="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/izon">http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/izon</A></P>
<P>The author, Lucy Izon, writes a freelance syndicated travel column known as &quot;Backpack
and Budget&quot; and has published a book called &quot;The Backpacker Journal.&quot;
  Besides info on the book, this site offers of tips on backpacking abroad and a
good list of budget travel publications available free from various tourist
agencies.  The focus is worldwide so there's only bits and pieces for Europe,
but it's worth a look. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Frankfurt:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.city.net/countries/germany/frankfurt_am_main">www.city.net/countries/germany/frankfurt_am_main</A></P>
<P>Excite's City Net has a &quot;resident&quot; Frankfurt site, but it's pretty
shallow.  The Hotels page (actually a jump to a Eurohotels' page) is one of
those that always baffles us -- what on earth is meant to be accomplished by
long lists of hotel names, accompanied  by nothing more informative than address
and phone number?  I suppose if you're wandering the streets and can't find a
phonebook (but can somehow log in to the Web) it would be mighty handy.  Or you
could print it out to take along, just in case Frankfurt doesn't have
phonebooks.  Whatever... 
<BR></P>
<P><A HREF="http://city-info.nacamar.de/city/frankfurt/e_frankfurt.html">http://city-info.nacamar.de/city/frankfurt/e_frankfurt.html
</A></P>
<P>A bit more meat here, with several pages on Frankfurt's history and cultural
attractions.
<BR>
</P>
<P><B>Frankfurt Subway System:</B>
<A HREF="http://metro.jussieu.fr%3A10001/bin/select/english/germany/frankfurt">http://metro.jussieu.fr:10001/bin/select/english/germany/frankfurt</A></P>
<P>They have a map, a list of stations, and an automated route-finder here.
<BR></P>
<P><B>Europe for the Visitor:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.webcrawler.com/select/trav.new.html">www.webcrawler.com/select/trav.new.html</A></P>
<P>A general gateway site and good starting point for travel in Europe. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>IcelandAir:</B><A
HREF="http://www.centrum.is/icelandair/schedule/auction">www.centrum.is/icelandair/schedule/auction</A></P>
<P>This smaller carrier is among those drumming up business on the Internet via
online seat auctions.  In a recent auction, minimum bid for an October roundtrip
between New York and a host of European destinations&#151;including London,
Glasgow, and Copenhagen&#151;was just $150.  Check out the Web page to see
what's up for bid next. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Online Air Reservations:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.reservations.com/">www.reservations.com</A></P>
<P>Add this entry to the Internet airline reservations biz -- you can set up a
traveler's profile here, make air reservations through their connection to the
Apollo computerized reservations system, and have your tickets sent by 2nd-day
air. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>United Connection Software:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.ual.com/">www.ual.com</A></P>
<P>You can now download the airline's United Connection software, which enables
you to make air, rental car, and hotel bookings from your PC via a direct
dial-up number.  Previously, one had to order the disks from United for $9.95. 
EV will be reviewing United Connection software in an upcoming issue.   
</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>U.S. Customs:</B>
<A HREF="http://www.customs.ustreas.gov/">www.customs.ustreas.gov</A></P>
<P>  Point your browser here for the latest info on duties, exemptions, and
other topics of interest to you, your luggage, and that stern-looking guy with
the badge.  It's the sort of stuff you want to know before your visit with him,
rather than after.    <BR></P>
<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">The Standards</FONT></H2>
<P>For those who are new to the Web (or new to <I>EV</I>), there are a few
travel sites so comprehensive we'll repeat their listing each issue -- these are
the best of the bunch and will lead you to lots more. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Lonely Planet:</B> 
<A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/">www.lonelyplanet.com
</A></P>
<P>The guidebook publisher has built what may be the most informative,
comprehensive travel information site on the Internet.  There are literally
hundreds of pages featuring detailed information on destinations all over the
world, and plenty on Europe.  Particularly good are the up-to-the-minute &quot;what's
happening&quot; listings for major cities -- perfect for downloading to your
EuroData itinerary before you take off.
<BR></P>
<P><B>Go Europe: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.goeurope.com/">www.goeurope.com</A></P>
<P>The European Travel Commission has a big budget and big ambitions for this
all-around European travel compendium.  You can pick from 26 member countries to
view everything from musical events to the latest weather forecasts.  A
Traveler's Forum lets you post messages and ask other travelers' advice on your
destination. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>The Webfoot Guides: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.webfoot.com%2Ftravel%2Fguides/">www.webfoot.com/travel/guides</A></P>
<P>A huge &amp; varied gathering of pointers to information sources on
worldwide destinations.  Some of what's pointed to is quite good, some less
useful.  You'll have fun exploring and will find lots of nuggets good for anyone
planning European travel.  
<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Weekly's Home Page: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net%2Ftwo/">www.traveler.net/two
</A></P>
<P>This page is hosted by Travel Weekly, the newspaper of the travel industry. 
More than 800 links, categorized for easy reference.  Recipient of a number of
well-deserved awards. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Org:
</B><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/">www.travel.org</A></P>
<P>This is one of the best travel sites around, covering destinations all over
the world covered with lots of information.  A terrific starting point for your
online travel explorations -- click the &quot;Europe&quot; graphic and dive in. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>WWW Travel Guide</B>
<A HREF="http://www.infohub.com/">www.infohub.com</A></P>
<P>A wide variety of travel-related links are to be found here, covering
destinations worldwide.  A good starting place for your Internet travel search.</P>
<P></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Have you run across a great European travel
site on the Internet?  Let us know about it!  Send e-mail to
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A>, attention EV Online.   
</FONT></B></I></P>
