<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Auvergne / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Seasons of Auvergne</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>By Douglas Walters</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Seasons of Auvergne by Douglas Walters--><BR></P>
<P><B>Auvergne is a remote, mountainous highland in central France,</B> famous
for its grass-roots culture and extinct volcanoes.  Everyone who goes there
loves it.  Here's why I do. 
</P>
<P><I>I love winter in Auvergne</I>&#151;especially out in the barn, amidst
the rhythmic sounds of the milking machines.  Snowflakes drift down out of the
evening darkness through the roof vents which run down the center of the long
barn.  Small mounds of snow pile up on the hay-covered floor in front of the
cows.  The tethered beasts are lined up in their stalls, loudly munching hay,
patiently waiting their turn while the farmer bucket-feeds the calves.  This is
a special blend of sound and smell which no combination of electronic
synthesizers can equal. 
</P>
<P>The dogs know the routine.  They've finished licking up the milk, and
they've already burrowed into the hay for the night.  The farmer takes a final
look at his herd, then a last drag of his rolled cigarette before he cuts the
power.  Everything suddenly falls dark and silent.  Outside it's dark.  The snow
has let up, at least for awhile.  The moon shines brightly, even as it slides
behind the rushing clouds of the next approaching snow squall.  Pine trees
swooshing in the wind and the snow dripping off the barn make the only noise as
the farmer walks back to the house. The next morning dawns sunny but, as milking
begins, so does the snow.  Down come the flakes; big wet ones through the small
roof vents.  They're more numerous than the night before, so the farmer looks
outside.  It's snowing heavily, and the house, 50 meters away, is barely
visible.  Everything&#151;the tractor, the cows' backs, the pines&#151;is
turning white. It's a winter wonderland, and it's only November.  At this rate
there could be a foot by the end of the day.  The sun returns at mid-morning
while the farmer walks back to the house for his sausage and wine break&#151;le
casse croute.  The squall moves off into the next valley.  It's almost an hour
before the next one blows in.</P>
<P>Towards Christmas the wind gets colder, and the snow squalls more frequent. 
The snow begins to pile up.  Christmas Eve.  Outside, it's a mixture of snow,
wind, and moon.  Inside the warm kitchen the smoke from the Gauloises mingle
with the roasting sanglier.  First up is the morel mushroom pie; the farmer
picked the tender mushrooms up on the plateau back in October.  He has been
harvesting the same fungal vein for most of his life.   La fete winds down
around early morning with some &quot;cinquante chevaux.&quot; In theory, &quot;50
horsepower&quot; is a digestif.  In actual fact, it's an acquired taste which
lives up to its name.  It's best tested in small quantities.  If you don't drink
it you can use it as fuel additive.  Fortunately everyone lives close to le
Perou, a tiny bourg of a dozen traditional rock buildings on the other side of
the valley.  During the casse croute on New Year's Morning, a baby avalanche
rumbles down from the plateau.  Later they'll increase in number as the days
grow warmer and longer. 
</P>
<P><I>I love springtime In Auvergne.</I>  It comes slowly.  The March snows
give way to April giboulees.  These are weird storms:  towering, isolated
cumulonimbus clouds which drop enormous puffs of round, soft sleet.  They bounce
off hard surfaces like tennis balls.  The fields, however, are wet and spongy
with fresh shoots of grass and clover which the farmer turns his anxious herd
back out to eat.  The cows' hooves sink deep into the black mud making cold
squishing sounds wherever they go. 
</P>
<P>Life is returning to the plateaus around le Perou.  The nut trees are
budding out slowly on the slopes, and the small, colorful songbirds are staking
claims.  One lonely-hearted male keeps attacking himself. He smashes headlong
into the kitchen's glass door which overlooks the valley.  Even the lazy,
overfed tomcat inside on the sofa seems to be shaking his head sympathetically. 
From the other side of the narrow valley even the cuckoo sounds happy.  The
small stream separating he and le Perou from the farm runs clear and cold.   
</P>
<P>In the distance, Auvergne's renowned puys rise up above the plateaus. These
steep, extinct volcanoes are gradually taking on their familiar green velvety
appearance.  But in the sunlight between giboulees it's still cool up on the
plateau.  Late in the day the farmer walks up and squashes across the soggy
pastures.  He scares up pairs of partridges.  Like the pheasants down in the
valleys, they manage to disappear behind single blades of grass.  Then night
falls, and the clouds and the giboulees vanish, too.  One or two lights from le
Perou are the only other signs of civilization.  But it's never really dark. 
Although the sun has left no trace of its own presence, its countless cousins
are everywhere.  Every minute or so a cosmic flash reminds us of our place in
the Universe.  And the days grow longer. 
</P>
<P><I>I love summertime in Auvergne.</I>  It's late July, and the farmer (he
calls himself a paysan)  has started cutting his wheat in the hot sun. As he
drives the tractor home through the cool darkness, a fat badger waddles across
the road.  The sunflowers are still only chest high. There are dozens of
shooting stars every hour.  They seem to chase the daylight away, but it must be
a struggle:  In this beautiful, far-off place, nobody wants to see the sun go
down...until it goes down and the curtain goes up on the Milky Way.  There are
no crass, neon reminders of the city around le Perou.  Here the Milky Way is a
cosmic carpet.  She unwinds silently overhead, pouring forth her eternal light
and making daylight out of darkness.  It bounces off the small stream down in
the valley.  What could make us feel more mortal... Sunflowers? 
</P>
<P>Now it's August.  The wheat and barley are in.  But there are vast fields of
sunflowers on the steep slopes.  They run right up to the narrow lane-and-a-half
roads which thread their way throughout the hills.  Just a few weeks ago the
sunflowers were bright, youthful maidens looking ambitiously skyward.  Now they
seemed to be thinking about the past, too .  They're bowed, brown heads are dry
and shriveled.  They seem to be praying as they await the reaper.  
</P>
<P><I>I love autumn in Auvergne</I>, because it usually comes with little
warning.  A clear, warm afternoon in late August suddenly clouds over.  A cold
gust front hits the plateaus around le Perou.  Low, churning clouds spill over
the hilltops at the far end of the valley. They rush forward like an invading
army, firing out a wall of rain and sleet.   
</P>
<P>The thunderstorm works itself into a 15-minute fury, and then summer is
gone.  The sun will come back out tomorrow in a cool west wind, but last week's
heat won't return.  Tonight the hearths in le Perou are working.  Soon it's All
Saints week; the air is clean and crisp, and on Monday winter suddenly returns. 
The livestock has long since grown shaggy.  There's still some green in the
fields, but the morning rain is cold, and some white is mixing in.  The farmer
keeps the cows in the field for as long as possible.  In the barn, he says, the
dust from the hay is bad for their respiration.  Two weeks later he decides it's
time to keep them in the barn, and they come home for the winter.  They don't
seem to mind much.  
</P>
<P>During an evening milking the farmer looks up in front of the lined-up cows
and sees snowflakes drifting down out of the evening darkness through the roof
vents.  The cows go on eating.  Small mounds of snow pile up on the hay-covered
floor.  &#164; 
</P>
<HR>
