<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: The Online Traveler</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>The Online Traveler<BR></H2>
<P><B> News Briefs:</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>The ICTA (Institute of Certified Travel Agents) will launch a new Web page
in September listing travel agents across the country in a database keyed to
destination specialties.  The agencies listed will be those that have completed
special educational programs on travel to particular areas, helping customers
better identify the agent most likely to be able to address the traveler's
interests.  The site's address is <A HREF="http://www.icta.com/">www.icta.com</A><BR><BR></LI>
<LI>The recent airfare frenzy -- sparked by Southwest's temporary $25 domestic
fares -- also brought the first real &quot;boom&quot; in Internet bookings,
according to news reports.  Apparently eager customers encountered so much
difficulty reaching swamped travel agents by phone, they turned <I>en masse</I>
to the Web.  Preview, an online agency in San Fransisco, reached a record
$300,000 a day in online ticketing, while Travelocity, one of the biggest online
travel sites, reported a 500% increase in bookings on their site at
<A HREF="http://www.travelocity.com/">www.travelocity.com</A>.  Other travel
companies with Internet booking capabilities -- including Southwest themselves
-- experienced a similar surge.  </LI></UL>
<HR>
<H2>European Travel Sites On the Internet<BR></H2>
<P><B><I>The Internet continues to explode with more and more travel
offerings.  You can literally spend days browsing and not begin to cover it all.
 Some of the interesting sites we've run across lately are listed below.  The
addresses were current as of September 1, 1996.  As noted in our last issue,
we're finding some unusually good web pages out there that deserve special
recognition, and these are indicated in the following pages with our European
Visits &quot;#1&quot; ribbon.  We welcome your own Internet picks and pans as
well:  please write to us at eurodata@nas.com to share your online observations
with fellow travelers.</I></B></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Walkabout Travel Gear</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.walkabouttravelgear.com/">www.walkabouttravelgear.com</A></P>
<P>A very interesting collection of travel accessories &amp; essentials.  They
also have a good deal of travel info and advice, a chat forum, and a large
collection of online links (including our own EuroData, which shows their good
taste!).  Stop here on the way to wherever you're going.<BR></P>
<P><B>Wimbledon</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.wimbledon.org/">www.wimbledon.org</A></P>
<P>If Walker Jackson's reminicense on his tennis-travel adventures piqued your
interest, check out the British tennis classic's own site on the Web.  Activity
here has calmed down somewhat since the tourney's end, but the page is still
there.<BR></P>
<P><B>Lofoten Islands</B></P>
<P></P>
<P><A HREF="http://home.sn.no/~perkaa/hist/vestvaag.html">http://home.sn.no/~perkaa/hist/vestvaag.html
www.adventuroustraveler.com/atb/europe/g3656.htm</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.lofoposten.no/home/lte/fiskmus.htm">www.lofotposten.no/home/lte/fiskmus.htm</A></P>
<P>The first of these is a &quot;Welcome to Lofoten&quot; page, which deals
mainly with Vestv&aring;g&oslash;y Island; some interesting local info and a
colorful map.  The second profiles a book, &quot;Climbing in the Magic Islands&quot;
from The Adventurous Traveler Bookstore.  There is a brief excerpt (which makes
the islands sound magic indeed!) and ordering information.  The third site is
for the Norwegian Fishing Museum, and has a nice photo of the museum --
impressive setting! -- and a list of current exhibitions.  There's also a link
to a Lofoten Tourist page, but it's still mostly under construction.<BR></P>
<P><B>Charlie Chaplin
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://home.sprynet.com/sprynet/gbond/chaplin.htm">http://home.sprynet.com/sprynet/gbond/chaplin.htm
</A></P>
<P>We couldn't find a site on Vivey, France, so we thought we'd throw this one
in.  Contains a long (and fascinating) essay on the Tramp, plus a remarkably
long  list of further links to Chaplin-ania on the Net.<BR></P>
<P><B>National Gallery in Prague</B>
</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.czech.cz/NG/">www.czech.cz/NG/
</A></P>
<P>Though still a-building, this collection of pages includes interesting
information on the history and current exhibits of Prague's premier art museum.<BR></P>
<P><B>Hungarian Hotels?
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.fastnet.com.au/hotels/zone9/hu/hu.htm">www.fastnet.com.au/hotels/zone9/hu/hu.htm</A>
</P>
<P>This site has an extensive listing of hotels in Hungary.  It also has lots
of flashy animated graphics, flickering text, whirling logos, and other such
foofraw.  <I>Information</I> about the hotels?  No, they apparently didn't have
time for that    just a listing of names.  All of the pages we clicked to were
essentially blank, though they do include a helpful form for emailing the site
with questions (such as, &quot;Why bother?&quot;)<BR></P>
<P><B>Hungarian Hotels!
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.columbus.hu/travelpg/hungexp.htm">www.columbus.hu/travelpg/hungexp.htm
</A></P>
<P>This one has done it better, at least for rates;  tables provide prices, for
a long list of hotels in Budapest and elsewhere.  Detailed descriptions are only
online for a few, however.  But if you've got a place in mind and want to know
what it costs, you may find it here.<BR></P>
<P><B>Venice: A Cultural Tour
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www1.iol.it/tci.sdp/html/e2006.htm">www1.iol.it/tci.sdp/html/e2006.htm
</A></P>
<P>A terrific site from Touring Club Italiano, with detailed descriptions (and
very tiny pictures, that you can expand if you like) of just about everything
you'd want to see in Venice.  Download the whole page to add to your EuroData
itinerary notes -- and match it to the site below to know when to schedule what.<BR></P>
<P><B>Venice Museum Hours
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.srtours.com/vmuse.html">www.srtours.com/vmuse.html
</A></P>
<P>Just what it says -- a list of hours of operation for Venetian museums. 
Information on closed days could be particularly helpful to check out if you're
planning a short visit.</P>
<P></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif">
<P><B>Baby Boomers' Venice
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.writing.org/venice.htm">www.writing.org/venice.htm
</A></P>
<P>They bill this as a &quot;guide to Venice for the over-forty&quot; but we
think the well-written advice found here would be useful to travelers of any
age.  Not selling anything, just a collection of handy and interesting tips on
eating, staying, and getting around in this lovely city.  Some nice photos too,
that don't take all day to arrive.<BR></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Little Venetian Glossary
</B></P>
<P><A
HREF="http://www.portve.interbusiness.it/wetvenice/glossario/glossario.html">www.portve.interbusiness.it/wetvenice/glossario/glossario.html
</A></P>
<P>Think you know Italian?  Check out this compendium of Venetian lingo.  Each
word is laid out next to the &quot;classic&quot; Italian version, along with an
English translation.  A definite take-along if you like knowing what you've
ordered for lunch.<BR></P>
<P><B>Cycling in Search of the Cathars
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eclipse.co.uk/pens/cat.html">www.eclipse.co.uk/pens/cat.html
</A></P>
<P>Brief profile of a book by two writers who spent four months bicycling
around the mountains and valleys of South-west France, following the history of
the Cathars.  You can email the British publisher for information on where to
buy the book.<BR></P>
<P><B>Portugal</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/peth">www.demon.co.uk/peth
</A></P>
<P>Nice site called &quot;Portugal Traveler's Handbook.&quot;  Tips and advice
on getting to, staying in, and getting around the country.  Accomodations
database is slick but seems to cover only youth hostels at present.  A nice
touch is the page of Travelers' Logs, with short descriptions by various
travelers of their experiences.<BR></P>
<P><B>European Walking Tours
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.walkingtours.com/">www.walkingtours.com
</A></P>
<P>This site offers detailed itineraries for the hikers' tours they conduct in
a variety of European countries.  Italiatour www.zenonet.com/italiatour/
Italiatour is the tour-operating division of Alitalia, the Italian airline. 
They have information available here on the variety of Italian vacation packages
available.  Nice site, but slow; they need to tame the graphics. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Driving in Europe
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.ideamerge.com/motoeuropa1/index.html">www.ideamerge.com/motoeuropa1/index.html
</A></P>
<P>This site offers a wealth of advice if you're planning to take the wheel
over there.  No maps, but plenty of text, and links to European car rental
sites.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Thomas Cook</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.thomascook.com/">www.thomascook.com
</A></P>
<P>The venerable travel company is offering a 5% discount to customers who book
through its Internet service.  Information on the large family of Thomas Cook
publications, including the European Timetable, is also offered here. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>European Union
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eurunion.org/">www.eurunion.org
</A></P>
<P>Put together by Europe Magazine, the house organ of the EU, this site
includes an archive of European Union history.  Fairly dry stuff but there's an
excellent listing of US tourist information offices and embassies, listed by
country (find this at www.eurunion.org/states/mslist.htm).<BR></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif">
<P><B>France in Your Glass
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http:///www.inyourglass.com">www.inyourglass.com
</A></P>
<P>These designers of specialty trips to the French wine regions (whose &quot;France
in Your Fax&quot; service is also noted in this issue's Check It Out section),
has put up an award-winning page with plenty of detail on their intriguing
culinary tours and vacation packages.<BR></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Small Italian Hotels
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.gteinc.com/">www.gteinc.com
</A></P>
<P>This site contains a variety of listings for small hotels, B&amp;Bs, villas,
pensiones, etc. for the budget traveler heading to Italy.  Current promotions
include rooms for 2 at a 3-star hotel in Rome, under $100 from November
3-December 26; rooms for 2 at a 3-star hotel in Rome, under $100 from November
3- December 26; and rooms for 2 at a 2-star hotel in Florence, under $100 from
November3-December 26, 1996.<BR></P>
<P><B>London Theatre Tickets
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.theatredirect.com%20/">www.theatredirect.com 
</A></P>
<P>This ticket broker for New York, San Fransisco, and London stages also
offers good deals on hotel/theatre packages.<BR></P>
<P><B>Continental Fare Specials
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.flycontinental.com/">www.flycontinental.com
</A></P>
<P>Following in the path of American Airlines and others, Continental is
offering special fare deals that are only publicised through an e mail
newsletter.  Travelers can sign up for the free weekly bulletins at the
airline's Web site. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Hotel &amp; Travel Index
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/htio/">www.traveler.net/htio/
</A></P>
<P>The 1500-page Hotel &amp; Travel Index is a quarterly compendium of hotel
amenities &amp; room rates at destinations worldwide, and is widely used by
travel agents.  Their new home page on the Web features a long list of hotels in
various destinations, most with pictures and detailed information including
rates.  Most tend to be upscale (4 star and up).<BR></P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif">
<P><B>Fodor's</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.fodors.com/">www.fodors.com
</A></P>
<P>Super online magazine!  The well-known guidebook publisher offers excerpts
from their books, including extensive hotel reviews, along with plenty of other
information in a very clear and attractive setting.<BR></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Isles of Scilly 
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.compulink.co.uk/~issco/">www.compulink.co.uk/~issco/
</A></P>
<P>Scilly Skybus, the airline that serves these tiny, distant British islands,
has posted schedules and fares here on the Web.  They may be moving soon, so if
the URL above is no good, try Lycos or another search engine.
<BR></P>
<P><B>Aer Lingus Ticket Auctions
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.aerlingus.ie/">www.aerlingus.ie
</A></P>
<P>One of the hot new trends for Internet airline sites is the ticket auction: 
typically, a number of seats on a particular route, sometimes for particular
dates, are put up for auction, and online visitors can submit bids via email;
highest bids win.  The Irish carrier Aer Lingus is the latest to give this a
try.<BR></P>
<P><B>Gay Travel
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.pridetravel.com/">www.pridetravel.com
</A></P>
<P>The Pride Travel Information Network offers information and a stack of
Internet links for those interested in gay- and lesbian-friendly destinations,
tour operators, and other travel info.  The &quot;Destinations&quot; section
doesn't presently cover Europe, but a number of the tours have European
destinations, including a French river barge cruise.<BR></P>
<P><B><I>Booking Air Reservations Online -- EV Tries Three Top Sites</I></B><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Internet Travel Network:</B>  <A HREF="http://www.itn.net/">www.itn.net</A>
 <BR>An elaborate travel-booking site, which you must register to use (no
cost).  Frankly, if this is the future of travel booking, I'd hang on to my list
of 800 numbers.  It takes an awfully long time to get anything done, there's no
apparent way to start over if you enter something wrong, and after a half-hour
of effort, it came up with a &quot;lowest fare&quot; for Seattle to London and
back -- in coach -- of $3,510.  We'll allow that we probably did something wrong
to get that, but the Byzantine interface makes it hard to figure out what.  We
moved on.<BR><BR></LI>
<LI><B>PC Travel:</B>  <A HREF="http://www.pctravel.com/">www.pctravel.com/</A><BR>Another
elaborate air &amp; hotel booking site, which also requires a no-fee
registration; somewhat easier to use than www.itn.net (though not much -- and
you can't start over here, either).  But at least we could actually afford to
go, as it came up with a Seattle/London fare on BA of $469.55.
<BR><BR></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><B>TravelWeb:</B>  <A HREF="http://www.travelweb.com/plane.html">www.travelweb.com/plane.html</A><BR>The
pioneer of online hotel booking has expanded into airline reservations; tickets
are issued by a Seattle travel agency, which sends them out by mail and also
provides a 24-hour customer service number.  Online car rentals through Hertz
are expected soon.  Here, our Seattle/London test turned up a $485.53 fare on
TWA; it was by far the most straightforward of the three sites we tried for
finding an airfare.<BR><BR></LI></UL>
<P><I>Editor's Note: We think all of these folks have a bit to learn about
dealing directly with travelers.  We had been puzzled that the first two sites
ignored our entered preference for TWA, only returning info for other airlines;
then when TravelWeb kicked back our first request with &quot;No available
flights,&quot; we realized that we'd been picking London Heathrow (LHR) as a
destination --  and TWA only flies to London Gatwick (LGW).  But how many folks
would know that if they're scoping out a first trip to Europe?  Ah, well.. it's
a fledgling industry.  They'll get better.</I></P>
<HR>
<H2>The Standards</H2>
<P><B><I>For those who are new to the Web (or new to EV), there are a few
travel sites so comprehensive we'll repeat their listing each issue -- these are
the best of the bunch and will lead you to lots more.</I></B><BR></P>
<P><B>Lonely Planet
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com./">www.lonelyplanet.com.
</A></P>
<P>The guidebook publisher has built what may be the most informative,
comprehensive travel information site on the Internet.  There are literally
hundreds of pages featuring detailed information on destinations all over the
world, and plenty on Europe.  Particularly good are the up-to-the-minute &quot;what's
happening&quot; listings for major cities -- perfect for downloading to your
EuroData itinerary before you take off.<BR></P>
<P><B>Go Europe
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.goeurope.com/">www.goeurope.com
</A></P>
<P>The European Travel Commission has a big budget and big ambitions for this
all-around European travel compendium.  You can pick from 26 member countries to
view everything from musical events to the latest weather forecasts.  A
Traveler's Forum lets you post messages and ask other travelers' advice on your
destination.<BR></P>
<P><B>The Webfoot Guides
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.webfoot.com/travel/guides">www.webfoot.com/travel/guides</A></P>
<P>A huge &amp; varied gathering of pointers to information sources on
worldwide destinations.  Some of what's pointed to is quite good, some less
useful.  You'll have fun exploring and will find lots of nuggets good for anyone
planning European travel.<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Weekly's Home Page
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/two">www.traveler.net/two</A></P>
<P>This page is hosted by Travel Weekly, the newspaper of the travel industry. 
More than 800 links, categorized for easy reference.  Recipient of a number of
well-deserved awards.<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Org
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/">www.travel.org
</A></P>
<P>This is one of the best travel sites around, covering destinations all over
the world covered with lots of information.  A terrific starting point for your
online travel explorations -- click the &quot;Europe&quot; graphic and dive in.<BR></P>
<P><B>WWW Travel Guide
</B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.infohub.com/">www.infohub.com
</A></P>
<P>A wide variety of travel-related links are to be found here, covering
destinations worldwide.  A good starting place for your Internet travel search.<BR></P>
<P><B><I>Previous Issues' Links</I></B></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/online1.htm">March/April 96</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/online2.htm">May/June 96</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/online3.htm">July/August 96</A></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Have <I>you</I> run across a great European travel site on the
Internet?  Let us know about it!  Send e-mail to
<A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A>, attention EV Online.  
</B></P>
