<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>The Online Traveler</H1>
<P><I><B>European Travel Online</B></I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>News Briefs:</I></H2>
<HR>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/forsyth.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></P>
<P><B>Forsyth Travel Library</B> is now on the Internet with information on
the full line of rail passes and publications they offer.  Located in Shawnee
Mission, Kansas, Forsyth Travel Library is the US distributor of the <I>Thomas
Cook European Timetable</I> and holds a long-time reputation as one of the
country's leading experts in European rail travel.  They are also authorized
agents for Rail Europe and can provide you with virtually any type of railpass
you require, along with point-to-point tickets, sleeper reservations,
International Youth Hostel memberships, and a good selection of maps and
guidebooks.  The site is still a-building but promises to be interesting.  Visit
them at <A HREF="http://www.forsyth.com./">www.forsyth.com.</A><BR></P>
<P><B>Rick Steves</B>, author of <I>Europe Through the Back Door</I>, can now
be found on <B>America Online</B>.  The well-known guru of off-the-beaten-track
travel hosts a number of online pages which focus both on independent travel and
Steves' own group tours.  Just click on <B>Travel</B> from the AOL Main Menu
and you'll run across him.<BR></P>
<P><B>Trav<I>elocity</I></B>'s enormous Internet site at
<A HREF="http://www.travelocity.com/">www.travelocity.com</A> is open for
business.  There's more travel stuff than you can shake a modem at -- reportedly
200,000 pages all told -- though it suffers somewhat from the &quot;mile wide
and inch deep&quot; syndrome; you can find information about almost everything,
but not very <I>much</I> information about anything.  And they need to fix an
annoying quirk that makes you re-select your destination -- starting at the
continent level and working your way down -- each time you change information
category.  The best parts are found in the descriptions of sights and
attractions and general travel advice, which come from travel info pioneers
Worldview.  Not much for hotels as yet, with lots of listings but only name,
address, and phone offered.  They're taking online reservations for some things
(including air travel) and hold 'live' chat sessions with travel personalities.<BR></P>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/elysees.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></P>
<P><B>Rail Pass Express</B> has added a chat room, the <B>Caf&eacute; Elsys&eacute;es</B>,
to their Web site at <A HREF="http://www.eurail.com/">www.eurail.com</A>.  The
online Caf&eacute; was was featured recently at the Internet World confab in San
Fransisco.  Come on in, pour an espresso, and talk travel.  Rail Pass Express is
also in the process of adding a <B>Britain by Britrail</B> site to go with
their excellent <B>Europe by Eurail</B> pages.<BR></P>
<P><B>Travelogix</B>, the worldwide airline, car rental, &amp; hotel
electronic booking service, is going to add an Internet gateway to widen their
market reach.  Currently, you have to use their proprietary software and
dedicated phone lines to use the service, which is $9.95 per month.  No URL
available as yet.</P>
<HR>
<H2><I>European Travel Sites On the Internet</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>The Internet continues to explode with more and more travel offerings. 
You can literally spend days browsing and not begin to cover it all.  Some of
the interesting sites we've run across lately are listed below.  The addresses
were current as of April 22, 1996. </B></P>
<HR>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/gspot2.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR><B>One
thing is new with this issue of EV's Online Traveler.  Because we're finding
some unusually good spots out there that deserve special recognition, we've
started awarding the soon-to-be-coveted <I>European Visits</I><B> &quot;Good
Spot&quot;</B> ribbon to sites that are really worth your online time.  We won't
hand them out easily, so you'll know we mean it when you see it.</B></P>
<HR>
<H2>The Reliable Standards</H2>
<P><B>For those who are new to the Web (or new to <I><B>EV</B></I>), there
are a few travel sites so comprehensive we'll repeat their listing each issue --
these are the best of the bunch and will lead you to lots more.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Lonely Planet</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/">www.lonelyplanet.com</A></P>
<P><B>The guidebook publisher has built what may be the most informative,
comprehensive travel information site on the Internet.  There are literally
hundreds of pages featuring detailed information on destinations all over the
world, and plenty on Europe.  Particularly good are the up-to-the-minute &quot;what's
happening&quot; listings for major cities -- perfect for downloading to your
EuroData itinerary before you take off.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Go Europe</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.goeurope.com/">www.goeurope.com</A></P>
<P><B>The European Travel Commission has a big budget and big ambitions for
this all-around European travel compendium.  You can pick from 26 member
countries to view everything from musical events to the latest weather
forecasts.  A Traveler's Forum lets you post messages and ask other travelers'
advice on your destination.</B><BR></P>
<H3>The Webfoot Guides</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.goeurope.com/">www.webfoot.com/travel/guides</A></P>
<P><B>A huge &amp; varied gathering of pointers to information sources on
worldwide destinations.  Some of what's pointed to is quite good, some less
useful.  You'll have fun exploring and will find lots of nuggets good for anyone
planning European travel. </B><BR></P>
<H3>Travel Weekly's Home Page</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/">www.traveler.net</A></P>
<P><B>This page is hosted by Travel Weekly, the newspaper of the travel
industry.  More than 800 links, categorized for easy reference.  Recipient of a
number of well-deserved awards.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Travel Org</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/">www.travel.org</A></P>
<P><B>This is one of the best travel sites around, covering destinations all
over the world covered with lots of information.  A terrific starting point for
your online travel explorations -- click the &quot;Europe&quot; graphic and dive
in.  With this issue's focus on Britain, we'll turn to travel.org for some
additional pointers.  The following are just a sample; there's a lot more at
their site so be sure to check it out for yourself.</B><BR></P>
<UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.interactive.line.com/british.html">British
Tourist Authority - British Monthly Planner</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.iinet.com.au/~cam/nt/nttop.html">National Trust
Properties in England</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/state51/knowhere">Knowhere: Alternative
Guide to the UK</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.digimark.net/rec-travel/hostels/euro.menu.html">The
European Hostel Guide</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/tube/index.html">WWW Tube
Journey Planner</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/hotelnet/windsor/home.htm">Windsor Castle</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.rbgkew.org.uk/">Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.city.ac.uk/london/entertainment/museums"> London
Transport Museum and others</A></LI>
<LI><A
HREF="http://catless.ncl.ac.uk/Vegetarian/Guide/Europe/England/index.html">Vegetarian
Restaurants throughout England</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/">Bodleian Library, Oxford</A></LI></UL>
<HR>
<P><B>Other Useful European Travel Links:</B><BR></P>
<H3>European Waterways</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.interport.net/cellular/ew.html">www.interport.net/cellular/ew.html
 </A></P>
<P><B>Lots of information here on cruising the waterways of Europe.  Indulge
your guests aboard a private boat complete with captain, crew, and chef.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Residences Orion</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.interport.net/cellular/orion.html"><B>www.interport.net/cellular/orion.html</B></A></P>
<P><B>European apartment living for as long as you like.  Great for families! 
They list a number of properties with locations close to business, cultural, and
recreational centers.  Apartment stays can offer a considerable savings over
hotels, if only because you can prepare most of your own meals and avoid
high-priced restaurants.</B><BR> </P>
<H3>World Cellular Service</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.interport.net/cellular"><B>www.interport.net/cellular</B></A>
</P>
<P><B>Need to keep in touch with business or family while traveling?  This
company offers cellular phone rentals for international travelers.   Reserve
before departure; your phone will be there when you arrive.  Available
throughout Europe, Asia, and Africa.</B> <BR></P>
<H3>Rail Europe</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.raileurope.com/"><B></B>www.raileurope.com/</A>.</P>
<P><B>  Home page of Rail Europe, the official US representative of European
railways.  Lots of information on European rail, including fares and services.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Museums in London</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/museums.html"><B>www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/misc/uk/london/museums.html</B></A>.</P>
<P><B>Great page to check out if you're heading to Jolly Old London. 
Addresses, phone numbers, hours of operation, etc. for a wide range of London
museums, including some off-the-wall places you may not know about.</B><BR></P>
<H3>UK Theatre Web</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.uktw.co.uk/">www.uktw.co.uk/</A></P>
<P><B> Offers up-to-date info on what's playing the West End &amp; other
theatres in London.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Hotels in the UK</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/hotel-uk">http://www.demon.co.uk/hotel-uk</A></P>
<P><B>An online information and reservations service for hotels in London and
the rest of the United Kingdom.  For some properties they sometimes offer
special rates available only on the Web.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Holland Tourist Information</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.nbt.nl/holland/home.htm">www.nbt.nl/holland/home.htm</A></P>
<P><B>You can search for a variety of Netherlands travel topics here.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Loews Hotels</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.loewshotels.com/">www.loewshotels.com</A></P>
<P><B>They show only one European listing, but it's a gorgeous Monte Carlo
property overlooking the Meditteranean (rooms from about $280).  If it suits you
they'll soon be able to take your reservation over the Net.</B><BR></P>
<H3>European Tourist Information Center</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.iol.ie/~discover/europe.htm">www.iol.ie/~discover/europe.htm</A></P>
<P><B>Another broad-based offering with selected cultural &amp; tourist
attractions profiled.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Relais &amp; Chateaux</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/hotelnet/relais/home.htm">www.u-net.com/hotelnet/relais/home.htm
</A> (UK)<BR></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.calvacom/relais/accueil.html">www.calvacom.fr/relais/accueil.html
</A> (Mostly France)</P>
<P><B>The very upscale hotel-and-restaurant group has its own Web page now
with information on properties around the United Kingdom and Europe.  They will
take reservation requests for hotels via e-mail.  (In a side note, they have
also begun taking advance reservations through travel agents for the top-rated,
often hard-to-book restaurants.  But show up -- there's a $60 no-show fee if you
don't.)</B><BR></P>
<H3>Diner's Grapevine</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.dinersgrapevine.com/">www.dinersgrapevine.com</A></P>
<P><B>If your budget is less lofty, this site includes quite a few restaurants
in the UK.  We checked it out because they've gotten a pile of awards, but after
a look we're not sure why.  They spend a lot of your bandwidth bragging about
themselves, and when you finally get a restaurant on-screen it tells you very
little.  (Sample description for The Actors' Retreat in London: &quot;Italian.&quot;)</B><BR></P>
<H3>Trencherman's Guide</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.dcs.ex.ac.uk/wcol/food_and_acc/trench.html">www.dcs.ex.ac.uk/wcol/food_and_acc/trench.html</A></P>
<P><B>A far more detailed listing of restaurants in England's West Country can
be found here.  They have details of each individual eatery (including pictures
of the proprietors on some).  This is part of the extensive collection of West
Country pages, many of which are very informative.  They do have a tendency to
use overlarge graphics so it's a bit slow going, but often worth the wait.</B></P>
<HR>
<H3><B>Web Guides</B></H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.wwwebguides.com/">www.wwwebguides.com</A></P>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/gspot2.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR><B><I>This
set of pages on England and the UK is a real winner.  (See the sidebar to this
issue's <A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/thames.htm">article on the Thames</A>,
which was reprinted by permission from a nifty page on the Web Guides site.) 
They've even got a complete Cadogan City Guide, &quot;London&quot; by Andrew
Gumbel, published online.  The entire text of the book is available and is
excellent reading.  You could spend a couple of hours looking at everything
they've put together here.</I></B></P>
<HR>
<H3>Walking in Britain</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm">www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm</A></P>
<P><B>&quot;There is an extensive network of local paths throughout the
country, with rights of way extending for some 140,000 miles...&quot;  Thus
begins this page on hoofing it through Britain, and the page extends quite a
ways itself as it imparts a stack of detailed knowledge on the subject. 
National Trails are covered along with less formal routes, and there are plenty
of  specifics on rules of the road and what to watch out for.  A &quot;must read&quot;
if you're planning an English hiking jaunt.  Also a  pleasantly non-commercial
site, though they do advise on the best places to buy maps &amp; gear.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Book-Browsing for the Adventure Traveler</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.gorp.com/waisdata/atbook/atsrch.htm">www.gorp.com/waisdata/atbook/atsrch.htm</A></P>
<P><B>You wouldn't believe how many books there are about traveling until you
spend some time here.  A relative of the Walking Britain page cited above, this
site lets you search by keywords for books on various flavors of adventurous
travel worldwide.  Punching in &quot;Europe&quot; brought up a bevy of unusual
titles, including Rock Climbing Guide to Europe, Slovenia Travel Survival Kit,
and Walking in the Black Forest.  Clicking on individual titles gets you a
synopsis, reviews, price, and online ordering information.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Internet Emporium</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.emporium.co.uk/hotguide/index.html">www.emporium.co.uk/hotguide/index.html</A></P>
<P><B>This site includes a hefty number of English hotels sorted by city or
county.  Information is limited except for a few &quot;featured&quot; hotels,
but there are a lot of names &amp; UK phone numbers if you're building a list of
possible stopping points.  Pages for the featured hotels are quite detailed,
down to rates and driving maps.<BR></B></P>
<H3>Affordable London</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.bynet.co.uk/afldn/index.htm">www.bynet.co.uk/afldn/index.htm</A></P>
<P><B>They offer apartment rentals by the week from $506, and apparently take
e-mail reservations.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Sisley Garden Tours</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.u-net.com/tka/sisley/">www.u-net.com/tka/sisley/</A></P>
<P><B>This user-friendly tour operator offers garden tours in the UK and
France.  Detailed itineraries, booking information, and even a gardening
crossword puzzle are online at this site.  Unfortunately, we've just been
e-mailed that the '96 tours are all filled.  But check it out anyway and think
'97.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Russian National Tourist Office</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.interknowledge.com/russia">www.interknowledge.com/russia</A></P>
<P><B>The official site of the Russian National Tourist Office, and very
impressively done.  For Moscow there's a Calendar of Events, Accommodations
Guide, museum hours, and quite a lot more.  St. Petersburg is also covered in
detail.  A must-stop site if you're going to Russia, though hotel information is
limited to names &amp; addresses.  Lots of good pictures which load quickly. 
Linguists only: If you want to test your Cyrillic reading skills, try
www.eurorussia.com.  (You'll need to download special fonts which they have on
hand.)  We have no clue what the site's about, but it certainly looks exotic.</B><BR></P>
<H3>TWA, USAir</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.twa.com/">www.twa.com</A>,
<A HREF="http://www.usair.com/">www.usair.com</A></P>
<P><B>Both of these airlines have recently put up Web pages with schedule and
route information.  TWA's site has detailed pages on a few of their European
GETAWAY Vacation packages as well.  Plus, you can enter to win 50,000 TWA FFB
miles just by signing in at their home page.</B></P>
<HR>
<H3><B>Stillwell's Bed &amp; Breakfast Guide</B></H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.stilwell.co.uk/welcome.html">www.stilwell.co.uk/welcome.html</A></P>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/gspot2.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR><B>An
extensive guide to &quot;good value overnight accommodation&quot; in Britain and
Ireland, with B&amp;B rooms averaging &#163;16 per night.  They don't take
reservations (or commissions) but provide you with all the contact information
you need to make your own arrangements.  Very detailed and very comprehensive;
if you've ever wondered where you'd stay in Woolacombe, Devon, they've got three
or four choices for you -- and a pub list to boot.  Exceptionally well-done site
with point-and-click maps, fast graphics, and neat search tools.  You can even 
find inns by such categories as &quot;Converted Barns&quot;, &quot;Older Houses
in Ireland&quot;, and &quot;Thatched Buildings&quot;.</B></P>
<HR>
<H3>Aer Lingus </H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.aerlingus.ie/">www.aerlingus.ie</A></P>
<P><B>The Irish airline is now Irish online, with schedules, a Vacation Guide,
and more.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Continental</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.flycontinental.com/">www.flycontinental.com</A></P>
<P><B>Yet another airline site, but in addition to the usual topics this one
is said to boast recipies, too; hopefully not for airline food.  Though if
you're dealing with that weekend guest who just won't leave...</B><BR></P>
<H3>Camelot International</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.itl.net/go/to/camelot/">www.itl.net/go/to/camelot</A></P>
<P><B>For some quick fun you can do a trace on family roots in Scotland here
-- just type in your surname and click.  The info comes back suspiciously fast,
however, and in pretty short order they want to sell you a mug with &quot;your&quot;
family crest on it.  If you want to look for yourself, they also offer apartment
and hotel reservations for your full-fledged genealogy trip.</B></P>
<H3>Genealogy in Ireland and the UK</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://midas.ac.uk/genuki">midas.ac.uk/genuki</A></P>
<P><B>For a more serious take on ancestor-hunting, start out here.  They
provide a full course on how to get started, where to look, and what to look
for.  Then, for Ireland and the United Kingdom, they'll take you into as much
detail as you can handle, on regions, archives, family names, and more.  As far
as we can tell, they won't try to sell you anything at all -- it's run by
genealogical society members who just want to help.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Guernsey (Channel Islands)</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://user.itl.net/~bebridel/">user.itl.net/~bebridel/</A></P>
<P><B>Take a tour of one of the larger Channel Islands (<A
HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/isles.htm">article this issue</A>) on this
privately maintained home page.  Lots of visitor info and a link to very
detailed lodging options for the Islands on Hotel Net
(www.u-net.com/hotelnet/channel.htm).</B><BR></P>
<H3>Bornholm, Denmark</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.bornholminfo.dk/web/uk/index.htm">www.bornholminfo.dk/web/uk/index.htm</A></P>
<P><B>A home page for the &quot;ideal holiday island&quot; off the coast of
Denmark.  It's a favorite with bike riders due to 200+ km of cycling routes
networking the scenic island.  The site offers details on places to stay, too.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Women Business Travelers</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.delta-air.com/womenexecs">www.delta-air.com/womenexecs</A></P>
<P><B>Delta Airlines and American Express co-sponsor this collection of
information and advice for female business travelers, whose needs &amp;
interests are too often neglected despite their estimated 40% share of business
travel.</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<H3>Paris</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.paris.org/">www.paris.org</A></P>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/gspot2.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR><B>Virtual
information on virtually everything in the World's Favorite City.  The site is
huge so be prepared to spend some time exploring.  &quot;Paris Kiosque&quot; is
an online magazine with top-quality articles and an immensely detailed,
up-to-date &quot;What's On in Paris&quot; calendar.  There are city maps, tons
of pictures, and you can even download a Metro map (if you have the patience -
it's big).</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<H3>Travel to Turkey</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.turknet.com/">www.turknet.com</A></P>
<P><B>Grand Circle Travel, a tour operator specializing in Turkey, is present
here, along with an online magazine (Turkish Style) and a guide to Turkish
hotels.  A good stop if you're heading to Istanbul.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Dr. Memory's Travel Pages</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.access.digex.net/drmemory/cyber_travel.html">www.access.digex.net/drmemory/cyber_travel.html</A></P>
<P><B>Profiled in a recent Travel Weekly article, this &quot;eclectic&quot;
home page can link you to more than 2,000 travel sites around the Net, from
run-of-the-mill to off-the-wall.  It's a non-commercial site run part-time by a
guy who wanted to learn Web programming and picked travel as his favorite
subject.  Worth a visit to see what he's come up with.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Hotels in Israel </H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.netmedia.co.il/info/hotelassoc/">www.netmedia.co.il/info/hotelassoc/</A></P>
<P><B>Prices, info, and photos covering a selection of Israeli lodging
options.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Belgium</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.freesun.be/Epicirie.html">www.freesun.be/Epicirie.html</A></P>
<P><B>An English-language online magazine about Belgium -- what's on, where to
stay, where to go.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Golf Travel Online</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.travelernet/two/twpages/http.gto.com">www.travelernet/two/twpages/http.gto.com</A></P>
<P><B>A worldwide database of golf vacations and resorts.</B><BR></P>
<H3>Overseas Connection</H3>
<P><A HREF="http://www.overseasvillas.com/">www.overseasvillas.com</A></P>
<P><B>If you're looking for the plushest in digs -- or just want to drool over
some -- this outfit can rent you a villa, castle, or penthouse in a variety of
locales. Our favorite was a Paris apartment with personal chauffeur and a
balcony view of the Eiffel tower.  Their &quot;Property of the Month&quot; is a
14th-century manor in the English countryside; they don't give a rate, but it
comes with eight bedrooms, a library, tennis courts, gymnasium, and a full-time
chef &amp; maid.  Don't bother getting out the Novotel vouchers...</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<P><B>Search The Web!</B></P>
<P><I>Don't forget to check with the Internet's premier search providers for
more sources of travel information: </I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo!</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://guide.infoseek.com/">InfoSeek</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.stpt.com/">Starting Point</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.mcp.com/">New Riders Yellow Pages</A></P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>Have you</I> run across a great European travel site on the
Internet?  Let us know about it!  Send us an <A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">e-mail</A>,
with &quot;Online Traveler&quot; in the subject heading.</B></P>
<HR>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/ev1.htm">Return to <I>European Visits</I>
Opening Page</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/eurodata.htm">Return to EuroData Home Page</A></P></BODY></HTML>
