<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Editor's Note /
Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#80FFFF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2><I><B>A Note from the Editor</B></I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Quite a few years back, I was astonished to read that the third most popular
activity for American visitors to Europe was &quot;shopping.&quot;  Of course,
in those days I was mostly a hitchhiking, hostel-sleeping,
Europe-on-no-money-a-day traveler, and what shopping I did involved tracking the
cheapest sausage vendors on the Messenplatz.  But still, I thought, even if one
could afford it this seemed an odd way to spend precious days in Europe; one
could shop anywhere.
<BR></P>
<P>Now that I have a few more trips behind me, and have by sheer longevity
acquired a bit more affluence (or at least more credit cards), I must admit to
being seduced now and then by the pure fun of Buying Things.  There is the
wooden bowl from the Ponte St Angelo in Rome; I'm sure I overpaid by a factor of
five&#151;I avoid noticing the same thing at Pier 1 for $2.99&#151;but it was
worth it to hear the hawker's entertainingly presented tale of woe.  There's the
cast-iron bell from Prague, which I watched the craftsman make with charcoal and
bellows; and the coffee tin from Salzburg, after a decade still vaguely holding
the scent, at least in my imagination, of the B&auml;ckerei am Markt where I
lingered over melange on a chilly morning by the River Salzach.  None of these
is important for what it is&#151;despite earnest effort, I have yet to find a 
need for a cast-iron bell&#151;but for the where, and when, and how-it-smelled
and how-it-sounded of the day I bought them.  Even more fun, in a way, are the
practical items for which there was a sudden need abroad, and which remain on
the job long after returning home:  the sturdy shoes I bought in Paris the day
my ancient, beloved hiking boots finally gave out; a razor I picked up at the
Stockholm railway station, and still use daily (well, okay, on days that I
actually leave the house).  Even though such items are no different from what I
might buy in town, I know the difference, and when I take them in hand or put
them on my feet, they smile to me in a way that K-Mart never will. 
<BR></P>
<P>We have a great overview of European shopping this issue, courtesy of Diane
Marshall; a tip on getting your VAT back; and a profile by Sophia Dembling of
some fascinating little shops in Amsterdam.  If you're going over for the
holidays, Jerri Clark Kirby has notes on Christmas in France, England, and
Germany (plus recipes, if you're staying home).  She also advises us on how to
keep your wallet in Rome, while Susan Milligan suggests ways to enjoy Paris
without much in it.   All this and Portugal, Prague, Frankfurt, and much more. 
Our gifts to you under the EV tree&#151;hope you like them.<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Scott Peterson, Editor</FONT></P>
<P><I>European Visits</I></P>
