<HTML><HEAD><TITLE></TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P><I>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</I></P>
<H1>Athens, Eye of Greece</H1>
<P><I>by Jerri Clark Kirby</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B>&quot;Athens, the eye of Greece, Mother of Arts</B></P>
<P>   <B> And eloquence.&quot;</B> -  <I>Paradise Regained,  John Milton</I></P>
<P></P>
<P>Look at a map of Europe; you'll realize that Greece has survived the
centuries in isolated splendor, separated from the rest of Europe by rugged
mountains to the north, its jagged coastline wrapped by three beautiful, deep
blue seas. Aside from the peninsula, which includes its venerable capital
Athens, there are some 14,000 sun-drenched islands, as inviting to travelers
today as they were to the earliest sailing explorers. 
</P>
<P>Entry procedures through Athens Passport Control and Customs are efficient
and fairly quick. From plane to customs' clearance took us less than 20 minutes.
 A quick stop to purchase drachmas at an airport bank (always open), and we were
off to explore ancient and new Athens.  Taxi cabs in Athens are cheap:  a 15
minute ride from the airport to our hotel was about 1300 drachmas, or
approximately $5.50; to the center of town would cost about 2000 drachmas, or
around $8.50.  Presently there are about 235 drachmas in one dollar.  Remember
that you can negotiate a price to your destination, but do so before you get
into the taxi.  Given the relatively low cost of Athens' hotels, we decided to
pamper ourselves at the five-star Ledra Marriott.   Among the outstanding
features of this particular hotel are non-smoking rooms, terry cloth
dressing-gowns in each room, complimentary newspapers each morning, a regular
shuttle bus to and from the center of town and -- most important to us -- a
flexible check-out time with no extra charge for staying a little longer.  This
courtesy is allowed guests except at the highest peak tourist times; all you
need do is make your wishes known at the desk.</P>
<P>A Greek businessman on our flight to Athens recommended the Kona Kai
restaurant at the Marriott as one of the best in town, and this Polynesian/
Japanese style restaurant has our vote. Food and service are splendid. There are
three restaurants and a roof-top lounge in the Ledra Marriott, all worthy of at
least one visit.  We elected to take our own leisurely walking tour the first
day. Since this was a return trip for us, the walk was designed to get the kinks
out and  re-acquaint us with one of our favorite cities.  Wearing comfortable
shoes and armed with a map and walking tour suggestions, we started out from
Syntagma Square (Constitution Square -- so named because it was here in 1843
that Athenians gathered and refused to leave until their first constitution was
completed, signed and sealed).</P>
<P>The Palace, with its impressive Greek columns and built by King Othonos in
1832, dominates the square.  It stands protectively over the tomb of the Unknown
Soldier, which is guarded by the elite skirted Evzone troops.  We watched the
colorful changing of the guard, executed with military precision by young men
who must be at least six feet tall to qualify for membership.  Throughout the
square, fat, healthy pigeons -- whose feeding is provided for by an official act
of Parliament --  are willing subjects for pictures, asking only a small fee of
peanuts (sold by nearby vendors).</P>
<P>About 100 yards from Syntagma Square are the National (formerly Royal)
Gardens, containing plant life from all over the Mediterranean.  Well-tended,
the Gardens produce a new pleasure at every turn.  Ancient and new statuary, a
small zoo, a duck pond, beautiful landscaping, lovely fountains and birds are
all there to delight you; or you may sit on one of the plentiful, clean benches
and watch the Greek world go by.  If you wish, you may also share your lunch
with one of Athens' uncountable cats, who like the pigeons are healthy and
well-fed. Quite regal, these Athens cats have always been a part of Greek
history and background scenery, and like the Greek people they are warm and
friendly.</P>
<P>Zappeion Park adjoins the Gardens and offers more serenity and calmness in
the midst of a bustling, crowded city.   We walked by the Royal Palace, now a
residence for visiting state dignitaries; the stadium, built in 1895 for the
modern version of the Olympic games; the Temple of Zeus, the largest of the
area's ancient temples, which was begun in the 6th century BC and took over 700
years to build; and Hadrian's Arch, built for a regal entry into the city by the
Roman Emperor.  We spent our day wandering happily through a few more monuments
to Athens' colorful history before finally arriving at the foot of the
Acropolis.  Here, for about $2.00, you can wander around the Parthenon, take
pictures, visit the small but complete archaeological museum, and view a
breathtaking Athens from the Sacred Rock (understandably referred to as the &quot;Crown
of Athens.&quot;) 	
</P>
<P>American Express, along with many other large &amp; small travel
organizations, offers half-day and full-day bus tours year round.  Buses are
modern, comfortable and air-conditioned.  Prices are designed for every budget
and guides speak fluent English, as well as many other languages. Tourist
information is available everywhere and native Greeks, who all seem to speak
English, are friendly and helpful.  From half-day bus tours of Athens to week
long cruises of the Greek Isles, an abundance of offerings guarantee your
enjoyment of Greece. You may elect to make all your arrangements before you
leave home, but personally I would recommend that you wait until you reach
Athens. On your own, you may explore on foot, by taxi, bus, train, rented car,
row boat or yacht. Whatever your needs and preferences, they are readily met.
</P>
<P>Shopping in Athens is still a bargain and you truly have not been to Athens
without at least a day spent in the Plaka and a meal in one of the famous Greek
tavernas, where food is delicious and cheap.  The Plaka is known world-wide for
its shops which offer virtually everything for sale, from linen kitchen towels
imprinted with Greek recipes to the finest furs and leather goods.  Film is the
exception; it is very expensive here and I suggest that you bring your own ample
supply, because you will find a picture at every step.  Bargaining is acceptable
in some shops and stalls, although it is done a little more quietly, and with a
little more reserve, than in the market places of the Middle East.</P>
<P>Adjoining the Plaka is the internationally known Flea Market, where it is
said that one can buy absolutely anything, new or used, at a reasonable or even
exceptionally low price.  Good antiques can be found here and the knowledgeable
can acquire them for marvelously low prices. Bargaining is more serious and less
subdued than in the Plaka.  Whatever you buy, it will be a bargain and your
drachmas will have purchased a souvenir of an unforgettable journey.  Coffee and
tea are regularly offered to customers in the shops and stalls of the Plaka and
the Flea Market. To refuse a shopkeeper's hospitality is to deny yourself a
pleasant social interlude with a warm, vital human being whose love for his
country and its long and colorful history is apparent and abundant, and whose
hospitality and friendship are genuine.</P>
<P>One shopkeeper, who immediately remembered us from previous visits, is
George Spiliopoulos on Filotheis Street in the Plaka. His store, A.Spiliopoulos
&amp; Sons, was founded by his father Athanasios and has been in the same
location for 65 years.   Handbags, shoes, sandals, boots and other leather
accessories are all hand-made by the family.  Athanasios Spiliopoulos, a
sprightly 96 years old, still hand-sews sandals and belts in the store. He
visits with customers and drinks lots of coffee for energy.  Prices here are the
best we have found in the Plaka for leather goods; anyone who shops the Plaka in
Athens is likely to remember this store.  
</P>
<P>Allow yourself plenty of time in Athens. Mingle with the friendly Greek
people, absorb the past, and enjoy the delicious Greek food and wine. Athens is
a magnetic place. You'll probably return.   &#164;
</P>
<HR>
<P>Want to learn more about Athens?  Send an email to agn@mail.hol.gr;  you can
get questions answered rather quickly.  For further information on  hotels,
museums, archaeological sites, and other tourist interests, visit
<A HREF="http://agn.hol.gr/hellas/attica/athens.htm">http://agn.hol.gr/hellas/attica/athens.htm</A>
on the Web.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B><I>Other travel resources for Greece:
</I></B></P>
<UL><LI>Heavenly International Tours: 1-800-322-8622</LI>
<LI>Cloud Tours: 1-800-223-7880</LI>
<LI>The Greek Island Connection: 1-800-241-2417</LI>
<LI>Greek Hotel &amp; Cruise Reservation Center: 1-800-735-5717</LI>
<LI>Hellastours, Inc.: 1-800-824-8535
</LI>
<LI>Contiki Holidays: 1-800-266-8454</LI>
<LI>Classical Vacations: 1-800-458-2863
</LI></UL>
<P><I>See also:</I></P>
<P><B>Greek National Tourist Organization</B></P>
<P><B>645 Fifth Avenue New York, NY 10022</B></P>
<P><B>212-421-5777</B></P>
<HR>
<P><I>An online resource for Athens:</I></P>
<P><A HREF="http://agn.hol.gr/hellas/attica/athens.htm">The City of Athens,
Greece</A></P>
<HR>
