<HTML><HEAD><TITLE></TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P><I>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</I></P>
<H1>When the Danube is Blue</H1>
<P><I>by Nathalie Zeidman</I></P>
<HR>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Even if its &quot;Beautiful Blue Danube&quot; isn't really blue, Budapest
will be true to your fondest imaginations.  There are always the spas and the
Gypsy music; and of course, there is the food.  In Budapest, every meal is a
feast -- even breakfast!  The Gallert Hotel's forty-foot buffet starts with
yogurt and kefir, continues with salads, cold meats, and local cheeses, and goes
on and on with eggs and sausage, fruit and sweets.</P>
<P>One food tourists can count on is red peppers, both sweet and hot like the
Hungarian temperament.  At breakfast this lipstick fruit is served pickled,
stewed, or scrambled with eggs; for lunch or dinner, stuffed with ground meat;
at any meal, baked and dressed with olive oil as salad.  Not to forget peppers
dried, finely ground into powder, and sprinkled as paprika on everything but
strudel.</P>
<P>Gulyas (goulash), a rich soup thick with meat and vegetables, is also
standard on the menu.  For something more delicate, try the Gundel Restaurant's
cold strawberry soup floating a dab of sour cream.  Catering to gourmets since
the days of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, Gundel, through cold wars and hot, has
scarcely deviated in its presentation and quality.  Besides Gundel's, there's
Hungaria, Karpatia, and Alabardos, among the best in a string of first-rate
restaurants.  Most big hotels also serve good food, along with Gypsy violins and
Magyar dancers.  In Budapest, no one just eats; everyone dines, whether it's on
the Buda or the Pest side of the Danube.</P>
<P>But don't worry about the figure -- what's put on at Gundel's can come off
(maybe) at the Thermal or Gellert Spas.  Spas have been a way of life ever since
the Romans encamped at Aquincum on the outskirts of Obuda (Old Buda) and
discovered the thermal waters.  Mosaic floors and remains of public baths (on
most tours) attest to the Romans' pleasure in a soak, a sweat, and a swim. 
Today's Budapest still provides those pleasures.  Gellert's Spa, for one, sports
more therapy baths and specialized massages than even the most decadent
Westerner has time for. 
</P>
<P>Budapest's newest is the Thermal Spa-Hotel on Margaret Island, an extensive
recreational parkland encircled by two branches of the Danube and reached by
launch, bus, or car.  The Thermal has the latest in medical equipment --
laboratory, x-ray, EKG -- in addition to its thermal pools, swimming pools,
saunas, mudpacks, water jet massages, curative gymnastics, electro-therapy, and
much more.  The Spa claims that its mineral water effectively treats a number of
chronic diseases, including osteoarthritis.  I have a friend who's been taking
the Thermal's cure since the hotel opened in 1979.  I think she's also been
taken at the Thermal's casino.</P>
<P>The Hilton, high on Castle Hill, also has a casino but no spa.  It's
magnificent views are curative, and the way it enfolds the remains of a
beautifully preserved 13th-century Dominican church into its contemporary
structure makes it the most unusual hotel in the Hilton chain.  On the Pest side
of the Danube, the Duna Inter-Continental, the Atrium-Hyatt, and the Forum line
up along the river, all within walking distance of interesting restaurants.</P>
<P>In Budapest, however, neither man nor woman lives by goulash alone; not with
a museum on almost every corner.  The exhibits at the National Museum include a
library from the country estate of a nobleman -- complete with original
paneling, fireplace, and hunting trophies -- and the rug-laden tent of a Turkish
general.  The Museum of Fine Arts displays a modest collection of old masters. 
As an added bonus, chamber music is often played in this museum's acoustically
perfect court. 
</P>
<P>The Castle, built by Empress Marie Therese high on a Buda hill overlooking
the Danube, houses several museums.  In one wing the National Gallery shows the
work of Hungarian artists spanning the centuries.  In another, archeological
digs reveal the ruins of a Gothic castle under the present one.  In some ways,
the view from the Castle Terrace is the Castle's premiere exhibit; on the
terrace, Prince Eugene of Savoy, astride his larger-than-life bronze horse,
surveys all of Pest.  It's a grand opera set, with  the stunning Neo-Gothic
Parliament Building at center stage.  If the Prince could turn his head north,
Margaret Island, the Buda Hills, and the Danube Bend would come into focus;
south, the impressive Chain Bridge.  Be warned: your arrival at the Castle
Terrace is not a good time to run out of film! 
</P>
<P>It's a comfortable walk from the Castle to Matthias Church, Budapest's
13th-century coronation basilica.  Around the corner from Matthias Square are
two of the city's most patronized pastry shops, noted for the nut torta, the
Korona and the Ruswurm.  The ultimate sweet experience is at Gerbaud's on
Vorosmarty Square; whether served in the red-damasked shop or on the terrace,
its strudel flakes at a sigh, and the dobestorta -- a multi-layered cake held
together with apricot preserve and glazed with burnt sugar -- is beyond compare.

</P>
<P>Gerbaud's is conveniently centered among Budapest's most fashionable shops,
selling everything from Herend china (a bargain) to peasant embroidery (pricey)
to couturier fashions at K-mart prices.  But before cashing that last traveler's
cheque for an Yves Saint Laurent look-alike, plan a Danube Bend trip by boat or
bus.  A typical tour includes the medieval fortress of Visegrad, the oldest
church in Hungary at Eztergom, Margit Kovacs Museum in Szentendre, as well as
lunch and wine-tasting.  Make it a priority! 
</P>
<P>When the end of the day finds you museumed- and toured-out, get pampered at
a spa, then plan an evening of theater.  Don't be put off by the 7:30pm curtain,
just when restaurants are opening their doors; during intermissions a buffet
laden with open-faced caviar and crabmeat sandwiches, pastries, ice cream, and
wine and coffee, is available.  Budapest is the city of List and Lehar, Bartok
and Kodaly.  The Erkel Theater and the State Opera House, both recently restored
to their former gilded luster, host local and visiting orchestras, ensembles,
and opera companies.  But the music everyone loves to love is Tzigane music; in
every restaurant, Gypsy violins move from table to table, singling, crying,
flirting, and turning a routine dinner into a second honeymoon (or thoughts of
one).  Later, throbbing melodies escape into the night, gracing the river with a
final touch of magic.  Under the spell of Gypsy fiddles, the Danube is blue.   &#164;</P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Some Travel Resources for Budapest</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Major Hotels:</P>
<UL><LI>Budapest Hilton: <B>1-800-HILTONS</B></LI>
<LI>Thermal Hotel Aquincum: <B>1-800-44UTELL
</B></LI>
<LI>Hotel Gellert: <B>1-800-44UTELL
</B></LI>
<LI>Duna Inter-Continental (Marriott): <B>1-800-228-9290
</B></LI>
<LI>Budapest Atrium-Hyatt: <B>1-800-233-1234
</B></LI>
<LI>Forum Hotel Budapest: <B>1-800-327-0200</B></LI></UL>
<P><BR></P>
<P>The above hotels generally run $150-250  per night for a double, somewhat
less in the off-season.  Many other accommodations in Budapest are also
available: contact <B>IBUSZ Hungarian Travel, 630 5th Avenue, Suite 2445, New
York, NY 10111</B>; or <B>Hungarian Hotels Sales Office, Inc., 6033 W. Century
Blvd, Suite 670, Los Angeles, CA 90405, 1-800-448-4321</B>.
<BR><BR> These fine tour companies also can help you with Hungarian plans:</P>
<UL><LI>Danube Cruises: <B>1-800-268-4155</B></LI>
<LI>Penta Tours: <B>1-800-243-4231
</B></LI>
<LI>Smolka Tours: <B>1-800-722-0057</B></LI></UL>
<P><BR></P>
<P>For further information, contact:<B><BR> Hungarian Tourist Board<BR>150
E. 58th Street<BR>New York, NY 10155<BR>1-212-355-0240</B></P>
<HR>
<P><I>Some online resources for Hungary:</I></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.fsz.bme.hu/hungary/budapest/budapest.html">Budapest
Page</A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.fsz.bme.hu/hungary/homepage.html">Hungary Home Page</A></P>
