<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>Discovering The Effects of a Turkish Bath</H1>
<P><I>by Jerri Clark Kirby</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><B><I>The Pleasure Known As &quot;Hamam&quot;</I></B></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Overlooked far too often by visitors to Turkey is one of their most
rewarding cultural exports. The Turkish bath, known as <I>hamam</I> in Turkish,
serves as much more than a place to take a bath: in Turkey, it is a place to
meet old and new friends.  Unfortunately,  the original purpose of the hamam is
becoming less important, resulting in fewer hamams. Yet Turkish people do still
go there to socialize.<BR></P>
<P>I had heard from worldly friends of the great after-effects of a Turkish
bath and wanted to go.  Having finally convinced my thoroughly western companion
that she would not come to some horrible end, we learned from a
tourist-guide-turned-friend that the Galatasaray Hamam, in an older part of
Istanbul was a good place to go.  So, off we went!<BR></P>
<P>I must confess that I was not without concern since I knew nothing of what
to expect.  My imagination had images of both of us suffocating in 500&#186;
steam, with old women removing at least three layers of skin with sand paper...
we would change back into our street clothes only to find that we had each
shrunk by half a foot.   My friend Jane was thinking much along the same lines. 
With good timing, we came to the mutual conclusion that we were being foolish
just as we arrived, and bravely marched into the women's door.  (Men's and
women's hamams are separate.)<BR></P>
<P>My apprehension diminished when I saw, not the 200-pound woman with a club
that I had imagined, but a very pleasant lady -- obviously experienced in
dealing with amateurs like ourselves.  She took our entrance fee, about 
US$2.50; for a little more, you can also have a massage.  This grandmotherly
lady said something in Turkish, to which we nodded uncomprehending and went into
the indicated room to change. Jane and I, both unused to changing in locker room
conditions, hesitated at first, looking for curtains to draw, shades to pull or
a door to hide behind. There was only one other lady, in the changing room
opposite. She was putting on her street clothes and her departure left the hamam
virtually empty.<BR></P>
<P>I quickly changed and draped the huge towel around me; Jane did likewise and
we looked at each other with &quot;what do we do now?&quot; looks.  The same
nice lady who had shown us in magically reappeared.  She managed to convey to us
that we needed to buy a bar of soap.  The cost was the equivalent of about 9 or
ten cents in U.S. money. (You can avoid the confusion by bringing your own
soap.)  Now the real terror surfaced: we stepped through the door to...the
hamam.<BR></P>
<P>But of course, there was nothing to be terrified about. The high-ceiling,
humid room was square.  Small sinks lined four walls.  A mysterious, large
marble slab was in the middle of the room.  Every so often, a drop of cold water
would plink down from the ceiling where the humidity had condensed.  The
grandmotherly woman, who was by now a friend, turned on one of the spigots and
hot water gushed out.   Soon it overflowed the small marble sink and spilled
onto the floor.  She gave us each a plastic bowl and, after we hung up our
towels, she started pouring hot water over us and chatting, still in Turkish. 
Then, she left us -- the only ones there -- to figure out what to do next.<BR></P>
<P>After a little indecision, we decided to lather up and rinse off.  Now what?
 We were stumped again until I remembered that my worldly friends had mentioned
something about &quot;lying on a marble slab.&quot;  We put cautious hands on
the marble first, just to make sure we wouldn't be fried.  The marble was
lukewarm and, as we became more confident, we moved towards the center of the
slab which became consistently warmer. So, we decided to relax on the slab --
and relaxing it was.<BR></P>
<P>Then a very tall, even older lady walked in, flashing us an incomplete but
reassuring smile. I tried to hide my relief as she claimed Jane as her first
victim.   &quot;It won't be all that bad,&quot; I reassured.  (Easy for me to
say!)  But any fears were again unnecessary.  All the nice lady did was
thoroughly scrub Jane with a soft washcloth and small shavings of soap, flip her
over like a fish, and do the reverse side.  Then she motioned for Jane to rinse
off and did the same for me before starting on Jane again, this time with
serious scrubbing in mind and a rougher scrubbing cloth, a <I>kese</I>, in
hand.  It was not sandpaper but was rough; to my grateful surprise, when my turn
arrived no skin scraped off and I actually felt all the things I was supposed to
feel:  rejuvenated, energetic and, above all, immensely clean.<BR></P>
<P>By now, we were completely at ease with our scrubbing friend, who sat down
near a sink and motioned for Jane to come and sit in front of her.  Then she
poured half the contents of a plastic vial into her hands.  It was shampoo and
she began to vigorously scrub Jane's hair and head. (When you reach this point,
remember to keep your mouth and eyes closed as she will probably scrub your
face, too.  Poor Jane, being first, wound up with a mouth full of lather.) 
After she finished, we rinsed off and went to change. Hair dryers were provided
and tips are expected after you change; the equivalent of a quarter to each lady
is eagerly appreciated.  We emerged spanking clean, with wide open pores ready
to soak in all the pollution of the big city.<BR></P>
<P>Hamans are usually less crowded at midday. However, at the end of a long day
of sightseeing, we went again and, overcoming our shyness, we shared the hamam
with other ladies, all of whom were Turkish. Once again we left feeling clean
and refreshed.<BR></P>
<P>Don't be afraid; going to a hamam is fun. Limited knowledge of the language
won't deter you from enjoying Galatasaray or any of the other reputable hamams
in Istanbul.  Reliable hotel people or tour guides can steer you in the right
direction for an experience that both business travelers and tourists will
enjoy. There is one warning, however. Beware of drinking alcoholic beverages
right after a trip to the hamam.  The alcohol goes through your system like a
bolt of lighting and, I am told, a new dimension in hangovers is born. Instead,
try a fresh fruit juice at the juice bar in your hamam or the juice stand just
outside.  Never will it have tasted so good!  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<H1>Roman Baths</H1>
<P><I>by James M. Dorsey</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P>The ancient Romans in Asia Minor certainly knew how to take a bath. 
Elaborate bath houses have been unearthed on Turkey's southern coast at the
ancient cities of Ephesus and Pergamon, showing elaborate heating and plumbing
systems.   But the luxury of the Roman bath is demonstrated nowhere better than
further inland at Pamukkale and the nearby ancient city of Heirapolis.<BR></P>
<P>About 20km from the Turkish city of Denizli, Pamukkale sits atop a set of
spectacular white cliffs covered in calcium.  Bubbling hot water from volcanic
springs has formed a series of shallow pools atop the cliffs.  The water
trickling down the cliffs over thousands of years has left a wedding-cake like
icing of white across the whole  mountainside.  Ailing Romans from all over the
empire once flocked to the site  and the purpose-built bath house to enjoy the
natural springs in  the hope of finding a miracle cure in the boiling mineral
waters.<BR></P>
<P>Now the site is a haven for modern tourists who can enjoy the luxury spring
baths from their hotel accommodation.  With the water a natural 48 degrees
Celsius, large communal  baths at Pamakkule give tourists a taste of old roman
luxury and  take the Turkish bath experience to a new level.  Signs in hotels,
signed by a Professor Dr. Nurten Ozer, detail  the health and mineral properties
of the waters.  According to the University of Istanbul's &quot;Medical Ecology
and  Hydro Climatology Search Application Centre&quot;, the waters can  relieve
a range of ills including rheumatoid disease, circulatory  system  disorders and
&quot;syndromes with peripheral vessel spasms&quot;.  So popular were the waters
among elderly and frail Romans that the city of Hierapolis was built here from
190 BC.<BR></P>
<P>The ruins, including the old bath house and 15,000 seat  amphitheater,
remain remarkably well preserved despite about 2000 years of earthquake
activity.  But the spectacular remains of the Necropolis, or cemetery,  attest
to the fact the waters did not do all the old Romans had  hoped.  St. Philip the
Apostle once visited, but the waters did him no  good. He was stoned to death
here while suspended upside-down on a  crucifix. A small church marks the place
of his martyrdom.<BR></P>
<P>At Ephesus, the magnificent ruins on the Aegean coast about  300km west, the
Romans proved their expertise with plumbing and water supplies.  The bath house,
an important meeting place in the centre of  town, was given to the city by the
most prominent woman citizen,  Scholastica the brothel owner.  The bath house
had four main bathing rooms. The heated water was pumped through each with the
water temperature regulated to  gradually cool as it passed from room to room. 
The hottest water also was pumped through vertical wall pipes to heat the
building.  Down the street, the used bath water provided a steady flow  through
the cisterns under the public toilets, which housed up to  40 customers a time
in an open room.  Here again the hotter water was pumped through pipes to
provide  warmth for the cold stone seats.  Today, visitors to the site can sit
on the old toilet seats, and marvel at the talents of the Roman plumbers.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
