<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>A NOTE FROM THE EDITOR</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H2>A NOTE FROM THE EDITOR</H2>
<HR>
<P>Britain remains far and away the most popular destination for Americans
going abroad.  Beyond the links of our common (more or less) language and shared
history, the attractions of &quot;this realm, this England&quot; are many and
varied.  London is one of the world's most vibrant and interesting cities, and
one of the most visitor-friendly.  From its earliest days as a Roman port, to
the world-leading days of Empire, to the courageous stand against tyranny in
World War II, London has also been a uniquely important player in the tale of
Western civilization, and its history is worn proudly in its natural and
man-made landmarks, its rich culture, and its diverse population.  Any trip to
Europe that begins with an arrival in London is well-begun indeed.<BR></P>
<P>One of the great things about the debut of the &quot;Chunnel&quot; train is
that it makes starting your trip this way much easier than it has been in the
past.  No longer must you set aside precious days merely to negotiate the
ferries, hovercrafts, customs points, coaches, airports, and inevitable long
queues that separated island from continent.  Now it's just another train ride;
in this issue of <B><I>EV</I></B>, which is largely focused on England, new
contributor <B>Bosley</B> <B>Wilder</B> gives us a passenger-eye view of this
swift EuroStar service on its run from Paris' Gare du Nord station to London's
Waterloo.  And in London, writer <B>Jerri Clark Kirby</B> returns to <B><I>EV</I></B>
to take us on a ride down the Thames, with glances at the numerous  riverside
points of interest.<BR></P>
<P>Of course there's a lot more to England than its capital, and in other
articles our writers offer views of Plymouth, Chester, Ambleside and the Lakes
District, and Chichester.  We're also honored to present a guest appearance from
renowned travel writers <B>George and LaVerne Ferguson</B>, who have kindly
shared with us an excerpt on royal Windsor from their popular <B><I>Britain by
Britrail</I></B> guide.  Another guest writer is a rather unusual one:  we've
come across a book called <I><B>A Satchel Guide for the Vacation Tourist in
Europe</B></I>, published in Boston in 1880, and in this issue we offer the
anonymous writer's long-ago observations on the historic cathedral at York. 
We'll be revisiting the <I>Satchel Guide</I> regularly in future issues, both
for excerpts of its timeless (and quite good) travel writing, and for some
fascinating glimpses at the European traveler's world of a century past.<BR></P>
<P>We do branch out from Merrie Old England to present a few other European
views:  <B>Bob</B> <B>Koff</B>, an expat living in St. Petersburg, gives us a
tour of his weekend; <B>Joyce Gregory Wyels</B> makes her first appearance in
EV to review some wonderful French eateries; and we get two looks at Turkish
baths, with a first-hand account from the prolific <B>Jerri Kirby</B> and a bit
of historical perspective courtesy of <B>James M. Dorsey</B>.  Finally, we have
several interesting short essays from Londoner
<B>David Whitehouse</B> under our <B>Europe Writes..</B> heading; and a
whopping five pages of buys and bargains in this issue's <B>Check It Out</B>
section.<BR></P>
<P>Hope you enjoy every bit of it.  As always, please don't hesitate to write
or <A HREF="mailto:72677.3722@compuserve.com">email</A> if you have
suggestions, gripes, or (best of all) tales of your own to tell.<BR></P>
<P><I>Scott Peterson</I><BR><I>EV Editor</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>About the cover...  </I></H2>
<P>The unusual cover art on our print edition this issue comes from <I>Image
Europa</I>, a computer-graphics studio specializing in images of European scenes
and landmarks.  In addition to being rather pretty, their illustrations -- which
are created from computer-enhanced photographs -- offer an opportunity for <B><I>EV</I></B>
to hold its own brand of &quot;Where Are You?&quot; contest.  Can you identify
the setting of this issue's cover?  Click
<A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/evcover2.htm">here</A> if you want to take a
shot at it (Graphic 101kb).</P>
