<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Online Traveler -
Internet links - travel bookmarks - Internet access - Web Resources</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#8000FF" VLINK="#808080" BACKGROUND="../send0619/clouds.jpg">
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>The Online Traveler</H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#400080" SIZE="+1">European Travel on the Internet: 
The Standards</FONT></B></I><BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#8000FF">For those who are new to the Web (or new to <I>EV</I>),
there are a few travel sites so comprehensive we'll repeat their listing each
issue -- these are the best of the bunch and will lead you to lots more. 
</FONT><BR></P>
<P><B>Lonely Planet:</B> 
<A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/">www.lonelyplanet.com
</A></P>
<P>The guidebook publisher has built what may be the most informative,
comprehensive travel information site on the Internet.  There are literally
hundreds of pages featuring detailed information on destinations all over the
world, and plenty on Europe.  Particularly good are the up-to-the-minute &quot;what's
happening&quot; listings for major cities -- perfect for downloading to your
EuroData itinerary before you take off.
<BR></P>
<P><B>Go Europe: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.goeurope.com/">www.goeurope.com</A></P>
<P>The European Travel Commission has a big budget and big ambitions for this
all-around European travel compendium.  You can pick from 26 member countries to
view everything from musical events to the latest weather forecasts.  A
Traveler's Forum lets you post messages and ask other travelers' advice on your
destination. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>The Webfoot Guides: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.webfoot.com/travel/guides">www.webfoot.com/travel/guides</A></P>
<P>A huge &amp; varied gathering of pointers to information sources on
worldwide destinations.  Some of what's pointed to is quite good, some less
useful.  You'll have fun exploring and will find lots of nuggets good for anyone
planning European travel.  
<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Weekly's Home Page: 
</B><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/two">www.traveler.net/two
</A></P>
<P>This page is hosted by Travel Weekly, the newspaper of the travel industry. 
More than 800 links, categorized for easy reference.  Recipient of a number of
well-deserved awards. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Travel Org:
</B><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/">www.travel.org</A></P>
<P>This is one of the best travel sites around, covering destinations all over
the world covered with lots of information.  A terrific starting point for your
online travel explorations -- click the &quot;Europe&quot; graphic and dive in. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>WWW Travel Guide</B>
<A HREF="http://www.infohub.com/">www.infohub.com</A></P>
<P>A wide variety of travel-related links are to be found here, covering
destinations worldwide.  A good starting place for your Internet travel search.<BR></P>
<P><B>The Rough Guides</B>
<A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/rough/europe">www.hotwired.com/rought/europe</A></P>
<P>The emphasis here, as in their print travel guides, is on fact-filled,
informative text; prose not poetry.  They pay particular attention to resources
for students &amp; budget travelers, but are well worth checking out for any
kind of itinerary.</P>
<HR>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Have you run across a
great European travel site on the Internet?  Let us know about it!  Send e-mail
to
</FONT><A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A><FONT
COLOR="#FF0080">, attention EV Online.  </FONT> 
</FONT></B></I></P>
