<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Note from the Editor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">A Note from the Editor</FONT></H1>
<HR>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Welcome to the third issue of European Visits.</FONT></B>
 In this issue we take a look at some of the ways of getting around Europe:
bicycle, foot, motorcoach, narrow guage train -- even horse-drawn wagon. 
Although personally I remain partial to the comfortable pleasures of EC rail, I
have to admit our writers have offered some intriguing and tempting
alternatives.<BR></P>
<P>There are a few conveyances we didn't cover, only because we couldn't find
articles to print:  travel by river and canal, for example, is something we'd
very much like to explore with our readers.  Anyone out there have a tale to
tell?  Taken a self-drive boat or a luxury hotel barge?  Or, have you loaded
your rental car aboard a car/sleeper train?  Barreled down the Alps on inline
skates?  Ridden a packmule through Estonia?  Pull together your notes or
recollections and send us a story.  You can take a look at the contributor
guidelines <A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/submit.htm">here</A>.<BR></P>
<P>Of course, if you're getting around you're also getting <I>somewhere</I>. 
So we've covered a few of our favorite <I>somewheres</I> in this issue too,
with fine articles on Vienna and Edinburgh.  We also have our usual eclectic
glances at Europe and European travel with more <I>Notes from London </I>from
David Whitehouse, and a new column  -- <I>Miss Elainey's Notes</I> -- offering
bits and pieces of news and gossip from Over There. And as usual, we have pages
jam-packed with items of interest for European travelers in our <I>Check It Out</I>
and <I>Online Traveler</I> sections. <BR></P>
<P>We've gone a bit more <FONT COLOR="#FF0080">colorful</FONT> in the online
edition this time, but we're still foregoing graphics and pictures for the most
part.  It isn't that we're anti-illustration; we just aren't convinced that very
many of the jpegs and gifs on the Net are worth the time it takes to receive
them.  Some of our contributors have accompanied their articles with gorgeous
glossy photos, but we tend to think that the place for gorgeous glossy photos is
in gorgeous glossy magazines, and there are plenty of those on the news stand. 
The online edition of <I><B>European Visits</B></I> was originally conceived
as a way to put informative text about European travel &amp; destinations in a
format that users of our <B>EuroData&reg;</B> itinerary-planning program could
download for use in their travel plans; though it has since evolved into
something a bit more elaborate, we still think that thoughtful travelers value
the written word, and that words are the best way to convey most information. 
What's your opinion?  So far, we've received four letters on the graphics vs.
no-graphics topic -- all four were &quot;thank you&quot; notes for keeping our
pages fast and simple.  (We did get one missive from a &quot;reader&quot; who
informed us that we desperately needed some Java animation to liven things up;
on further discussion, it proved that the correspondent was a consultant
specializing in developing Java animations.  Hmm.)<BR></P>
<P>Finally, we received a number of guesses on last issue's cover contest, but
nobody got it right except the editor's mother, and we couldn't give her the
prize.  The answer?  Our #2 cover illustration was created from a photograph of
the vividly colorful, beautifully proportioned rear staircase at <B>London's
Victoria &amp; Albert Museum</B>.  We'll do another contest soon -- and we'll
try not to make it so hard next time!<BR></P>
<P>I hope you enjoy the issue.  As always, your letters and comments are more
than welcome: just e-mail us at <A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A>
and let us know what you think.<BR></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Scott Peterson, Editor</FONT></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">European Visits</FONT></B></I></P>
<HR>
