<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Bicycle Touring</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="../../../../msoffice/clipart/clouds2.gif" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">July / August 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Bicycle Touring</FONT></H1>
<P><EM>by Nick Gregory</EM></P>
<HR>
<P><STRONG><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Tips for Traveling Awheel</FONT></EM></STRONG><BR></P>
<P>One of the best ways of exploring the locale when on a tour or holiday is by
bicycle.  It is slow enough to allow you to blend into the pace of life and mix
with the people, while still allowing you to travel reasonable distances and see
some diversity in a limited time.  However, potential cycle-tourists have many
questions:  How far can I expect to travel in a day if I haven't ridden a bike
for twenty years?  How do I transport the bike from one country to another? 
What about my luggage?  Can I avoid busy highways?......and so on.   So, if you
are tempted by travel awheel, with the breeze in your hair and the birds
singing, here are a few answers to get you going.<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Hiring:</FONT></B>  The hiring of a bike is
possible in just about every country in Europe.  In the Netherlands a basic
three-speed machine can be hired easily from most rail stations or bike shops
for about $5 a day and perhaps a deposit or passport details. These are
generally well maintained and perfectly adequate for the terrain. (You will find
that everyone else is riding one very similar.)  Other countries where hiring is
easy and widespread include Belgium, Northern Germany, France (SNCF rail
stations) and Denmark.  In France it is possible to hire a basic bike at one
station and then leave it at another.  In mountainous areas there are often
mountain bike hire centres that have grown around climbing and hiking centres. 
Chamonix in the French Alps was one of the first and has some of the best
off-road terrain available, though it is only for the fit.  In countries where
the general public does not cycle so readily, the availability of cycles for
hire is less evident; however, the local tourist information office can usually
find at least one hire centre for you.<BR></P>
<P>If you bring your own cycle to Europe, you may wonder how to transport it
from one area of interest to another without riding the intervening miles. Well,
there are a number of alternatives.<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Air:</FONT></B>  To bring your trusty steed from
North America in the first place you will by all likelihood have flown across
the Atlantic with it.  (Unless you can afford to ship it separately, or come
over on the QE2!)  Flying trans-Atlantic is probably the easiest flight to make
with a bicycle as the standard luggage allowances are that much higher on these
flights  (two pieces of luggage, each not to exceed 32kg as opposed to a 20kg
maximum on other flights).  Some tips, though:  make sure you confirm that the
airline knows that you are bringing a bicycle and check their packing
requirements.  If they do not require the bike to be boxed then turn the
handlebars sideways and remove the pedals and other extremities.  I do not box
my bike if I don't have to, because at least an unboxed cycle is obvious to
baggage handlers as a reasonably fragile item, unlike a cardboard box which may
end up at the bottom of a luggage container.<BR> </P>
<P>In Europe luggage restrictions on flights are often limiting, but one trick
is to take the bike as one piece of luggage, then put all the other bags into a
sack and make that the other piece whilst placing any heavy objects into your
hand luggage. Some airlines charge for carrying a bike.  Shop around, if
possible, for the more cycle-friendly airlines. <BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Train:</FONT></B>  There is some disparity among
rail operators and their cycle carrying policies. I have known a bike to be sent
on a day ahead in Spain, only to arrive two days after the owner.  Quite a few
rail services carry bikes on separate services to the rider, but charge quite
highly for it.   On British rail services there is a booking system and a $4.50
fee to take a bike on Inter-city services and a first-come, first-served system
on local services off-peak.  In France bikes travel separately on most long
distance services.  Channel tunnel services were supposed to be carrying
bicycles from the onset, and even had the carrying hooks fitted, but there were
some problems early on, so it is best to check for current policies.  Another
service that was to be introduced prior to the summer of '96 was a ride-on
service between the Chunnel terminals, to compete with the cross-Channel
ferries.  With so much disparity between services in different countries, the
best advice with is to check with the national tourist bureaus of the countries
you intend to visit.<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Ferry:</FONT></B>  Most ferry services in Europe
do not charge to carry a bicycle (or other human-powered vehicles -- e.g.
tandems, trikes etc.) and only charge the rider a foot-passenger fee. One
exception seems to be Scandinavian Seaways who charge a few dollars for the bike
per single crossing.  On most services a place can be obtained on the day of
sailing; if the service is particularly infrequent, it may pay to book a few
days in advance.  Bicycles enter the car deck with the other vehicles, so take
care on the decks and watch for oily patches that are slippery.  Crew members
will direct you to a corner where your machine can be left (locked).  Remember
to take all you will need for the voyage from the bike, as you cannot return to
the car-deck while the ship is at sea.  This is particularly important to
remember on the longer sailings!  Personally I find ferries a wonderful way to
travel and a useful source of inexpensive overnight accommodation -- it's almost
like a mini-cruise.</P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Bus:</FONT></B>  Long-distance buses used to be
totally against carrying bikes, but now some operators have seen the light and
allow boxed bikes to be carried at an additional fee.  A scheme started by the
Dutch, and now operated by a UK company as well, runs a regular bus service
through France, Italy and possibly Spain from various pick-up points in Northern
Europe with dropping-off points along the route.  Bikes are kept in a trailer
behind the bus and the service is operated through the summer like any other,
except that is exclusively for cyclists.  (See also <I>Organized Holidays</I>,
below.)<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Cycle routes:</FONT></B>  The network of cycle
dedicated routes throughout Europe grows annually.  In 1993 the Danish
government alone opened 2000 km of new national cycle routes, and a grant of &#163;40
million in the UK to the Sustrans organization will enable construction of a
good part of the national network, including part of the Atlantic Arc project. 
In the Netherlands it is possible to undertake a full national tour and hardly
come close to a motor vehicle.  The bicycle is at home in Northern Europe:  I
have been reliably informed that it is possible to ride from Amsterdam to Vienna
on cycle routes of one form or another.  A useful guide available from the
Danish tourist authorities is &quot;Cykel Guide: Denmark rundt pa cykel.&quot; 
The main text is in Danish but there is an English summary, and maps of all the
national cycle routes.  These routes link every part of the country and are well
sign-posted, making Denmark ideal for both the beginning and experienced
cycle-tourist.<BR></P>
<P>The &quot;Atlantic Arc&quot; route is a project undertaken to link the
western-most nations with a coastal cycle route from Cadiz in Spain to Skye in
Scotland through Portugal, France, England, Wales and Ireland.  Its is based on
the now famous riverside routes along the Rhine and Danube, which utilize
country lanes, riverside promenades and specially-built cycle routes.  With a
little careful preparation, a bicycle tour of Europe can be a largely
traffic-free experience.  Remember that in some countries  using cycle paths is
obligatory, and the police will stop you from riding on the roads if there is a
dedicated path.  (In most countries these are signed with a white cycle on a
circular blue background.)<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Organized Holidays:</FONT></B>  There is a large
and growing number of companies who organize cycle tours in Europe, ranging from
those who will carry your luggage, provide a bike and mechanic, and book your
luxury hotel accommodations, to those who only suggest routes for you to
undertake on your own.  Whatever your tastes, abilities, or budget there is an
organized tour for you in any number of countries.  Wine-tasting your way around
the Chateaux of France, mud-plugging the mountain trails of mid-Wales, or
sauntering from one beach to another in Greece, bicycling can offer maximum
freedom to explore and view at leisure.<BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">More Information:</FONT></B>  One excellent
source of information is the Cyclists Touring Club (CTC), who can give all
manner of advice including information sheets on every country and many regions.
 They also organize and advertise tours regularly, can supply suitable
insurance, and offer other services for an annual fee of &#163;25.  Contact CTC
at Cotterell House,  69 Meadrow, Godalming, Surrey GU7 3HS, UK; Tel 0044 (0)
1483 417217, fax 0044 (0) 1483 426994.  &#164;<BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Nick Gregory is a travel writer living in Powys,
UK.</FONT></I><B> </B></P>
<HR>
