<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B><BR></P> 
<H1>Row Upon Row</H1>
<P><I>by Nathalie Zeidman</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Chester, A Town Comfortable With Present &amp; Past</I><BR></H2>
<P>I have this thing about walled cities. That's what brought me to Chester in
the first place.  But it's the Rows that held me there.  Picture streets of
stunning town houses, all black and white Tudor like a flock of magpies; from
the ground floor to the third floor, levels of shops.  To the rear of the
balcony, still more shops, sometimes a block deep.  Malls, it seems, are not the
invention of some Dallas or Los Angeles developer. <BR> </P>
<P>Actually, shopping malls have been hiding in Chester, behind a facade of
black timber and white stucco mullioned windows and gabled roofs, since the
1300s.  Inside, however, the Rows have gone twentieth century:  escalators move
you up and down, plastic charge cards move you in and out.  My own plastic
didn't get much use in the Row, despite  temptations like the Welsh cupboard. 
But as my husband Jerry said, &quot;Shipping's never worked for us.  How are we
going to carry it?  And more to the point, where would we put it once we're
home?&quot;   So I passed up the cupboard and the Waterford and Crown Derby to
go in it, the Liberty cotton by the yard, the Laura Ashley frock and Burberry
raincoat.  We almost succumbed to a counter snack of pizza sloshed down with a
diet cola, but opted instead for a proper tea at The Gallery in sprawling St.
Michael's Row. The Gallery serves freshly baked scones and those dainty chicken
and cucumber sandwiches for which the English are noted, and for which they
charge what a deli in Santa Monica might for a hero or submarine.<BR></P>
<P>Not that the Brits don't have their own version of a grossed-out sandwich. 
For under two dollars you can get a gargantuan baked potato stuffed with every
imaginable filling, from potted, pickled and preserved meats to vegetarian
concoctions.  A fast food chain with the fetching name of  &quot;Spud U Like&quot;
franchises a cubbyhole in Bridge Street Row, but it wasn't their gourmet treats
that lured us there: one floor below the eatery are the remains of a
2000-year-old Roman bath.<BR></P>
<P>Little remains of the wall the Romans built to keep out the Celts and other
uncivilized invaders. The walls we walked, solid chunks of mellowed sandstone
pink in the sun, were built in the Middle Ages. Prom these walls we looked
outward to the lazy River Dee, a scene waiting to be immortalized on canvas by a
latter day Constable or Turner.   Further on, the grassy oval of Roodee spread
out before us; horses have been racing there since fifteen-something. The other
side of the wall gave us a seagull's view of the enclosed town.<BR></P>
<P>Charles I could see it all from his tower:  the town, the river, the
racetrack and the heartbreaking rout of his forces of his forces by
Parliamentary troops.  Today the King Charles Tower is a mini-museum, filled
with momentos of the siege during England's bloody Civil War, when the town was
a Royalist stronghold and Cromwell did it in.  From the tower we had a close
view of the Chester Canal, one of the many that were cut to join English towns
when highways were unpaved and treacherous.  During the summer, the museum
attendant told us, a horse-drawn barge takes visitors on various trips,
including one to Chester's famous zoo. <BR></P>
<P>We started and ended our two mile circuit of the walls at Eastgate, the
easiest gate in Chester to find:  just look for the lacy wrought-iron clock,
faced with coral and turquoise enamel, that stands above the gateway like an
oversized birdcage.  This Victorian gem, erected in honor of the widowed queen's
Diamond Jubilee, is the second most photographed clock in the UK.  In our album
it's numero uno.  We snapped it from the street and from the wall, at a distance
and up close.  Like the Rows, the Jubilee Clock is uniquely Chester.   Around
the corner from the Eastgate is the Chester Cathedral.  We were advised to enter
the grounds via the medieval gateway, across the street from the town hall. 
That put us in Abbey Square, an enclave of handsome Georgian town houses where
once the cue to the loo was  &quot;I'm going to the garden to pluck a rose.&quot;
 Credit modern plumbing with taking the  poetry out of everyday life. <BR></P>
<P>Intimate is not a word usually associated with cathedrals but it suits
Chester's, thanks no doubt to its days as a Benedictine Monastery, when monks
walked enclosed cloisters and abbotts prayed in narrow stalls.  We had a 'cuppa'
and a bun in the refractory, then sat in the choir at evensong.  What better way
to end a day of poking around the Rows, scaling the walls, and viewing all
things old, strange and beautiful.<BR></P>
<P>Poking around on our own was no problem.  How could we miss?   Everything
within the walls and much without is special.  But just to be sure, we bought a
booklet describing self-guided walks at the Chester Heritage Center.  At the
Center, an  audio-visual program uses rare woodcuts and drawings to bring the
town's past to life.  It's a program guaranteed to arouse even the most
reluctant tourist's sense of adventure.   The self-guided walks were easy enough
but we wanted something more personal, so we joined one of the small groups that
 leaves twice a day from the Information Center.  Volunteer guides are history
buffs loaded with titillating tidbits of  centuries-old gossip:  like the one
about the monk who was entertaining his mistress when the Abbott unexpectedly 
showed up.  Did she jump out of the window on her own or did her clerical
boyfriend give her a little shove?  As for eavesdropping, our guide pointed to a
row of seventeenth century houses.  &quot;Notice how the second floor eaves
project  beyond the first?  Linger under an open window and you're guilty of
eavesdropping.&quot;<BR> </P>
<P>Today radio talk shows have replaced &quot;eavesdropping.&quot;  A switch of
the dial and you can hear how proud Mrs. Burton is of  her newborn grandson
James.  &quot;A plush teddy for you, Mrs. B., for that precious little bundle.
And for Mrs. Merchant, a &#163;20 supermarket shopping spree for your correct
answer to the morning puzzle. Radio Shropshire, here!&quot;  A more cheerful
sort of  Shropshire Lad than Houseman's, that announcer.<BR></P>
<P>No wonder I fell in love with Chester and didn't want to leave.  Here is a
town comfortable in its present and its past.  Escalators glide above the Roman
baths; first-class restaurants hide in every Row.  One restaurant we were
particularly impressed with was La Boheme in Watergate Street Row.  Valerie
Bellis, ebullient owner of the Chester Town House, the  B&amp;B where we stayed,
recommended it.  In the background at the bistro, mellow jazz; on the table,
simple superb French:  mushroom soup, fresh poached salmon and creme brulee.  A
bottle of Mouton Cadet and our bill was still under forty dollars. <BR></P>
<P>Slow Boat, on the second floor of a new building just outside the walls, was
another of Valerie's suggestions.  An extensive Cantonese menu featuring prawns
in all sorts of sauces, a view of the town walls, and moderate prices make Slow
Boat a  good trip.  A free booklet, &quot;Eating Out In The Chester Area.&quot;,
lists other choices; while &quot;What's On In Chester,&quot;  another give-away,
sent us to the Gateway Theater to see Caryll Churchill's brilliantly performed
<I>Serious Money</I>, a  clever satire of insider trading on the New York and
London Stock Exchanges.  &quot;What's On&quot; also listed a variety of
concerts, from jazz to philharmonic, including a military tattoo; day and night
cruises on the River Dee, with and without  barbecues and music; day trips by
coach to Northern Wales; and local museums.  The Fifteenth Annual Chester Folk
Festival  was scheduled for the Spring Break Holiday Weekend, but we were back
in London by then, thinking about James Boswell.  In his diary, the eighteenth
century biographer wrote: &quot;Chester pleases my fancy more than any other
town I ever saw.&quot;  <BR></P>
<P>Mr. Boswell, my sentiments exactly!  &#164;<BR></P>
<HR>
<H2>Getting There</H2>
<UL><LI>By rail:  frequent trains from London's Euston Station; 2 hours.</LI>
<LI>By coach: from London's Victoria Coach Station: 4 hours</LI></UL> 
<P><BR></P>
<H2>Staying There</H2>
<UL><LI><B>The Chester Town House</B>, a recently renovated 17th century B&amp;B;
 ask for room  #1 or#2. Rooms though modest in size have every convenience
including hair dryer and remote control TV. In the heart of the walled town but
quiet at night.</LI>
<LI><B>The Blossoms</B>, a newly converted 3-century old coaching inn.
Attractive, good location within the walls.</LI>
<LI><B>The Chester Grovesnor</B>; part of the Grovesnor chain; first rate.</LI>
<LI><B>The Queen's</B>. Opposite the train station, half a mile outside the
walls. Beautiful early Victorian hotel, newly renovated with large rear garden.
Free car parking.</LI></UL>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I>- Nathalie Zeidman</I></P>
