<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Amsterdam / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">In Pursuit of Gezellig</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>&quot;Amsterdamland&quot; in Winter, by Sophia
Dembling</I></FONT></B></P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<P><!--In Pursuit of Gezellig   Amsterdamland in Winter By Sophia Dembling-->It
was cold when we arrived in Amsterdam.  Very, very cold.  Even the locals
complained as they huddled in their winter clothes, necks pulled into their
mufflers like turtles, shoulders hunched against a biting wind that whirled the
snow.  The sky was steel gray, the sun&#146;s halfhearted blue light barely
penetrated the clouds.  But the apartment we&#146;d rented had doilies on the
tables, lace curtains on the windows, and Napoleon and Josephine&#146;s
portraits painted on the lamps that graced the mantle.  As  soon as the
apartment&#146;s owner had shown us around and given us keys and maps, we
cranked up the gas heaters, made tea, and curled up on the couches to plan the
weeklong visit ahead.  Madness, perhaps, to head north in the dead of winter.
But then, is there any place cozier than Amsterdam, with its sweet little
streets and dollhouse-size buildings?  The Dutch word for cozy is gezellig, and
that was what I sought this blustery January week.
<BR>
</P>
<P>Amsterdam is pure <I>gezellig</I>, even wearing winter gray.  My companion
called it  <I>Amsterdamland</I>&#151;a theme park version of a European city,
with canals and streets so picturesque it is difficult for a photo-taking
tourist to get anywhere.  Every turn presents a photogenic display: bicycles
leaning against iron railings, narrow gabled buildings, church steeples
presiding over canals.  There are none of the grand spaces and monuments of
Paris, but many small beauties, like a divine and intricate needlework.  Each
one must be admired, photographed, then photographed again.   
<BR></P>
<P>Our little apartment was a few blocks from the Heineken brewery, within easy
walking distance of the Rijksmuseum. For $60 a night, we had two bedrooms,
kitchen, living  room, cable TV,  telephone (though we couldn&#146;t make
outgoing calls), bathroom with a  shower, and enough gezellig to sustain us
through the cold.  A tasteful Dutch friend declared, without admiration, the
apartment&#146;s decor &#147;very Dutch&#148; with its doilies, fussy
chandeliers, scenic lampshades and bric-a-brac clutter.  My companion and I,
however, were charmed.  And undaunted:  after warming ourselves a bit that first
night, we set out into the cold again for a bite to eat at the Cafecox, around
the corner from the City Theatre and a hangout for Amsterdam&#146;s theater
crowd.  Afterwards, shivering in the wind, we decided the best place to be on
such an eve was indoors, so we headed to the Tuchinsky cinema, a beloved,
beautifully preserved  over-the-top art deco confection that drew throngs of
locals in out of the cold. 
<BR></P>
<P>The theater has six movie screens; the big downstairs theater remains at its
art deco best.  We saw a James Bond movie in a smaller, upstairs auditorium.
Dutch is a peculiar,  difficult language (is it really wise to use so many
letters per word?) but Dutch people are  gracious about this and speak English
fluently. Rather than being dubbed, English-language movies are subtitled in
Dutch, which was pleasant, though it would have been  fun to see Dutch coming
out of Pierce Brosnan&#146;s mouth.  Other than that first evening, the coldness
outside and the gezellig inside the little apartment discouraged me from going
out much at night. However, the days warmed  slightly over the week, the sun
grew braver and the city sparkled in its wintry rays.  Each day after breakfast
(we stocked the kitchen with bread, bananas, coffee and other  breakfastables),
I set out exploring, not to return until after dinner at restaurants chosen
wholly for their gezellig&#151;for it is when the blue light fades to gray and
the thermometer starts its night-time descent that I most need such things. 
<BR></P>
<P>Despite the cold, Amsterdammers simply went about their business, bustling
around the city, jingling bicycle bells at hapless pedestrians, filling cafes
with cigarette smoke and conversation. And on this visit, there was an
additional and unusual charm to the city:  the  canals had frozen hard enough to
ice skate on&#151;an occurrence of once every six years or so.  Amsterdammers
enthusiastically enjoyed the novelty with hockey sticks, big dogs, toddlers and
friends. It was like a holiday, and those not trying the ice lingered along the
canals and enjoyed the show.  
<BR></P>
<P>The city bustled with tourists, too.  The Anne Frank Haus manages to be
evocative even  when solid with people, though it is difficult to imagine the
loneliness of a child when you  you can&#146;t turn around for the crowd.  The
Rembrandhuis, Rembrandt&#146;s one-time home in  the city&#146;s Jewish quarter,
was less crowded and I spent a couple of hours sighing over his engravings.   
<BR></P>
<P>The Rijksmuseum is so vast it is difficult to feel crowded there, and I
whiled away a pleasant afternoon wandering its galleries.  The Van Gogh Museum,
spacious, modern and bright, basked in the sunshine of Arles and color.  On a
chilly morning, the red light  district was particularly bleak, but it is there
the enchanting Museum Amsetlkring is  tucked.  This was the canalside home of a
wealthy 17th-century merchant, and it is a wonderful Escher-like maze of rooms
and staircases.  Most astonishing is the ornate  Catholic church in the attic, a
legacy of the Calvinist movement that turned the nation Protestant and forced
Catholicism underground, in a manner of speaking.  Most gezellig is the
17th-century kitchen that fairly begs one to pull up a chair and have a cup of
coffee.<BR></P>
<P>In the wintertime, Amsterdam&#146;s cafes fold up their umbrellas and bring
business inside, where you can sit by a window and  watch the serene scenes
outside. My companion and I went several times to a little brown cafe near the
Rijksmuseum, the Hans en Greitje.  Touristy, perhaps, and the walls were painted
brown rather than stained by years of tobacco smoke as the name brown cafe
implies, but it was genial and gezellig, the food was tasty and it seemed to
attract nearly as many locals as tourists.   
<BR></P>
<P>We found other spots,  too&#151;a quiet, sunny cafe on the Leidsplein where
we had breakfast a couple of mornings and could easily have idled the day away;
Bojo, a kitschy Indonesian restaurant with delicious inexpensive meals; Cafe
Berkhout, a comfortable Amsteryuppie hangout where we ate Dutch comfort food.   

<BR></P>
<P>In Amsterdam&#146;s 17th-century golden age, when much of the city was
built, your tax bill was determined by how wide your building was, which is why
buildings are tall and  narrow.  Restaurants, for the most part, are small and
thickly cluttered with chairs, tables  and clientele.  Putting on coats, hats
and mufflers in such spaces requires a complicated,  restrained wriggle and if
can result in your smacking one patron with your coat sleeve while trailing a
muffler in someone else&#146;s coffee.  
<BR></P>
<P>But there was only one real hardship&#151;at least for me&#151;to a winter
visit. Blessed with no  sense of direction at all, I frequently get lost when I
travel. Ordinarily, I am happy to  totter about until I find my way, but my
pleasure in such wandering decreases with every  degree the temperature falls
below freezing. On a couple of occasions I found myself  wandering confusing
straats and pleins stupidly, peering at my map and struggling with 
unpronounceable street names while darkness fell and the wind sliced through my
coat.  I  didn&#146;t dare get on a bus or trolley for fear it would take me
someplace unfamiliar from  which I might never return. 
<BR></P>
<P>But of course, sooner or later I would be climbing the narrow stairs to the
gezellig little apartment again, to sip tea in front of the heater and plan the
next day&#146;s wanderings.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><I><B>Getting there:</B> You can find good off-season deals to Amsterdam
in the winter. Check consolidators&#146; prices. Among the airlines flying to
Amsterdam are American Airlines, British Airways, KLM Royal Dutch Airlines,
United Airlines, TWA, and Lufthansa. 
</I><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Money:</B>  There are approximately 1.60 gilders (also called
florin, and abbreviated fl) to $1; fl1 = $0.62.<BR><B>Accommodations:</B> 
Renting an apartment is a particularly delightful and economical way to visit a 
city. We found ours in a magazine. KoVerlaan, Gaaspstraat 69, 1079-VD 
Amsterdam, Netherlands; 011-31-20-642-5190. It was small&#151;one bedroom was
closet-sized with a lumpy twin bed&#151;but suited our purposes perfectly. 
Another company that rents apartments and houseboats is Amsterdam House B.V.,
Willemina J.I. Visser, Amstel  176a, 1017 AE Amsterdam, Netherlands. 
</I><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Winter Packages:</B>  The Netherlands National Reservations Centre
offers winter packages.  Contact NCR, Postbus 404, 2260 AK Leidschendam, The
Netherlands.   Information:  For more information about travel in Holland,
contact the Netherlands Board of Tourism, 225 N. Michigan Ave., Suite 326,
Chicago, Ill. 60607; (312) 819-0300.</I><BR></P>
<HR>
