<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Of Lorgnettes &amp;
Tassels, Shopping in Amsterdam / Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine /
Travel in Europe / Amsterdam</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>Of Lorgnettes and Tassles</H2>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Shopping Amsterdam</FONT></B></I></P>
<P><BR><I>by Sophia Dembling</I></P>
<P><B> First, there was shopping.</B>  In the 17th century, Amsterdam was the
commercial capital of Europe. It was trading that brought the prosperity from
which  grew the Netherlands' Golden Age, when art and culture flourished.  In a
way, we can thank shopping for Rembrandt. That gives it some extra dignity,
doesn't it?   And consumer zeal still flourishes in Amsterdam; a shopaholic's
willpower is sorely tried by hundreds of specialty shops that take trivialities
and with sheer quantity, variety and dramatic flourishes of display, raise them
to high, irresistible art.  How can anyone resist a room lined with buttons?  A
wall dripping tassels?  Beads arrayed like brightly colored sweets?  A
smorgasbord of toothbrushes?  Shopping in Amsterdam is a sensual delight. <BR><BR></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>If you're feeling particularly pretentious and need a lorgnette to complete
your look (or slightly less pretentious, and would settle for a pince nez) visit
<B>Donald E. Jongejans</B>, which sells nothing but antique, never-worn,
eyeglasses. The small, somewhat  grungy shop has a huge selection of frames
dating from the 1800s to the 1970s. Find cat glasses, mod glasses, Jackie O.
glasses,  Buddy Holly glasses. Some are non-prescription sunglasses, most can be
fitted with prescription lenses by your own  optometrist. This is the shop that
supplied the spectacles for the movie The Last Emperor. Prices start at about
$18.  <I>Donald E.  Jongejans, Noorderkerstraat 18.
</I> 
<BR></P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>You might be tempted to dance with your mop in a kitchen all tricked out
with the frivolity sold at <B>Kitsch Kitchen</B>.  The shop is  an explosion of
color and kicky plastic gewgaws, imported mostly from Africa, Latin America and
China. Even dishwashing is  less dreary if you do it in rubber gloves trimmed
with ruffles and flowers, and a rainbow colored scrub brush might make 
scrubbing the floor less of a chore. (Or maybe not.) Plastic tablecloth fabric
in bright colors and fruit and floral prints is sold by  the meter. Prices start
at about $2. <I>Kitsch Kitchen, Eerste Bloemdwarsstraat, 21.</I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>It's not that <B>Dorothea de Boer</B> has a particular thing for buttons. 
It's just that she took a look around and &quot;I noticed there wasn't any
button shop,&quot; she said.  So she opened Knopenwinkel. And a fine button shop
it is, from its giant button door handle to its more than 14,000 different
buttons (not counting different sizes of some styles) from all over the world. 
With parquet floor and shiny wood and marble fixtures, the setting is suitable
for fine jewelry -- and these buttons are more than just something to keep your
pants on .  There are handmade rhinestone and silk-wrapped buttons, polished
seashells and mother-of-pearl, coral, nut, leather, water buffalo horn, Czech
glass, plastic and much, much more.  Prices start at under $1.  <I>Knopenwinkel,
Wolvenstraat 14.  </I>
<BR></P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>Who knew dental care could be fun?  <B>de Witte Tanden Winkel</B> is
devoted entirely to teeth and with a splurge here, you could brush after every
meal for a week and never use the same brush twice.  The array includes
toothbrushes with handles filled with floating shells or, better yet, little
plastic veggies.  There are a pair of brushes built like Adam and Eve,
Danish-modern wooden brushes, Hello Kitty brushes, a selection of electric
toothbrushes and, for the truly meticulous, interdental brushes, for brushing
between the teeth.  Prices start at about $3.  <I>de Witte Tanden Winkel,
Runstraat 5.  </I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P> Where you decide to hang your tassels is none of our business, but you're
sure to walk out with at least a couple if you walk into <B>H.J. van de Kerkhof</B>,
which has been selling trimmings for 60 years.  Gerda van de Kerkhof says all
tassels are handmade -- a better tassel-making machine has yet to be built. 
Sizes range from itty-bitty to bigger than your head, some are lanky, some
pudgy, some are tassels made of tassels.  Dangle them from your ears, hang one
around your neck, tie a couple around your waist.  Or whatever.  Prices start at
about $1.50.<I> H.J. van de Kerkhof, Wolvenstraat 9-11.  
</I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>When the sun streams into <B>Coppenhagen 1001 kralen</B>, it illuminates a
rainbow of 5,000 beads displayed in glass jars in the spacious shelf-lined shop.
 Beads range from basic to kicky to exquisite.  Perhaps a glass peanut, a red
Cupid, a green cat?  Or maybe Venetian glass, millefiori, or antique African? 
Buy a handful, buy a necklace, buy one perfect bead.  Prices start at under $1.
 <I>Coppenhagen 1001 kralen, Rozengracht 54.  
</I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P><B>Hester van Eeghen</B>'s small leather goods have an architectural
quality to them -- she points out echoes of classic step-gabled Dutch houses in
some of her designs.  &quot;I don't have the intention to make souvenirs,&quot;
she said, but there is that possibility.  All of Ms. van Eeghen's innovative
pieces are made in Italy, including a portfolio based on a 17th century closet,
with all sorts of fascinating doors and hidey-holes; and a clever reversible
briefcase, black on one side, purple on the other.  Prices start at about $30
for a wallet.  <I>Hester van Eeghen, Hartenstraat 1.  </I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>When you think about it, a baby hammock makes perfect sense.  It cradles
gently, holds firmly, and rocks soothingly.  And you can buy a hammock for baby,
or anyone else, at <B>Maranon</B>, which sells nothing but.  The striking
two-room store by the flower market has white walls, terra cotta floors, and
rows of hammocks on wooden displays.  Many of the hammocks are handmade and
natural died and styles range from simple open weaves to more elaborate weaves,
stripes and trims.  Prices start at about $23 for an infant hammock.  <I>Maranon,
Singel 488-490.</I>  
<BR></P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>In the exquisitely sparse <B>Hoeden M/V</B>, the high-style hat displays
are the show. Hats by about 20 international designers stand on stalks, perch
like puff pastries behind glass, sprout from a mantelpiece under a crystal
chandelier.  Patricia Underwood's fetching mink affair, at nearly $1,000, is the
priciest item in the shop; the hats of Philip Treacy's bridal collection are
whipped-cream concoctions; or try one of Dutch designer Miriam Nuver's
complicated canvas numbers.  &quot;They are very shapey,&quot; said the
saleswoman, smacking one into submission.  There's also a large selection of
men's traditional Borsalinos. Hat shapes can be tweaked to suit your style, if
need be. <I>Hoeden M/V, Herengracht 422.  
</I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P><B>Peter Doeswijk</B> is an artist-dilettante who buys phones from the
phone company and paints them with cow prints, angels, zebra stripes, and other
bold patterns.  He makes as many as he feels like, sells as many as he can.  Ask
nicely and he'll take you upstairs to show you the wacky furniture he makes
also, from recycled materials such as crates and tin cans.  He made a coffee
table from a desk chair so it can raise and lower, a whimsical off-kilter liquor
cabinet, and his lamps have tin can shades.  (But what he really wants to do is
produce -- he's currently working on a documentary about lullabies around the
world.)  Prices start at about $30.  <I>Peter Doeswijk, Vijzelgracht 11.</I>  
<BR></P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>It's impossible to resist poking your nose into <B>'t Winkeltje</B>, curio
shop extraordinaire. There's something about the building itself, with its row
of colorful masks above the windows, the boxes full of junk outside the door,
the display windows packed with tin toys, glass knickknacks and candles,
snowstorm balls, teapots, dolls, piggy banks and plates.  &quot;It all looks
old, but it's new,&quot; says owner Carla Aarsman.  Everything but the shop
itself, which is 40 years old, and the original cash register, which can ring up
sales only as high as 9 guilders, 99 1/2 cents, about $6 by today's exchange
rate.  Prices start at about 20 cents (for a small plastic baby, should you need
one). <I>'t Winkeltje, Prinsengracht 228.  
</I><BR></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/package.gif" WIDTH="27" HEIGHT="23">
<P>Sometimes a gal's just got to color-coordinate.  When the urge strikes,
<B>Palette</B> can help.  Palette has selection of shoes and handbags they will
dye to match anything, or choose one of two pump styles for a fabric wrap in one
or two fabrics.  Trimmings also are available.  Dying takes about a week and
fabric wraps about two weeks, but they're happy to ship the shoes home to you. 
Prices start at about $100.  <I>Palette, N.Z. Voorburgwal 125.</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Note to serious shoppers:</B> When in Amsterdam, pick up a hot pink book
titled De <I>'96 Amsterdam Original &amp; Gun-Shopping Gids</I>. [CQ]  This
book is so well designed -- with maps, photos, phone numbers, addresses and
opening hours for some of the coolest shops in town -- that the fact it's
written entirely in Dutch is only a small obstacle to its usefulness.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
