<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Norway's Lofoten Islands</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Norway&#146;s Lofoten Islands<BR></H2>
<P><B><I>&quot;Part scream, part roar, and so powerful that not even the
Niagara falls can raise their voice higher to the heavens.&quot;   - E A Poe</I></B><BR></P>
<P><I>by Nick Gregory</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Arriving on the ferry from Bodo the islands emerge from the ocean like a
huge wall of rock</B>, the entire archipelago blended together to form a row of
impenetrable sharks teeth rising up as if to tear at the blue fabric of the sky.
 Lofoten is the archipelago that juts out into the Arctic and Atlantic Oceans
north of the Arctic circle in Norway, between the 67th and 68th parallels. 
There are seven principle islands famed for their beauty and ruggedness,
white-capped mountain peaks to white sandy beaches and attractive fishing
villages.  The seas around Lofoten are unique too, home to cod from the freezing
arctic and whales the warm waters flow from the south to give the islands a
milder climate than areas at a similar latitude like Alaska and Greenland.  The
two most south westerly islands of the archipelago, Rost and V&aelig;roy, are
famed for their bird colonies with Rost alone believed to have a colony
containing a quarter of the sea birds in Norway, as many as 2.5 million.<BR></P>
<P>Both these islands are linked by a daily ferry in the summer to Bodo on the
mainland and Moskenes.  On the ferry from V&aelig;roy to Moskenes the route
crosses the Moskenes Maelstrom, one of the worlds fiercest and an inspiration to
both Edgar Allen Poe and Jules Verne.  On Moskenes island the fishing villages
lie one after another like jewels in a necklace.  Red-painted wooden huts stand
stilted over the sheltered harbour waters backed by the huge cliffs of the dark
mountains.  Racks of fish left to cure in the cool air leave a distinctive
aroma.  From &Aring; at the south-western tip and the end of the Kong Olavs Veg
(King Olavs road) through Sorv&aring;gen, the site of the worlds second wireless
telegraph station built in 1906 and now home to a permanent exhibition in
connection with the village's unique telecommunications history.<BR></P>
<P>&Aring; itself is home to the Norwegian fishing village museum where one can
appreciate the atmosphere of a genuine traditional village including boat
houses, forge, steam processing plant for cod-liver oil and fishermans huts, all
of which blend with the surrounding village to take the visitor back in time. 
There is also the Stockfish museum where you can learn about the thousand year
old Stockfish industry and how it is used still as a trade commodity and where
it is exported.  On through Moskenes where ferrys to the mainland and southern
islands can be taken as well as excursions in the summer to the &quot;outside &quot;
of the islands including the Kollhellaren Cave.  Take a guided tour to see the
3000 year old cave paintings.  There is also the chance to hire a skippered
fishing boat for a day and try out your skills at deep sea angling or even
experience life on a working boat.<BR></P>
<P>A few minutes from Moskenes by road, after a few rises and dips along the
coast, a superb view of Reine meets the traveller.  The speckling of red against
the blues and greens of nature in a scene that fills the senses.  Snow still
lingering on the higher peaks and shimmering turquoise sea below.  Take the boat
trip along the fjord, one of Norway's most beautiful and then a walk to the far
end to enjoy the enormity of the suroundings.  A half hours journey by bus will
take you through Hamnoy and across the bridge to the adjoining island of
Flakstad.  To the left, the road to Fredvang leaps over humped bridges from
islet to islet like a giant concrete sea-serpent.  From Fredvang, a fishing
village on the outside of Moskenes island, there are numerous hiking trails
leading to remote areas of the Yttersida (the outside) as well as cabins for
hikers and an excellent bakery.  Stay on the bus past the Fredvang exit to
Ramberg, the islands' administrative centre located next to a white sandy beach
overlooking the Arctic Ocean and a great place to camp and watch the Midnight
sun<BR></P>
<P>Just outside the village is the beautiful wooden church with its
characteristic onion-shaped cupola built in 1780.  Inside the altar pre-dates
the rest of the church and the pulpit was painted by the master painter Godtfred
Ezechiel.  Away from the Kong Olavs Veg, on the Vestfjord coast, lie the fishing
villages of Sund and Nusfjord famous for the sculptured representations of the
Sund smith and Nusfjord protected as one of the original construction custom
projects during the European Architecture Conservation Year in 1975.  Today
Nusfjord is one of the representative scenes of Norway that can be found around
the World.<BR></P>
<P>For the outdoors-minded, there's the Flakstad trail, a footpath leading from
Napp past the Storb&aring;thallaren, a stone age settlement, to the abandoned
fishing village of Ostre Nesland; it is a ghostly way when the mists are rolling
in off the sea.  By tunnel from Napp to the island of Vestv&aring;goy, here it
not far to the town of Leknes and one of the two airports on the Lofotens.  On
the south coast route from Leknes you'll come to Stamsund and one of the two
calling ports for the Hurtigruten  coastal steamer service.  Nearby is the
tourist office and youth hostel as well as the Nordland Puppet theatre and a
number of local handicraft shops.  There is also some alpine skiing available in
the winter with superb views over the sea on clear days.   Also along the south
coast are a number of fine white sandy beaches that slip into turquoise waters,
giving the impression of a tropical paradise, although only hardy creatures
actually enter the water!<BR></P>
<P>Back on the KOV from Leknes is the village of Borg, site of the biggest
Viking chieftans homestead to be excavated in Scandinavia, here you can see
reconstructions of Viking life and exhibitions of archaeological finds from the
area.  Exhibits include the ship &quot;Lofotr&quot; and the authentic boathouse
replica.   Back in the present and headed east over the small island of Gimsoy
and onto V&aelig;gan the road moves back to the south coast and a short
diversion leads to the &quot;Venice of Lofoten&quot; at Henningsv&aelig;r, a
large fishing village and centre of the famous Lofoten art community, with a
number of galleries and exhibitions including the Karl Erik Harr and a
photographic exhibition by the celebrated artist Wilse.  Around the town of
Kabelv&aring;g and into Svolv&aelig;r, the capital of Lofoten and regional
centre with transport links to the mainland.  High above the town of some 4120
inhabitants is the Svolv&aelig;rgeita or &quot;Svolv&aelig;r Goat&quot;, an
unusually shaped rock pinnacle that is renowned as a challenge to climbers and
only summited for the first time in 1910.  The small town harbour atmosphere of
Svolv&aelig;r makes it a great place to use as a tour base for those with their
own transport.  It too has a number of celebrated galleries in its own right
that include works by artists such as Gunnar Berg.<BR></P>
<P>From the harbour take a tour up the famous Trollfjorden by boat, its steep
cliff faces rising high above the Raftsundet strait or the express boat to
Stokmarknes that takes this route north.  By road from Svolv&aelig;r you head
north to the ferry at Fiskebol and onto the Vester&aring;lens, or perhaps take a
detour from the main route through Laukvik on the north coast and another
excellent view of the open Arctic Ocean and Midnight sun in summer.  Arriving in
Melbu on the ferry from the Lofotens look back, and maybe there'll be a huge
rainbow rising from the fjord and spanning the mountains of the archipelago in
the grandeur that they deserve.   &#164; </P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>Fact File:</I></B><BR></P>
<P><B>Lofoten Islands Tourist Information:</B> Destination Lofoten AS, PO Box
210, N-8301 Svolv&aelig;r; Tel.  760-73000, Fax.  760-73001.   Also try the
office of the Norwegian Tourist Board in your home country.<BR></P>
<P><B>Getting there by air:</B> There are flights to Leknes, Svolv&aelig;r and
the two outlying islands of V&aelig;roy and Rost.  All flights to these airports
seem to go via Bodo with SAS, Braathens and Wideroe and there are connections
from Oslo, Stockholm and Bergen amongst others.   Ask about the limited number
of 'bargain' seats available to foreigners on internal flights.  I took one with
Braathens from Narvik to Oslo for 550Nkr as compared to the normal one-way fare
of over 2200Nkr.  Look for the booklet Flyruter i Norge for all internal flights
info.   For those with a little more spending money, try Lofotfly who hire
seaplanes to explore the region.  tel.  948 50547<BR></P>
<P><B>Rail:</B> The nearest railheads are at Bodo and Narvik.  There are two
trains a day from Trondheim to Bodo on the Norwegian Nordlandsbanen.  For those
on a budget the overnight train in the summer affords views of the scenery lit
by the Midnight sun and arrives at about 10am to connect with bus services.  The
day train leaves Trondheim at 0830 and arrives in Bodo at 1828.   The Narvik
train is run in co-operation with the Swedish railways and there are two trains
from Stockholm and one from Gothenburg daily, although only one from Stockholm
is direct.<BR></P>
<P><B>Sea:</B> From Bodo there is a car-ferry to Moskenes with five departures
daily in the summer, one of which calls at the islands of V&aelig;roy and Rost
(1500 from Bodo).  Sailing time for the direct services is approx 4 hours.  
Cost is 102 Nkr (US$15) for adult foot passenger and cars from 375Nkr one -way
including driver and dependant on vehicle length.   There is also the Hurtigrute
coastal steamer which calls at Bodo and then Stamsund and Svolv&aelig;r in both
directions on its journey from Bergen to the Russian border (Daily).   Express
boat from Bodo and Narvik to Svolv r.  Foot passengers only.   Car-ferry from
Skutvik (mid-way between Bodo and Narvik) to Svolv&aelig;r with two or three
departures a day in each direction.  Adult foot passengers 50Nkr and cars from
174 Nkr.<BR></P>
<P><B>Bus:</B> There are fast buses from all the local airports and they link
the larger towns of the region.  Pay as you board and ask about alighting at
smaller villages, it is quite possible.  There is also a good bus service the
length of the Lofotens and linking Harstad and Tromso to the north.  Car rental:
In Svolv&aelig;r, see Avis (tel 760 71140), Budget (760 70000), Europecar (760
71255) and Hertz (760 70720).<BR></P>
<P><B>Accomodation:</B>  For the budget traveller there are youth hostels at
Kabelv&aring;g (760 78103), Stamsund (760 89334) and &Aring; (760 91121) as well
as on the islands of Rost(760 96109) and V&aelig;roy(760 95375) with prices
ranging from 75Nkr; get more info from Norske Vandrerhjem, Hostelling Int&#146;l
Norway, Dronningengst.  26, N-0154 Oslo;  Tel 22421410, Fax 22424476.<BR></P>
<P><B>Camping:</B> Whilst there are numerous good campgrounds (lists available
from the tourist offices) on the islands it is perfectly legal and acceptable to
camp on open ground away from habitation for a couple of nights, but remember to
leave everything as you found it and open fires are not allowed from April to
September due to fire risk.   Ask for the Norwegian Camping Guide which has a
list of campgrounds nationally and a free map.  Also try the NAF (like AAA in
the US) at Postboks 494 Sentrum, 0105 Oslo, tel 22341500 fax 22341420, for their
free list and map.  A list of hotels, motels and pensions can be obtained from
the tourist offices free of charge.  The Midnight sun is visible from 27th May
to the 17th July on the Lofotens.  The best view points are on the open sections
of the northern coast.<BR></P>
<P><I>- Nick Gregory  
</I></P>
