<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Albania</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">July / August 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H1>Albania</H1>
<P><EM>By Susan Milligan</EM></P>
<HR>
<P><STRONG><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">A Country Being Created Before Your
Eyes</FONT></EM></STRONG><BR></P>
<P>The border guard surveyed our American passports and peered curiously at us
as we stood at the security station dividing Serbia and Macedonia.  &quot;Why do
you want to go to Albania?&quot; he asked, when we explained that we were
planning merely to pass through Macedonia en route to Tirana.   At first, we
took the question as a mini-interrogation; after all, there had been a war on in
the Balkans, and to him we could be smugglers. But in fact he was genuinely
baffled.  Albania?  For vacation?<BR></P>
<P>Though it is not yet a vacation site for the traditional tourist, Albania is
heading in that direction, anxious to pump up its fledgling market economy with
tourist trade.  But for the adventuresome and the curious, newly-opened Albania
is utter fascination.  Today the foreign traveler is heartily welcomed by the
Albanian people, who are just as anxious to see what outsiders are like as the
travelers are to meet the Albanians.</P>
<P></P>
<P>There is much to see in Albania, but this is almost beside the point.  You
will want to see Albania for the same reason you rushed to an R-rated movie when
you turned 17:  you couldn't do it before.  Albania is one of the few places
left in the world where you can watch a country being created in front of your
eyes -- sometimes, it appears, from scratch.  After 48 years as the most
hermetically-sealed of the former Soviet bloc nations, Albania  is awakening
with a start.  Everything is in flux here:  the economy, the political system,
and the popular culture.  The streets are a bizarre mix of old and new:  just
five years ago, there were no private cars in Tirana.  Now, the chaotic streets
are clogged with Mercedes-Benzes, competing for road space with pedestrians,
horses pulling carts, bicyclists and the ubiquitous begging Gypsy child. 
Walking the neighborhoods of Tirana can be dangerous; not for reasons of street
crime or violence, but because the Albanians aren't used to sharing the road. 
Barely used to being behind the wheel of their own cars, drivers here look like
16-year-olds with learner's permits.  They gleefully keep their hands pressed to
the car horns, appearing to delight in almost running pedestrians off the road.<BR></P>
<P>Where would a local of Albania, the poorest nation in Europe, get a
Mercedes?  &quot;Stolen,&quot; said a local police officer, with a shrug, as he
watched the scene from the sidewalk.  &quot;Yes, absolutely, stolen,&quot;
agreed one of the hordes of illegal money-changers who clog the city's main
square, standing undisturbed next the policeman as he calculated the daily rate
of exchange between the dollar and the leke.  Along the side roads, many of them
still dirt and gravel, novice entrepreneurs sell odd auto parts.  Passing by are
old men in tattered suits, walking their goats on leashes.  Sheep graze and
children play among the thousands of dome-shaped, cement bunkers scattered
throughout the country -- bunkers which once symbolized Soviet-controlled
Albania's isolation and hostility to the outside world.  The houses are still in
poor shape, and Albanians are still among Europe's poorest citizens, but many
apartments now have TV satellite dishes.  There were no private phones in
Albania until three years ago, and most locals still have no phones, or  for
that matter flush toilets.<BR></P>
<P>That didn't stop an Italian firm from opening a luxury hotel in March, with
a restaurant and a planned business center and shopping arcade.  It's quite a
switch from the days when the city's single, communist-run hotel occasionally
closed because it had no food to serve.  &quot;It's really a developing country
and a developing environment,&quot; said Cameron Pippitt, an official for the
United States Agency for International Development, which is helping Tirana move
toward the modern world.  &quot;A few years ago, there were no cafes, no kiosks,
no private restaurants,&quot; Pippitt said.  Now the busy avenues of Tirana are
loaded with charming coffee bars and well-run Italian restaurants.  Most of
these establishments are filled with men -- women in substantially Muslim
Albania tend to stay home, tending house and children -- and female travelers
should be prepared for verbal harassment on the street.  But the new restaurants
are of good quality and are still inexpensive for the foreigner.<BR></P>
<P>Much of the foreign influence in Albania comes from Italy, which has a
long-time historic connection to its across-the-sea neighbor.  American firms
are reluctant to invest in Albania because the infrastructure is still fairly
primitive, officials say.  The upside for the tourist is that Western influence
is displayed in charming espresso bars, not (as in other parts of Eastern
Europe) fast-food joints erected next to dilapidated housing.<BR></P>
<P>This is not to say that Albanians are hostile to Americans -- quite the
opposite.  A number of Albanians have relatives in the States, and see the U.S.
as a friend and an escape from an earlier life.  &quot;You are German?&quot; a
cafe owner asks curiously.  &quot;No, American,&quot; was the response.  He
threw up his hands and grinned; then refused to accept payment for an ice-cream
cone.  Vendors at a crude market near Tirana's aged-looking train station were
also excited to receive American visitors, forcing apples into our hands.  There
is a remarkable spirit and optimism among Albanians, even the older citizens who
lived for so long in such a repressive environment.  At the central market on
Boulevard Deshmorit e Kombit, Tirana's main drag, an elderly man in clothes that
appeared to pre-date his own birth was tearing out the pages of a book.  He
rolled up the pages to create makeshift containers for the peanuts he was
selling.  Other pages he threw onto the burned-out grass.  &quot;Enver Hoxha,&quot;
he explained, invoking the hated name of Albania's onetime dictator and pointing
to the book -- apparently about Hoxha or written by him.  The man pointed to the
pages, then ripped them out gleefully.  &quot;Enver Hoxha,&quot; he said again.<BR></P>
<P>In nearby Durres, Albania's main port, locals are capitalizing on the change
in the country and the economy.  Boats go frequently between Durres and Italy,
carrying goods and travelers.  A shopping mall is also in the works for the
beach town, a development that would have been unthinkable five years ago.  The
beachside villa that Hoxha stayed in on vacations is now empty, opened
occasionally for visiting dignitaries.  Vacationers can enjoy Durres's sandy
shores, which are pleasant and conveniently close to Tirana, though not as
popular as Albania's southern beaches.  &quot;All Albania has changed,&quot;
said Durres cafe-owner Avni Beojri.  &quot;Before, the regime made it very
difficult, because if I spoke about the government, I would be in prison.&quot; 
Beojri's children, like many young Albanians, hope to move elsewhere in Europe
or to the States, where they see more opportunity.  &quot;Jobs are a very big
problem because of the new economy.  After three or four years, it will work,
but now, it's difficult, because wages are small,&quot; Beojri said.<BR></P>
<P>But Beojri wants to stay in his hometown of Durres, the nation's main port. 
&quot;For me, the life is in our land,&quot; he said.  For the visitor, life is
also easier now.  There are reasonably-priced as well as luxury hotels, complete
with the indoor plumbing, electricity and other amenities lacking in many
Albanian homes.  Notably, some hotels charge more for foreigners than they do
for Albanians, but the price is still cheap.<BR></P>
<P>Getting to Albania is getting easier as well.  Until 1988 the number of
tourists was tightly controlled, and those few were permitted the see the
country only with a government escort, said Ilir Toci, a travel consultant with
Albtourist.  In 1988 the state began bringing tourists from Dubrovnik, a coastal
Croatian (then Yugoslav) town.   In 1989 more tourists were allowed in, and the
door was opened completely in 1991.  Last year Albtourist alone handled 8,000
clients, including day-trippers from the nearby Greek island of Corfu. <BR></P>
<P>The boat from Italy is the easiest route.   Twelve airlines fly into Tirana
airport -- although you may, like tourist Mary Agocs,  have to wait for workers
to clear the runway of goats before landing.  The longest, but perhaps most
visually spectacular way to arrive in Tirana is by bus from Skopje, Macedonia
(for political reasons, you cannot come directly from Serbia). The nine-hour bus
ride provides a breath-taking vista of the country, including peaceful,
ultra-blue Lake Ohrid, a favorite new vacation spot for Albanians and
Macedonians, who share the border lake.  The bus winds precariously around
mountains, stopping for the occasional goat or donkey before dropping travelers
off near Tirana's bustling Scanderbeg Square.<BR></P>
<P>For the tourist, Albania's advantages are also its disadvantages.  Only a
few hotels and restaurants are up to Western standards.  But the prices are
cheap and the nation's tourist agencies make up in enthusiasm and effort what
they lack in services.  Albania Travel and Tours offers one-to-fourteen-day
excursions to other areas of tourist interest in Albania, including several
archeological sites and small, traditional villages in the north of Albania. 
Trekking and hunting trips are also available, as are trips to Lake Ohrid.
Prices in Albania are low for the foreigner, with the most expensive, 2-week
excursion trip adding up to $540 per person, including lodging and most meals. 
But Albania's greatest tourist hope is its unspoiled southern coast, with its
sandy beaches along the blue Ionian Sea.  In the coastal town of Dhermi,
visitors can stay at a hotel that was once reserved by the communists as an
incentive vacation spot for workers.  Still, Albania's fledgling tourist
industry cannot yet offer the variety, number and quality of accommodations
available, for example, in neighboring Italy.<BR></P>
<P>The Albanian government is quickly moving to improve standards, government
officials say.  They also are working to open several old military airports for
commercial use, making trips beyond Tirana more convenient.  &quot;For people
who want to see something unusual, this is a curiosity,&quot; said Ilir Toci, a
travel consultant.  &quot;And services get better every day.&quot;  &#164;<BR></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Susan Milligan is a freelance writer.</FONT></EM></P>
<HR><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/pport2.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="349" HEIGHT="156">
<HR>
<H2>Visiting Albania<BR></H2>
<P><STRONG><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">New Business Hotels in Tirana, Village-Stays
in the Countryside</FONT></STRONG><BR></P>
<P>Two new business-class hotels have opened in the Albanian capital of Tirana
to cater to the country's growing Western tourism, according to recent articles
in Travel Weekly.  The Tirana International, centrally located on Scanderbeg
Square, was extensively refurbished in its conversion from a state-run high-rise
to a 161-room, superior first-class hotel, and reopened in March 1995 for
operation by Italian-based Turin Hotels International.  The <B>Europark Hotel</B>,
a more deluxe 138-room property managed by the Austrian firm Rogner
International, is newly built and opened in August 1995.  Both hotels feature
rooms with private bath, direct-dial telephones, satellite TV, air conditioning,
and minibars, with the Europark additionally offering swimming, tennis, and
conference facilities.  Rates at the Tirana International are $120 single, $140
double, and $180 for suites; the Europark charges $150 single, $190 double, and
$220 for suites.  With Albanian tourism still in an early stage of development
the hotels have largely been occupied by businesspersons to date, but their
managers are eager to welcome leisure travelers as well.  Bookings at either
property can be made directly or through travel agents; contact Utell
International, <B>800-44-UTELL</B>.<BR></P>
<P><I>Travel Weekly</I> also reports that <B>Ecotourism Ltd</B>., a British
tour operator, will be organizing a village tourism project this summer which
will allow travelers to book stays in converted private homes in the village of
Upper Qeparo, which overlooks the Ionian seacoast from atop a 1,000 foot rocky
cliff.  Although the project will have only four rooms available this summer,
they hope to expand to fourteen by next year.  The room rentals will be located
in three refurbished houses, which are being brought up to modern interior
standards while keeping their original stone exteriors; each twin room will
offer private bath and access to a shared swimming pool. Ecotourism Ltd. plans
to organize complete itineraries for travelers that combine a week in Corfu with
a week in southern Albania, and will include transport by ferry and automobile
from Corfu to Upper Qeparo.  Ecotourism Ltd. specializes in creating
environmentally-friendly tour programs, with an emphasis on demonstrating that
development of tourism can co-exist with maintaining local heritage,
architecture, and tradition.  For further information, contact <B>Ecotourism
Ltd., 4 the Lancasters, 162-164 Fulham Palace Road, London W6 9ER, United
Kingdom</B>; telephone (011) 44-181-758-5883, fax (011) 44-181-748-5033.  They
can also be reached by e-mail at <B><A HREF="mailto:ecotourism@gn.apc.org">ecotourism@gn.apc.org</A></B>.
&#164;<BR></P>
