<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<H1>Cruising the English Chunnel</H1>
<P><I>By Bosley Wilder</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>But Where are the Fish?</I><BR></H2>
<P>Europe's biggest new travel sensation, the splendid engineering feat known
as The Chunnel, finally opened on November 21, 1994, after years of negotiations
and progress, and some $15 billion.<BR></P>
<P>The sophisticated Eurostar, gliding along at up to 186 mph, transports
passengers between Paris and London in three hours.  The London-to-Brussels run
takes fifteen minutes longer.   Twenty minutes of that time are spent in the
tunnel itself beneath the English Channel, a crossing remembered by the more
seasoned travelers among us as a chug-and-splash overnight by train and ferry
between Folkestone and Calais.<BR></P>
<P>Not so improbably, this  international train with its state-of-the-art
trilingual operating system still experiences some glitches.  Adapting to the
various operating conditions of three different national railway designs and the
Tunnel, the system must adjust to three types of electrical power supply, from
the third rail on the southern UK rail system, to new, overhead high-speed lines
in France and Belgium, to the conventional lines north of London.  In the
train's first year and a half of operation, the sleight of hand needed to
perform these shifts has not been perfect -- with the result that taking the
Chunnel to get to a pressing  appointment can occasionally be a bit like playing
roulette, though here the odds are in one's favor.<BR></P>
<P>Eurostar's London head office explains that out of 1,000 runs each month, &quot;one
or two&quot; are apt to be delayed from five minutes to over an hour on entering
or leaving the Tunnel, owing to the  required changeover from electronic to
manual operation at the switchpoints. (A computer-age version of the old
streetcar trolley  conductor having to stop at certain intersections to switch
overhead electric power lines?)  Eurostar has been beset by a few other
problems, like last year's French railroaders' three-week strike. But the
majority of travelers -- and there have been over 3,000,000 on Eurostar since
its initial run -- still find a good journey.<BR></P>
<P>The other day, having lingered over the magnificent vaulted glass ceiling of
that huge and most beautiful of railway stations, Paris' Gare de Nord, I
descended the stairs to board the great Eurostar.   My first view of the sleek,
handsome, yellow, bullet-nosed engine that was about to whiz  us to London in
the coming three hours was reassuring.   A Pierre Balmain-suited hostess helped
me find my seat.  I arranged myself comfortably, and smiled at the seat
companion opposite.  Seats are arranged face-to-face; two on two in tourist
class, two on one in first class.  There is plenty of leg room, with a small
table convenient for snacks or newspapers between the passengers.  The resulting
comfort merits high marks over airplane accomodations.  At 5:02 p.m. the train
slid silently out of the station.  The quiet and efficiency of the train made it
hard to believe one was moving as we rolled through the outskirts of Paris. 
Tall buildings seemed to merge, poplar trees slipped by.  Barely five minutes
out of the station, passengers looked incredulously out of the windows to a
rural scene of cows and pasture.  What happened to the sprawling suburbs of
Paris?  And all those small towns one chugged through  on the old <I>chemin de
fer</I> of the past?  Picardy flashed by in a sort of virtual-visual Doppler
effect.  The <I>zooomssst!</I> of a train passing in the opposite direction
lasted barely a few seconds.  I got up and moved around the train, checking out
the amenities.<BR></P>
<P>Food vendors moved carts through the coaches, with attractive-looking
sandwiches, fresh pastries, and drinks.  In first class, meals are served at the
seats.  The train carries telephones, changing rooms, and two bar cars.  Two
areas of the train are especially available to handicapped passengers, with
narrow wheelchairs provided that can easily navigate the aisles and washrooms. 
About one quarter of the train's 794 seats are reserved for smokers.  Storage
shelves at each end of a coach as well as overhead compartments provide ample
storage space for baggage.<BR></P>
<P>As Eurostar approaches the tunnel, it continues silently over the tracks,
with no sense of that &quot;swoosh&quot; experienced on entering a tunnel by
conventional train; you could be sitting at home playing cards.  We were ten
minutes &quot;into the Tunnel&quot; when a Customs Inspector came through our
coach, and nothing but his words indicated that we had descended to between 30
and 50 meters under the seabed, in a 7.6-meter tube of a tunnel, and that
somewhere out there fish were swimming over our heads!  About ten minutes later,
over the loudspeaker came an amiable British accent:  &quot;This is your Pursar.
 Welcome to Great Britain!&quot;  And we swept into London's ultra-modern
Waterloo International Station, as smoothly, as effortlessly  as a lark.  My
watch read 7:07 p.m.  Taking into account the hour's difference between  France
and England, the train ride between the two of the world's great cities had
taken three hours and two  minutes.  &#164; <BR></P>
<HR> 
<H2>Traveler Information:</H2>
<P>Eurostar's Paris-London run has 11 services daily in each direction (up from
seven, a year ago); the London-Brussels run, six.  The line carries around
40,000 passengers a week.  At the present time, fares on the London-Paris
Eurostar and the London-Brussels runs are identical.  First class is $154
one-way. The first class price includes a four-course airplane-style meal,
complete with champagne and/or other beverage.  Double the fares for all round
trips.  Second class is $123.  Discovery Special, which requires a 14-day
advance and is not refundable, is $75.  Group rates are available. Tel:
800-387-6782.  A good savings suggestion for the traveller wishing to ride the
Chunnel one way and fly one way between London and Paris:  British Midland, the
second largest air carrier in the United Kingdom (and a United Airlines Mileage
Plus partner), offers a special one-way fare of $109 for passengers who are
non-European citizens.  Tickets must be purchased in the U.S. Tel: 800-366-6387.
</P>
<HR>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rpex3.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" ISMAP="ISMAP">
<P>Visit <B>Rail Pass Express</B> on the World Wide Web at
<A HREF="http://www.eurail.com/">http://www.eurail.com</A></P>
