<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Frankfurt  / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Germany / Frankfurt / K&ouml;ln /
Cologne Cathedral / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>Frankfurt</H2>
<P><BR>
<I>by Susan Ladika</I><BR></P>
<P><B>For most Americans, a visit to Frankfurt simply means flying into the
airport</B>, renting a car, and speeding down the Autobahn into the German
countryside.  On first sight, Frankfurt is a city filled with chrome and glass
bank buildings, but dig a little deeper to discover its charms. While it lacks
the beauty of a Vienna or a Munich, this city straddling the Main River has
labored to refurbish or reconstruct its best-known historical landmarks.   
<BR></P>
<P>The Romer, first built in 1305, again houses plush offices of city hall. 
Hauptwache, a guard station erected in 1729, now houses a cafe.  Kaiserdom, its
most imposing cathedral, was renovated in time for the city's 1200th anniversary
celebration in 1994.  More recently, Frankfurt has earned its reputation as the
financial capital of Germany.  The city houses the central banks for both  the
European Union and for Germany, along with more than 400 banks from around the
globe.  The multitude of banks and their towering skyscrapers give rise to the
city's two nicknames:  Bankfurt and Mainhattan.  
<BR></P>
<P>The city's reputation as a modern-day financial center comes as no surprise.
 As early as the 1200s, Frankfurt was gaining  prominence as a site for German
trade fairs.  And even today, the bulk of Frankfurt's visitors come on business
trips.  Nonetheless, Frankfurt keeps an eye to its past.  The key symbol of the
city's history is Romerberg, a square in the heart of the old city.  The
square's most distinctive feature is three pinkish buildings, collectively known
as the Romer, which were built in 1305.  A century later, they became the city
hall.  But a barrage of Allied bombs in 1944 reduced the Romer&#151;along with
much of Frankfurt&#151;to rubble.  Following WW II, Frankfurt had to be rebuilt
almost from the ground up, and many modern buildings were thrown together to
fill the housing gap.  
<BR></P>
<P>But the city took great pains to restore the Romer to its former glory. 
Later, half-timbered houses were constructed on the other side of the square. 
Cafes dishing up traditional German fare fill many of the buildings, and tables
are set outside in summertime for diners to sit out under the warming sun.  Just
off Romerberg is Kaiserdom, built on foundations dating from 852.  Emperors have
been crowned at the pinkish-toned cathedral since the mid-1500s, and visitors
can climb the stairs in the adjacent tower for a bird's-eye view of the city.  
A few blocks from Romerberg is another famous Frankfurt church, Paulskirche. 
It's considered the cradle of German democracy because the first elected
parliament met within its walls in 1848.  Nearby is Goethehaus, a tribute to
Johann Wolfgang Goethe, the country's best-known poet.  The building was
destroyed during World War II, but has been meticulously reconstructed, and
filled with possessions from the poet and his family. 
<BR></P>
<P>Frankfurt also celebrates it culture with a string of museums dotting the
southern bank of the Main River.  Among them is the Stadel Museum, whose
collection contains paintings from most European schools and periods.  The
Museum of Applied Arts houses 30,000 handicrafts produced in Europe and Asia
throughout the centuries.  Frankfurt features an abundance of theater troupes
and concert venues.  The classical Alte Oper, refurbished in 1980, is home not
only to operas, but to rock shows and conferences.  
<BR></P>
<P>For visitors longing for the outdoors after a night in the confines of an
airplane or a day of museums, the city offers the Frankfurt Zoo and the
Palmengarten.  At the zoo, most animals are housed in areas that resemble their
natural habitat.  One section lets visitors view the nocturnal habits of small
animals.  The Palmengarten contains a massive greenhouse full of tropical and
semi-tropical plants, while native European flora dot the grounds.  For that
special beer stein to bring home for  Dad, or the latest in European fashion,
Frankfurt has an abundance of shops.  But plan your excursion early in the day;
shops  generally close at 6pm everyday but Thursday, and by 2pm Saturdays.  On
Schillerstrasse and Goethestrasse, exclusive boutiques like Tiffany and Hermes
hug the sidewalks, while more reasonably priced merchandise (at least by
European  standards) can be found along the Zeil, one of the busiest shopping
streets in Europe.  
<BR></P>
<P>For bargain shoppers, try the flea market in Sachsenhausen on Saturday
morning.  Everything from antiques to junk can be found among the jumble on the
south side of the Main River.   The Sachsenhausen section of the city also is
known for its German gemutlichkeit.  The local apple wine, along with boisterous
conversation, flows freely around the table, accompanying such specialities as
sausage, pretzels and sauerkraut.  
<BR></P>
<P>Frankfurt also is an ideal base for day trips into the countryside.  One of
the area's oldest sites is Saalburg, a fort reconstructed on Roman ruins dating
from the first entury. Ancient Roman artifacts are on display, and visitors can
walk the walls of the ruins.  
<BR></P>
<P>Nearby is Hessenpark, an open-air museum full of buildings from the region. 
If an old, historic structure winds up in the path of the wrecking ball, it is
carefully dismantled, trucked to the park, and reassembled like an over-sized
jigsaw puzzle.  The buildings are grouped together in villages representing
various regions, and drugstores and schools are equipped as they may  have been
in centuries gone by.  More contemporary history can be found in Bad Homburg, a
spa town discovered by the Romans and later developed as a place for European
aristocracy in the 1800s.  As tribute, the King of Siam built a temple in the
town's Kurpark, and Czar Nicholas I constructed a Russian chapel nearby.  Two
complexes offering swimming and a fitness center also are located in the park,
and visitors arrive by the busload to play blackjack, baccarat and roulette at
the casino.   
<BR></P>
<P>Then it's time to get in that rental car and zip off down the Autobahn, to
the next quaint German town.  &#164;  </P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Cologne Cathedral</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B>(Excerpt from &quot;A Satchel Guide to Europe&quot;,
1880)</B></FONT></I><BR></P>
<P><B>Cologne</B>, or <B>K&ouml;ln, </B>is 43 miles by rail from
Aix-la-Chapelle.  This famous city was originally the chief town of the ancient
Ubii, the Oppidum Ubiorum of Tacitus; but it became known as Colonia Agrippina
from A. D 51, when Agrippina, who was born here while her father  Germanicus
held command in the district, induced her husband Claudius to send a colony of
veteran soldiers to the place.  It afterwards became the chief town of Germania
Secunda or Inferior.  The Roman remains consist of what is called the
Pfaffenport, supposed to be the old Porta Claudia, and some fragments of the
walls.  Many statues, sarcophagi, mosaic pavements, etc., have been found in and
about the city. 
<BR></P>
<P>The Cathedral is the glory of the modern city, and when completed will be
the grandest Gothic church in the world.  It was begun in 1248, but the work
went on slowly, and the choir was not consecrated until 1322.  Little more was
accomplished after that date, and nothing from the be ginping of the 16th
century until our own day.  In 1795 the French used the building as a hay
magazine, and stole the lead from the roof.  In 1816 its restoratlon was begun
under the auspices of the King of Prussia, and since then more than &#163;400,000
(or two millions of dollars) has been expended upon it.  The entire structure is
now completed with the exception of the towers, which are to be more than 500
feet high. The interior, according to Baedeker, is 448 feet long and 49 broad,
or 249' through the transepts; and the choir is 49 feet high.  The magnificent
south portal (234 feet high), finished in 1859, cost &#163;105,000, or more than
half a million dollars.  The stained glass in the windows of the north aisle
(1508-9) is much admired.  It may be compared with the Munich glass in the south
aisle, presented by Louis of Bavaria in 1848.
<BR></P>
<P>In the choir the carved stalls and the statues on the pedestals attached to
the pillars are of the 14th century.  The Chapel of the Three Kings contains a
gorgeous shrine of the latter part of the 12th century, enclosing the bones of
the Magi, brought by the Empress Helena from Constantinople to Milan, and
afterwards transferred by Frederick Barbarossa to Cologne.  A fee is charged for
showing this shrine and the treasury, which contains a silver shrine and other
costly relics.  There is a separate fee for admission to the choir and choir
chapels (open without charge at certain hours); also for the choir gallery, the
outer gallery, and central tower.  These  last should be visited for the views
of the interior of the church, and of the city and the surrounding country,
which they afford.  &#164;   
</P>
<P><I>The  piece above continues our occasional excerpts from &quot;A Satchel
Guide to Europe&quot;, a book published in Boston in 1880 for the benefit of
aristocratic Americans embarking on the Grand Tour.  As always with these
excerpts, remember that the writer's words of advice were written over a century
ago, and one or two things may have changed!  The Cathedral, however,  today
completed (and restored from the brutal damage of two wars since the Satchel
Guide writer viewed it), is still quite magnificent.  The Cathedral is almost
immediately adjacent to the main rail station; if your rail plans take you
through Cologne, as many routes do, check the schedules to see if you can stop
over for an hour or so.  It's worth it.
</I></P>
