<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Notes from Paris</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">September / October 1996</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2>Europe Writes...</H2>
<P><I>Notes from Paris by David Whitehouse</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Duty Free: The Party&#146;s Over
<BR></B><BR> The European Commission is taking an increasingly hard line on
duty-free purchases made by travelers within the EU, which it believes
constitute a distortion of the European single market.  EU finance ministers
voted in 1992 to phase out the tax concession, but allowed a 6-year transition
period until June 1999.  The single market was created in 1992 to try to create
a level playing field for free trade across the continent.  Mario Monti, the
commissioner for the single market, says the long duty-free transition period
has craeted a situation which is &#147;far from satisfactory.&#148;  Monti said
the removal of frontier controls as a result of the Schengen agreement had made
it harder to monitor the actual level of purchases made.  The current duty-free
ceiling per passenger stands at ECU90 ($115) for journeys between member states.
 Responsibility for enforcing these limits has been passed on to retailers and
travel authorities -- who naturally aim to sell as much as possible. 
</P>
<P>In a recent report unanimously accepted by his fellow commissioners, Monti
argues that duty-free &#147;can produce distortions of competition not only
regarding tax-paid goods, but especially between different means of transport. 
For example, Eurotunnel, which operates the Channel Tunnel, is angry that it may
not offer duty-free goods while competing services can. 
</P>
<P>Monti firmly rejected any extension of duty-free beyond 1999, and criticized
member states as being poorly prepared for the switch.  The International Duty
Free Confederation said it would continue to press for a reprieve.  It argues
that tax-free trade increases employment and means cheaper tickets for
travelers.  But real political capital has been invested in the full
implementation of the single European market, so it looks like travelers should
load up while they have the chance. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Eurostar in Overdrive<BR><BR></B>  Passenger traffic on the Eurostar
train which links London, Paris, and Brussels has surged by 40% since its
acquisition by the private London and Continental Railways (LCR) consortium in
April.  The service is already close to matching in 1996 the 1995 passenger
total of 3.5 million, and has a final target for this year of 6.5 million. 
Continued rapid progress of this sort is absolutely essential.  The service has
been heavily loss-making since its launch in 12994.  </P>
<P>LCR, which includes the Virgin Group and National Express, must push
passenger traffic to 10 million per year if it is to start making money and
achieve a successful stock flotation of Eurostar.  Eurostar&#146;s early
performance was hurt by overpricing.  Tickets cost &#163;99 when the service was
launched -- too high to achieve genuine mass-market penetration.  Eurostar has
tacitly acknowledged this and the lowest economy fares have gradually come down
to around &#163;50. 
</P>
<P>The Brussels link remains the clear underperformer with trains on average
only 40% full.  The Belgian capital cannot realistically compete with London and
Paris in terms of tourist pull.  But the city enjoys a crucial, and still
growing, role as the capital of the European Union.  The answer may be to more
clearly differentiate the Brussels leg of the network as dedicated to the needs
of the business traveler.<BR></P> 
<P><B>EU Confidence Vote for Emerald Isle<BR><BR></B>  Rapidly escalating
sectarian tensions may be threatening the rebuilding of tourism in Northern
Ireland.  But the European Union Commission has given a vote of confidence to
the Emerald Isle&#146;s tourist assets by approving a package of aid worth &#163;283
million in support of a range of transport and environmental projects south of
the border in the Republic of Ireland.  A grant of &#163;69.1 million is being
set aside to fund the extension of Dublin&#146;s rapid transit rail line, and to
improve track and signaling on the railways.  &#163;93.6 million is to be spend
on five road-building projects in the counties of Kildare, Cork, Louth, and
Wexford.  The aim is to ease traffic congestion and improve the environment. 
Funded conservation projects include the protection of the Lough Ree on the
River Shannon, and the improvement of water quality in the River Suir.  The
extension of the sewer network in Killarney is seen as essential to help cope
with a boom in tourism.<BR></P>
<P><I>David Whitehouse is a journalist working in Paris for a major
international news service. 
</I></P>
<HR>
