<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Paris / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Rue Cler</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>Can a Street Be a Sight?  by Rick Steves</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Can a street be a sight by Rick Steves--><BR></P>
<P><B>Greatness is a matter of contrast.</B>  A warm shower is great after a
cold one.  A noble city is royal after Zurich.  A cozy street is a slow-motion
reunion of lovers when imbedded in the heart of Paris. 
<BR></P>
<P>Calling Paris grand is like calling God smart.  Even the M&eacute;tro stop
for my village home in Paris is grand: it&#146;s Ecole Militaire.  Ascending
from the M&eacute;tro, the French Annapolis, with a front yard made for breaking
in jackboots (1,000 at a  time), is a holler away.  But turn your back on that
and you have Flo&#146;s, a patisserie filled with the kind of food you giftwrap.
 And around the corner is <I>rue Cler</I>. 
<BR></P>
<P>Walking down rue Cler makes me feel like I must have been a poodle in a
previous life.  It&#146;s a cobbled pedestrian street lined with shops run by
people who&#146;ve found their niche...boys who grew up on quiche.  The crepe
man proudly makes crepes like he just figured it out.  Aproned fruit stall
attendants coax doll-like girls into trying their cherries.  Ladies, after a
lifetime of  baguette munching, debate the merits of the street&#146;s rival
boulangeries.  And young girls look chic in just-out-of-bed hair.  
<BR></P>
<P>And proudly sporting its one star, as if that&#146;s all there was, the
Grand Hotel Leveque pries apart a cafe and a cheese stall just  wide enough to
plant its front door.  Hotel Leveque is rand in the sense of grand old days. 
The cackle of Mimi, the  receptionist who is endlessly entertained by her
inability to understand her English-speaking guests and the thin soprano of  the
singing maid (who bicycles to work when city workers, who make double her wage
with no need to sweat, strike in  order to get free parking) waft up the
courtyard that provides air but no view to half the rooms.  After long spirals
of museum-going, sightseers pull ever-heavier knees up spirals or stairs. 
Yesterday&#146;s sheets line the halls  in rumpled white mounds but my bed&#151;straight
and tidy below its Lincoln log pillow&#151;says recline. 
<BR></P>
<P>Surveying Paris from my 4th floor window, Mansart&#146;s town survives. Only
the churches and the Biffel Tower exceed the six  story code.  Buildings fill
the city like waffle mix&#151;done just about right.  Below me is village Paris,
my market street, rue Cler.<BR></P>
<P>Across from Hotel Leveque, above the Boeuf-Cheval-Triperie awning, a golden
horse head surveys the crowds.  He knows  those with day bags, fanny packs and
cameras eat the boeuf.  Those toting baguettes, dogs and baby strollers eat the
horse  and tripe.  Those with less than that wait for the end-of-the-day &#147;food
dump&#148; as shops fill the rue Cler trash cans with no-longer-fresh food.  
<BR></P>
<P>Joining two beefeaters at a cafe, they tell me they conceived their daughter
here two years ago and named her Paris.  Now they&#146;re back, their first time
away from the child, buying souvenirs with their baby&#146;s name on them. 
Connoisseurs of good  living keep rue Cler in business.  Flower shops add a
fragrance to the breeze.  A man with working class hands cradles a  bouquet and
a baguette in his arms.  Another greedily hurries home with his tart.  &#147;Pear
and chocolate&#148; he giggles. &#147;The  <I>vieux Corse</I> cheese can only
be found on rue Cler,&#148; another local brags.  Every shop is jammed save the
health food store. Even bums drink a better wine on rue Cler.  &#164;<BR></P>
<P><I>This piece originally appeared in Rick Steve&#146;s highly entertaining
<B>Europe Through the Back Door Newsletter</B> (Oct. 1996).  For a free
subscription to the quarterly, 64-page newsletter&#151;which offers a number of
other nifty essays plus information on the well known travel guru&#146;s books &amp;
escorted tours&#151;write to <B>Europe Through the Back Door, 120 Fourth Ave.
North, PO Box 2009, Edmonds WA 98020-2009</B>.  You can also fax (206) 771-8333,
call (206) 771-8303, or visit them on the Web at
<A HREF="http://www.ricksteves.com/"><B>www.ricksteves.com</B></A>.
</I></P>
