<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Europe Write; notes
from Paris by David Whitehouse / Airlines / British Airways / traffic in London
/ Travel in Europe / </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>Europe Writes...</H2>
<P><BR><I><B>Notes from Paris by David Whitehouse</B></I><BR></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><I>Fighting for Libert&eacute;</I></FONT>
</B><BR></P>
<P>A fierce battle between Britain and France has broken out over the fate of
Air Libert&eacute;, a private French airline which went into receivership at the
end of September.  British Airways (BA) has set its sights on acquiring the
concern.  BA already has a stake in the French market through its control of the
TAT airline.  Libert&eacute; and TAT together would constitute the largest
airline presence in France after Air France.  BA is not particularly interested
in Libert&eacute;'s equipment or services, but its precious landing slots at
airports are a different proposition.  </P>
<P>If BA is successful, its new group would control almost 25% of the 250,000
slots at Orly Airport.  These plans are a source of concern for the French
government.  They would prefer to see a takeover of Libert&eacute; by the French
regional airline Air d'Outre Mer (AOM).  But there is a big snag.  AOM is owned
by Credit Lyonnais, the struggling French state-owned bank which the government
has bailed out with public money.  Such aid can only be authorized after careful
scrutiny by the European Commission in Brussels; BA argues that conditions
governing the subsidies to Credit Lyonnais will be broken if the bank takes a
private airline under its wing.  An alternative French escape route may be
available.  Jacques Maillot, head of the French travel business Novelles Fronti&egrave;res,
has confirmed that he wants to buy both Libert&eacute; and AOM to forge a new,
privately-owned group.  Maillot also heads the Corsair charter airline. 
</P>
<HR>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><I>Breaking the Gridlock</I></FONT></B><BR></P>
<P>The difficulties which tourists encounter in trying to navigate their way
around the car-dominated environment of London are legendary.  An ambitious plan
to route traffic through a series of deep underground tunnels has already been
touted (see <A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/ewrites4.htm">EV #3, &quot;Europe
Writes...&quot;</A>.   Now, plans to pedestrianize parts of Trafalgar and
Parliament Squares are moving back into the spotlight, with a feasibility study
to receive funding support from the National Lottery, according to a report in
<I>The Independent</I>, a British newspaper.<BR></P>
<P>The most likely schemes include pedestrianizing the north side of Trafalgar
Square, next to the National Gallery, which would create a pedestrian zone
between Leicester Square and Trafalgar Square.  Pedestrianizing the south side
of Parliament Square, next to the Palace of Westminster, is also a possibility. 
The report will also look at improving pedestrian access around Charing Cross
station, and at speeding bus times in the area.
<BR></P>
<P>At peak times in central London, traffic moves no faster than did the horse
and cart, and action is urgently needed.  Sir Jocelyn Stevens, chairman of
English Heritage, says:  &quot;Westminster Abbey, the Palace of Westminster, and
St. Margaret's Church are designated a World Heritage site, but the space
between them is prominently occupied by cars.&quot;  Malcom Haxby, associate
director of planning at Westminster Council, says:  &quot;In the past, schemes
have foundered on the problems of worries about increased traffic jams.  Now we
are looking at it the other way round.  We're going to say, here's a good
scheme, let's implement it, and then sort out what to do with the cars.&quot; 
Lottery funding will provide half the cost of the &#163;250,000 report, which
will take a year to complete and will be called &quot;World Squares for All.&quot;
 &#164;
<BR></P>
<P><I>David Whitehouse is a journalist working in Paris.</I> </P>
<HR>
