<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>Plymouth</H1>
<P><I>by Nick Gregory</I></P>
<HR>
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I>A City of Britain's South Devon Coast</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Just two minutes' walk from the railway station, the view from North Cross
along the dip and rise of Armada Way, a pedestrian boulevard mosaiced with
rockeries and artificial streams, reveals the heights of the Hoe. The view is
dominated by the candy-striped pinnacle of Smeatons Tower, and the lush green of
the lawns and the flower arrays that lead to it -- for Plymouth is a former
winner of Britains &quot;City in Bloom&quot; competition -- contrast with the
hustle of a city centre on a summer afternoon.<BR></P>
<P>The train journey into the city passes spectacular scenery along the coast
between Dawlish and Teignmouth, where red cliffs tower over the train as
breakers crash onto beaches segregated by the more resistant rocky outcrops. 
These had to be tunneled through by Isambard Kingdom Brunel, as he designed his
Great Western Railway to meet the fast Clippers from the Indies and the East.  A
little further on the route climbs and drops steeply over the banks of the South
Hams, rolling green dairy pasture to the left and the heathered tors of Dartmoor
to the right.  The train continues through the medieval castled town of Totnes,
where steamer trips can be taken down the river Dart to the picturesque harbour
of Dartmouth.  Passing the Plym estuary with its mud flats and wading birds, the
traveler arrives in the city a little under four hours from London's Paddington
station. <BR></P>
<P>The downtown area of Plymouth was completely razed during heavy bombing by
the German Luftwaffe in 1941and thus saw reconstruction during the 1950s and 60s
-- a time when square and concrete seemed like a good idea. Within the past ten
years, however, pedestrianisation of the main commercial areas and some
extensive landscaping has transformed the centre and added considerable
character.  The huge sun-dial at the intersection of Armada Way and New George
Street is a centerpiece to the refurbishment and has become the unofficial
meeting and busking point for the city's inhabitants.  A little farther down,
New George street is the entrance to the covered market, which exudes the
vitality of a trade market with the concern for appearance of a quality flea
market.  Fruit, vegetables, fish, meat and a plethora of other goods can be
found in this glass-domed Aladin's cave.  It is open daily except for Sundays.<BR></P>
<P>Up the hill from the dominating tower of the Civic Centre, past the large
hotels and the anchor from the World War Two aircraft carrier <I>Ark Royal</I>,
open space returns with a commanding view from the Hoe Promenade over Plymouth
Sound, the large natural harbour nestled between headlands at Rame in southeast
Cornwall and Bovisand, which houses fortifications left from the Napoleonic wars
and is now home to a world- renowned diving centre.<BR></P>
<P>The Smeatons lighthouse tower, far and away Plymouth's most photographed
feature, is no longer used for the purpose of guiding shipping away from the
famous &quot;wrecking rocks&quot; of the westcountry; but for a small fee it
serves as an excellent viewing gallery for the surroundings, including (on a
clear day) the Eddystone Rock light, fourteen miles to the south west, and the
former situation for the Smeatons Tower (1759-1882). Directly in front is
Drake's Island (St Nicholas Island), which was used once as a fortification, and
later as an adventure sports centre, before being sold to a private buyer.<BR></P>
<P>Within a few minutes' walk from the Tower is the Plymouth Dome, a visitor
and info centre with interactive displays depicting life in the city through the
ages.  A viewing area offers telescopes for watching the shipping in the port,
with computer screens giving details of the ships present.  Carefully crafted
displays recreate Elizabethan scenes around the viewer and show the old pre-war
city in full sight, sound and smell.<BR></P>
<P>A short walk around the seafront, past the Aquarium and Citadel, is the
Barbican, the city's oldest quarter with many buildings appearing as they would
have been in the times of Drake, Raleigh and the Pilgrim Fathers.  Narrow
cobbled streets criss-cross in front of Sutton pool and the working fish market.
 The Elizabethan houses are filled with curio shops and antiques, and cheap
eating can be had at the many &quot;fish and chip&quot; shops, which are
supplied fresh from the quay.  Elizabethan House, in the rather inappropriately
named New Street, is open to visitors and is furnished as it was four hundred
years ago.<BR></P>
<P>A plaque by some rather ordinary-looking steps commemorates the departure of
the Pilgrim Fathers from this point as they escaped  persecution and sailed for
the New World. These steps are, of course, the &quot;Mayflower Steps.&quot; 
Other famous sailings from the port include Drake's global circumnavigation and
Darwin's travels of evolutionary discovery aboard the Beagle.  A number of good
pubs can be found close by with names reminiscent of such a history.  They
provide an excellent oppurtunity to sit and take in the scenery and atmosphere,
whether it be sunny or blowing a strong prevailing &quot;sou'westerly.&quot; 
<BR></P>
<P>In Southside Street the working Plymouth Gin distillery is still operating
and open as a pub, with the stills visible through clear screens from the
upstairs bar.<BR></P>
<P>Being a port of some history, Plymouth has a famous nightlife.  Although
much tamed these days, it was once compared to Hamburg's Reeperbahn and is still
lively, with numerous clubs and pubs dotted along the eastern end of Union
Street and a nationally renowned theatre on Royal Parade. With the decline of
the naval base, once the largest in Europe, neon signs and thumping music no
longer draw so large a military clientele; so the atmosphere is more up-market. 
The pubs and restaurants of the Barbican area offer an alternative to the gaudy
brilliance of Union Street, though they can become quite crowded on weekends.<BR></P>
<P>For sightseeing, open-topped buses run in the summer around the circuit of
tourist attractions, starting at the info kiosk on the intersection of Armada
Way and Royal Parade.  There are also boat trips from the Barbican and Hoe to
the dockyard, past the art deco swimming pool at Tinside and William of Orange's
victualling yard; longer trips can be taken up the river Tamar to the Royal
Albert Bridge, built by Brunel to take his railway over the river and into
Cornwall, and on up to Calstock and the tin mine attraction at Morwellham Quay. 
These offer a pleasant voyage through some beautiful scenery and a relaxing
break from the city.<BR></P>
<P>One excellent outing on a summers day is to take the foot-passenger ferry
from Stonehouse (near the western end of Union Street) to Cremyll and the Mount
Edgecombe country park.  From there a walk of a few miles through woods and
along the seashore, overlooking the Sound to the fishing village of Cawsand,
leads you to an inexpensive bus back to the ferry.  There are numerous wonderful
spots to stop for a picnic and admire the view, although you must bring your own
food as the supplies available are limited to ice creams and confectionary. The
park contains numerous architectural follies and gazeboes, as well as abandoned
forts built to defend the home of the British Navy from the French.  Farther
around the coast, but beyond walking distance, is the bay at Whitsands and a
large sandy beach at the foot of high cliffs.  To the north of the city is
Dartmoor, with its heathered bleakness dotted with the cracked monoliths of
granite tors.  Shaggy ponies herd by the roadsides in the summer, begging like
wild urchins from the tourists who park to admire the scenery,.  Watch for the
distinctive profile of Brentor to the west, an extinct volcano with a church
built on top.  According to legend, it was constructed to stop the Devil from
emerging from the depths of Hell after his cloven-hoofed form was seen by a
villager.<BR></P>
<P>A bus ride from Plymouth Bretonside bus station can take you to one of
several destinations for hiking on the moors, including Princetown, whose famous
prison that dominates the town.  Those who are up to it and properly equiped
should remember to take an Ordnance Survey map, to follow an excellent walk that
heads south around South Hessary Tor and then east to Burrator and the
reservoir.  From there it is a short distance to Dousland or the prettier
village of Meavy for another bus.  Check out the ford just outside Meavy, but
don't try to drive through it except with the sturdiest of vehicles!<BR></P>
<P>East of the city is the village of Yealmpton, where the reputed thatched
home of  &quot;Ole Mother Hubbard&quot; of nursery-rhyme fame is to be found.  A
a mile or so further along the A379 is the entrance to the National Shire Horse
Centre, where these immense and beautiful animals can be seen in a working
environment, along with other attractions including a traditional blacksmith's
forge.  On the same bus route are the twin villages of Newton Ferrers and Noss
Mayo, which face each other over the steeply sheltered waters of the river Yealm
estuary.  Yachts sit on the calm waters moored where once small fishing boats
were, and the water front cottages are now the abode of the wealthy, but the
scenery is unalterably quaint, and perhaps sums up the South Devon coast in a
single visit -- if that is all you can spare.  &#164;<BR></P>
<HR>
<H2><B><I>Plymouth:  Fact File</I></B></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B><I>Getting there </I></B><BR></P>
<P><B>Rail:</B> There are regular trains from London and the north with good
connections to all major centres in the UK. From London Paddington about three
and a half hours and fares from L25 APEX return. Trains can also be taken down
into Cornwall as far as Penzance.  <I>British Rail (0044) 1752 221-300</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Bus:</B>  National Express coaches run regularly to London, Heathrow
Airport and the north. Fares are generally cheaper than the train, but a
slightly less frequent service.  Local and regional services are plentiful and
frequent with connections to most towns and throughout the city.  <I>National
Express (0044) 1752 222-666; Plymouth Citybus (0044) 1752 222-221</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Road:</B>  Fast motorway connections to the rest of the country. M5 and
A38 from Bristol. Roads are generally good throughout, although the high hedges
on small country lanes can be rather intimidating to the uninitiated.  Devon has
more road mileage than any other county in the UK.<BR></P>
<P><B>Air:</B>  Regular service to London with connections to international
destinations.  <I>Brymon Airways (0044) 1752 705-151</I><BR></P>
<P><B>Ferries: </B> Regular sailings to and from Roscoff (France) and
Santander (Spain).  <I>Brittany Ferries (0044) 1752 221-321 </I><BR></P>
<P><B><I>Getting Around</I></B><BR></P>
<P>Information on buses can be obtained from the information kiosk on the
intersection of Armada Way and Royal Parade, although most bus stops downtown
have a route guide and timetable on them. For more general information, the
Tourist information bureau is situated on the groud floor of the Civic Centre,
which is the tall building on the opposite side of Royal Parade to the bus info
kiosk.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B><I>Accomodation</I></B><BR></P>
<P>Hotels:  Several international standard hotels, mostly congregated on the
Hoe or Downtown:</P>
<P><B>Novotel Plymouth </B> <I>(0044) 1752 221-422</I></P>
<P><B>Copthorne</B> <I>(0044) 1752 224-161</I></P>
<P><B>The Continental</B>  <I>(0044) 1752 220-782</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P>For the budget traveller, the Citybus 33a/34a from the Downtown runs past
the Youth Hostel in Stoke, a building of Greek architechture set in extensive
grounds with an impressive marble floored entrance hall.  Within Plymouth, there
are also numerous cheaper hotels and quality B&amp;B's to be found. Many are
near the Hoe and Barbican. Contact Tourist Info for more details.</P>
<P><B>Youth Hostel:</B>  Open most of the year. Prices upto L9.10 per person. 
IYHA membership required. <I>(0044) 1752 562-189</I><BR></P>
<P><I>- Nick Gregory</I></P>
