<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: Gloucester</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Gloucester Cathedral Redux</FONT></H1>
<P><EM>by Nathalie Zeidman</EM></P>
<HR>
<P><STRONG><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">A Delightful Stop in the Cotswalds</FONT></EM></STRONG><BR></P>
<P>It was one of those happy accidents travelers dream about.  We were watching
Episode One of the BBC's latest dramatic series, &quot;The Choir&quot; -- a tale
of conflict in the cathedral.  Even more intriguing than the conflict was the
cathedral itself.  In the distance, the square tower crowned by four geometric
spires was strangely familiar.  Close-up, the late afternoon sun spilled
stained-glass colors into a corridor we'd seen before.  &quot;Aldminster
Cathedral&quot;, the announcer called it, but when a troupe of schoolboys dashed
along the stone-paved passage, we remembered.  This was no Aldminster; it was
Gloucester Cathedral, and we'd been there.  By accident!<BR></P>
<P>Several years before, my husband Jerry and I were spending the week at the
Queens Hotel in Cheltenham Spa, a Cotswald town known for its formal gardens and
Regency architecture.  The Queens was Regency outside and in, its facade a Roman
temple, its interior formal yet comfortable.  We were so charmed with the decor
we preferred walking the four flights, for views of the lobby from each landing,
to riding the 1830's cage elevator.  As we learned over the iron railing
enclosing the huge square stairwell we pictured the gentry -- Jane Austin types
in high-waisted gowns -- posed on the stairs.  They had  come to the spa to take
the cure; we had come to explore as much of the Cotswalds, particularly its
churches, as lay within a two-or-three-hours' bus ride. <BR></P>
<P>The Cheltenham-Gloucester Omnibus Depot was a short, gorgeous walk from the
hotel.   On the way we passed nothing but terraces and crescents, each lined
with Regency houses, their facades set off by ornate wrought-iron balconies and
porches and Corinthian columns.  Some Regency fronts concealed offices, even
restaurants.  Our first day in Cheltenham we discovered  the Mandarin Inn.  Over
dim sum we drew up two lists of towns to visit:   &quot;absolutely must&quot;
and &quot;if possible.&quot;<BR></P>
<P>Because of its connection with Dickens, Tewkesbury was an &quot;absolutely
must.&quot;  Tewkesbury, my  notes said, is a village filled with Tudor houses
and inns.  At one of these inns, the &quot;Hop Pole,&quot; Dickens sat Mr.
Pickwick by the fire to warm himself after a long day's stagecoach ride.  Though
the day was mild when we bused into town, the fire was lit in the Hop Pole's
dark paneled public room -- a good place, we discovered, for &quot;shepherd's
pie.&quot;  We couldn't remember if that dish was one of Mr. Pickwick's
favorites, but we did remember to toast the gentleman scribbler with a pint.  He
would have approved of both the toast and the pint, we thought.  Pickwick would
also have approved of the way we narrowed our &quot;if possibles&quot; to
intriguing place names:  Stow-on-the-wold, Bourton-on-water and Lower Slaughter.
 Stow-on-the-wold charmed us with its limestone buildings and oversized market
square, where once the most important wool merchants gathered to do business. 
As for Bourton-on-Water, the River Windrush rushes along its main street.  And
despite its sinister name -- <I>Slaughter</I>, from the Saxon <I>Sloh,</I>
means marshy place -- Lower Slaughter is simply a delightful thatched village.
<BR></P>
<P>We saved what we considered the best for last: Ledbury and Great Malvern,
each known for a  remarkable church.  We are in love with church architecture. 
Back home, commercial buildings  like Trump Towers are considered works of art;
in Britain it's churches.  Besides its church, Ledbury is known for cobbled
lanes barely wide enough for two people to walk abreast, top-heavy houses in
black and white, and Ye Old Talbot Inn.  A 16th century coaching inn, the Talbot
is riddled with bullet holes made when Prince Rupert had a skirmish with the
Round-heads.   Ledbury's real treasure, however, is St. Michael's and All Angels
Church.  St.  Michael's was  begun in Norman England, as its curved front
doorway attests.  The rest is Gothic:   sharp angles, pointed arches, tapering
spires, stained glass; a description to fit most English churches.  What makes
St. Michael's a national treasure is its rare separate bell tower, a tower that
wears a splendid spire like the conical headdress of a medieval queen.  There
are only five such detached towers in the whole county.      For all its
antiquity and charm, Ledbury's St. Michael's is a  country church.  Except for
its spire it nestles unobtrusively among the village's half-timbered houses. 
Great Malvern's Priory Church stands on a rise framed by the Malvern hills, a
picture worthy of Constable.     Climbing the steep streets of the Victorian
town we noticed first the  Priory's great central tower, at once massive and
decorative.  It came to us that just that morning, changing buses in Gloucester,
we'd seen another such tower at a distance.   We followed the Malvern tower  to
the Priory, &quot;one of the finest parish churches in England,&quot; according
to <I>The Little Guide  to Malvern Priory</I>.  Inside, we walked up the south
aisle, down the north, poked around the choir stalls, and bent down to try to
figure out the carvings on the monks stalls.  We thought we could trace farmers
weeding and haymaking, a sort of wooden calendar.  It was easier to identify the
Old Testament figures, Adam and Eve and Noah, in the fifteenth-century  stained
glass windows of St. Anne's Chapel.  We moved slowly, careful not to miss a
transept or a clerestory window, a paneled arch, a doorway, a wooden screen.<BR></P>
<P>Exhausted, behind schedule, and facing a layover in Gloucester, we caught
the bus as it was pulling out.  By the time we got to Gloucester we were rested
and the wait of an hour or two didn't seem so daunting.  &quot;Here's a chance
for a closer look at that tower,&quot; we decided.  Close up, the cream-colored
cathedral tower differed from Malvern Priory's not only in size -- it was taller
and broader -- but in its stone lacework and soaring spires.  A side door opened
into a long corridor, almost immediately overrun by schoolboys peeling off dark
jackets as they raced for the choir changing room.<BR></P>
<P>When the processional began there were fewer than a dozen of us scattered
among the pews.  Down the central aisle red-robed choir boys, their faces framed
by white Renaissance ruffs, moved two by two.  Black-robed parish priests and
other church dignitaries followed.  Not an Anglican, I couldn't distinguish
among them, but it didn't matter.  It was the choir, especially the pure high
notes of the boy sopranos, that stayed with us.  And it was the choir that
helped us relive that evensong when we saw the BBC drama on television.  For
whatever reason, for us, no choir before or since has equaled Gloucester's.    
Afterwards we sat in a sweets shop near the cathedral, drinking Earl Grey tea
and munching Mcvittie's digestive biscuits.  A busload of tourists  swarmed in
and even as they were seated began the kind of table conversation people on
tours engage in.  &quot;I can't imagine,&quot; said one,&quot; why Dorothy would
want to move from Des Moines.&quot;  &quot;It isn't as though Duluth has more to
offer,&quot; said another.  My eyes met Jerry's.   I raised an eyebrow with the
look of superiority I've cultivated for just such moments.  Jerry nodded.<BR></P>
<P>&quot;How could anyone this close to Gloucester Cathedral even mention Des
Moines or Duluth?&quot;  I was indignant.  &quot;If this isn't the high point of
any trip to the Cotswalds, what is?&quot;  Then it hit us.  Two hours before,
Gloucester Cathedral wasn't even on our &quot;if possible&quot; list.  We looked
at each other sheepishly, smiled at the company at large, paid our bill and
left.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Getting to Gloucester and Cheltenham:</FONT></B></I></P>
<P>
&#183; By Rail:  Trains bound for Cheltenham leave London Paddington about once
per hour.  Travel time to Gloucester is roughly one and three-quarter hours. 
Thomas Cook Table #529 &#183; By Bus:  National Express from London&#146;s
Victoria Coach Station; 2 hours, 40 min.</P>
<P>
&#183; By Car: The A40 from London runs to Gloucester via Oxford and Cheltenham;
driving distance approx. 105 miles.<BR></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Where to Stay in Cheltenham:</FONT></B></I></P>
<P>
&#183; The Queen&#146;s Hotel, The Promenade, Cheltenham, GL50 1NN UK; expensive
&#183; Lipyiatt House (Award-winning Victorian B&amp;B), Lypiatt Road,
Cheltenham, GL50 2QW, UK; moderate
</P>
<P>&#183; Stretton Lodge Guest House, Western Road, Cheltenham, GL50 3RN UK;
moderate<BR></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">How to Get Around in the Cotswalds:</FONT></B></I></P>
<P>&#183; Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Omnibus Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>&#183; Day &#147;Explorer&#148; tickets for unlimited travel in the area<BR></P>
<P><I><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">What to Look For in Cheltenham:</FONT></B></I></P>
<P>&#183; Rotunda Buildings (original Spa Pump Room), now a bank on Montpellier
Street, one of the most elegant shopping streets in England
</P>
<P>&#183; Pittsville Pump Room (1820s) to taste mineral waters &amp; visit New
Gallery of Fashion<BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">- Bosley Wilder
</FONT></I></P>
