<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B><BR></P>
<HR>
<H1>French Restaurants</H1>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/review.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>Reviews by Joyce Gregory Wyels</I></P> 
<HR>
<H2><I>A Mediterranean Medley</I></H2>
<P>For many travelers, lunch or dinner at a fine restaurant can be the
highlight of a trip to the French Riviera.  Here are a quartet of legendary
restaurants on France's C&ocirc;te d'Azur that serve the cuisine for which this
region is famous.  All are upscale establishments that require reservations.</P>
<HR>
<P><I><B>Le Moulin de Mougins</B></I><BR></P>
<P>&quot;To be a chef is to share happiness,&quot; says master chef Roger Verg&egrave;.
 At his Moulin de Mougins, the restaurant where he has honed his prodigious
talents for the past quarter century, Verg&egrave; shares happiness with film
stars from the nearby Cannes Film Festival and food lovers from around the
world.  Verg&egrave; was among the first to bring the natural flavors and
culinary traditions of his native Provence to the world's attention, deftly
adding a soup&ccedil;on  of African influence to create what he calls &quot;Cuisine
de Soleil&quot;  (Cuisine of the Sun).<BR></P>
<P>Since Verg&egrave; creates a new menu each morning, it's impossible to
predict your choices on a given day.  I can only tell you that my perfect dinner
went something like this:  a refreshing peach drink (of the kind that Verg&egrave;'s
esteemed Aunt Celestine preferred); squash blossom with black truffles; loup (a
local fish similar to sea bass) with braised lettuce and Vermouth sauce; venison
with Autumn vegetables; a raspberry pastry sauced with liqueur; and never-ending
sweets--a &quot;light&quot; Cappuccino cookie, petits fours, gourmandises du
moulin  (chocolates).  Superb wines from neighboring Cassis and the C&ocirc;tes
de Provence complemented the menu selections, with a Corsican Muscat finishing
off the meal.<BR></P>
<P>Given Verg&egrave;'s reputation, neither the extraordinary cuisine, the fine
wines nor the original works of art that fill gardens and interior surprised me.
 But I'll admit to being surprised--and charmed--when our host emerged from the
kitchen to greet us and inquire about our meal.  Roger Verg&egrave; infuses le
Moulin with his warm, engaging, unpretentious personality.<BR></P>
<P><I>Le Moulin de Mougins, F06250 Mougins, Tel. 93 75 78 24</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>Ch&acirc;teau Eza Hotel-Restaurant</I></B><BR></P>
<P>On a clear day you can see forever, or at least as far as Monaco and St.
Tropez on the fabled C&ocirc;te d'Azur.  Ch&acirc;teau Eza, atop the nearly
vertical medieval village of Eze, offers luxury accommodations for twenty
fortunate travelers and memorable dining experiences for the rest of us.  <BR></P>
<P>Following telephoned directions, my husband and I left our car at the foot
of the village (where donkeys wait to carry guests' luggage up the narrow
cobblestone streets), then hiked up stone steps that may have been cut into this
steep promontory by the Romans.  <BR></P>
<P>Our efforts were well rewarded.  Chef Andr&egrave; Signoret, who once cooked
at Paris' H&ocirc;tel le Crillon, favored us with an exquisite combination of
venison, foie gras and truffles, preceeded by a parmesan risotto with braised
mushroom caps and followed by a tomato-oregano marinated ch&egrave;vre.  Then,
since we had &quot;earned&quot; dessert by virtue of our strenuous climb, we
sampled dessert chef Fran&ccedil;ois Seurin's signature <I>noir-amer</I>,  a
beautifully presented confection secreting a rich coffee liqueur .<BR></P>
<P>Ch&acirc;teau Eza has dinner menus starting at 350 francs.  A lunch menu
that includes wine, tax and service can be had for 250 francs.  Specialties
include lobster with ratatouille and lemon thyme jelly, sauteed Mediterranean
bass with wild baby fennel, and rack of lamb au jus with little stuffed
vegetables--all, of course, accompanied by stunning Mediterranean views from the
glassed-in dining room and adjacent terrace.<BR></P>
<P><I>Ch&acirc;teau Eza Hotel-Restaurant, 06360 Eze Village, C&ocirc;te
d'Azur; Tel. 93 41 12 24, Fax 93 41 16 64</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>La R&egrave;serve de Beaulieu</I></B><BR></P>
<P>Now an elegant small hotel-cum-restaurant in the pretty town of
Beaulieu-sur-Mer, La R&egrave;serve de Beaulieu began life as a Florentine-style
villa in 1880.  By the turn of the century, transformed into a restaurant that
catered to royalty, La R&egrave;serve called itself &quot;the restaurant of
kings and the king of restaurants.&quot;<BR></P>
<P>Current chef Jean-Paul Bonin still creates dishes fit for a king in the
Dining Room of La R&egrave;serve, offering classic selections as well as a
constantly changing roster of regional specialties.  His roast lamb subtly
flavored with herbs and served with wild mushrooms offers a taste of Provence,
while beef Charolais comes from the white cattle that graze throughout the heart
of France.  Veal cutlet served with polenta, and turbot with gnocchi &quot;alle
verde,&quot; suggest the restaurant's Italian origins as well as the proximity
of the Italian border. <BR></P>
<P>Our dinner featured a rosace (local fish) with r&ocirc;moulade of celery,
accompanied by a Ch&acirc;teau Simone white from Aix-en-Provence, and roast veal
with souffl&egrave;ed apples and a pepper confit, which we enjoyed with one of
Bandol's great reds, Domaine Tempier 1990.  Appetizers range in price from 150
francs to 320 for the lobster carpaccio, main dishes 180-290.<BR></P>
<P>After a digestif,  it's pleasant to stroll along the beach or into the town
of Beaulieu itself.  Midway between Monaco and Nice, it's still one of the best
addresses on the Riviera.<BR> </P>
<P><I>La R&egrave;serve de Beaulieu, 5 Boulevard du G&egrave;n&egrave;ral
Leclerc, 06310 Beaulieu-sur-Mer; Tel. 93 01 00 01, Fax 93 01 28 99</I></P>
<HR>
<P><B><I>Restaurant de Bacon</I></B><BR></P>
<P>The old town of Antibes, built by the Greeks and fortified by successive
inhabitants over the centuries, welcomed Pablo Picasso to its Grimaldi Palace in
1946.  Picasso responded by creating his masterpiece, &quot;La Joie de Vivre&quot;
plus some fifty other works of art, which today's visitor can view in the same
building, now the Picasso Museum.<BR></P>
<P>The joyful Riviera spirit that inspired Picasso also animates Restaurant
Bacon, probably the best fish restaurant along this stretch of the coast.  Here
the masterpiece is Bouillabaisse; no one does the traditional Mediterranean fish
soup better than Etienne Sordello at Restaurant Bacon.  Large chunks of eel,
rascasse, and other Mediterranean rockfish swim in a saffron-flavored broth,
enhanced by grated cheese and croutons spread with a spicy rouille.  <BR></P>
<P>Assorted &quot;Amuse Bouche&quot;  (appetizers) and Bacon's signature salad
preceeded our hearty soup.  Wines were a Domaine de Valette Blanc 1994 and a Ch&acirc;teau
de Miraval Ros&egrave;  1993, both C&ocirc;tes de Provence, both perfect
complements.  We finished with a warm millefeuille  and petits fours. <BR></P>
<P>A 250-franc menu offers a choice of appetizers including soupe de poissons;
grilled fresh fish; choice of desserts and petits fours.  For 400 francs the
selections expand to include duck foie gras or a salad of poisson cru.<BR></P>
<P>Relaxing at an ocean-view table in this charming seafront restaurant,
watching sailboats bob on the water while enjoying fine food and wines, one
experiences a little of the &quot;joy of living&quot; that Picasso discovered in
Antibes.<BR></P>
<P><I>Restaurant de Bacon,Boulevard de Bacon, 06000 Cap d'Antibes; Tel. 93 61
50 02, Fax  93 61 65 19</I></P>
<HR> 
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/joie2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> 
