<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Story Title</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I><B>European Visits</B></I></P>
<P><B>A Newsletter of European Travel</B></P>
<HR>
<H1>Chichester</H1> 
<P><I>by Bosley Wilder</I></P>
<HR>
<H2><I>Tootling In and Out of English History</I></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Webster defines &quot;To tootle&quot; as, &quot;to drive or move along in a
leisurely manner.&quot;  Certainly this is a most enjoyable and practical  way
to arrive at Chichester, the county town of West Sussex, England.  Seventy miles
south of London on the A23, and one of Sir Lawrence Olivier's favorite cities, 
Chichester is an impressive reminder of the Roman occupation.  Its ancient
cathedral dominates this modern, attractive English town between the famed
Sussex Downs and the sea, and one of the most important cultural centers of
southern England.<BR></P>
<P>Who has gone  to Chichester?  Here are some of the famous in whose footsteps
you may follow:  Cogidubnus, the Celtic king who built his grand palace at
Fishbourne;  King Canute, who ordered the tide to retreat (it didn't).  Many,
many Roman soldiers.  Elizabeth I, who really did sleep here at the Royal Arms
Inn.  Queen Victoria, who  sampled the Milk Punch at the Royal Arms, and enjoyed
it so much that the name of the inn was changed to the Old Punch Bowl.  Mahatma
Ghandi, General Eisenhower.  Leonard Bernstein, commissioned to compose the &quot;Chichester
Psalms;&quot; William Blake, whose poem &quot;Jerusalem&quot; was inspired by
views of the South Downs;  Turner, who drew his famous landscape painting &quot;Chichester
Canal;&quot; John Keats, who began writing &quot;The Eve of St. Agnes&quot;
here.<BR></P>
<P>Founded by the Romans, the city retains many sections of its early defensive
walls, built on Roman foundations.  It is possible to walk through sections of
the ancient city that encloses the compact center of the Tudor Market Cross,
where all roads meet.  Not far from the city itself, ruins over the countryside
include the Fishbourne Roman Palace and Museum.  These survivors of antiquity
give one an awesome sense of exploits, culture, and habitations as they existed
two thousand years ago.  Throughout this charming area of West Sussex, the far
and recent pasts combine in nature, and in the variety of museums, stately homes
and gardens, to give the visitor a fascinating experience of a particular spot
on earth.<BR></P>
<P>The West Sussex Downs are among the most beautiful uplands in the entire
world.  Heading south by car from London toward Chichester, tootling along
narrow backroads with the undulating hills defining the landscape pleasures the
eyes and the spirit.  To walk the moors on a sunny or misty day, to take in the
pastoral landscape stretching away for miles, is sheer poetry.  No wonder some
of England's finest writers, from Shakespeare to Shelley,  have sung their
praises.  Along the roads one finds ideal stopping off places:  country pubs;
guest houses and small hotels for overnight stays.<BR></P>
<P>The chalk Downlands and villages north of Chichester enjoy their own
heritage and atmosphere. Many have ancient churches and a pub in which you can
savour the local hospitality.  Throughout the countryside are picnic areas;
horse riding, with a network of bridle paths, and quiet country lanes that offer
opportunity to explore the area by bicycle, getting to know how people live and
work in the countryside.<BR></P>
<P>As one nears Chichester, the Cathedral dominates the landscape.  Dedicated
in 1108, it is a fine example of Norman architecture with stunning Gothic
additions.  The focal point of the city, its spire rising above the Sussex
plain, is a major landmark visible for miles around.  One of the city's
principal cultural attractions is its internationally renowned Festival Theatre,
the darling of Sir Lawrence Olivier, and its annual arts festival, the
Chichester Festivities, which take place in mid-summer.  Throughout the year,
concerts, jazz, opera, thrillers, and other entertainments thrive.  When the
Chichester Theatre was first founded back in the fifties, it was a forerunner of
many of today's theatres,  ahead of  its time with its in-the-round seating and
its extraordinary lighting possibilities.  Today it remains one of England's
most  prestigious modern theatre complexes.<BR></P>
<P>For the many interested in gardens(for which England is justifiably
renowned), the recently restored West Dean Gardens  retains in its walled
tranquillity a delicious ambience of the Edwardian age.  The garden contains
thirteen original  glasshouses dating from the 1890's, including vinerys, fig
and peach houses, and melon and pineapple pits as well as a wide range of floral
displays, cut flowers, herbs and local fruits. A two-and-one-half mile walk
through the park and  arboretum  offers, in addition to the fine walk itself,
splendid views of the local Downland landscape.  The Prince of Wales's Institute
of Architecture has been active in recreating the accoutrements of the Garden.<BR></P>
<P>One must visit the lovely Pallant House, an elegant Queen Anne townhouse,
holding one of the finest collections of porcelain and French furniture of its
time, as well as an interesting museum collection of domestic gadgets from the
beginning of the Industrial Revolution:  a humane mouse trap, a wasp trap, a
clockwork spit at the fireplace; and several labor-saving devices of the time,
newly invented and beginning to be popular, like an apple peeler and corer and a
bottle jack. Upstairs, off the master study, the original owner built a privy
with a veritable privy shaft leading to the basement--rare, indeed, in an age of
chamber pots.  Pallant House was built in 1712, by Henry Peckham, a young,
upcoming wine merchant. It is interesting to note that Pallant House cost 3,000
British pounds to build --extremely expensive at a time when the most costly
town house was worth 500 British pounds. This was a most lavish Queen Anne-style
residence.  Over a door is the owner's motto, <I>Tentanda via est </I>( &quot;The
way is to be tried&quot;), certainly not unsuitable for a rising industrial
tycoon who was to make a fortune selling wine.<BR></P>
<P>The city also boasts a fine new leisure center with two swimming pools,
sauna, squash courts, bowling greens, tennis courts and an archery club.  In the
vicinity one can  find sailing, windsurfing, fishing --even a flying school and
hot air  balloon ascents in the summertime.  What more can a visitor wish for?<BR></P>
<P>A most fascinating adventure is a visit to the Fishbourne Roman Palace and
Museum.  Discovered only in 1960, when a workman digging a trench cut into the
remains of the largest Roman domestic building yet found north of the Alps, it
is  one of this century's most important archaeological finds in Britain.  Part
of the remains appear to be the palace of the  Celtic king, Cogidubnus; the
Roman establishment, initially part of a military base, was established in A.D.
43.  Here are glimpses of a magnificent first century Roman palace, with mosaic
floors, under-floor heating systems and a bath suite.  Through the spring and
summer, the museum offers hands-on activites in mosaic making, and pottery
through the ages,  with special emphasis on the Roman production.  Here is an
exciting look into the past for both adults and children.   Access for disabled
visitors is very good; there are also free tape-guided tours for visually
handicapped visitors. <BR></P>
<P>Tootling about over Roman roads, cruising a route straight as an arrow past
Arundel Castle,  visiting thatched cottages, 11th century chalets and 16th
century manors is quite good fun.  Along the way there is also Pulburough Brooks
Nature  Reserve, with splendid opportunities for bird-watching in its over 400
acres of nature preserve covers and wetlands.   Tagmere Aviation Museum tells
the story of military flying from the earliest days through 1970. <BR></P>
<P>The heirs and owners of many of England's stately homes are today having to
offer public tours of the premises and  gardens, and lectures on their history,
in order to make ends meet.  Many a lord and lady are up against it
economically.  Goodwood House, ancestral home of the Dukes of Norfolk, is a
great repository of art and other cultural treasures.   Family portraits by Van
Dyck and Reynolds among others look down on a fine collection of Sevres
procelain and royal relics as well as Napoleonic booty.  Enjoyable lessons in
history as well as a peek into the the historical &quot;other half.&quot;  I
personally have always envied those high, tapestried, canopied beds and
comforting foot warmers; although certainly NOT any of the pre-twentieth century
plumbing devices. . . <BR></P>
<P>In a country not especially noted for its cuisine,  the Chichester area has
a variety of attractive restaurants with quite edible viands.  English roast
beef can be hard to beat. With a little search, I savoured an up-market
steak-and-kidney pie.  Fish and chips are usually quite good, and are on most
luncheon menus.  My companion and I tend, however, to stick to the pubs for
lunch.  Grandma used to say there's not too much you can do to a ham sandwich;
and the varieties of ales, bocks and lager beers in England are suberb, and
unbeatable anywhere on the Continent.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><B>IF YOU GO:</B>  Chichester is well connected by road to London(70
miles).   There is also regular train service from London.</P>
<P>For full details, contact the Chichester  Information Centre:  29A South
Street, Chichester, PO19 1AH,England  This tourist center is very helpful.  <B>Telephone:
44 (1243)775888</B> </P>
<HR>
