<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: The Online Traveler</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1>The Online Traveler</H1>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">News Briefs:</FONT></H2>
<P><BR></P>
<P>The <B>World Wide Web</B> now boasts more than 6.5 million adult users,
according to a recent report in <I>Web Week</I> magazine, with home users
comprising some 23%.  Given the Web's portrayal as a &quot;Generation X&quot;
hangout, a statistic that may surprise some is that nearly a fourth of users are
over fifty.  About 10 percent say they've used the Internet to make travel
reservations or buy tickets.<BR></P>
<P><B>Globalink Inc.</B>, a software company specializing in language
translation, is now offering a Windows program designed to help Web surfers
translate overseas pages into English.  <B>Web Translator</B>, which retails
for $49, can convert text to and from Spanish, French, and German, with 
Portuguese and Italian capabilities to be added soon.  For more information,
visit Globalink at <B><A HREF="http://www.globalink.com/">http://www.globalink.com</A></B>.<BR></P>
<P><B>Southwest Airlines</B> has become the largest airline yet to offer
booking over the Internet, with introduction of a system that allows travelers
to make ticketless reservations on Southwest's Web page at <B><A
HREF="http://www.iflyswa.com/">http://www.iflyswa.com</A></B>.  A secure
browser such as Netscape 2.0 must be used, and reservations made at the site can
only be canceled by phone.<BR></P>
<P><B>Rick Steves</B> of <I>Europe Through The Back Door</I> fame, whose
presence on AOL was noted last issue, also is on the Web: check him out at <B><A
HREF="http://www.halcyon.com/rsetbd">www.halcyon.com/rsetbd</A></B>.  Thanks to
Jenifer Poole of <B><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/">www.travel.org</A></B>
for this tip.<BR></P>
<P><B>American Arlines</B> is following United Airlines in offering a
disk-based electronic booking product.  In addition to reserving American
flights with <B>AAccess</B>, you can book hotels and rental cars.  The software
is $6.95 and connect fees are waived through the end of the year; no indication
of what they'll be after that.  Call American Airlines to order; you have to be
a member of their AAdvantage frequent flyer program.  Editors Note: <I>European
Visits</I> will be doing a review of both this and <B>United Connections</B>
software in an upcoming issue.</P>
<HR>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rpex3.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR>Visit <B>Rail
Pass Express</B> on the World Wide Web at
<A HREF="http://www.eurail.com/">http://www.eurail.com</A></P>
<HR>
<H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">European Travel Sites On the Internet</FONT></H3>
<P><BR></P>
<P>The Internet continues to explode with more and more travel offerings.  You
can literally spend days browsing and not begin to cover it all.  Some of the
interesting sites we've run across lately are listed below.  The addresses were
current as of July 1, 1996.  As noted in our last issue, we're finding some
unusually good web pages out there that deserve special recognition, and these
are indicated in the following pages with our <B><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">European
Visits</FONT></I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080"> &quot;#1&quot;
</FONT></B>ribbon.  We welcome your own Internet picks and pans as well:  please
write to us at <B><A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A></B>
to share your online observations with fellow travelers.</P>
<HR>
<H4>Internet Bike Resources for Europe</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.abeline.it/fbp-eur.htm">www.abeline.it/fbp-eur.htm</A></P>
<P><I>This site presents a jumping-off point for a variety of Web resources on
bicycle travel in Europe.  Sponsored by Florence (Italy) Bike Pages, which cover
biking in and around Florence in good detail.  Other links for Austria, Britain,
Netherlands, Switzerland, and Sweden.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Castles in the Air, Castles Everywhere</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://fox.nstn.ca/~tmonk/castle/castle.html">http://fox.nstn.ca/~tmonk/castle/castle.html</A></P>
<P><I>A set of web pages devoted to nothing but castles -- tours, histories,
legends, and more.  If your heart quickens at ancient grey stones towering in
the mist, be sure to stop by.  The webmaster is a true castle lover and it
shows.  There's even a &quot;Castles for Kids&quot; page for the little knights
and maidens in your court.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>County Kerry</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://ireland.iol.ie/kerry-insight">http://ireland.iol.ie/kerry-insight</A></P>
<P><I>All about one of Ireland's most beautiful &amp; historic regions,
including Tralee and the Dingle peninsula (see Jerry McRorie's <B>Travel by
Peddler's Wagon</B> in this issue).</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Edinburgh</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.efr.hw.ac.uk/EDC/guide/contents.html">www.efr.hw.ac.uk/EDC/guide/contents.html</A></P>
<P>Online guide to Scotland's leading city.  Includes a large city map (54k)
with point-and-click links, and detailed descriptions of sights and attractions,
although no lodging information.</P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Britain by Boat</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.rscom.com/boat/">www.rscom.com/boat/</A></P>
<P><I>The official site of British Waterways, an organization devoted to
promoting travel on Britain's extensive canal system.  They have a map of the
canal system, a searchable index of information on boat services, and a listing
of links to other British boating Web sites.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Britain by Foot</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm">www.gorp.com/gorp/activity/europe/britain.htm</A></P>
<P><I>Everything you need to know before setting out to see the British
countryside on foot, including where to get trail maps, what to bring, and where
to stay along the way.  </I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>London Walking Tours</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://scim.co.uk/londonwalks/">http://scim.co.uk/londonwalks/</A></P>
<P><I>The oldest walking tour company in England's capital, London Walks gives
a complete rundown on their offerings here, and you can e-mail them for more
information.  Dozens of tours are described and they are all just &#163;4.  The
web site also gives profiles of their many experienced guides, so you'll have an
idea who you're walking with.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>European Motorhome Travel</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.spectrav.com/27035.html">http://www.spectrav.com/27035.html</A></P>
<P><I>A California operator for motorhome rentals in Europe.  Brief
information on rates, models, etc., and a toll free number (800-468-3876) for
reservations.  Also, see</I> <B><A HREF="http://www.drm.de/">http://www.drm.de</A></B><I>for
more detailed online data from a German rental firm.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Tuscany Camping</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.ats.it/metamarketing/toscana.html">www.ats.it/metamarketing/toscana.html</A></P>
<P><I>Extensive listing of campgrounds and related info for Italy's lovely
Tuscan region.  A point-and-click map lets you pick your area and takes you to
alphabetized listings.  Most are just address and Italian phone number, but some
can be clicked through to pages of their own with prices and other details. 
Nicely done site.</I></P>
<HR>
<H4><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="79">   
 In Italy Online</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://lainet3.lainet.com/~initaly/index.html">http://lainet3.lainet.com/~initaly/index.html</A></P>
<P><I>A self-described &quot;webzine compiled by American writers who have
lived twenty years or more in Italy.&quot;  Packed with information, including
an interesting page on farm stays in Italy with details on how to book one for
your next trip.  Italian cooking vacations, villa rentals, events calendar, much
more. Terrific &quot;visit to Italy&quot; and winner of a number of awards.</I></P>
<HR>
<H4>International Home Exchanges</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.homexchange.com/ten/index.html">www.homexchange.com/ten/index.html</A></P>
<P><I>International postings of homes and apartments for rent or exchange. 
Lots of listings for Europe including some wonderful-sounding villas.  The site
provides ample detail on each property including what location the owner is
looking to trade to; some listings will either exchange or simply rent to you.
You can search by country for properties that interest you.  This site is an
excellent resource if you're looking for the advantages of private lodgings for
a longer stay overseas.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Vienna City Guide</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.atnet.co.at/Tourism/Vienna/">http://www.atnet.co.at/Tourism/Vienna/</A></P>
<P><I>A straightforward site whose many pages offer &quot;lots of useful infos&quot;
for your Vienna visit.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Hospitality Exchange</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://hospex.icm.edu.pl/~hospex/WhatIsHospex.html">http://hospex.icm.edu.pl/~hospex/WhatIsHospex.html</A></P>
<P><I>This organization facilitates low- or no-cost temporary lodging for
traveling students and academics by maintaining a database of those needing &amp;
those offering a place to spread a sleeping bag in varied locales.  You're asked
to join in order to get digs, but there's no charge. They just provide the
communications infrastructure; all lodging arrangements are up to members to
work out privately by email.</I></P>
<HR>
<H4><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="79">   
 Online Guide to the Baltics</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.omnitel.net/OurSite/Travel/viyp">www.omnitel.net/OurSite/Travel/viyp</A></P>
<P><I>WOW!  If you're heading to Vilnius, Kaunus, Klaipeda, Riga, or Minsk,
don't miss these terrific online guides.  Lavish detail, particularly good for
lodging but covering just about everything else you could want too.  Some of the
graphics are a bit slow but the data is worth waiting for.  You can also order
the complete guides, ranging from 48 to 80 pages, in free printed versions by
sending the publishers International Reply Coupons.  Details at the Web site.</I></P>
<HR>
<H4>E-Mail European Rail Schedules</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.bahn.de/">www.bahn.de</A></P>
<P><I>At this site you can enter a query on schedules or services on European
railways, and you will get an automated e-mail response about half hour later
with route details.  We tried it and it does work; they say they processed over
34,000 queries last month.  It may seem a cumbersome way to get information, but
the 30 minute turn-around can just about beat Rail Europe's telephone on-hold
time some days!</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Swiss Rail</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.sbb.ch/">www.sbb.ch</A></P>
<P><I>Timetables, routes, and other information on the extensive and scenic
Swiss railway system.  The timetable query form produces fast, detailed results
for point-to-point travel options, and covers major international routes as well
as Swiss..</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Ecotourism</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://greencross.unige.ch/tournet/tournet.html">http://greencross.unige.ch/tournet/tournet.html</A></P>
<P><I>If you want to ensure that your travel is easy on the Earth, this
Swiss-based organization can help identify some options.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Travel, Packing and Photo Hints</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.afn.org/~afn11300">www.afn.org/~afn11300</A></P>
<P><I>Betty, the author of this page, is a veteran of travel to seven
continents, and herein shares some pithy experiences and advice.  Also offers an
extensive collection of Web travel links.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Inside Flyer Magazine Online</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.insideflyer.com/">www.insideflyer.com/</A></P>
<P><I>Randy Peterson, guru of frequent flyer information, has a snazzy online
version here.  Check out the reviews of airline FFB programs before you choose
which ones to join.</I></P>
<HR>
<H4><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/1st.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" WIDTH="52" HEIGHT="79">   
 French Travel Gallery</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.bonjour.com/wta">www.bonjour.com/wta</A></P>
<P><I>Very flashy, high-tech site with beaucoup info on travel in France
organized by region and topic.  Exceptional hotel listings, including that true
rarity -- genuine budget lodgings (as low as Ff220, or about $47) in Paris. 
Many can be booked online.  Lots more to see here; if you have the browser
plugin RealAudio (and you can download it free if you don't) you can even listen
to pronunciation of a few essential French phrases, such as &quot;O&ugrave; sont
les toilettes, s'il vous pla&icirc;t?&quot;</I> </P>
<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">The Standards</FONT></H2>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">For those who are new to the Web (or new to <I>EV</I>),
there are a few travel sites so comprehensive we'll repeat their listing each
issue -- these are the best of the bunch and will lead you to lots more.</FONT></B></P>
<H4>Lonely Planet</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/">www.lonelyplanet.com.</A></P>
<P><I>The guidebook publisher has built what may be the most informative,
comprehensive travel information site on the Internet.  There are literally
hundreds of pages featuring detailed information on destinations all over the
world, and plenty on Europe.  Particularly good are the up-to-the-minute &quot;what's
happening&quot; listings for major cities -- perfect for downloading to your
<B>EuroData</B> itinerary before you take off.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Go Europe</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.goeurope.com/">www.goeurope.com</A></P>
<P><I>The European Travel Commission has a big budget and big ambitions for
this all-around European travel compendium.  You can pick from 26 member
countries to view everything from musical events to the latest weather
forecasts.  A Traveler's Forum lets you post messages and ask other travelers'
advice on your destination.</I></P>
<H4>The Webfoot Guides</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.webfoot.com/travel/guides">www.webfoot.com/travel/guides</A></P>
<P><I>A huge &amp; varied gathering of pointers to information sources on
worldwide destinations.  Some of what's pointed to is quite good, some less
useful.  You'll have fun exploring and will find lots of nuggets good for anyone
planning European travel. </I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Travel Weekly's Home Page</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.traveler.net/two">www.traveler.net/two</A></P>
<P><I>This page is hosted by Travel Weekly, the newspaper of the travel
industry.  More than 800 links, categorized for easy reference.  Recipient of a
number of well-deserved awards.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>Travel Org</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/">www.travel.org</A></P>
<P><I>This is one of the best travel sites around, covering destinations all
over the world covered with lots of information.  A terrific starting point for
your online travel explorations -- click the &quot;Europe&quot; graphic and dive
in.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<H4>WWW Travel Guide</H4>
<P><A HREF="http://www.infohub.com/">www.infohub.com</A></P>
<P><I>A wide variety of travel-related links are to be found here, covering
destinations worldwide.  A good starting place for your Internet travel search.</I></P>
<HR>
<P>Have <I>you</I> run across a great European travel site on the Internet? 
Let us know about it!  Send e-mail to <B><A HREF="mailto:eurodata@nas.com">eurodata@nas.com</A></B>,
attention <B>EV Online</B>.</P>
