<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Brussels / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Brussels</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>By Esme Voss</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Brussels by Esme Voss--><BR></P>
<P><B>I had only three days in Brussels,</B> not really enough time to see
everything I wanted to see, but just enough to eat, shop and yes, overdose on
chocolate.  Many people visit Brussels on a business trip, or even as a brief
stopover to some other place.  If you don&#146;t have much time to spare, you
can still enjoy what must be one of Europe&#146;s most underrated cities. 
Underrated because although there are no famous monuments, such as the Eiffel
Tower, or ancient tourist traps, like Pompeii,  Brussels holds its own by
offering the visitor delights of a different kind: excellent food, good shopping
and Art Deco architecture.  In three days, I managed to lead a decadent life.  I
ate well, picked up my e-mail and surfed the Internet at a Vietnamese cybercaf&eacute;,
shopped, marveled at the beautiful Art Deco buildings and even managed to
squeeze in a visit to a modern art museum. <BR></P>
<P>I picked up a good map and started in the <B>Gran&#146; Place</B>, the
center of Brussels and its biggest tourist attraction.  The Gran&#146; Place was
once Brussels&#146; central marketplace and the names of the narrow, curving
streets reflect that history: Rue des Bouchers (Butchers&#146; Street), Rue Au
Beurre (Butter Street) and Rue des Harengs (Herring Street). Today, many of the
old guildhouses are filled with restaurants, cafes and chocolate shops and
although they look very old, in reality, the guildhouses date back only to the
early 1700s when the square was rebuilt, in the already pass&eacute; Flemish
Baroque style, after it was destroyed by the French.  The Gran&#146; Place is an
excellent place to sit in the sun, drink beer or linger over a cup of
cappuccino.   
<BR></P>
<P>Not far from the Gran&#146; Place is the <B>Rue Neuve</B> which is lined
with discount shops and big department stores.  Here one finds the giant French
bookstore, FNAC, and the Belgian department store, Inno.  There is also a Virgin
Music Store in the Anspach Center on the Boulevard Anspach a few paces from the
Bourse (stock exchange).   For a more eclectic selection, try the shops on the
rue Antoine Dansaert  off the Boulevard Anspach near the Bourse.  This street
has become a mecca for Brussels&#146; hip and funky.  Here one finds the latest
from Belgian designers, such as Dries van Noten and Ann Demeulemeester, as well
as trendy restaurants frequented by trendy PIBs (people in black). 
<BR></P>
<P>For a completely different pace and ambiance, head to the tranquil, leafy
square called the <B>Place du Grand Sablon</B>.  Unlike the Gran&#146; Place,
the Place du Grand Sablon is quiet and dignified.  Designer boutiques (including
the newly opened Emporio Armani), antique shops and the beautiful church of
Notre Dame du Sablon line the periphery of the square.  Actually, I came here to
try the pastries at Wittamer.  Forget your diet.   The choice of pastries is
simply staggering and everything looks so sinful.  I tried a rich chocolate
mousse cake topped with a chunk of dark chocolate.  Other temptations include
napoleons filled with thick layers of cream, cakes soaked in liqueur and topped
with cream and shaved chocolate, and fruit tarts.  If you happen to be in this
area during the lunch hour, stop off at <B>Le Pain Quotidien</B>, which is a
chain of lunch caf&eacute;s that serve inexpensive creative salads and
sandwiches.    
<BR></P>
<P>Not far from the Place du Grand Sablon are the <B>Mus&eacute;es Royaux des
Beaux-Arts</B>, which consist of a modern art museum (Mus&eacute;e d&#146;Art
Moderne), and a more traditional collection (Mus&eacute;e d&#146;Art Ancien)
with paintings of Rubens and Van Dyck.  The modern art museum focuses on Belgian
artists, including Delvaux and Magritte.   
<BR></P>
<P>For hard-core shopping, nothing beats the area around the Avenue Louise,
which intersects the Boulevard Waterloo and Avenue de la Toison d&#146;Or. 
Here, one finds the big-name designers such as Gucci, Louis Vuitton, and Chanel.
 For those on a more earthly budget, indoor shopping centers, such as the
Galerie Louise (on the Avenue Louise) offer a wide range of shoes, bags,
clothes, sportswear and gifts.  My favorite shop is the <B>Galerie Louise is
Y-Enzo</B>, a shoe store that carries Patrick Cox and Prada.  Other shops in the
area that offer good value are <B>Max Mara</B> (women&#146;s clothes), <B>Sergio
Rossi</B> (women&#146;s shoes), <B>Zara</B> (high street, young women&#146;s
and men&#146;s clothes) and <B>College</B> (women&#146;s clothes).   
<BR></P>
<P>Since I was pressed for time, I decided one day to combine two activities:
pick up my e-mail and eat Vietnamese food.  For this, I chose a cybercaf&eacute;
called <B>@Internem</B> which also doubles as a Vietnamese restaurant.  @
Internem is located on the Boulevard General Jacques, just at the border of
Brussels and the suburb of Ixelles, and is accessible via one of the trams that
travels down the Avenue Louise.  I arrived shortly after the lunch hour and
ordered a large steaming bowl of pho (Vietnamese noodle soup with meat and
vegetables).  The restaurant itself is tastefully decorated and the front room
has four computers with large screen (17-inch) monitors.  The owners of the
restaurant are more than willing to assist customers in picking up their e-mail
and doing a bit of surfing on the World Wide Web.   
<BR></P>
<P>The best eating in Brussels is done in the evening.   One could go crazy
trying to figure out where to eat as there is a restaurant to suit just about
everyone and every budget. Sure, there are places where expense account
Eurocrats blow their countries&#146; national budgets, but they aren&#146;t
necessarily the best.  My favorites near the Gran&#146; Place are:  <B>Taverne
du Passage</B>, 30 Galerie de la Reine, which serves excellent, but heavy
Belgian food at reasonable prices in a turn-of-the-century salon with long
tables, mirrors and high ceilings; and <B>&#145;t Kelderke</B>, 15 Gran&#146;
Place, a cellar with long tables and benches, another inexpensive restaurant
that serves Belgian food.  Both places fill up fast though and getting a table,
especially at &#145;t Kelderke at 9 o&#146;clock in the evening is nearly
impossible.   
<BR></P>
<P>If you want to splurge, but not break the bank, <B>La Quincaillerie</B>, 45
rue du Page, near the Horta museum, serves oysters and wonderful French cuisine
in a turn-of-the-century former hardware store that retains original ironwork
railings on its interior balconies. Art Deco lovers, who happen to be around the
area during the day, should not miss the <B>Horta Museum</B> (which used to be
Victor Horta&#146;s house) on 25 rue Americaine (closed Mondays). 
<BR></P>
<P>Finally, what would a trip to Brussels be without sampling the beer?  My
favorite beers are Duvel and Kriek (which has a sweet berry taste).  Be warned:
both have a very high alcohol content.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><I><B>Practical information:</B>  The country code for Belgium is 32 and
the city code for Brussels is 2.  In general, one should make reservations for
dinner.  Restaurants near the Gran&#146; Place tend to be open till late in the
evening, but fill up fast.  Approx. exchange: $1=30 BF (Belgian francs). 
</I><BR></P>
<P><I><B>Hotels</B></I><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>&agrave; Hotel Rembrandt</B>, 42 rue de la Concorde, 1050 Bruxelles
(phone 32-2-512-7139; fax 32-2-511-7136) off Avenue Louise &#151;charming hotel
close to the shopping areas of Avenue Louise and Boulevard Waterloo.  Excellent
location, but the neighborhood is a bit creepy at night because there are very
few people walking around (unlike the Gran&#146; Place).  If you like to stroll
outside in the evening, you are better off staying in one of the hotels off the
Gran&#146; Place.  The only problem is that the Gran&#146; Place can be noisy. 
One night stay at the Rembrandt: 2300 BF. Ask for room 15.  
<BR></LI>
<LI><B>&agrave; Hotel Argus</B>, 6 rue Capitaine Crespel, 1050 Bruxelles
(phone 32-2-514-0770; fax 32-2-514-1222) off Avenue de la Toison d&#146;Or -
modern hotel with very little character and small rooms - that &#147;chain hotel&#148;
feel; more expensive that the Hotel Rembrandt which has more charm and is just a
couple of blocks away.  One night stay: 3200BF.  
<BR></LI>
<LI><B>&agrave; Arlequin</B>, 17 rue de la Fourche, 1000 Bruxelles (phone
32-2-514-1615, fax 32-2-514-2202) off the Gran&#146; Place - very convenient,
but like the Argus, is new and has no charm whatsoever.  The rooms are also very
small, but there is a dining room on the 7th floor where breakfast is served,
with a view across the Gran&#146; Place and its surroundings.  One night stay:
2400 BF.  
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><I><B>Dinner</B></I><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>&agrave; Taverne du Passage</B>, 30 Galerie de la Reine (512-3731) off
the Gran&#146; Place - excellent, but heavy Belgian food at reasonable prices in
a turn-of-the-century salon with long tables, mirrors and high ceiling.  It is
open for lunch and till midnight.  
<BR></LI>
<LI><B>&agrave; &#145;t Kelderke</B>, 15 Gran&#146; Place (512-3694) - hearty
Belgian cuisine in a cellar.   &agrave; La Quincaillerie, 45 rue du Page
(538-2553) - oysters and French food - moderate to expensive; valet parking; a
turn-of-the century former hardware with ironwork railings on the balconies. It
is very busy at dinner so reservations are a must. 
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><I><B>Lunch</B></I><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>&agrave; @Internem</B>, 68 Blvd. General Jacques, 1050 Ixelles
(649-4509) - excellent Vietnamese restaurant/cybercaf&eacute; where you can pick
up your email, surf the Internet and enjoy a large, steaming bowl of pho
(190BF).  Email address: <A HREF="mailto:cyberfood@pophost.eunet.be">cyberfood@pophost.eunet.be</A>;
their World Wide Web site is located at <A HREF="http://www.internem.be/">http://www.internem.be</A>
 
<BR></LI>
<LI><B>&agrave; Le Pain Quotidien</B> - inexpensive salads, sandwiches, good
and fast service. There is one in front of the Notre Dame du Sablon and at 16
rue Antoine Dansaert. 
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><I><B>Sweets</B></I><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>&agrave; Wittamer</B> - a pastry salon on the Place du Grand Sablon -
offers a sinful, tempting array of pastries and chocolates.<BR></LI>
<LI><B>&agrave; Corn&eacute; Michel</B> - a chain of Belgian chocolate stores
(there are several around Brussels).  My Belgian friends think their chocolates
are too rich, and that&#146;s exactly why I like them.  The chocolate truffles
are excellent.<BR></LI></UL>
<HR>
