<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Andorra / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Andorra</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>&quot;The longest shopping mall in the world&quot;,
by Nathalie Zeidman</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Andorra  The Longest Shopping Mall in the World By Nathalie Zeidman--><BR></P>
<P><B>In the heart of the Pyrenees,</B> halfway between Toulouse in France and
Barcelona in Spain, lies one of the smallest countries in the world&#151;with
one of the world&#146;s longest shopping malls. 
<BR></P>
<P>Andorra, of course, is more than a shopping mall.  It has skiing slopes,
camping facilities, hiking trails; historic caves and medieval architecture;
wild boar and partridge in the mountains, salmon trout in lakes and rivers.  But
in town there are shops.  Lots of shops!  When we arrived in mid-April the
Pyrenees were capped in snow, their slopes wrapped in fir, their meadows
brightened by  daffodils, heather and rhododendron   Spectacular scenery was
lost on us, however, in our eagerness to make Andorra La Vella, the capital,
before dark.  We needed to settle on lodgings, look the town over, and maybe
before dinner do a little shopping in this discount paradise.<BR></P>
<P>Parked in the main square, more sloping oblong than square, we might have
been in southern France&#151;with one difference. Here the traffic cops are
women, all in jeans, red ski jacket, white gloves and peaked cap above a pony
tail.  The officer flagging signals took time to coo over a baby in a buggy and
listen to our bastardized Spanish-French.  The Andorran language is neither; it&#146;s
Catalan.  The McDonald&#146;s sign, in English, reminded us we were hungry but
not McDonald&#146;s hungry.  Since we planned only an overnight in Andorra
anyway, we&#146;d have to spend  the afternoon sightseeing, possibly getting in
a little shopping.  Our Toulouse chocolate bars  would have to do until dinner.

<BR></P>
<P>With a map of Andorra La Vella and its suburbs in hand, we passed shop after
shop on the ground floor of residencias.  Less than half-a-mile and we were at
Casa De La Vail.  Once the home of a noble Andorran family, this rough stone
building, like a medieval fort, exemplifies the sixteenth-century mountain style
characteristic of Andorra.  Today  it houses both the Principality&#146;s seat
of government and its Ministry of Justice.  From kitchen with hanging copper
pots to paneled chapel, and main room where the General Council of Europe&#146;s
oldest Parliament meets the guided tour, it&#146;s a useful introduction to this
miniature country. 
<BR></P>
<P>In the nearby suburb of Ordino the Casa D&#146;Areny De Plandolit is laid
out in much the same military style as the Casa De La Van, except that its stone
is plastered over and wrought-iron balconies decorate the facade.  An interior
lentil is dated 1613, though the house is thought to be older.  Now a museum
bearing the name of a famous Andorran political reformer, it&#146;s worth at
least the two hours we gave it.  In the reception room, side saddles, branding
irons and a bear collar are standouts.  If the wine cellar is a reminder of the
Principality&#146;s former copious wine production, the olive oil cellar with
stone sink bears witness to the care given this precious liquid, once available
only in prosperous households.  In the meat cellar, a variety of typical
preserved Andorran pork products including sausage, trotters, and ears are hung
from rope, out of the reach of  rats.  We weren&#146;t tempted but in the
kitchen we looked longingly at the tinned biscuits and chocolate on the dresser
and the flat and braided breads in the bakery.  We were hungry.  Better to put
off till tomorrow the Meritxell Sanctuary and the shopping binge. 
<BR></P>
<P>In the heart of suburban Santa Coloma, less than a mile from one of the
longest shopping malls in the world is Hotel Garden.  Looking like a Swiss
chalet, the Hotel Garden boasts tennis court and swimming pool but doesn&#146;t
have a garden.  When we arrived dinner was not yet being served, so we crossed
the road to the Parador where it was.  There, against the back wall, quail were
turning on the spit in a slate fireplace; in the center of the room, steaks were
grilling over a propane fire in an iron cauldron.  We had to have the quail
because it was there in front of us.  We  had to have cannelloni to see if
Andorrans could do Italian, paella to see if they could do Spanish, troute a la
Andorrana to see what they&#146;d learned from the French and hare because it 
was on the menu.  A bottle of &#147;Marques de Caceres,&#148; the local version
of a Spanish Rioja, made  us happy to be overeating in this rustic Andorran inn.
 
<BR></P>
<P>We slept well.  Before going down to breakfast we stood on our balcony
blinking at the brilliant sun on snow-white slopes. What a scene to wake up to! 
In the Hotel Garden&#146;s breakfast room jig- saw puzzles, chess sets and
French paperback novels waited for those with more time here than we had.  We
had to be out of Andorra La Vella before lunch and in Barcelona before dinner,
and  still had the last of the sightseeing and the first of the shopping ahead
of us.  
<BR></P>
<P>Twenty-five years ago Meritxell, the sanctuary of the Blessed Virgin,
patroness of the Principality, caught fire and was razed to the ground except
for a few stone arches.  The sanctuary&#146;s replacement designed by
contemporary Spanish architect Richard Bonfill, has the feel of Le  Corbusier;
curves and angles merge with old arches into the hillside   On the same road as
the Sanctuary, ultimate symbol of Andorra&#146;s piety, sits the Magatzens
Pyrenees, ultimate symbol of Andorra&#146;s commerce. Known also as the Casa
Perez, for the family that founded the business in the thirties, the present
four-story block-long structure was built in the sixties.  Shops with discounted
prices may line Andorra La Vella&#146;s main streets; but for convenience,
variety and price the Casa Perez is the Galleries Lafayette, Marks &amp; 
Spencer, and Macy&#146;s all in one.  	<BR>&#147;How are these prices possible?&#146;
we asked Felix Giralt, head of publicity for the company.  	<BR>&#147;Simple,&#148;
said Giralt. &#147;We don&#146;t tax luxury items.&#148; Jewelry, furs,
perfumes, objects d&#146;art, and designer clothes are among those items.  
<BR></P>
<P>The bargains start in the subway (basement) with cameras and photographic
equipment, the best of the name brands; the same for radios, hi-fis, tapes and
discs.  From the subway it&#146;s an easy escalator glide to the main floor and
men&#146;s clothes&#151;Burberry and Cardin, among other top-name designers. 
Rolex watches and Paloma perfumes are prominently displayed.  Gold and precious
stones for men and women wink from velvet boxes.  Sporting and camping equipment
are also on the main floor, as well as designer clothes for women and children. 
Food, the newest department, is on the second floor.  I can&#146;t remember when
I&#146;ve seen such a display of caviar and foie gras&#151;not even in Fortnum &amp;
Mason&#146;s or Fauchon&#146;s.  The top floor is  given over to services:
travel agencies, beauty shops and art galleries. 
<BR></P>
<P>Most items are discounted thirty percent, but by far the biggest bargain is
cigarettes&#151;fifty  percent off.  Giralt explained that by arrangement with
American tobacco companies, Andorra is licensed to make name-brand cigarettes
using half American tobacco and half Andoran.  If either Jerry or I still
smoked, we could have coughed our way through the rest of the trip for
practically nothing.  As for a fur coat, in southern California who needs one? 
I&#146;m allergic to perfume; Jerry&#146;s loyal to his old Pentax.  Several art
books were tempting, but we were on our way to Barcelona where Las Ramblas,
Barcelona&#146;s great shopping/strolling street, is said to be the place for
bargains in art books.  That didn&#146;t prove to be the case; but we had no
regrets.  If we didn&#146;t take advantage of the discounts at one of the
longest shopping malls in the world, at least we&#146;d been there.  &#164;    
</P>
<P><I>For further information about Andorra, call the Andorran Embassy at
(212) 750 8064.
</I></P>
<HR>
