<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Europe Writes  /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Europe Writes...</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>Notes from Paris, by David Whitehouse</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><B>Egon Ronay&#146;s &#147;Inner Circle&#148; to be Watchdog for the Caviar
Traveler; A Tale of Two Concordes 
</B><BR></P>
<P>&#147;British Airways&#146; Concorde service is far superior to that of Air
France,&#148; said Egon Ronay, the famous hotel and restaurant critic, at the
launch of his campaign to raise standards of service to high-spending
international travelers.  Ronay flew Air France from Paris to New York, then on
to London with BA.  The flights were fully paid to ensure objectivity.  &#147;The
BA Concorde oozed luxury, refinement, and a genuine concern for passenger&#146;
well-being,&#148; he concluded.  &#147;The French Concorde should droop its nose
in shame.&#148;<BR></P>
<P>&#147;Where,&#148; asked Ronay, &#147;have all the truffles, caviar, foie
gras gone?  Have the French lost all their taste for luxury?&#148;  He called
Air France&#146;s onboard meal &#147;exceptionally forgettable&#148; and the
Concorde lounge at Charles de Gaulle airport a &#147;disappointing mediocrity.&#148;
<BR></P>
<P>&#147;The service, which was reasonably efficient, lacked the real caring
one should have felt, or sincere friendliness or natural kindliness.  Even its
Concorde lounge was almost tawdry.  The head of cabin staff should be relegated
to the ranks, and the chef relegated to the kitchen sink.&#148;  In contrast, BA&#146;s
lounge at New York&#146;s Kennedy Airport was &#147;palatially spacious,
supremely comfortable, decorated with relaxed taste.  The lounge staff could not
have been bettered.  The flight attendants also seemed truly pleased to see the
passengers, and the amount of attention was almost embarrassing.  The main
course was the best dish I have had on an airline, whereas I have rarely had a
blander tasting dish than the one provided by the French Concorde.&#148; 
<BR></P>
<P>Ronay&#146;s comments came at the recent launch of Egon Ronay Alert, the
Internet-based voice of the Egon Ronay Inner Circle, a new action group that
seeks to force higher standards of service for high-paying international
travelers.  &#147;I am declaring war on poor services,&#148; said Ronay.  &#147;Egon
Ronay Alert will reveal the good and expose the bad.  There is now no hiding
place for those providing sub-standard services, whether they are leading
airlines, 5-star hotels, or multi-starred restaurants with absent chefs.&#148; 
<BR></P>
<P>&#147;Our sophisticated electronic systems ensure that within hours of
getting feedback from Inner Circle members, service providers can be downgraded
or upgraded on our barometers of satisfaction, and that information immediately
broadcast globally.&#148;  Confidential sources within the travel industry and
snap visits by Egon Ronay &#147;inspectors&#148; will complement the feedback. 
Ronay&#146;s move is an imaginative attempt to employ electronic media as a tool
of consumer pressure.  The strength of the name leading the campaign should
produce real results.  Yet the project is confined to the top-end of the market.
 Travelers on more run-of-the-mill budgets have an even greater need for a
similar high-profile initiative.  Over to you...   &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><I>You can read the full text of Mr. Ronay&#146;s report, &quot;Tale of Two
Concordes&quot;, on the <B>Egon Ronay Alert</B> website at
<A HREF="http://www.egon-ronay.infocomint.com/">http://www.egon-ronay.infocomint.com</A>.
 The site requires visitors to fill out a brief registration form, then allows
free access for 60 days.  After the trial period, an &#147;Inner Circle&#148;
annual membership of $250 is required, which includes two members-only dinners
with Mr. Ronay at luxurious dining establishments (scheduled in January 1997 at
the Dorchester in London, and the Pierre Hotel in New York).    The subscription
fee is not inexpensive, but neither is the class of travel to which Mr. Ronay's
expertise is applied.  If you&#146;re the sort of traveler who needs to know the
latest engagements of Europe&#146;s top chefs, or what&#146;s been done lately
to the lobby of the Savoy, these reports might be just your cup of tea.       &#151;Ed.
</I></P>
<HR>
