<HTML><HEAD><TITLE></TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/redev3.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H2>Submission Guidelines</H2>
<HR>
<P>
<B>European Visits</B> seeks article submissions from both experienced travel
writers and ordinary travelers (not to mention extraordinary travelers!). 
Articles accepted as features are paid at a minimum of $.05 per word, with
several accepted per month.  We're  also happy to consider amateur contributions
in any category; these are not paid but  the author receives a byline, a free
print-edition subscription, and one of our <B>&quot;I'd rather be in Europe...&quot;</B>
T-shirts, aprons, jumbo mugs, or mouse pads.</P>
<P><I>Professional writers:</I> <B>PLEASE SPECIFY</B> with submission if you
are submitting for paid consideration only. We recognize that .05/word is not a
great rate and hope to do better in the future as the publication gets on its
feet; in the meantime, if you're an experienced pro feel free to include your
credits, name your price, and we'll do what we can.</P>
<P><B>Subject matter:</B> Our publication is about <I>visiting Europe</I>. 
We'll include material on Israel &amp; other Middle Eastern countries, and also
Iceland, as many travelers combine visits to these places with  stopovers in
Europe.  Turkey, Eastern Europe and Russia are within our range. We can't use 
material on Caribbean, Hawaii, South America, Africa, Asia, India, Australia, or
 North America.  (They're all fascinating places and someone should start online
magazines  about visiting them -- or someone already has.  But we didn't.)  We
are also interested  in good, short pieces about the processes &amp; pitfalls of
travel in general, primarily for  the <I>Travel Tips</I> category, and will use
an occasional piece on nifty or unusual travel gear  in the <I>Reviews</I>
category.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Categories</B></P>
<P><I>General:</I> Articles of general interest on the subject of European
travel.  Length 500-2500 words.  One or two images are a plus but maps &amp;
sketches are preferred to photos. Previously published work okay provided you
can convey relevant reprint rights.  Review: Share your personal experience with
a hotel, restaurant, nightclub, museum, activity, train route, guided tour, or
whatever, that made a particular impression on you. Length 200-1000 words.
Include the basic what-where-who-how much, and indicate when your own experience
took place.  Negative reviews may occasionally be used though we prefer to focus
on what's good out there.  Multiple short reviews with or without a common theme
can be sent as one submission.  </P>
<P>Note: Reviews is the largest article category in European Visits and  the
easiest for amateur contributors to get into.   Hints for first-timers: Keep it
simple, be  concise, tell what you know.  Be scrupulously honest with your
fellow travelers. 
</P>
<P><I>Travel Tips:</I> Any pearls of wisdom on the overall topic of planning,
enjoying &amp; surviving European travel.  Length: 50-500 words.  EV is largely
intended for veteran travelers, but basic advice can be useful if it's
well-written and has some original angles.</P>
<P><I>Special Interest:</I> Articles focused on European travel as it relates
to specific interests, hobbies, vocations, or lifestyles.  Examples could
include academic or study trips,  cooking-school vacations, language immersion,
gay &amp; lesbian interests, religious pilgrimage, antique hunting, etc. (A very
wide etc!)  Length: 500-1500 words.   
</P>
<P><I>Current Events:</I> Articles offering timely information on what's going
on in European culture or politics.  Length: 150-500 words. Preference given to
articles submitted by European residents.  Also, see Europe Writes...(below). 
</P>
<P><I>Europe Writes:</I> Limited exclusively to articles submitted by native
or expatriate European   residents.  Length: 150-750 words.  Any topic relating
to your local area or country, but keep in mind that you're writing for
visitors.  Articles submitted in your native language with accompanying English
translation are of particular interest (total length of both should fall within
guidelines). 
</P>
<P><I>Destinations:</I> Articles about specific cities, regions, or countries.
 Length: 500-2500 words.   Quality prose is always appreciated, but be
informative as well as poetic.  Write for people who will actually go there and
tell them what they need to know.  (What do you wish  you'd known before you
went?)  Out-of-the-way spots &amp; Eastern European locales are particularly
desired, but don't hesitate to offer more common destinations if you can do them
well. 
</P>
<P><I>Itineraries:</I>  This special category is specifically for itineraries
created with  Personal Programs' EuroData&#174; travel-planning software for
Microsoft Windows (The software  is available for free download from our Web
site at http://www.eurodata.com), or from CompuServe's Travel Forum Library
(Europe Section).   Itinerary submissions should include both a text description
-- tell us why it's a <I>fabulous</I> itinerary -- as well as the EuroData
<TT>.itn</TT> file itself.  Published itineraries, past and present, will be
made available for other EuroData users to download for their own adaptation. 
Text length: 50-150 words.  (Most descriptive text should go in the itinerary's
Daily Notes or Itinerary Notebook sections - be sure to send any <TT>.nt</TT>
files that go along  with the itinerary.)  Maximum itinerary length: 21 days. 
</P>
<P><I>Jokes, cartoons, poetry, fiction:</I> We'd like a sprinkling of these
now &amp; then.  Be careful  with jokes:  if you read it in print or on-line,
it's likely to be copyrighted.  Cartoons should be line art only (2-color depth)
and not over 3k (also see Image Guidelines).  Poetry and fiction can be up to
5,000 words but we only publish &quot;liner notes&quot; (50-100 words) which you
must provide; the actual content is made available to interested readers via an
FTP download. 
</P>
<HR><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/redevptr.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>Check Us Out:</I> (For the travel trade only) Unabashed self promotion! 
If you have a terrific  European travel product, travelers' service,  Web site,
publication, or anything commercial that will interest European visitors, tell
us about it here.  This is not paid advertising -- acceptance is based on the
degree of interest &amp; value we see in what you present.  The  unusual
opportunity or unusually good value gets our attention.  Strictly limited to
specific European travel offers: half-price clubs, win-a-free-vacation contests,
card mill schemes and the like are not of interest.  Always include pull dates.</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Where to send:</B></P>
<P>
Submissions by email are greatly preferred.  Send via CompuServe (72677,3722) or
Internet (eurodata@kc.grapevine.com) as messages for shorter pieces or as
attached .txt files.  Send submissions on disk (3.5&quot; dos compatible only)
or hard copy to:	 Personal Programs, 4718 Neptune Circle, Ferndale WA 98248.</P>
<P>Miscellaneous Notes: Include SASE if you want postal submissions returned. 
Response is by email only, usually  within 30 days.  Payment for paid
submissions within 30 days of publication, by check via  postal mail.  Please
include your SSN if you are submitting for pay as we will need it before we can
cut a check.  We retain reprint rights for 1 year after first appearance,  after
which all rights revert to author.</P>
<HR>
<P><I>Return to <A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/eurodata.htm">EuroData Home
Page</A></I></P></BODY></HTML>
