<TITLE>European Visits: Europe Writes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800000">
<P><EM><STRONG>European Visits:</STRONG> A Newsletter of European Travel</EM></P>
<P><EM>July / August 1996</EM></P>
<HR>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004080">Europe Writes...</FONT></H1>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Notes from London by David Whitehouse</FONT></EM></P>
<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Tunnels: The Great Escape?</FONT><BR></H2>
<P>Constant traffic congestion and poor public transport hinder many visitors'
enjoyment of the huge variety of attractions offered by London. Whoever is tired
of London is tired of life, observed Dr. Samuel Johnson two centuries ago. But
the difficulties of moving around mean that many are now simply tired of the
capital.<BR></P>
<P>Today, at peak times, the famous black taxis and red double-decker buses
travel no faster than a horse and cart. The 2-km trip from Trafalgar Square to
St Paul's Cathedral can take 45 minutes by cab. In the 1980s it was believed
that congestion would be relieved by a huge new ringroad which now encircles
London. But the British  experience has been that building more roads simply
encourages more traffic. The tube is the world's longest underground rail
network, but is plagued by endless breakdowns. The above-ground rail network is
also appalling. Poor transport infrastructure is a major problem that will have
to be overcome if Greenwich is to successfully host the Millennium celebrations
in the year 2000.<BR></P>
<P>An ambitious plan to reroute traffic underground through a series of deep
tunnels presents at least a glimmer of hope. The scheme, which has been granted
government funding for a feasibility study, was dreamt up by Gabriel Khoury, a
research fellow at Imperial College. A series of double-decker tunnels would be
built from the edge of London into the centre, where the traffic would arrive at
massive new underground car parks. The tunnels would bypass the inner suburbs
and would allow rapid, free-flowing access into the centre of London, which at
present is impossible to achieve. As well as reducing journey times, the tunnels
could improve central London's environment, which at present is disfigured by
the swathes of traffic. Dr. Khoury cites similar plans in Boston, where the aim
is to put 18% of traffic underground, and claims that his strategy for London
could be implemented within the early years of the next decade.<BR></P>
<P>A crucial feature of the propose routes, to be called London Expressways, is
that they would be tolled, probably at a rate of between 40p and 70p per mile.
Britain has yet to break away from its habit of treating roads as a free good.
Massive overuse of roads is the consequence, with the consumer not having to
bear any of the enormous costs that result from blocked highways. Road access,
particularly on a small, crowded island, is a scarce commodity and should be
priced accordingly. Dr. Khoury's tunnels may or may not prove to be a viable
solution in engineering terms. But any transport strategy that allows free road
access into central London to persist will be doing a disservice to the millions
who visit the capital each year.<BR></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Air travel: State Aid Junkies</FONT><BR></H2>
<P>Travelers stand to gain from greater competition in the industries that
service them. That applies in air transport as much as in other sectors. But
European Commission policies on state aid often seem designed to hinder rather
than help the development of more competitive services. Financial assistance
from governments for poor quality airlines can have a huge impact in an industry
where margins are thin. The badly managed and uncompetitive are rewarded, and
innovative new entrants are firmly discouraged. <BR></P>
<P>Neil Kinnock, the European Union (EU) transport commissioner, talks tough on
state aid. He says it must be justified by the &quot;market investor&quot;
principle -- financial help can only be approved if a private investor would
reasonably make the same cash injection in expectation of a future profit. Aid,
he argues, should be given on a &quot;first time, only time&quot; basis.  
However, Iberia, the Spanish flag carrier, is a prime example of how EU member
states have been allowed to get away with propping up ailing national airlines
with generous dollops of state aid. A Pta120bn handout for Iberia was approved
in 1992, on condition that there was no further application for help before the
end of 1996. But Iberia was back for more in late 1994, with a request for
clearance of aid worth Pta130bn. After a hugely bureaucratic round of
consultations, approval for part of the aid, worth Pta87bn, was given at the
start of this year. Yet another helping, worth Pta20bn, is to be considered
early next year. Iberia continues to suffer from heavy losses and high service
costs. So much for the market investor principle. The Iberia case has
established a precedent that other state airlines will grasp at as soon as they
run into trouble. TAP and Sabena, respectively the Portuguese and Belgian
national airlines, have also benefited from generous Commission decisions.<BR></P>
<P>National airlines across the EU have been coming under increasing pressure
from low-cost startups. Competition will intensify in April next year with
deregulation of the air industry in Europe. Airlines in EU countries will be
free to undertake domestic flights in other member states, and all players will
be keen to present themselves as eligible alliance partners. But the political
forces which defend the special interests of national carriers may mean that
traveling customers do not reap the full benefits.<BR></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">Air travel: cut out the middle man</FONT> <BR></H2>
<P>Stelios Haji-Ioannou is not yet 30 but his US-style cut-price airline
easyJet is making inroads into the European air travel market. His bright orange
aircraft have the company telephone number emblazoned in huge digits on the
fuselage. Haji-Ioannou proposes to cut the travel agent out of the equation and
sell you flight tickets for as little as &#163;29 ($45). <BR></P>
<P>Competing entirely on price unfortunately tends to recall the days of
Freddie Laker. But Haji-Ioannou is confident he has a winning formula. EasyJet
started flying between Luton, in southern England, and Scotland, and has now
grown to take in Amsterdam, Nice and Barcelona. 250,000 seats have already been
sold.  Cutting out the travel agent is an essential part of the easyJet recipe. 
&quot;The whole concept of the travel agent is absurd,&quot; says Haji-Ioannou. 
&quot;They appear to be agents of the traveler but are actually agents of the
airlines.&quot;  He argues that traditional ticketing systems add a whole
unnecessary layer of cost and proudly claims never to have paid travel agents a
penny. Direct advertising and telephone sales take their place. Passengers pay
by credit card over the telephone and are sent a receipt with a confirmation
number. They simply present this number along with their identification when
they arrive at the airport. The entire administrative staff of easyJet amounts
to 12; Haji-Ioannou is passionate about abolishing paper and insists that every
document to arrive at the offices is scanned into the computer system before
being thrown away.<BR></P>
<P>Using Luton rather than London is another reason why such low fares are
possible. EasyJet reckons this saves about $15 per passenger. Prices depend on
how far ahead you book as well as how popular the time at which you wish to
travel. A &#163;29 flight to Scotland could turn into &#163;59 if you leave it
too late and want to go on a busy Friday flight. <BR></P>
<P>All too good to be true? The sky is not entirely clear for Haji-Ioannou.
Together with his father he owns the Troodos Maritime shipping line. In 1991,
one of its tankers, the<I> Haven,</I> blew up in Genoa, killing five and
causing a major environmental disaster. Haji-Ioannou and his father still stand
accused of manslaughter. An obsession with safety at easyJet may be one
beneficial by-product of the disaster:  &quot;If you think safety is expensive,
try an accident.&quot;   &#164;<BR></P>
<P><I>David Whitehouse is a journalist who has recently moved from London to
Paris.</I></P>
<HR>
<H2>Floating Currency</H2>
<P><EM><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">From Travel Weekly &quot;Insider&quot;</FONT></EM><BR></P>
<P>Anyone who ever has stood in an overseas bank line, squinting at the red
electronic listing of exchange rates, has yearned for a single currency
standard.  Now the world finally has a new option for a key currency:  the
disposable underwater camera.  A firm selling satellite communications systems
for cruise ships sent a cover letter to <I>Insider</I> saying &quot;at an
affordable $9.50 per minute, a one-minute call costs less than a disposable
underwater camera.&quot;  Statements like that are the main reason <I>Insider</I>
owns a calculator.<BR></P>
<P>By <I>Insider</I>'s calculation, that means a typical ship-to-shore call
costs the equivalent of 4.73 disposable underwater cameras, or &quot;ducs&quot;
(in homage to the European Union's proposed &quot;ecu&quot;).  Therefore, a
seven-day eastern Caribbean cruise aboard Royal Caribbean's Sovereign of the
Seas starts at 73.57 ducs, per person, double occupancy, excluding air.  The
agent commission on that booking, of course, would be 7.3 ducs.  And Royal
Caribbean's six-ship construction program will eventually cost the cruise
company 157,894,736.84 disposable underwater cameras.<BR></P>
<P>That's payable by check, because they just don't make camera bags that big. 
&#164;<BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FF0080">This tongue-in-cheek bit originally appeared in
the April 29, 1996 issue of <B>Travel Weekly</B>.  Reprinted by permission. 
<B>Travel Weekly</B> is the newspaper of the travel industry, published twice
each week by Reed Travel Group.  For subscription information, call <STRONG>(800)
360-0015</STRONG>.</FONT></I></P>
