<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Historic Flanders /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Historic Flanders</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>By Nick Gregory</I></FONT></B></P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Historic Flanders by Nick Gregory--><BR></P>
<P>Art nouveau facades face Renaissance facades, across cobbled streets lined
with street cafes serving dark Trappist and sweet beers.  Flowers line the canal
and cascade in colorful window boxes.  Here is found the legacy of the grand
centres of Northern European merchant trade. 
<BR></P>
<P>Lying between Brussels, Amsterdam, Paris and London, the historic towns of
Flanders ring a bell for both the past splendors of merchant trade, and a
strong, stubborn character, which carries with it joviality and a relaxed
atmosphere.  Beer and waffles, canals and castles are all here to be enjoyed,
through narrow cobbled streets and in majestic cathedral squares.  The scene is
marked by a diverse wide range of influences:  Spanish, British, French, Dutch.

<BR></P>
<P>Bruges&#151;&#147;Bruges the Beautiful&#148; as it is often described&#151;is
one of the loveliest towns in Europe.  Having reached the peak of prosperity
under the rule of the House of Burgundy in the 14th and 15th centuries, it
became a centre of artistic excellence, attracting such painters as Van Eyck,
Memling and Van der Groes.  An exceptionally important collection of works can
be viewed at the Groeninge Museum (Municipal Museum of Fine Arts) and at the
Memling Museum.  The best way to see the city and its fine treasures is to take
one of the canal tours, which run from March through October, and on weekends
during December and holiday periods.  They depart from several locations,
leaving for a round trip every 35 minutes.  The canals themselves (known as
Reien) take you through some of the loveliest  parts of the city, which was once
an important maritime port.  Its transcontinental connections were dependent on
its canal network, and linked to the open sea by the Zwin.  The rather
wonderfully named &#147;Lake of Love&#148; or Minnewater was the original
interior port.  
<BR></P>
<P>Just a few minutes walk from the Minnewater is the Princely Beguinage of the
Vine.  Founded in 1245, the tiny white-washed houses are arranged around a
grassy square, and although the Beguines have moved elsewhere there are still
Benedictine nuns living here.  A sense of calm and tranquillity pervades in the
whispered silence. 
<BR></P>
<P>The Burg Square, which contains the ornate Town hall, Old Registry, Palace
of Justice and the Basilica of the Holy Blood (dating back as far as the 12th
century), is most impressive with turreted and steepled roofs and intricate
masonry work forming statues and bas-reliefs on the facade of the 14th century
town hall, depicting biblical and historical scenes.  Inside the Old Registry is
the main tourist information office for the city.  In summer months, the square
also acts as the starting point for horse-drawn carriage tours. 
<BR></P>
<P>Near Burg Square is the Market Square, dominated by the Belfry at its
southern end.  Here is perhaps the place to enjoy one of the city&#146;s fine
beers, a Brugse Tripel or a heavy dark Straffe Hendrik.  But beware&#151;it is a
potent brew if drunk in the afternoon. 
<BR></P>
<P>For those foot weary from slogging around the sights of Europe on a
whistle-stop tour, try hiring a bicycle from the railway station, a bike shop,
or even some of the hotels. There are ubiquitous cycle-lanes away from the
traffic, and priority is more often than not given to cyclists at junctions. 
The terrain is flat and a few minutes of pedaling can soon have you out into the
polderlands, perhaps following a tree-lined canal to the lovely small town of
Damme, only 8km away.  Keep a look out for the picturesque windmills&#151;and
don&#146;t overdo it on the Damme Pralines (chocolate truffles) or Damme Mokke
(blue cheese).  Alternatively, take the paddle-steamer that shuttles to Bruges
and back between April and September. 
<BR></P>
<P>About 50km southeast of Bruges is its twin and for centuries its chief
rival, Gent (also spelled Ghent or Gand).  The ancient capital of the County of
Flanders, the city has a unique atmosphere quite different from the romantic
charms of Bruges.  Artistic refinement and an ancient vitality are strongly
evident.  The church of St Niklaas, which reflects the evolution of the Scheldt
Gothic style through the 13th, 14th and early 15th centuries, is situated
between the bridge of St Michiel, which itself offers superb views of the major
sights in the central area, and the Belfry, which contained the bell (the &#147;Klokke
Roeland&#148;) used to call the citizens of the city to arms.  A small park
below the tower contains its successor, &#147;De Triomfante&#148; cast in 1660. 
<BR></P>
<P>Beyond the Belfry is St Baafs Cathedral, the scene of the baptism of Emperor
Charles in 1500 and the home of the &#147;Adoration of the Mystic Lamb&#148; by
the brothers Van Eyck.  Painted in 1426-32, it portrays the redemption of
humanity and on the reverse are the portraits of the sponsors.  Also on view in
the cathedral is the &#147;Conversion of St Bavo&#148; by Rubens. 
<BR></P>
<P>Some remarkable buildings are to be found along the Graslei and Korenlei,
near the Bridge of St Michiel which were the old trading quays.  These merchant
houses and Guildhalls date from the 12th to 17th centuries in an assortment of
styles, including Romanesque, Gothic, and Renaissance.  Their reflections in the
still waters of the canal make a beautiful sight.  In addition to the
traditional boat tours of the city, those seeking more adventure can hire a
mini-yacht to glide over the canals and the winding river Leie.  Each boat can
take four and booking is compulsory, although experience is not required. 
<BR></P>
<P>Just off the canal system in the city but surrounded by its own moat is the
Castle of the Counts or &#147;Gravensteen&#148; which was built for Philip of
Alsace in the 12th century.  In the style of the Crusader castles in Syria, it
contains a small museum with what are referred to as &#147;instruments of legal
procedure&#148;.  It&#146;s a torture chamber!  A bit more fun is the Gent
Festival, held in mid-July for ten days around the St Jacobs area.  It involves
street theatre, music and dance among other things and tends to turn the place
upside down. 
<BR></P>
<P>In the middle ages, together with Bruges and Gent, Ypres (Leper) was one of
the wealthiest cities in Flanders. However, a series of wars and sieges after
the 13th century led to its gradual decline until the First World War, when as
part of the western salient during the entire 4-year period it was completely
destroyed.  Since that time, the original buildings have been painstakingly
restored to their original plans and the rich heritage of the town and its
tenacious people can be enjoyed again. 
<BR></P>
<P>The entire region of Westhoek is still marked by that conflict.  With
countless cemeteries filled by row upon row of identical white crosses, it is
clear just how many lives were lost.  Every evening, at the Menen Gate, the Last
Post is played by a bugler in commemoration.  About 12 km west of Ypres is the
town of Poperinge, the hops capital of the Belgium, where this vital ingredient
for beer is referred to as &#147;green gold&#148; and is celebrated bi annually
in either the Hops Festival or the National Beer Weekend, which occurs in the
third weekend of September&#151;the only difference being that there is no &#147;Hops
Parade&#148; during odd years.  If you arrive at any other time, there are a
large number of specialty beers available in the local taverns, including the
Watou Witbier (white beer). 
<BR></P>
<P>Traveling north towards the coast some 30km is Veurne (Furnes).  It is often
known as &#147;Spanish Veurne,&#148; because it was under the control of the
Archdukes Alberto and Isabela of Navarre when it reached its peak of prosperity
in the 17th century.  The historical GroteMarkt is surrounded by step-gabled
houses in the Flemish Renaissance style and in the yellow-brick, so typical of
this Westhoek region as well as the blue-stone facade of the town hall.  The
numerous cafes in the square are excellent for trying the Babelutten caramels or
a Slapers bier (sleepers beer). 
<BR></P>
<P>In all, Flanders holds a wealth of variety and history.  &#164;</P>
<HR>
<P><B>Information</B>: Belgian Tourist Office, 780,Third Ave Suite 1501, New
York NY 10017; Telephone 212 758-81-30; Fax 212 355-7675 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Getting there</B>: Air&#151;The nearest major international airport is
Brussels, although good connections to the area are available from Amsterdam,
Paris and London.   Rail&#151;Direct services to Brussels operate from
Amsterdam, Paris, London, Cologne and several other international cities. Change
at Brussels for connections to Gent and Bruges. Change at Gent for Veurne and
Kortrijk for Ypres and Poperinge. Rail services are fast and frequent.  A return
fare from Brussels to Bruges costs around $15. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Bruges (Brugge)</B>: Easily accessible by train with at least two trains
per hour from Brussels.    There is a bus service from the station to the centre
of the city.  Also large car parks around centre, but do not drive into central
area as chaos will ensue.  Boat excursions on the canals run from March to
October and in December and holidays. Cost is 150 BEF per person.  You can also
become what the tourist office refers to as a &#147;privileged visitor&#148; by
hiring a bicycle; available from the station or one of several hire shops (and
some hotels) for around 275BEF, or 150BEF with a valid rail ticket.  Horse and
buggy rides through the centre are available March to October for 800BEF per
carriage (max 5 persons) and lasts about 35 minutes.  Departing the Burg except
Wednesdays, when they depart from the Belfry.  There are also minibus tours of
the centre in many languages (headphones provided) for around 330BEF. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Gent (Ghent)</B>: Frequent rail services, twice an hour to Brussels and
Bruges as well as Luxembourg, Antwerp and the coast.  From the station take
trams1, 10, 11 or 12 for the Koren Markt and centre.  Gent is located at the
intersection of two of Europes major motorways and offers easy road access. 
River and canal excursions from the Graslei and Korenlei cost around 150BEF. 
For mini-yacht hire from the Coupure-Lindelei, call Rederij Minerva on
09/221.84.51.  In July and August there are boat trips to Bruges and Deurle, but
check with the Tourist Office for dates in 1997.  From April to October there
are walking tours available which last two hours and are in different languages.
These depart every day at 14.30hrs from the tourist office. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Ypres (Leper) and Poperinge</B>:  Train connections to major cities via
Kortrijk and bus number 744 runs from Ypres and Poperinge to Veurne.  For war
cemetery information contact the local tourist office in Ypres and guided tours
are available.  In Poperinge there are boulder lifting competitions (info:
057/33.40.81) after which you may need to involve yourself in the Hops festival
or Beer Weekend on the third weekend of September which is more of a pageant and
connoisseurs event than a binge. In 1997 the Beer weekend will be held and 98
will see the festival. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Veurne (Furnes)</B>: Situated on the Gent-de Panne route with trains
every two hours.  An organized walk around the town including a guide brochure,
entry to the Town Hall, Bakery Museum  and a lunch stop can be arranged by the
tourist office. There are a number of signed cycle routes in the Veurne-Ambacht
region including some to the nearby coastal resorts, descriptive brochures and
hire details also available from the tourist office. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Budget Accommodation</B>: Hostels&#151;There are two in the Bruges area
(050/53 26 79 for the closest to the centre).  Gent (09/233 70 50) , Vleteren 
(between Ypres and Veurne 057/40 09 01) and Kortrijk (056/20 14 42).   
Campgrounds&#151;There are easily accessible sites near Bruges, Gent, at Kemmel
near Ypres/ Poperinge and at Koksijde near Veurne.</P>
