<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Hungary; Budapest /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Side Trips</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>Branching Out From Budapest; by Andrea Kirkby</I></FONT></B></P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Side Trips  Branching Out From Budapest by Andrea Kirkby-->
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rail6.gif" ALT="(Access by rail)" ALIGN="LEFT"><B>Szekesfehervar</B>
is one of Hungary&#146;s historic towns.  Istvan I founded the royal basilica
here in 1016, and for hundreds of years the kings of Hungary were crowned here. 
Nowadays, though, much of its glory has faded.  The basilica is ruined, and
though you can visit some interesting ruins of it, with a few delicate carvings,
and some odds and ends of stonework, the medieval feeling has gone.  In fact the
only medieval part left is the Gothic Chapel of St Anne.  However, there are
still some pretty houses, and one site definitely worth a visit is the &#145;Black
Eagle&#146; pharmacy museum.  I must admit that pharmacy museums tend to be all
the same&#151;there&#146;s one in Aix, I think I&#146;ve seen one in Krakow&#151;but
if you haven&#146;t seen one, the array of glass jars, earhtenware sarcophagi,
and venerable old counters is a real fairytale.<BR></P>
<P><B>Holloko</B> is a UNESCO world heritage site, and unfortunately places
like this can sometimes feel rather too well preserved. But the site, under a
castle ruin, is characteristic, and the array of beautiful old houses is worth
seeing.  It&#146;s disappointing, though, to note that most of the old people
have decided to sell these pretty, but impractical houses, and move to new&#151;and
architecturally undistinguished&#151;houses elsewhere.  If you can spare the
time, the countryside around this area deserves your investigation. Hungary&#146;s
ranges of hills are not particularly high or scenic compared to Poland&#146;s or
Slovakia&#146;s Tatras, or the Romanian landscape of Transylvania, but they have
a delicate beauty all to themselves.<BR></P>
<P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rail6.gif" ALT="(Access by rail)" ALIGN="LEFT"><B>Esztergom</B>
is the ecclesiastical capital of Hungary&#151;the home of Hungarian Catholicism.
 Its looks tally with its status; the 1850s classical basilica which dwarfs the
town is reputed to be one of the five biggest churches in the world.  Like many
classical buildings in Hungary it completely ignores landscape and townscape,
but its brooding presence gives Esztergom a special atmosphere.  Don&#146;t
forget to visit the crypt underneath, where the Archbishops rest in a circular &#145;Egyptian&#146;
mausoleum&#151;spectacular and spooky.  If subterranean gloom doesn&#146;t
appeal, you can go up to the dome for a panorama of the Hungarian mountain
ranges, such as they are. 
<BR></P>
<P>One small piece of past glory remains: the red marble Bakocz chapel, a
Renaissance marvel.  Apparently when the basilica was built, this chapel was
taken apart piece by piece, every item numbered, and eventually put back
together again just as it used to be.  Some parts of the Romanesque royal palace
also remain, though they appear to have been heavily restored in some places;
Esztergom, like other Hungarian towns, came in for some battering from the
Turks.  
<BR></P>
<P>If you like <I>Mozartkugeln</I>, <I>gemutlichkeit</I> and Salzburgisch
charm, go straight to Szechenyi ter and the rococo.  The handsome houses and
Town Hall are more fun than wandering around trying to find original Romanesque
fenestration plans&#151;at least they were for my companion, who doesn&#146;t
share my obsession with collecting every piece of Romanesque architecture east
of Vienna. 
<BR></P>
<P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rail6.gif" ALT="(Access by rail)" ALIGN="LEFT"><B>Visegrad</B>
sits on the best part of the Danube bend, where it runs constrained by narrow
gorges between the Borzsony and Pilis hills.  It was the residence of kings from
the fourteenth century, but its greatest days were the days of Matthias Corvinus&#151;Matyas
&#145;the Crow&#146; (he had one on his coat of arms).  Matyas, Hungary&#146;s
Renaissance king,  led a court the equal of any in Europe in culture and
gracious living. 
<BR></P>
<P>The original fort was built in the mid-thirteenth century, with an immense
hexagonal tower at the centre of the foritfications.  From the fortress, there&#146;s
a view of the entire Danube bend laid out below.  Later, the Visegrad palace
became the focus of struggles between the various kings and claimants&#151;since
the Holy Crown of Hungary was kept here, and only one crowned with this crown
was the rightful king.  But it&#146;s Matyas&#146;s wonderful buildings and rich
cultural heritage that amaze the visitor today. 
<BR></P>
<P>Visegrad&#146;s most recent claim to fame is its hosting of the Visegrad
Accords of 1991, when Arpad Goncz of Hungary, Lech Walesa of Poland and Vaclav
Havel of the Czech Republic sat down to sign an agreement between their three
countries for a post-Communist future.  I certainly hope they enjoyed their
visit to this pleasant place.   
<BR></P>
<P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rail6.gif" ALT="(Access by rail)" ALIGN="LEFT"><B>Szentendre</B>
was a refuge for the Serbs, fleeing from Turkish invasions in the seventeenth
century. Out of its seven churches, four are Serbian - at least if the
iconostases are anything to go by.  Greeks and Dalmatians also fled here, liking
the culturally tolerant town. Besides the churches - the Catholic parish church
and its Serbian counterpart are isolated on top of the hill, surrounded by a
cobbled market and a little wall - there are some nice baroque houses on the
fine main square (actually a triangle). But the town has become a real tourist
trap with too many tatty folk art shops.<BR></P>
<P><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/rail6.gif" ALT="(Access by rail)" ALIGN="LEFT"><B>Vac</B>
is a delightful baroque town. It had a bishop as early as the eleventh century,
but it now posseses a classical cathedral in among the other eighteeneth-century
buildings, and has a number of lovely churches. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Pannonhalma</B>, for those with a spirit of adventure and a car&#151;or
access to one of the coach tours for pilgrims&#151;is a wonderful and very
strange place.  In the whole plain of Pannonia there seems to be only one hill
of any size, and the monastery of Pannonhalma is jammed down right on top of it.
 The monastery goes back to the twelfth century or before, and there&#146;s a
very fine doorway with wonderful carving and glowing red marble, but externally
it now looks very classical. A guided tour will show you round in about half an
hour, but you can easily spend more time here walking in the gardens beneath the
monastery or just looking at the amazing view from the balcony. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Szambek</B>&#151;or <I>Schambeck</I> should you be a German-speaker&#151;is
an unspoilt little village about half an hour&#146;s drive from Budapest. 
Higgledy-piggledy houses, palisaded farmyards, and above it all a magnificent
ruined Romanesque abbey.  One of my favourite places round Budapest.  On the way
back, I had to stop as a deer and her fawn decided to cross the road in front of
me.  
<BR></P>
<P><I>Other side trips:</I><BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Take a cruise</B> down, or preferably up, the Danube.  The most
interesting places (Esztergom, Visegrad, Szentendre) are all north of Budapest,
whereas the southern stretch is really for nuclear power station lovers. 
Cruises leave from near the Vigado concert house.  If you&#146;re in the mood,
it&#146;s possible to take the not-so-blue Danube all the way to Vienna.<BR></LI>
<LI><B>The Great Plains.</B>  Country-lovers will want to take a trip into the
Nagyalfold to the south of Budapest. It&#146;s an extensive plain, a region
proud of its horses and its horsemanship through the centuries. Rumour has it
that some of the horses here are even better trained, and perform even better
tricks, the the Spanish Riding School&#146;s Lippizaner stallions. The plain is
dotted with little houses, each with its own well - a bucket swung from a pole,
a characteristic construction. Ocsa, a pretty village with thatched houses, is
probably the first place to make for.  &#164;</LI></UL>
<HR>
