<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Paris / Travel
Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#408080" VLINK="#004080"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo6.gif">
<P><BR></P>
<H2><I><FONT SIZE="+4" COLOR="#FF0080">Of Magic, Fans, and Piaf</FONT></I></H2>
<P><B><FONT SIZE="+2"><I>&quot;Little-Known Museums In and Around Paris&quot;
-- A Book Review</I></FONT></B></P><IMG SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evline.gif">
<P><!--Of Magic, Fans, and Piaf  Little-Known Museums In and Around Paris A
Book Review-->
<B>So you&#146;ve looked at the Louvre</B> and elevated at the Eiffel.  You&#146;ve
mastered the medieval at Cluny and reviewed the revolution at Carnavalet.  Are
you done with Paris?<BR></P>
<P>Not even close!  It&#146;s possible that no city in Europe, and perhaps in
the world, boasts more unique, eclectic, and obscure museums than does the City
of Lights.  From tools to dolls, place-settings to pottery, magic to money,
Paris offers a dizzying array of special-interest visits to tickle even the most
jaded fancy.  Now, writer <B>Rachel Kaplan</B> has put together an enjoyable
compendium to help you sort through the options.<BR></P>
<P><I><B>Little-Known Museums In and Around Paris</B></I><I> (Henry N.
Abrams, 208pp, $19.95)</I> combines excellent photographs and detailed,
well-written overviews to profile 30 of Paris&#146; most interesting,
off-the-beaten-track museums.  All but eight are within the arrondissments of
the city; the remainder are an easy day trip, and most are accessible by public
transportation.  The book includes detailed M&eacute;tro directions for each
site, with driving or rail information for those further afield, and also
provides information on opening hours and days of operation (important, as they
can be odd and/or few).  Which of them will go on your must-see list depends on
your interests &amp; tastes; among those we find especially intriguing:<BR></P>
<UL>
<LI><I><B>Le Mus&eacute;e de la Curiosit&eacute; et de la Magic (The Museum
of Curiosities and Magic)</B></I>&#151;Open just three days a week in a series
of caves below the Marais district, this museum offers a fascinating look at the
history of magic and optical illusions, from tricks used to dazzle temple
visitors in ancient Egypt to the conjuring routines of minstrels and fools in
Europe&#146;s royal courts.  There are a variety of stage props and &#147;tools
of the trade&#148; on display from many different eras, plus profiles of famous
practitioners&#151;including the &#147;father of modern magic,&#148; one R.
Houdin, a 19th century magician so respected that a talented American would
later honor him with the stage name Harry Houdini.  Museum tours are available
in English, and there is a continuous magic show from 2:30pm until 6:00pm..   
<BR><I>Le Mus&eacute;e de la Curiosit&eacute; et de la Magic, 11 rue Saint
Paul, 75004 Paris; Tel. (01) 42-72-13-26.  
</I><BR></LI>
<LI><I><B>Le Mus&eacute;e de l&#146;Evantail (The Fan Museum)</B></I>&#151;Devoted
entirely to the &#147;quintessential accessory for the woman of fashion.&#148;
this small showroom features fans of every imaginable design, material, and
history.  The museum&#146;s own space was once the location of a tr&eacute;s
chic fan shop, and today curator Anne Hoguet&#151;herself a professional
fanmaker&#151; recreates both the elegance and the endless variety of this
nearly vanished art.  Open Tuesdays only, in the 10er.  <BR><I>Le Mus&eacute;e
de l&#146;Evantail, 2 Boulevard Strasbourg, 75010 Paris; Tel. (01) 42-08-19-89.</I><BR></LI>
<LI><I><B>Le Mus&eacute;e de l&#146;Outil (The Museum of Tools)</B></I>&#151;A
drive some 50km out of Paris, to the curiously-named town of Wy
dit-Joli-Village, will reward you with this homage to the skilled artistry of
farmers, smiths, and craftworkers in devising the implements of their trades
through the ages.  The collected items&#151;more than 3,500 all told&#151;range
from the ancient to the timeless, with curator Claude Pigeared paying special
attention to handcrafts that have largely disappeared in modern times, such as
rope- and nail-making.  The museum is located in the rooms of an excavated Roman
bathhouse, itself a national historic site.  It&#146;s open Sunday afternoons
only, though arrangements can be made for small groups on other days.
<BR><I>Le Mus&eacute;e de l&#146;Outil, Wy-dit-Joli-Village. 95240 Val d&#146;Oise;
Tel. (01) 34-67-41-79.  
</I><BR></LI></UL>
<P>These are just a taste&#151; <I>Little-Known Museums</I> offers
twenty-seven more, each a fascination in its own way.  A number of the museums
are devoted to particular artists &amp; performers (Edith Piaf, Erik Satie, and
Eug&egrave;ne Delacroix, among others) and will be of special interest to their
fans.  In each case Ms. Kaplan&#146;s coverage is both entertaining and thorough&#151;she
even explains the origin of that village name&#151;and you will only wish you
had time to visit each and every one of them.  But even if you must miss a few,
if you&#146;re going to Paris don&#146;t miss this book.  Highly
recommended.																<I>-MJT
</I></P>
<HR>
