<HTML><HEAD><TITLE></TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P><I>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel</I></P>
<H1>Where the Swiss Go</H1>
<P><I>by Jerri Clark Kirby</I></P>
<HR>
<P><BR></P>
<P>Rapperswil is a charming medieval town situated on the shores of  Lake
Zurich.  Its history goes back to the 13th century, and it is about as perfect a
place to relax as you can imagine. 
</P>
<P>The first buildings were constructed of wood;  they were rebuilt with stone
later in the late 13th and early 14th centuries.  The stone foundations are
massively, though gracefully, in evidence as you stroll through the streets. The
Rapperswil Castle, as old as the town itself, underwent restorations in the late
80's.  It houses a permanent Polish exhibition in memory of the Polish National
Museum, which was established in the same castle from 1870 to 1927 by Polish
emigrants, under the control of Count Ladislaus Plater. 
</P>
<P>You can get a good feel for the history of Rapperswil by merely strolling
through the streets and looking at the many pictures commemorating historical
events, painted on the walls of various homes and buildings.  The castle is the
oldest landmark in this town; the old parish church is the second oldest. These
two buildings dominate the medieval section; fortifications were built around
both buildings until a little over 150 years ago.  Rapperswil belongs to the
Canton (province or tiny state) of Gall and has about 8,500 inhabitants. 
Nicknamed the &quot;town of roses,&quot; Rapperswil boasts around 8,500 rose
bushes -- one for each inhabitant --  in the public gardens near an old Capuchin
monastery.  Impressively, the townspeople have provided a special rose garden
for the blind and disabled, offering special &quot;touch and smell&quot; bushes.
 
</P>
<P>Up on a hill above the public gardens is an open deer park.  Wild deer are
protected here and tame enough, in some cases, to be fed by willing tourists. 
Down by the waterside is an aquarium, stocked with all the known types of fish
found in Lake Zurich.  You can take lake tours, rent rowboats and sailboats, as
well as inner tubes.  Miniature golf and hot air balloon rides are offered,
along with a myriad of lakeside sports activities.  A few small islands, a short
distance from the shore, beckon boat renters who enjoy picnic lunches with the
many birds living there. Several seaside restaurants specialize in lake trout.
The first one we tried had an &quot;all you can eat&quot; menu of local lake
fish for a very reasonable cost. 
</P>
<P>The Knie Children's Zoo is a big draw in the summertime. The zoo is run by
the Swiss National Circus and you might catch a few impromptu circus acts; a
regular dolphin show equals anything I have seen in the U.S. and there are pony
rides, elephant rides and horse-drawn trams.  The monkeys are lots of fun to
watch and there is a petting zoo, which includes llamas.  A huge whale is part
of the Noah's Ark play yard and this is the only zoo in the world I've seen
where you walk through a human silhouette-shaped opening, according to your
size, instead of a gate or door! 
</P>
<P>Friday has traditionally been Market Day since 1415.  Fresh produce, fish,
spices, herbs, bread, cheese -- anything you can imagine that can be sold fresh
-- are available in this morning market.  There is also a shopping mall and
specialty shops where we found the best deal we had ever seen on Swiss cuckoo
clocks, from very small to very extravagant.  Scarves from India, carvings from
Africa, jewelry from the Middle East; the array of international products was
rather amazing and prices extremely reasonable. 
</P>
<P>There are maybe 10 hotels in Rapperswil and a few family hostels. The Swiss
wisely book all major holidays a year in advance; in fact, we saw few foreigners
in Rapperswil. Most were Swiss families enjoying Swiss hospitality.  From
Zurich, there are many ways to get to Rapperswil. You can drive out the Seedamn
Causeway; you can hop a train in Zurich, (which is really the best way), or you
can take a boat.  In any event, do stop in for a leisurely few hours in
Rapperswil.  Tourist information is readily available and, as in all of
Switzerland, English is spoken everywhere.   Now I know where the Swiss go in
the summer and why they keep it to themselves!  &#164;
</P>
<HR>
<P><I>Some online resources for Switzerland:</I></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.travel.org/switz.html">Switzerland Page in <I>Travel
Org</I></A></P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.switzerlandtourism.ch/">Switzerland Welcomes You!</A></P>
