<TITLE>European Visits: A Newsletter of European Travel - Shopping in Europe /
Travel Stories about Europe / Online Magazine / Travel in Europe / Amsterdam,
London, Milan, Rome, Frankfurt, Zurich, Madrid, Shannon, Glasgow</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000080" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FF00FF"><IMG
SRC="http://www.eurodata.com/evlogo.gif">
<HR>
<H2>Shopping: Europe's Classic Good Luxe</H2>
<P><BR><I>by Diane Marshall</I></P>
<P><B>Nothing quickens a woman's heart</B> --and many a man's -- more than
great shopping.  And nowhere does it come any better than in Europe.  What makes
it special is the European flair for chic styling, masterful design and
attention to detail, all of which are apparent in everything from fashion and
fabrics to crystal and ceramics, from evening wear and eyeglasses to watches and
writing instruments.  Europe entices with thousands of charming boutiques, whose
exquisite window displays tease of the treasures within.  The selection will
astound you.  The personal service, unique merchandise and alluring ambiance of
boutiques scattered throughout diverse neighborhoods affords a distinctive
shopping experience.  There's nothing as grand as Paris's rue de
Faubourg-Saint-Honore district with its ultra chic couture houses or as
sophisticated as London's Saville Road area, home to the world's best tailors. 
And who could imagine a Rome without the Piazza di Spagna, the nucleus for
Italian fashion?  Come, follow us through the far-flung streets of Europe on the
world's best shopping spree. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Paris</B>:  Both the Right Bank and Left Bank offer a dizzying profusion
of boutiques.  The former radiates luxury and sheer elegance.  Its ne plus
ultra-posh couture salons converge along the tony rue de Faubourg-Saint-Honore,
rue Saint-Honore, avenue Montaigne, Champs-Elysees, place de la Madeleine,
avenue George V and rue Francois 1er.  Even if you're not buying, a day spent
window shopping is a feast for the eyes.  For exclusive crystal, porcelain and
cutlery, shop either side of the Seine.  Big names reside on the rue de Paradis
(Left Bank) and rue Royale (Right Bank).  Likewise, art galleries and antique
shops dot the entire city, but three clusters deserve special attention:  the
Porte de Clignancourt flea market, the area south of the Seine and north of the
rue de l'Universite (Left Bank), and the district around the upper end of the
rue du Faubourg-Saint Honore (Right Bank). 
<BR></P>
<P>The Left Bank represents the pulse of Paris, a district of trends.  It's the
very heart of Parisian shopping.  The look is definitely hip, fashion-forward. 
The area's more avant-garde designers lure a young and savvy crowd that shops
for sophisticated costume jewelry, art books, exotic fragrances, fantasy
footwear and offbeat art.  The broad boulevard St. Germain, center of the
student quarter, bisects the Left Bank.  Though it has its share of trendy
boutiques, the bulk of the shopping is to either side of the boulevard, along
rue Jacob, rue de Seine, rue Bonaparte, rue des Saints-Peres, rue de
Furstenberg, rue de Beaune, rue Saint-Sulpice, rue du Bac and rue des Canettes. 
Fashion-smart women haunt Rue de Grenelle and rue des Saints-Peres (Left Bank)
for innovative shoes and equally forward clothing.  Their next stop might be Rue
d'Alesia, where prices are radically reduced in shops that sell last season's
designer stock and samples, or the rue de la Pompe, whose stores feature
second-hand designer and couture fashions, many worn only once or twice. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Brussels</B>:  Any serious shopping in Europe's capital begins in the
elegant galleries, covered pedestrian arcades lined with shops, boutiques and
cafes exuding a glossy international theme.  The Galeries Royales de
Saint-Hubert,  the most magnificent of the city's age-old shopping complexes,
was built in 1846, making it the world's first shopping mall.  It exemplifies
Belgian shopping at its most elegant, and is worth a visit just to see its
beautiful design.  Equally refined are the Galerie Louise, Galerie de la Toison
d'Or and their neighboring streets-Avenue Louise, a chestnut-lined boulevard
where soigne ladies stalk the best couture salons, art galleries and interior
decor showrooms; and Avenue de la Toison d'Or, whose trendy cafes, clothing
boutiques and art galleries cater to a youthful, professional clientele.
<BR></P>
<P>The Rue Neuve, a bustling pedestrian district near the Grand Place, may have
less polish, but no fewer places to spend your Belgian francs.  Major chain
stores compete with ready-to-wear boutiques, international toy stores,
department stores and book and souvenir shops.  Search for bargains at the Old
Market (place du Jeu de Balle), the quintessential flea market.  Its highbrow
weekend cousin, at the Place du Grand-Sablon, has better quality antiques. 
Place du Grand-Sablon is the center of Brussels' thriving art and antique trade.

<BR></P>
<P><B>Shannon</B>:  When Shannon Airport launched the world's first duty-free
airport store in 1947, it started a revolution in shopping.  Today there are
many pretenders to the title of best duty-free airport shop, but almost 50 years
later, Shannon remains at the top of many a serious shopper's list. It's a
single complex crammed with more terrific buys.  Names that used to be the
privilege of the jet-set crowd-Dunhill, Rolex, Waterman, Lancome-are now de
rigueur stock at Shannon.  And prices here are as attractive as the selection,
with savings of 20 to 40 percent on Irish sweaters and linens, tweed jackets and
ties, the best Irish and European crystal and china,  woolens, christening
gowns, toys, perfumes and collectible figurines. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Vienna</B>:  Satirist Karl Kraus remarked that &quot;the streets of
Vienna are surfaced with culture as the streets of other cities are with
asphalt.&quot;  We'd expect nothing less from this city of Habsburg aristocracy.
 The legacy of that era manifests itself today in the exquisite costume jewelry,
toys and tin soldiers, textiles, glass, porcelain and confectionery artfully
displayed in the windows of boutiques and cafes along the city's most
prestigious shopping streets:  Kohlmarkt, Graben Strasse and Kaerntner Strsse. 
In between some of the city's oldest stores, new designers cater to a young,
trendy market.  A number of fashion houses and souvenir shops specialize in
loden garments and other traditional Austrian folk costumes called Tracht.<BR></P>
<P>Mariahilfer Strasse boasts Vienna's two department stores, Herzmansky and
Gerngross, and a number of up market boutiques selling fashions, leather goods
and Austrian souvenirs.  Dorotheum, the 178-year-old auction house, may have
started as a pawn shop, but today it's as prestigious as Christie's and
Sotheby's.  Because it auctions merchandise that varies from bric-a-brac to
authentic Biedermeier, you often can take home a bargain.  Antique dealers and
galleries, many specializing in a single style or period, abound on neighboring
streets, between Spiegelgasse and Braeunerstrasse.  Head for Linke Wienzeile and
its side streets to buy less expensive antiques.  While browsing, admire the
architecture of the apartment buildings that at the turn of the century made
this a prestigious address.  Not far away is the Naschmarkt.  On Saturdays it
hosts a flea market at its southern end. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Glasgow</B>:  Buchanan Street is a microcosm of Scotland's best.  Myriad
boutiques along the mostly pedestrian street supply shoppers with an exhaustive
selection of high-quality Scottish tartans, tweeds, leather goods, glassware and
ceramics, as well as international fashions, textiles and housewares.  Princes
Square, also on Buchanan Street, is Scotland's premier center of fashion and
design, with many international designers and specialists ranging from
hairdressers to interior design and the Scottish Craft Centre.  If you're short
on time but want the best, head for Frasers, the city's biggest department
store.  The store's luxe interior makes it worth a visit.  Gordon Street is a
veritable stockpile of British designerdom -- Liberty, Burberry, Laura Ashley
and Jaeger among others -- and an easy place to part with your pounds.
<BR></P>
<P>If you adore jewelry, direct yourself to the Argyll Arcade, which has more
jewelers under one roof than anyplace else in Scotland.  One end of the arcade
leads back to Buchanan Street; the other to the St. Enoch Shopping Centre.  Exit
through Debenham's department store onto yet another popular-and
crowded-pedestrian area, Argyle Street, which has a smattering of trendy
clothing and shoe stores and gift houses.  Less formal and expensive shopping
awaits on weekends at The Barras market, whose barrage of collectibles, genuine
antiques and junk will exhaust all but the most obsessive collector.<BR></P>
<P><B>Amsterdam</B>:  New York has Madison Avenue, Amsterdam has P.C.
Hoofstraat.  The fashion mavens of the world meet here, making it the city's
toniest-and priciest-thoroughfare.  Van Baerlestraat crosses P.C. Hoofstraat and
competes with it for smartly turned-out customers, especially the area between
Vossiusstraat and Jan Willem Brouwersstraat.  Kalverstraat has some of the
city's biggest bookstores and an eclectic mix of trendy shoe stores, fashions
and sporting goods.  Well-known ready-to-wear retailers cling together on
Leidsestraat, Heiligeweg and Spiegelgracht. 
<BR></P>
<P>There's a street market for almost everything, including exotic foodstuffs
and fabrics, antiques and carpets.  At the Bloemenmarkt flower vendors sell
their bulbs, plants and dried flowers from floating barges.  Oudemanhuis bustles
with buyers and sellers of books, new and old.  The city's largest open-air
street market, Albert Cuyp Markt, offers bargains on food, clothing, spices,
jewelry and even fresh fish and olives.  Zwarte Markt and Oosterse Markt,
translating to the Black Market and Eastern Market, respectively, boast a bounty
of bargains on new, old and Oriental merchandise.  Search carefully and bargain
hard for the real antiques at Waterlooplein Markt  and Rommelmarkt, two popular
flea markets.  Mondays are blue-and green, yellow, purple, and turquoise-at the
Lapjesmarkt, where you can choose from thousands of fabrics in assorted colors.

<BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF80">(Ed's Note: for more on Amsterdam Shopping, see
<A HREF="http://www.eurodata.com/amster1.htm">Of Lorgnettes and Tassles</A> in
this issue.)</FONT></I><BR></P>
<P><B>Frankfurt</B>:  With a turnover of more than a billion Deutsche marks a
year, Frankfurt's Zeil is one of the busiest shopping streets in the world. 
Mostly large department stores queue along the pedestrian area between the
Konstablerwache and Hauptwache.  Pockets of more exclusive shopping are down the
side streets.  Goethestrasse, with its upscale fashion boutiques, has the
greatest cachet.  Schillerstrasse is a must for the best names in crystal and
china.  Steinweg has smart shoe shops.  Rossmarkt  is frequented for its 
accessories.  Jewelry is the hallmark of Kaiserstrasse. The trendiest boutiques
are located between the Hauptwache and Eschersheimer Gate.  Shop the
Hauptbahnhof center for mid-priced ready-to-wear, cosmetics, home furnishings
and accessories.  Furriers still keep shops along Duesseldorfer Strasse. 
Fressgasse (Eater's Alley) is all about food, glorious food: this popular street
located just off the Hauptwache is dotted with cafes, restaurants and
delicatessens purveying the grandest cheeses, best chocolates and most delicious
wines, to take home or eat on the spot. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Madrid</B>:  Calle Ortega y Gasset and Calle Serrano, running through
the swish community of Salamanca, host a prestigious gathering of Spanish and
international fashion names.  Prices are high, but so is the quality.  Scattered
among the big names are boutiques showcasing some of Spain's less well-known,
but very talented designers.  Collectors haunt the Calle del Prado and adjacent
streets for period furniture, home furnishings and antique jewelry.  Search for
antique books at the Cuesta de Moyano, a permanent antique book fair.  Calle
Almirante, just off Paseo de Recoletos, showcases the work of Spain's more
avant-garde fashion designers.  The district surrounding Puerta del Sol hosts
department stores, El Corte Ingles and Galerias Preciados-ready-to-wear
retailers, and tourist shops.  Though the Gran Via isn't what it used to be, the
lower end still has many fashionable names and several high-quality crafts
stores. 
<BR></P>
<P>New shopping arcades filled with designer boutiques catering to well-heeled
shoppers have sprung up throughout the city.  Among the best are the elegant
Galeria del Prado, Moda Shopping, the ultramodern La Vaguada and numerous
Multicentros de Madrid center, each catering to a different clientele.  The
Serrano Multicentros has chic designer boutiques, the Princesa location attracts
the younger generation.  The Sunday flea market, El Rastro (Calle de Ribera de
Curtidores), is invariably crowded.  Bargains are to be had, but only by the
wary shopper willing to dicker. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>London</B>:  With its chic shops and funky flea markets where treasures
abound, London has an infinite capacity to surprise.  The best shopping areas
for high fashion and hip, sporty boutiques include Sloane Street and Square,
Beauchamp Place, South Molton Street, Regent and Oxford streets.  The most
sought after bespoke tailors and shoemakers reside along Saville Row, Jermyn
Street and St. James's Street.  Many of the most respected jewelers are based on
Bond Street.  Piccadilly and Knightsbridge are the domain of the best department
stores. 
<BR></P>
<P>You're sure to find indispensable gifts to take home in the museums around
Trafalgar Square and Cromwell Road.  The National Gallery's Sainsbury wing
(Trafalgar Square) has a state-of-the-art emporium with books embracing every
period of art history, poster-sized reproductions of the museum's collection,
post cards, puzzles and address books.  St. Martin-in-the-Fields (Trafalgar
Square) features unusual replicas of medieval carvings, brass rubbings of
reliefs dating back to the 11th century, reproductions of Celtic crosses, and
books on religion, art and music.  The gift shop in the Victoria &amp; Albert
Museum sells reproductions of its extraordinary collection of applied art and
design.  Look for jewelry, coasters and trays based on designs by William
Morris, silk ties with M.C. Escher's graphics, silver-plated pillboxes made from
original 19th-century molds, and cloisonn&eacute; pens.
<BR></P>
<P>The noisy, bustling boutique at the Natural History Museum (Cromwell Road)
focuses on children.  Stuffed lions and tigers and bears range from a few inches
to three feet long.  Prehistoric animals get star billing on posters, puzzles,
post cards and books.  Fossils and gemstones are sure to delight a budding young
archaeologist.  London has markets for antiques, books and prints, crafts,
second-hand goods, food, flowers and even a few that are open only during lunch.
 If your time is limited, put Portobello Market at the top of your list.  It's
really three markets in one:  sections for antiques, fruits and vegetables, and
second-hand goods.  At Camden Markets, another lively group of markets, vendors
sell cheeses, fruits and vegetables, antiques, fashions and jewelry by young
designers, ceramics and knitwear, silver, well-traveled leather luggage,
household goods, old telephones and scores more. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Rome</B>:  The city's most desirable shopping is in the old center, away
from the hustle and bustle of modern Rome. Here you'll find the celebrities of
Italian fashion, jewelry, shoes and gifts on streets fanning out from the Piazza
di Spagna:  Via Condotti, Via del Corso, Via Borgognona, Via Frattina and a few
others.  Of these, Via Condotti offers the most luxe stores, while your teens
will feel right at home shopping Via del Corso's less-expensive trend-setting
boutiques for fashions and accessories.  When it's a question of home
furnishings and interior decor with Italian design flair-the classics or
hi-tech-Romans head for Via del Babuino.  Unless, of course, it's antique
furniture they're looking for, then they favor the Via dei Coronari and Via
Margutta.  Bookstores, artisan workshops and art shops commingle along Via del
Pellegrino.  Collectors of antique books and prints prefer the Mercato delle
Stampe, where they can browse among the stacks of old maps and literary works
from past ages.
<BR></P>
<P>The Via Cola di Rienzo is dotted with dozens of gourmet shops selling fresh
pates, cheeses and choice dried meats, imported comestibles and Italian
specialties like olive oils, vinegars and condiments.  Simpler fare is sold in
the stalls of Rome's many food markets:  Campo de' Fiori, surrounded by
delicatessen and bread shops; Piazza delle Coppelle, small but colorful; Piazza
San Cosimato, specializing in cheeses and meats; and Mercato di Testaccio, where
butchers, fishmongers and grocers purvey their delicacies.  Rome's other markets
feature a little bit of everything-dried and fresh flowers, antiques,
handicrafts, Italian specialties, gifts and foods.  At Sunday's Porta Portese
Russian vendors sell caviar and ethnic gifts along Via Ippolito Nievo. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Milan</B>:  Designer Laura Biagiotti, the Queen of Cashmere, and the
other great Italian-and Euro-Japanese-designers hold court here, in Milan,
concentrated on:  Duomo/Vittorio Emanuele II, Corso di Porta Ticinese, Via della
Spiga, Via Montenapoleone, Via Borgopesso  and Via Sant' Andrea.  These streets
bespeak loudly of their chic clientele through dazzling showroom window displays
that highlight a single collection or the season's best.  Well-known names and
up-and-coming designers spill over into regentrified Brera, friendly and
charming with cobblestone streets lined with less expensive shops, trendy
restaurants and cafes, art galleries, artisan workshops and up-to-the-minute
nightclubs.  Concentrate on the main streets, Via Brera and Via Solferino, then
venture onto side streets like Madonnina, Corso Garibaldi, Via Fiori and Via
Fiori Oscuri. Corso Vercelli and Corso Magenta preside over the high-bourgeois
residential refuge of Magenta.   Between stately homes there are smart
restaurants and boutiques-more frequented by impeccably clad residents than
tourists-dotting the wide, tree-lined streets.  Shops sell classic fashions,
fine leather goods, understated jewelry, linens and gifts for the home. 
<BR></P>
<P><B>Zurich</B>:  Thinking Swiss means watches, chocolates, Army knives,
shoes and music boxes, all of which are sold along Zurich's upmarket
Bahnhofstrasse.  While it's no surprise to find major fashion designers and
department stores, it's the numerous specialty stores that sell everything from
luscious chocolate truffles and hand-crafted lace and linens to fashionable
legwear and swank leather goods that promote its reputation for exclusive
shopping.   Make the Bahnhofstrasse your first stop for timepieces ranging from
Swatch to Patek Philippe. 
<BR></P>
<P>Zurich sprawls along both banks of the Limmat River.  The city's second most
important shopping area follows the east side along the Limmatquai and its side
streets.  Foods, fashions, perfumes, lace, needlework, shoes, hats, cotton
undergarments and porcelain are good values in stores along Rennweg and the
smart Storchengasse and Muensterhof.  Langstrasse, between Helvetiaplatz and
Limmatplatz, runs through the heart of a working class neighborhood.  Though the
window displays lack the styling and panache of the boutiques along
Bahnhofstrasse, the stores carry much of the same merchandise...and at lower
prices.  On the east bank, antique shops are concentrated around Neumarkt,
Rindermarkt and Kirchgasse.  On the opposite bank, windows display art nouveau
and art deco collectibles along Rindermarkt and Abraham.  &#164;  <BR></P>
<P><I><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Diane Marshall </FONT>is the former managing
editor of Travel Holiday magazine and The Savvy Shopper. 
</I></P>
<HR>
<H2>Bring It On Home: ETS offers VAT Refund Service<BR></H2>
<P>Europe Tax-Free Shopping (<B>ETS</B>) offers a plan which simplifies VAT
refunds for travelers by providing thousands of retailers across Europe with
standardized Tax-Free Shopping Cheques, which customers can receive along with
their purchases upon presentation of appropriate passport information.  When
leaving Europe, the cheques are stamped by outgoing Customs and can then be
cashed in at a nearby ETS refund window.  The small fee charged by ETS can be
well worth it, as the service enables you to get all of your VAT refunds handled
in a single transaction, before you even board the plane for home.  More than
100,000 European retailers participate in the plan and display the ETS logo in
their windows.  For more information, ask your travel agent for an ETS brochure,
or contact ETS at 233 S. Wacker Drive, Suite 9700, Chicago Illinois, 60606 (<B>312-382-1101</B>).
 On the World Wide Web you'll find them at<A HREF="http://www.taxfree.se/">http://www.taxfree.se</A>;
in addition to information on the ETS program, the site offers shopping tips and
maps of European cities and airports.
</P>
